</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEADWATERS-HALT-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 HEADWATERS LOGGING PLAN HALTED  &HT;     By HARRIET CHIANG 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A judge blocked a plan Monday by Pacific Lumber
Co. to log a section of unprotected land within California's
Headwaters Forest Reserve. Environmentalists had opposed the
logging, saying it would cause irreparable harm to wildlife and
would disrupt visitors to the wilderness area.
</P>
<P>
   The Sierra Club and Environmental Protection Information Center
in Garberville sued in March to stop the lumber company from using
helicopters to lift fallen timber from the ``Hole in the
Headwaters,'' a 705-acre patch of land owned by the company and
surrounded by public land.
</P>
<P>
   Pacific Lumber acquired the patch of land as part of the $480
million deal last year with state and federal agencies to create a
7,500-acre wildlife preserve.
</P>
<P>
   In ruling in favor of the environmentalists, San Mateo Superior
Court Judge Quentin Kopp said the lumber company's harvesting plan
to bring in Chinook helicopters marks a significant change from the
original proposal and requires public review.
</P>
<P>
   While Kopp granted the environmentalists' request for a
preliminary injunction, the judge also required the Sierra Club to
post a $250,000 bond to cover the profits the lumber company says
it will lose from the delay.
</P>
<P>
   Kopp, who went to Eureka in June to hear a day of arguments, was
called into the case after Humboldt County judges either recused
themselves or were challenged by lawyers involved in the suit.
</P>
<P>
   Kathy Bailey, forest conservation chairwoman for the Sierra Club
of California, called the bond requirement ``troubling,'' saying it
could have a potentially chilling effect on future lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   However, she said, ``at this point the main thing for us is that
he has issued a temporary injunction.''
</P>
<P>
   John Campbell, president and CEO of Pacific Lumber, said the
company was disappointed with the ruling but confident it would
ultimately prevail in a trial. ``Our inability to operate this plan
will result in hardship for the company and our employees,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell stressed that the property does not include old-growth
trees. ``We have made improvements to the harvest plan to increase
protection for fish, wildlife and water quality,'' he said, adding
that the changes provide the ``proper balance between sustainable
timber harvesting, job preservations and environmental
protection.''
</P>
<P>
   Frank Bacik, the lawyer for Pacific Lumber, said the 705 acres
are third-growth _ or previously harvested _ forest. ``It's not a
pristine wilderness,'' he said. ``It's all commercial.''
</P>
<P>
   After the California Department of Forestry and Fire Protection
approved the company's logging plan in February, environmentalists
filed suit, contending that noise from the helicopters would harm
the area's wildlife and disturb visitors to the reserve.
</P>
<P>
   The plaintiffs also charged that Pacific Lumber's use of an
access road would further destabilize a landslide area that
provides habitat for salmon in the Elk River.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, Bailey said, environmentalists hope to purchase the
area, which she called ``a very important part of the reserve.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to make sure that the Elk River remains protected
so that the salmon do not become extinct,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In his 19-page opinion, Kopp agreed that the company's plan to
use the road required further public review because it differed
significantly from the original proposal.
</P>
<P>
   He lashed out at the California Department of Forestry for ``its
silence'' over potential adverse effects from use the road.
</P>
<P>
   ``CDF did not notify the public of an opportunity for review,''
Kopp wrote. ``It did not solicit public comment. Instead, it
ignored the request of petitioner Sierra Club for simple
notification of receipt of a proposed amendment.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A believer in orchestration might reasonably conclude CDF's
actions were intentionally executed to prevent public exposure or
comment,'' Kopp wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Although Kopp wasn't drawing any conclusions, he said he wanted
to explore further how CDF handled the issue.
</P>
</TEXT>
