<HEADLINE>
2001 ALL-STAR GAME IN SEATTLE: A TRAFFIC JAM OF JOY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ A year from Tuesday Seattle will be enveloped in
baseball's All-Star Game.
</P>
<P>
   The early line: Fewer rubber bullets than WTO, but less
dope-smoking than EMP.
</P>
<P>
   (Alert to Eugene anarchists: Mayor Paul Schell is happy to
concede downtown again, but don't even think about messing with the
new ballpark.)
</P>
<P>
   All three events are brought to you by Microsoft money (don't
forget, the techies own a big chunk of the Mariners, too), so it's
all one big link to the same CPU.
</P>
<P>
   Since forward thinking created all the wealth that brought these
wonderful events, it continues to be smart to look ahead and plan
for the 2001 game. Actually, I might be a little late already,
since SoDo traffic already has had to begin queuing for the
contest.
</P>
<P>
   Over the weekend, the Mariners sent to Atlanta a huge delegation
of owners, executives and staffers to observe the game's
operations. Which should guarantee one thing: massive cost
overruns.
</P>
<P>
   But regardless of cost (that's the civic motto now, isn't it?),
the good times for Puget Sound-area baseball fans at this
celebration are broader and more diverse than what can be observed
via the TV coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle hasn't hosted an All-Star Game since the dark ages of
1979. Much has changed. Here is what's in store (and if it isn't,
shame on the Mariners and the host committee):
</P>
<P>
   Balloting: As the center of the Internet universe, Seattle will
be the first city to host the game in which players were voted upon
entirely by e-mail. Starting at catcher for the American League:
Joe Oliver (JavaScript error message 27).
</P>
<P>
   Rosters: Also for the first time, players must bring a note from
a medical doctor before being excused from play. Or in cases
involving a certain center fielder, a note from a psychologist.
</P>
<P>
   Highlight videos: At the request of a certain player (and his
psychologist), stadium video highlights of rival outfielders will
not be shown.
</P>
<P>
   Media coverage: The Seattle dailies will produce gargantuan
special sections about the All-Star Game, the immortality of
baseball and its vivid place in the cosmos. Each paper will stage a
contest to find a person who will read every word, the winner
earning the right to be named Publisher for Life.
</P>
<P>
   No one will win.
</P>
<P>
   Home run contest: Lately this event has come close to upstaging
the game. But Seattle's pitcher-friendly ballpark is a threat to
its success. So the fences will be moved in to just beyond the
infield. Hundreds of homers will be hit, the crowd will go crazy.
By the following season, Commissioner Bud Selig will have made the
dimensions mandatory for every park.
</P>
<P>
   Run around the bases: A popular event for kids won't be allowed
because the field conditions are so delicate that groundskeepers
tend to lose their jobs over it. So the event will be moved to the
parking garage and expanded to something called Run Around David
Wells.
</P>
<P>
   Game-day special promotion: After winter rains rusted in place
the roof that was almost never used during the baseball season,
Mariners owners will issue wire brushes and safety harnesses to the
first 20,000 fans. Once they get the roof mechanism unstuck, fans
will be allowed to keep the equipment as All-Star souvenirs.
</P>
<P>
   Pre-game ceremony: Chicago White Sox shortstop Alex Rodriguez
will receive his World Series ring from the Mariners, whom he left
in free agency after the championship. Rodriguez will thank the
fans and say it was truly a team effort, a point contradicted by
the 15 games the team is behind Oakland in the AL West.
</P>
<P>
   Concessions conflagration: After fans from around the country,
many visiting the ballpark for the first time, sample the first
$10, six-ounce cups of beer in Major League Baseball history, they
will protest by setting the stadium on fire.
</P>
<P>
   Post-game fireworks: Traffic will be so constipated that fire
trucks cannot reach the stadium until the fire's temperatures melt
steel. Fire officials will later say it wouldn't have made a
difference; the department budget could not have afforded the
parking.
</P>
<P>
   Economic impact: Estimates, done by the same people who insist
50,000 fans at Seafair are actually 500,000, will range to $10
billion for the local economy. But there is no private money
available to build the replacement stadium. So the Mariners will
agree to play two years at Husky Stadium until the state finances a
stadium built with a fireproof, fixed concrete roof.
</P>
<P>
   P-I columnist Art Thiel can be reached at 206-448-8135
</P>
<P>
   or artthiel &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
