<HEADER>
A8697 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-FUGITIVE-HUNT-LADN     07-11 0935
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FUGITIVE-HUNT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A WAY TO BRING FLEEING MURDER SUSPECTS BACK FROM MEXICO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) &HT;    By LISA VAN PROYEN 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It took 19 months to convince a Mexican judge that
Jose Luis Del Toro Jr. is an American and should stand trial in the
United States for the brutal death of a Florida woman.
</P>
<P>
   But thousands of other fugitives have fled south of the border
from Los Angeles and elsewhere with little fear of extradition
because Mexico will not return its own citizens who face the death
penalty to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   A Florida congressman has proposed a law that would have
tremendous implications in Los Angeles by sanctioning Mexico and
other countries for failing to cooperate in extraditions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our main objective is to close the loophole. We want the
criminals to be held accountable for their heinous acts,'' said
Martin Baker, a spokesman for Rep. Dan Miller, R-Bradenton, who
sponsored the bill, HR 3212.
</P>
<P>
   The bill comes as Mexico's new reform-minded president, Vicente
Fox, has pledged to crack down on crime and corruption in his
country.
</P>
<P>
   Some police officers and officials in Los Angeles support
Miller's bill, although others say it could backfire.
</P>
<P>
   ``When people get pushy with Mexico, the emotions of the nation
surface because we've always been looked at as the Big Brother,''
said Detective Art Zorrilla, who heads the Los Angeles Police
Department's Foreign Prosecution Unit. ``Sometimes, pushing our
weight around really works against us.''
</P>
<P>
   Each year, about 50 people accused of violent crimes in Los
Angeles flee to Mexico, Zorrilla said. Mexico has refused to send
back any of its citizens.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead, they tell us, `Bring us your evidence, and we will
try him here,' '' Zorrilla said. ``It's a sovereignty thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Zorrilla believes Mexico might change its policy if the high
number of crimes committed by Mexican nationals here against other
Mexican nationals is clearly demonstrated to officials across the
border.
</P>
<P>
   Miller's bill seeks to build a case against Mexico by requiring
the State Department to submit an annual report to Congress about
delays for extraditions and actions taken. If five or more
grievances are filed against a country for not extraditing a
criminal, that nation could be deemed uncooperative. Sanctions,
including the denial of visas to high-ranking officials, could also
be imposed.
</P>
<P>
   That would've been the case with Sheila Bellush, whom Del Toro
is accused of shooting to death in 1997 before slitting her throat
in front of her 2-year-old quadruplets.
</P>
<P>
   After a series of appeals that Baker refers to as ``stall
tactics,'' a judge in Mexico agreed to allow the extradition. Del
Toro pleaded guilty last week in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Miller wants to make sure families don't have to battle
Mexico over extradition and cooperation on criminal cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's trying to make sure that cases like this don't happen
again and make it easier to return them. No victim's family should
be forced to wait 19 months or longer to face justice,'' Baker
said.
</P>
<P>
   The bill is awaiting hearings by the Judiciary and International
Relations committees before being reported to the House.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles congressional representatives said they have not
decided how to vote on the bill, but they agree with its intent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Murderers, rapists and other criminals must never be allowed
to evade the American justice system by crossing international
borders,'' said Rep. Howard Berman, D-Mission Hills.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Brad Sherman, D-Woodland Hills, agreed that reforms are
needed, but not necessarily by denying visas to high-ranking
officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best way to make sure they are adequately tried and
punished if they are guilty is to have them extradited to the
U.S.,'' Sherman said.
</P>
<P>
   For now, Los Angeles police look for justice in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Since his unit was formed in 1985, detectives have filed more
than 300 cases in Mexico, with a 40 percent to 50 percent
conviction or clearance rate, Zorrilla said. A case can be cleared
if the criminal has died.
</P>
<P>
   Preparing a case for filing in Mexico can take anywhere from two
months to a year, with detectives working six weeks alone on
translating the murder scene, witness statements and evidence
reports into Spanish.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have all kinds of problems,'' said homicide Detective Bob
Vanina.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here, I can make a phone call and somebody can computer-access
a name for us. Down there, that's not the case. They all seem to be
hand-written records,'' Vanina said. ``It's frustrating here
because you do all this work and you never get to place the
handcuffs on the suspect.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the fugitives Los Angeles police have asked Mexican
authorities to look for is Jose Rodriguez, who detectives say was
recently spotted in a Mexican town.
</P>
<P>
   The 16-year-old is accused of fatally stabbing his 36-year-old
uncle with a kitchen knife in Van Nuys on June 4 after they clashed
over the teen-ager's drinking, said Detective Al Aldaz.
</P>
<P>
   The uncle, Alvaro Montenegro, simply wanted to give his nephew a
better life in the United States, providing him a job and shelter
at his home after the youngster arrived illegally two months
earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Police suspect someone drove Rodriguez to the border after
Montenegro's slaying.
</P>
<P>
   On June 14, detectives traveled to Mexico City to file the case,
said Van Nuys homicide Detective Jim Rahm.
</P>
<P>
   Zorrilla said the advantage with this case is that the suspect
was immediately identified by family members who witnessed the
killing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
