<SLUG> BC-LA-COPS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
L.A. POLICE PLAN TO JOIN IN PROTESTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) &HT;    By ALEXA HAUSSLER 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Los Angeles police will likely demonstrate at next
month's Democratic National Convention, the police union said,
despite landing a lucrative new contract.
</P>
<P>
   Some city officials say protests could harm an already bruised
police image if officers join the tens of thousands of
demonstrators expected to vie for the public spotlight during the
Aug. 14-17 convention.
</P>
<P>
   But Ted Hunt, president of the Los Angeles Police Protective
League, said on Monday that police union members will be creative
and not destructive if they decide to protest what they call a lack
of quality-of-life issues in the new contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will not in any way, shape or form jeopardize the public
safety or the safety of the visitors of Los Angeles,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Police on Saturday ratified a contract that includes a 13
percent pay raise over three years _ higher than the contract for
L.A. County sheriff's deputies _ and improved benefits. City
officials scrambled to try to hammer out a contract to try to
thwart possible demonstrations at the convention.
</P>
<P>
   However, the department's rank and file also was clamoring for
more community policing and condensed work schedules, neither of
which was included in the contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody's been listening to us,'' Hunt said. ``They are just
flat-out not listening to what we have to say.''
</P>
<P>
   And while city officials agreed that officers have a right to
protest during the convention, they said they would rather that the
police settle their issues in a different setting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like them to feel that we have an open and responsive
enough government that they feel they can resolve their grievances
this way rather than taking to the streets,'' said Councilman Joel
Wachs. ``It might be detrimental to the public's perception of law
enforcement.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Wachs, also a mayoral candidate, said he doesn't blame
the officers for their reluctance in approving the contract despite
the fact that it is higher than many police contracts.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are happy with the economic package that was offered but
there are other things that are needed,'' Wachs said. ``Everything
isn't about money, and working conditions are important.''
</P>
<P>
   Councilman Mike Feuer, who was on the panel of city officials
that negotiated the contract, said the rank and file's issues need
to be addressed, possibly though a third-party mediator.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all recognize that there are some key issues that need to
be discussed further,'' said Feuer, who is running for city
attorney. ``But something like a DNC protest is not the most
productive way of going about addressing those concerns.''
</P>
<P>
   Councilwoman Jackie Goldberg, also a member of the city's
negotiating team, said she thinks the officers are having
difficulty accepting changes in the new contract, including tougher
disciplinary systems and more power for the chief of police.
</P>
<P>
   But, she added, ``They got a lot of money and that usually helps
the medicine go down.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Goldberg said she has no objection to protests at the
convention.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as it's on their own time, they don't lose their
freedom-of- speech rights when they become police officers,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Mayor Richard Riordan agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether it's the police union or the teachers union, everyone
has an opportunity to express their First Amendment right,''
spokesman Peter Hidalgo said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
