r a BC-BUSH-NAACP-SFCHRON &LR;      07-11 1194
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-NAACP-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ACKNOWLEDGING THAT RACISM STILL EXISTS, BUSH PLEDGES TO
UPHOLD  CIVIL RIGHTS
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By MARC SANDALOW 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ In another break from Republican Party orthodoxy,
Texas Gov. George W. Bush acknowledged Monday that racism is alive
in America and criticized his own party for not doing enough to
combat it.
</P>
<P>
   ``For our nation, there is no denying the truth that slavery is
a blight on our history, and that racism, despite all of the
progress, still exists today,'' Bush told 2,000 delegates at the
annual convention of the NAACP.
</P>
<P>
   ``For my party, there is no escaping the reality that the party
of Lincoln has not always carried the mantle of Lincoln,'' Bush
said, pledging to make enforcement of civil rights laws a top
priority of his presidency.
</P>
<P>
   For Bush, it was another foray into a topic ordinarily shunned
by fellow Republicans, and another opportunity to distance himself
from the most extreme elements of his own party.
</P>
<P>
   It follows appearances in recent weeks to traditionally
Democratic leaning organizations like the National Council of La
Raza and the League of United Latin American Citizens in which Bush
has touted his credentials as a ``compassionate conservative.''
</P>
<P>
   The GOP's presumptive presidential nominee spoke of ending the
discriminatory practices of ``redlining and profiling,'' of
providing health care and housing for the poor and of expanding and
of improving standards at public schools to end the ``soft bigotry
of low expectations.''
</P>
<P>
   The 16-minute address was met with polite, though hardly
enthusiastic, applause. Eyes rolled, but most members were
forgiving, when Bush needed three tries to correctly pronounce the
name of famed black eductor W.E.B. Du Bois.
</P>
<P>
   The most remarkable aspect of Bush's speech to the NAACP may be
that he delivered it at all.
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago, Republican presidential candidate Bob Dole
snubbed the organization's invitation as a ``setup.'' The group was
also shunned by President Bush in 1992 and by President Reagan in
the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Though Dole apologized later in the campaign, his absence
angered some NAACP officials and led many African Americans to
conclude that he had written off their community.
</P>
<P>
   Bush acknowledged the incident in the opening moments of his
address, and seemed intent on not repeating the mistake.
</P>
<P>
   ``While some in my party have avoided the NAACP, and while some
in the NAACP have avoided my party, I am proud to be here.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the days of President Franklin Roosevelt, African
Americans have formed a loyal base of support for the Democratic
Party. No more than a third of black voters have cast ballots for a
Republican presidential candidate since President Dwight
Eisenhower's election in the 1950s.
</P>
<P>
   There is no evidence that the Democrat's huge advantage with
African Americans will disappear in November. The only question is
whether Bush's attempts to woo minority voters can chip away at
Vice President Al Gore's support.
</P>
<P>
   A recent NBC/Wall Street Journal Poll showed Bush with 17
percent of the black vote, compared to 71 percent for Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``For those of you who support me _ I see a couple here, I hope
you won't change your opinion,'' Bush to the laughter of the
overwhelmingly Democratic crowd. ``For those who don't, I hope you
... give me the chance to tell you what is in my heart.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush acknowledged that the ``history of the Republican Party and
the NAACP has not been one of regular partnership.'' He added: ``We
are not limited by what we have done, or what we have left undone.
We are limited only by what we are willing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   There was no immediate public response from GOP officials.
Though most Republicans advocate strict enforcement of civil rights
laws, as Bush did Monday, the traditional GOP position has been to
emphasize the progress that has been made to alleviate racism and
to take credit for offering opportunities to blacks and other
minorities.
</P>
<P>
   It is not the first time that Bush has tried to distinguish
himself from elements of his own party. Last fall, Bush criticized
GOP leaders in Congress for suggesting that tax refunds be deferred
to some low-income workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think they ought to balance their budget on the backs
of the poor,'' Bush said at the time, angering some Republicans who
thought his comments provided ammunition for Democratic opponents.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sh1  &LR; Assessing His Appeal
</P>
<P>
   Some observers believe that the greatest political benefit to
Bush appearing before the NAACP and other traditionally liberal
groups will come not from from minorities but from swing white
voters who are leery of the Republican Party's conservative fringe.
</P>
<P>
   ``What more could you do to establish yourself as a
compassionate conservative than consistently reaching out to
minority groups,'' said David Bositis, an analyst at the Joint
Center for Political and Economic Studies, a think tank devoted to
minority issues.
</P>
<P>
   Bositis predicted that despite his outreach, Bush will probably
not draw more than 10 to 15 percent of the black vote, about the
same amount received by the last several Republican presidential
candidates.
</P>
<P>
   In accordance with its tax-exempt status, the NAACP cannot
endorse political candidates. On several issues _ ranging from its
support for affirmative action, gun control, a higher minimum wage,
a hate crime law and the removal of the Confederate flag from the
South Carolina statehouse _ the NAACP is clearly in far closer
harmony with Gore than Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Gore will address the NAACP convention tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   Just before Bush began speaking, the convention was disrupted by
four protesters carrying signs and shouting their objection to the
execution in Texas of convicted murderer Gary Graham. The four were
removed by security guards as a choir sang to drown out the
disturbance.
</P>
<P>
   Several of Bush's popular stump lines fell flat, as when he
advocated a plan for financial assistance to low-income homeowners.
</P>
<P>
   ``Behind all these proposals is a simple belief. I believe in
private property. I believe in private property so strongly, I want
everyone to have some.''
</P>
<P>
   The line was met with silence.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, several in the audience gave him credit simply for
being there.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a step in the right direction,'' said Lewis Woods, an
NAACP member from North Carolina, who hasn't voted for a Republican
President since Eisenhower.
</P>
<P>
   ``Face it _ they haven't done anything for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the Democratic politicians in attendance were less
charitable.
</P>
<P>
   ``This man needs to show us more if he wants more from us,''
said Rep. Eleanor Holmes Norton, the non-voting Democratic
congresswoman from Washington, D.C. ``
</P>
<P>
   ``African Americans are way past the point where they are going
to give candidates credit just for showing up.''
</P>
<P>
   Other Democrats attacked Bush even before he spoke.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am here to sound an alarm to the country,'' said Rep. Eddie
Bernice Johnson, D-Texas. ``Americans should look past
`compassionate conservatism'' and see it for what it is _ it is
compassion for conservatives _ right wing conservatives.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-11-00 0039EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
