r s BC-BKL-SPARKS-MIDSEASON-     07-11 0592
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKL-SPARKS-MIDSEASON-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPARKS MORE THAN HAPPY AT HALFWAY MARK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PAMELA LEWIS  
 c.2000 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ The Sparks have arrived at the halfway mark
of 2000 WNBA season as the hottest team in the league with the
second-best record. There's no question as to how they reached this
pinnacle in the franchise's brief history.
</P>
<P>
   Defense.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Michael Cooper has preached it from the beginning of
training camp and made it a major part of the team's practice. It's
been put to the test and has yielded positive returns with a
12-game winning streak and a 16-2 overall mark, second only to the
three-time defending champion Houston Comets.
</P>
<P>
   The Sparks' numbers speak for themselves. Their opponents have
been limited to a .380 field goal percentage _ lowest in the
league. They are second in rebounds, blocks, and steals.
</P>
<P>
   The coaches' preparation has been another contributing factor,
but it starts and ends with defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The defense) changes each game because each team is a little
bit different,'' Cooper said. ``That's the biggest adjustment we've
made.
</P>
<P>
   ``The players are actually buying into our concept for the games
and they're doing a very good job. ... Everyone is coming in and
just being focused.''
</P>
<P>
   With 14 games remaining, Cooper's Sparks are sitting in good
position with seven of the next eight games at the Forum, where
they are 9-0 going into tonight's home game against the Portland
Fire. The Sparks defeated the Houston Comets once (90-84) and host
them again Friday _ a game which could go a long way toward earning
home-court advantage in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Sparks are such a good team that when they get a jump on
you, they will continue to sustain that lead throughout the game,''
said Utah coach Fred Williams, whose team lost to the Sparks 92-72
on Sunday. ``They play very well, they move the ball around, they
created a lot of inside touches with the basketball, but they also
attacked us from the outside. They have so much versatility that
they create so many problems for anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   This could be the year for center Lisa Leslie to snatch MVP
honors. Monday she was selected the league's player of the week for
the second time this season and seems to be getting better with
each game. Like everyone on the team, her defense has picked up and
she's beginning to jump-start her offense. She's averaging 17.7
points, 9.3 rebounds and 2.5 blocks.
</P>
<P>
   But it's not just Leslie. Forward DeLisha Milton, Leslie's
Olympic teammate, and swing Mwadi Mabika have been effective on
both ends of the court. Milton and Mabika, along with guard Tamecka
Dixon and reserve swing Allison Feaster, have each led the team in
scoring at least once.
</P>
<P>
   Previously looked upon as the league's most underachieving team,
the Sparks are finally playing at a high level.
</P>
<P>
   ``It feels good and you don't want to have a letdown,'' said
Leslie, who has been selected to play in next Monday's WNBA
All-Star Game. ``It's so weird because no matter how much we win we
feel like we don't get the respect that we deserve and we always
feels like we're the underdogs. I guess we're going to always feel
like that until we actually win a championship, but with that that
keeps us fired up.''
</P>
<P>
   NOTES: Mabika had 26 points and 10 rebounds in the Sparks' 94-81
victory in Portland last month. The Fire, led by Sophie
Witherspoon's 26 points, defeated Washington 75-58 on Sunday to
improve to 5-12. Witherspoon is u6OIEp
</P>
</TEXT>
