<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-ALLSTAR-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE STARS ARE OUT IN ATLANTA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JIM CAPLE  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ If a major league official contacts you this morning,
don't blink, don't hesitate, don't waver for a moment. Just say
yes, you would be honored to play in the All-Star Game, and catch
the first available flight to Atlanta. After that, you can call
your agent and check if there's a bonus clause in your contract.
</P>
<P>
   They are the greatest players in baseball, the very reason there
is an All-Star Game. Mark McGwire. Ken Griffey Jr. Alex Rodriguez.
Barry Bonds. Cal Ripken Jr. Mike Piazza. Greg Maddux. And none of
them will play in Tuesday night's game due to injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Eight players, including seven elected starters are out due to
injury, and that doesn't count Pedro Martinez, who would have been
named to the team had he not been on the disabled list. The only
position where an All-Star isn't hurt is second base _ and
Cleveland's Robbie Alomar, hit by a pitch Sunday, has a sore right
elbow and might not play.
</P>
<P>
   League officials were desperately calling players into the wee
hours Sunday night, and as of yesterday morning, the National
League still was looking for a catcher to replace Piazza on the
roster. ``Our guy, Javy Lopez, went to Puerto Rico,'' Atlanta's
Bobby Cox, the National League manager, said. ``And we understand
that with Todd Hundley, there's a very ill person in his family
that he had to attend to. And we're trying to locate a couple other
guys.''
</P>
<P>
   They eventually recruited Chicago Cubs catcher Joe Girardi,
whose All-Star qualifications evidently were that he is hitting
.304 and was able to find a baby-sitter.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball's All-Star selection process includes the nationwide
distribution of millions of ballots, Internet polling and agonizing
decisions by leAPf managers after careful consultation with league
executives and opposing managers. After all that, the final spots
essentially were open to anyone who answered the phone first.
</P>
<P>
   (begin ital) For an all-expenses paid trip to Atlanta and front
row seats to the All-Star Game, just be the 10th caller with a .280
average ... (end ital)
</P>
<P>
   Aske &QR; }hat could possibly be at the root of all the injuries and
absences, Mets All-Star pitcher Al Leiter Sa
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-11-00 0044EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
