<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-11 00:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8718 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-BBO-GONZALEZ-COLUMN-T     07-11 1475
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-GONZALEZ-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW GENERATION GRABS SPOTLIGHT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Mark McGwire and Ken Griffey Jr. can't play because of
knee injuries. A thumb injury kept Barry Bonds out. Concussions
sidelined Mike Piazza and Alex Rodriguez. A back injury prevented
Cal Ripken Jr. from being here.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, the All-Star Game needs a different name.
</P>
<P>
   The No-Stars? The Some-Stars? How about the New-Stars Game.
There are 24 first-time All-Stars at this year's game, and some of
them are among the best players in the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really miss those guys, absolutely, but the guys here are
All-Stars,'' NL manager Bobby Cox said. ``They deserve to be here
because of the numbers in the first half. The game is going to be
nice, because there's some great players.''
</P>
<P>
   The 71st midseason classic is missing some of the traditional
stars, but that just allows some of the younger stars to prove that
they belong.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of ironic you've got so many young superstars here,
and a lot of the guys who have been superstars for a while are
injured,'' Pirates outfielder Brian Giles said. ``You've got great
young players. Todd Helton, Vladimir Guerrero, Edgardo Alfonzo, the
list goes on. They've put up the numbers and are worthy of this
opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   Although they lack the marquee appeal of the likes of McGwire,
Griffey, Bonds and Rodriguez, there's little doubt that most of the
newcomers belong.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't have to look farther than their numbers,'' Mariners
All-Star pitcher Aaron Sele said.
</P>
<P>
   Good idea.
</P>
<P>
   Blue Jays first baseman Carlos Delgado is hitting .363 with 28
home runs _ tied with Bonds for second in the majors behind McGwire
_ and 80 runs-batted-in. Royals first baseman Mike Sweeney is
batting .360 with 78 RBI. Angels third baseman Troy Glaus has 25
home runs.
</P>
<P>
   Royals outfielder Jermaine Dye is batting .319 with 22 home runs
and 65 RBI. A's first baseman Jason Giambi is hitting .334 with 22
home runs and 78 RBI. Giles is hitting .317 with 21 home runs and
72 RBI.
</P>
<P>
   A's starter Tim Hudson is 10-2. Marlins right-hander Ryan
Dempster is 9-5 with a 3.65 earned-run average. Red Sox closer
Derek Lowe has 19 saves.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of young talent in the big leagues, especially
in the American League,'' Hudson said. ``It's a good opportunity
for all the young guys to come out here and show the fans there's
some pretty good talent coming up.''
</P>
<P>
   The new guys might not have the national name recognition of
McGwire, Griffey, etc., but neither did some of the established
stars when they first came up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe it's kind of like a cycle,'' Sweeney said. ``Maybe some
of the first-time guys this year in seven or eight years will be
like guys like Pudge Rodriguez and Griffey who are here every year.
Maybe they'll be perennial All-Stars.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps they will. Until that time, though, maybe the best
moniker for this game is the Unproven-Stars.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they're still up there,'' Delgado said of the
traditional stars. ``They've been doing it for a long time. I've
been doing it for a short time. One thing I'm a big fan of is
consistency. If I'm still doing it in five years, I will consider
myself up with those guys.''
BRAVES' GALARRAGA BASKS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The brightest smile in Turner Field on Monday belonged to
Atlanta Braves first baseman Andres ``Big Cat'' Galarraga. And why
not? The feel-good story of the season has become the feel-good
story of the All-Star Game.
</P>
<P>
   Galarraga is on the NL team after missing all of last season
because of cancer in his lower back.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no words to express how special it is,'' Galarraga
said. ``From being home sick to going to the All-Star Game, it's
exciting. This year is something really special.''
</P>
<P>
   Galarraga is batting .294 with 20 home runs and 62 RBI, making
his selection an easy one for his manager.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, he was our MVP the first half,'' Bobby Cox said.
</P>
<P>
   That isn't what Cox expected, however.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought it would be a slow process, and if he was able to
start the season that would be good,'' Cox said. ``We thought maybe
we'd carry him through the first month or so and see what happens.
But right from the very first day, he came in and did all the work
the other guys did.''
</P>
<P>
   While not as dramatic as a return from cancer, Pirates catcher
Jason Kendall also overcame a lot to make it to the All-Star Game.
He fractured his ankle last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It means something to me, because I know how hard I worked to
get back,'' he said. ``Last year at this time I was sitting on my
couch heavily medicated with my foot up.'' ALICEA ALMOST AN
ALL-STAR
</P>
<P>
   Texas Rangers second baseman Luis Alicea had a second chance to
become an All-Star when the injury bug almost claimed the Indians'
Roberto Alomar.
</P>
<P>
   Alomar has a sore right elbow, and wasn't sure if he could play.
AL manager Joe Torre said Alicea would be considered as a
replacement if Alomar was a scratch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Luis was one of the guys I definitely felt bad about leaving
off the club for a couple of reasons,'' Torre said. ``He's having
probably a career year, and he played for me. He's definitely one
of the considerations.''
</P>
<P>
   Alomar, though, was determined not to join McGwire, Griffey,
Bonds et al., on the sidelines.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to try my best to play,'' he said. ``I came here to
play. I didn't come here to sit on the bench.''
</P>
<P>
   John Blake, the Rangers vice president for communications who is
attending the game, was asked to be prepared to get in touch with
Alicea just in case, but never had to make the call. RODRIGUEZ
STAYING PUT
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this season, Rangers catcher Ivan Rodriguez said he was
considering changing positions in a few seasons to save the wear
and tear on his body.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, he indicated he's staying behind the plate for many more
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to change positions,'' he said. ``I'm a catcher,
and I'm going to be a catcher for a long time. As long as my legs
and my body can hold up, I'm going to be behind the plate.
Everybody talks about changing positions, but I have plenty of
years behind the plate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being a catcher is a tough position, but I like to work hard
to keep myself strong. That's what I'm feeling right now. I have
plenty more years behind the plate.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez had talked about going to infield coach Bucky Dent's
school in the off-season to learn how to play second. And now?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll probably go there to teach kids and probably get some
ground balls, but that doesn't mean anything,'' he said. ``I'm
going to be behind the plate. That's my position.'' RANDY VS.
BOOMER
</P>
<P>
   Diamondbacks ace Randy Johnson and Blue Jays 15-game winner
David Wells were announced as the starting pitchers for the
All-Star Game.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson pitched Sunday and only can work an inning, but Cox
picked him to start because he's leading the NL in victories, ERA
and strikeouts.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Randy Johnson's got an inning in him, you want him to be
the first guy out to pitch,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Wells, who's leading the majors in victories, was picked to
start by Torre, the Yankees manager. The Yankees traded Wells for
Roger Clemens before the 1999 season, a deal that made ``the
Boomer'' bitter at the time.
</P>
<P>
   But Wells, sitting next to Torre at a news conference Monday,
said he didn't feel vindicated by the All-Star start.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there's a point to prove,'' he said. ``When
things like that happen you just have to treat it as business, and
don't hold any regrets over it. New York was a place where I wanted
to play. That's where I wanted to end my career. But you when have
a chance to trade for Roger Clemens, you'd be crazy not to.''
</P>
<P>
   Torre, whose team is having a tougher-than-expected battle with
the Blue Jays in the AL East, had the final word.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it was just to prove a point, you've done it so you can
stop now,'' he said. A TRADE THAT WORKED
</P>
<P>
   Ryan Dempster had only been in the Rangers' farm system for a
year when he was traded to the Florida Marlins during the 1996
season, a deal that brought John Burkett to Texas and helped the
Rangers win their first-ever division title.
</P>
<P>
   Dempster was upset at the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``The initial reaction was disappointment,'' he said. ``I was a
young guy, I was only with the team for a year, and I though why
don't they want me? Why are they trading me away?''
</P>
<P>
   The trade turned out to be the best thing to happen to him,
however. He was in an organization building with youth, and made it
up to the majors last year. This season, he's an All-Star.
</P>
<P>
   ``It turned out to be a turning point for my career, being with
an organization that took a different route,'' he said. ``I was
able to get some experience at a young age. You never know what
could have happened. I could still be pitching in Triple A.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
