<SLUG> BC-POTTER-SALES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POTTER CREATING BOOKSTORE FEVER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PAM PARK 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Weekend sales of the new Harry Potter title were
hotter than a witch's cauldron, retailers report.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes &AMP; Noble Booksellers, whose outlets around the country
held special debut parties from midnight Friday to 1 a.m. Saturday,
sold a scorching 114,000 copies of the fourth installment, ``Harry
Potter and the Goblet of Fire,'' in the first hour.
</P>
<P>
   By Sunday evening, the chain had sold more than 500,000 copies _
breaking its previous retail and online records for any book on its
first day of sale.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers ordered a record 100,000 copies through the company's
Web site, Barnes &AMP; Noble.com.
</P>
<P>
   Online bookseller Amazon.com received 389,000 orders through the
weekend, about 18 percent from new customers.
</P>
<P>
   Amazon.com, which teamed up with FedEx to deliver 250,000 copies
on Saturday _ the first day of distribution _ called the effort one
of the largest sales and distribution events in e-commerce history.
</P>
<P>
   Amazon.com also reported a bump in sales of other children's and
fantasy books.
</P>
<P>
   Although some retailers discounted the title, the sales figures
are still impressive at a suggested retail price of $25.95.
</P>
<P>
   San Fernando Valley area consumers shared the enthusiasm, with
Borders Books and Music in Canoga Park selling more than 400 copies
of the new title and a large number of the earlier books by English
author J.K. Rowling over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Anthony Horsley, community relations coordinator, said sales at
the Borders Cafe were ``amazing,'' but Harry Potter may bring
longer term benefits because new customers came to the store.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes &AMP; Noble's Encino store saw an increase in sales of other
books, possibly due to about 300 children and parents who enjoyed
the late-night debut party while waiting to grab Rowling's new
hardback the instant it was released.
</P>
<P>
   ``While people were waiting, they looked for other things,''
said Jaime Rodriguez, community relations manager.
</P>
<P>
   Weekend sales were not available, but Rodriguez said the store
sold several hundred of the books and had more on hold.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it was far beyond expectations,'' he said. ``There was
such hype about the book, and people all across the country were
waiting to get it.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez said a first press run on a John Grisham novel might
be about 2.5 million copies. ``Harry Potter and the Goblet of
Fire'' had an initial press run of about 3.8 million copies, and
most stores ran out long before the weekend did.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez, 31, said he read 432 pages of the 750-page book over
the weekend and forced himself to put it down at 1 a.m. Monday so
he could get enough sleep to go to work.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really, really good,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
