<BODY>
 PM-BUDGET-NYT 
c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; For TUESDAY PMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Tuesday, July 11.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-ISSUES (Washington) _ A look at the main issues under
discussion during the summit. By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE-PAROLE (Paris) _ France has been caught up in a debate
over whether a criminal, Patrick Henry, whose murder case led to
the abolishment of the death penalty, should be paroled after 24
years in jail. On Monday, the justice minister rejected Henry's bid
for freedom. Henry's 1977 case played a vital role in France's
eventual decision to end the death penalty in 1981. By Suzanne
Daley.
</P>
<P>
   SALVADOR-GARDEN (San Salvador, El Salvador) _ Like a testament
to life's stubborn triumph, a rose garden filled with thick,
fragrant blossoms rises at the site where soldiers killed six
Jesuit priests at the Jose Simeon Canas Central American University
in 1989. Nearby, a votive candle flickers in the room where the
soldiers then killed a housekeeper and her daughter, hoping to
eliminate any witnesses. It did not work. One woman saw the crime
and helped build a case against the gunmen. More important, more
than a decade since the killings, tens of thousands of people from
around the world have sought out the Jesuit residence's tiny garden
to bear their own witness to the faith of eight people they
consider martyrs who defended the poor during this country's civil
war. A foreign journal by David Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Locator map has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   TURKEY-POLITICS (Istanbul) _ The increasing likelihood that a
73-year-old former prime minister will go to prison for remarks in
a political speech six years ago is sending a chill through
Turkey's political elite and bringing widespread calls to relax
laws that restrict freedom of speech. An appeals court last week
upheld the one-year sentence and lifetime political ban imposed on
former Prime Minister Necmettin Erbakan on the charge of
``provoking hatred'' in a 1994 speech. Since the ruling, political
leaders have scrambled to diminish the decision's impact on
Turkey's efforts to portray itself as a modern democracy and to
join the European Union. By Douglas Frantz.
</P>
<P>
   CANADA-POLITICS (Calgary, Alberta) _ Stockwell Day, the new
leader of Canada's official opposition, offers a conservative face
rarely associated with Canadian politicians: support for a flat
income tax, tougher sentencing for criminals, and beefed up
military spending. But his sudden sweep to national prominence,
culminating with his decisive election Saturday night as leader of
the new Canadian Alliance, seems vaguely familiar, leading some
press commentators to call him the ``Pierre Trudeau of the Right.''
By James Brooke.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   RACE-POLL (Undated) _ Thirty-five years after the dismantling of
legalized segregation, a majority of Americans maintain that race
relations in the United States are generally good, but blacks and
whites continue to have starkly divergent perceptions of many
racial issues and they remain largely isolated from each other in
their everyday lives, according to a nationwide poll by The New
York Times. By Kevin Sack.
</P>
<P>
   NJ-WHITMAN-PHOTO (Trenton, N.J.) _ After enduring two years of
criticism for the racial profiling practices of her state troopers,
Gov. Christie Whitman is suddenly struggling with a self-inflicted
public relations problem: a photo of the governor herself frisking
a black man, and grinning as she does it. The photo, which has been
subpoenaed by two New Jersey troopers who have filed a
discrimination suit against the state, was taken by a trooper
during a 1996 trip Whitman made with officers as they patrolled in
Camden. It was obtained by the Associated Press and published in
several New Jersey newspapers last weekend. By David Kocieniewski.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CAMPAIGN _ (Moved in ``p'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   GORE-MILITARY (Undated) _ A look at the military service of Al
Gore: In some ways, Army Private Al Gore was never and could never
have been just one of the guys, another grunt. Recruiters were
afraid to even sign him up without calling in a supervisor, once
they heard his name and caught on that he was that anti-war Sen.
Albert Gore's son, just out of Harvard. No less than the Army's
highest-ranking officer, Gen. William Westmoreland, singled him out
during a visit to Fort Rucker, Ala., where Pvt. Gore was stationed
for more than a year. Yet there is no evidence that Gore sought
special treatment, or that the extra notice he got anyway provided
any real protection. On the contrary, within the parameters of his
job as an Army journalist, Gore probably assumed more risk than he
had to. By Melinda Henneberger.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photos [NYT6,7) have been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-GUARD (Undated) _ A look at Gov. George W. Bush and his
National Guard service. By Nicholas D. Kristof.
</P>
<P>
   REPUBS-CONVENTION (Undated) _ The schedule for the Republican
convention breaks with tradition. The roll call will be conducted
over several days, as everyone agrees that it's a snoozer. Also the
vice presidential nominee will speak on Wednesday, to keep that day
interesting, leaving George W. Bush to dominate the final night of
coverage. By Peter Marks.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   LOW-POWER-RADIO (Washington) _ The FCC and Republicans in
Congress have been fighting for months over the commission's plan
to license thousands of low-power radio stations. And now the first
batch of applicants for the spectrum have come in. By David
Leonhardt.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   CLANCY-CHARITY (Undated) _ In 1992, Tom Clancy embarked on a
philanthropic mission worthy of Jack Ryan, the idealistic hero of
his popular techno-thrillers. Clancy wanted to help children who
had cancer and other grave illnesses use the Internet to talk to
one another and learn about their diseases. His children's health
network would also enable parents to search out the best doctors.
And it would let doctors tap into the same worldwide database to
share their expertise and find the latest research. Now Clancy is
scuttling the foundation, and what went wrong is the subject of a
legal mud fight. By Michael Moss and Jim Rutenberg.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT5) has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-U.S.-FLIGHTS (Washington) _ The long rivalry between New
York and Chicago has a new front: the Transportation Department is
expected to decide this summer which city will become the take-off
point for a lucrative set of new flights to China. The decision has
added importance because of the increase in travel that is expected
follow China's likely entrance into the World Trade Organization.
Doing New York's bidding is Delta Air Lines, which wants to fly to
Beijing from JFK. Delta executives argue that New York's size and
economic importance so outweigh Chicago's as to make the decision
an easy one. American Airlines, which would fly from O'Hare to
Shanghai, responds that Chicago's location trumps demographics.
This contest, however, comes with a twist: Chicago and New York
could both end up losing, and the airlines' carping may be hurting
both of their cases. By David Leonhardt.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   CONSECO-WENDT (Undated) _ Gary C. Wendt took the cash up front
when he agreed to become chairman and chief executive of Conseco
Inc., the company disclosed on Monday. Conseco, the troubled
insurance and financial services company, said that it paid Wendt a
signing bonus of $45 million when he joined the company last month.
He was also given 3.2 million shares of stock, now worth $31.2
million, as well as options to buy 10 million more shares. Wendt,
the former chief executive of General Electric Capital, will not
get a salary for the first two years he runs Conseco, but he will
get a bonus of no less than $8 million, and as much as $50 million,
at the end of the two-year period, depending on how high the stock
price is. By Floyd Norris.
</P>
<P>
   PHOTO-SUIT (New York) _ The National Basketball Association has
filed suit against The New York Times Co., accusing it of violating
the terms of its photographers' press passes by selling photographs
from the 1999 NBA playoffs. The suit appears to be the first time a
sports league has tried to control the use of the material
journalists' gather at sporting events. It underscores a growing
determination of the owners of entertainment properties to control
their products and any profits that come from them. The Times sold
a package of five photographs of Knick games for $900 on its online
store. By Felicity Barringer.
</P>
<P>
   EARNINGS-MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ As the second-quarter earnings
season gets into full swing this week, with reports expected from
General Electric, Motorola, Yahoo and J.P. Morgan, the outlook is
the best it has been for years. But a look back at 1994 shows that
even great earnings news may not lift stock prices much when the
Federal Reserve is still intent on raising interest rates to slow
growth. By Jonathan Fuerbringer.
</P>
<P>
   K2DESIGN-AD-COLUMN (New York) _ A leading agency in the
interactive services field is branching out with its first
acquisition, entering the potentially lucrative but risky realm of
wireless services. K2 Design Inc. in New York, which handles
Internet marketing for advertisers like Hewlett-Packard, IBM,
Philips and Standard &AMP; Poor's, plans to announce on Tuesday that it
will join with a venture capital partnership to indirectly acquire
for $14.8 million in stock and cash a majority interest in
SilverCube Inc. A wireless professional services company,
Silvercube works for marketers like General Motors and Edmunds, a
clearing house for automotive data. By Stuart Elliott.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CULTURE (Moved in ``e'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   LINCOLN-CENTER-FESTIVAL (New York) _ How Lincoln Center balanes
the new offerings of its summer festival with the more conservative
tastes of its audience. By Robin Pogrebin.
</P>
<P>
   CALLAS-MEMORABILIA (Paris) _ Arts Abroad: Belongings of Maria
Callas to tour Monaco, Tokyo and New York before returning to
France for display and sale. By Alan Riding.
</P>
<P>
   TUFF-BOOK-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``Tuff,'' by Paul Beatty (Knopf).
Reviewed by Richard Bernstein.
</P>
<P>
   TV-STRANGER-REVIEW (Undated) _ On PBS's P.O.V.: ``Stranger With
a Camera.'' Reviewed by Julie Salamon.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY (Moved in ``k'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   COLLINS-COLUMN (Undated) _ Gail Collins contemplates the
choosing of vice-presidential candidates.
</P>
<P>
   FRIEDMAN-COLUMN (Beirut, Lebanon) _ Thomas L. Friedman examines
the lessons of Lebanon in the Israeli-Palestinian conflict. f
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPORTS (Moved in ``s'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TEN-SAMPRAS-INTERVIEW (Undated) _ Pete Sampras reflects on
Wimbledon, his parents and his future.
</P>
<P>
   BBO-ANDERSON-COLUMN (Undated) _ Sports of The Times column on
beanballs: Roger Clemens's pitch that hit Mike Piazza was the
latest striking example of a too-familiar habit in baseball. By
Dave Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   BBO-ALLSTARS (Atlanta) _ Advance on the Tuesday All-Star Game,
focused on the appearance by Jorge Posada, a step in his evolution
in what has become a breakout season for him. By Jack Curry.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE TIMES (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SCI-GENES-FOOD (Undated) _ Against a backdrop of increasing
concern over the safety of genetically modified crops, the National
Academy of Sciences took the unusual step on Monday of joining with
six foreign academies of science to urge the increased development
and use of biotechnology crops to solve problems of hunger and
poverty in developing nations. By Carol Kaesuk Yoon.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-OKLA-CANCER (Undated) _ Federal officials shut down all
government sponsored clinical trials involving human subjects at
the University of Oklahoma College of Medicine in Tulsa after 26
patients died. The patients, all suffering from melanoma, were
injected with a vaccine. There is no proof the vaccine caused the
deaths but procedures were not followed.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-TICK-BITE (Undated) _ Scientists are studying the chemical
weapons in tick saliva hoping to discover a tick vaccine and drugs
for controlling clotting and inflamation. By Andrew C. Revkin.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-SPACE-STATION (Undated) _ Construction of what is to become
the largest structure that humans have ever put into space has been
on hold, awaiting the late arrival of the station's critical
Russian-made command and living section. The long-overdue service
module, called Zvezda, which means ``star'' in Russian, is to
rocket into orbit Wednesday and put an end to the hiatus of almost
two years in building what is to become a sprawling international
research complex in space. By Warren E. Leary.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-ARCTIC-ICE (Oslo, Norway) _ Melting Arctic caps may yield
environmental disaster, but have some economic benefits. Scientist
theorize the extent of the damage and the future of the caps and
explore a new theory in which the caps melt each summer. By Walter
Gibbs.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-GREAT-LAKES (Alpena, Mich.) _ Alien species such as sea
lamprey are killing off native species like Lake trout in the Great
Lakes. Biologist and wildlife mangers are trying to save the
ecological future of the Great Lakes. By David Binder.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-CONCH-SHELLS (Undated) _ The remarkable strength of conch
shells. Scientists are studying them to discover nature's
evolutionary engineering that could inspire tougher ceramics that
could be used in furnaces and combustion engines. By Kenneth Chang.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-QUANTUM-EXPERIMENTS (Undated) _ How the fuzziness of the
atomic world, described by the equations of quantum mechanics,
solidifies into the larger, everyday world is a long-standing
puzzle, that physicists have been able to ignore until now. But now
scientists have pushed the eerie phenomena of quantum mechanics
much closer to the everyday world with an experiment that is a
simplified version of the concept of Schroedinger's cat. By Kenneth
Chang.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-WATCH (Undated) _ News and notes on science: Items on the
discovery of the tomato growth gene, the migration of butterflies
through the Sierra Nevada with a warning for motorists and the
deaths of tigers at a zoo in India. By Henry Fountain.
</P>
<P>
   NOUR-AFRICAN-WOMEN (Boston) _ A conversation with Nawal Nour,
who has set up the African Women's Health Practices at Brigham and
Women's to deal with the special gynecologic needs of the large
immigrant community. Many of there have undergone the ritual of
female circumcision. By Claudia Dreifus.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-ALLERGY (Undated) _ There are promising results from new
experimental trials of anti-IgE, which targets the antibody IgE and
can stop allergy attacks at their source. By Randi Hutter Epstein.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-PATENTS (Undated) _ Sometimes the treatment can be more
harmful, and demoralizing, for the patient than he or she can bear.
A case in point: the many who had to stop eating to stop the
aspiration of fluids into their lungs. By Sandeep Jauhar.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BRODY-HEALTH (Undated) _ The Personal Health column: The
benefits of drinking large quantities of water are vast, and even
include reducing jet lag. First of two articles. By Jane E. Brody.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-YOUNG-DOCTORS (Undated) _ The shock of baby-faced doctors:
almost half of practicing doctors are under 45, and the greatest
proportion is between 35 to 44. Some people are unprepared to take
advice from a younger person: we are used to taking care of younger
people, not having younger people take care of us. By Alcia Ault.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NYT News Service &LR;  &QL;
</P>
