<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INSIDE-CAMP-DAVID-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD ONCE AGAIN DESCENDS ON SUMMIT SHANGRI-LA, CAMP DAVID  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (TIMELY for Tuessday's Camp David Summit)   (This timely 400-word ``separate-buy'' article is from THE
INDEPENDENT newspaper in London.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By ANDREW MARSHALL  
 c.2000 The Independent, London  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Camp David, once named Shangri-La, was a retreat
for President Franklin Delano Roosevelt from the stifling heat
which blankets Washington in the summer.
</P>
<P>
   Presidents ever since have used it as a vacation home, a place
to entertain guests and a workplace where the daily pressures can
be held at bay.
</P>
<P>
   Former Soviet leader Nikita Khrushchev wrote of the place: ``I
couldn't for the life of me find out what Camp David was. Not even
our Embassy in Washington could tell us. We were finally informed
that Camp David was what we would call a `dacha.'''
</P>
<P>
   The cabins, named after trees, sit on the side of a small
mountain in 135 acres of woods, and meetings are supposed to be
less pressured but also at arms length from the press.
</P>
<P>
   This quaint theory ignores the existence of cell phones: at
previous meetings, both sides have briefed reporters extensively
while the talks were under way.
</P>
<P>
   The inhabitants of Thurmont, the nearest town to Camp David,
were somewhat blase at the flurry of activity on their doorstep.
They seemed more concerned with the local fire department's annual
carnival, according to reporters who had travelled to the area.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've done this before,'' said Wayne Stackhouse, president of
the fire company. ``Reporters and (officials) were all hustling and
bustling around. The townspeople kind of took a back seat.''
</P>
<P>
   All 97 hotel rooms in Thurmont sold out within hours of the
announcement of this week's summit. Thurmont Elementary School will
house the press, with separate classrooms for the Israeli and
Palestinian press (who get on no better than one might imagine).
</P>
<P>
   Reporters and Israeli officials will be staying at the Rambler
Motel; the Cozy Country Inn, where bedrooms are named after
presidents and news organizations, is the other main place in town.
</P>
<P>
   The Reagan Cottage has a queen-size water bed and a
corner-mirrored Jacuzzi; the Kennedy Room has a bidet. The Clinton
Room has no special facilities, but does have chocolate cigars, a
gesture which the owners were apparently thinking of at the
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Freeze, who runs the Cozy Country Inn, remembered a
previous U.S.-Soviet summit when Russian officials descended on the
bar and staged a drinking contest with the locals.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Russians won that one, no comparison,'' he told the
Washington Post. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this 400-word article from THE INDEPENDENT newspaper in
London, it must be purchased from the New York Times Syndicate's
sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at
732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is weyded(at)nytimes.com. If
unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at
816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
