<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-11 02:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8732 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a BC-SPLIT-SISTERS-LEBANON     07-11 0953
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPLIT-SISTERS-LEBANON-INDEPENDENT-FISK-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PALESTINIAN FAMILIES DIVIDED BY NEW ISRAELI FENCE  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (TIMELY for Tuesday's Palestinian Summit, Camp David)   (This 725-word ``separate-buy'' article is from THE INDEPENDENT
newspaper in London. Correspondent Robert Fisk was recently named
``Amnesty International Print Journalist of the Year.'')  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By ROBERT FISK  
 c.2000 The Independent, London  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   AIT AL-SHAAB, SOUTHERN LEBANON _ The rocks were littered with
old Pepsi cans and empty water bottles and dead bushes but Haji
Mariam Badran scrambled towards the Israeli frontier wire with the
help of her stick.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talked to my sister Sheikha on the phone and she promised to
be here at 11:30,'' the old woman wheezed. ``We have been here
since 10:30. And now the Israelis tell us to go away.''
</P>
<P>
   Mariam Badran's story is as pitiful as it is tragic. In 1948,
she fled Palestine when the Jewish army attacked their village near
Acre. Her sister stayed with her mother. She lives in the squalor
of the Ein el-Helweh refugee camp in Lebanon; Sheikha still lives
in the family home, complete with an Israeli passport.
</P>
<P>
   And on the very day that Sheikha called from Israel to confirm
their meeting at the wire, the Israelis decided to call an end to
the family reunions over the frontier fence.
</P>
<P>
   Somewhere beyond the green watchtower and the five Israeli
soldiers in their poncho hats, Sheikha was vainly waiting to see
Mariam. To no avail.
</P>
<P>
   Mariam's son Fadel and grandson Ahmed were with her. It was
little comfort. ``I will tell you how I came to be here and Sheikha
came to be there,'' she told me.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the Jewish soldiers came in 1948, Sheikha and I were
sitting on our mother's lap at the front of our house. The Jews
fired into the air and I ran to the back of the house and across a
field where I came across my uncle.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't see my mother and sister though they ran into the
house. But my uncle thought they had fled and so he came here to
Lebanon with me. And that was how I lost my home and my sister
stayed there. I can never go back to live there.''
</P>
<P>
   For days, the Palestinians from the Lebanese camps had stood at
the wire in the midday heat, shouting at long-lost relatives on the
other side.
</P>
<P>
   Three young men got engaged to Israeli Arab girls _ Palestinian
girls _ from Haifa by shouting their promises through the barbed
wire. One of them thought the Israelis might permit a family visit
once the couple were married, that he might even obtain an Israeli
passport.
</P>
<P>
   A girl had called to her friends: ``I come from Sabra and
Chatila. Have you heard of that place? There was a massacre there.
You must resist. Don't let us down.''
</P>
<P>
   The Israelis decided to end it all. They shouted at strangers
not to approach the frontier _ a useless instruction since the
strangers are in Lebanon and the Israelis must now remain behind
their frontier fence.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations is now driving down both sides to verify a
total Israeli military withdrawal from Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   Just down the road at Rmeich there are some very worried
Christian Lebanese villagers. The mother and father of Beshara Said
are standing outside the family home, only hours after 10
truckloads of heavily-armed Hezbollah men turned up to search their
home.
</P>
<P>
   ``They wouldn't let the police or the `mukhtar' (village leader)
into the house with them,'' Said's mother says. ``They didn't allow
the government forces of law and order to intervene.''
</P>
<P>
   It turned out that Beshara Said was a member of Israel's
mercenary ``South Lebanon Army'' militia, that Hezbollah had
discovered he had fled to Israel and wanted to check out his home.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Said admitted ruefully that, yes, the Hezbollah men had
found guns and uniforms in the house.
</P>
<P>
   In their determination to avoid Christian-Muslim fighting, the
Hezbollah action might therefore be explained. But not allowing the
police to enter the Said household smacked of something else:
Hezbollah justice rather than state justice.
</P>
<P>
   Syria, Lebanon, Palestine. It's the old equation back at the
frontier fence _ with Syria still demanding the return of all the
Israeli-occupied Golan Heights even without its former card in
southern Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   As for Mohamed Badran, Mariam's son, he was watching a swallow
dip and soar over the rocks and bushes. ``I just told my son Ahmed
to watch the bird,'' he said. ``And as we did, the bird flew over
the frontier wire into Palestine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish I was a bird.'' &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
