<SLUG> BC-AZR-BUDGET-AZR(a) </SLUG>
 bc-azr-budget-azr 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (a) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Arizona Republic plans to move the following stories for use
by
</P>
<P>
   clients of the NYTimes News Service for Tuesday, July 11. If you
</P>
<P>
   have any questions, please call The Republic News Desk at (602)
</P>
<P>
   444-8286.
</P>
<P>
   CYBERSHRINK (Phoenix) - You're struggling with a problem. You
need to get help, but you'd sooner be seen naked on the pitcher's
mound at Bank One Ballpark than in the waiting room of a
psychiatrist's office. Perhaps there's no such stigma, but your
budget leaves little room to pay $100 for a therapy session. Or
your schedule is too packed to take the time. Not to worry. Judy
Gifford is in. And she's in on the wave of the future, online
counseling, which is already causing controversy within the mental
health community. By DOUG CARROLL. Story will move in the ``L''
category.
</P>
<P>
   MONTINI-COLUMN (Phoenix) {ndash} I don't carry it in my wallet
anymore, but I always know where it is, in case someone with the
government asks. On the back of my draft card it says I'm supposed
to keep it in my personal possession at all times. I did that for
years. My friends and I figured the law would come after us if we
didn't comply. Looks like that has changed. Story will move in the
``A'' and ``K'' categories.
</P>
</TEXT>
