   Not to worry.
</P>
<P>
   Judy Gifford is in.
</P>
<P>
   And she's in on the wave of the future, online counseling, which
is already causing controversy within the mental health community.
</P>
<P>
   ``Growing up, I always wished I'd been a pioneer,'' says
Gifford, who is busy these days turning her Phoenix-based Web site,
www.find-a-therapist.com, into a full-service online counseling
center.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is like (beginitalic)Star Trek(enditalic). I love being
`out there.'''
</P>
<P>
   E-therapy is indeed out there to its critics, whose concerns
center on three areas:
</P>
<P>
   Anonymity. It's easier for clients and counselors to
misrepresent themselves online. And visual cues, often vital, are
lost.
</P>
<P>
   Privacy. How can clients be sure that their words aren't going
out to all of cyberspace?
</P>
<P>
   Legality. It's generally agreed that online counselors should be
held responsible for following the guidelines of the state in which
they're licensed to practice. But the Internet knows no
geographical borders, making codes of conduct difficult to enforce.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no training or research in Internet therapy, and
there's no definition of what it is,'' psychology ethics expert
Thomas Nagy told the online companion of
(beginitalic)Wired(enditalic) magazine.
</P>
<P>
   But to Gifford and other proponents, much of the skepticism is a
natural fear of the unknown. They say that the benefits of
accessible, affordable care far outweigh the risks. Besides, it's a
wired world, and technology is becoming less intimidating all the
time, particularly to a generation that has grown up with it.
</P>
<P>
   According to a Harris poll, more than 60 million people searched
for health information online last year, and 40percent of those
were looking for information about mental health. Some experts
predict that more than one-fourth of all counseling will be
conducted online within five years.
</P>
<P>
   However, a recent survey by Putnam Investments indicates that
Americans are more than seven times as likely to use the Internet
as a referral for advice than as the actual source of advice. So,
the office visit is far from passi.
</P>
<P>
   Tempe counselor Barbara Albrecht sees advantages in online's
convenience but remains skeptical.
</P>
<P>
   ``It can sabotage the authentic experience of face-to-face
interaction (between counselor and client),'' she says. ``A
therapist can't assess body language or physical demeanor and is at
a disadvantage. Clients can hide in their defenses too easily.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, e-therapy is being put to use, and quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's here, and it's not going to go away,'' says Marian
Dunaway, Gifford's clinical director, who has been recruiting,
screening and interviewing counselors from all over the country for
e-mail, real-time chat and telephone counseling.
</P>
<P>
   Find-a-Therapist is a small-business success story that sprang
from Gifford's traditional practice, FindingStone Counseling Center
which has offices in central Phoenix. The Web site began two years
ago as a counseling directory and referral service and is now the
largest of its kind, with a database of more than 6,000 therapists.
</P>
<P>
   Gifford admits being a former cyberphobe. Terrified of being
left behind by technology, she bought a computer from a friend for
$300 and began to play around with it. When she saw that ``the
whole world could see what I put up,'' she kept refining her own
Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Gifford acknowledges that online counseling has limitations, but
she says it shouldn't be invalidated on that basis. She's working
to ensure clients' privacy and to secure the services of first-rate
counselors.
</P>
<P>
   With online, her reputation is on the line.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's another service delivery model,'' she says. ``The
question is: How do we use this technology and make it the best it
can be, in an ethical, clinical and professionally sound way?''
</P>
<P>
   Soon, the whole world may be logging on for the answer.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Reach the reporter at Doug.Carroll(a)ArizonaRepublic.com or
(602) 444-8190.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
