<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-11 08:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8753 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-MONTINI-COL-AZR &LR;      07-11 0588
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-COL-AZR </SLUG>
  
BC-MONTINI-COL-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    NO DODGING DRAFT FROM YOUR PAST(a) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By E. J. MONTINI(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (PHOENIX) - I don't carry it in my wallet anymore, but I always
know where my draft card is, just in case someone with the
government asks.
</P>
<P>
   On the back of the card it says I'm supposed to keep it in my
personal possession at all times. I did that for years. My friends
and I figured the law would come after us if we didn't comply.
Looks like that has changed.
</P>
<P>
   According to an article I read in the paper, the government now
says that, nationwide, the number of young men registering for the
draft has gone down. ``It is estimated that 88 percent of all young
men who should register do,'' the article said. In Arizona, only 82
percent have registered. No one seems too worked up about it,
however. Officials describe the problem as a ``lack of public
awareness.''
</P>
<P>
   The current crop of eligible draftees started being born in
1975, the year the Vietnam War ended, the year listed on my old
card.
</P>
<P>
   There was no ``lack of public awareness'' in those days.
</P>
<P>
   Between 1964 and 1973, the Selective Service says, 1,766,910
young men were drafted into the military. The first year the
government staged a draft ``lottery'' was 1969. It was on TV. Just
as the war was on TV.
</P>
<P>
   For that first lottery, 366 blue plastic capsules containing
birth dates were placed in a large glass jar and drawn by hand. The
first capsule to be removed contained the date Sept. 14. It meant
that all men born on Sept. 14 between 1944 and 1950 were assigned
No. 1. Many were in high school, or just out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boys'' would have been a better word to describe them, but no
nation likes the idea of sending boys to war. So, we call them
``men.'' That first year, the highest lottery number to be drafted
was No. 195. From then on, those assigned numbers more than 200
were considered safe. Those with numbers less than 100 had a good
chance of being declared ``men.'' The ``random sequence number'' on
my draft card is 74.
</P>
<P>
   I didn't know anyone my age who failed to register. Maybe we
thought Uncle Sam would find us if we didn't. Or that someone would
turn us in. Or maybe we were patriotic, even those who registered,
got their cards, then burned them.
</P>
<P>
   I wasn't bold enough to do that. At least, not until after I was
informed that no one from my crop of 18-year-olds would be drafted.
After that, the local draft board sent me an updated card. Leaving
me with two. I took my old card to a student rally and casually lit
it up. Like most young ``men'' in those days, I was hoping to
demonstrate the vehemence with which I opposed America's foreign
policy in a way that might impress college girls.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't work.
</P>
<P>
   The women must have sensed it wasn't outrage I was expressing,
but relief. And guilt - at least a little - for being luckier than
guys a year or two older. You'd think that would pass over time.
</P>
<P>
   At the Vietnam Veterans Memorial in Washington D.C., some
visitors leave behind objects. They've done so since the memorial
opened. The National Park Service has 80,000 objects in warehouses.
The number grows each year. Some have left letters or personal
notes. Military medals. Crosses. Teddy bears. A motorcycle was left
at the Wall once. And paintings. Sculpture. Cans of C-rations.
Flags. Even, I've been told, some draft cards.
</P>
<P>
   Reach Montini at Ed.Montini(a)ArizonaRepublic.com or (602)
444-8978.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-11-00 0803EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
