<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-11 08:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8755 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-R-LEVENDOSKY-COLUMN-N     07-11 1291
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-LEVENDOSKY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIVIDED HIGH COURT RENDERS INCONSISTENT RULINGS 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating for all needing.)  (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 (EDITOR'S NOTE: Charles Levendosky, editorial page editor of the
Casper (Wyo.) Star-Tribune, has a national reputation for
commentary on the U.S. Constitution. His email address is
levendos(AT-sign)trib.com.) 
By CHARLES LEVENDOSKY   
 c.2000 Casper (Wyo.) Star-Tribune   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the final week of its term, the U.S. Supreme Court released a
number of significant decisions that gives the public a peek into
the deep divisions within the court.
</P>
<P>
   On June 26, the high court ruled in Dickerson vs. U.S. that the
Miranda warnings outlined in its 1966 Miranda vs. Arizona decision
are ``concrete constitutional guidelines for law enforcement
agencies and courts to follow.''
</P>
<P>
   The question before the high court had been whether a law
concerning confessions passed by Congress two years after the 1966
Miranda decision would override the court's requirement that law
enforcement officials must read the Miranda warnings to those in
custody before interrogating them.
</P>
<P>
   The court emphasized that the Miranda warnings are a
constitutional rule to help enforce the Fifth Amendment's
prohibition that ``No person ... shall be compelled in any criminal
case to be a witness against himself.''
</P>
<P>
   The court further stated that ``Congress may not legislatively
supersede our decisions interpreting and applying the
Constitution.'' Therefore, the right to remain silent remains
intact as a constitutional principle.
</P>
<P>
   The 7-2 decision was written by Chief Justice William Rehnquist,
who has been a frequent critic of the Miranda decision and has
written a number of high court decisions that narrowed the
application of the Miranda warnings. He acknowledged the exceptions
the high court has made to Miranda, but asserts in the decision
simply that ``no constitutional rule is immutable.''
</P>
<P>
   Justice Antonin Scalia wrote a stinging dissent, which Justice
Clarence Thomas joined, that accuses the high court of exercising
``immense and frightening antidemocratic power'' and ``judicial
arrogance'' that reaches beyond the bounds of the U.S.
Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Scalia and Thomas would have Miranda warnings scattered to the
winds because they don't believe the high court's interpretation of
the Fifth Amendment can override the majority vote of Congress in
passing legislation to the contrary.
</P>
<P>
   Scalia expressed his dislike of the court's decision by making
an argument based upon separation of powers and the limited powers
of the federal courts; however, one should not be fooled by this
argument. In their dissent, both he and Thomas assert that the high
court cannot create rules of constitutional status that help
interpret and enforce fundamental rights found in the Constitution.
Basically, that assertion is pure nonsense.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court has created many constitutional rules on how
best to interpret a particular right. For instance, the high court
has in the past announced a rule on how to determine whether
government has violated the Establishment Clause and involved
itself impermissibly with religion (the Lemon rule); it also
announced a rule on how to determine whether printed material is
legally obscene or not (the Miller rule).
</P>
<P>
   And neither Scalia nor Thomas have been shy in telling Congress
it has overstepped its bounds in passing laws that oppose the
Supreme Court's interpretation of the Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Both justices voted in the court majority that struck down civil
rights legislation passed by Congress that allows victims of
sexually motivated violence to sue their attackers in federal
court. In a May 15 decision (U.S. vs. Morrison) written by
Rehnquist, the high court said Congress had exceeded its powers
under the Commerce Clause and the Fourteenth Amendment.
</P>
<P>
   And Scalia and Thomas dissented in the June 28 Stenberg vs.
Carhart decision. The 5-4 majority on the court struck down
Nebraska's law that prohibits late-term abortions, even if the
health of the woman is at risk. Neither Scalia nor Thomas found the
preservation of the health of a pregnant woman convincing enough
reason to overrule Nebraska's law.
</P>
<P>
   In the Boy Scouts of America vs. Dale decision on June 28, the
high court ignored its own previous rulings regarding exclusion
based upon gender. Rehnquist delivered the opinion for the 5-4
majority which included Scalia and Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   The Boy Scouts of America doesn't want to be forced to admit
homosexuals into its membership. A New Jersey law prohibits
discrimination on the basis of sexual orientation in places of
public accommodation. The Supreme Court of New Jersey found that
the Boy Scouts violated the state's public accommodation law by
revoking Dale's membership based upon his avowed homosexuality. The
Boy Scouts of America appealed.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, the U.S. Supreme Court forced the Jaycees to open
its national membership organization to women because it violated
the Minnesota Human Rights Act (Roberts vs. U.S. Jaycees, 1984). In
1987, a unanimous high court forced a Rotary Club to open its
membership to women (Board of Directors of Rotary International vs.
Rotary Club of Duarte) because it violated a California law that
prohibits businesses from discriminating based on gender.
</P>
<P>
   A year later, the high court forced the New York State Club
Association, Inc. to open its membership to women based upon a New
York City law that prohibits discrimination by clubs with more than
400 members.
</P>
<P>
   In each case, the court ruled that the organizations' right of
association must give way to the more compelling state interest
that prohibits gender discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   By what rationale did the high court distinguish the Boy Scouts
case from the other discrimination cases? It didn't.
</P>
<P>
   The court, instead, focused on the Boy Scouts of America's free
speech rights. Rehnquist wrote that ``a state requirement that the
Boy Scouts retain Dale as an assistant scoutmaster would
significantly burden the organization's right to oppose or disfavor
homosexual conduct. The state interests embodied in New Jersey's
public accommodations law do not justify such a severe intrusion on
the Boy Scouts' right to freedom of expressive association. That
being the case, we hold that the First Amendment prohibits the
State from imposing such a requirement through the application of
its public accommodation law.''
</P>
<P>
   The Boy Scouts of America contends that it teaches young boys
who are Scouts that homosexuality is immoral and, therefore, it
would violate its shared goals and values to admit homosexuals as
members.
</P>
<P>
   However, as Justice John Paul Stevens points out his dissent,
the Scoutmaster Handbook (1992) directs Scout leaders to refer all
questions about sexual matters to the boy's parents, religious
leader or school.
</P>
<P>
   And, indeed, until this case the Boy Scouts of America had made
no public statement about finding homosexuality immoral.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, this activist high court felt free to ignore its
past rulings and New Jersey's anti-discrimination law.
</P>
<P>
   This court, with its ultraconservative triad of Rehnquist,
Scalia and Thomas who are occasionally joined by Justices Sandra
Day O'Connor and Anthony Kennedy, has no center. Its decisions
bounce from case to case _ often depending upon the swing votes of
O'Connor and Kennedy _ so that in the same sphere of issues, the
court may rule one way on Tuesday and rule another way on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Over time, the result of a divided court is a body of decisions
that are unclear in their meaning and intent. And that hurts
everyone _ the people, law enforcement officials, lower courts,
legislators and, again, the people.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-11-00 0804EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000711.0040 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-11 09:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
