u f BC-TECH-VENTURE-BOS &LR;      07-11 0875
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-VENTURE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE NEXT WAVE: ORDERING TELECOM SERVICES ONLINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BETH HEALY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Fresh off his last success _ the $275 million sale of Epicon to
Nortel Networks _ Steven Domenikos is attracting substantial
backers for his new venture, TeleGea.com. The Waltham, Mass.
start-up makes software to help big telecom companies sell their
services on the Internet, something giants like AT&AMP;T and WorldCom
are talking a lot about doing these days.
</P>
<P>
   TeleGea.com has landed $42 million in its third venture round.
Financiers include Investor AB, a Swedish company with a big
investment in Ericcson; Ray Stata, cofounder and chairman of
Norwood chip maker Analog Devices; and others.
</P>
<P>
   Ordering telecom services online is the next wave, industry
analysts say. They predict individuals and businesses will buy
everything from simple home phone service and Internet connections
to wireless services over the Web, and will set up conference calls
that way as well.
</P>
<P>
   Says Rob Rich, a senior analyst at the Yankee Group in Boston:
``This is really the year, we think, of e-commerce for
telecommunications services.'' Virtually every major telecom
company, he notes, told Yankee in a recent survey that they were
launching e-business strategies in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The phone companies are jumping on this concept, because they
save money on salespeople and mall stores when customers buy
direct. The question is how they'll handle the Web channel.
</P>
<P>
   TeleGea's model is to license software to telecom players _ a
market of about 5,000 companies, Domenikos says _ for an annual fee
that starts around $100,000 and can reach into the millions. It
already has a few customers, including rewardcall.com. It's named a
WorldCom executive to its board.
</P>
<P>
   Domenikos sees this sort of telecom exchange working a little
like cash machines. A consumer or a business can do one-stop
shopping on the Web for virtually every phone or wireless need. The
telecom companies, he says, ``have a huge need to automate their
ability to deliver these services in a more streamlined way.''
</P>
<P>
   There are plenty of companies angling for a piece of this
market. Some big phone carriers are working to come up with answers
internally. And hordes of outsiders are proposing a variety of ways
to create telecom ``superstores'' on the Web. One TeleGea rival
that's taking a software approach is Cygent.com in San Francisco,
Yankee Group says.
</P>
<P>
   Domenikos has the benefit of his Epicon track record behind him.
In that venture, he was an early player in the application service
provider business, selling software programs that businesses access
via the Web instead of running in-house. The biggest investor in
Epicon, he saw the Chelmsford, Mass. company's value triple in the
five months before it was acquired in June. TeleGea is 14 months
old.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hiring has become a nearly full-time preoccupation of venture
capitalists. And it's not so much for their own firms as for their
portfolio companies.
</P>
<P>
   In a step that's become common on the West Coast, Bessemer
Venture Partners has acquired Lexington Partners, the Boston
recruiting and human resources consulting firm. It's essentially a
three-year-old, one-woman show, run by Judy Sundue, who's spent the
past 20 years helping tech firms hire thousands of engineers,
consultants, and top executives.
</P>
<P>
   Bessemer managing partner Rob Soni says he's been trying to get
Sundue to partner up with his firm more formally for ages. He calls
her ``the best recruiting person in North America,'' citing, for
one, her hiring of about 800 people a year for Sybase during its
boom years in the mid-1990s. She's done lots of hiring and HR
consulting for Bessemer in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Bessemer tapped two additional recruiters on
the West Coast for the new unit, called Bessemer Search Group.
</P>
<P>
   Hiring, Soni says, ``is absolutely a huge problem for all of us.
Microsoft and Cisco have the same problem.'' The venture firms
aren't staffing up and running ads for their portfolio companies to
be nice. They're doing it to protect their investments, of course.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'll go to a board meeting,'' Soni says. ``You'll say,
`Where are we on this issue?' And they simply haven't gotten to
it.'' The VCs have to help start-ups bring in bodies _ at all
levels _ or the business plans they bet big money on can't get off
the ground.
</P>
<P>
   John Hoagland, a venture and tech recruiter at Pendleton James
Associates in Boston, says his firm only began to focus on this
sector three years ago. Now the demand is huge. And in this
economy, it's tough to fill jobs given the flood of new companies
sprouting up.
</P>
<P>
   CEO searches are the toughest, Hoagland says. The best
candidates are looking for top companies, top technology, big-name
investors, and a location they like.
</P>
<P>
   With all of the start-ups out there, he says, ``You've got
people sitting in CEO seats right now who really don't belong
there.'' He adds: ``If you're working with top-flight investors who
expect top-flight talent, it's a thin market.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Beth Healy is a member of the Globe staff. She can be reached by
e-mail at bhealy(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-11-00 0913EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
