<DOCNO> NYT20000711.0041 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-11 09:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8763 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-TECH-FOREIGN-ART-BOS &LR;      07-11 0770
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-FOREIGN-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 NET LETS FIRMS HIRE WORKERS WHO TOIL A WORLD AWAY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX PHAM  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Work for a Silicon Valley company without
leaving the comforts of your home _ be it in Boston or Bombay!
</P>
<P>
   While lawmakers in Washington, D.C., wrestle over how many
immigration visas to hand out to foreign workers to alleviate a
crushing shortage of technical talent in the United States, the
invisible hand of the market is forging its own solution, with a
little help from the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Firms such as HotDispatch, HelloBrain, Guru.com, WebPRN, and
eLance are connecting companies with scarce labor. That, in itself,
isn't unusual. What's new is that the workers are often thousands
of miles away from employers. Many of them have never met their
employers, and some don't even know who they're working for.
</P>
<P>
   Take Ben Ruedlinger, a 24-year-old graduate student at the
Massachusetts Institute of Technology who has completed four
projects that were posted on HelloBrain's Web site. Ruedlinger
estimates he makes an average of $50 an hour on these projects,
which range from writing a computer screen saver to helping to
develop ``smart appliances,'' such as stoves that sense when a pot
is boiling. Most companies pay by the project, which can range in
remuneration from several hundred dollars to several hundred
thousand dollars each.
</P>
<P>
   But the experience has a strange Mission Impossible feel to it
because Ruedlinger has no idea who he's worked for. He's also
signed confidentiality agreements that prevent him from discussing
these projects in detail. The idea is that firms don't want to tip
their hand to competitors. This has become increasingly common as
companies come to rely on outside talent to get projects done.
</P>
<P>
   Ruedlinger works from his South Boston home, but he could be
anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   Guru.com's chief executive, James Slavet, estimates that his San
Francisco company has ``gurus'' from 140 countries. HelloBrain's
engineers live in 83 countries from Malaysia to Russia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why wait in line for a visa and emigrate to San Jose when you
can help design the operating software for the next great Internet
router from your home in Delhi?'' said Bharat Sastri, CEO of
HelloBrain in Santa Clara. ``And the battle in the US Congress
about whether or not to grant more visas could fade away. The
Internet has created a world without geographic boundaries.''
</P>
<P>
   Fade, perhaps, but not disappear, industry executives argue.
Several hundred thousand information technology jobs in the United
States will go unfilled this year, according to Navi Radjou,
analyst with Forrester Research. The sheer volume of workers
needed, combined with the requirement for physical collaboration on
the most complex projects, means many jobs can not be farmed out
remotely.
</P>
<P>
   But some will be. Corporate spending on outsourcing services is
estimated to grow from $51 billion in 1998 to $81 billion in 2003,
according to International Data Corp. Much of that money will go
toward hiring technical talent such as Bogdan Putinica, a
24-year-old Romanian living in Bucharest.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is another way in which the Internet . . . is changing
our lives and the way we work as developers,'' said Putinica, who
has worked on two Internet projects posted on HelloBrain.
</P>
<P>
   This blurring of international boundaries, while positive for
companies, is raising tough policy questions about wage and labor
standards, said Scott McKay, director of development for
HotDispatch in Cambridge, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   ``People in India, the Philippines, or Russia are just as smart,
just as motivated, but they can work for one-fifth the wage,'' said
McKay. ``That presents some interesting legal and economic
issues.''
</P>
<P>
   What if a worker is from Cuba, with whom the United States has
no diplomatic relations? Or what if the worker is from a country
that doesn't have minimum wage laws? And will the outsourcing of
projects to workers in other countries displace jobs and suppress
wages here?
</P>
<P>
   Not all implications will be negative. Sastri of HelloBrain
believes the Net will allow international workers to get
well-paying jobs without having to uproot themselves, while host
countries such as the United States will not have to physically
accommodate these workers.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Alex Pham is a Globe reporter covering Silicon Valley. She can
be reached by e-mail at pham(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
