<HEADLINE>
WIRELESS: KEEP IT SHORT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER J. HOWE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Those new wireless ``family plans'' offered by AT&AMP;T, Cellular
One, Verizon and others _ where you and family members can share
minutes _ make sense financially only if your family doesn't gab a
lot, according to a new survey.
</P>
<P>
   Details differ by plan, of course. But Econ One, a wireless
research firm on Los Angeles, found that generally you will save
money compared to having individual accounts for every family user
only if each person in the family makes a total of about 150 to 300
minutes of calls a month.
</P>
<P>
   If Mom, Dad, Bubba, and Sis yack for 600 minutes apiece each
month, you'll probably save 10 to 45 percent by getting individual
accounts instead of a family plan, said Econ One's Charles Mahla.
But if most of your calls are free ones to family members on the
plan, the family plan probably makes sense.
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line: Scrutinize each plan and your own calling
habits before assuming a family ``bucket of minutes'' is really a
good deal.
</P>
<P>
   The same survey found Greater Boston continues to enjoy some of
the lowest wireless rates in the country, ranking 20th of 25 big
cities surveyed. Averaged across plans ranging from 30 to 600
monthly minutes, Boston cell phone users pay 4 to 12 percent less
than people in New York, Miami, Chicago, and San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The new ``Bluetooth'' wireless technology scheme has come,
offering us all sorts of services we probably never knew we wanted.
It lets us use our cell phones to buy a Coke from a vending machine
or change the channel on the TV set.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, though, there's a Bluetooth-based service that might
make the world a better place: a system to make phones shut up in
places like movie theaters, convention halls, and churches.
</P>
<P>
   Start-up BlueLinx Inc. of Charlotte, N.C., has developed a
service called Q-Zone. It makes Bluetooth-enabled wireless phones
switch to a quieter ring or buzz mode inside a designated ``quiet
node.'' It's coming to market next year, but will only hush up
newer phones with the Bluetooth system built in.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A new ``Portrait of America'' poll by Rasmussen Research offers
another antidote to the wireless Web hypestorm.
</P>
<P>
   When 1,000 Americans were asked whether they could envision
themselves using a wireless phone, Palm Pilot, or pager to get
news, sports scores, and stock quotes, 58 percent said no and only
28 percent said yes. Another 14 percent said they were not sure.
But among those interested, 58 percent said they would take the
phones on vacation to keep getting their wireless stream of
factoids.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
