<HEADLINE>
TEXTRON HOPES MASSAGING SEAT SITS WELL WITH CAR MAKERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROSS KERBER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MANCHESTER N.H. _ If the vibrating bed wasn't enough, get ready
for the massaging car seat.
</P>
<P>
   The product is developed by Textron Inc.'s McCord Winn
auto-parts division, which says two car makers have signed up to
offer the seats on 2002 models.
</P>
<P>
   When switched on, the seat operates via a pump that inflates and
deflates up to 10 small air bladders just behind and below the
driver.
</P>
<P>
   A test ride in a leather sample chair in a company conference
room felt like several kneading hands to the lumbar region. Textron
says it can configure the chair to soothe the thighs as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty subtle,'' says Scott Moran, a director of
strategic planning at the company. But when the company loans out
sample chairs to test engineers, he says, ``they're really hard to
get back.''
</P>
<P>
   Textron has already sold thousands of an earlier version of the
seat to Cadillac, BMW, and DaimlerChrysler.
</P>
<P>
   The Cadillac versions, a $1,000 option, adjust automatically via
sensors that sample the pressure in each air bladder, then conform
them to a driver's specific weight and girth. The measuring chip is
sensitive to within a fraction of a pound per square inch _ enough
to lower one side of the seat to account for a driver's wallet.
</P>
<P>
   Other designs are adjusted through switches. All of the chairs
help drivers stay more comfortable, and thus more alert, said
marketing manager Ryan Weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Textron won't identify the car makers planning to use the
massaging feature. In addition to Cadillac, Textron provides seat
designs to BMW and DaimlerChysler, and to seat-suppliers like
Johnson Controls.
</P>
<P>
   The seat business is only a small product line for Rhode
Island-based Textron, whose properties range from Cessna Aircraft
and Bell Helicopter to lawn care machinery and motion-control
systems.
</P>
<P>
   Revenue last year was $11.5 billion; the company had income from
continuing operations of $623 million. Automotive parts accounted
for 25 percent of its business last year.
</P>
<P>
   Textron's stock has fallen 22 percent since January, analysts
say partly on concerns the company remains too dependent on
cyclical orders from auto makers. Even boosters like Sanford C.
Bernstein analyst Lisa Shalett rank the company only ``market
perform,'' though in a recent report she wrote the automotive unit
``should prove resilient to cyclical downshifts.''
</P>
<P>
   Textron says its auto-related businesses still offer plenty of
upside. One possibility: supplying Cessna Aircraft with luxury
insides. ``It doesn't make sense for a pilot to step out of a
$60,000 car and into an airplane with a really basic interior,''
says Textron spokeswoman Susan Bishop.
</P>
<P>
   Textron also has developed a ventilated seat, which blows hot or
cool air behind a driver. The total market for the high-tech seats
in Europe and North America is worth around $350 million, Textron
estimates.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ross Kerber is a member of the Globe staff. He can be reached by
e-mail at kerber(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
