<SLUG> BC-LIZ-CLAIBORNE-INTERVIEW-FAIRCHILD-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIZ'S WILDLIFE LESSONS  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by clients of ``HIGH STYLE AND MORE.''
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, see end of text. 
 &HT;    
 By ERIC WILSON 
 From W magazine) 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
 &HT;    NEW YORK _ While Liz Claiborne _ the company _ has grown into a
$2.8 billion apparel giant over the past 10 years, to the point
that someone buys a product created by the company five times every
second, Liz Claiborne _ the woman _ hasn't really thought about
clothes much more than five times in the entire decade.
 &HT;    She's been more concerned with the fate of elephants in Myanmar,
fish and eagles in Madagascar and European brown bears in the
Carpathian Mountains of Romania, among a roster of other wildlife
conservancy issues, all of which she and her husband and business
mentor, Art Ortenberg, have championed since they willfully
divorced themselves from the apparel industry 11 years ago to
pursue adventures in the West.
 &HT;    It would hardly be fair to call the couple's retirement an
inactive one, yet to most of the industry, having heard hardly a
peep from the designer since she left, the idea of Liz Claiborne as
a person has simply faded into a legend behind what has become one
of fashion's most powerful corporations.
 &HT;    The persona issue is one that Liz Claiborne, the woman, has had
to deal with, as well.
 &HT;    ``Today, it doesn't really mean that much to me,'' she said
recently, breezing into the offices of the Liz Claiborne and Art
Ortenberg Foundation, located 15 stories above the Liz Claiborne
flagship on Fifth Avenue.
 &HT;    ``It's another part of me that isn't at the front of my
awareness these days,'' she said. ``When I'm in Montana and someone
comes up to me and says, 'Aren't you Liz Claiborne?' it takes me a
second to realize what they are asking.''
 &HT;    Claiborne is 71 and looks nearly the same as she did when she
retired. She is tan and wears a black T-shirt and pants, a white
Liz Claiborne jeans jacket and big, red Liz Claiborne glasses, all
of them kept from her days at the helm of the company.
 &HT;    The only thing not Liz Claiborne about her is a white Polo Sport
cap, which she wears to mask the result of chemotherapy treatments
for a rare cancer that affects the lining between the abdomen and
the reproductive organs, with which she was diagnosed three years
ago.
 &HT;    She is near the end of her treatments and doing well, Claiborne
said, and recently accepted the Council of Fashion Designers of
America's Humanitarian Award for the work she and Ortenberg have
done through their foundation.
 &HT;    The foundation devotes a substantial portion of its funds to
Third World countries, supporting more than 50 conservation
programs in the United States, Africa, Asia and Central and South
America.
 &HT;    To a large degree, Claiborne is still fed up with a number of
things about the fashion industry. Always outspoken during her
career, Claiborne often complained about women's roles in the
industry and department-store chargebacks, and during this
interview last week, she made it clear that her view of the
industry has not necessarily improved with age:
 &HT;    
 &HT;     QUESTION:  What have you been up to for the past decade?
 &HT;     LIZ CLAIBORNE:  We happened to have been enjoying the benefits
of having been in the fashion industry, meaning monetarily, and
enjoying our lives. We're very involved in the foundation. We have
ranches in Montana, and then we have a house in St. Barths.
 &HT;    We hadn't planned Montana. We had planned the West. Art had felt
it would be nice to have a place out West, and I couldn't have
agreed more _ I'd always loved horses. Art's assistant at the time
was helping to plan a trip to Canada and she had subscribed to a
magazine called the Hideaway Report. She said, ``On your way to
Canada, why don't you stop off, because it sounds like the kind of
place you'd like.''
 &HT;    And yes, we never got to Canada. We stayed there and we bought a
lodge that took in paying guests. We discovered it was for sale and
we bought it, almost on the spot, after four days. It was perfect
for us. We love Montana because it's different than other areas of
the West, such as Colorado and New Mexico, that are very populated
areas. Montana is tiny.
 &HT;    
 &HT;     Q:  Have you maintained any connections to the fashion
industry?
 &HT;     A:  Not at all, except for friends. When we left, we left.
 &HT;    I gather the industry is very different today. It's not as much
fun. It's harder and everything is concentrated. I know I
complained about it then, but I'll complain about it today. The
stores are overstocked. It's hard to find individual looking
things. There's quite a sameness going on, but I guess that always
existed. I'm sure 10 or 15 years ago, I'd be saying the same thing.
 &HT;    But I gather from some of my old friends that it's not as much
fun as it used to be. There was at least some discussion of style
then and what really is important from a fashion point of view for
the department store. Today, I gather, it is all the bottom line.
 &HT;    
 &HT;     Q:  How does it feel to be Liz Claiborne today?
 &HT;     A:  Honestly, it feels pretty good. We did achieve a wonderful
company and what we have been able to do with the money we made out
of that company is something Art and I are both very proud of and
will continue to be proud of as it goes further. I'm 71 and I feel
pretty good.
 &HT;    
 &HT;     Q:  Do you feel women's roles in fashion have changed?
 &HT;     A:  I feel that hasn't really happened, except for a few
exceptions _ and one really publicized one _ and certainly at the
company, referring to Liz Claiborne, it hasn't really happened.
 &HT;    There is a glass ceiling. All the top echelon of people who
really make the decisions are male, but the second string is a very
open position for women. I still feel the minute it comes to real
heavy business types of decisions encompassing a whole company or a
whole department store, there are very few women who are in
control, except for Linda Wachner, who I was referring to earlier,
who's having her own problems, none of which have to do with being
female.
 &HT;    
 &HT;     Q:  How do you feel about that situation? (Calvin Klein sued
Wachner, his biggest licensee, last month, over what he called
trademark violations and breach of fiduciary duty. Wachner
countersued.)
 &HT;     A:  I have to say I'm really on Calvin's side. I can't help but
be on Calvin's side. In this country in particular, you have very
little control over your designer name once you have sold it or
licensed it.
 &HT;    
 &HT;     Q:  What do you find in stores today?
 &HT;     A:  I hate to name names, but I gravitate toward a few
designers, though I will shop at stores that are not department
stores.
 &HT;    I'll shop at the Banana Republic because they have some simple
things that I like. I shop at Ralph Lauren a lot these days. He has
a taste level and that all-American look, and I admire him for
being able to change while maintaining that taste level.
 &HT;    
 &HT;     Q:  When Liz Claiborne first started opening its own stores,
you said New York would not be an ideal location. Today, the
Claiborne flagship is downstairs.
 &HT;     A:  That was a coincidence. We were in this space before the
store was, and, as a matter of fact, we got a letter from the
gentleman who was the head of retail, apologizing and saying,
``You're not going to be happy about this, but we're moving in.''
 &HT;    
 &HT;     Q:  One of the greatest successes of Liz Claiborne during your
tenure was the creation of a line of clothing that women could wear
to the office _ career clothes. It's an interesting point where we
are today, when men and women alike are having a difficult time
understanding how to dress themselves casually for careers.
 &HT;     A:  I would think so. There were certain codes then, although
we never had a code. Although the company became known for career
dressing, it was never one of my principals going into business.
 &HT;    Having been a designer all my adult life, I didn't feel you had
to dress in this business suit as a woman and try to be competitive
with men in your dress. I felt you could dress in a much _ not
softer, but less tailored way _ and more colorfully.
 &HT;    We never really were an Evan Picone or a Jones in their navy
blue suits. I never was considered good at that, but I felt women
did want to look put together and should look put together at the
office, so what we tried to do was to pre-digest looks and put them
out so that they were highly understandable and they would put them
together the way they wanted to. They were never sold as units,
they were always sold as separates, but color coordinated, which
was one of the keys, and the way it was displayed was terribly
important, which is why today I say it is more difficult because
everything looks like a bargain basement, no matter what the price.
 &HT;    
 &HT;     Q:  When you started your business, did you ever think you
would be a star?
 &HT;     A:  No. It was at an event when I used to travel the country a
lot and do fashion shows and personal appearances. It had gotten to
the point they had scheduled me very tightly _ I had to do a
breakfast show, a luncheon show and fly to another city to do an
evening show. Once the plane was late getting to the other city,
something like an hour and a half, and I thought, ``Well they've
gone ahead with the show,'' and when I landed they greeted me and
said, ``If you can rush there, everybody is still waiting.''
 &HT;    I changed in the hotel room in about two seconds flat and went
out, and when I walked in that room, the applause. I still get
emotional about it, because it was the first time I realized it was
like being a star for a short while.
 &HT;    It was a great feeling, but it was a feeling also of
responsibility when you have women reacting that way and depending
on you. They were very quick also to write me when they didn't like
me. In one year, I got bombarded for a season when they didn't like
their clothes. They didn't buy them and they told me so, so you
realize that you've got to measure up.
 &HT;    
 &HT;     Q:  What do you think was the most important contribution you
have made to American fashion over the years?
 &HT;     A:  I think fashion and quality at a price, before it was
readily available. There were the designers, and then there was
what was called better sportswear, which was uptight stuff. There
wasn't much in between.
 &HT;    And responding to that woman out there. She wasn't a kid. She
was somebody who was working, whether she was a teacher or in a
business environment or a nurse, and somehow I had a rapport with
her and understood what she needed.
 &HT;    
 &HT;     Q:  You once said your parents were displeased when you told
them that you wanted to be a dress designer.
 &HT;     A:  Rather. My father was very old-fashioned, to the point
where I never went to school, because it wasn't mandatory in Europe
for a girl to go to school, particularly an American citizen.
(Claiborne grew up in Brussels.) He wanted me to be a painter.
 &HT;    
 &HT;     Q:  Once the company became successful, did he change his
opinion?
 &HT;     A:  I think he was proud of the success of the company, but he
wouldn't invest in it. He never told me so, but I'm sure he was
proud of me.
 &HT;    
 &HT;     Q:  How are you doing with your treatments?
 &HT;     A:  I'm at just about the end of it, but they still want me to
have a few more treatments, and it gets a little bit more difficult
as you get to the end, because your body has had so much, and it
takes a little bit longer to recuperate.
 &HT;    But I feel great and when I first heard I was going to have to
go through chemo, I thought, ``Oh my God, this is terrible,'' but
it's not that bad. It really is not, and I'd like to be able to
tell everybody that. So, you spend a bad day or two or three bad
days a month. Anybody can do that.
 &HT;    
 &HT;     Q:  Would you ever design again?
 &HT;     A:  I still love fashion, mind you, and I love clothes. I'll
never get over that, and thank God for the fashion industry, but
no, it's not for me anymore.
 &HT;    
 &HT;     Q:  Any other thoughts?
 &HT;     A:  It used to be very exciting to work in the fashion industry
from every point of view, and the business point of view as well,
because if you didn't sell, there was no point in being in
business. I think my biggest kick as a designer was seeing my
clothes walk down the street, and being able to recognize my
clothes on so many people. That was a big thrill.
 &HT;     c.2000 Fairchild Publications 
