A8885 &Cx1f; ttg-z
a k BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-N     07-11 0657
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ENVYING THE HAIRY WISDOM OF COCKROACHES
</HEADLINE>
  By DAVID GRIMES   
 Herald-Tribune, Sarasota, Fla.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   One of the things this column has
going for it, other than its superior absorbency, is its unwavering
commitment to bringing you, the squeamish reader, the latest news
on cockroaches.
<TEXT>
<P>
   In previous columns, I have suggested making the cockroach the
official Florida state bird and I have even passed along a
moneymaking scheme by which we can sell our abundant native
cockroaches to the Japanese for $70,000 a pop.
</P>
<P>
   I expect no praise or reward for this, just as I expect no
praise or reward for a column I wrote suggesting that people can
improve their mood by plunging their noses into the armpits of
elderly women.
</P>
<P>
   The latest cockroach news, reported by Reuters, is that
cockroaches can sense danger by the way wind ruffles tiny hairs on
their back legs.
</P>
<P>
   On the surface, this may not seem like important information.
How many of us, after all, really have the time or inclination to
chase after cockroaches with little battery-powered fans when a can
of Raid is just as effective and requires no running?
</P>
<P>
   The question is, how do cockroaches can tell the difference
between a good wind and a bad wind? A good wind, to a cockroach,
might be what comes from a crumb of Oreo just before it hits the
floor. A bad wind would be the breeze created by the heel of a
penny-loafer just before it sends the cockroach to that great Pest
Motel in the sky.
</P>
<P>
   That cockroaches are able to distinguish the difference is just
another example of how much smarter insects are than us. At this
very moment, the breeze from the air-conditioning vent is ruffling
the hairs on the back of my legs and I have no idea whether someone
is going to hand me a million dollars or smack me upside the head
with a baseball bat. All I know for certain is that my electric
bill is going to be high.
</P>
<P>
   Ultra-sensitive hairs on the back of our legs would certainly
save us from doing a lot of dumb things. Sitting through
back-to-back episodes of Greed: The Series is something that
springs immediately to mind. When the hairs on the back of your
legs stiffen like the quills on a porcupine, then you know the
Jerry Springer show is coming up next or, possibly, WWF Smackdown!,
though there are those who argue that the two shows are actually
the same.
</P>
<P>
   People would not buy cars like the Yugo or the Chevy Vega if
their leg hairs were as sensitive as a cockroach's. People wouldn't
wear copper bracelets or put magnets in their shoes, and the whole
body-piercing phenomenon would never have happened.
</P>
<P>
   With better-tuned leg hairs, no one would pay a restaurant $40
for a bottle of wine that can be purchased at the grocery store for
one quarter the price.
</P>
<P>
   Pokemon and Beanie Babies and $5-a-pack baseball cards would sit
on store shelves, collecting dust.
</P>
<P>
   The person who thought of hooking up cars to the Internet would
not be hailed as an innovator but would instead be fired for gross
stupidity.
</P>
<P>
   Builders who call $200,000 homes ``affordable housing'' would go
bankrupt overnight.
</P>
<P>
   People who see Christ's face in the stain on a side of a
building would be unable to pull on their pants due to their spiky
leg hairs.
</P>
<P>
   Even his most devoted fans would finally come to terms with the
fact that Elvis is really dead.
</P>
<P>
   One can only hope that advances in modern cockroach science will
continue and someday researchers will figure out a way to make
people's leg hairs as sensitive as a bug's.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, you could try gluing a couple of cockroaches to
your calves and see if that makes you any smarter.
</P>
<P>
   If you feel a breeze, don't be alarmed. It's probably just
somebody spritzing you with Raid.
</P>
<P>
   (David Grimes is a columnist for the Herald-Tribune in Sarasota,
Fla. The Herald-Tribune is a member of the New York Times Regional
Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
