<HEADER>
A8888 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-OSTEOPOROSIS-GRAPHIC1     07-11 0696
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSTEOPOROSIS-GRAPHIC11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    How to detect brittle bones
 &HT;    By Patricia Guthie
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Scans can predict, detect problems
</P>
<P>
   Just 10 years ago, detection and treatment of osteoporosis
wasn't done, because technology and drugs to deter the disorder
didn't exist. Today, doctors can see, treat, predict and prevent
the disease that is putting 28 million Americans at risk for
fractures and potential life-threatening complications.
Osteoporosis costs $38 million a day for hospital and nursing home
care. The first step to prevention or treatment is a bone scan.
</P>
<P>
   WHO SHOULD
</P>
<P>
   BE TESTED?
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Every woman entering menopause; women lose up to one-third of
their bone mass when estrogen declines.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Younger women who have several risk factors, such as
undergoing a hysterectomy with ovaries removed, family history of
osteoporosis, past or current smoking, small body frame, past
broken bone, or suffering anorexia at some point in their lives.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Older men who have suffered fractures, suffer from arthritis,
have a family history of osteoporosis, suffer low testosterone, or
have taken medication that reduces bone strength, such as cortisone
or anticonvulsants.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Tests should be repeated every couple of years.
</P>
<P>
   WHAT CAN A TEST DO?
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Detect low bone density.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Predict chances of a fracture.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Confirm a diagnosis of osteoporosis if a fracture already has
occurred.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Determine rate of bone loss if tests are conducted every few
years.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Monitor the effects of treatment.
</P>
<P>
   WHAT TYPE OF TESTING?
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Central machines measure bone mass in the hip, spine and total
body and are the most accurate; scans cost $200 to $300. These
tests, known as DXA or DEXA, are recommended for people who've
already experienced a fracture, for women under 50 who've undergone
surgical removal of the ovaries, or for women who are entering
menopause and have other risk factors. The test is also used to see
if bone density has improved with treatment.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Peripheral machines measure finger, wrist, heel or shin and
sometimes are used as a screening tool to determine whether more
expensive testing is needed; scans cost $50 to $100. They are
typically performed on men and women 65 or older who do not have
any osteoporosis risk factors. The machine is portable.
</P>
<P>
   WHAT HAPPENS
</P>
<P>
   IN SCREENING?
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Central scans: Patients lie face up on the table of the
machine fully clothed. A specialist operates the machine using a
computer and an armlike device that glides over the body, using a
low-dose X-ray. The largest weight-bearing bones in the body _
femur (thigh), pelvis and bottom five spinal vertebrae _ are
scanned. The scan takes 15 minutes. A computer program instantly
assesses the mass of the bones, then compares it to healthy
patients of the same age and ethnic group. A comparison is also
made to a healthy younger person. After the scan, a radiologist
interprets the findings, and patients typically find out results
from their doctor.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Peripheral scans: A heel scan is most common. The patient sits
and removes sock or stocking from the nondominant foot; it is
positioned in the machine with an ankle brace. Gel is put on both
sides of the heel, where two soft rubber pads are placed.
Ultrasound waves move through the heel and measure bone density.
Results instantly appear on a computerized window and are recorded
by the technician.
</P>
<P>
   WHAT DO
</P>
<P>
   DOCTORS RECOMMEND?
</P>
<P>
   Depending on scan results, a patient may be told to:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Eat a diet rich in calcium and vitamin D, or take calcium and
vitamin D supplements. Calcium intake should be 1,000 to 1,200
milligrams per day.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Engage in weight-bearing exercise, such as walking or lifting
weights, which helps build bones.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Quit smoking; limit alcohol intake.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Take drugs to treat or prevent osteoporosis.
</P>
<P>
   Sources: National Institutes of Health, National Osteoporosis
Foundation, Piedmont Rheumatology Consultants, Emory Osteoporosis
and Bone Health Program; research by staff writer Patricia Guthrie.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
