<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ADVISORY-NEWHOUSE </SLUG>
  
 (Attention editors: this advisory describes the top offerings from
Newhouse News Service for Tuesday, July 11. For information about
purchasing articles as a ``separate-buy, contact Debra Weydert of
the New York Times Syndicate at 1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697;
e-mail: weyded(at)nytimes.com.)
<TEXT>
<P>
   NO-WHINE-NEWHOUSE _ Riding the new century's technological
innovation and economic expansion is an ethic of individual
initiative and accountability, expressed with the hipness and
attitude of youth. And in a land where Jerry Springer is a minor
deity and the culture of complaint, alibi and blame so strong that
a conservative commentator once dubbed us a Nation of Victims, such
personal responsibility is bracingly refreshing. Photos. About
1,900 words.
</P>
<P>
   SHARK-CANCERCURE-NEWHOUSE _ Andrew J. Lane finds himself in the
crossfire of separate federal regulations. He markets shark
cartilage tablets as a dietary supplement under the natural dietary
supplement law that allows nontraditional products to be sold over
the counter without federal approval. But his claim that the
supplement is a cure for cancer places his product in conflict with
the law governing pharmaceuticals that requires rigorous scientific
data and Food and Drug Administration certification. About 1,000
words.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-11-00 1133EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000711.0074 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-11 12:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8896 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-MISSISSIPPI-BLUES-HNS     07-11 0998
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MISSISSIPPI-BLUES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     MISSISSIPPI MUD BROTHERS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MICHAEL D. CLARK  
 &HT;     c.2000 Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Embracing the state of Mississippi is like rooting for the
Cleveland Indians or championing eight-track tapes: You'll never be
accused of being a fair-weather fan or jumping on the bandwagon.
</P>
<P>
   Often noted for high unemployment and poverty and low
educational achievement, the Magnolia State has an image problem
that often overshadows one of its most prominent and enduring
exports: the American music created in the North Mississippi hills.
</P>
<P>
   In another couple of decades, the acoustic blues of R.L.
Burnside, Mississippi Fred McDowell, Junior Kimbrough and Othar
Turner could be lost forever. But brothers Luther and Cody
Dickinson of the band North Mississippi Allstars have taken it upon
themselves not to let that happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Delta blues, urban blues and early Chicago stuff? Those were
eras ago,'' Luther said by phone from a tour stop. ``The
(Mississippi) hill country is a contemporary phenomenon. Othar is
still throwing picnics, and Burnside is still cooking.''
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to Luther, 27, and Cody, 24, the old-timers may have a
legacy they never imagined. With their first album, Shake Hands
With Shorty, the North Mississippi Allstars have electrified and
modernized the music of their in-state influences. The project has
fused several generations of artists into a musical style that
should be hailed as the counterpart to southern Mississippi Delta
blues.
</P>
<P>
   The album features technological makeovers of songs by McDowell
and Burnside invigorated with looping to help bring the music to a
younger audience. Preservation of the tin-roof beats and hardwood
stomps that created the songs was essential. Still, purists might
say it's a bastardized form of the original art. The original
artists, however, appear to approve and have taken the Dickinson
boys under their wings.
</P>
<P>
   The band has been touring for several years, but its current
U.S. tour may be its first significant cultural exchange with the
rest of America. There is not much room on rock radio for a couple
of white kids updating a black musical tradition. But since Shake
Hands With Shorty was released in May, the North Mississippi
Allstars have been hailed by critics from publications as diverse
as Rolling Stone and the New York Times.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the accolades spring from the Allstars' interpretive
abilities.
</P>
<P>
   But it's the brothers' excavation of _ and reverence for _ the
music and musicians that warm others. In taking on the music of the
hills, the band has created a unique blend of Los Angeles
techno-sheen, college folk noodling and retro muddy blues licks.
The Allstars have become the next generation of storytellers and
lobbyists for a way of life fast being forgotten.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mississippi is God's country,'' Luther Dickinson said, adding
that he's never felt out of place as a white kid playing from a
predominantly black musical tradition. ``It's very harmonious, and
the music brings us together. People who have never lived an
integrated lifestyle shouldn't talk. I'll defend it to anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Born in Fayette County, Tenn., guitarist and vocalist Luther and
drummer Cody grew up listening to Van Halen and Black Flag and
formed punk bands with such names as Pigs in Space and DDT.
</P>
<P>
   The turning point in Luther's musical education occurred after
the family moved to Mississippi when he was a teen. Luther soon met
and played informally with Othar Turner, a 92-year-old
fife-and-drum man.
</P>
<P>
   They started by listening to recordings of Turner stamping out
acoustic Mississippi blues in the 1920s and '30s. The old musician
hypnotized Luther with stories about the music's roots.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually Luther started accompanying Turner on guitar. As
Mississippi and Delta blues are often performed in a solo format,
it was a great honor to be asked to sit in.
</P>
<P>
   ``Othar is a first-generation bluesman. He's a farmer, a
connoisseur of bootleg whiskey and a womanizer. He's a link to the
past,'' said Luther, who now sits in on jam sessions with the old
master at his home. ``He's got this real rhythmic groove a
trancelike rolling groove.''
</P>
<P>
   Through Turner, the Dickinsons learned of McDowell, whose many
songs include You've Got to Move, later refurbished by the Rolling
Stones.
</P>
<P>
   McDowell died in 1972. They also developed a relationship with
Burnside, a blues legend of the same era as Muddy Waters and John
Lee Hooker.
</P>
<P>
   None of the old bluesmen has toured with the North Mississippi
Allstars, which makes the band's name a misnomer. The boys concede
it's a bit tongue-in-cheek, especially when they are touring with
only a core band in which they are joined by bassist Chris Chew.
</P>
<P>
   The Allstars label is more of a collective name that covers
second-generation Mississippi blues players who often tour with the
band and who played on Shake Hands With Shorty. These include
Burnside's adopted son, guitarist Kenny Brown, and kin Garry
Burnside on bass and Cedric Burnside on drums. The album is
enhanced by the piano of East Memphis Slim and the guitar of Alvin
Youngblood Hart.
</P>
<P>
   To see who the Allstars are on any given night, Luther Dickinson
said, you have to be at the show. New friends and collaborators
could be part of the future. The Allstars have been working on a
project with the Jon Spencer Blues Explosion, and Luther recently
played and produced on a solo effort by Jimbo Mathus of the
Squirrel Nut Zippers.
</P>
<P>
   When there is some downtime at home, it is often spent jamming
at R.L.
</P>
<P>
   Burnside's juke joint or Turner's farm near the hill town of
Holly Springs, just down the road from the Dickinson house. This is
an area where Luther and Cody Dickinson would one day like to build
their own juke joint, a place where they have vowed to keep a
residence.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people here are playing their blood and families' music,''
Luther said. ``We just lucked into it. ''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
