<DOCNO> NYT20000711.0075 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-11 12:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8897 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-TV-JUDGES-HNS &LR;      07-11 0299
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-JUDGES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     NO ORDER IN THE TELEVISION COURT 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARK McGUIRE  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ Syndicated shows used to be primarily if not
solely reruns and game shows, that second genre still holding the
Nos. 1 and 2 spots with ``Wheel of Fortune'' and ``Jeopardy!''
</P>
<P>
   Then talk shows took over, and everyone who could stroll a
studio audience riser while speaking into a microphone at the same
time was given a shot. Thank you, Phil Donahue, thank you.
</P>
<P>
   Now most talk shows are tanking _ Ricki, Sally, Jerry, Montel
and Sally Jessy all saw their ratings drop _ as the next new king
of syndication bringing things to order.
</P>
<P>
   If you are sick of ``Judge Judy'' and ``Judge Joe Brown'' and
the rest of the courtroom shows, there's some bad news coming: Here
comes the judge. And another judge. And another.
</P>
<P>
   ``Judge Hatchett,'' ``Curtis Court,'' ``Moral Court,'' ``Power
of Attorney'' and ``Arrest and Trial'' (more of reality show) are
joining the roster of television jurists.
</P>
<P>
   This doesn't even count Laura Schlessinger, who delivers moral
judgments on a daily basis.
</P>
<P>
   ``Court (shows) has worked as a genre,'' Jay Isabella, director
of programming for syndicated show buyer TeleRep, said at a
gathering of New York broadcasters in Bolton Landing last month.
``You have to give ``Judge Judy'' credit: She took it to new
heights.''
</P>
<P>
   The question now is whether the glut of court shows will start
to cancel on another out, just as the majority of talk shows
blurred into background noise.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Mark McGuire is the television and radio writer for the Albany
Times Union, P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212. His electronic mail
address is mmcguire(at)timesunion.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
