<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-11 12:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8898 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-OSTEOPOROSIS11-COX     07-11 1061
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSTEOPOROSIS11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    New screenings and drugs are helping fight the bone-robbing
ravages of osteoporosis
 &HT;    By Patricia Guthrie
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Every morning, Barbara Wenzel gets a dose of preventative
medicine at the A.G. Rhodes Retirement Home.
</P>
<P>
   There, on the shady patio of the Emory University geriatric
center, she visits her 98-year-old mother, Katherine Wenzel, or
``Mama'' as she's affectionately called by her only child, the
nurses and other residents.
</P>
<P>
   Katherine is mentally alert and has ``the strong heart of a
teenager,'' says her attentive 66-year-old daughter. If not for a
disease that quietly eroded her bones for decades, Katherine would
still be in her Decatur home of 40 years with Barbara and their
cat, Missy.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it weren't for this danged osteoporosis, Mama would still
be out kicking up her heels, wouldn't you, Mama?'' Barbara asks,
gently arranging her mother's pink bow. ``Oh, we'd go to the
movies, the beach, wedding receptions, conventions for my work,
we'd do everything together.''
</P>
<P>
   While the diagnosis of osteoporosis came too late for Katherine
_ too late to prevent a broken hip, too late to prevent her right
leg from fracturing in four places until it now lies limp and
useless, and too late to keep her spine from developing the
telltale forward-bending stoop called a dowager's hump _ it's not
too late for her daughter.
</P>
<P>
   Both women take calcium supplements and Fosamax, a drug that
slows down bone loss. It's the first of several
osteoporosis-fighting medications that is making a big difference
for a generation of women who watched the painful disease rob their
mothers of height, health and vitality.
</P>
<P>
   Family history is the biggest risk factor, and the biggest
predictor of osteoporosis, experts say. But new screening and drugs
can now prevent the disease, even in women who have inherited ``bad
bones.''
</P>
<P>
   Under treatment by Dr. Nelson Watts, director of the Emory
Clinic Osteoporosis Program, Katherine's bone mass has improved,
but the damage to her spine, hip and leg can't be undone.
</P>
<P>
   When first X-rayed, Barbara's bones were progressing into
osteoporosis. Just recently, they've have improved to
``borderline'' brittle, but not before a small slip five years ago
resulted in a broken leg.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank goodness for modern medicine,'' Barbara said one recent
morning as she wheeled her mother back to her room. ``Or this could
have been my future, too.''
</P>
<P>
   In medical terms, osteoporosis is the disease resulting from
reduced bone density that leads to increased susceptibility of
fractures.
</P>
<P>
   In everyday terms, it is your elderly aunt or grandmother who is
in the hospital again from a broken hip.
</P>
<P>
   And it could be you, especially if you are a slender or
small-framed white woman past menopause, the profile of the person
most at risk for developing osteoporosis.
</P>
<P>
   Over a lifetime, osteoporosis will lead to broken bones in one
in two women, and one in eight men, according to the National
Institutes of Health.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every year, there are 1.5 million fractures due to
osteoporosis,'' said Watts. ``If you add up all the cases of heart
attacks, stroke and breast cancer, it's still less than the number
of osteoporosis fractures.''
</P>
<P>
   That could have enormous implications in the next few years as
43 million American women reach menopause, when osteoporosis
usually begins.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole goal is to figure out who's at high risk and to get
them treatment to prevent it,'' said Dr. Felicia Cosman, medical
director for the National Osteoporosis Foundation, and an
endocrinologist with Helen Hayes Hospital in West Haverstraw, N.Y.
``If we start implementing it, we could make a big impact. If not,
it's going to be very expensive for us in another 10 to 20 years if
we don't reach these people and treat it.''
</P>
<P>
   Men are not immune from getting osteoporosis but their risk is
lower because their bones are 20 percent to 30 percent more dense
than a woman's. They also do not lose estrogen, which is the
biggest bone-thinning culprit of women. It's not uncommon for a
woman to lose one-third of her bone mass during menopause. By age
80, some women may have lost 50 percent of their bone mass.
</P>
<P>
   Although osteoporosis affects all ethnic and racial groups, it
largely strikes white and Asian women because their bone structure
is the least dense. White women 65 or older have twice the
incidence of fractures as African-American women.
</P>
<P>
   Across the nation, 10 million people already have the disease
and 18 million more have low bone mass, 80 percent of them women.
And like Katherine Wenzel, they and their doctors may not even know
it until the damage is done.
</P>
<P>
   For many, the first indication of the disease is too late _ when
a small fall or bump results in a fracture or a collapsed vertebra.
</P>
<P>
   ``Osteoporosis is a silent crippler, that's why it's so
important to get screened for it,'' said Dr. Kimberly Wilson of
Piedmont Rheumatology Consultants. ``It's an epidemic in our
country. But we can detect it and we can even predict the future of
its course. Most importantly, we can treat it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're starting to look at recommending bone density screening
just like we do mammograms.'' Wilson said. Screening costs are
covered by Medicare and most health insurance plans. The word is
getting around, as evidenced by the backed-up bone-scan
appointments at Piedmont Hospital. The tests are generally ordered
by a primary care doctor or a specialist.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I started working here two years ago, I saw about six
patients a day,'' said Pauline Merz, a Piedmont radiologic
technologist who specializes in the field called bone densitometry.
``Now, I see between 18 to 20 patients a day, and there's a
three-month waiting list.''
</P>
<P>
   Many more women might benefit from bone screening. While older
white women are the usual victims, it can affect younger women,
especially if they've suffered an eating disorder, and young men if
they have other underlying medical conditions, such as low
testosterone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Osteoporosis is an equal opportunity disorder,'' Watts
cautioned. ``I have many patients in my practice that are men, and
I have black women. Nobody is immune from it.''
</P>
<P>
   Patricia Guthrie writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
