<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-11 12:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8899 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-OSTEOPROSIS-DRUGS11-C     07-11 0297
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSTEOPROSIS-DRUGS11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WHAT DRUGS ARE AVAILABLE?
 &HT;    By Patricia Guthrie
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   These drugs rebuild bone density and prevent further bone loss:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Fosamax: Acts like glue to help rebuild the bone by binding
osteoclasts, the cells that break down bone. This drug, called a
bisphosphonate, shows a remarkable 50 percent reduction in spine
and hip fractures after three years. Benefits begin in the first
year and increase in the second and third years.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Actonel: The newest drug approved. It's similar to Fosomax but
also helps with glucocorticoid-induced osteoporosis (from arthritis
medications) in men and women.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Hormone replacement therapy: Slows bone loss in postmenopausal
women. A 50 percent reduction in spinal fractures is seen in women
taking HRT for three to five years; longer use continues to lower
the risk. Also reduces many of the symptoms of menopause and may
lower heart disease risk, but may raise risks of breast cancer.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Evista: Helps restore estrogen and bone loss. It's the first
drug known as selective estrogen receptor modulators (SERMS)
approved for osteoporosis. It's an alternative to hormone
replacement therapy, but it doesn't relieve hot flashes or other
menopausal discomforts. Study participants, however, experienced
lower incidence of breast cancer at the same time their risk of
fractures decreased by 30 percent to 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Calcitonin: A hormone that reduces bone-dissolving activity.
It's usually recommended for those who can't take the above
medications, because it's not as effective. But it does relieve
back pain from spinal fractures. It's taken as a nasal spray or
injection.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
