<HEADER>
A8927 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-BOOK-REVIEW-MYSTERIES     07-11 0847
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-REVIEW-MYSTERIES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     ACTION REACHES THE BOILING POINT IN `HOT SPRINGS' 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By BOBBIE HESS  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ In ``Point of Impact,'' ``Black Light'' and
``Time to Hunt,'' Stephen Hunter created the unforgettable
character Bob Lee Swagger, a Vietnam veteran and master sniper.
</P>
<P>
   Now Hunter goes back to 1946 and introduces Earl Swagger, Bob
Lee's father, in ``Hot Springs'' (Simon &AMP; Schuster, $25, 474
pages). A survivor of the war in the Pacific, Earl is haunted by
the memory of the men he led in battle who never returned. He also
carries the emotional scars left by his abusive and drunken father,
whose actions caused his younger brother Bobby Lee to commit
suicide.
</P>
<P>
   Retired from the Marine Corps, Swagger is now working in a
lumber mill in his native Arkansas and is married to a beautiful
young woman he met while on leave to sell war bonds. His drinking
increases and he is slightly drunk when presented with the Medal of
Honor for his heroic actions at Iwo Jima. A suicidal Swagger gets a
reprieve when he is recruited to train an elite team of law
officers whose sole purpose will be to rid Hot Springs, Ark., of
its gambling dens and whorehouses. He will work with the legendary
D.A. Parker, a retired FBI agent who ended the careers of many
well-known gangsters.
</P>
<P>
   Hot Springs is run by Owney Maddox, who grew up on the mean
streets of New York. Hot Springs is a favorite vacation spot of
movie stars and gangsters alike. One day when Swagger and Parker
are on a scouting trip of the town, Swagger has a run in with Bugsy
Siegel. Maddox watched the confrontation and tries to hunt down the
man who knocked Siegel down. After a series of successful raids by
Swagger's team, Maddox hires a lethal crew to take out the raiders.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hot Springs'' is a richly told tale driven by complex
characters, strong dialogue and a unique plot. Hunter imbues
Swagger with great courage, a sense of decency and loyalty. He
deftly fleshes out a real man as Swagger comes to terms with his
past and his fear of impending fatherhood. Hunter is one of the
best storytellers of his generation and he just keeps getting
better.
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   ``Listen to the Silence.'' By Marcia Muller. Mysterious Press.
$23.95. 289 pages.
</P>
<P>
   Sharon McCone owns her own detective agency and has a great
relationship with her significant other. Her best friend has just
gotten married at a house in Sea Cliff. Life is nearly perfect
until McCone gets a call from her brother John telling her that
their father had just died.
</P>
<P>
   She flies to San Diego for the funeral and to take care of her
father's personal effects. Going through boxes of papers she finds
a folder that contains her birth certificate and to her horror, her
adoption papers. Her brothers and sisters had teased her when she
was little because she didn't look like them. But her parents
always said she took after her great-grandmother, who was a
Shoshone Indian. McCone confronts her mother, who refuses to tell
her why she was adopted.
</P>
<P>
   Enraged and deeply hurt, McCone begins a investigation to find
out who her birth parents were. The search will take her to
Flathead Indian Reservation in Montana, where she will learn some
of her family's secrets. It will take her to Carmel, Calif., where
she will meet her birth father, then to Northern California, where
the real dangers of the past begin to cause present-day evil.
</P>
<P>
   The author Marcia Muller really brings out McCone's pain so that
readers can feel her devastation at having her whole life seem a
lie. She realistically unravels this intriguing tale, weaving
Indian culture to enrich the plot. A very satisfying mystery.
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   ``The Fifth Woman.'' By Henning Mankell. Translated from the
Swedish by Steven T. Murray. The New Press. $24.95. 425 pages.
</P>
<P>
   Mankell's 10th mystery featuring Swedish Police Detective Kurt
Wallander is one of the most intricate police investigations put to
paper.
</P>
<P>
   A woman in Ystad, Sweden, receives a letter from a police
officer in Africa informing her that her mother and four nuns have
been killed in a remote desert town.
</P>
<P>
   A year later, a retired car dealer who writes poems about birds
is found impaled on pungee sticks in a ditch near his home. Another
man is reported missing after he fails to board a plane to Nairobi
for an expedition to look at orchids. Days later, his emaciated
body is discovered tied to a tree. He had been strangled.
</P>
<P>
   Wallander is sure the murders are the work of a lone monster,
but there are few clues to link them. The killings had been well
planned and Wallander is sure he is hunting a very intelligent
madman.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Fifth Woman'' is hampered by over-attention to police
procedure. This is more detailed than a Tom Clancy techno-thriller.
However, Muller has created a very driven character in Wallander,
whose personal life is almost non-existent because of his obsession
with the murders. An original mystery that would be greatly
enhanced by some tighter editing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
