<HEADER>
A8938 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      07-11 0589
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     REDEMPTION FOR ALL BUT HOMOSEXUALS? 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ROB MORSE  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The images were powerful ones. There was the
frail Pope John Paul II asking clemency for prisoners, while brawny
prisoners in T-shirts served as altar boys, cried and kissed the
pontiff's ring.
</P>
<P>
   Then came the bad news in this year dedicated by the pope to
redemption and pardon.
</P>
<P>
   John Paul bitterly condemned gays for holding a festival and
parade in Rome the same year as the Roman Catholic Church's jubilee
year. The pope said the festival was an ``offense to Christian
values'' and that homosexual acts are ``contrary to natural law.''
</P>
<P>
   The pope asked clemency for felons who robbed, raped and killed,
yet gave none to gays for holding a parade? There's something very
wrong here.
</P>
<P>
   True forgiveness is hard even for the pope. You might even say
forgiveness is contrary to natural law.
</P>
<P>
   Vengeance, bitterness and jealousy come much more naturally. Why
else would Christian teachings spend so much time on the subject of
turning the other cheek and forgiving those who trespass against
us?
</P>
<P>
   It's easy to forgive those who haven't trespassed against us
directly, such as felons who robbed or beat up someone else. Here
we must give the pope credit, because he publicly forgave the man
who shot him.
</P>
<P>
   Why not forgive gays? Is a perceived insult, a parade, so much
worse than a bullet?
</P>
<P>
   John Paul went on to say that homosexuals should not be
subjected to ``unjust discrimination,'' but should be treated with
``respect, compassion, delicacy.''
</P>
<P>
   Why? You guessed it. Because homosexuality is a disorder.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the pope put it more scientifically than that, saying
homosexuality is ``objectively disordered.''
</P>
<P>
   The church has rethought its positions on Galileo and even
Darwin, but it's odd to me that the pope is defending its position
on homosexuality with scientific sounding phrases.
</P>
<P>
   As a lapsed Episcopalian, I don't know much about Catholic
doctrine. But I have one simple question: If homosexuality is
against natural laws, then what is celibacy?
</P>
<P>
   Homosexuality occurs in nature in significant percentages, while
celibacy does not. At least it didn't occur very much in nature in
my neighborhood when I was young.
</P>
<P>
   Even when celibacy is demanded of priests, it seems that many
are unable to maintain it.
</P>
<P>
   Homosexuality seems a particularly sore subject with the
Vatican, much more so than it is with ordinary people, who tolerate
gay marches and don't think about whether their gay or lesbian
cousins are objectively disordered.
</P>
<P>
   The laity does not protest too much, but the hierarchy does.
</P>
<P>
   As an admirer of the pope's intellect, courage and kindness
toward the poor, I was moved by his prisoners mass, and heartened
to see his generosity toward them in a year he has dedicated to
redemption and pardon.
</P>
<P>
   Then he proceeded to show how difficult it can be to forgive and
love one's neighbors. I can forgive him. But if I were gay or
Catholic, I don't think I could.
</P>
<P>
   We could expect better from a great man like Pope John Paul II,
and that's the sad part. He could have forgiven the felons and
forgotten the gay parade at the very least.
</P>
<P>
   If the pope can't overcome human laws of petty bitterness, then
who are we to be infallible?
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
