<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-11 13:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8940 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-SPORTS-VIOLENCE-BOS &LR;      07-11 1621
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPORTS-VIOLENCE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE PLAYERS IN A RINKSIDE TRAGEDY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOANNA WEISS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   READING, Mass. _ They were two strangers with uncannily similar
lives, similar triumphs over rough-and-tumble pasts, similar
reputations as devoted dads.
</P>
<P>
   Both lived in neat suburban homes with white flowers in the
yards and hockey sticks propped against the walls. They rounded up
neighborhood kids for street hockey games, and tended to be calm
and quiet when they watched their own children play.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, what drew Thomas Junta, 42, and Michael Costin, 40,
into a fight last week _ a fight so brutal that it has become a
national symbol of rage _ was this unlikely fact: The boys playing
hockey at the Burbank Ice Arena were getting too rough.
</P>
<P>
   It's a common problem, parents say, at loosely organized ``stick
practices'' on summer afternoons. The more advanced kids start
checking, and the less-skilled kids wind up crying and bruised.
Junta sat in the stands, watching his 10-year-old son skate, and
worried that things were getting dangerous. So he called down to
Costin, the father who was overseeing the game.
</P>
<P>
   In so many words, Junta told Costin to take control of the ice.
In so many words, Costin told Junta that everything was fine. And
within minutes, an argument over limiting the violence erupted into
a brutal fight, spilling from the ice to the hallway to the floor
beside the vending machines. That's where police found Costin, his
face battered past recognition, lying in blood.
</P>
<P>
   How a request to keep the peace ended up this way, with one man
dead and another charged with manslaughter, is a mystery. The
incident has become Exhibit A in the coast-to-coast lament over
youth sports, zealous parents, and a culture of rage.
</P>
<P>
   But as Junta turned himself in to police Monday, and friends and
relatives prepared for Costin's funeral, a larger question
lingered: Was the tragedy last Wednesday an aberration _ a
testosterone-fueled error in judgment _ or sad proof that a violent
past is hard to overcome?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This year had marked a long-fought victory for Michael Costin:
He finally gained custody of all four of his children. It was a
triumph, it seems, over a checkered past. Because the Costin who
was buried Tuesday _ a quiet, churchgoing man who lived with his
mother and spent all of his time with his children _ seemed a far
cry from the man who wove in and out of the criminal-justice
system.
</P>
<P>
   A resident of Lynnfield for most of his life, Costin was about
15 when violence first struck close by. His brother, Dennis, 17,
was killed in his home of a stab wound to the heart. His father,
Augustine, 42 at the time, was convicted of manslaughter.
</P>
<P>
   It was a few years later that Michael Costin _ who grew to 5
feet 11 inches and 175 pounds _ began his own series of scrapes
with the law. According to the Massachusetts Criminal Offender
Registry, he went to prison seven times between 1983 and 1995, for
crimes that ranged from assaulting police officers to breaking and
entering with a loaded gun.
</P>
<P>
   In the midst of that turmoil, Costin married a woman from
Ireland. Their marriage split up a few years ago, said Augustine
Costin, who is now 67 and divorced from Costin's mother.
</P>
<P>
   Some of Costin's most recent legal troubles stemmed from a
conflict with his ex-wife, said Paul Dowling, who says he became
friends with Costin five years ago, when they attended Alcoholics
Anonymous meetings.
</P>
<P>
   Dowling said that Costin's children were living with their
mother when Costin staked out her house with a video camera. He was
trying to keep an eye on unsavory behavior he felt was taking place
in front of his children, Dowling said.
</P>
<P>
   Costin was arrested for breaking and entering and wound up in
prison for 15 months.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was trying to protect the kids,'' Dowling said. ``He loves
his kids more than anything. That's all he pretty much talks
about.''
</P>
<P>
   Friends and relatives agree that Costin's children were his
life. In recent years, Costin's two older sons, now 12 and 11, were
living with Augustine Costin, while the younger son and daughter,
10 and 9, lived with Michael and his mother. Costin worked
tirelessly to bring them all under one roof.
</P>
<P>
   The children were united in January, and since then Costin's
devotion to his family was all-consuming, said Gene Ellison, a
longtime friend. When Costin wasn't working _ he had a job laying
carpet _ he was organizing activities for the kids, or attending
their sporting events. One woman said she remembers seeing him at
hockey games, often with a child climbing over him happily.
</P>
<P>
   He would entertain his children's friends, as well, said
neighbors, who remember Costin piling kids into a teal Toyota
minivan and taking them miniature golfing, to the movies, or to the
mall.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, many of his most recent acquaintances knew Costin only
as the consummate single father.
</P>
<P>
   ``He turned his life around completely,'' said Cindy Sochat, a
mother whose children stayed at Costin's house, and sometimes went
to church with the Costin family.
</P>
<P>
   ``My son spent a lot of time with him,'' she said. ``I
completely entrusted my son to Michael, and even with all this
information about his past I still feel like I made the right
decision.''
</P>
<P>
   If Costin was a jovial, sometimes-goofy presence with children,
though, he was more reserved among the hockey-parent crowd. Though
he sometimes made small talk with mothers and fathers at sporting
events, he often stood alone, watching the games in silence, one
woman said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   That's exactly the way sports parents in Reading described
Thomas Junta, a 6-foot-2-inch, 275-pound truck driver who was a
regular at his children's hockey games, baseball games, and swim
meets.
</P>
<P>
   In a town that rumbles with enthusiasm for sports, the Juntas
seemed a model famly. Junta's wife, Michelle, coached Reading kids
in swimming, and last year helped to organize a girls ice hockey
team for Reading High School. His daughter, 16, is a star hockey
player on that team. His son, 10, plays a variety of sports.
</P>
<P>
   And Thomas Junta, by many accounts, was a devoted father who
cheered them on without frustration, and was quick with an
encouraging word for other children.
</P>
<P>
   As a teenager and young man growing up in Boston's Charlestown
section, where he played football for Charlestown High, Junta had
his share of run-ins with police.
</P>
<P>
   Records in Charlestown District Court indicate that in March
1975, Junta allegedly broke into a Metropolitan District Commission
skating rink in Charlestown and did $3,300 in damage. Age 17 at the
time, he was charged with willful and malicious destruction of
property. He was later found not guilty.
</P>
<P>
   The incident came three months after he had been sentenced to a
one-year jail term on a charge of using a vehicle without the
authority of the owner. Junta appealed the decision, but court
records do not indicate what became of the appeal or whether he
served time.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors Monday said Junta was also charged with assault and
battery in 1992. There was no finding in the case.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years Junta's record has been clean, so much so that a
judge decided to release him Monday on $5,000 cash bail. And people
who know him in Reading, where he has been a truck driver for 13
years, describe him as well-mannered and calm, a generous man who
took other children under his wing.
</P>
<P>
   Junta's next-door neighbor, who would not provide her name, said
local children would congregate in front of his house for impromptu
games, or climb into his truck for a ride to hockey practice.
</P>
<P>
   Another friend from Reading, who asked to remain anonymous, said
he met Junta on a trip to New York, accompanying a swim team. As
other parents unpacked their bags, the man said, Junta sat quietly
in a hotel hallway, playing catch with somebody else's son.
</P>
<P>
   At hockey games, too, Junta often stood alone, said another
Reading man, who also asked not to be identified. Sometimes, he
would quietly compliment other children's playing, the man said.
Other times, parents wouldn't even realize he was there.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Though Junta and Costin seemed to stay calm, many parents
concede that violence at sporting events is hardly rare. At the
Burbank Ice Rink, which hummed with games and activity on Sunday,
parents told stories of being thrown out of games themselves, or
coaching in the face of a horde of screaming grown-ups.
</P>
<P>
   Sports have become a huge commitment, in terms of money and
time, said Dan O'Brien, who accompanied his son to the rink. In the
face of that investment, he said, parents' emotions can often get
the best of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there's a parent in the stands who's been at
some sort of hockey game that can't relate to that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   When parents lose their temper, though, O'Brien said, they're
usually surrounded by friends _ people who can calm them down and
talk them back to reality. There seemed to be nobody in that role
last Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   There were no inner voices, either. If strength of character
helped both Junta and Costin grow into their roles as model dads,
it didn't help them regain self-control this time.
</P>
<P>
   Now, their relatives and friends are left to wonder: Why didn't
they just walk away?
</P>
<P>
   ``Almost every day, I think, our feelings change,'' Gene Ellison
said. ``Going from frustration and being angry about this, to
bewilderment. How could something like this happen?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Raphael Lewis, Marcella Bombardieri, Scott S. Greenberger, and John
Ellement of the Globe staff, and correspondents Ieva Augstums and
Scott Helman contributed to this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
