<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-11 13:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8951 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-SCI-GENOME-ETHICS-BOS     07-11 1388
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-GENOME-ETHICS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCIENTISTS, ETHICISTS SEEK COMMON LANGUAGE OF NEW FRONTIER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL PAULSON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Suddenly, science seems to have found God.
</P>
<P>
   Flush with the victory of sorting out the basic language of the
human body, scientists and politicians have turned to the language
of faith in an effort to ascribe meaning to the human genome
project.
</P>
<P>
   In the process, biologists are challenging today's philosophers,
theologians, and ethicists with a variety of difficult questions.
Chief among them: What does it mean to be human if our fates are
determined by a sequence of genes?
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, society's moralizers, citing the lesson of the
Manhattan Project, in which the much-heralded discovery of fission
was used to make atomic bombs, are offering their own challenge to
science: How can one ensure that this newest scientific marvel will
be used to benefit, not harm, humanity?
</P>
<P>
   The rarefied worlds of metaphysics and morality have collided
with molecular biology, and a debate once taking place in academic
journals is being thrust into the public realm.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, crowing at a White House news conference last
week that scientists had completed the first survey of the entire
human genome, declared: ``Today, we are learning the language in
which God created life.''
</P>
<P>
   And Dr. Francis S. Collins, director of the National Human
Genome Research Institute, said, ``We have caught the first glimpse
of our own instruction book, previously known only to God.''
</P>
<P>
   Theologians argue that it is striking _ but not surprising _
when scientists invoke God to explain the complexity of human
biology.
</P>
<P>
   ``When human beings unlock such secrets, they get an appropriate
sense of awe, a sense that here they are in the presence of the
divine, and even the most secular scientists reach for language
that sounds theological at times like this because they have a
sense of the significance of what they're doing,'' said David P.
Gushee, a professor of Christian ethics at Union University in
Jackson, Tenn.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, many theologians are skeptical: Is this really the
language of God? Are God's secrets really being revealed?
</P>
<P>
   Fearful that scientific explanations for human development will
obfuscate crucial issues of morality, theologians are attempting to
inject caution into the euphoria of the moment.
</P>
<P>
   ``My advice is that this is no time to hyperventilate, either in
the panic of euphoria or in the panic of terror,'' said Daniel B.
McGee, a professor of ethics at Baylor University in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Debates over the theological and moral questions posed by the
genome project are already underway in a variety of forums,
encouraged by scientists who recognize the risks as well as
benefits of biotechnology, and by non-scientists who are flocking
to the burgeoning field of bioethics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to be teaching in the area of bioethics for the
first time next spring, and it's daunting because I'm not naturally
scientifically inclined,'' Gushee said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But you can't be a responsible 21st-century ethicist without
at least trying to weigh in on these issues.''
</P>
<P>
   The National Institutes of Health is already giving grants to
theologians and others who include religious perspectives in their
exploration of the implications of genetic research.
</P>
<P>
   And in classrooms around the country, professors are encouraging
students of philosophy and religion to begin grappling with the new
questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a textbook example of a philosophical tangle, and it's
intrinsically interesting,'' said Jonathan Westphal, an Idaho State
University philosophy professor who plans to take up the human
genome project with his Problems of Philosophy students at Harvard
Summer School this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``One always knew that genetics was a proper science, but the
detail and the power of it is confronting us in a sharper form,''
Westphal said.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to take the debate beyond universities, the
University of Vermont College of Medicine is hosting the nation's
only effort at a statewide conversation on the ethical issues posed
by the human genome project.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're absolutely convinced that public discussion of these
issues is essential,'' said Edward J. Mahoney, the Catholic
theologian who is co-director of Vermont's Community Genetics and
Ethics Project.
</P>
<P>
   Mahoney said Vermonters are grappling with two sets of issues
posed by the genome project: the potential for discrimination in
employment and insurance made possible by genetic profiling, and
the more abstract problem of how human beings will view one another
once genetic technology makes some diseases preventable for those
who have access to the new science.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happens to our attitudes with regard to what it means to
be human? To have a disease? To be well?'' Mahoney asked. ``There
is a danger in reducing our answers to the genes.''
</P>
<P>
   For philosophers and theologians, the primary question posed by
the human genome project is an updated version of the age-old
debate over free will.
</P>
<P>
   How much of our lives is determined by some combination of our
genes and our environment, and what room is left for divine action
or human choice?
</P>
<P>
   ``The code of life, the instruction book, the blueprint _ all
these are very misleading metaphors that seem to lead to the notion
that we're determined by our genes,'' said Phillip R. Sloan,
director of the University of Notre Dame's Program in Science,
Technology and Values.
</P>
<P>
   Sloan and other intellectuals say the more science reveals about
the role of genes in human lives, the more they need to think about
the role of human freedom.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm assuming genes do play a significant role in determining
every aspect of our humanity . . . to the very core of our
identity, our mood, our personality, and that's traditionally what
religious people have termed the soul,'' said the Rev. Ronald
Cole-Turner, a professor of theology and ethics at Pittsburgh
Theological Seminary.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we're really going to have to struggle to come to a mature
understanding which gives genes their proper place without making
them the high-tech version of fate. We are shaped and defined and
limited by our genes, but what we do with those capabilities is
entirely up to us,'' Cole-Turner said.
</P>
<P>
   Even as the religious and philosophical world gets worked up
over the question of free will, these thinkers are also posing
tough questions to the world of science about social justice,
values, and ethics.
</P>
<P>
   Who will have access to genetic technology? Where is the
boundary between using knowledge of genes to stop a disease and
using that same knowledge to create designer babies?
</P>
<P>
   In interviews, several said the Manhattan Project should serve
as a cautionary note about how science can be used in destructive
ways.
</P>
<P>
   ``We forget all the ways that human beings have used technology
to exploit one another and ruin their own lives,'' said the Rev.
Amy Laura Hall, a professor of theological ethics at Duke Divinity
School. ``If enough people could walk through the Holocaust Museum
and then read some of the stuff coming out on genomics, maybe that
would make a difference.''
</P>
<P>
   But few are willing to walk away from a technology that might
help cure disease.
</P>
<P>
   ``A number of people with religious dispositions are saying,
`Don't play God,' arguing that the bodies we have inherited . . .
are the ones God intended, and if you get in there with your
wrenches and screwdrivers, you're violating God's creation,'' said
the Rev. Theodore F. Peters, a professor of theology at Graduate
Theological Union in Berkeley, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   ``I find that utterly stupid. I don't think God had intended
that some kids are going to get stuck with a gene for cystic
fibrosis, and somehow it's immoral for us to go in there and try to
select it out.''
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line, theologians say, is that more conversations
need to take place before the knowledge about the human genome is
put to use.
</P>
<P>
   ``This raises ethical questions that science itself can't
solve,'' said Ian G. Barbour, a professor of physics and religion
at Carleton College in Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been given the power to understand and change the world,
but we must do it responsibly,'' Barbour said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
