NYT-07-11-00 1335EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000711.0083 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-11 13:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8953 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-WRONGFULLY-IMPRISONED     07-11 1095
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WRONGFULLY-IMPRISONED-ART-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 LESSONS BEHIND THE WALL 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DICK LEHR  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
(begin itals) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Going to prison for a crime that I did not commit is more
painful than death. I have decided that I must be strong, continue
to pray and that the truth will finally come out.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(end itals) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Donnell Johnson wrote those words in December 1995, in
a letter to his church from the prison cell, where he sat accused
of murdering a 9-year-old boy a few weeks earlier. The truth did
come out, when his conviction was overturned in late March.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting recently with his mother, Robin Johnson, in the kitchen
of her apartment, and, at another time, in his church in
Dorchester, he handles his letters for the first time since he
wrote them.
</P>
<P>
   Then 16, now 22, Johnson is mostly looking ahead these days.
He's working in the mail room of a local hospital. He has met a
girl he calls his ``special friend.'' In September, he'll head to
Mississippi Valley State University, one of several colleges that
have accepted him. His church, the Dorchester Temple Baptist
Church, has established a scholarship fund for him.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson entered prison as an unremarkable hanger-on, a Boston
gang wannabe of sorts, straddling two worlds _ the street and his
home, anchored by a churchgoing mother. Behind bars, he renewed his
faith, earned a high school diploma, read widely, and emerged
wanting to study psychology.
</P>
<P>
   His five-year prison stay, which took him from adolescence to
manhood, transformed him. It's a journey reflected in letters he
wrote to his mother and others. Now free, but with prison still
fresh in his mind, he's undergoing a thaw _ a period of slowly
coming out of himself, opening up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I picked this up when I was incarcerated,'' he says. ``I won't
call it loner, but I always, like, stayed by myself almost. Before,
I liked being around people. I think now, it's like I don't want to
step outside my comfort zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will change. Especially through prayer. It's like trying to
make yourself whole again, but it's not like a light switch that
you can switch back and forth.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
(begin itals) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just chilling in my room listening to music. I'm getting
sick of this place. I'm going insane in the membrane.''
</P>
<P>
   (To Aunt Dee, Jan. 26, 1995) &QL; 
 &QL; 
(end itals) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Though charged three months earlier with murder, Johnson uses
the sing-song line, borrowed from the rap group Cyprus Hill, as
part of his pose to appear cool, calm.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it had really hit me,'' he says. ``I thought I'd
be out of there.''
</P>
<P>
   No chance.
</P>
<P>
   It all began in 1994, when 9-year-old Jermaine Goffigan, playing
outside on Halloween night, was killed in a gang-related shooting.
Witnesses said one of the shooters was light-skinned and
freckle-faced, and the young Johnson fit the description. In less
than 24 hours, he was arrested. In 1996, he was convicted of
first-degree murder as a juvenile, and sentenced to serve 18 to 20
years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   From prison, however, the early letters are newsy, chatty,
upbeat, all printed in neat block letters on lined paper,
painstakingly copied, he says, from hurried and illegible
scribblings of ``what's on my mind.''
</P>
<P>
   ``So how life been treating you?'' Johnson asks his mother in a
letter in December 1994. He customizes lyrics of another song:
``You gave me life. You gave me all my hopes and dreams. Oh sweet
Mama. Now I realize all the joy you put inside of me. Oh, I miss
you. I really miss you.''
</P>
<P>
   The 16-year-old seemingly can't fathom how much worse it will
get. Surely, someone will come forward to clear him of the murder
charge. That's what friendship and loyalty are all about. ``The
street always knew the truth that I didn't do it,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   The naive expectation gave him attitude, so in an early letter
he could be flip, borrow the line ``insane in the membrane,'' to
refer to the monotony of the juvenile facility he figured he would
soon leave.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're mostly in one large room, 24-7. Same old faces every
day. Same routine,'' Johnson says as he puts the letter aside.
``It's like being in a casket but still living.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
(begin itals) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I was a fool hanging with the big boys breaking all the
rules. Sometimes I didn't listen to you and acted crazy . . . I
wish I can take the pain away and go back in time, so I can change
all my foolish mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   (To his mother, May, 10, 1995) &QL; 
 &QL; 
(end itals) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As he writes home on his first Mother's Day behind bars, the
early optimism has evaporated. In its place is a new tone of
self-reflection. No ``friend'' has come forward to say police have
arrested the wrong person. Police and prosecutors are satisfied
that the youth they describe as an up-and-comer in the Heath Street
is a cold-blooded ``child killer.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the time my perspective on life was starting to
change,'' Johnson says. ``I'd been fluctuating between two worlds,
and just hanging out with those guys sparked all this to happen.''
Police witnesses ``wouldn't even have had a picture of me'' to
identify as the killer, he began to realize, if he hadn't been
flirting with the street gang.
</P>
<P>
   His ``foolishness'' had also provided police with other material
to cast him as a killer. He'd been caught once in school with a
butcher knife. He'd gotten into a few fights. He'd even been
arrested in an unrelated street skirmish. The mistakes buried the
actual, mostly unremarkable life he'd led as the teenaged son of a
churchgoing woman.
</P>
<P>
   He started to see something else, too. The friends he had sought
in the gang were betraying him with their silence. He appealed to
them in one of his open letters to his church: ``Many teens know
who committed the murder but they are afraid to talk. I plead with
my friends. TELL THE TRUTH.''
</P>
<P>
   But the street remained mute. Rescue would come from within, not
without.
</P>
<P>
   ``You realize when your freedom is stripped from you there's a
lot more to life than sitting in jail,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   This time, when Johnson puts the letter down, he and his mother
exchange a glance. Robin Johnson is the first to speak.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I seen this letter, I knew he was the person I'd thought
he was,'' she says. ``It was very emotional for me. I knew that
everything I taught him was in there.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
