<HEADLINE>
UPPER CONNECTICUT RIVER VALLEY SHARES MUCH MORE THAN A BRIDGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILLIAM A. DAVIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CORNISH, N.H. _ The covered wooden bridge over the Connecticut
River linking Cornish with Windsor, Vt., is no ordinary upcountry
public works project.
</P>
<P>
   Built in 1866, by an unschooled but uncommonly skilled local
bridgewright named James Tasker, it is 450 feet long and the
longest such bridge in the country.
</P>
<P>
   At a bend in the river with an unobstructed view of Mount
Ascutney to the southwest, the bridge is probably the most
photographed, sketched, and painted object in a countryside that
doesn't lack for subjects. It is also a beloved emblem of the
region residents call the Upper Valley, a beautiful place where
people in two states share both a river and a common heritage of
artistry and craftsmanship.
</P>
<P>
   For the numerous writers and artists who summered and settled in
and around Cornish in the late 19th century, forming the colorful
creative community known as the Cornish Colony, the covered bridge
and view of Mount Ascutney were inspirational motifs. To the
artisans in the workshops and machine tool factories of Windsor,
however, the bridge was an example of the fine workmanship that
earned the area the nickname Precision Valley.
</P>
<P>
   The Cornish Colony included painters and illustrators such as
Maxfield Parrish and popular writers of the day like Winston
Churchill (the best-selling turn-of-the-20th-century American
novelist, not the British prime minister). The leading light was
Augustus Saint-Gaudens, the foremost American sculptor of his era.
Aspet, Saint-Gaudens's 150-acre Cornish estate off Route 12A, is
now a national historic park (603-675-2175, www.sgnhs.org).
</P>
<P>
   Sited on a hill overlooking the river with a superb view of
Ascutney, Aspet was a haven and source of inspiration for
Saint-Gaudens and his wife, Augusta. Until his death in 1907, it
was also the social center of the Cornish Colony.
</P>
<P>
   The national park includes the sculptor's preserved home with
original furnishings, his studio, an art gallery, elaborate
Victorian formal gardens, hiking trails, and bronze recasts of some
of Saint-Gaudens's most famous monumental sculptures.
</P>
<P>
   Sculptures are exhibited in Saint-Gaudens's old studios and
placed around the grounds. Some stand in outdoor ``rooms,''
landscaped enclosures walled with hedges. One of the best-known
pieces is the Civil War memorial to Colonel Robert Gould Shaw and
the men of the African-American 54th Massachusetts Volunteer
Regiment; the original stands at the State House in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Others include the once shocking nude Diana, goddess of the
hunt, that graced the top of the original Madison Square Garden
building in New York and was the first statue in America to be
illuminated at night. Also represented is the haunting Adams
Memorial, which depicts a hooded figure representing ``the mystery
of the hereafter.''
</P>
<P>
   There are frequent special exhibitions at Aspet and a summer
concert series Sundays at 2 p.m. on the estate lawn. The series
continues through Aug. 20.
</P>
<P>
   The private Cornish Colony Gallery and Museum (603-675-6000,
www.almagilbert.com), also on Route 12A, is in Mastlands, the
former riverside Cornish estate of Rose Standish Nichols, a colony
member and pioneer female landscape designer. Works by 20 Cornish
Colony artists are exhibited.
</P>
<P>
   Museum director Alma Gilbert is an art dealer specializing in
Maxfield Parrish, and he is given particular prominence. A standout
among the Parrish works on view is a large, colorful mural
depicting a Renaissance festival in which many of the figures were
modeled by colony members. Fine examples of Parrish's work can also
be seen in the Vermont National Bank in Windsor and in the town
hall of neighboring Plainfield, N.H.
</P>
<P>
   Windsor boasts that it is the birthplace of Vermont because it
was here that the first constitution of ``the free and independent
state of Vermont'' was adopted. The Main Street tavern where the
framers of the constitution met in 1777 is now the state-run Old
Constitution House Museum (802-828-3051) and has changing exhibits
on Vermont history.
</P>
<P>
   The town's contribution to the industrial revolution is recalled
down the street at the American Precision Museum (802-674-5781).
Housed in a handsome brick mid-19th-century former armory building,
the museum has the country's largest collection of historically
significant machine tools. This is more exciting than it sounds,
and among the objects of industrial precision currently on view are
several rare antique automobiles.
</P>
<P>
   Contemporary nonindustrial Vermont craftsmanship is well
displayed nearby at the Vermont State Crafts Center (802-674-6729)
on Main Street. The center features jewelry, weaving, pottery,
furniture, baskets, and prints.
</P>
<P>
   Windsor visitors can also watch glass blowers, potters, and
other artisans at work in the innovative See It Made industrial
park.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
