<HEADLINE>
`NUDE BUT NOT LEWD' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY MORRIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Should you bare it all? Think about it: Going without clothes
sure solves a packing problem.
</P>
<P>
   This week is the 25th annual Nude Recreation Week, featuring
open houses, concerts, and festivals nationwide at more than 230
clubs, resorts, and campgrounds throughout North America. There are
35 clubs on the East Coast.
</P>
<P>
   According to the American Association for Nude Recreation, nude
vacations are one of the fastest-growing segments of the travel
industry. ``This is the perfect opportunity for people who are
interested in experiencing nude recreation to visit a club in their
area,'' said Gregory Smith, president of the association. ``A wide
variety of fun activities are planned for this year, and there
really is something for everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Nude-recreation supporters are trying to communicate their credo
that ``nude is not lewd'' and that most options are couple- or
family-oriented. The nude association says two-thirds of clubgoers
are married couples and 92 percent are older than 35.
</P>
<P>
   Nudists say no-clothes vacations are great equalizers: Without
clothes, no one knows if you are rich or poor.
</P>
<P>
   For information on Nude Recreation Week, call 800-TRY-NUDE or
visit www.aanr.com. The association also produces the ``North
American Guide to Nude Recreation'' with information on
clothes-free vacations on land and sea, including resorts,
bed-and-breakfasts, and RV campgrounds.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Quilt festival &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The art of the quilt is alive and well. Testimony to this will
be found at the 24th annual Vermont Quilt Festival July 21-23 where
seven of the more than 400 entries will be by quilters under age
17. Quilters from 22 states and three Canadian provinces will have
their works on view on the Norwich University campus in Northfield.
``Many festivalgoers may not be quilters, but they surely are
aficionados once they leave,'' said Richard Cleveland, festival
director. Twenty-one of the entries are by Massachusetts residents.
The festival includes the sale and appraisals of quilts, workshops,
and evening programs. Hours are 9 a.m. to 5 p.m. and on July 23, 9
a.m. to 3 p.m. Admission for adults is $7; for seniors, $6; and
under 18, free. For information, call 802-485-7092. Also on the
Norwich campus will be the Vermont Hand Crafters 20th Annual
Festival of Vermont Crafts.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Lipizzans in Vermont &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Original Royal Lipizzan Stallions of Austria are again
performing in North Hero, Vt., through Aug. 20. The program is
under the direction of Colonial Ottomar Herrman, who as a boy
witnessed General George Patton's rescue of the Lipizzans and
return to Austria. Herrman brought the horses to America, where
they winter in Florida. The Herrman family summers in Vermont where
members offer performances Thursdays through Sundays. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Malta flights &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Malta Tourism Office reports twice-weekly direct flights to
Malta are being offered from New York through July. The 10th annual
Malta Jazz Festival will be July 21-23 and will feature Latin
performers. For information, call the Malta Tourism Office in New
Jersey at 973-884-0899. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Jellyfish on view &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   They have no eyes, no brain, no heart, and they can wield a
painful sting. And, if you head to the ocean, chances are you've
come across them _ jellyfish. The Aquarium of the Pacific in Long
Beach, Calif., has just opened a gallery dedicated to the more than
one dozen sea jellies, as they are properly known. These mysterious
creatures have survived for more than 650 years and can range in
size from smaller than a pencil eraser to larger than a basketball
court, and consist of 95 percent water. The exhibit explores all
the wonders of these creatures, which are found on both coasts, and
tells which jellyfish to look out for. Included is a Sting-O-Meter
where you can safely find out what different sea jelly stings might
feel like. For information, call 562-590-3100.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Art in Puerto Rico &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Puerto Rico, with a 500-year history of artistic life, has just
opened the Museo de Arte de Puerto Rico in San Juan. The opening
exhibition, ``Treasures of Puerto Rican Painting,'' showcases the
rich talent of Puerto Rican artists and will be on view through
January. More than 250 pieces of art are being shown, including
works by the island's most recognized artists, Campche and Rafael
Tufino. There is also a five-acre sculpture garden. For information
on Puerto Rico, call 800-866-7827 or visit www.prtourism &QC; 
.com. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Scenic highways &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Thirty roads in 20 states have been designated All-American
Roads or National Scenic Byways for 2000. US Transportation
Secretary Mortimer Downey said the roads provide visitors with a
unique driving experience and are considered destinations unto
themselves. Being designated All-American Roads helps preserve
these roads that have become American icons, Downey said. In New
England, the Acadia Byway in Maine was named an All-American Road,
and named National Scenic Byways were Connecticut State Route 169
and the Merritt Parkway; Old Canada Road, Rangely Lakes, and
Schoodic scenic byways in Maine; and the Kancamagus Highway in New
Hampshire. For information, visit www.byways.org or call
800-4-BYWAYS.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Potholes in the roads &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When you're on the road this summer, always read the fine print
and be a little skeptical when visiting historic sites, says James
W. Loewen, adjunct professor of sociology at The Catholic
University of America in Washington and author of ``Lies Across
America: What Our Historic Sites Get Wrong.'' Be wary, he says of
words such as ``traditional'' or ``according to.'' For example, he
notes that Lincoln's Birthplace Cabin in Hodgenville, Ky., was
actually built 30 years after Lincoln's death. ``The National Park
Service does not go out of its way to tell you the cabin is not
where Lincoln was born. In fact, signs tell tourists not to use
flash photography and risk damaging the logs,'' said Loewen. The
shriving and starving image of George Washington in Valley Forge is
also false, he says. In fact it was a mild winter, and ``the food
was monotonous but adequate.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Sea voyages &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   You've seen ``The Perfect Storm,'' now what? Visit the new
Mystic Seaport exhibit ``Voyages: Stories of America and the Sea,''
which offers a national perspective on the sea's role in defining
our national identity. Seven sections devoted to immigration,
foreign trade, recreation, inspiration, Navy life, fisheries, and
the nation's rivers feature interactive and hands-on exhibits, live
performances, and videos. The fisheries portion begins with the
start of the 500-year-old codfish industry and ends as Fred
Calabretta, one of the exhibit's creators, notes, ``modern
fishermen are as endangered as the wild aquatic species they
hunt.'' The display examines the unsolved problem of supply vs.
demand. Mystic Seaport is the nation's leading maritime museum with
a historic village and tall ships. It's just off Interstate 95 in
Mystic, Conn. For information, call 888-973-2767. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Plastic anniversary &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Did you realize that the term ``charge it'' is just 50 years
old? In 1950, a world without cash was inconceivable, but that's
when ``plastic'' was born. In 1949 Frank McNamara dined at a New
York restaurant only to find he had left behind his wallet. That
incident, which he managed to finesse, led to his developing the
Diners Club Card. When he returned to the restaurant in February
1950, he paid the bill with a small cardboard card _ a Diners Club
Card _ and signed for the purchase. In the credit card industry,
that event is known as the First Supper. The credit card concept
soon caught fire, including a movie, ``The Man from the Diners
Club,'' and by 1952 became the first international charge card.
This year, Diners Club earned its third successive Freddie Award
for Best Affinity Charge Card Program. Its Club Rewards offers
points that never expire and other services. For information, call
800-234-6377 or visit www.dinersclubus.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Icy stay &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   How would you like to stay in a hotel built of ice? Until now
the only place in the world where you could do so was Sweden. Now
the concept is coming to Quebec City. Planned to open in January
2001, the second ice hotel will offer a cinema, art galleries, a
chapel, sleeping accommodations for 100, and a bar where vodka will
be served on the rocks _ naturally.
</P>
<P>
   The hotel is planned to be open for three months each year and
then rebuilt the next winter. Accommodations are expected to be
about $100 a night.
</P>
