<HEADLINE>
`BIG DIG' PROCEEDS KEEP ON PILING UP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS C. PALMER JR.  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The Big Dig has certainly lived up to its name _ most
notoriously in its expanding pricetag. So it should come as no
surprise that it's growing in yet another area _ dirt.
</P>
<P>
   What was at its birth billed as a job requiring the excavation
of 10 million cubic yards of dirt and other material, a figure
later increased to 13 million or 14 million, is now forecast to
cough up at least a staggering 15 million cubic yards.
</P>
<P>
   That's enough to fill a football stadium 15 times. The average
garden wheelbarrow, by the way, hauls about 5 cubic feet _ or
roughly one-fifth of a cubic yard.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Barnett, the Central Artery/Ted Williams Tunnel's chief
``materials'' official, said the dirt has been coming out of the
ground faster and in greater quantities than his scientific
calculations had projected.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're at the peak,'' Barnett said in a recent interview
focusing on what's been taken out to make way for the Big Dig and
where it's gone. ``We've been at peak excavation rates for the last
six calendar quarters.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the higher volume of dirt pales in comparison with the
Big Dig's rising cost _ now pegged at $13.6 billion _ the dirt
overrun is emblematic of how the massive project has grown in scope
in unexpected and unpredictable ways.
</P>
<P>
   Big Dig officials say the dirt has gone so many places, with
removal expenses varying so widely, that it is impossible to
estimate the final cost of moving all that dirt.
</P>
<P>
   A major part of the dirt dilemma was resolved three years ago
when the Big Dig negotiated a contract with a developer to take as
much as 11 million cubic yards for Quarry Hills, a sprawling
project South of Boston that will bury a landfill to make way for a
golf course, four Little League fields and at least two soccer
fields.
</P>
<P>
   That piece of the dirt removal could cost about $100 million,
based on the $8 per ton the Big Dig pays to dump dirt at Quarry
Hills.
</P>
<P>
   A new park on Spectacle Island in Bosotn Harbor absorbed much
more dirt than Big Dig engineers originally thought it would.
</P>
<P>
   For the past 18 months, 1 million tons of dirt have been taken
out every three months, said Barnett, who carries around a fat
leather notebook filled with charts, lists of Big Dig contracts,
dirt storage sites, and possible dirt repositories.
</P>
<P>
   Dirt is an general label that includes soil, rocks, clay and
other material being taken from the ground, Barnett said.
</P>
<P>
   He also is armed with sundry formulas. Such as: A cubic foot of
sand weighs about 90 pounds, but a cubic foot of wet sand weighs
100 pounds. And: One cubic yard equals roughly 1.6 tons.
</P>
<P>
   That means what's coming out of the ground to make room for the
Ted Williams Tunnel and eight underground highway lanes through
downtown weighs an estimated 22 to 23 million tons.
</P>
<P>
   All that dirt requires the daily deployment of an armada of 400
to 500 dump trailers _ something many regular Southeast Expressway
commuters should be readily aware of.
</P>
<P>
   A standard ``tri-axle'' dump truck, which have three sets of
rear wheels, carries about 18 cubic yards.
</P>
<P>
   The peak dirt-hauling day was June 6, 1999 when Boston lost the
single greatest amount of weight in its long history.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Barnett said, approximately 13.5 million cubic yards
have been taken out of the ground, leaving another 1.5 million
cubic yards still to be scooped out.
</P>
<P>
   While nothing special to look at, the dirt does have interesting
historical and scientific significance.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the material being hauled out is termed ``historic
fill'' because it is being taken from what once were mudflats
surrounding the Shawmut Peninsula that were filled in to create the
modern city.
</P>
<P>
   And the dirt also includes till and clay deposited by retreating
glaciers thousands of years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Resembling the consistency of Silly Putty, the clay is dense,
slick grayish material, known as Boston Blue Clay. The clay and
till are widely used to cap or shape landfills.
</P>
<P>
   Other material coming out in smaller quantities includes debris
such as pilings and timbers, asphalt, and rock.
</P>
<P>
   A tiny but unanticipated amount of hazardous materials,
including dangerous PCBs, arsenic, chromium and certain leads, also
have popped out.
</P>
<P>
   To determine whether certain loads of dirt are suitable for
disposal in Massachusetts or must be shipped to out-of-state sites
that handle contaminated material, soil samples are taken at the
Big Dig site, Subaru Pier in South Boston, or at the dirt's final
destination.
</P>
<P>
   Barnett said the oddest contamination they have encountered is a
sizable chunk of land saturated with olive oil.
</P>
<P>
   An early plan to provide clay to some of the 82 communities
statewide looking to cap their landfill never materialized because
of scheduling, high transportation costs and the availability of
cheaper plastic.
</P>
<P>
   Still, some communities will reap the Big Dig's clay windfall.
</P>
<P>
   Modern Continental Construction Co., for example, is ferrying
about 500,000 tons of clay to suburban Melrose to be used as the
foundation for baseball fields in Mt. Hood Park.
</P>
<P>
   Though they have four years to figure it out, officials still
don't know what they will do the last million cubic yards of dirt
they expect to excavate in 2004.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have a definite location,'' Barnett said. ``But we
have some ideas.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
