<HEADER>
A8962 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-WRONGFULLY-ACCUSED-2N     07-11 0911
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WRONGFULLY-ACCUSED-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-ART-BOS  
 BOSTON: ... in there.''  
 
(begin itals) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Hi Sis! How are you doing and feeling? So you started school
already? I hope you do real well this year and make the family
proud. I know you might not believe me but school is very
important. Get all the knowledge you can, because there is a lot of
children in the world who is not fortunate to go to school.''
</P>
<P>
   (To sister Robin, Aug. 18, 1997) &QL; 
 &QL; 
(end itals) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When Johnson was arrested, he was a sophomore at East Boston
High School, an average but indifferent student. Now he was
educating himself. His body might be confined behind bars, but not
his mind.
</P>
<P>
   He began to read widely _ ``The Autobiography of Malcolm X,''
Claude Brown's ``Manchild in the Promised Land,'' books about the
South African leader Nelson Mandela. ``I didn't learn about my own
people in public school, but I learned it behind the wall,'' he
says. ``History had been my worst subject in school. I couldn't
stand it. Now, it's my favorite.''
</P>
<P>
   His interest took him beyond African-Americans, to books about
Italian and Jewish immigration to the US.United States. What he
learned gave him far more than the high school diploma he earned.
It gave him a worldview wider than the streets he'd left behind.
</P>
<P>
   ``The adversity that people went through _ that just gives you
motivation,'' he says. ``I was like feeding off this.''
</P>
<P>
   Not only was Johnson reading, but he was also writing. He joined
a poetry club _ ``10 of us and a teacher.'' Some of his ``love
stuff'' was printed as part of the workshop, but not the ``more
creative stuff'' written when he let his imagination and feelings
run free. ``I was worried it would be misunderstood,'' he recalls,
``and the district attorney was always looking for something
against me.''
</P>
<P>
   He told a friend of his mother's in early 1997 that he liked to
write ``to preoccupy my mind and to get some of the stress off my
chest.'' It was more than a distraction. ``I think I might be an
author on the side, when I'm not practicing law,'' Johnson wrote in
the Jan. 3, 1997, letter. ``I have all these ideas about story
after story, that is unbelievable.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
(begin itals) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to continue to put pressure on the District Attorney's
office and the Boston Police to pursue the real killers and to
release me. If I do not do it or speak out, who will? I will
definitely be forgotten, and I am not trying to go out like that.''
</P>
<P>
   (To a friend of his mother, Jan. 16, 1997) &QL; 
 &QL; 
(end itals) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Johnson's resolve to clear his name intensified last year when,
after his 21st birthday, he was transferred from the relative
safety of the juvenile facility to the state prison in Concord.
``Let me know who to watch my back for,'' he scribbled in a quick
letter to his mother on March 23, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I got to the adult thing, I could have got killed or
stabbed,'' he says, ``when I never should have been in there from
day one.''
</P>
<P>
   By the time he was moved to prison, he had changed. He was more
self-reliant, better educated. He'd rediscovered a faith he had
never thought much about before. His letters more frequently
acknowledged the support of his ``loving church family.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if you believe in God,'' he says. ``But God did
tell me. He reassured me I'd be home.''
</P>
<P>
   The break finally came last summer. Ralph C. Martin III, the
district attorney who'd always said Johnson was a killer, began to
reconsider his position when members of the Heath Street gang,
seeking leniency after being arrested on federal drug charges, told
investigators Johnson was innocent.
</P>
<P>
   With a new police inquiry underway, Johnson was released just
before Thanksgiving. Then, in late March, upon a motion from
Martin, Juvenile Court Judge Paul D. Lewis vacated Johnson's murder
conviction. Martin and the Boston police commissioner, Paul Evans,
publicly apologized and said new evidence had led to the dramatic
reversal of fortune.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't new evidence,'' Johnson says today, with traces of
lingering bitterness. Today, the prime suspects in the murder are
the ones Johnson, his lawyer and supporters cited all along to
police.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thank Ralph for doing what he did,'' Johnson says. ``He
stepped up like a man, you know. I know it was a hard thing to do.
But it's still kind of like, wow, you know, they were always
running away from the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   He's not writing as regularly as he was in prison, but he still
reads, though the subject matter has changed from history to
religion. ``Spiritual books. Biblical books. I get them from
friends. Family. I'm really looking forward to going to school.''
</P>
<P>
   Having fantasized in prison about studying law or becoming a
writer, Johnson, guided by his own remarkable journey, recently
decided to study psychology. ``I'm interested in how the mind
works,'' he says, ``and I want to help people, especially in
one-on-one situations.''
</P>
<P>
   To do that, he eventually wants to go back behind the walls.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe I went through that for nothing,'' he says.
``It's really disturbing to me, knowing some are innocent, and I
want to be a spokesman for the guys inside.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not saying I'm going to be militant against to the
government. I want to work with government. The point is you got to
help these people. I lived through it, my family lived through it,
and the reality is there are other innocent men and women in
jail.''
</P>
</TEXT>
