<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLIPHANT-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A GOOD SIGN FOR GORE THAT CAMPAIGN IS FINALLY UP AND RUNNING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS OLIPHANT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; WASHINGTON -- Give or take a formality, the Democratic
national convention began the other day _ upstairs at the White
House. The picture that summed it up had nothing directly to do
with Al Gore, who was off drawing distinctions with Republicans
that any Democrat can understand.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the picture had President Clinton surrounded by roughly
two dozen Chicago Daleys, as in Mayor Richard and brother Bill, who
has left the Commerce Department and Clinton's Cabinet, on his way
to Nashville and the levers of Gore's presidential campaign. That
would also include their still-formidable mother, widow of
Chicago's patriarch, Duh Mare.
</P>
<P>
   Gleeful politics was in the air. But the atmosphere was hardly
ideological; my partner in crime as writer in attendance was the
right's relentless tribune, Robert Novak, whose home base remains
The Chicago Sun-Times _ a reminder that with the Daleys this
business is more personal than substantive.
</P>
<P>
   Nor was the atmosphere triumphal. At this very early juncture in
an election, the best any grown-up Democrat can hope for is a
competitive, closely contested fight. But the tone was set by an
obviously relieved, happy, and now directly involved President
Clinton.In the president's view, Daley has already made a
difference since taking over the campaign, in two ways. The first
is his attitude that no grumpy Democrats should be on the sidelines
throwing darts, be they the unions guys still smarting over the
China trade vote or the longtime Gore pals shunted aside last year
by then-campaign chairman Tony Coelho. In a Daley effort, the tent
is big and loyalty counts; you want to help and you're in.
</P>
<P>
   Republican strategists point to Clinton's freshly invigorated
involvement as a sign of weakness, not unity, likely to enhance
Gore's vice presidential nonstatus. They have a point, but Clinton
is happy because he has a role, not the role. And he is especially
happy because his role pushing an agenda at a GOP Congress
complements the agenda Gore has stitched together over the last
year _ from taxes to education to health care.
</P>
<P>
   In the president's view, Gore has been helped significantly
below the radar screen since May by a series of TV commercials put
together by the Democratic National Committee, pushing that agenda
and Gore's views in 16 of the state's most likely to be the site of
hard-fought campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   This advertising, however, was not accompanied by a similarly
focused Gore out on the road. To put it mildly, he was all over the
lot, and it hurt. That is the second area where Daley has made his
presence known. A believer in clarity and simplicity, as well as
middle-class, working-family Democratic politics, Daley has helped
steer Gore's campaigning onto an ``I'm on your side'' track,
focusing his attack not so much on Governor George W. Bush as on
the business interests (oil, insurance, and drugs) and GOP
congressional leaders opposing his views, who are supporting Bush.
</P>
<P>
   More than anything, that is why the party's convention has in
effect begun. A running mate and happy gathering in Los Angeles
still count heavily, but more important is an effort to stitch
together the hydra-headed monster known as the Democratic Party
around an agenda that unites its presidential and congressional
wings.
</P>
<P>
   This is also the segment of the electorate whose misgivings more
than cover the gap between the vice president and Bush in polling
data, especially when the first-impression sentiments about Ralph
Nader are thrown in. In demographics as well, the slight Bush lead
is the result of better than typical impressions of a Republican
among women, the elderly and Hispanics.
</P>
<P>
   None of this is issue-based. The reverse appears true. Most soft
Bush supporters and undecided potential voters, while vaguely
liking the governor and just as vaguely looking for ``a change,''
also tend to be Democratic in voting habit, in general agreement
with Gore on Medicare, health care, and prescription drugs, and in
general disagreement with Bush on across-the-board income tax cuts.
Gender politics, moreover, awaits the handling of the abortion
issue in Bush's selection of a running mate and the treatment of
prochoice activists at the Republican convention.
</P>
<P>
   There is a Democratic case to be made, and what is different
lately is that Gore has been making it forcefully. There was fear
in top Democratic echelons a month ago that however early it is,
Bush might open a double-digit lead in the polls that would enhance
an aura of inevitability. This has happened before without an
elected president on the ballot _ in 1948 for Dewey over Truman, in
1952 for Eisenhower over Stevenson, in 1968 after the Republican
and Democratic conventions for Nixon over Humphrey, in 1976 for
Carter over Ford, and in 1988 for Dukakis over Bush's dad. That is
no reliable prediction of either the result or the point spread.
</P>
<P>
   So far that hasn't happened this year. The reason Democrats were
smiling at Daley's reception was that they are on the same page
again and that Gore is campaigning like a Democrat. That doesn't
appear to have won them much more than a chance to stay in the
game, but for Bill Daley it has been a solid few weeks running the
longest-running Democratic convention ever.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Oliphant is a Globe columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
