<SLUG> BC-MCGRORY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A HUMBLING ADVENTURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN MCGRORY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ I was in the middle of nowhere, on the edge of mankind
_ 6 miles down a gravel road through the same Montana mountain
range that Ted Kaczynski used to call home. Thoughts of Deliverance
kept echoing in my mind.
</P>
<P>
   I was in Marysville, a booming gold-rush community of 4,200
residents at the turn of the century, now a ghost town populated by
50 hearty individuals. The dance hall and grocery store still stand
on the dusty Main Street as they did 100 years ago, only now they
are abandoned, the ceilings collapsing among the remnants of the
more fortunate times left behind.
</P>
<P>
   I knocked on the door of a nearby house, hoping to ask why
someone would choose to live in such a remote place, expecting a
shouted admonition to leave or a warning shot fired into the
ice-blue Montana sky.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, a pleasant man in his early '30s came to the door. When
I introduced myself, he said simply, ``Oh, yeah, last we heard, you
were in Nebraska. We've been waiting for you.''
</P>
<P>
   He saw my look of shock and explained, ``My mother lives in
Nashua (N.H.). She called and told me about this Globe person
driving cross country. She said I should e-mail you and invite you
to Marysville. Ends up, you came anyways.''
</P>
<P>
   And that, ladies and gentlemen, is Exhibit A in just how small
the world has become. First, there were telephones, and then
televisions, and then faxes and cable transmission, and on this
trip I learned that even country farmers carry cellular phones as
they plow their fields of grain. And now, in the age of the
Internet, there's barely a distant corner of America that really,
truly seems all that far away.
</P>
<P>
   His name is George Darcy. He invited me to sit, served drinks,
introduced his fiancee, Bobbie Zumbrunnen, with whom he shares a
crafts business, the Marysville Trading Company.
</P>
<P>
   They talked of their 40-mile bike rides, skiing on the nearby
hills, the hikes through rattlesnake-infested woods with their two
appreciative dogs. The mortgage on their home and store amounts to
less than a lease payment on a lower-end Lexus.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a beautiful town to live in,'' George says, his eyes
drifting toward the Aspen-covered mountains.
</P>
<P>
   A few minutes later, Ann Korting stops by the front porch. She
has lived in Marysville all of her 82 years and remembers back when
the town was packed with 17 saloons and her family ran the food
store. These days, she foots the electricity bill for the tiny
church and cleans what used to be the schoolhouse, where she was
the town's teacher.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot that I miss,'' she says, remembering a time when
there were barber shops and jewelry stores and families lived in
the wooden houses that now sit hollow on the nearby hills. ``I
liked it when the mill was running and people were working. I loved
it then. I miss all those friendships.''
</P>
<P>
   I ask why she stayed after the gold rush ended and one of the
world's most lucrative mines was closed, and she replies, ``Because
I've always loved it.''
</P>
<P>
   At night, I come to find, the town becomes crowded with visitors
from Helena, Butte, and Great Falls who flock here to dine at the
Marysville House, where the steaks, shrimp skillets, and Australian
lobster tails are cooked under a tent in the backyard and
reservations are accepted only by mail because the restaurant has
no phone. Word is that if the postmistress is angry that her
husband has been frequenting the bar, she won't deliver their
letters. No one particularly seems to mind.
</P>
<P>
   Such is the quirkiness of small-town America _ a thought that
fills my mind as I point my convertible west for the final
nine-hour leg to Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Away from the massive cities on the two coasts, we are a nation
awash in land _ gorgeous mountains, endless prairies, gentle
rolling hills. And on that land thrive a people who are unfailingly
kind and relentlessly optimistic _ filled with pride in what they
have, and hope that their lives will get even better. Such are the
traits of America.
</P>
<P>
   Pulling into Seattle, I think of the waitress in Powder River,
Wyo., laughing as I sampled fried rattlesnake at the Tumble Inn
(tastes like tires, not chicken). I remember a lone conductor
waving a brawny arm from the engine of a train chugging through the
Dakotas. I recall an aging farmer hacking at weeds in a field of
soybeans that spread far into the Nebraskan dusk. He told me he was
``semi-retired,'' though he had been working since early morning.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, I spy the glistening waters of Puget Sound. I expect to
feel elated, having crossed this land by car. Mostly I just feel
humbled. The road just taken was long and sweet indeed.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Brian McGrory's e-mail address is mcgrory(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
