<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAKING MONEY THE OLD-FASHIONED WAY IN THE NEW ECONOMY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a recent newsletter mailed out to clients, Berkshire
Partners, a Boston private equity firm, described some of its
recent investments.
</P>
<P>
   There was Savers, a chain of used clothing stores; US Can, a
maker of containers; Casella Waste Services, a waste management
company; and Active Aero Group, an air-freight company that ships
parts to the auto industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you detect a distinctly `old economy' bias in all this,
yep, that's us, mostly,'' the firm's partners wrote in the
newsletter.
</P>
<P>
   At a time when much of the private equity world is being lured
by the siren song of venture capital and the Internet, Berkshire
Partners is sticking to its knitting. The company is putting its
money into the kind of traditional businesses it has been backing
for the past 14 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew we didn't have the skill set to be successful venture
capitalists,'' said Carl Ferenbach, a managing director and one of
the founders of Berkshire Partners. ``And besides, we believe in
our core business.''
</P>
<P>
   Why not? By Berkshire's own reckoning, its annual internal rate
of return on its 60 past investments is in the neighborhood of 60
percent. Accurate performance numbers are hard to pry loose in the
venture and private-equity world, but Berkshire says each of its
five investment funds has ranked in the top 25 percent of
comparable funds.
</P>
<P>
   Like other private-equity firms, Berkshire uses its own money
and money raised from others to make investments in mainly private
businesses. In 1998, Berkshire raised $880 million for a new round
of investments. Investors get their money back when those
businesses are sold or go public.
</P>
<P>
   ``I consider them to be one of the top buyout groups in the
country,'' said Daniel Steele, who manages investments for the
Massachusetts Institute of Technology. MIT has been investing with
Berkshire since 1992. The endowments of Yale and Princeton are also
Berkshire investors.
</P>
<P>
   Steven Galante, the publisher of Private Equity Analyst, a
newsletter, said Berkshire has a ``fabulous reputation.'' He also
credits the firm with breaking new ground in some of its
transportation and telecommunications investments.
</P>
<P>
   Berkshire's investments are an eclectic lot. Over the years, the
firm has put money into specialty retailers, manufacturers,
business services, surface transportation (snore), and wireless
communications.
</P>
<P>
   The bet on wireless was a big winner. According to Berkshire,
its $65 million investment in Crown Castle Corp., which owns and
operates cellular telephone towers, has already returned at least
$750 million.
</P>
<P>
   The partners at Berkshire are not Luddites. They acknowledge the
Internet has huge implications.
</P>
<P>
   ``For each of our companies we ask, `What is freely available
information going to mean?' '' said Kevin Callaghan, one of
Berkshire's managing directors. ``Can their value be snatched away?
Is the Web going to be a threat or an opportunity?''
</P>
<P>
   Berkshire sees its role as providing a bridge between the old
and the new economies. Toward that end, the firm recently hooked up
with Mainspring, a Cambridge e-consulting company, to provide Web
advice to its portfolio companies. Some of those companies already
have major Internet operations of their own.
</P>
<P>
   But when it comes to investment areas, Berkshire prefers to
troll the old economy for opportunities. ``There are a lot of good
neglected companies out there that the world doesn't care about,''
Callaghan said.
</P>
<P>
   Casella would seem to fit that description. The Vermont waste
and recycling company is publicly traded. Its stock has dropped
from $18 a share to $10 since the beginning of the year, in part
because it is in a slow-growing, unglamorous business.
</P>
<P>
   Berkshire reasons that companies like Casella have greater
potential than the world recognizes. They generate good cash flow,
they have limited competition, and they may be able to participate
in industry consolidation down the road.
</P>
<P>
   ``We also still believe in the business cycle,'' said Callaghan.
``There will be worse times again. And some of these businesses are
recession-resistant. They are safe companies to be invested in.''
</P>
<P>
   Berkshire's investors don't seem bothered by the firm's
steady-as-she-goes approach. At a recent conference, they delivered
a clear message: Keep doing what you are doing.
</P>
<P>
   Carl Ferenbach said Berkshire intends to do just that. ``This is
an extraordinary country,'' he said. ``God help us if we can't find
places to put our money.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
