A8967 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-PROSTITUTES-FOE-HNS &LR;      07-11 0503
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PROSTITUTES-FOE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     ANTI-PROSTITUTION CRUSADER RELEASED FROM JAIL 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By PETER HARTLAUB  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A San Francisco man who tried to liberate his
neighborhood of prostitution by bombarding cars with steel bars was
freed from jail Monday after a jury convicted him of a handful of
misdemeanors rather than more serious offenses.
</P>
<P>
   Douglas Chin, 46, was arrested in March and charged with two
felony counts of assault with a deadly weapon and two felony counts
of throwing an object at a moving vehicle. The engineer said he
remained in jail to make a point rather than paying the $30,000
bail.
</P>
<P>
   ``I spent 10 years staying awake every night,'' Chin said after
he was released. ``I think four months (in jail) was well worth
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Chin said repeatedly after he was released that his
rebar-hurling days are over.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone else is going have to take up the battle. I'm worn
out,'' Chin said. ``All I want is to get some sleep.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mission District resident had testified that he threw the
eight-inch pieces of reinforced metal bar on cars driven by johns
who had solicited prostitutes in his neighborhood. Chin could have
faced seven years in jail if he had been convicted of the four
felonies, but the jury reduced the charges to misdemeanors.
</P>
<P>
   Superior Court Judge Jack Berman sentenced Chin to time served
and ordered him released. The judge also proclaimed his support for
the jury's decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``For what it is worth, the court would have agreed with your
verdicts in all respects,'' Berman said.
</P>
<P>
   Franz Fuetsch, the lawyer representing Chin, said the attention
surrounding the case ``has made it possible, I think, on a daily
basis for people to live a more healthy life.''
</P>
<P>
   Assistant District Attorney Maria Bee did not back down after
the verdict was read, maintaining that she believed Chin committed
felonies.
</P>
<P>
   Chin took the stand in his own defense during his two-day trial,
which ended Friday. Chin told the jurors that he felt helpless
after his neighborhood became overrun by prostitutes and their
clients. He said his intent was to either get rid of them or bring
attention to the problem in a court of law.
</P>
<P>
   Jurors deliberated for about six hours on Friday and Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Chin was arrested in March after the police spotted someone
throwing the pieces of rebar at two passing cars from a church
rooftop at 19th and Capp streets in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   When they climbed onto the roof of the Russian Convent of St.
Vladimir, they found Chin, who was wearing a ski mask.
</P>
<P>
   Chin said after he was released from jail that he used his
knowledge of physics while throwing the rebars, and never expected
anyone to get hurt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cars are pretty sturdy nowadays,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He also said that while in jail, he met a man who made his
living working the area.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was locked up with a pimp. We got along fine,'' Chin said.
``We talked things out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
