<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-11 13:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8971 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-SMARTERKIDS-SHAKEOUT-     07-11 0878
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SMARTERKIDS-SHAKEOUT-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 ONLINE TOY STORE RIDES OUT THE STORM 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEPHANIE STOUGHTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   On the surface, SmarterKids.com Inc. doesn't look like an
e-commerce company whose stock has sunk below the $2 mark.
</P>
<P>
   The Needham, Mass. online seller of educational toys is forging
ahead into new areas such as test preparation and tutoring
services. Last month, it opened a new distribution center in
Mansfield, Mass. _ one of the first designed with an Internet
retailer's special needs in mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll stick to our knitting,'' said David Blohm,
SmarterKids.com's chief executive officer.
</P>
<P>
   Like many dot-com executives, Blohm hopes to weather Wall
Street's hostility and an ongoing shakeout that has snuffed out
several of his online competitors, including Toysmart.com, Red
Rocket and ToyTime.
</P>
<P>
   But so far, SmarterKids.com has had a tough time shaking off the
association. Its stock price has tumbled from $17.125 on Dec. 1 to
$1.65625 Monday. And in spite of SmarterKids.com's financial and
Web-site improvements, most Wall Street analysts seem less
interested in the company, Blohm acknowledged.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole psychology has turned against (online retailers),''
said Steven Tuen, an analyst with IPO Value Monitor in New York.
``It will be hard for them to get over the hump.''
</P>
<P>
   The company's slumping stock price also is making it difficult
for executives to meet long-term goals such as growing through
acquisitions. With a market value of $35 million, the company has
enough money to fund its operations through 2001. But
SmarterKids.com may have to raise more funds next year.
</P>
<P>
   Executives predict SmarterKids.com will break even in 2002, when
its revenue is projected to be between $80 million and $100
million. Last year, the company lost $34.7 million on $5.4 million
in sales.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike many of its e-commerce colleagues, SmarterKids.com
began pinching pennies early in the game. The company restrained
itself in the fourth quarter of 1999, when e-commerce firms
splurged on television and radio ads. After dot-com stocks crashed
this spring, SmarterKids.com began cutting its advertising and
marketing budgets.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be no TV ads this year,'' said Al Noyes, the online
seller's executive vice president.
</P>
<P>
   By trimming advertising spending, the Web site is effectively
slowing new visitor growth. But SmarterKids.com hopes to increase
its sales by turning more repeat buyers into loyal shoppers.
</P>
<P>
   A frequent buyer who has a eighth grader, for instance, might
receive an e-mail advertisement for a game that helps teach
algebra. On the other hand, shoppers who frequently return
merchandise or only seek discounted items would get dropped from
the company's marketing list faster than you can hit your delete
button.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bargain shoppers, God bless them,'' Noyes said. ``But they'll
only come to your site for a bargain.''
</P>
<P>
   The tactic isn't entirely new. Savvy traditional retailers have
used technology to quietly weed through customer lists, plucking
out people they deem unworthy of receiving catalogs and notices of
special discounts.
</P>
<P>
   SmarterKids.com is paring expenses across the board. It has
saved money by moving about half of its shipping to the US Postal
Service, which has become more competitive with leader UPS. And it
has cut more fulfillment costs by packing and shipping orders on
its own.
</P>
<P>
   Before its new warehouse opened in Mansfield, the company
outsourced the work to J.L. Hammett, a school-supplies distributor
based in Braintree, Mass. But SmarterKids.com wanted more control
over its operations, as well as a distribution center that would
meet the needs of a rapidly growing e-commerce company.
</P>
<P>
   SmarterKids.com continues to distance itself from regular toy
stores. Unlike Toys ``R'' Us Inc. and eToys, this Internet retailer
sells neither Barbie nor G.I. Joe. Instead, SmarterKids.com
recommends educational toys based on individual profiles of
children.
</P>
<P>
   At the Web site, parents build profiles by entering their
children's ages, educational level and interests. SmarterKids.com
uses that information to suggest various educational toys and
games, as well as to fine-tune its marketing.
</P>
<P>
   The Web site has used its skills in personalized shopping to
springboard into other areas. Parents can now get information on
how their infants should be developing, as well as what each state
requires children to learn at their respective grade levels. The
site then offers test-preparation tools.
</P>
<P>
   SmarterKids.com recently agreed to provide consumers with K-12
instruction through ChildU, an online learning company. Through a
partnership with Real Time Learning, based in San Francisco,
SmarterKids.com will be able to offer online tutoring for children
in grades 3 through 12, along with workshops for parents.
</P>
<P>
   This fall, the online education store will launch an area that
helps teachers find products for their classes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know this stuff works,'' Blohm said. ``The challenge is
telling the whole world that this stuff works.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
