<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-11 13:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8977 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-JORDAN-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      07-11 0632
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JORDAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRONG ECONOMY CRUCIAL FOR GORE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBERT A. JORDAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Although Vice President Al Gore continues to lag behind Texas
Governor George W. Bush in the presidential race, most of Gore's
supporters believe that his issues _ and the continued strong
performance of the economy _ will propel him past Bush and into the
White House.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, according to an Associated Press report, began this week
to focus on issues that he and other Democrats see as winners with
the electorate:
</P>
<P>
   --HMO reform, including a patients' bill of rights.
</P>
<P>
   --Prescription drug benefits.
</P>
<P>
   --An increase in the minimum wage.
</P>
<P>
   --dditional environmental protections.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Gore hopes to link Bush to the more
conservative elements of the Republican leadership and to the
special-interest groups that he and President Clinton blame for
preventing the passage of these and other Democratic-sponsored
measures that appear to be popular with voters.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, of course, is hoping to persuade voters that it was
Federal Reserve chairman Alan Greenspan, not the Clinton-Gore
administration, who created and maintained the ongoing economic
boom. That is going to be a tough sell; most voters gave Clinton a
second term because they believe he, not Greenspan, gets the
credit.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's challenge is to convince voters he was a key partner in
the Clinton administration's handling of the economy, and that he
plans to continue the same policies.
</P>
<P>
   But Gore knows, as he tries to catch up to Bush in the polls,
that a good economy alone may not be enough to carry him into the
presidency.
</P>
<P>
   That apparently is why Gore, who recently switched campaign
managers, has now changed his campaign strategy to focus on issues
he and his campaign team believe will resonate with voters as both
parties move closer to their nominating conventions.
</P>
<P>
   Gore knows that most voters believe the Republican-led Congress
has been more focused on trying to get a popular Clinton out of
office than working on legislation that would benefit the public.
He also knows the GOP is vulnerable to his latest charge, that the
Republican-led House and Senate have been a
do-nothing-for-the-people Congress.
</P>
<P>
   GOP leaders also know they are vulnerable to this charge, which
is why they are now trying to pass health reform legislation,
though not of the size and scope of Democratic bills on the same
issue. Gore and other Democrats argue that GOP measures, including
rights for managed-care patients, are not reforms. If they were,
they argue, these measures would not have the backing of major
campaign contributors from large drug companies, large insurance
companies, and HMOs.
</P>
<P>
   But even if Gore can seize momentum on the issues, he still
lacks one key element that helped Clinton win reelection:
personality.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps one reason Bush leads Gore in the polls is that he seems
to be more appealing, at least image-wise. Bush has managed to grow
in the eyes of many voters since his battles with US Senator John
McCain of Arizona in the earlier primaries, to the point where he
is appearing to some voters as more presidential than Gore.
</P>
<P>
   But if Gore's new campaign strategy begins to show signs of
connecting with the voters, that could change. Bush may have a more
difficult time trying to defend the efforts of his GOP colleagues
in Congress in preventing the passage of bills that most Americans
want and need.
</P>
<P>
   More than anything else, though, Gore needs to have the economy
going strong right up to Election Day. If the economy goes south
during the remaining weeks of the campaign, Gore's campaign may
well go in the same direction.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Robert A. Jordan is a Globe columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
