<HEADER>
A8980 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-TEN-WIMBLEDON-BOS &LR;      07-11 1532
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-WIMBLEDON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE CREAM ROSE TO THE TOP AT THIS WIMBLEDON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB DUFFY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Oh, right, the tennis. Yes, come to think of it, there
was some of that, too.
</P>
<P>
   The 114th rendition of Wimbledon seemed like a two-week
diversionary tactic, with uproar on the periphery drowning out the
competition on the sacred lawn. But the momentous coronation of
Venus Williams Saturday and the record reinstallation of Pete
Sampras Sunday elevated the game back to its rightful eminence.
</P>
<P>
   Williams's 6-3, 7-6 dethroning of defender Lindsay Davenport was
majestic not in its execution but in its ramifications. The match
itself was an exchange of errors _ 11 service breaks in two sets _
as Williams acknowledged, ``I really think we both were just
feeling pressure.''
</P>
<P>
   But Williams's nerves were less fragile and she became the
second African-American woman in history _ the first since Althea
Gibson in 1958 _ to reign at the All England Lawn Tennis &AMP; Croquet
Club.
</P>
<P>
   She immediately indicated that she will be a most accessible
monarch. That was manifested by her exuberant celebration, in which
she bounded up into the stands to share the glory with her father,
Richard _ who was too busy dancing on the roof of the broadcast
booth to make much contact with his daughter _ and most of all, her
beloved younger sister and unfortunate semifinal victim, Serena.
</P>
<P>
   Venus's triumph fulfilled the destiny Richard envisioned when he
started training the girls in downtrodden Compton, Calif. He has
been accused of being a domineering mentor, but the fact is he
instilled in both daughters a sense of proportion _ the message
that tennis is only one facet of life _ sadly lacking on the WTA
Tour.
</P>
<P>
   Venus, who had bought a gown at home in Palm Beach Gardens,
Fla., before she left for London in anticipation of wearing it at
the Champions' Ball, showed her grasp of balance in the wake of her
triumph.
</P>
<P>
   Going into the match, she said, ``Sure, the tennis part of my
life, I'd be much happier (winning). But winning, losing, money,
riches, or fame doesn't make you happy.''
</P>
<P>
   But she'd better get used to all of the above, except losing.
Davenport emphasized that the recent success of Venus and 1999 US
Open champion Serena presages the Williams Chapter in women's Grand
Slam annals.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Sampras has rewritten the book from the male
perspective. His 6-7, 7-6, 6-4, 6-2 victory over gallant Patrick
Rafter made him the most prolific winner in history. It was his
seventh Wimbledon crown, tying the record of Willie Renshaw set
during the tournament's far simpler infancy in the 1880s, when
title defenses involved playing one match.
</P>
<P>
   More important, it was Sampras's 13th Grand Slam triumph,
snapping the record he had shared with Roy Emerson for the most
success in tennis's four major events: Wimbledon, the US Open,
French Open, and Australian Open.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras has never won a French, but has four US and two
Australian Opens in his Grand Slam count. Emerson won all the
majors at least once but during the game's amateur era, before
1968. So let that debate end before it starts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Time will tell if it will be broken,'' said Sampras after he
played tennis for 2 hours 58 minutes and watched raindrops for 2:57
before claiming his ultimate prize. ``I think in the modern game,
it could be difficult. It's a lot of commitment, a lot of good
playing at big times. You never know. There are guys that are great
players that could possibly do it. But it's not easy.''
</P>
<P>
   It was, in fact, as difficult to grasp as it was to set.
</P>
<P>
   ``With everything that's happened, I'd say this is one of my
best moments,'' said Sampras. ``Over time, I'll appreciate it much
more than I am right now. I'm sure as the months and years go by,
I'll look back at these two weeks as the most diffiuclt, the most
satisfying.''
</P>
<P>
   And the most unprecedented.
</P>
<P>
   Until those precious moments, the women's side was more
disruptive.
</P>
<P>
   A genuinely disturbing matter was the allegation of Alexandra
Stevenson _ a tabloid sensation last year when it was revealed that
her mystery father was basketball great Julius Erving _ that she
had been subjected to racial slurs and harassment during her rookie
WTA Tour season. Alexandra's obtrusive mother, former Boston
television sportscaster Samantha Stevenson, is always within her
shadow, even at press conferences. And it seemed that media-savvy
Mom was manipulating the news allotment as Alexandra parceled out
the dirt in doses. At one press conference, she was generally vague
about the charges she and her mother had lodged in a London
newspaper. Then in her farewell address after she'd been eliminated
in the third round, Alexandraa felt free to unburden herself of the
specifics, targeting two French women: Amelie Cocheteux had called
her a ``piece of (expletive) black girl,'' she said, and both
Cocheteux and Anne-Gaelle Sidot had engaged in physical
confrontations with the 19-year-old and her mother.
</P>
<P>
   If true, the offenses are damnable. Cocheteux denied making the
slur and Sidot said she had pulled down the bill of Samantha
Stevenson's cap only after Stevenson had made a derogatory remark
to her. The WTA Tour issued a statement saying it had investigated
all the allegations and found no grounds for punitive measures.
</P>
<P>
   The French also were involved in an internal flap. Nathalie
Tauziat's tell-all tome, ``The Underside of Women's Tennis,'' was
so popular that three of her countrywomen _ Amelie Mauresmo, Julie
Halard-Decugis, and Sandrine Testud _ threatened to boycott the
Olympics if the author is chosen for the French team.
</P>
<P>
   On the court, there were distractions aplenty. Anna Smashnova
felt she was being heckled by the husband of her second-round
opponent, Katalin Marosi-Aracama, and took retaliatory measures,
firing a ball into the stands at him. But she committed a head
fault, missing her target and beaning a woman spectator, for which
Smashnova won herself a fine from the WTA.
</P>
<P>
   One of Anna Kournikova's doubles matches was interrupted by a
35-year-old wearing nothing but the slogan of the Russian's
omnipresent sports bra ads, ``Only the balls should bounce,'' on
his chest. The intruder, Mark Edwards, described himself as a
``professional streaker'' but did not indicate the college at which
he'd learned the trade.
</P>
<P>
   Kournikova's doubles partner, Natasha Zvereva, was the
instigator rather than the recipient of undesirable attention. She
made an obscene gesture to the crowd late in the duo's semifinal
loss to the Williamses and was fined $1,000.
</P>
<P>
   History, the very foundation of the so-called Millennium
Championships, was offensive to at least one participant. While 65
former champions and finalists were being honored with a parade at
Centre Court, Jennifer Capriati complained to a referee that the
musical accompaniment was bothering her during her third-round
match. Perhaps she thought it was coming from a car radio and could
be turned off. At any rate, the band and Capriati played on.
</P>
<P>
   Had there been a trophy for boorishness, Damir Dokic would have
been the leader in the clubhouse _ except that he was nearly banned
from it. After his daughter, eventual semifinal loser Jelena, won
an early match, her father celebrated by brandishing a flag of St.
George, denouncing part of the local citizenry as ``fascist,''
exalting the WTA as ``criminal and poison,'' smashing a TV
reporter's cell phone, and trying to settle the damages with a
credit card that the journalist rejected while demanding cash.
Dokic was taken into police custody and avoided jail time _ which
would have given ``cell phone'' a whole new meaning _ only because
the sportscaster declined to press charges.
</P>
<P>
   And there was the ultimate novelty act, the unprecedented
semifinal clash of clan, Williams vs. Williams. While the sisters
insisted they were thrilled about the circumstances because it
guaranteed that one of them would be in the final, their demeanor
on Centre Court before, during, and after Venus's straight-set
victory belied any sense of pleasure amid the worldwide scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   The men were hardly one-dimensional, either.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Tarango followed a five-set, four-hour loss to Paul
Goldstein by refusing the customary handshake from his fellow
Stanford alum. Then Tarango accused Goldstein of unsportsmanlike
conduct because he was treated twice before his opponent's serves
late in the match for an injury Tarango claimed was phony.
Goldstein pleaded innocence; Tarango could have pleaded ignorance
for his behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras was another sideshow source. His march toward history
became a limp after he developed tendinitis in the lower left leg
just before his second-round victory over Karol Kucera. Then he was
displeased with the lack of vigor in Jonas Bjorkman's handshake
after a fourth-round match and said it was indicative of a smear
campaign against him by ATP Tour colleagues who doubted the extent
of his injuries. Bjorkman said that's always the way he shakes
hands when he's just been crushed.
</P>
<P>
   Blessedly, the championships eclipsed all the preliminary acts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
