<HEADLINE>
A SOURCE THAT REMAINS NAMELESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A few items to share while I search for this column's permanent
name . . .
</P>
<P>
   --Tim Duncan was expected to re-sign with the San Antonio Spurs
Tuesday. The free agent center had spent about nine days deciding
between offers from the Spurs and Orlando Magic. The Celtics,
obviously, had no chance of signing Duncan. But wouldn't it have
been intriguing if they had given themselves that chance?
</P>
<P>
   It sounds unrealistic, but it might have happened if Rick Pitino
had come to Boston along with an experienced general manager. For
the record, I love Pitino as a coach. If your team was in a tie
game with five seconds left, you would want Pitino designing your
final play. He is a sideline genius. In the front office, though,
you don't want him home alone.
</P>
<P>
   The Celtics could have been players in this free agent season if
they had kept Chauncey Billups, Ron Mercer, Dee Brown, and Pervis
Ellison from Pitino's first team. All are free agents now, which
means that Boston would have the option of re-signing them
(unlikely) or clearing their cap space and going after Duncan,
Grant Hill, or a combination of two medium-priced free agents (more
likely). Pitino still could have made the Travis Knight-Tony Battie
deal and he would have had even more room.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the Celtics are standby passengers, waiting to talk
with the players that other teams bypass.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(begin itals) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --How about ``The Daydreams of a Talking Dread''? Get it?
Talking ``head'' and talking ``dread(locks)''? Never mind . . .
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(end itals) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --I'm not surprised by Mike Tyson's actions as much as I am by
those who find his actions surprising. I don't know about you, but
I crossed the no-shock threshold when he (itals)twice bit off a
man's ear.(unitals) Maybe I'm sheltered, but I haven't come across
a lot of folks who do that.
</P>
<P>
   --So, where do you stand? Did Roger Clemens bean Mike Piazza
intentionally? If this were a court case _ and if I were Roger _
I'd be calling Johnnie Cochran this morning.
</P>
<P>
   --Orlando Brown, the 350-pound Cleveland lineman who was struck
in the eye by an official's weighted flag last season, has called
Cochran. Brown's injury could be career-threatening. This brings
new meaning to the cliche of officials putting too much of
themselves in the game.
</P>
<P>
   --Unless someone has some classic Lenny Bruce/Richard Pryor
material on the subject, I think I've heard enough Izzy Alcantara
jokes.
</P>
<P>
   --Nomar Garciaparra is his generation's Joe DiMaggio. Joe D in
his first four years (2,319 at-bats): 117 strikeouts. Nomar in his
first 3 1/2 years (2,072 at-bats): 217 strikeouts.
</P>
<P>
   --I'm going to miss Keyshawn Johnson vs. Ty Law twice a season.
Law is the Patriots cornerback who is confident enough to believe
that he can play offense; Number 19 (as Johnson likes to call
himself) is the Buccaneers receiver confident enough to believe he
can play offense _ on a basketball court. During an unusual
interview in which he would have talked for five hours if I had let
him, the 6-foot-4-inch Johnson claimed that he could have played
college ball. ``Could I play for North Carolina? Probably not,'' he
said. ``Could I play for Pepperdine? Yeah.'' What about Fordham?
``Hell,'' he said, ``I'd be the star of that team.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(begin itals) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --How about ``Emptying Out The Desk Drawer of the Sports Mind''?
I'll have to negotiate with Ryan's lawyers on that one.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(end itals) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --Sometimes even the sorry Clippers get it right: The Celtics
had agreed to select Missouri point guard Keyon Dooling with the
No. 11 pick in the NBA draft, but the Clips made a deal with the
Magic and swiped Dooling at No. 10.
</P>
<P>
   --In the last 25 years, only two men with coaching and general
managing duties have led teams to an NBA championship. Can you name
them?
</P>
<P>
   --Pete Sampras (13 Grand Slam singles titles) never has to
apologize for sharing the same sentence with Bill Russell (11 NBA
titles).
</P>
<P>
   --Any day now, Bill Parcells is going to read aloud from the
Jets' depth chart _ ``No. 1 receiver Wayne Chrebet'' _ and panic.
Parcells is a football genius, but what's he waiting for? The
return of Al Toon?
</P>
<P>
   --The Washington Redskins appear to be perfect. Bruce Smith and
LaVar Arrington. Brad Johnson and Jeff George. Darrell Green and
Deion Sanders. For some reason, though, I have recurring 8-8
visions for this team.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(begin itals) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --How about ``Nobody Asked Me, But . . .'' Jimmy Cannon began
that one. But since so many people have borrowed his style, I might
be able to get away with it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(end itals) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --Trivia answer: Two Texas guys, Gregg Popovich (1999) and Rudy
Tomjanovich ('94, '95).
</P>
<P>
   --Just once, wouldn't you love to pick up the paper and read
that the Bruins were pursuing a major free agent? Something like
``Bruins Court Lindros'' or ``Bruins, Habs In Fight For Messier.''
</P>
<P>
   --He was the first to use the exaggerated first-down signal. He
was not the first to make the NFL uncomfortable. He wore mink
coats. He wore sunglasses. He sometimes spoke like the NFL's
``Shaft'' when he wanted to make a point. ``I'm as black as they
come,'' he said, trying to explain that Troy Aikman didn't have a
problem with black players. If Aikman did, Michael Irvin reasoned,
he would certainly have a problem with the self-proclaimed
Playmaker. Irvin retired Monday after 12 seasons with the Cowboys.
You'll remember a lot of things about him, many of them negative.
But don't be surprised when he is a first-ballot Hall of Famer. He
was that good.
</P>
<P>
   --Call me impressionable, but Tiger Woods's dominance at Pebble
Beach and Venus Williams's mastery at Wimbledon have me thinking of
golf and tennis lessons.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Michael Holley is a Globe columnist. He can be reached by e-mail
at holley(at)globe.com.
</P>
