<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-LONGWOOD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO OF THE BEST PUBLIC GARDENS IN AMERICA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CAROL STOCKER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Early in the last century two cousins living six miles apart on
opposite sides of the Delaware/Pennsylvania border created two very
fine gardens. They were also very large, about a thousand acres
each.
</P>
<P>
   But instead of letting their paradises die with them, as people
usually do, the cousins endowed theirs and opened them to the
public. Today Longwood Gardens and Winterthur survive as two of the
best public gardens in America and have helped turn the region
southwest of Philadelphia into America's top botanical tourist
destination.
</P>
<P>
   Almost a million people a year visit Longwood Gardens near
Kennett Square, Pa., the creation of Pierre S. du Pont. He was
chairman of both the Du Pont Co. (1919-1940) and General Motors
(1920-1929), two presumably well-paying jobs. He bought the initial
202 acres in 1906 to preserve old trees on it that someone wanted
to log off and ended up adding about 800 acres more and turning the
estate into an amazing horticultural display garden that rivals the
best in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   In nearby Delaware, his slightly younger second cousin Henry
Francis du Pont inherited Winterthur from his father in 1927.
Inspired by the folk art collection of yet another cousin, Electra
Havemeyer Webb, who was in the process of creating Vermont's
Shelburne Museum, this du Pont increased the mansion's size to
almost 200 rooms and filled them with the best antique American
furniture, china, and architectural bits and pieces that his money
could buy. He was ready to spend every cent he had on it and,
during the Depression, almost did.
</P>
<P>
   H.F. was a hands-on kind of guy who did not have to report to an
office. Instead he turned the gentleman's farm he inherited into a
prize-winning dairy operation and supervised planting the
surrounding woodlands with tens of thousands of flowering trees,
azaleas, and wildflowers.
</P>
<P>
   In this he was abetted by the pioneering Boston-trained
landscape architect Marian Cruger Coffin, whose motto was that
money, maintenance, and manure could achieve miracles. And with
H.F., she proved her point. Today Winterthur is the world's leading
museum of American decorative arts set in a vast naturalistic
garden that provides a lovely frame for the collection.
</P>
<P>
   May is the peak time for both gardens, which require a day
apiece, especially if you visit Winterthur's spectacular period
rooms of antique furniture.
</P>
<P>
   Longwood spares no expense to mount a 12-month display in its
complex of 20 greenhouses. There's a festival with 15,000
chrysanthemums in November. The conservatory Christmas show
features blooms, choral concerts, and colorful fountains against
the backdrop of 400,000 outdoor lights.
</P>
<P>
   Longwood combines horticulture with 400 performing arts events
each year to keep the calendar full. A 2,000-seat outdoor theater
has a 10-foot-high water curtain composed of hundreds of individual
jets that form an opaque screen that rises and falls between
performers and the audience.
</P>
<P>
   Another even larger fountain garden provides illuminated
displays on summer nights; they are accompanied on four special
nights by fireworks.
</P>
<P>
   August features also include artificial ponds with tropical
waterlilies with seven-foot lily pads.
</P>
<P>
   The 80 acres devoted to high-maintenance gardening would make a
French king feel right at home. There are groves of wisterias
trained and pruned into tree form to look like purple weeping
willows when blooming in mid-May. There's even a topiary garden.
Idea gardens contain information on the latest cultivars of
annuals, perennials, roses, vegetables, herbs, ground covers,
ornamental grasses, and vines with suggestions on how homeowners
might make use of them.
</P>
<P>
   On my mid-April visit I saw live willow branches simultaneously
woven and planted to take root and grow into living huts and
sculptures, a garden foll that first caught on in England. Some
90,000 tulips were blooming in dozens of combinations in
600-foot-long beds. Any gardener who has tried to create drama by
pairing varieties of tulips knows how easily such matchmaking can
resemble a blind date gone awry, thanks to the varying forms,
heights, and bloom times of this diverse plant.
</P>
<P>
   But Longwood was characteristically helpful in labeling each
tulip variety so home gardeners could painlessly duplicate the
combinations they found appealing. I liked the mix of Pink
Impression and Ivory Floradale Darwin hybrid tulips best. Other
winning combos included a mix of red, white, and pink double early
tulips (Schoonard, Electra, and Peach Blossom) and also orange
fritillaria imperials combined with Orange Monarch and Queen of the
Night triumph tulips and Melody Purple pansies.
</P>
<P>
   On that visit I was also cheered to see native dogwood trees,
long devastated by widespread disease, once again putting on a good
show. Casey Score, who's in charge of integrated pest management
for Longwood, said that some years are better than others, and that
a program of pruning out dead wood and watering is followed through
the summer. ``Also, people like to use dogwoods as specimens, but
they're naturally understory trees that do better with a little
shade,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But even in spring, the outdoor garden can't upstage the ever
changing year-round series of shows mounted inside the
high-ceilinged glass conservatories, which cover almost four acres.
I saw an indoor recirculating ``river'' with lifesize bronze cranes
wading off shores of cymbidium orchids that is an unforgettable
vision for any first-time visitor. Huge spheres of plants cascaded
from the ceilings like flowering chandeliers.
</P>
<P>
   Towering delphiniums rose toward the ceiling like stalagmites in
a floral cavern. One of the world's largest organs with 10,010
pipes, also housed in the conservatory complex, rumbled in the
background.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Winterthur
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Winterthur offers another memorable but totally different
experience. It is as understated and naturalistic as Longwood is
flamboyant and formal.
</P>
<P>
   While Longwood boasts 20 indoor and 20 outdoor gardens,
Winterthur is a single seamless natural landscape, with a large
population of wildlife, including the rare wood ducks that nest in
its series of ponds.
</P>
<P>
   The high points of my visit to Winterthur included seeing a pair
of foxes racing across an open field and a determined bluebird
chasing a tree swallow away from its nest. Anyone who has ever put
up a bluebird box knows how rare it is to actually find a bluebird
in one, but at Winterthur most of the 45 nest boxes dotting the
rolling fields were mounted by an occupying blue sentinel during my
visit.
</P>
<P>
   After years of benign neglect, the garden at Winterthur has been
restored over the last decade under the leadership of Tom Buchter,
former head of the New England Wildflower Society in Framingham,
Mass. His first job was not to plant but to remove unwanted plants
that had seized the opportunity to seed themselves and grow large
enough to obscure the views H.F. had carefully created, shade out
his ornamental plantings, and obscure the architectural lines of
the Italianate garden Coffin designed behind the mansion. When
volunteer viburnums were removed from the understory, thousands of
daffodils that had long lain dormant began to bloom again.
</P>
<P>
   Winterthur has no formal fountains but it is rich in natural
springs that produce a watershed critical to the area's drinking
water, so its 26 gardeners have cut back to a minimal use of
gardening chemicals. The museum has just completed an environmental
management study to encourage wildlife, including the uncommon
Appalachian azure butterfly that frequents the azalea woods where
black cohosh serves as host plant for the caterpillars.
</P>
<P>
   Now a new garden is being installed especially for children
called ``Enchanted Woods''; it will open next June. The area will
include a giant elevated ``Bird's Nest,'' a Maypole, seating for
storytelling, and an ``Acorn Tearoom,'' encircled by old stone
columns around child-sized furnishings. A ``Faerie Cottage'' and a
``Forbidden Faerie Ring'' of wooden mushrooms will deliver an
unexpected misting to the adventurous child who dares step within,
adding to the region's legacy of magic.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-11-00 1356EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
