<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-11 13:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8985 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u t BC-TRAVEL-MALTA-2TAKES-B     07-11 1475
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-MALTA-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GETTING AN EDUCATION ON MALTA 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS  
 (Includes history sidebar.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GLORIA NEGRI  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   VALLETTA, Malta _ When I told people I hoped to travel to Malta,
the general reaction was: ``Where is Malta? Who owns it? What
language do they speak there? Why are you going?''
</P>
<P>
   The questions came with other gratuitous comments: ``Is that
where Bogie's Maltese falcon came from?'' Or, ``I have a Maltese
cat.''
</P>
<P>
   I am embarrassed to say I didn't know that much about Malta,
myself, and casting off, as I did, on a last-minute trip there
after a stay in Sicily, I didn't have time to read up on it.
</P>
<P>
   When I learned that the Maltese islands were some 60 miles south
of Sicily and reachable by plane or ferry, I decided I had to go.
Since the ferries were not yet on a regular schedule _ it was early
April _ I took a 25-minute Air Malta flight from Catania, Sicily,
to Valletta, Malta's capital.
</P>
<P>
   At Catania airport, I met Irene Weaver, who told me her husband,
Stephen, was on the staff of the American embassy in Malta and that
her family lived in Brockton, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   This confirmed for me that Malta was, indeed, an independent
republic (since 1964), with a parliament (which I later visited in
Valletta), a prime minister, and a president, all things I should
have known and not just surmised.
</P>
<P>
   When we arrived in Malta, I shared a taxi with Irene to Sliema,
where she lived and where I would be staying, and learned that she
had been a medevac nurse in southeast Asia when her husband was
with the embassy in Singapore. She said she would have a friend,
Clotilde Mifsud, call me and fill me in on what I should see and,
in particular, what I should know about Malta, which turned out to
be a lot.
</P>
<P>
   On the map, Malta appears to be several tiny specks, much
smaller than Sicily, which is about the size of New Hampshire. Two
of the five islands are uninhabited islets; one, Comino, has a few
farmers; and the other two, Malta and Gozo, are the main ones.
</P>
<P>
   The island called Malta is about the size of Martha's Vineyard.
I was astounded on the ride from the airport to find a brightly-lit
metropolis instead of a small tropical island.
</P>
<P>
   While Malta doesn't have many sandy beaches, its rocky coastline
offers breathtaking views of the Mediterranean and opportunities
for water sports.
</P>
<P>
   In early spring, purple blossoms of the Judas tree, blooming fig
and fruit trees dot the landscape.
</P>
<P>
   In the lovely resort town of Sliema, Clotilde, who is of Maltese
parentage, operates Goddess Tours to Malta but she lives part of
the year in Portsmouth, N.H. I learned some things _ mainly that my
five days in Malta were not enough _ on a walking tour with her
along Sliema's winding cobblestone streets.
</P>
<P>
   She told me that the ubiquitous covered wooden balconies,
painted in vivid blues and greens, on the limestone rowhouses were
a carryover from times when Malta was ruled by the Arabs or the
Spaniards. The balconies served as sort of a modesty shield,
Clotilde said, for women who might want to look out on the street
below without revealing too much of themselves.
</P>
<P>
   However, a Maltese man I later met disputed this story, but his
explanation was not so romantic.
</P>
<P>
   From Clotilde and the tours I took with S. Mifsud &AMP; Sons Ltd.,
or SMS, one of Malta's premier tour operators, I learned that Malta
has some of the world's oldest temples and monuments, going back to
4000 BC to the Neolithic, or Stone Age, and predating the pyramids
in Egypt and Stonehenge on England's Salisbury Plain, and that its
history and culture were unique.
</P>
<P>
   I learned the importance in Malta's history of the Knights of
St. John of Jerusalem, a crusader and hospitaler order founded in
the 11th century to care for sick pilgrims in the Holy Land. In
1291, after long combat with the Turks, the Knights, now more
popularly known as the Knights of Malta, left the Holy Land for
Rhodes and, in 1530, came to Malta.
</P>
<P>
   The Spanish king, Charles V, who then ruled Malta, donated the
Maltese islands to the Knights for an annual rental of one
peregrine falcon. The Knights' reign lasted 268 years.
</P>
<P>
   The Bogart film, ``The Maltese Falcon,'' revolves around a
Maltese falcon statue of solid gold, covered with jewels and
coveted by Sidney Greenstreet and Peter Lorre.
</P>
<P>
   While Malta's culture, its prehistoric ruins, and its history
have few parallels, I found the civility of its warm and friendly
people, many of whom are fluent in several languages, to be one of
its greatest assets.
</P>
<P>
   There was Charlie, a taxi driver who came to my hotel to take me
on what should have been a 10-minute trip to the suburb of
Madliena. A Boston friend suggested I look up her cousin in Malta
and, when I did, Valerie Wood invited me for tea at her Madliena
villa.
</P>
<P>
   (Valerie was born in Malta and married an Englishman and is one
of the few women invested as a member in the Order of Malta for her
charitable work in both England and Malta.)
</P>
<P>
   The 10 minutes Valerie said the trip would take stretched to
almost an hour with Charlie and I flying through red lights and
zooming up and down cliffs trying to find her. It was a feat of
derring-do sadly familiar among both Maltese and Boston drivers.
</P>
<P>
   We had agreed on a fare beforehand though neither Charlie nor I
spoke the other's language. Now, he was indicating it would cost
much more. Once he stopped for directions at a farm stand and got a
bag of ful, a large green broad bean, but no directions. In the
taxi, he snapped the pod and gave me a bean. When we finally got to
Valerie's, Charlie refused to accept the extra fare. The shared ful
must have bonded us.
</P>
<P>
   There was the waitress. Before I had figured out Malta's money,
she refused to take a tip from my outstretched hand, saying, ``Our
pleasure to serve you was enough.''
</P>
<P>
   In Sliema, I stayed at the handsome, balconied Crowne Plaza
Hotel, overlooking the Mediterranean, where the accommodating staff
mirrored that general goodwill and the fare included a sumptuous
breakfast with a variety of Malta's famous home-baked crusty
breads.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder more and more tourists are visiting Malta, among them
increasing numbers of Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Marika Doublet of the Malta Tourism Authority in Valletta said
the number of tourists over the last 10 years has increased
dramatically, with American tourism showing an upswing of 7,019
visitors in 1980 compared with 18,558 in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Mario Farrugia, the ebullient manager of the the groups and
cruises department for SMS tours, said more and more cruise ships
are making Malta a destination and that many of the passengers are
American.
</P>
<P>
   American business presence is also evident. I was surprised to
see not only a McDonald's, but a Burger King, Pizza Hut, Kentucky
Fried Chicken, and, most recently, a TGIFriday's, the last in what
looks to have been a small medieval castle. Scenes in the film
``Gladiator'' were shot here. There is also a Marks &AMP; Spencer, the
British apparel shop.
</P>
<P>
   When I was in Malta in April, the American dollar wasn't faring
too well against the Malta pound, or Malta lira, as it is also
called _ one pound cost about $3. As of a week ago, a dollar was
worth .43 lira.
</P>
<P>
   The language, a Semitic one with Arabic roots, was another
surprise. While I was expecting Italian, French, and English, I
found the tongue not at all recognizable. English is an official
language _ Malta was a British colony for more than 150 years. _
and so is Maltese, a befuddling melange of Phoenician (the
Phoenicians are believed to be the first known people to settle in
Malta in the 9th century BC), Arabic, Italian, Spanish, French, and
English.
</P>
<P>
   All these people, over the years, ruled Malta, coveting not only
its natural beauty and mild climate but its strategic location in
the heart of the Mediterranean between Europe and Africa.
</P>
<P>
   The Maltese language only adds to the country's exotic aura as
do the Arabic-sounding names of its towns and villages.
</P>
<P>
   Try pronouncing names on the map of Malta like Burmarrad,
Naxxar, San Gwann, Msida, Hamrun, Tarxien, Zejtun, Birzebbuga,
Marsaxlokk, Siggiewi, and Zurrieq. `'Triq'' is seen on many signs.
It means ``street.''
</P>
<P>
   Malta is still a strategic port. When I was there, the HMS
Illustrious , fresh from a relief mission to flood-devastated
Mozambique, was in Grand Harbour.
</P>
<P>
   The Malta Independent, one of the nation's several newspapers,
reported that during World War II, an earlier namesake of the
aircraft carrier defended the vital Malta convoy, was heavily
damaged by bombing in 1941, and repaired by Maltese workers. During
the war, Malta was heavily bombed by Germany and Italy. In 1989,
presidents Bush and Gorbachev held a summit on the Soviet cruise
ship Maxim Gorky in Malta Harbor.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
