<HEADLINE>
WALKING AND DINING WITH CAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD P. CARPENTER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Silent Cal isn't all that silent after all.
</P>
<P>
   Calvin Coolidge, the president with a reputation for reticence,
is the latest historical figure to be portrayed in a walking tour
of Boston that is spiced with lots of conversation and subtle good
humor. And Coolidge, ably played by actor-historian Jim Cooke,
would have been well qualified to reminisce about Boston. He was,
after all, a Massachusetts legislator, lieutenant governor, and
governor before becoming vice president and, in 1923, president.
</P>
<P>
   Participants take a quick trip to the 1920s during the
three-hour tour, titled ``Coolidge's Boston: Beans, Brahmins &AMP;
Bulfinch,'' which includes lunch. Everything begins at 1 Milk St.,
at the old Boston Transcript building in the heart of what was once
the city's thriving Newspaper Row. From there, Coolidge, complete
with straw hat, natty suit, and Yankee accent, leads walkers down
Washington Street to show them the Adams House, where he lived for
a dollar a day as a state representative in 1906, and where as
governor in 1920 he learned that he'd been nominated for vice
president. En route, he recognizes a portion of Filene's department
store but little else, and when he reaches the site of the Adams
House, it's no longer there!
</P>
<P>
   Undaunted, he takes walkers up a side street for a brief visit
to the legendary Brattle Book Store, then to Boston Common, where
he notes that in his day puritanical types often covered up the
tops of the topless sculptures in the Common fountain. He heads for
that Charles Bulfinch masterpiece, the gold-crowned State House,
along the way pointing out historic buildings and monuments and
branding an amphibious Boston Duck Tours vehicle ``funny looking.''
</P>
<P>
   At the State House, he acknowledges that his statement as
governor during the 1919 Boston police strike _ ``There is no right
to strike against the public safety, by anyone, any time, any
place'' _ propelled him to national prominence. He also tells how
his driver, a state trooper, wanted to take him places with the car
lights flashing and the siren blaring. No, said Coolidge; instead
the trooper should be the first Massachusetts driver to obey the
law _ a statement that shows some things never change.
</P>
<P>
   Scollay Square _ once a haven for burlesque, bars, and goodness
knows what else _ has certainly changed, though. Eyeing the
buildings that dominate the square now known as Government Center,
the Coolidge character comments, ``Doesn't look at all familiar.''
</P>
<P>
   There are more stops, including the Suffolk County Court House
(``No, I don't recall a lawyer named Ally McBeal'') and King's
Chapel Burying Ground, where an ancestor of Coolidge's vice
president, the patriot Charles G. Dawes, is buried. And then it's
off to the Parker House, a haven for generations of politicians,
for a fulsome lunch, complete with Parker House rolls and Boston
creme pie.
</P>
<P>
   Coolidge has done a lot of talking these past three hours. So,
he is asked, what does he think of the moniker Silent Cal? The
reply:
</P>
<P>
   ``Nevah did me any hahhm.''
</P>
<P>
   (The Coolidge tour, which is presented by Historic Boston Walks,
takes place Tuesdays. On Wednesdays, Ben Franklin, played by Bill
Meikle, conducts a ``Seedbed of Rebellion'' walk, and on Fridays,
Abigail Adams, portrayed by Linda Myer, offers the women's
perspective in an ``Eyewitness to the Revolution'' walk. Lunch with
Franklin or Adams is at Le Maison Robert. And on Thursdays,
beginning Aug. 3, Myer will play Sophie Tucker in a walk through
Boston's Jazz Age in 1928, with lunch in a North End restaurant.
All tours begin at 9:30 a.m. and cost $39, including lunch, taxes,
and tips. For more information or reservations, call
781-648-0628.) &QL; 
 &QL; 
Travel Trivia: Which state has a one-word motto, and what is it?
(Answer at end of column.) &QL; 
 &QL; 
In a name: Soweto in South Africa was derived from South West
Township. (With thanks to faithful contributor Mike Schuster of
Foxborough, Mass.) &QL; 
 &QL; 
Quotable: ``If an ass goes traveling, he will not come home a
horse'' _ Thomas Fuller, English physician and writer. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Travel bookshelf: One of several projects of the not-for-profit
Boston History Collaborative is a literary trail, launched last
year. In addition to available tours (visit www.lit-trail.org), a
guidebook, ``Literary Trail of Greater Boston'' by Susan Wilson
(Houghton Mifflin, $10, paperback) tells you the best ways to
traverse the lush literary landscape of Boston, Cambridge, and
Concord, where so many authors lived and stories were set. The book
is also sprinkled with quotes such as this one from ``The Late
George Apley'' by J.P. Marquand: ``Marriage . . . is a damnably
serious business, particularly around Boston.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Advice to go: If you're taking the family pet on your driving
vacation (or anywhere else), here's a reminder from Sherpa's Pet
Trading Co.: Never leave a pet alone in a car if the temperature is
above 75 degrees. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Now that's luxury: Manhattan by helicopter and Connecticut by Rolls
Royce are two impressive features of a four-night ``Town &AMP;
Country'' package at the Four Seasons Pierre Hotel in New York City
and the Mayflower Inn in Connecticut's Litchfield County, both luxe
properties. The package begins with a chauffeured ride from
LaGuardia, Newark, or Kennedy airport to the Pierre and a guest
room or suite overlooking Central Park or the skyline. A personal
guide will then provide a daylong, customized tour of the city. The
next day, a vintage Rolls Royce takes the guests to the rustically
romantic Mayflower, and a room or suite with a fireplace and an
outdoor balcony. The following day, it's a tour with a private
guide of the area's many antiques shops. And the next afternoon, a
private helicopter returns the guests to their New York area
airport. Such pampering carries a price: $7,860 for two people in a
guest room or $9,220 for a suite. For more information, call the
Pierre at 212-838-8000. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Did you guess it? Rhode Island. The motto is ``Hope.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
