<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-11 14:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8989 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u t BC-TRAVEL-MALTA-2ND &LR;  &UR; TAK     07-11 1411
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-MALTA-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 VALLETTA, Malta: ... Malta Harbor.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A must-see for tourists interested in Malta's colorful history
is the documentary,``The Malta Experience,'' shown in Valletta in a
building once used as a hospital by the Knights.
</P>
<P>
   Valletta, the city, should be experienced on foot. Malta's
walled capital sits on a rocky promontory between two deep harbors
and overlooks Fort St. Angelo and Fort St. Elmo, built by the
Knights against the Turkish armada. The Knights created Valletta in
the 16th century and named it for Jean de La Valette, who was
grandmaster of the order at the time.
</P>
<P>
   Valletta's hilly streets leading down to the harbor and its
secret gardens bring San Francisco to mind. This is the seat of
parliament, where, our SMS guide John Zammit-Dimech told us, the
National Party has 35 members and the Labor Party, 30.
</P>
<P>
   Valletta also has the University of Malta and Errol Flynn's old
yacht, ``The Black Pearl,'' is moored in its harbor.
</P>
<P>
   My first visit to Valletta was on a blustery, rainy Sunday with
Agnes Spiteri, a knowledgeble SMS tour guide who once lived in the
States.
</P>
<P>
   Renato, the driver, took us along Marsamxetto Harbour to St.
John's Co-Cathedral, built by the Knights in 1573 and where, that
Sunday, Mass was being televised live by Italian television.
Malta's main and only other cathedral is in the old capital of
Mdina.
</P>
<P>
   The 16th-century cathedral is so beautiful we decided to stay
through Mass and Agnes told me about the tombs of 400 Knights under
marble slabs with their coats of arms set in St. John's marble
floors.
</P>
<P>
   Each of the order's eight auberges, or groups from the various
countries, that made up the Knights have their own chapel. Among
the cathedral's art works are two canvases by Michelangelo Merisi,
known as Caraveggio.
</P>
<P>
   Renato then drove us to Mdina where I followed the indefatigable
Agnes through the driving rain into St. Paul's Catacombs, an
underground Christian burial ground dating to the fourth and fifth
centuries, groping my way down a flight of stone steps through
narrow limestone passages, lit by oil lamps, where tombs were cut
into the rock.
</P>
<P>
   The rain made much more sightseeing in Mdina impossible, but I
was content to learn more in the car from Agnes about how
present-day Maltese live. She told me about the religious
`'festas'' that are regularly held in most Maltese towns and
villages in this predominantly Catholic country to honor their
patron saints. There are fireworks displays, the streets are
festooned with banners and flowers, and the statues are carried,
much like at the religious festivals in Boston's North End.
</P>
<P>
   I couldn't leave Malta without visiting Gozo, Malta's smaller of
its two main islands, and a 30-minute boat trip across Gozo Channel
on a boat very much like the Nantucket ferry.
</P>
<P>
   On Gozo, which is one-third the size of the main island, there
are the megalithic temples of Ggantija, which were built of local
limestone around 3600 BC, earlier, it is said, than the first
pyramid in Egypt and Stonehenge in England.
</P>
<P>
   I went on a bus tour of Gozo with Tony Piccinino, a guide for
SMS tours. Because my time was limited, I signed on with the only
tour available, for German-speaking tourists.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Tony, who is fluent not only in Maltese and English, but
also in German, I couldn't understand a word but Tony obliged with
an English version of the tour during breaks.
</P>
<P>
   When I told Tony I was from Boston, his face lit up and he asked
me if I knew Jay Leno. I told him I didn't and asked how he knew
him. ``We get everything on television in Malta,'' said Tony, a
former teacher who worked around the world for oil companies.
``That includes NBC and I watch Jay every night.'' He proved that
by reciting some of Leno's jokes.
</P>
<P>
   The Stone Age Ggantija temples are stunning and are considered
to be the oldest free-standing monuments in the world. Local legend
says that a female giant named Sunsana carried the gigantic rocks
on her head from a great distance so the temples could be built. A
more logical version is that they were moved to the site on stone
rollers.
</P>
<P>
   In Gozo's capital of Victoria, also known as Rabat, we climbed
the ramparts of the Citadel, built in medieval times and
re-fortified by the Knights and visited the cathedral in the square
of the citadel. The cathedral is dedicated to the Assumption of Our
Lady.'' It was demolished in an earthquake in 1693 and rebuilt four
years later. A ``false dome'' (a trompe l'oeil) was painted by
Antonio Manuele from Messina, Italy, and conveys the same effect.
</P>
<P>
   We also visited a shop where women were making and selling the
lace items for which Gozo is famous. In Gozo, we stopped at Dwejra
to get into small launches (for a mere $2) for a spectacular ride
through the ``Azure Window,'' a limestone grotto into the electric
blue waters of the Inland Sea.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the brevity of my stay in Malta, I was unable to
visit the many other prehistoric temples. At some of the sites
there are statues representing the Goddess of Fertility, the
so-called ``fat ladies,'' were discovered in archeological digs.
Some of the statues are in a squatting position; others standing.
They are carved out of globigerina limestone, terra cotta and
alabaster.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, I had to leave Malta before hearing any of the
``fat ladies'' sing.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
SIDEBAR &QL; 
 &QL; 
The History of Malta, according to the Web site of the Malta
Tourism Authority and others. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Maltese archipelago consists of three islands: Malta, Gozo
and Comino, the last inhabited by only a few farmers. (There are
also two uninhabited islets named Cominotto and Filfla).
</P>
<P>
   The earliest signs of human activity in Malta date back to the
Neolithic Period of about 4000 B.C. Evidence of the existence of
the New Stone Age Man was found at Ghar Dalam, a cave near
Birzebbuga in the south of Malta. Here, archeologists also
discovered the remains of animals from previous eras including
deer, hippopotami and dwarf elephants. These are remnants from the
time when Malta formed part of the land mass which connected
modern-day Europe with the African continent. Subsequent
colonizations brought a race of temple-builders, possibly from
nearby Sicily.
</P>
<P>
   The Aghlabid Arabs from North Africa started to raid the Maltese
archipelago as early as 836 A.D., but were repelled by the
Byzantines. However, a year later, they sent their fleet from
nearby Sicily and managed to overwhelm the Christian defenders.
</P>
<P>
   The Arabs held Malta for over two centuries during which the
island prospered as the new rulers introduced improved systems of
agriculture and irrigation and new produce such as cotton and
citrus fruit. However, the principal legacy of the Arab domination
of Malta is the Maltese lnguage itself which in its roots is
closely akin to Arabic.
</P>
<P>
   Arab sovereignty over Malta ended with the Norman invasion and
conquest of the islands in 1090, although their influence remained
essentially unrestricted until they were finally expelled in the
early years of the 13th century.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Norman'' period was rather short-lived and was followed by
an era of uncertainty as Malta passed through a rapid succession of
rulers; the Swabians (Germans), the Angevins (French) and the
Aragonese (Spanish).
</P>
<P>
   In 1530, the King of Spain, Emperor Charles V, granted the
islands on fief to the International Order of the Knights of St.
John of Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   The Knights administered the islands for 268 years until 1798,
when Napoleon Bonaparte drove them out and occupied the country in
the name of the French Republic.
</P>
<P>
   Following a brief occupation, the French were forced to
surrender after two years of a land and sea blockade by combined
British and Maltese forces, and in 1800, Malta became a part of the
British Empire.
</P>
<P>
   In 1964, Malta attained its indepndence and 10 years laer, in
1974, it was declared a Republic within the Commonwealth.
</P>
<P>
   Until the 1960s, the Maltese economy depended mostly on the
British services and the Naval Dockyard. After independence,
industry and tourism advanced at a fast pace and at present Malta
and Gozo have established a good industrial base and flourishing
tourist enterprise.
</P>
<P>
   The people speak their own tongue - Maltese, a language of
Semitic origin. Through the ages, many foreign words, particularly
Italian, became part of the language, and Maltese is the only
Semitic language written in Latin characters.
</P>
</TEXT>
