<SLUG> BC-COLUMN-POP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHERE'S THE HARM IN HARRY? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RENEE GRAHAM  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mere Muggle that I am _ that's Potter-speak for a mortal
untouched by magic _ I wouldn't know the difference between
Quidditch and Crookshanks, or Lord Voldemort and Rubeus Hagrid.
I've never entered the enchanted world of Harry Potter, the British
boy wizard and hero of four phenomenonally successful novels by J.
K. Rowling, although I'm starting to feel like one of the few
people who haven't. The first three books have sold a whopping 31
million copies worldwide, and the latest installment, ``Harry
Potter and the Goblet of Fire,'' received an unprecedented first
printing of nearly 4 million books, many of which were quickly
snapped up when the title was released last week.
</P>
<P>
   Since the first book, ``Harry Potter and the Sorcerer's Stone,''
was published a few years ago, the series has been all the rage
among children (and a good many adults), and praised by literary
critics and educators for introducing a generation of kids weaned
on video games and MTV to the eternal joys of reading.
</P>
<P>
   And it's all unfolded without the usual accompaniment of
McDonald's action figures and such. (That will come next year, when
the first Harry Potter movie is released. Warner Bros., which owns
the rights, has already secured nearly 50 licensing deals.)
</P>
<P>
   Imagine that _ millions of kids giddy about a series of books!
The notion of kids begging Mom or Dad to stay up past their
bedtimes so they can finish a chapter, or spending their lunch
hours debating the merits of ``Harry Potter and the Chamber of
Secrets'' vs. ``Harry Potter and the Prisoner of Azkaban,'' isn't
just heartwarming, it's miraculous.
</P>
<P>
   So for the life of me, I can't understand why some folks are
insisting the books be banned, denouncing them as dangerous and
detrimental to kids.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to some conservative Christians _ I refuse to call them
fundamentalists because there's absolutely nothing fun about these
people _ the Harry Potter series topped last year's American
Library Association list of the most-challenged books. Several
school districts have restricted access to the books. In Zeeland,
Mich., elementary and middle-school students could check the books
out of their school library only if they had a permission slip from
their parents. Zeeland superintendent Gary Feenstra also banned
reading the books aloud in classrooms. (A 14-member panel of
teachers and parents eventually overturned Feenstra's edict,
although the books are still forbidden in classrooms.)
</P>
<P>
   And the culture police were all over television this past
weekend, with their stern faces and narrow minds, yammering about
how the books could lead to devil worship, murder, even a repeat of
the Columbine tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   ``As we expose our kids to the occult, we expose our kids to
blood, to violence, we desensitize them to that,'' said the Rev.
Lori Schepers, identified on CNN as a ``troubled youth counselor.''
``What I can expect is those kids, as they mature, have a very good
chance of becoming another Dylan Klebold and those guys in
Columbine.''
</P>
<P>
   Even more absurd was Fletcher Brothers, a pastor and founder of
something called Freedom Village USA. He argued that because the
books deal with witchcraft, and witchcraft is recognized by some as
a religion _ well, I'll just let him say it:
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a religion here, and for 37 years we have lived
under this myth of the separation of church and state. And,
therefore, religion does not belong in the classroom,'' Brothers
said. ``Any pastor, any person involved in Christian work can tell
you, (anyone) who's ever tried to do anything with the public
schools, most administrators would agree that the bottom line is,
if it's religious, it cannot be in our schools.''
</P>
<P>
   He later lamented, ``We have more kids that know more about
Harry Potter than they know about Jesus Christ.'' Wow _ first the
Beatles, now Harry Potter. What's a savior gotta do to get some
respect these days?
</P>
<P>
   First of all, if Christianity has survived the lion's den and
televangelists, and Pat Buchanan, I can't imagine it being torn
asunder by a fictional wizard, and his world of hobgoblins, flying
brooms, and vengeful lords. In fact, there's never been any
indication that the books have anything at all to do with any
religion, let alone promoting one while underminding another.
</P>
<P>
   As for the violence, yes, the books can be bloody and scary.
But, I would imagine, no more so than children's fairy tales like
``Little Red Riding Hood,'' literary classics like ``The Lord of
the Rings,'' and, yes, the Bible.
</P>
<P>
   At their core, the Potter books are about good triumphing over
evil, about an orphaned child raised by cruel, uncaring relatives
who discovers that he is, in fact, quite special. Where's the
danger in that? Instead of harming children, the Potter books open
to them worlds of adventure, possibility, and, most important, a
world of words that fire up young imaginations more than any movie
or action figure could.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, the success of the Harry Potter books is something
to be celebrated, not condemned. And any myopic talk accusing the
books of being anti-Christian tools of the devil, or enemies of the
Constitution, is _ to use a bit of Potter-speak _ a crock of
codswallop.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Renee Graham covers the pop scene for The Boston Globe.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
