<HEADER>
A8992 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOK-RESERVATION-BOS &LR;      07-11 0735
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-RESERVATION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEGAL LEGERDEMAIN AND THE MAKING OF FOXWOODS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILLIAM A. DAVIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
WITHOUT RESERVATION 
The Making of America's Most Powerful Indian Tribe and Foxwoods,
the World's Largest Casino 
By Jeff Benedict 
HarperCollins, 376 pp., $26 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Despite what the title might suggest, the story Jeff Benedict
tells in ``Without Reservation'' is not an inspiring account of how
a small band of impoverished Native Americans pulled themselves up
by their own moccasin strings.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, he claims, the Mashantucket Pequots of Ledyard, Conn.,
got to be owners of the billion-dollar-a-year money machine that is
Foxwoods casino thanks to a couple of legal fast shuffles by their
leaders and lawyers. The big losers, he says, were Congress, the
State of Connecticut, and local landowners whose property the tribe
snapped up at bargain prices with taxpayers' money. And besides,
Benedict maintains, the Mashantucket Pequots aren't even an
authentic Indian tribe and should never have been allowed to open a
casino in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   For all its nonfiction importance, the book is written in a
florid, novelistic style that is more annoying than effective.
Excess verbiage often obscures important points, and lack of an
index and time line contributes to the confusion.
</P>
<P>
   There is also a lot of suspiciously precise detail about
long-past events. Twenty-five-year-old conversations are recalled
word for word, for example, and Benedict always seems to know what
the weather was on a given day, the color of socks or shirts people
wore, and even what they were thinking at key moments.
</P>
<P>
   How they did it may be in dispute, but it's a fact that no
American Indian tribe has come so far so fast as the Mashantucket
Pequots. Today, the tribe has more than 600 members (all of whom
are cut in on the casino action) living on a reservation of
2,000-plus acres. Not so many years ago there was only one
acknowleged Pequot: an elderly woman named Elizabeth George, who
lived by herself in a ramshackle house on a reservation of 214
acres. When George died of a heart attack at 78, in 1973, the
reservation was abandoned.
</P>
<P>
   Two years later George's grandson, Richard ``Skip'' Hayward,
reorganized the tribe after being contacted by Tom Tureen, a
Maine-based lawyer specializing in Indian rights. Under Hayward's
leadership, the Pequots brought a suit seeking land, a cash
settlement, and federal recognition as a tribe.
</P>
<P>
   Federal recognition _ which not incidentally brings with it the
right to operate a casino _ is usually granted by the Bureau of
Indian Affairs. As Benedict tells the story, Tureen's brilliant
legal maneuvering enabled the Pequots to sidestep the rigorous BIA
recognition process. As part of a 1983 settlement, the tribe was
federally recognized by act of Congress, something rarely done.
</P>
<P>
   Federal recognition guidelines require among other things that a
tribe have a long-standing organization, preserve Native American
culture and traditions, and be in continuous occupation of any land
claimed. The long-scattered and much-intermarried Pequots could
meet none of these standards, in Benedict's opinion. He also
asserts that genealogical records show that Elizabeth George _
supposedly the link to the original Pequot tribe _ was not a Pequot
at all but descended from the Narragansett tribe of Rhode Island.
Congress might also have acted differently, according to Benedict,
had the Pequots not concealed their intentions to start gaming
operations on their reservation.
</P>
<P>
   Money can't buy harmony, and Benedict reports that the
Mashantucket Pequots are now a deeply divided tribe. Although still
very large, their casino revenues are declining, and the tribe has
amassed considerable debt because of what Benedict describes as
lavish spending and poor supervision. The tribe is also now
bitterly split between those members who had previously identified
themselves as Caucasians and others who had been considered
African-American.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without Reservation'' has been denounced by tribal leaders,
who declined to cooperate with Benedict while he was researching
it. However, there have also been calls for a congressional
investigation that could lead to revocation of the tribe's federal
status. The odds of that happening are long, but the odds don't
always favor the house.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
