<HEADER>
A8993 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l BC-FASHION-FAT-HNS &LR;      07-11 0805
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASHION-FAT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     HOW TO DRESS WITHOUT WORRYING ABOUT THE EXTRA POUNDS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By CYNTHIA ROBINS  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Whether she's a petite or a 3X, when a woman
tries on clothes and peeks at herself in a three-way mirror, she
always asks: ``Does this make me look fat?''
</P>
<P>
   You don't hear guys discussing their posteriors in a new pair of
Dockers (unless it's a parody ad), and you certainly don't hear
them voicing too much concern that maybe they have THO (Tummy
Hang-Over) from too many slices of pizza and Bud. So . . . this is
truly a girl thing. Much to our chagrin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Does This Make Me Look Fat?'' is also the title of clothing
consultant and ``Today Show'' contributor Leah Feldon's latest
book. She has subtitled it: ``The definitive rules for dressing
thin for every height, size and shape.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Women say this all the time, and men don't because women have
many more curves than men have,'' Feldon said. ``Men are flat
chested, and dressing well is a matter of proportion to them. Plus,
they don't have to deal with hemlines. They wear pants _ basically
a uniform _ and they deal with very few variations. Most women wear
totally different looks all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   And not all of them are flattering.
</P>
<P>
   Feldon, a petite, dark, leggy woman with a gamine face and a
bubbly manner, is the kind of woman other women envy. She is
slender and stylish, given to black clothes and good gold jewelry.
In other words, she's very New York fashionista, mitigated by the
fact that she lives with her songwriter husband in Nashville,
Tenn., most of the time, where, she groans, ``there is absolutely
no place to shop.''
</P>
<P>
   Shopping used to be her career, especially in the 1970s and
1980s when she styled shoots for television and print advertising,
including Revlon, Clairol, Monet jewelry and Black Velvet whiskey.
Burned out with New York, she headed to Florida, where she
co-hosted ``PM Magazine'' in Jacksonville. But before long she
moved to the West Coast, while still writing for People magazine
and appearing on the ``Today Show'' with Jane Pauley and Tom
Brokaw. Her first book was ``Woman Style,'' which, she says,
``explained the nitty-gritty of color, line, texture, design and
composition,'' the very things she was taught as an art history
major in college.
</P>
<P>
   So she's heard that particular question: ``Does this make me
look fat?'' enough times to call it ``the universal fashion
question. I figure: Why would anyone want to look heavier?'' she
says laughing.
</P>
<P>
   The book is detailed and covers topics from ``the Ten Top
Reasons for Camouflage Chic'' to ``The Most Common Mistakes We
Women Make'' (which include following fads; not finding a
``uniform'' or a specific set of clothes that will take you
everywhere; choosing quantity over quality; and how to tame the
chaos of an unorganized closet _ else how do you know what you
already own?). But to hone it down to it simplest outlines, I asked
Feldon to give Five Rules of Thumb for thinning fashion tips
dressing thin that work for everyone.
</P>
<P>
   _ Go monochromatic. A dark, one-color silhouette always makes
you look a lot thinner than you are. And, she said, you can always
add a color accent like a great pin or a scarf.
</P>
<P>
   _ The vertical thing. ``Look for vertical lines in design,''
Feldon said, ``with longer, smaller lapels which will bring the eye
up and down. No double-breasted coats.'' She also warned: No
horizontal stripes if you're hippy and no belts to break up the
line of a longish jacket if you're short waisted.
</P>
<P>
   _ Make it fit. Forget sizes, Feldon said. Buy what fits. She
said the clothes in her closet vary from size 4 to size 8. ``Even
within some brands, clothes will fit differently.'' The point is:
``You don't have to look like you're wearing somebody else's
clothes. If it's too big, it'll make you look fat.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Camouflage. Accentuation of the positive and visually
eliminating the negative sounds very pat, but it works. For
instance, if you have what Feldon calls ``thunder thighs,'' avoid
Spandex pants and Bermuda shorts. If your upper arms tend to be
heavy, avoid sleeveless dresses or dresses where a sleeve hits you
at the chubbiest part. ``Throw a chiffon scarf over your arms and
shoulders,'' Feldon said. The point here is looking in the mirror
and being very truthful with yourself as to your figure's assets
and debits and dress them accordingly.
</P>
<P>
   _ Accessorize. ``You know how the wrong shoes can absolutely
ruin an outfit,'' Feldon said, ``like wearing clunky shoes with
chiffon. . . . Chunky heels on sandals look awful from the back.
They make a heavy leg look heavier and a slim woman look
ungraceful. I'm still into elegance and grace _ which won't go out
of style any time soon.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
