<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-11 14:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9002 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l BC-SPONGE-CONTRACEPTIVE-     07-11 0682
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPONGE-CONTRACEPTIVE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     CONTRACEPTIVE SPONGE MAY RETURN TO THE MARKET 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By RICHARD A. MARINI  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Today contraceptive sponge, immortalized in an episode of
the television show ``Seinfeld'' and unavailable since 1995, may
soon be back on drugstore shelves if it clears a few remaining
regulatory hurdles.
</P>
<P>
   Introduced in 1983, the Today Vaginal Contraceptive Sponge was
easy to use, available without a prescription and could be left in
place for up to 24 hours and through multiple acts of intercourse.
The soft, polyurethane foam device acted as a physical barrier
between sperm and the cervix and also contained the spermicide
nonoxynol-9.
</P>
<P>
   For a time, Today was the best-selling over-the-counter female
contraceptive device on the market, selling 250 million sponges by
the time its manufacturer, Whitehall-Robins Healthcare, voluntarily
removed it from the market in January 1995. While there were never
any serious questions about the safety and efficacy of the device,
the company decided it would be too expensive and time-consuming to
make government-mandated upgrades to its manufacturing plant in
Hammonton, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the time we determined it would take 36 months to get the
product back on the market,'' said Fran Sullivan, a spokeswoman for
the Madison, N.J.-based company. ``By then, too many consumers
would have switched to other contraceptive devices.''
</P>
<P>
   In what has become a classic ``Seinfeld,'' the character Elaine
is so distraught that Today is being taken off the market that she
decides to use her dwindling supply only with men lucky enough to
be deemed ``spongeworthy.''
</P>
<P>
   Allendale Pharmaceuticals Inc. recently purchased the rights to
the Today sponge, including the name and manufacturing equipment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm astounded by the awareness of this product,'' said Gene
Detroyer, president and chief executive of the Allentown, Pa.-based
company.
</P>
<P>
   The company originally announced it would begin marketing the
sponge by late spring or mid-summer. But according to Detroyer, the
Food and Drug Administration, which regulates contraceptive
devices, has cancelled two scheduled plant inspections necessary
for final approval. And the FDA's non-prescription drug advisory
committee has also scheduled a hearing for Wednesday to discuss the
re-marketing and labeling of the product.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Staab, chairman and chief scientific officer of the
company, said he is puzzled by the hearing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sponge was approved back in the early '80s and the science
behind it hasn't changed. I think it's just a matter of some
well-intentioned bureaucrats who want to make sure the product is
reviewed as thoroughly as it possibly can be.''
</P>
<P>
   He also expressed concern that the advisory committee will
recommend labeling changes that may confuse users by misstating the
sponge's pregnancy prevention rate. Most, but not all, peg it at 80
percent to 90 percent. Failure of the device is largely blamed on
misuse.
</P>
<P>
   ``The act of lovemaking is a very personal matter,'' he said.
``And each couple must choose the contraceptive method that's best
for them.''
</P>
<P>
   The advisory committee can either recommend approval of the
labeling as is, or suggest changes. Advisory committee
recommendations are usually accepted by the FDA.
</P>
<P>
   While applauding another birth control option, Jeffrey Hons,
head of the San Antonio office of Planned Parenthood, said he did
not expect the Today sponge to greatly shake up the market.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'll be one of a number of over-the-counter contraceptives
available, but I don't see it being more popular than the birth
control pill or sterilization for women, or the condom for men.''
</P>
<P>
   Hons also warned that the sponge will stop the spread of
sexually transmitted disease.
</P>
<P>
   The Today sponge has already been approved for sale in Canada
and should be available there in the coming weeks. In the United
States, it is expected to sell for about $2 per sponge and come in
packages of three, six and 12 sponges.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
