<P>
   MIDEAST-SUMMIT _ CAMP DAVID, Md. _ Spot coverage of the the
opening of final status peace talks between Israel and the
Palestinians. President Clinton is taking a major gamble to push
the stalled negotiations to a resolution of a final framework. The
talks will focus on three issues: the future of Jerusalem; borders
of a Palestinian state; and fate of millions of Palestinian
refugees around the world. Developing. (Deans, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-GRASSROOTS _ JERUSALEM _ Right-wing Israelis are taking
to the streets to save, as they see it, their land and homes.
Left-wingers turned out Tuesday night to save their prime minister.
Still traumatized by the 1995 assassination of peace-making Prime
Minister Yitzhak Rabin, some left-wing Israelis vow they will show
more support for a peacemaker this time. Some feel their silence in
1995 helped create the atmosphere for Rabin's death and they don't
want to repeat the mistake. The battle for the grassroots is under
way and even Ehud Barak, while meeting in Camp David, will be
keeping an eye on public opinion polls back home. (Kaplow, Copx
News Service).
</P>
