<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-11 14:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9008 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-SUNWISE12-COX     07-11 0481
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUNWISE12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EPA OFFERS SCHOOLS 'SUNWISE' PROGRAM TO CUT SKIN CANCER RISK
 &HT;    By ROB O'DELL
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The federal government and local schools are
teaming up to teach children about the dangers of sun exposure.
</P>
<P>
   The SunWise program, offered by the Environmental Protection
Agency, is designed to provide schools a free and easy way to teach
children how to protect themselves from overexposure to the sun and
how to develop sun-safe behaviors, said Linda Rutsch, the program's
schools coordinator.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the long run, the SunWise program hopes to reduce instances
of skin cancer, but for now we want to educate children about the
harmful effects of the sun,'' Rutsch said. ``Because the majority
of a person's exposure to the sun occurs during youth, now it is a
critical time to get the message to young people.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Joel Wilentz, a dermatologist from Hallandale, Fla., said
although adults are often warned about the dangers of the sun,
children are often allowed to play in the sun unprotected.
</P>
<P>
   ``The skin never forgets it exposure to the sun,'' Wilentz said.
``One bad sunburn during childhood doubles the chance of getting
skin cancer later in life.''
</P>
<P>
   It is estimated that 80 percent of a person's lifetime exposure
to the sun occurs before the age of 18, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The SunWise program provides its partner schools with classroom
lessons and background information for kindergarten through eighth
grade. The program teaches children about sunscreen, use of proper
clothing, and limiting exposure to the sun at the times when it is
strongest, Rutsch said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The SunWise program is designed to provide maximum
flexibility, because the program can be used as stand-alone
teaching tools or to complement existing school curricula,'' Rutsch
said. ``The time commitment necessary to implement SunWise is
minimal, but the potential payoff in lower skin cancer rates is
very high.''
</P>
<P>
   The program also includes information about sun exposure through
the EPA's Web site, and allows students to study daily measurements
of ultraviolet radiation, Rutsch said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Through the site, the students can study daily UV data,
weather conditions, and daily sun-protection practices,'' Rutsch
said. ``The students can study the UV index on the National Weather
Service's Web site, and measure the amount of UV by using hand-held
monitoring devices that are loaned to the schools by the SunWise
program.''
</P>
<P>
   More than 200 schools are participating in the SunWise program
nationwide. Schools, individual classrooms or entire school
districts can register either on line or by sending a registration
form to the EPA.
</P>
<P>
   On the Web: www.epa.gov/sunwise
</P>
<P>
   Rob O'Dell's e-mail address is rodell(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
