<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEDDING-SNAKES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     HOLY MENAGERIE: COUPLE TIE KNOT AMID SNAKES AND BATS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JENNIFER A. DLOUHY  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW BRAUNFELS, Texas _ A Corpus Christi couple exchanged ``I
do's'' Monday over the bleating of goats and screeching of macaws
at the Snake Farm 30 miles north of San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   This wasn't a traditional wedding, with flowing dresses,
pristine pews and an altar bedecked with flowers. Instead, guests
congregated at picnic tables under a shelter, while Michael
Stockton, 23, slipped a ring on the finger of Danita Palmer, 18.
Rubber snakes dangled from the rafters. Palmer's long white dress
skimmed the dirt.
</P>
<P>
   And, just feet away were a host of unusual witnesses: baboons
and bats and bearded dragons, chickens and a chuckawala lizard,
ostriches and iguanas, an emu and a snapping turtle.
</P>
<P>
   Also: Hissing cockroaches crawling in a nearby aquarium, the
calico cat wandering underfoot, or the diamondback rattlesnakes
slithering in a snake pit.
</P>
<P>
   It was an unusual setting for a matrimonial exchange, but for
Palmer and Stockton, a fitting one.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're both just crazy about reptiles,'' said Palmer's
mother, Mona. ``She works at a pet shop. He works at the Humane
Society.''
</P>
<P>
   And together, they own more than 10 of the creatures, including
an Indian Python and a legless lizard.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like a zoo over there,'' said Mona Palmer, who doesn't
share her daughter's appreciation for all things slithering.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once, she told me, she was playing with the snake and fell
asleep. When she woke up, the snake had slid under her shirt,''
Palmer said, shuddering. ``Eww.''
</P>
<P>
   Stockton has traded snakes with Snake Farm owner John Mellyn
since Mellyn took over the roadside attraction six years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``We always came up to the Snake Farm. We love this place,''
said Graham Criglow, one of Stockton's friends. ``We're not normal
people. This is what we enjoy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it would be great,'' Mellyn said. ``After all ...
people like to get married on roller coasters these days.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, this is a first for the tourist hot spot along Interstate
35. Although it has been luring school groups and picnickers for
more than 30 years, the Snake Farm has never been a draw for
brides-to-be.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-11-00 1459EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
