<HEADER>
A9031 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-PROFESSOR-SMOKING-HNS     07-11 0500
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PROFESSOR-SMOKING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     COURT CLEARS PROFESSOR TO OPPOSE SMOKING 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By BOB EGELKO  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A California appellate court says that a leading
critic of the tobacco industry can continue to fight smoking from
his perch as a University of California professor.
</P>
<P>
   An industry-allied group, Californians for Scientific Integrity,
sued the University of California in 1998 over Stanton Glantz's use
of his university job and resources to push for tougher state
action against smoking. The suit contended that Glantz's activities
were a misuse of tax money.
</P>
<P>
   But the 3rd District Court of Appeal said Glantz's activity was
authorized by the Legislature, which has directed the state to
``play a leading role in promoting a smoke-free society by the year
2000.''
</P>
<P>
   Glantz, a professor of medicine at UC-San Francisco, was a
founder and former president of Californians for Nonsmokers'
Rights. He has worked for state and local bans on smoking in public
buildings and for stronger messages in state-funded anti-smoking
ads.
</P>
<P>
   His studies on smoking and health have been disputed by tobacco
companies, which have tried to get Congress and the California
Legislature to cut off his government funding. The suit by
Californians for Scientific Integrity initially included a
challenge to the validity of a study by Glantz that found that
prohibitions on smoking in restaurants did not hurt tourism. That
claim was later dropped and the group ultimately sought only to
halt the alleged misuse of state funds for lobbying.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were attempting to intimidate me and the university,''
Glantz said Monday. ``The university stood up to the thugs in
cigarette companies again and won again.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark A. Perry, a lawyer for the group that sued the university,
said no decision has been made on a further appeal. He said he
disagreed with the court's conclusion that the general statements
in state law about a smoke-free society authorized Glantz to use
state funds to promote anti-smoking policies.
</P>
<P>
   Perry denied Glantz's assertion that Californians for Scientific
Integrity was a front for the tobacco industry, but said it is
partially funded by the National Smokers' Alliance, which draws
funding from tobacco companies.
</P>
<P>
   The appellate ruling, issued Thursday, upheld a decision by
Sacramento County Superior Court Judge Joe Gray to dismiss the
lawsuit without a trial. The court said California law forbids
certain types of state-funded political activities, such as the use
of state funds to influence election campaigns, but does not
prohibit activity that the Legislature itself has authorized.
</P>
<P>
   ``The state of California has taken an unambiguous position
against smoking and tobacco-related diseases'' and has chosen the
university, through research and education, ``to play an integral
part in achieving those goals,'' Justice Fred Morrison said in the
3-0 ruling.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-11-00 1513EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
