<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PAGEEXPRESS-BUDGET-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 PageExpress budget for the week of July 10, 2000
<TEXT>
<P>
   PageExpress, a new service from The New York Times Syndicate,
consists of paginated pages built with content from Cox Newspapers
and The New York Times News Service. The pages are easy to retrieve
from a web site. You can use them just as they are or customize any
or all of the elements _ text, fonts, photos and graphics _ to suit
your needs.
</P>
<P>
   For more information on these pages, or to view a sample, use
your web browser to visit http://nytsyn.com/pageexpress.
</P>
<P>
   For the password to download and use the pages, call Bob Farnell
at The New York Times Syndicate: 800-972-3550 or e-mail him at
farnellb &LR; nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   Unless otherwise noted, pages are available after 2 p.m. Tue.,
July 11.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FOOD &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PAGE INCLUDES FOUR COLOR PHOTOS
</P>
<P>
   AMERICAN PIE: Whether based on fruits, nuts, vegetables or
custards, pies have played a rich role in our culinary heritage for
hundreds of years. (Includes 5-column color photo illustration of
an apple pie and American icons, 1-column color photo of three
cherries.)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: TIPS BOX: Tips for making a perfect crust.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: BAKING TIPS: Tips on how to make perfect pies. (Includes
2-column color photo of a maple nutcracker pie.)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: RECIPE: Recipe for Cherry Pie. (Includes 1-column color
photo of a slice of cherry pie.)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: CYBERSPICE: Many cooks choose to improve their dishes by
adding liquor.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHEELS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PAGE INCLUDES THREE COLOR PHOTOS
</P>
<P>
   2000 MAZDA 626 ES: Mazda claims to have made dozens of changes
to its family-oriented 626 sedan for the 2000 model year. The
improvements are striking, more so inside than outside. (Includes
4-column color photo of the 2000 Mazda 626 ES, 1-column color photo
of the car's interior.)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: AT A GLANCE: Fact box previewing the 2000 Mazda 626 ES.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: SHARP DRIVING: Old-fashioned rules of civility should
still apply to driving on our nation's roads. (Includes 1-column
color photo of columnist.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PERSONAL TECHNOLOGY &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PAGE INCLUDES FIVE COLOR PHOTOS
</P>
<P>
   GIRLS ARE GEEKS, TOO: A Texas software designer is going
straight to the source to find out what girls like and dislike
about technology. The results of her informal interviews will
translate into future products. (Includes 4-column color photo of
girls working on a computer at a slumber party, 1-column color
photo of the software designer.)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: LIST BOX: A list of facts about the use of technology by
teens.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: TECHNOBUDDY: There are some great pieces of technology out
there, and here is where I tell you about some of the ones that
impress me and are useful in my life. (Includes 1-column color sig
of columnist.)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: GADGETS: Canon has introduced a printer designed for
people who use set-top boxes, such as Microsoft's WebTV, to browse
the Internet via their televisions. (Includes 18-pica color photo
of the printer.)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: TECH TOOLS: Ontrack's SystemSuite 2000 goes head-to-head
with Norton's SystemWorks and comes out pretty well. (Includes a
6-pica color photo of cover of software package.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TRAVEL &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PAGE INCLUDES THREE COLOR PHOTOS
</P>
<P>
   FUN IN JAZZLAND: Jazzland opened May 20 on the outskirts of New
Orleans expecting to attract 1.5 million visitors during its
110-day season. Five themed areas _ Jazz Plaza, Kids' Carnival,
Mardi Gras, Pontchartrain Beach and Cajun Country _ feature a gumbo
of rides, shops and restaurants. (Includes a 3-column color photo
of a dancer at Jazzland.)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: JAZZLAND BOX: A list of things to do when at Jazzland.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: BIG EASY FISHES Something fishy is going on in the
Crescent City this summer. The place is literally swimming with
fish _ more than 200 big ones, creatively painted by Louisiana
artists. (Includes a 6-pica color photo of a painted fish.)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: TRAVEL GUIDE: Fodor, the travel-guide giant, has issued a
new line of books that takes portability to the extreme. (Includes
a 3-column color photo of a pocket travel guide.)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: TRAVEL BRIEFS: Bored airline passengers now have a new way
to spend their time. Others.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BOOKS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PAGE INCLUDES FOUR COLOR PHOTOS, ONE COLOR ILLUSTRATION.
</P>
<P>
   WILD ABOUT HARRY POTTER: With the release of the latest
installment in the ``Harry Potter'' series, Harry mania is sweeping
the nation. Here is a primer in case you've missed the frenzy.
(Includes a 4-column color illustration of a girl dreaming about
Harry Potter scenes.)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: OBITUARY WRITER: In ``The Obituary Writer'' the drama of a
failed journalist comes in dead on arrival.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: KOREA BOOKS: Three new books explore the often debated
Korean Conflict. (Includes three 18-pica color photos of books.)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: N.Y. TIMES BEST SELLERS LIST
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HEALTHY LIVING PAGE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PAGE INCLUDES TWO COLOR ILLUSTRATIONS
</P>
<P>
   MEDICAL MYTHS: Propelled by e-mail and the Internet, hoaxes that
prey on the anxieties of ordinary people are proliferating as never
before. They have become so common, in fact, that the Atlanta-based
Centers for Disease Control and Prevention has introduced a page on
its Web site to knock them down. (Includes a 4-column color
illustration of a comic-book cover with the subject being medical
horrors.)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: WEB BOX: A list of Web sites to learn more about medical
hoaxes. (Includes 18-pica color illustration of a computer.)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: HOAX TIPS: A list of tips to help you avoid falling for
medical misinformation.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: HOAX LIST: A list of some of the most famous medical
hoaxes.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: MENINGITIS: The Centers for Disease Control has issued an
appeal to students to be aware of the dangers of meningitis.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: MENINGITIS BOX: Answers to some basic questions on
meningitis.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LIFESTYLES: HOME &AMP; GARDEN (Available by 2 p.m., Thu., July 13) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   KEEPING IT GREEN: This summer you're determined to keep your
grass green no matter what extremes Mother Nature dishes out.
Neither temperatures in the triple digits nor weeks without rain
will prevent you from having a lush lawn that will be the envy of
all your neighbors. (Includes color photos depicting ways to keep
your lawn green during the summer.)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: LAWN TIPS: Additional tips to make sure your yard stays
green and healthy.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: PAINT JOB: Painting takes so much work that it's a good
idea to do it right and get the most years possible out of the job.
(Includes 18-pica color photo of a man using a paint roller.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NASCAR (Available by 5 p.m., Thu., July 13) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   STICKING THROTTLE: Drivers think NASCAR needs to approve a
button that would allow engines to be cut off in cases where
throttles stick. It appears stuck throttles contributed to the
deaths of drivers Adam Petty and Kenny Irwin. Other racing circuits
have ``escape'' buttons when these incidents happen.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: NASCAR IMAGE: NASCAR drivers say they aren't ready for
sainthood, but they have been able to avoid the bad headlines
created by athletes in other sports.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: DRIVER STANDINGS/WINSTON CUP
</P>
<P>
   WITH: DRIVER STANDINGS/BUSCH SERIES
</P>
<P>
   WITH: WINSTON CUP MONEY LEADERS
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FOCUS (Available by 5 p.m., Fri., July 14) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CLASSIC CARS, ANCIENT CITY: The names come out a little
differently in Arabic. DeSoto becomes something like ``Tozata'' and
Chrysler sounds like ``Kleezler.'' But those old bombs you might
find in an auto collector's garage in America make for colorful and
practical transportation in Syria. The country's streets are flush
with fins and crawling with chrome. (Includes a 3-column color
photo of a classic car sitting in a garage, a 2-column detail shot
of a car, a 3-column photo of a Syrian in front of his car and a
2-column color photo of a Syrian working on his car.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
