<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SF-INITIATIVES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     VOTERS MAY GET A BREAK FROM USUAL FLURRY OF BALLOT ISSUES 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JIM HERRON ZAMORA and ILENE LELCHUK  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ San Francisco is famous for its long ballots,
but so far this year only an initiative limiting political
donations is certain to be voted on in November.
</P>
<P>
   However, supporters of three other initiatives delivered
thousands of signatures to the Department of Elections by Monday's
deadline in the hopes of getting their measures on the ballot.
Voters may also get a chance to create a municipal utility district
to compete with the Pacific Gas and Electric Co.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the three voter initiatives are sponsored by tenant
groups and already have drawn legal challenges from landlords.
</P>
<P>
   The third measure would ban cars on Saturdays from a section of
Golden Gate Park along JFK Drive, already the rule on Sundays.
Sponsored by cyclists and in-line skaters, the measure has not yet
drawn significant opposition.
</P>
<P>
   The Board of Supervisors and Mayor Willie Brown each have until
Aug. 9 to add initiatives of their own. So far it is not clear that
they will add anything.
</P>
<P>
   Supervisors Gavin Newsom and Mark Leno have been floating the
idea of a November ballot measure to make it city policy to support
nonprofit education uses for the waterfront over new, glitzy
commercial tourist attractions. The idea comes in negative response
to a proposal, approved by the Port Commission, to create a faux
San Francisco attraction on the waterfront.
</P>
<P>
   Supervisors also are deciding whether they can put a measure on
the ballot to create a municipal utility district with an elected
board.
</P>
<P>
   The Coalition for Lower Utility Bills wants voters to have a
city-owned alternative to PG&AMP;E. The group, which turned in 23,400
signatures last week, contends that public utility districts charge
about 23 percent less for electricity than corporations.
</P>
<P>
   But the city attorney's office maintains that the planned voter
initiative would bypass state laws governing the creation of new
utility districts. The Board of Supervisors has taken up the
matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we can't get the board to put us on the November ballot,
then we will ask a judge to put us on,'' said Neil Eisenberg, a
supporter of the initiative.
</P>
<P>
   The tenants issues have drawn the most controversy.
</P>
<P>
   One would restrict the practice known as ``tenants in common,''
in which unrelated investors form groups to buy duplexes or
apartment buildings and then each participating investor takes a
unit as his or her home. The process takes rentals off the market.
But it often allows renters who could not otherwise afford to buy
real estate to become homeowners.
</P>
<P>
   The other initiative would limit rent increases that landlords
charge tenants to pay for improvements or renovations to a rental
property.
</P>
<P>
   In the past week landlords have filed suits against both
measures, claiming violations of state and federal law. The
landlords will ask judges to keep each initiative off the ballot,
but so far neither suit has been heard in court.
</P>
<P>
   The only initiative already on the ballot is sponsored by the
city's Ethics Commission. Because it was put on the ballot by the
commission, the initiative did not require the signatures of nearly
10,000 registered voters. The measure would create a public
financing scheme in races for the governing Board of Supervisors.
</P>
<P>
   Under the plan, candidates for supervisor would be eligible for
public money if they agree to spending caps: $75,000 in the general
election and $20,000 more for runoffs. They also would have to
raise at least $7,500 on their own in individual amounts under
$100.
</P>
<P>
   Each qualified supervisorial candidate could receive up to
$60,750 in taxpayer money under the plan. The total yearly cost
could not exceed $2 per San Francisco resident. The has nearly
800,000 residents.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
