<SLUG> BC-GIULIANI-RATS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE MAYOR SMELLS A RAT NEAR HOME 
</HEADLINE>
   By ERIC LIPTON    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Citing frequent encounters with rats on his porch at
Gracie Mansion, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani announced the formation of a
new city task force Monday to examine ways to control the rodent
population in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rats are horrible,'' Giuliani said, recalling the uninvited
visitors to his porch with its East River views during recent
summers.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you see them, no matter how immune you are to anything or
how brave you think you are, the rats get you really scared. They
can bite you, they can spread disease and they are frightening
animals.''
</P>
<P>
   The creation of the task force comes after reports in recent
weeks of intense rat infestation problems in Queens County and at
the Baruch Houses on the Lower East Side public housing project.
</P>
<P>
   The city, Giuliani said, is looking for new ways to intensify
the battle. City Councilman Bill Perkins, who held a recent hearing
on the problem, said one step could be to appoint a ``rat czar'' to
coordinate how city agencies respond to sightings. Perkins and
Councilman Stephen Fiala have also proposed legislation that would
require developers to exterminate rats before starting construction
projects.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani encouraged city residents not to expect too much.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is unrealistic to think you are not going to have rats,''
the mayor said, before adding, without hesitation, that ``you
should not have as many as we have.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
