<SLUG> BC-ARTS-AWARDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRAEMIUM IMPERIALE WINNERS ARE   NAMED 
</HEADLINE>
   By KATHRYN SHATTUCK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The American painter Ellsworth Kelly, the French sculptor Niki
de Saint Phalle, the British architect Richard Rogers, the German
composer Hans Werner Henze and the American composer and lyricist
Stephen Sondheim are the recipients of the 12th Praemium Imperiale
Awards, presented by the Japan Art Association for outstanding
achievement in the arts. The recipients were announced Tuesday at a
ceremony at the Tate Modern in London.
</P>
<P>
   The five awards, among the largest in the arts with a stipend of
about $140,000 each, are given in areas not covered by the Nobel
Prizes: painting, sculpture, architecture, music, and theater-film.
The prizes will be presented, along with commemorative medals from
the Japanese imperial family, in Tokyo on Oct. 26.
</P>
<P>
   Recipients of the awards are selected each year by the art
association on the recommendations of a board of international
advisers representing Britain, France, Germany, Italy, Japan and
the United States. Past recipients have included the actor John
Gielgud, the painter David Hockney, the architect Frank O. Gehry
and the cellist Mstislav Rostropovich.
</P>
<P>
   The association also presents a grant of about $47,000 to an
organization that supports the development of young artists. This
year's winner is the Ulster Youth Orchestra, which said it planned
to use the award to perform and study in England for the first
time.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement ceremonies are rotated among the advisers' home
cities. This year's host was Sir Edward Heath, the former British
prime minister, who has been an adviser since the awards began in
1989.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
