A9095 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-SIMPLE-COOKING-NYT &LR;      07-11 0567
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIMPLE-COOKING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONION CONFIT FIT FOR TUNA 
</HEADLINE>
   By MARK BITTMAN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Cooking onions very slowly brings out amazing flavor,
a rich sweetness. Just by themselves they taste great, but when you
combine them with the liquid exuded by olives and tomatoes, you get
a gloriously juicy base for any fish fillet or steak. With meaty
grilled tuna or swordfish, the onions make an easy summer dish with
a Provencal accent.
</P>
<P>
   Onions cooked this way can be considered a confit, a term that
has been adapted to apply to almost any food that is slow-cooked to
achieve the ultimate in tenderness. A confit often involves lots of
fat, but onions give off so much liquid you need very little, just
a few tablespoons of olive oil. They essentially stew in their own
juices. The only considerations are a low flame and a fair amount
of time, about 30 to 40 minutes. The onions should not brown at
all.
</P>
<P>
   While the onions are cooking, you can finish the rest of the
dish. As the grill is heating for the fish, pit and chop the olives
and dice the tomatoes. I don't bother to skin them; just core them
and shake out most of their seeds before chopping them. Grilling
the fish takes just six minutes if you use tuna, closer to 10
minutes if you choose to overlook the current boycott (based on
possible overfishing) and use swordfish. The fish can be cooked as
individual steaks or in one slab, then cut into serving portions.
</P>
<P>
   Thyme is the perfect herb for the onions, but you can use bay
leaf instead, or you can finish the dish with a handful of chopped
basil, chervil or parsley. If you like, you can also cook some
finely chopped aromatic vegetables, like carrots, celery, fennel
and garlic, along with the onions.
</P>
<P>
   The fish is very straightforward: just seasoned and grilled.
Although I like this dish best with tuna or swordfish, it's almost
as good with grilled boneless chicken breasts, as long as they're
not overcooked.
</P>
<P>
   TUNA OR SWORDFISH WITH ONION CONFIT
</P>
<P>
   Time: 45 minutes
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   3 large or 4 or 5 medium onions, peeled and thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 large thyme sprig or 1 bay leaf
</P>
<P>
   2 medium tomatoes, cored
</P>
<P>
   1{ to 2 pounds tuna or swordfish, cut into steaks or left whole
</P>
<P>
   About { cup pitted and roughly chopped black olives.
</P>
<P>
   1. Put olive oil in a 10- or 12-inch skillet, and turn heat to
medium. Add onions, a good pinch of salt, pepper and bay leaf or
thyme. Cook, stirring, until mixture starts to sizzle, a minute or
two. Adjust heat so that you need to stir at most only every 5
minutes to keep onions from browning as they soften; do not allow
to brown. Cook at least 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   2. Meanwhile, cut tomatoes in half and shake out seeds, then cut
into {-inch dice. Heat a grill until moderately hot.
</P>
<P>
   3. When onions are very soft, almost a shapeless mass, season
fish and grill, turning once, for a total of about 6 minutes for
tuna, 8 to 10 minutes for swordfish; check for doneness by making a
small cut in center to peek inside. While fish is grilling, stir
olives and tomatoes into onions, and raise heat; cook, stirring
occasionally, until tomatoes liquefy and mixture becomes juicy.
Taste, and adjust seasoning. Serve fish on a bed of onion confit,
whole fish cut into serving portions.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-11-00 1557EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000711.0133 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-11 16:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9099 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-ROME-MUSEUM-NYT &LR;      07-11 1014
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROME-MUSEUM-NYT </SLUG>
  
 STATUE OF `SHE-WOLF' SEPARATED FROM CHILDREN FOR FIRST TIME IN 500
YEARS   By ELISABETTA POVOLEDO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME _ Forcibly separating a mother from her young children is
always heartbreaking. It is even harder when they have been
together 500 years. But that is what has happened here, where a
bronze, ``The She-Wolf'' of the Capitoline Museums, has been
separated from her legendary (and also bronze) children, Romulus
and Remus, for an exhibition celebrating the myth of the founding
of Rome.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition, which runs until Oct. 15, inaugurates the
opening of a new area of the Capitoline Museums, renowned for their
collection of ancient Roman sculptures, including ``Dying Gaul,''
the ``Capitoline Venus'' and the ``Resting Faun,'' which inspired
Nathaniel Hawthorne's 19th-century novel ``The Marble Faun.''
Admired by generations of illustrious visitors (the Italian poet
Giovanni Pascoli even wrote odes to their statues), the museums
also have an important collection of paintings by Titian,
Caravaggio, Guido Reni and Rubens.
</P>
<P>
   ``The She-Wolf'' has always been a symbol of the Eternal City,
diffused throughout the ancient world by Roman coins bearing the
image. ``The She-Wolf'' celebrated in the exhibition is a
fifth-century-B.C. statue donated to the city in 1471 by Pope
Sixtus IV along with three other bronze statues that had been at
the Lateran Palace. These statues formed the core of the Capitoline
Museums collection, the world's oldest collection of public art.
</P>
<P>
   The bronze statues of Romulus and Remus were added after ``The
She-Wolf'' arrived on the Capitoline. They were separated for
restoration and study, but this has not produced any definitive
indication of their possible creator or of their age, though
scholars agree that the twins date from the Renaissance.
</P>
<P>
   The legend of Romulus and Remus, the founders of Rome, is
thought by some scholars to date to the fourth century BC. The twin
sons of Rhea Silvia and the god Mars, they were ordered drowned in
the Tiber. Luckily for them, the basin in which they were placed
came to rest at the site of the future Rome, and a she-wolf suckled
them until the shepherd Faustulus found them.
</P>
<P>
   For five centuries Romans were accustomed to seeing the chubby
cherublike brothers suckling the ferocious-looking ``She-Wolf.''
But today they are motherless.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is the first time the twins have been separated from the
Lupa in 500 years,'' said Claudio Parisi Presicce, who coordinated
the scientific and technical aspects of the exhibition. ``I hope
they won't suffer.''
</P>
<P>
   He says that the technique used for casting the statues, similar
to that used to make armor, may mean it was done in a famous
workshop in Ferrara, which was very much in vogue at the end of the
15th century.
</P>
<P>
   ``The She-Wolf'' and the statues of Romulus and Remus are on
show in separate rooms in a new gallery for temporary exhibitions,
part of a $20 million restoration that will more than double the
Capitoline Museums area by the end of 2001. In late April the first
phase of the so-called Grande Campidoglio (the big Campidoglio, as
the Capitoline Hill is known in Italian) was completed.
</P>
<P>
   The collection of the Capitoline Museums is in two buildings,
the Palazzo dei Conservatori and the Palazzo Nuovo. They face each
other on Capitoline Hill, the highest of the seven hills of ancient
Rome, and for centuries the political and religious heart of the
city.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the improvements to the galleries have been mostly
structural and cosmetic: improving the illumination (with enormous
handmade Murano glass chandeliers), repainting the rooms in their
original pastel colors, restoring the carved ceilings from a dull
brown to their original multicolored intensity and cleaning parts
of the collection.
</P>
<P>
   A tunnel connecting the three main buildings of the Capitoline,
built in the early 1940s but closed for the last 30 years, was also
reopened, providing access to the Tabularium, the
first-century-B.C. Roman state archive built above the Roman Forum,
affording a spectacular view of the ruins below.
</P>
<P>
   Restoration of a wing added in the 1920s when Mussolini was in
power provided some surprises. When the floors were removed,
workers found the remains of the foundations of the
sixth-century-B.C. Temple of Jupiter, the most famous temple of
ancient Rome. The restoration of this part of the museum was halted
to allow the archaeological dig to continue. So far the finds have
excited scholars. For instance, next to the temple, archaeologists
discovered ruins that date from the 16th to the 6th century B.C.,
including tombs of small children.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is all very important because the original situation of
the Campidoglio was not known before this dig,'' explained Anna
Mura Sommella, the director of the museum, ``but we have found a
complex archaeological situation which will better explain the life
of this hill.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of the remains of the Temple of Jupiter will be
incorporated in a glass-domed area that will be built to house the
original equestrian statue of Marcus Aurelius. The statue, first
put in the Campidoglio in 1538 as part of Michelangelo's design for
the piazza, has been in the courtyard of the Palazzo Nuovo since
1990. (The horse and rider in the center of the Piazza del
Campidoglio is a copy put there in 1997.) A fresco high up in the
Room of the Eagles in the Palazzo dei Conservatori shows what
Capitoline Hill looked like just before Michelangelo's project.
</P>
<P>
   Though the view overlooking the Forum from the Tabularium is
spectacular, it is rivaled by the view from a newly opened cafe
seating more than 300 on the terrace of the Palazzo Caffarelli,
next to ``The She-Wolf'' exhibit. The cafe, a large bookstore and
remodeled ticket offices are part of the museum's attempt at
modernization.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is the oldest museum in the world, so we didn't want to
change much,'' Mura Sommella said. ``But after all, this is no
longer the 18th century, when Stendhal would visit the museum by
candlelight.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-11-00 1604EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
