 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: Each week, The San Francisco Chronicle's panel of
professional tasters tries a different product available in
supermarkets.  
 
 Taster's Choice: Lean Cuisine Leads the Chicken Teriyaki Pack   By Robin Davis  
 c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  In the world of frozen foods, chicken teriyaki is
one of the most popular. It comes as frozen dinners, bowls and, in
the latest variation, as skillet meals, designed to be cooked
stovetop in a skillet.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Today's panel tasted eight frozen chicken teriyakis, pitting
each kind against the other. Results were mixed as to which types
the panel liked best, but the overall feeling was that the skillet
dinners fell short. The panel thought they often looked better than
the bowls and dinners, but the flavors were at best
one-dimensional.
</P>
<P>
   The teriyakis ranged in size from single- to multi-servings. All
were cooked according to preferred package directions, though all
can be made in the microwave and most in a conventional oven.
</P>
<P>
   The highest ranking went to  &UR; Lean Cuisine &LR;  (14 ounces, $3.89 at
Safeway). This meal has all of the components _ chicken, rice and
vegetables _ separate on a microwaveable plate. Panelists liked the
way this product looked and most thought the flavors were well
balanced. One panelist particularly liked the crisp-tender
vegetables, but another thought the textures were too mushy. Four
would buy it and one might.
</P>
<P>
   Second place went to  &UR; Uncle Ben's &LR;  (12 ounces, $3.49 at
Andronico's), which came in a bowl. The biggest complaint was that
there was little distinction in the textures of the ingredients.
But most of the panelists thought the sauce was well balanced. One
particularly liked the sesame notes. Two would buy it and three
might buy it.
</P>
<P>
   Third place went to  &UR; Stouffer's &LR;  (25 ounces, $5.69-$5.79 at many
supermarkets). One panelist commented, ``looks like it should taste
fabulous, but it doesn't.'' Some liked the crunchiness of the
vegetables, but most found the flavors one dimensional. Two would
buy it; three would not.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Chung's Express &LR;  (24 ounces, $5.99 at Andronico's), the only
product to come in pouches, came in fourth. Most panelists agreed
that this product was much too sweet. One also detected unpleasant
chemical notes. But one dissenter admitted he didn't mind the
sweetness; he was put off by the ``mishmash of ingredients.'' One
would buy it; four would not.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; King's Hawaiian &LR;  (131/4 ounces, $2.99-$3.19 at many
supermarkets) _ another bowl _ came in fifth. Three panelists found
the mixture mushy and sticky. One thought the chicken was dry, but
another liked the sweet/salty balance in the sauce. One might buy
it; four would not.
</P>
<P>
   The panel also tasted Marie Callender's skillet meal, Birds Eye
Chicken Viola and Healthy Choice, but they ranked too low.
</P>
<P>
   Panelists were John P. Carroll, cookbook author; Marc Halperin,
culinary director, Center for Culinary Development; Shelley
Handler, consultant and food writer; Donna Katzl, chef-owner, Cafe
For All Seasons, San Francisco; and Kirk Webber, chef-owner, Cafe
Kati, San Francisco. All products are tasted blind.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
