 CHRON  
 Cook's Books: Despite Crafty Design, Recipes Need Work  &HT;       
 By Deb Wandell 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO _  &LR; That old saw, ``You've gotta have a gimmick,''
buzzes through your mind when you pick up ``The Cook Pack,'' a
pop-up cookbook by chef and BBC-TV personality Gary Rhodes.
<P>
   Twenty ``no-fail'' three-course meals for two, a pocket-size
shopping list and wine guide are bound up in hardback something
like a photo album. It's an eye-catching, if curious, format, and
at first, it's unclear whether to read it or play with it. Turn to
the first laminated page, and there's the author, smiling as he
straddles a chair. Pull a tab and his hair stands on end. Keep
flipping and up pop a cheese grater (actual size), a large wedge of
Swiss, a scratch 'n' sniff page.
</P>
<P>
   Billed as the cure for the culinarily challenged, it's cleverly
designed to appeal to the novice. Rhodes promises to make even the
most reluctant chefs jump at the opportunity to make an elegant
spread at home by taking them through every step, from stocking the
kitchen and setting the table to mixing the cocktails and timing
the preparation down to the minute.
</P>
<P>
   The recipes are non-threatening, and most meals can be made in
less than two hours, with canned or prepared ingredients providing
shortcuts.
</P>
<P>
   Tabs on the outside of each page make it easy to flip to
sections for cocktails, fish, meat, chicken and vegetarian dishes.
Pages start with a menu and brief description of the meal along
with a little bit of cutesy inspiration from the author (``Why not
be romantic and sexy by feeding each other using your fingers''),
then fold out for a list of ingredients and the play-by-play.
Graphics on the facing page illustrate the menu's theme, but they
do little to show how the food should look.
</P>
<P>
   On first inspection, it seems like the ideal book for college
students or friends moving into their first apartment. Yet a closer
look reveals the book leaves a lot of guesswork for cooks.
</P>
<P>
   The British publishers make few allowances for American cooks _
measurements are given in ounces rather than tablespoons and cups,
and the metric conversion wheel in the back of the book is useless.
And while it's easy to assume that the Cos lettuce called for in
the Caesar salad is another name for romaine, it's hard to guess
with groundnut oil. A short glossary in the back of the book seems
more of an afterthought _ with definitions for pesto and couscous,
but nothing clarifying treacle.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the more straightforward recipes are worth trying, like
the caramelized onion and Camembert tart and watercress with walnut
oil in the ``no-meat'' section. A small wheel of cheese is set on a
bed of rosemary-scented slow-cooked onions and then baked in puff
pastry. As promised, it made an impressive entree, cheese spilling
out of the pastry as it was sliced and oozing onto the plate. The
piquant watercress salad helped cut the richness.
</P>
<P>
   Canned borlotti beans were hard to find for the borlotti bean
soup, but the recommended substitution of cannellini beans worked
fine, combined with sauteed carrots and onion, fresh tomatoes and
strips of savoy cabbage for a hearty _ if unspectacular _ first
course. A sprinkling of Parmesan cheese helped bring the flavors
together.
</P>
<P>
   Also intriguing are recipes for slow honey and ginger roasted
duck with spring onion mashed potatoes, and a pan-fried pear with
Stilton and walnuts; and grilled mascarpone plums sound like a nice
ending to a menu that includes spicy parsnip soup and roast
marinated lamb.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, an entree of roast pork sausages with dressed
up canned gravy served on a bed of mashed sweet potatoes couldn't
have sounded more unappealing. The same goes for the fish pie with
cheesy potato topping.
</P>
<P>
   The cocktail section has some interesting suggestions, but a
true martini fan would wince at a recipe that mixes six ounces of
vermouth with three ounces of gin.
</P>
<P>
   Such slips and oversights peppered throughout ``The Cook Pack''
take the wind out of Rhodes' ``no-fail'' claim. And while the
pop-up gimmick is a kick, and the design intriguing, as a cookbook
it is not much of a success.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; ``The Cook Pack,'' by Gary Rhodes (Van der Meer Publishing; &LR; 
 &LR; pop-up book; $29.99). &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
