<SLUG> BC-SECRET-SALAD-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: Each week, The Chronicle offers readers the recipe
for an outstanding dish at a Bay Area restaurant, plus the chef's
secrets for making it a success. Tips and recipe follow in optional
trim. 
 
 Secrets of Success: A Califoria Classic   By Michael Bauer 
 c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  In the 1970s the connection between goat cheese
and California cuisine became a running joke, and when you added it
to a salad it was the ultimate clich e .
<TEXT>
<P>
   Never mind that goat cheese with salad has been a staple of the
French brasserie for generations. And new generations of
Californians are discovering how wonderful that combination can be
at Baker Street Bistro, the charming neighborhood bistro near the
Marina.
</P>
<P>
   For this delicious salad, rounds of goat cheese are crusted in
crushed walnuts and fresh thyme. They're warmed, then placed on a
nest of mixed baby greens that are delicately dressed with a
red-wine vinaigrette with a touch of balsamic vinegar and Dijon
mustard.
</P>
<P>
   The recipe is done to perfection by Jose Sanchez, who trained
with Fredy Girardet in Switzerland for five months before taking
work in Europe and Tokyo. He took over the kitchen at Baker Street
Bistro in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   When you enter the cramped quarters, which now spread out over
two small storefronts, with a postage-stamp-size kitchen in the
center, you'll be greeted by Jacques Manuera, who opened this
bargain-priced place in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Baker Street Bistro, 2953 Baker St. (near Lombard Street), San &LR; 
 &LR; Francisco; (415) 931-1475. Breakfast, lunch and dinner &LR; 
 &LR; Tuesday-Sunday. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
SECRETS OF SUCCESS
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Fresh thyme. &LR;  Coating the cheese first in the fresh herbs
adds a clean, herbal flavor to the mild goat cheese.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Chilling the cheese. &LR;  The cold cheese retains its shape while
the nuts brown. The inside becomes warm and creamy when the cheese
is gently heated in the oven.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
WARM GOAT CHEESE SALAD
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   15 ounces fresh goat cheese
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon minced fresh thyme
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper, to taste
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup coarsely ground walnuts
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons red wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons balsamic vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon Dijon mustard
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   12 (1/4-inch-thick) slices French bread
</P>
<P>
   8 tablespoons olive oil + oil for baking sheet
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon minced parsley
</P>
<P>
   1 pound mixed salad greens
</P>
<P>
   2 cups halved cherry tomatoes or chopped tomatoes
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon minced mixed fresh herbs (such as tarragon,
parsley, marjoram)
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Divide the cheese into 6 portions (about 21/2 ounces each) and
shape into flat rounds (about 3/8 inch high). Sprinkle each round
with thyme, salt and pepper. Coat with walnuts. Place the cheese
rounds in the freezer until very firm, about 20 to 30 minutes, but
do not let them freeze. Once chilled, the cheeses may be kept in
the refrigerator for up to 1 day.
</P>
<P>
   Combine the red wine vinegar, balsamic vinegar and mustard in a
small bowl, whisking to blend. Gradually whisk in the vegetable oil
until the vinaigrette is completely emulsified. Season with salt
and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Arrange the bread slices on a baking sheet. Use 7 tablespoons of
the olive oil to drizzle on both sides of the bread. Sprinkle with
the chopped parsley. Bake until crisp and golden brown, about 12 to
15 minutes. Maintain oven temperature.
</P>
<P>
   Lightly oil a small baking sheet.
</P>
<P>
   Heat the remaining 1 tablespoon olive oil in a saute pan. Saute
the rounds of goat cheese over medium heat until the nuts are
browned, about 1 to 2 minutes. Transfer the cheeses to the prepared
baking sheet. Bake until the cheeses are warmed through, about 5
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Toss the greens with about half of the vinaigrette. Season with
additional salt and pepper, then add more vinaigrette if needed.
</P>
<P>
   Place the tomatoes in a bowl and toss with the remaining
vinaigrette.
</P>
<P>
   Divide the greens among serving plates. Place toasts on plates
and top each salad with a warm goat-cheese round. Garnish with the
tomatoes and fresh herbs; serve immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 800 calories, &LR;   &LR; 23 g protein, 44 g
carbohydrate, &LR;   &LR; 60 g fat (15 g saturated), 33 mg cholesterol, 688
mg sodium, 4 &LR;   &LR; g fiber. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
