<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEARN-STRATA-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: Every other week, The Chronicle features ``Learning
to Cook'' by Marion Cunningham, a cooking teacher and cookbook
author best known for her revisions of the Fannie Farmer cookbooks.
This column is intended for novices in the kitchen. &HT;     
 Learning To Cook: Old Dish Learns New Tricks   By Marion Cunningham 
 c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO _  &LR; Strata is an old recipe that usually was thought
of as breakfast fare. It is a humble dish that was designed to use
up day-old or stale bread.
<P>
   Strata usually contained bits of ham or cooked bacon and a mild
melting cheese, which were layered between slices of bread in an
oven-to-table baking dish. A simple mixture of milk and beaten eggs
was poured over the top, then it was baked. Today, strata still is
pleasing and very satisfying for breakfast or brunch.
</P>
<P>
   The great appeal of strata is that in our hurried modern lives,
this dish can, in fact, must be assembled a few hours ahead,
preferably the night before, so the bread can soak up all the
custard and the flavors can blend. All that's left to do the next
morning is to preheat the oven and bake the strata.
</P>
<P>
   Lately, I've been preparing strata with vegetables and cheese.
This variation makes a great supper dish. You really can use any
almost filling with the bread, eggs and milk.
</P>
<P>
   Try serving the following recipe for supper, accompanied by a
fresh, green salad and fruit or ice cream to finish the meal.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; VEGETABLE STRATA
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   Butter for baking dish
</P>
<P>
   2 zucchini
</P>
<P>
   1 globe eggplant
</P>
<P>
   1 yellow onion
</P>
<P>
   3/4 pound mushrooms (any variety)
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper, to taste
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 day-old loaf sliced Italian bread
</P>
<P>
   8 ounces white cheddar cheese
</P>
<P>
   4 large eggs
</P>
<P>
   2 cups milk
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Butter the bottom and sides of a 9 x 12 x 2-inch baking dish.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; To prepare the vegetables:  &LR; Cut off the stem and root ends of
the zucchini. Cut the zucchini into 1/8-inch slices. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Trim off the cap and base of the eggplant, then cut the eggplant
in half lengthwise. Wrap one half in plastic and refrigerate for
another use. Set the other half on its side and cut into 3
lengthwise slices. Hold the slices together, place them cut-side
down on a board and cut into 1/2-inch slices lengthwise. Holding
all the slices together, cut crosswise into 1/2-inch cubes. Set
aside.
</P>
<P>
   Cut off the stem and root ends of the onion and peel off the
outer papery skin. Cut the onion in half lengthwise. Wrap half and
refrigerate for another use. Place the other half cut-side down on
a cutting board and cut lengthwise into 1/4-inch-thick slices.
Holding the slices together, cut crosswise into 1/8-inch dice.
</P>
<P>
   Using a damp cloth (or a mushroom brush) wipe off the mushrooms
so no dirt is clinging to them. Break off the steams. Cut the stems
in half or thirds and set aside. Cut the mushroom caps into
1/4-inch slices. Holding the slices together, cut crosswise into
1/2-inch pieces.
</P>
<P>
   Combine all the vegetables and season lightly with salt and
pepper, moving the pieces around so the seasonings are evenly
distributed.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Cooking the vegetables:  &LR; Pour the olive oil into a large
skillet. Tilt the pan so the olive oil evenly coats the inside.
Turn the heat to medium-high. When the oil feels very warm when you
place your hand about an inch above the skillet, add the
vegetables, spreading them out in the pan. Cook, stirring
constantly until they are lightly browned. This takes about 6 to 8
minutes. Remove from heat. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Preparing the bread and cheese:  &LR; Cut off the crusts from the
bread slices. Coarsely grate the cheese.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Mixing the eggs and milk:  &LR; Crack the eggs and drop into a bowl.
Using a fork, stir and mix the eggs until they are all one color.
Add the milk and stir briskly to blend well.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Assembling the dish:  &LR; Fit a single layer of bread slices into
the baking dish. Top with half of the vegetables. Sprinkle one
third of the grated cheese over the vegetables. Add another layer
of bread slices, then repeat layering, ending with a layer of
bread.
</P>
<P>
   Drizzle the egg-milk mixture over the top. Sprinkle with the
remaining cheese. Cover with plastic wrap and refrigerate
overnight, or for at least 3 hours before baking.
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Remove the dish from the refrigerator and take off the plastic
wrap. Place the dish in the oven and bake for 40 minutes. Test for
doneness by inserting a toothpick into the center. If it comes out
with wet custard clinging to it, return to the oven to bake another
10 minutes. Test again. The top of the strata should be lightly
browned and the toothpick should be moist with crumbs, but not wet.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4 to 6.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 545 calories, &LR;   &LR; 25 g protein, 52 g
carbohydrate, &LR;   &LR; 27 g fat (12 g saturated), 192 mg cholesterol, 766
mg sodium, 3 &LR;   &LR; g fiber. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-11-00 1610EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
