<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WALKCAL-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: Food Lovers' Walks is a bi-weekly column that covers
neighborhoods in San Francisco and other Bay Area cities where a
casual stroll turns up culinary treasures. &HT;     
 Food Lovers' Walks: Calistoga Shows It's Food-Friendly   By Karola Saekel  
 c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; CALISTOGA, Calif. _  &LR; If Gold Rush millionaire Sam Brannan had been
able to consult a  &LR; feng shui &LR;  book in 1860 before he laid out his
dream of a Saratoga Springs of the West, the little town of
Calistoga might never have slipped into relative obscurity and its
visionary founder might not have ended up broke and broken.
<P>
   But the  &UR; Calistoga Bookstore &LR; , with its fine selection of books
on wine and  &LR; feng shui &LR; , wasn't around then.
</P>
<P>
   So Brannan's hotel burned to the ground, the dance pavilion,
race track and most other trappings of a smart spa fell into
disrepair, leaving behind a pleasant backwater where visitors could
find mud baths, eminently proper massages and sustenance of sorts,
but hardly fine cuisine _ until a good century later.
</P>
<P>
   Even today, despite an abundance of good restaurants, Calistoga
retains the feel of a small Western town, with low-slung buildings
and an old railroad depot that houses the chamber of commerce and
tourist-oriented businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Among things you won't find are fast-food or chain operations.
If you want to sip a latte, don't look for any of the familiar
logos, but the  &UR; Calistoga Roastery &LR;  will serve you well. With its
friendly, laid-back service, slightly ramshackle appearance and
homey food, it's the antithesis of the slick efficiency of a chain.
</P>
<P>
   If you're an early riser, snatch a cup of coffee, a croissant
and bread for later at chef Fred Halpert's  &UR; Napa Valley Ovens &LR; ,
which opens at 6 a.m. and closes ``whenever we run out of most
things.''
</P>
<P>
   A later possibility is tiny  &UR; Good 'N' Airy Angel &LR; , which lets
you supplement coffee with a toothsome sweet or an ice cream cone.
For serious breakfast, one of the most popular choices is
 &UR; Cafe Sarafornia &LR; . But why Sarafornia? The story goes that Gold Rush
millionaire Brannan _ who abandoned his Mormon faith rather than
fulfill his tithing duties _ was inebriated at a ceremony promoting
his resort as the Saratoga of California. At least that's what he
meant to say. What came out was ``the Calistoga of Sarafornia.''
Hence, the name of the town _ and now the restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   The shopper with food and wine in the mind is in luck here. On
the high end, there is  &UR; Enoteca &LR;  fine wines and antiques. The only
second-story business in town, it is located in the high-ceilinged
former ballroom of the 1887 International Order of Odd Fellows
(IOOF) building.
</P>
<P>
   Owner Margaux Singleton scours the world for hand-crafted wines,
including many rare dessert wines. Prices can go as high as $1,300
for a bottle, but, she asserts you can also get some nice wines for
$10.
</P>
<P>
   A unique experience awaits at  &UR; Ca'toga Galleria d'Arte &LR; ,
internationally acclaimed muralist Carlo Marchiori's stunning
gallery. Along with whimsical  &LR; commedia dell'arte &LR;  masks, screens
and wall decorations, Marchiori creates fabulous ceramic plates,
bowls and platters. Twelve-inch plates start at $60, and prices go
up from there.
</P>
<P>
   For the artistically inclined with a more restricted budget,
there is  &UR; Evans Ceramics Gallery &LR; , the only direct retail outlet of
Evans Designs of Healdsburg, a group of artists that produces fine
glass and ceramics, including Raku ware. Prices are 40 to 90
percent off what these pieces fetch in high-end department stores
worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   For shoppers who want to combine practicality with aesthetics,
the  &UR; Home and Garden Shop &LR;  of  &UR; Palisades Market &LR;  is not to be
missed _ yet it's easy to miss since it is located behind the
market. Owner Victoria Gott has assembled an eclectic mix of basics
like white Cordon Bleu tableware; Asian serving pieces (including
square plates, the current darlings of trendy restaurants); casual
table linens and much more.
</P>
<P>
   The Gott family started Palisades Market eight years ago selling
high-end vittles: artisan breads, cheeses, p &LR; a &LR; t &LR; e &LR; s, wine,
made-to-order sandwiches and picnic-oriented take-out.
</P>
<P>
   Vicki Gott and sons Joel and Duncan have since expanded. First
came the home annex, now they are remodeling the original store,
adding more space for the deli and bake shop.
</P>
<P>
   They are also reopening the drive-in at the next-door former
glider port, calling it Fred's Refresher (they already operate
Taylor's Refresher in St. Helena).
</P>
<P>
   Palisades' take-out or a sandwich or salad from  &UR; Calmart &LR;  across
the street (no relation to the San Francisco market by that name),
are the most casual lunch options, but most of the nearly two dozen
local restaurants serve lunch.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Pacifico Restaurante Mexicano &LR;  serves good food at great prices
(many items well under $10) in a cheery setting. At  &UR; Catahoula &LR; 
 &UR; Restaurant and Saloon, &LR;  chef/owner Jan Birnbaum's New
Orleans-inspired food is sophisticated and plentiful _
rabbit-crawfish gumbo, a pulled pork sandwich with slaw and
barbecued sweet potato chips. Everything is house-made, even the
bun and the bread-and-butter pickles on the oven-roasted sirloin
burger.
</P>
<P>
   The handsome  &UR; Brannan's Grill &LR; , with a decor that blends
elements of the original 1906 building with modern design, also
serves substantial fare _ think voodoo shrimp or hanger steak.
</P>
<P>
   Several restaurants offer patio seating. Two favorites are the
 &UR; Calistoga Inn, Restaurant &AMP; Brewery &LR;  and  &UR; Wappo Bar &AMP; Bistro &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   The inn (yes, there are rooms for rent) also serves micro brews,
including barley wine (actually a dark, dense beer with a hint of
sweetness), so strong it's only poured by the half-pint. There are
hot entrees, but the best bets are generous sandwiches like grilled
chicken breast, bacon, guacamole, lettuce and tomato on focaccia
for $9.25. Even if you don't capture one of the prized tables above
the river, a stone fountain splashes coolness amid the dappled
sunlight.
</P>
<P>
   At eclectic Wappo, with menu inspirations circling the globe,
the leaf-shaded patio has a Mediterranean feel _ as does the
friendly, why-hurry service. Thai noodle salad with chicken is a
local favorite, and you would be hard put to find a better or
prettier Ni &LR; c &LR; oise salad with grilled fresh tuna.
</P>
<P>
   Lunch prices at these and most nearby restaurants range from
$9-$14.
</P>
<P>
   As a last stop, visit the  &UR; Sharpsteen Museum &LR;  for a glimpse into
Calistoga's history. Its front area is Sam Brannan's own opulent
Victorian ``cottage,'' the only remaining building of his grand
resort, moved to this site in the 1970s and furnished with
appropriate period pieces. But don't look for a kitchen. The
eccentric entrepreneur's guests were expected to take their meals
in the hotel.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
CALISTOGA
</P>
<P>
   The area code for the following businesses is (707).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; STORES &AMP; GROCERS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Calistoga Bookstore &LR; , 1343 Lincoln Ave.; 942-4123
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Ca'toga Galleria d'Arte &LR; , 1206 Cedar St. (off Lincoln
Avenue); 942-3900 (closed Tuesday-Wednesday)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Calmart Groceries and Delicatessen &LR; , 1491 Lincoln Ave.;
942-6271
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Enoteca &LR; , 1345 Lincoln Ave., Suite C; 942-1117
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Evans Designs Gallery &LR; , 1421 Lincoln Ave., 942-0453
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Good 'n' Airy Angel Bakery &LR; , 1408 Lincoln Ave.; 942-0714
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Napa Valley Ovens &LR; , 1353 Lincoln Ave.; 942-0777 (opens 6
a.m., closed Tuesday)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Palisades Market and Home and Garden Shop &LR; , 1506 Lincoln
Ave.; 942-9549
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Sharpsteen Museum &LR; , 1311 Washington St. (near Lincoln Ave.);
942-5911
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; RESTAURANTS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Brannan's Grill &LR; , 1374 Lincoln Ave.; 942-2233
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Cafe Sarafornia &LR; , 1413 Lincoln Ave.; 942-0555
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Calistoga Inn, Restaurant &AMP; Brewery &LR; , 1250 Lincoln Ave.;
942-4101
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Calistoga Roastery &LR;  and cafe, 1631 Lincoln Ave.; 942-5757
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Catahoula Restaurant &AMP; Saloon &LR; , 1457 Lincoln Ave.; 942-2275
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Pacifico Restaurante Mexicano &LR; , 1237 Lincoln Ave.; 942-4400
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Wappo Bar &AMP; Bistro &LR; , 1226-B, Washington St. (near Lincoln
Avenue); 942-4712
</P>
