<HEADER>
A9113 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-ALZHEIMER'S-0712-COX     07-11 0808
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALZHEIMER'S-0712-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HUMAN TRIALS UNDERWAY FOR ALZHEIMER'S DRUG
 &HT;    By JEFF NESMITH
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A small group of Alzheimer's disease patients
suffered no apparent side effects from an experimental vaccine that
appears to remove brain cell ``plaques'' associated with the
disease, drug company researchers revealed Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Food and Drug Administration-approved trial was not designed
to reveal whether the vaccinations were effective in treating the
disease, said officials of Elan Corp., a pharmaceuticals
development company.
</P>
<P>
   However, many scientists believe the plaques impede brain cell
function and cause cell death in persons with Alzheimer's disease.
</P>
<P>
   If the vaccine is ultimately approved for use on human beings,
it could be given both to prevent Alzheimer's disease in persons at
risk and to treat active cases, Elan officials said.
</P>
<P>
   They declined to speculate about when a treatment based on the
substance might be available. The company does not expect to begin
conducting trials that may determine the substance's effectiveness
in humans until late next year. It could be at least a year after
that before the company applies for an FDA license to market the
vaccine _ and months more before a treatment is available to the
public.
</P>
<P>
   In a presentation at the World Alzheimer (cq, singular) Congress
2000 here, researcher Dale Schenk said tests on laboratory animals
show the vaccine provokes an immune response that clears
disease-causing substances called ``amyloid plaques'' from diseased
brain tissue.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think it causes antibodies to 'tag' the amyloid cells so
that scavenger cells in the brain come along and remove them,''
Schenk said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   Although the plaques are found in the brains of most individuals
with Alzheimer's, it is not known whether they are a cause _ or a
result _ of the disease process.
</P>
<P>
   A protein known as beta amyloid has been identified as a primary
component of the plaques.
</P>
<P>
   Over 1,000 persons attending the conference sat in silence while
Schenk showed slides of brain tissues of mice before and after
receiving the vaccine, which has been designated ``AN-1792'' and is
a synthetic form of the naturally occurring beta amyloid protein.
</P>
<P>
   The synthetic protein stimulates production of antibodies
leading a biochemical attack on the plaques, Schenk said. After the
plaque cells are ``tagged'' by the antibodies, he said, other brain
cells called microglial cells begin engulfing them and removing
them from the brain.
</P>
<P>
   Elan, which was founded in Dublin, Ireland, has offices and
plants in Ireland, Israel and several U.S. cities, including
Gainesville, Ga., and Miramar, Fla. The company revealed a year ago
in the journal Nature that AN-1792 removed plaques from mice that
had been genetically engineered to develop human Alzheimer's
disease.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to single doses given to 24 Americans with early and
moderate Alzheimer's disease, the vaccine is being given in
multiple doses to a larger group of volunteers in Great Britain,
Schenk said.
</P>
<P>
   So far, there are no results from the British trial, which is
designed to show both whether the vaccine has harmful side effects
and whether it causes persons who receive it to build up antibodies
to the beta amyloid protein.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just a few years ago, talk of a potential vaccine for
Alzheimer's disease would have been viewed with much skepticism,''
said Bill Thies, vice president of medical and scientific affairs
of the Alzheimer's Association. ``Announcements like this that are
grounded in solid scientific research give us tremendous hope.''
</P>
<P>
   Ivan M. Lieberburg, executive vice president of Elan, declined
to reveal company projections about the potential market value of
the proposed vaccine but noted that between 150,000 and 200,000
Americans are diagnosed with Alzheimer's disease every year.
Currently, over 20 million Americans are believed to have
Alzheimer's or some other form of dementia.
</P>
<P>
   --STORY COULD TRIM HERE
</P>
<P>
   In another study presented at the conference, Dutch scientists
reported that persons who ate large amounts of vegetables and took
vitamins E and C were slightly less likely of contracting
Alzheimer's disease and other forms of dementia.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers compared recorded dietary habits and health
records of over 5,000 persons for a period of six years. The
reported slight but significant decreases in Alzheimer's and
dementia risk among those who took the two vitamins and ate
vegetables but found no relation between eating fruit or taking the
food supplements beta carotene, flavonoids and selenium.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   On the Internet: www.alzheimer2000.org
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Nesmith's e.mail address is jeffn(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
