<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HARRYPOTTER-REVIEW-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARRY POTTER'S STILL GOT THAT MAGIC
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF GUINN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``Harry Potter and the Goblet of Fire''
</P>
<P>
   by J.K. Rowling
</P>
<P>
   Fiction
</P>
<P>
   Levine/Scholastic, $25.95
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   By JEFF GUINN &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Because of all the hoopla _ a first printing of 3.8 million; the
frantic efforts by the publisher to keep the book under wraps until
its official publication last Saturday; the movie deal; the
gazillion toys about to flood every Toys R Us in existence _ it's
hard to judge ``Harry Potter and the Goblet of Fire'' objectively.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the attention from Wall Street and Hollywood, it's still
the fourth book in a one-a-year series for kids, not adults.
``Goblet'' was long rumored to have a ``darker'' story line than
the previous Harry titles, mostly because author J.K. Rowling
realized her young audience was growing up along with their
favorite fictional wizard-in-training. Some major character was
going to ``die'' in this one, the grapevine suggested. Harry was
going to discover girls.
</P>
<P>
   All that turns out to be true, but within the simpler context of
children's literature. No reasonable grown-up is going to plow
through ``Goblet's'' overlong 734 pages without finding lots of
plot developments that defy logic, even magical logic. In the
process of trying to cram all sorts of subplots into what should
have been a much tighter, focused story, Rowling throws innumerable
characters and red herring twists-and-turns onto her literary wall
in hopes some will stick. Not enough do.
</P>
<P>
   Harry's fourth adventure finds him sprung early from his annual
summer indenture to Muggle (nonmagical) relatives. He attends the
finals of the International Quidditch Cup with his friends Hermione
and Ron and the bumptious Weasley family. The great event is
sullied by a demonstration by ``Death Eaters,'' Muggle-hating
wizards who follow Harry's nemesis, evil Lord Voldemort.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Harry and pals return to Hogwarts, where they begin
the fourth of their seven-year training program. Almost instantly,
it is announced that Hogwarts will participate in a long-banned
``Triwizard Tournament,'' where champions from Hogwarts and two
other schools of magic will compete in a series of highly dangerous
challenges. The winner receives a bag of gold and, of course,
recognition as the finest young wizard or witch around. Hogwarts
hosts the contest, which carries over from fall through spring.
</P>
<P>
   Harry, now 14, is supposedly too young to enter his name as a
possible contestant. A magic ``goblet of fire'' will determine each
school's champion. When teams from the other schools arrive, the
goblet selects their representatives, and Hogwarts'. But, after
long moments, the goblet tosses out a fourth contestant _ Harry
Potter, of course.
</P>
<P>
   It's a dangerous honor. Harry is instantly shunned by most
Hogwarts classmates, who feel he's somehow cheated his way in.
There's also the real possibility that Voldemort or one of his
minions has connived to enter Harry so he can be conveniently
disposed of during the tournament. An eventual wizardly throw-down
between Harry and Voldemort leaves both antagonists bloody but
determined to fight again.
</P>
<P>
   Then come the subplots. Yes, a few involve pubescent romance,
but those are pretty well tossed aside once they've been
introduced. Rowling also uses ``Goblet'' as a soapbox for her
thoughts on racism, animal rights and the tabloid press.
</P>
<P>
   This is, certainly, allowable. C.S. Lewis made his ``Narnia''
yarns allegories for Christian faith. T.H. White's ``The Once and
Future King'' used the Arthurian legend as a platform for pacifism.
</P>
<P>
   But Rowling simply goes on too long. She'll be forgiven by Harry
loyalists, who love any Hogwarts sub-tales whether they're really
necessary or not. But Harry-come-latelys, kids who try to start
with ``Goblet'' instead of ``Harry Potter and the Sorcerer's
Stone,'' the first in the series, are going to wonder what all the
fuss has been about.
</P>
<P>
   Prior to ``Goblet's'' publication, parents seemed most worried
on one of two fronts _ the anticipated death of a beloved
character, which might shatter young psyches, and the focus on
magic/witchcraft, which could lead innocents into devil worship.
Neither concern is necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, someone nice dies near the end of the book. But,
predictably, it isn't someone who would have been considered a
major cast member in the three previous tales. And, yes, there are
spells and incantations, but they're far removed from truly
sinister real-life witchery. Rowling has faults as an author, but
she certainly seems to have a responsible attitude on this subject.
</P>
<P>
   All 734 pages of ``Harry Potter and the Goblet of Fire'' will be
gleefully devoured by Rowling's millions of kid readers. They'll
close the book already anticipating next year's fifth installment.
So, on that level, the book is a success.
</P>
<P>
   As literature for adults, ``Goblet's'' an occasional spark, not
a full-fledged fire. But the book wasn't really written for us, was
it?
</P>
<P>
   (Jeff Guinn is books editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can call him at (817) 390-7720, or e-mail:
jguinn(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-11-00 1618EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
