<DOCNO> NYT20000711.0143 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-11 16:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9115 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-INS-RIGHTS12-COX     07-11 0388
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INS-RIGHTS12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    RELEASED WOMAN SAYS SHE DOES NOT REGRET FIGHT TO 'LIBERATE' IRAN
 &HT;    By MIRIAM A. GARCIA
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Mahnaz Samadi, fresh from a federal prison, said
Tuesday she did not regret her efforts to ``liberate'' her native
Iran from a repressive government.
</P>
<P>
   Samadi was ordered released by an immigration court Monday after
being held for 98 days, sometimes in shackles, by the Immigration
and Naturalization Service on suspicion of being associated with a
terrorist group.
</P>
<P>
   Samadi, 35, says she was tortured when she was held in an
Iranian prison between 1982 and 1986, and says the government
executed two of her brothers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I witnessed things that made me determined to fight,'' Samadi
said through a translator at a Capitol Hill news conference.
</P>
<P>
   She fled to the United States in 1994, but INS officials say she
fraudulently attained political asylum because she did not disclose
her affiliation with the National Liberation Army of Iran, the
military wing of the Iranian resistance.
</P>
<P>
   The INS took her into custody this year after she was deported
from Canada, which said her past associations made her a danger to
the community.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I was safe here,'' Samadi said. ``But I found
instead I was betrayed.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought freedom of political belief was sacred here,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   At the court nearing Monday in Arlington, Va., the INS agreed
not to deport Samadi to Iran, but she is subject to deportation to
a third country. Maria Cardona, an INS spokeswoman, said there are
no plans to deport her to another country at this time.
</P>
<P>
   Samadi will remain in this country until it is safe for her to
return to Iran, her attorney Michael Maggio said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only reason she wants to be here is because she can't be
in Tehran safely,'' Maggio said.
</P>
<P>
   Samadi's release was sought by 62 members of Congress who wrote
a letter to Attorney General Janet Reno.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Ileana Ros-Lehtinen, R-Fla., described Samadi as a
``freedom fighter'' who has dedicated her life to fighting for
democracy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not regret fighting to liberate my country,'' Samadi
said.
</P>
<P>
   Miriam A. Garcia's e-mail address is miriamg(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
