<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-11 16:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9122 &Cx1f; tad-z
r w BC-GUN-RALLY-0712-COX     07-11 0564
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUN-RALLY-0712-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Reno kicks off ``First Monday'' anti-gun rally
 &HT;    By Eunice Moscoso
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Attorney General Janet Reno joined lawmakers
Tuesday to announce ``a national day of action to end gun
violence.''
</P>
<P>
   The event _ ``First Monday 2000'' _ is planned to coincide with
the first day of the Supreme Court term, Oct. 2.
</P>
<P>
   At a kick-off rally, Reno told an auditorium full of students
``to feel as passionate and speak out with as much vigor as those
who think their guns are their most precious possession.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We have got to take the force, the feeling, the power that I
sense in this nation and translate it into action,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   According to organizers, about 200 events will be held at U.S.
campuses and communities around Oct. 2 to spark discussion and
activism to reduce gun violence.
</P>
<P>
   At Tuesday's rally, Secretary of Housing and Urban Development
Andrew Cuomo said gun violence is the ``one glaring aberration'' in
a time of unprecedented ``promise, hope and progress'' in the U.S.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to gun violence, ``we not only are not the leaders
on the globe, but we are the caboose on the train,'' he said. ``In
some ways we are the most uninformed, the most unintelligent when
it comes to this issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Some members of Congress also attended the rally, including Rep.
Connie Morella , R-Md., and Rep. Carolyn McCarthy, a New York
Democrat who is the leading gun control advocate in the House.
</P>
<P>
   ``First Monday'' is an annual, national initiative coordinated
by Physicians for Social Responsibility and the Alliance for
Justice, a coalition of liberal advocacy groups. Previous events,
held mostly at U.S. law schools, were designed to encourage budding
lawyers to work with public-interest advocacy organizations on
different issues.
</P>
<P>
   This year, gun control proponents said they hope to organize
events at more communities and colleges, including schools of
social work, nursing, medical, and public health.
</P>
<P>
   Some October events will feature a 30-minute documentary film,
``Up in Arms,'' directed by Liz Garbus and Rory Kennedy. According
to the Alliance for Justice, the film presents the ``epidemic of
gun violence'' in America and provides examples of successful
activism by citizens from all walks of life.
</P>
<P>
   Other groups sponsoring First Monday 2000 include Handgun
Control, Inc., the American Bar Association and the American
Academy of Pediatrics.
</P>
<P>
   Gun violence claims the lives of more than 32,000 people each
year and injures an estimated 90,000 more, according to the First
Monday web site.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's rally, at the headquarters of the National Education
Agency, comes one week after the NEA voted to launch a petition
drive for Congress to pass ``meaningful gun control'' next year.
</P>
<P>
   After a vigorous debate at its national convention in Chicago, a
clear majority of NEA delegates supported a motion urging
affiliates of the teachers union to collect signatures on petitions
favoring ``licensure, registration, bullet imprinting, child safety
locks, (and) mandatory background checks including waiting
periods.''
</P>
<P>
   On the Web: www.firstmonday2000.com, www.psr.org, www.afj.org
</P>
<P>
   Eunice Moscoso can be reached by e-mail at
eunicem(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
