<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-11 16:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9124 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-LIVING-TRUSTS12-COX     07-11 0642
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIVING-TRUSTS12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MANY ELDERLY FALL FOR 'LIVING TRUST' SCAMS, PANEL TOLD
 &HT;    380&AMP;add.
 &HT;    Eds: Material for a box at end of story.
 &HT;    By LARRY LIPMAN
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Elderly Americans are being victimized by scam
artists selling living trusts to people who often don't need them,
a Senate panel was told Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Living trusts are legal documents that transfer a person's
property into a trust with the intention of protecting assets and
avoiding costly probate proceedings when the person dies.
</P>
<P>
   But unscrupulous sellers are peddling living trusts which often
are legally defective and are frequently a device to raid an
unsuspecting senior's life savings, the Senate Special Committee on
Aging was told.
</P>
<P>
   ``What these fast-talking crooks don't tell their clients is
that the 'living trust' they're selling could become the buyer's
'living hell,' `` said Esther ``Tess'' Canja, president of AARP,
formerly the American Associ a living trust company that was shut
down in California.
</P>
<P>
   Once a living trust was signed, salesmen would pressure elderly
victims into converting their assets into insurance annuities which
paid low interest over a long period. The salesmen would make a
hefty commission from the sale of the annuity.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Walter Kulinski, an 82-year-old Wisconsin man, fell victim to
such a scheme.
</P>
<P>
   Kulinski was sold a living trust by United Seniors Alliance, and
$280,000 he owned in mutual funds and stocks were converted into a
long-term annuity that he could not use for 10 years without
substantial penalty.
</P>
<P>
   ``What does an 82-year-old man need with a 30-year annuity?''
asked his daughter-in-law, Judy Kulinski, who testified before the
Senate panel.
</P>
<P>
   United Seniors Alliance was shut down and paid Kulinski less
than $27,000 restitution, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Regulation of living wills and annuity sales are generally
handled by state governments, but Sen. John Breaux, D-La.,
suggested there may be room for federal involvement to stop scam
artists from closing operations in one state and opening in
another.
</P>
<P>
   Elaine Kolish(cq), associate director of the Federal Trade
Commission's bureau of consumer protection, said the FTC has
received relatively few complaints about living trusts.
</P>
<P>
   But the FTC on Tuesday released a pamphlet for consumers giving
them advice on how to make sure they purchase a credible living
trust. The pamphlet will be distributed to a variety of elderly
organizations and is available on the commission's Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Chuck Grassley, R-Iowa, the committee's chairman, said the
elderly should be extremely careful when setting up a living will.
</P>
<P>
   ``My advice to older Americans is: find a financial planner who
lives in your town, who has roots in your community, and stick with
that person. A stranger who knocks on the door may be here today,
gone tomorrow, along with a chunk of your savings.''
</P>
<P>
   On the Web:
</P>
<P>
   Senate Special Committee on Aging: www.senate.gov/(tilde)aging
</P>
<P>
   AARP Wills and Living Trusts:
www.aarp.org/confacts/money/wills-trusts.html
</P>
<P>
   Federal Trade Commission: www.ftc.gov
</P>
<P>
   Larry Lipman's e-mail address is larryl(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   HOW TO AVOID LIVING TRUST SCAMS
</P>
<P>
   _ Use a lawyer. Most state laws require that an attorney draft
the trust.
</P>
<P>
   _ Don't buy at home. Go to the lawyer's or financial planner's
office. Door-to-door living trust sales are usually a scam.
</P>
<P>
   _ Ask for written credentials. Check with references of
satisfied customers. Check with the local Better Business Bureau.
</P>
<P>
   _ Beware AARP references. AARP does not endorse any living trust
companies.
</P>
<P>
   Source: Federal Trade Commission
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
