<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-11 16:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9126 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-TV-PERKINS-COLUMN-TEX     07-11 0819
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-PERKINS-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`YOUNG AMERICANS' IS AN OLD APPROACH FOR THE WB
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEN PARISH PERKINS 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Will is the epitome of the poor kid who for years eyed the
glistening boarding school across town as a utopia of perfect
lawns, perfect people, perfect life. If only he could get in. He
does, buying the strenuous entrance exam on, of all things, the
Internet, and the ``poor kid with good grades,'' as Will describes
himself in voice-over, is admitted.
</P>
<P>
   Buying a prep school's exam on the Internet is only one of the
improbable twists masquerading as drama in ``Young Americans,'' a
series that has assembled a collection of actors so gorgeous they
almost seem to blend into the magnificent architecture, greenery
and rolling hills surrounding them.
</P>
<P>
   If only someone had been as calculating with the script, which
can make even the prettiest of these people look as though they're
performing a high school production. ``Young Americans,'' beginning
its summer run Wednesday night, is the typical WB serial, in which
story and character development are secondary to ``types'' being
tossed into an assortment of emotional turmoil.
</P>
<P>
   Will (Rodney Scott) is the pulse of this five-person ensemble, a
local boy representing this quaint little New England hamlet called
Rawley. (It's actually filmed right outside Baltimore.) It's a
perfect little place from the viewers' vantage point, but Will is
quick to give us the lowdown. ``OK place to grow up,'' he says at
the beginning of the episode. ``But as far as options, kinda
limited.''
</P>
<P>
   He's a smart boy from a poor family breaking townie tradition by
joining the enemy, the all-boys Rawley Academy, which is filled
with rich kids who zip around town in fast cars and make the sort
of authoritative smirks that come with the knowledge that they
could buy the whole place if they wanted.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder Will's father looks less than thrilled while dropping
him off at school in the old pickup; Mom wants to kiss him goodbye
while Dad merely sneers. But, as Will lets us know, he has no
choice. ``For those who attend here,'' he says, ``the future can be
anything.''
</P>
<P>
   The future is already anything for Scout (Mark Famiglietti),
Will's rich-boy roommate who has enough confidence and charisma to
go for Bella (Kate Bosworth), a local girl working at her father's
gas station and waiting to be discovered by, well, judging by her
working digs, Playboy.
</P>
<P>
   The two become so passionate so fast that you almost believe
Bella when she answers Scout's ``What are you thinking?'' question
with ``Is this the guy I'm going to spend the rest of my life
with?''
</P>
<P>
   Even with a story line that will eventually throw cold water on
their heated hormones and viewers for a loop, Scott and Bella
aren't the episode's most intriguing couple. That honor belongs to
Hamilton (Ian Somerhalder), son of the school's dean, and Jake
(Katherine Moennig), a motorcycle-riding rebel whose character is
also a direct rip-off of a recent Oscar-noteworthy film. I wouldn't
dare spoil the fun you'll have watching these two go through their
paces. (Not that you probably won't get it during the first two
scenes.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Young Americans'' will probably be a flat experience to anyone
who watches TV regularly since it does little more than remind us
of other television shows we've seen and probably like a whole lot
better.
</P>
<P>
   At least it's a knockoff with pretensions. Executive producer
Steven Antin, a rising feature-film screenwriter, (he wrote and
produced ``Inside Monkey Zetterland'' in 1993) believes that this
is a gleaming original. For that reason alone, ``Young Americans,''
even with that posturing, self-confident name, provides some
inadvertent entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the series is so lacking in original thought that it
has introduced a teacher named Finn (Ed Quinn), who is, of course,
a glib, earnest, shaggy-looking fellow who considers Hemingway the
greatest man who ever lived.
</P>
<P>
   It's Finn who finds out about Will's Internet purchase and
hounds him to do ``the right thing.'' But this, too, only leads to
the delivery of overcooked dialogue and more evidence of how hollow
and self-adoring this series appears to be.
</P>
<P>
   Will asks Finn if he can take the exam again, which Finn
permits, as long as he throws in an essay about his life and what
he wants out of it. After having to sit through parts of the essay,
courtesy of Will's voice-over, we get this:
</P>
<P>
   ``Got good news and bad news,'' Finn tells Will. ``The good news
is that you passed. The bad news is that you're a writer.''
</P>
<P>
   And about that cheating, well, let's forget it.
</P>
<P>
   (Ken Parish Perkins is TV critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7862, or e-mail:
kpperkins(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
