<HEADLINE>
REPLICAS OF COLUMBUS' SHIPS FALLING APART UNDER TEXAS GROUP'S CARE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ART CHAPMAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Spain always found Texas a confusing place to do business.
</P>
<P>
   The conquistadors never really had a good time in our state, but
they were worried sick the French would get it.
</P>
<P>
   Turns out, the French didn't want it that much either, and
eventually both countries were more or less escorted out.
</P>
<P>
   Spain got friendly with Texas again in 1993 when it allowed
replicas of the New World-famous Nina, Pinta and Santa Maria to
sail to Corpus Christi where the ships were supposed to receive a
glorious home.
</P>
<P>
   The Spanish were again disappointed. No gold, no silver, no
grand home for the ships.
</P>
<P>
   The three ships are closed to the public now, two of them
dry-docked and in disrepair. All the promises broken.
</P>
<P>
   They are replica ships, but they are spectacular replicas. We
got to see one in North Texas about there years ago when it was
trucked up Texas highways from Corpus Christi to the canals of Los
Colinas.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, hundreds of schoolchildren from small Texas towns
crawled all over the Nina.
</P>
<P>
   Teachers made the ship part of their lesson plans months in
advance of the visit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We estimate that by the end of this trip, about 10,000
schoolchildren will have visited the Nina, and about 15,000 to
20,000 people in all,'' Lisa Fisher of the Columbus Fleet
Association, the nonprofit organization that has custody of the
three ships, said at the time.
</P>
<P>
   The association had a crew of nine along on the trip, including
the ship's captain, first mate, shipwright and several hands.
Volunteers also helped from time to time, leading groups aboard the
ship, answering questions and selling souvenirs.
</P>
<P>
   Spain moved the replica ships to Corpus Christi because
thousands of Texans wrote to Spain's King Juan Carlos and asked for
them. In 1992, the ships sailed the route Columbus took from Spain
and were on display in Miami before going to Corpus Christi.
</P>
<P>
   They remained the property of the king of Spain, but the
Columbus Fleet Association had a 50-year lease agreement with the
Spanish government.
</P>
<P>
   It was supposed to be a cozy arrangement that brought glory to
Spain and tourists to Corpus Christi.
</P>
<P>
   But since 1995, the Pinta and Santa Maria have been sitting on
concrete behind the Corpus Christi Museum of Science and History. A
crash with a barge damaged them.
</P>
<P>
   The Nina is docked at the Lawrence Street dock, but all three
are closed to the public. The fleet association decided in October
that it couldn't keep its commitments with Spain and that the ships
should be returned.
</P>
<P>
   The association threw up its hands and agreed it did a lousy job
of taking care of the Columbus ships. It decided to gather them up
and hand them back _ in pieces, more or less _ to Spain.
</P>
<P>
   This week, another group said it wanted to reopen the ships to
at least generate some income; resurrect some interest, and to
bring tourists back to the city's Museum of Science and History.
</P>
<P>
   The Columbus Fleet Association, the group that admitted that it
ruined the project in the first place, objected.
</P>
<P>
   Spain, in the meantime, doesn't know what to do. It has said it
will look at a new agreement, but this time, it is also
entertaining an offer from a group in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   (Art Chapman writes a weekly column on things Texan. You can
call him at (817) 390-7422, or e-mail: artc(at)star-telegram.com.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
