<SLUG> BC-MASTER-CHEF-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOBSTER WITH PEACH COLESLAW 
</HEADLINE>
  (This is the fourth of eight columns by Michel Richard, the chef
and owner of Citronelle in Washington. They are being written with
Marian Burros.) 
 By MARIAN BURROS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A long time ago my wife came back from the market and
gave me some peaches that were as hard as a rock, as they too often
are. I decided to slice them very, very thin and mix them with a
crisp salad. The flavor wasn't right, so I tried the peaches in a
coleslaw instead. Because we always serve lobster with fruit, like
papaya, I put this coleslaw with it. The flavors are sweet and
sweet, and it's a very refreshing dish for summer.
</P>
<P>
   Although we do not have sweet salads in France, when I came to
the United States I fell in love with coleslaw. Unripe peaches are
not dripping with juice, but they do have a little peachy flavor
and good firm texture. Cut into julienne strips, they are a perfect
replacement for cabbage. The sweet and sharp flavors are so
unexpected.
</P>
<P>
   I make the dressing with yogurt because my wife and I are always
trying to lose some weight, so we use yogurt instead of oil. Yogurt
also has acidity and creaminess. When the peaches sit in the
dressing overnight, it wilts them, as happens with regular
coleslaw. And I mix in ginger and chives for some savory flavor _ I
don't want it to taste like fruit salad.
</P>
<P>
   The soft texture of the lobster and the crispness of the peaches
make a very good balance in a very elegant dish. I steam the
lobster, then massage the meat with olive oil and warm it in a very
low oven to keep it very, very moist. (If you have guests, you can
steam and shell the lobster early, then finish the dish in
minutes.) I also drizzle the lobster with lemon juice and maple
syrup for sweetness and extra flavor. Sugar would only taste sweet
here, but maple syrup has a burned caramel flavor, and adds extra
complexity to the lobster.
</P>
<P>
   You could also use sauteed scallops because scallops, like
lobster, are sweet and tender.
</P>
<P>
   I've tried this with white peaches, but it does not look as
good. Although unripe yellow peaches are very pale, they provide a
delicate color contrast to the other ingredients.
</P>
<P>
   I garnish the dish with a fresh herb, usually chervil, for a
little anise flavor, but anything but cilantro will do. And just to
make the coleslaw look like a mimosa salad, like a flower, I
sprinkle it with sieved hard-cooked egg yolk, heated in a microwave
to dry it out so it doesn't clump. It looks very elegant although
it doesn't add much flavor.
</P>
<P>
   LOBSTER WITH PEACH COLESLAW
</P>
<P>
   Time: 40 minutes, plus at least 2 hours' marinating
</P>
<P>
   For the coleslaw:
</P>
<P>
   { cup plain whole-milk yogurt
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons sugar
</P>
<P>
   Juice of { small lemon
</P>
<P>
   { teaspoon finely grated fresh ginger
</P>
<P>
   4 unripe peaches (1\ pounds), peeled and cut into [-inch
julienne strips
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 hard-cooked egg yolk
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons chopped chives
</P>
<P>
   For the lobster:
</P>
<P>
   2 lobsters, 1 to 1{ pounds each
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon maple syrup
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   Chervil and curly parsley, for garnish
</P>
<P>
   1. To prepare coleslaw: In a medium bowl, combine yogurt, sugar,
lemon juice and ginger. Add peaches, and season to taste with salt
and pepper. Cover and refrigerate for at least two hours,
preferably overnight.
</P>
<P>
   2. To prepare lobster: Preheat oven to 300 degrees. Place a rack
in a large steamer (or a roasting pan filled with an inch of water)
and bring water to a boil. Steam lobsters for 4 minutes. When
lobsters are cool enough to handle, carefully remove meat from
knuckles and claws so that meat remains intact. Break tails from
bodies. Leaving tails in shells, cut tails in half lengthwise.
</P>
<P>
   3. Mix maple syrup with lemon juice, and set aside. Massage meat
with olive oil, and season with salt and pepper to taste. Place in
a glass baking dish with tail meat facing up. Bake for 4 minutes,
or until meat has turned white and is no longer transparent.
</P>
<P>
   4. To serve, put egg yolk through a sieve, and dry it for 10
seconds in a microwave oven on high. In center of each of four
plates, place a portion of peach coleslaw. Sprinkle coleslaw with
egg yolk and chives. Remove lobster tails from their shells, and
rub lobster with a little more olive oil. Arrange a lobster claw,
knuckle and half a tail around coleslaw. Drizzle with maple syrup
mixture, and garnish with chervil and curly parsley.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
