u e BC-GORKY-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT     07-11 1123
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORKY-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BLACK ANGEL': THE LIFE STORY OF AN ARTIST   WHO EMBRACED MYSTERY 
</HEADLINE>
   (Editors: Publication notes appear at end of review.)  
 By ROBERTA SMITH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of these days Arshile Gorky, the great, and first, Abstract
Expressionist, will get the biography he deserves, but it won't be
easy. Gorky, born Manoug Adoian in the western Armenian province of
Van around 1904, was a flamboyant dissembler. The Turks' genocidal
campaign from 1915 to 1918 wiped out much of his family and his
past and made ``starving Armenian'' a painfully familiar phrase.
Fiercely private, Adoian re-created himself as a Russian, a cousin
of Maxim Gorky, a student of Kandinsky and a graduate of Brown
University.
</P>
<P>
   His arrival in the United States in 1919 was followed by an
arduous and willful artistic metamorphosis. He took what he needed
from Cezanne, Picasso, Ingres and Goya, often by copying paintings
at the Metropolitan Museum of Art. He then forged a fabulously
synthetic yet original style inspired by the art of Miro,
Surrealist automatism, his childhood memories of the Armenian
landscape and two crucial summers spent in the lush countryside of
northern Virginia. As has been widely acknowledged, his paintings
laid the foundation for Abstract Expressionism.
</P>
<P>
   Gorky committed suicide in 1948 after losses that echoed his
youth _ a devastating studio fire, the diagnosis a few weeks later
of advanced cancer, and painful injuries suffered in a car accident
while driving with his dealer, Julien Levy. The last straw was
estrangement from his wife, Agnes, worn down by poverty, the care
of two young children and Gorky's incommunicativeness and jealousy.
</P>
<P>
   Since his death, an understanding of Gorky's achievement has
often been hindered by mistrust, recrimination, feuding and amateur
or partisan writing. Friends and family alike have often
perpetuated Gorky's fictions and sometimes added to them. Despite
such challenges, Gorky biographies are on the verge of becoming an
annual event. Last summer brought ``From a High Place: A Life of
Arshile Gorky,'' by Matthew Spender, a writer and the husband of
Gorky's elder daughter, Maro. An often tedious book that rarely did
justice to Gorky's art, it nonetheless provided the first detailed
and measured account of his epic life, clearing up decades of
mystery and misinformation while revealing some of the complex
psychological pressures and conflicts that drove Gorky.
</P>
<P>
   Now comes a book that makes the shortcomings of Spender's effort
seem relatively minor: Nouritza Matossian's 500-page ``Black Angel:
The Life of Arshile Gorky,'' a shambling, argumentative if
impassioned retelling that slips and slides all over Gorky's life,
often casting it back into the haze while bringing his art weirdly
to life.
</P>
<P>
   Matossian, who lives in London and has written a biography of
the composer Iannis Xenakis, is the first Armenian to attempt a
full-scale biography of Gorky. She conducted lengthy interviews
with his sister, Vartoosh Mooradian, before her death and was able
to read Gorky's letters in the original. She seems to have done a
lot of field work. Her book is studded with personal reminiscences,
some published here for the first time, of people from all phases
of his life. She revisited the places of his childhood and is well
versed in Armenian art.
</P>
<P>
   She approaches her task with a pronounced agenda, which is to
make Gorky the savior of lost Armenian culture, the succor of
Armenian pain. She continually relates his mature work to his
childhood experiences, many of which are conjectural in the first
place; gives lengthy biographical or religious interpretations of
his semiabstract forms; and connects his motifs to the illuminated
manuscripts, carved tombstones and church frescoes of Armenian
culture. (``He did not have to borrow from Africa or the South
Pacific like other artists,'' she writes.)
</P>
<P>
   Matossian's second agenda, which is increasingly irritating as
the book wears on, is to be the savior of Gorky. Thus she discounts
most American critics of the period and glosses over or ignores the
work of other scholars with interests similar to hers, including
Harry Rand's heavily interpretive ``Arshile Gorky: The Implications
of Symbols'' from 1981.
</P>
<P>
   Matossian's strength is a kind of visual reverie. She has an
unusual knack for describing the formal and the physical aspects of
a painting or drawing, the way shapes build and surfaces accrue,
which befits an artist as technically obsessed yet as
improvisational as Gorky. Some of the most engaging passages of
this book are descriptions of paintings, although one tires of the
paucity of corroborating illustrations. She is also good at
creating a sense of the special way artists see, of the way they
look at the landscape and examine other art. When she begins to
ascend into the interpretive stratosphere, one is sometimes willing
to go with her, even against one's better judgment.
</P>
<P>
   Details like facts seem almost beneath Matossian, and her
editors as well. Wilfredo Lam is first Haitian, then Cuban; New
York museums include the Metropolitan Museum of Modern Art and the
Whitney Museum of Modern Art. Her relentlessly melodramatic tone
ends up blunting the true and horrible drama of her subject's life.
Her Gorky walks this book like a movie hero _ or the subject of a
Hollywood biography. He looks great and sounds great and casts a
big shadow, but the backgrounds and people around him remain
uniformly vague, his relationships cursory, his inner life
unexplored.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately Matossian herself seems to be the book's main
character. She likes to make inflammatory characterizations in
passing, describing Le Corbusier, for example, as ``a womanizer who
covered architects' plans with doodles of women's protruding
buttocks.'' She seems caught up in old rivalries, like that between
Gorky and Pollock. Lee Krasner's brief appearance during a trip to
Provincetown is footnoted thus: ``Curiously, when Lee Krasner was
interviewed on Gorky she did not mention this holiday with him,
perhaps because she was not with Pollock at the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Everywhere, the immense hurt of Gorky's life and afterlife,
surrogate for the larger Armenian tragedy, is furiously protected.
At a party where Gorky danced, as he often did, ``A photograph was
snapped so writers could lampoon him later for pretending to be a
peasant dancer.'' By the end of this book, Matossian's agenda has
become an enormous chip on her own shoulder, one that, for all her
enormous effort, does Gorky more harm than good.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BLACK ANGEL
</P>
<P>
   The Life of Arshile Gorky
</P>
<P>
   By Nouritza Matossian
</P>
<P>
   576 pages. The Overlook Press. $40.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-11-00 1638EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
