<HEADLINE>
CINCINNATI BOOKSTORE LOVER VISITS TEXAS _ FOR HALF PRICE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ALYSON WARD 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Matt Tauber planned the classic road trip. Or, more accurately,
a road trip with the classics.
</P>
<P>
   The 28-year-old Cincinnati stockbroker flew to Texas last month
and spent a week driving all over the state _ to visit bookstores.
</P>
<P>
   Tauber collects old and hard-to-find books, and Half Price Books
is one of his favorite haunts at home in Ohio. On the Half Price
Web site (www.halfpricebooks.com), he discovered that 28 of the
chain's 63 stores are located in Texas. (Twelve are in the Fort
Worth-Dallas area.)
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea flashed in my brain _ what if I went to Texas, took a
week and went to all of them?'' Tauber says. ``I had vacation time
and didn't have a plan.''
</P>
<P>
   So he plotted a course through Texas, visiting four or five
stores each day. Half Price has locations in the Metroplex, in
Houston and San Antonio, in Austin, Bryan and Corpus Christi. The
bookstore chain started in Dallas 27 years ago, and since then it
has expanded into eight other states. Tauber says he visits one of
the Cincinnati stores at least once a month.
</P>
<P>
   ``I usually buy at least one thing _ it could be 25 cents or
$20,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Tauber keeps a mental list of what he's looking for, but he also
keeps an eye out for the unexpected at the Half Price stores, which
offer an ever-changing hodgepodge of new and used items.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of potluck,'' Tauber says. ``Every store is
different. You can go in one month, and the next month you go in
and they have different stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Tauber has his own hodgepodge of books; his collection contains
a few hundred books, and they're mostly stored in boxes in his
home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a backlog of stuff I haven't read, so this (vacation)
probably isn't the best idea,'' he says, carrying his selections to
the checkout counter at Fort Worth's Ridgmar store.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't leave Texas empty-handed. Tauber mailed his finds home
in two boxes _ more than 100 books. He found old Peanuts books by
Charles Schulz and some other comics, books about the Beatles and
Bob Dylan, history books, CDs and ``obscure comedy albums,''
including a Groucho Marx radio show.
</P>
<P>
   The grand total for Tauber's hundred-or-so books: barely more
than $250. Not bad for a week of shopping. (Of course, he did
receive a 15 percent discount _ a friendly Texas welcome arranged
by the Half Price corporate office.)
</P>
<P>
   Tauber sent a letter to the corporate office in Dallas,
announcing his plans for a Half Price vacation. He arranged to pose
for a photo with employees of every Texas store he visited; he's
including the photos in a scrapbook that chronicles his trip.
</P>
<P>
   With store employees (and a handful of reporters) anticipating
his arrival throughout the state, Tauber's solo trip through Texas
wasn't exactly unnoticed or anonymous. But Tauber was a little
amused by the attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess it's nice for people to take an interest in your
vacation,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
