<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 AM-PAGE1-CONSIDER-NYT
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are considering for
the Page 1 of Wednesday, July 12. The N.Y. Times News Service night
supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-TALKS (Thurmont, Md.) _ Ledeall: In the verdant hills of
Maryland, far from the arid land that is the object of their bitter
dispute, the Israeli and Palestinian leaders began their fateful
peace summit at Camp David on Tuesday with the far-reaching, most
think improbable, goal of ending their 52-year-old conflict. On the
first day of an open-ended, secluded meeting, President Clinton
ushered the leaders, Prime Minister Ehud Barak of Israel and
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat, into the presidential retreat
where he hopes that the chemistry of the place and the moment can
induce a spirit of ``principled compromise'' that yields a
substantive peace agreement. By Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-CLINTON (Thurmont, Md.) _ During President Clinton's
seven years in office, there is no world leader who has journeyed
more often to the White House than Yasser Arafat. Thirteen times,
the Palestinian leader has met there the American president.
Starting Tuesday, the White House will see whether that investment
can be made to pay in a peace settlement. Administration officials
say Clinton is banking on his relationship to make the critical
difference at Camp David as Arafat and Prime Minister Ehud Barak of
Israel weigh the difficult compromises required for an agreement to
end decades of hostility and violence. By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   BOSNIA-MEMORIAL (Srebrenica, Bosnia-Herzegovina) _ Sitting on
the grass weeping, her legs folded beneath her, Tima Mehmedovic,
pointed to the spot where she had last seen her husband. Five years
ago to the day, he was among more than 7,000 men from Srebrenica
who were taken away by attacking Serbian forces and killed in the
worst massacre Europe has witnessed since World War II. On Tuesday
she was among thousands of Muslim women and a few dozen men,
relatives of the dead and missing, who returned to the site for an
emotionally charged memorial service. They came in fleets of buses,
under heavy police protection, many of them, like Mehmedovic,
returning for the first time to their hometown since those fateful
days in 1995, at the height of the war in Bosnia, when they were
separated from their menfolk and herded on to buses to be deported.
By Carlotta Gall.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``p'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-FUNDRAISING (Washington) _ A look at the Democrats bid
to topple the Republicans' fragile, six-seat majority in the House
of Representatives and their fund-raising efforts. By John M.
Broder and Don Van Natta.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``s'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   BBO-ALLSTARS (Atlanta) _ In the annual All-Star Game, 8:35 p.m.
EDT start, David Wells will start for the American League against
Randy Johnson of the National League. By Jack Curry.
</P>
