<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOUR12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Armstrong maintains hold as Tour de France finishes 11th stage
 &HT;    By Suzanne Halliburton
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   REVEL, France _ With eight support riders from his U.S. Postal
Service team forming a shield, Tour de France leader Lance
Armstrong maintained first place Tuesday as the race ended its 11th
stage.
</P>
<P>
   The cyclists rode 135.4 miles from Bagneres-de-Bigorre to Revel,
through thunderstorms and sunshine, past the lush green fields of
southern France. By afternoon's end, Armstrong stood on the podium
for a second day, wearing the yellow jersey of the leader,
accepting his bouquet of yellow flowers, and kissing the cheeks of
his presenters the customary three times.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were nice to me in the peloton (group of riders),''
Armstrong said of his protectors. ``I didn't see that many people.
It was windy, and it rained on and off. So I stayed in front most
of the day.''
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong, defending champion of Austin, Texas, finished 24th
Tuesday, 5 minutes and 5 seconds behind stage winner Erik Dekker.
Jan Ullrich, the 1997 Tour champion who is considered Armstrong's
main rival, finished just ahead of him in 24th, but with the same
time.
</P>
<P>
   The race ends July 23 in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong finished the day much as he started, staying 4:14
ahead of Ullrich and 5:10 over Christophe Moreau. Marc Wauters was
fourth at 5:18, with Peter Luttenberger fifth at 5:21.
</P>
<P>
   Dekker's victory, which he celebrated with a flurry of air
punches, did little but give him another chance to step atop the
podium. It was his second stage win of the Tour, but despite
picking up more than five minutes on Armstrong, he remained in 47th
place, 20:40 out of the lead.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's stage up the summit of Hautacam basically decided the
contenders for the Tour. Because Armstrong finished second in that
stage and so far ahead of the other top riders, he was able to zoom
from 16th overall to first.
</P>
<P>
   Many in the European media declared the race for the final
yellow jersey as over, describing Ullrich as shaken by Armstrong's
performance.
</P>
<P>
   Marco Pantani, the 1998 Tour champion, said after Armstrong
donned yellow: ``Armstrong is on another planet.''
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong, however, did not celebrate his yellow jersey status
Monday night as he tried to play down the thought that he had this
marathon of an event clinched at the halfway mark.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't have any champagne,'' he said. ``If I'm lucky enough
to win the championship in Paris, then maybe I'll have some
champagne.
</P>
<P>
   He said his climb up the Hautacam did not physically tire him
for Tuesday's stage, which with its relatively rolling terrain was
opposite of Monday's steep route in the Pyrenees.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't sleep very well,'' Armstrong said. ``It was just one
day in the mountains. I didn't feel fatigued like I did last year.
The fatigue definitely will be there in the Alps. That's the
majority of the race.''
</P>
<P>
   Today is the first off day for the Tour, with riders traveling
198 miles to Carpentras for the start of Thursday's stage 12. The
12th stage ends with a summit climb to Le Mont Ventoux, more than
2,000 feet above sea level.
</P>
<P>
   You may contact Suzanne Halliburton at
shalliburton(at)statesman.com or 445-3954.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
