<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-11 16:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9135 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d BC-VEGGIE-SALADS-COX     07-11 0904
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VEGGIE-SALADS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Now is the time to vary salad choices
 &HT;    By Ann Heller
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio - If life was fair and just, July would be the
salad days of summer.
</P>
<P>
   But as any backyard gardener knows, Mother Nature is contrary.
About the time the temperature wilts the appetite, when a nice
green salad sounds like supper, the tender leaf lettuce of June
begins to bolt and turn bitter.
</P>
<P>
   Even sources of salad greens at local farm markets dry up. The
frustrated cook may be tempted to go back to the supermarket _ but
supermarket greens from distant parts of the continent are what we
are stuck with for the rest of the summer.
</P>
<P>
   There still are salads to be made from the local vegetable
bounty. Corn salad is an easy and favorite option once the first
taste of corn on the cob has been sated. Tomatoes and cucumbers
partner in a classic Greek chopped salad with olives and feta
cheese. Summer squash, green and yellow, make a colorful salad.
</P>
<P>
   But when you want a green salad, the best choice is a green bean
salad. We've got enough variations on the basic salad to carry you
through every weekend until September, when good local salad greens
return.
</P>
<P>
   Here are the basics:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Buy small to medium beans, not big ``beany'' beans.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Rinse in cold water. Remove the stem ends, but don't bother
with the thin tail. That's just doubling your work, and it's
perfectly edible.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Cook the beans in an abundance of well-salted water, about a
teaspoon of salt for a pound of beans.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Cook just until the beans are tender crisp. They will continue
to cook a bit while cooling.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Drain and spread the beans out flat to cool (California
cooking guru Alice Waters insists the beans retain more flavor this
way, rather than cooling the beans under cold water, a favorite
chef's trick).
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Make the vinaigrette ahead of time, but don't toss the beans
with the dressing until the last minute because the acid (the lemon
juice or vinegar) in the dressing will discolor the beans. However,
the dressing can be combined with other ingredients, such as
tomatoes, onion, peppers, shell beans, olives, etc.
</P>
<P>
   I like to cut corn from the cob and add it to a green bean
salad. It adds a touch of sweetness. Ditto red bell peppers, which
also provide color contrast. The red bell peppers available now are
not locally field-grown _ though some hothouse specimens turn up at
farm markets.
</P>
<P>
   SUMMER GREEN BEAN SALAD
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 to 6 servings
</P>
<P>
   1 pound small green beans
</P>
<P>
   1 cup corn kernels cut from 2 ears
</P>
<P>
   1 red bell pepper
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup homemade vinaigrette (recipe follows)
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup slivered basil, or small leaves of lemon basil
</P>
<P>
   Cook the beans in a large pot of salted boiling water for 4-5
minutes, until cooked but still crisp. Drain and spread out to dry.
</P>
<P>
   If the corn is very fresh, young and tender, it need not be
cooked. Otherwise, place the kernels in a small strainer and blanch
for a minute in boiling water. Drain well.
</P>
<P>
   Cut the pepper into quarters and remove seeds and ribs. Cut off
the top and bottom to square up the edges, then slice into batons
the same shape as the beans.
</P>
<P>
   The beans and bell pepper slices can be combined in a salad bowl
and topped with the corn ahead of time.
</P>
<P>
   Just before serving, toss with the vinaigrette and basil.
</P>
<P>
   Proportions of vinegar and oil in a vinaigrette depend on the
acidity of the vinegar and the quality of the oil. Extra virgin
olive oil is best, though not everyone has developed a taste for
it. Light olive oils are preferable to vegetable oils. Vinegars
vary from red and white wine vinegar to balsamic, and my everyday
favorite is sherry vinegar. A little Dijon mustard helps emulsify
the dressing.
</P>
<P>
   VINAIGRETTE
</P>
<P>
   Makes 1/2 cup
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons wine vinegar, preferably sherry vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1 clove garlic, halved
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/8 teaspoon freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon Dijon mustard, optional
</P>
<P>
   6 tablespoons extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Combine the vinegar, garlic, salt, pepper and mustard, if using,
in a small container and shake well. Add the oil and shake again to
blend.
</P>
<P>
   You can make corn salad with corn cut from leftover corn on the
cob it if has been lightly cooked. Or you can cut the kernels off
the cob and drop into boiling water and blanch for a minute. Or do
as some corn lovers do _ use raw kernels in this salad.
</P>
<P>
   CORN SALAD WITH LIME DRESSING
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 to 6 serving
</P>
<P>
   2 cups fresh corn kernels, cut from 4-5 ears
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup sliced, pitted Kalamata olives
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup chopped red bell pepper
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup halved cherry tomatoes
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoons snipped garlic chives or regular chives
</P>
<P>
   1/2 large avocado, diced
</P>
<P>
   lime dressing (recipe follows)
</P>
<P>
   Combine the corn, olives, red pepper and cherry tomatoes with
the chives. Toss with the dressing and set aside. Just before
serving stir in the diced avocado.
</P>
<P>
   LIME DRESSING
</P>
<P>
   Makes 1/3 cup
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons canola oil
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon grated lime rind
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons fresh lime juice, strained
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon kosher salt
</P>
<P>
   freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   Combine all the ingredients in a small jar with a tight lid.
Shake well
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from a recipe in Ladle Leaf &AMP; Loaf by Lisa Cowden
(Houghton-Mifflin, $16).
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
