<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCMAKEOVER-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCDONALD'S IS REINVENTING ITSELF TO RECOUP LOST MARKET SHARE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WORTH WREN JR. 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BURLESON, Texas _ Diners in Plano eat Big Macs while sitting on
mahogany-stained wood chairs under crystal chandeliers, one of
which hangs from a faux gold-leaf replica of a 17th-century
medallion in a French chateau.
</P>
<P>
   In Burleson, customers can do their banking or grocery shopping
online or play computer games as they scarf down a burger and fries
while sitting on burgundy-colored seats, surrounded by wood
paneling accented with Texas limestone.
</P>
<P>
   Did somebody say this is McDonald's?
</P>
<P>
   Those two variations on the McDonald's theme are part of the
chain's collaboration with its approximately 5,000 franchisees
worldwide, said McDonald's USA President Allan Feldman.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we want to do is to give them the freedom and the tools
to be able to tailor their business to best fit the needs of that
community,'' he said on a recent tour of those two Metroplex
stores.
</P>
<P>
   ``In total over the last 18 months, the McDonald's system has
spent over $400 million reinventing its systems,'' Feldman said,
citing combined outlays by the company and franchisees nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   The world's largest fast-food chain has been scrambling for
years to regain lost U.S. market share _ and add more.
</P>
<P>
   In January, McDonald's stock dropped 10 percent when the company
said earnings this year will be lower than analysts' estimates,
despite a 40 percent rise in fourth-quarter 1999 profits.
</P>
<P>
   Now, after nine consecutive quarters of increased sales,
McDonald's is trying to cement those gains and build on them. It
has bought into three other chains, Chipotle for Mexican burritos
and tacos, Donatos for pizza and Italian cuisine, and Boston Market
for chicken and homestyle meals. It also invested in Food.com, an
online meal deliverer.
</P>
<P>
   And the company is focusing on its namesake restaurants. Feldman
talks about ambience and improving service, new menu items and
changing the food preparation system for the entire chain of 27,000
restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   McDonald's is adding items for aging baby boomers and other
health-conscious consumers, including three salads and the Fruit 'N
Yogurt Parfaits, two chicken sandwiches and Breakfast Bagels.
</P>
<P>
   Some things, however won't change, Feldman said. ``A Big Mac is
a Big Mac.''
</P>
<P>
   The way Big Macs are made has, however, changed, McDonald's
officals said. Gone are the premade sandwiches and other menu items
in heated bins. Now the patties come hot off a two-sided griddle,
the buns are toasted and the sandwiches are assembled only when
they're ordered, said Dave Hamilton, vice president for the
Southwest region, which covers a 385-store territory.
</P>
<P>
   The approach is new to McDonald's, but not to Sonic and some
other fast-food chains.
</P>
<P>
   McDonald's has tried previously to become more competitive, not
always successfully. The McLean burger, for example, was a failure.
And a corporate-driven national price war _ the 55-cent Big Mac and
breakfast deals in 1997 _ turned into a fiasco when franchisees
rebelled and refused to cut prices.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts at A.G. Edwards say it's too early to judge McDonald's
latest strategic redirection, which began in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   But the company has high hopes for it, an optimism that some
local franchisees share.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've moved away from a centralized approach to the
business,'' said John Charlesworth, McDonald's USA's Midwest
Division president.
</P>
<P>
   The centralized price controls also changed in 1997. ``We don't
control prices. Our owner-operators do,'' Feldman said, adding that
the only nationally advertised price is the $1.99 Happy Meal.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas-based franchisee Ed Bailey, co-owner/operator of the
Plano store and 30 others in the Metroplex, said the people at
McDonald's headquarters lost sight of their mission for a time but
have more than regained it.
</P>
<P>
   Fort Worth-based franchisee Joe Jasper said, ``From my view,
anecdotally, the relationship between McDonald's Corp. and its
franchisees is at its highest level of recent history.''
</P>
<P>
   The cyber offerings in Burleson are the brainchild of Jasper and
his brother, computer systems specialist Gene Jasper. ``It's my
personal view of what I see McDonald's could be in the future,''
Joe Jasper said.
</P>
<P>
   Sales are up 25 percent to 30 percent or more at Jasper's
Burleson restaurant, which reopened about two months ago, and at
three others he has similarly upgraded, he said. ``We have covered
our costs over the last 12 months,'' Jasper said. He is upgrading
another restaurant in the Cultural District in Forth Worth.
</P>
<P>
   The McMagination concept, which includes assortedcomputer games
and may include Internet links, is evolving, Jasper said. But other
franchisees from as far away as Australia, Japan and South America
have visited to examine it, Jasper said. So far, about 16 have
similar formats, which may eventually go chainwide.
</P>
<P>
   Bailey said the year-old Plano store has generated 60 percent
more sales than projected. The restaurant's dessert sales have
doubled since the McTreat Dessert Center for walk-up orders went
into operation, he said.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
