<SLUG> BC-NETWATCH0711-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Here comes the bride... she's wired
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Meet Peter and Melanie. They are getting married Sept.
6, and you're invited.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, anybody who watches NBC's ``Today'' show is invited.
In fact, anybody with Internet access can log onto the ``Today''
Web site (www.today.msnbc.com) and decide exactly what kind of
wedding Peter and Melanie will have.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Ginsberg, Melanie Nelson and millions of amateur wedding
planners around the world are part of a special segment called
``Today ties The Knot.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Zucker, executive producer of ``Today,'' said allowing
millions of viewers to have a part in the planning of a real
couple's wedding via the Web, then to see it happen right there at
Rockefeller Plaza in New York, would be a groundbreaking event. He
said the combination of the Web and TV can add an entirely new
dimension to the way people plan weddings.
</P>
<P>
   Peter and Melanie's interactive wedding adventure is an amazing
combination of old and new media. ``Today'' show viewers seem to be
an incredibly wired bunch who cast 130,000 votes to decide where
co-anchor Matt Lauer should go on the last stop of his
round-the-world stunt last May.
</P>
<P>
   Even more voters than that have been coming to the ``Today'' Web
site to help plan the couple's wedding. It's bad enough having
everyone from Mom to Aunt Gladys right down to the woman at the
Starbucks counter offering wedding advice. Think about Peter and
Melanie, who have a couple of hundred thousand people they don't
know deciding whether Melanie should go with the Carolina Herrera
or Paloma Blanca wedding gown.
</P>
<P>
   At least they don't have to invite them to the reception.
</P>
<P>
   Back on June 20, ``Today'' and wedding Web site TheKnot.com
(www.theknot.com) formed a 12-week partnership to choose a couple
and help them plan their wedding on live TV, along with the wedding
experts at TheKnot. Each week, viewers can tune in to watch Peter
and Melanie get tips on planning their wedding and then vote on
what one of the most significant days in their lives will be like.
</P>
<P>
   On the July 5 show, the giggling, hand-holding couple were shown
the wedding rings as selected by viewers, who cast more than
100,000 votes on the morning show's Web site. Next came the
opportunity to vote for a wedding gown and tuxedo. Peter seemed
concerned that no cummerbunds were involved, but Carley Roney,
editor-in-chief of TheKnot.com, assured Peter that he'd be hip
enough for his own wedding and possibly even the Oscars in whatever
tux viewers chose for him.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, the couple has agreed to go along with voters'
choices without a word of complaint. Clearly this is every
mother-of-the-bride's dream. And a lot of these mothers, even moms
who don't use the Web, are getting vicarious thrills by asking
wired friends to vote to give Peter and Melanie the wedding their
own unruly daughters didn't get.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for TheKnot says people are fascinated with Peter
and Melanie's interactive wedding because most have been to
weddings or endured the trauma of trying to plan one. Now they'd
like to do it right.
</P>
<P>
   That's one way of looking at it, but there could be more to it
than that. This type of reality TV is tailor-made for Internet
tie-ins. See the real people. See their dilemmas. Vote to help them
solve their problems, or vote them out of the limelight. What if
viewers had been able to decide if Puck got voted off ``Real
World'' or which ``Survivor'' cast member gets booted off the
island each week?
</P>
<P>
   However, you won't find anything that drastic or weird on the
``Today'' show, and that's just fine. This is a kinder, gentler way
to watch real people get on with their lives. Peter and Melanie are
real people (read all about them on the MSNBC Web site), and they
really are engaged to be married. They were selected from more than
1,000 couples who wanted to get married on the show, by a panel of
130,000 viewers who went to the Web site and voted for them.
</P>
<P>
   And the Web site makes this little slice of reality TV so
interesting. Not only do we get to plan the couple's wedding, we
also get to watch them get married outfitted with all the wedding
gear we've selected for them.
</P>
<P>
   We'll have to wait until September to find out what Peter and
Melanie really think of all this. Over the next 12 weeks, we'll be
able to vote on everything from who caters the reception to where
they go on their honeymoon.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there are probably a few decisions Peter and Melanie will
make for themselves that we won't get to vote on _ and that's
probably the way it ought to be.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
