<SLUG> BC-TECH-FAMILY0711-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Online newspaper access facilitates getting the facts
 &HT;    By Anne Meyers
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ I admit that when it comes to information gathering, I
have a personal bias toward newspapers. Online access to
out-of-town and local news stories is available with the click of a
mouse.
</P>
<P>
   Last month my father was making copies at his local Kinko's
store. He was well inside the store when a Ford Probe hopped the
curb, plowed through the store window and ended up on top of him.
</P>
<P>
   The police called my mother to meet them at the emergency room.
My mother called me from the hospital and told what she knew, which
was just not enough.
</P>
<P>
   I searched Web sites of their hometown media outlets and found
short news stories about the accident. These sites provided more
detail about the type of car and the driver's status.
</P>
<P>
   Living far from my family removes me from emergency room trips
and important day-to-day involvement. I miss being part of their
chaos, and I do what I can to stay tuned. I kept in contact with my
mother by telephone during the day of my father's accident and the
next morning headed back to my computer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can we find a picture of Grandpa on the Internet now?'' my
7-year-old asked. ``Will there be more stories about him?''
</P>
<P>
   My daughter and I logged on and found a newspaper article with a
photograph. The few new details helped us feel more plugged in.
</P>
<P>
   The next day we traveled to see my father. My mother showed us a
videotape of the television news. There were images of the
accident's aftermath. Real life is strange sometimes.
</P>
<P>
   I am curious. I am interested. And I am detail-hungry.
</P>
<P>
   The media (in its haste to get the story out) can sometimes be
wrong with the details, but they work to keep the public informed
at a fast and stressful pace.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of my father's accident, his age changed from story
to story, and the initial radio reports of the severity of his
injuries frightened my mother on her drive to the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   I still find this source to be more accurate than the usual path
that these stories take in person-to-person communication. In my
circle of neighbors and friends, there have been many stories that
made headlines.
</P>
<P>
   I try to read the story as soon as it hits the conversation
rounds so I understand better what the gossip is about. Then I feel
informed and may even be able to be helpful in some way.
</P>
<P>
   As Web time becomes as commonplace as couch time, I am finding
more people turning to the Internet in ways that I do.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, my friend Lisa's aunt was killed in a terrible car
accident that took four lives. Lisa checked online resources near
the accident scene including The Augusta Chronicle
(www.augustachronicle.com) for details. She wanted to know more.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, when Lisa and I talked, the story had not been posted
to the newspaper's site. We searched headlines from other sources
including First Headlines (www.1stheadlines.com), a compilation of
stories from hundreds of news sources.
</P>
<P>
   There are Web sites with links to newspaper sites. Newspapers
Online! (www.newspapers.com) is another free service, helping
people find newspaper links all around the world. Another old
favorite is the Internet Public Library, hosted by the School of
Information at the University of Michigan
(www.ipl.org/reading/news/).
</P>
<P>
   There are many large and small news organizations sharing
stories online. CNN (www.cnn.com) and MSNBC (www.msnbc
</P>
<P>
   .com) are just a few of the broadcast entities informing us
round-the-clock on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   For the stories that do not hit the big time, check the local
newspapers online for a chance to learn more.
</P>
<P>
   Many sites offer new and old stories for free; others charge for
access to archives.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
