<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-SAVVY0711-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Getting rid of Spam takes a lot of effort
 &HT;    By Sue Cleere and Jacki Rudd
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _
</P>
<P>
   Dear Sue and Jacki:
</P>
<P>
   I am at wit's end. I have no idea how I got on this list, but I
get daily junk from support (at)justsaywow.com that I do not want.
There is a lengthy address at the bottom of the message on how to
``unsubscribe,'' but I've been told that trying to unsubscribe will
result in being put on even more lists. Is there a way to
unsubscribe?
</P>
<P>
   _ John R. Adams, Loganville, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Sue: Spam, or junk mail, is unwanted or unsolicited e-mail, the
electronic variety of what can pile up in your mailbox at home. It
can be annoying, invasive and downright difficult to get
unsubscribed from.
</P>
<P>
   Jacki: It's also giving a lunch meat a bad name. For an overview
on spam, surf to www.mindworkshop.com
</P>
<P>
   /alchemy/nospam.html.
</P>
<P>
   Sue: There are sites that send e-mail telling you how to
unsubscribe. Then, once you respond, they've got you. Lots of sites
are doing it. They send out thousands of messages telling you about
their service. They tell you how to unsubscribe, as if you already
belong.
</P>
<P>
   Jacki: Pretty sneaky. Once you reply, they know your e-mail
address is legit and they zero in.
</P>
<P>
   Sue: One way to find out who is behind these sites is to go to
Network Solutions Web site at www.networksolutions.com/. This is
the place to register a domain name and to check who owns a domain
name. I clicked on the WHOIS Lookup link. Then I popped the
``justsaywow.com'' domain in the look-up search field.
</P>
<P>
   Jacki: We found the name of the person administering the site,
an address, a phone number, his e-mail account and who is
maintaining his Web site servers. Check it out for yourself. Be
aware that sometimes this information is outdated, but it's a good
place to start. Anyone can run this kind of check. Perhaps a chat
with the administrator?
</P>
<P>
   Sue: Another avenue is to talk to your ISP. Many ISPs offer spam
protection. You also may be able to run a local filter on your
e-mail account that deletes these incoming messages so you never
have to be bothered with them again.
</P>
<P>
   Jacki: If all else fails, there are a few online companies that
keep an eye on spammers. Look at www.mail-abuse.org/rbl
</P>
<P>
   /reporting.html or www.abuse.net/.
</P>
<P>
   Dear Readers:
</P>
<P>
   One of our first columns dealt with free ISPs. We received many
requests to run those names again. With help from you, we added to
the list. Here you go: Juno (juno.com); freeinternet
(www.freeinternet.com/); NetZero (www.netzero.com/); BlueLight.com
(www.bluelight.com/); freewwweb (www.freewwweb.com); iFreedom
(www.ifreedom.com); and AltaVista
(www.zdnet.com/downloads/altavista/). Remember, you can find free
ISPs by doing a simple Web search for ``free Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   Sue Cleere and Jacki Rudd write for The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution. E-mail questions to techsavvy(at)ajc.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
