<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Shop for tech support, not gigabytes and megahertz
 &HT;    By Bill Husted
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When you purchased your last microwave oven, did you
spend much time checking out who made the microwave transmitter? Or
did you make note of the cooking wattage? Did you spend some time
reading ``Microwave Ovens Made Simple''?
</P>
<P>
   My guess is that _ unafraid and untutored by any adult education
classes in the operation of microwaves _ you went down to the store
and simply picked out a microwave that was in your price range and
that looked big enough for your purposes.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe you haven't noticed _ you're not alone if you haven't,
because I don't hear many people talking about this yet _ but
personal computers are finally reaching the microwave oven stage in
the market cycle.
</P>
<P>
   Now, unless you are buying a PC to play games or to perform some
really complex and specialized task, the truth is that it doesn't
much matter what kind of computer you buy. I spent a few minutes
looking through the ads in Sunday's newspaper, and even the bargain
basement machines are much more powerful than my home PC.
</P>
<P>
   I have an old 350-megahertz Pentium II machine. And the slowest
machines I found in the ads were running at 500 megahertz. But the
truth is that _ unlike things were even a year ago _ there is no
real urgency for me to upgrade my PC.
</P>
<P>
   If you've read this column for a long time you may remember
Husted's First Law of Computer Purchasing: Replace your computer
when it can no longer perform your tasks in a reasonably efficient
manner. Despite the fact that I'm practically a computer genius
(just ask my mom), the tasks at my house are pretty simple. I do
word processing, figure my taxes, mess with the Internet and use
the computer to edit and store electronic photographs. And even the
old 350-megahertz PC breezes through those jobs.
</P>
<P>
   That shouldn't be surprising. Home PCs are now much more
powerful than the big mainframe computers that businesses used 10
years ago, enormously faster than the computers that were aboard
the Apollo spacecraft that landed on the moon. And, despite the
fact that software programs seem to get fatter and more heavily
laden with mostly useless features each year, most of the programs
that I use still do not strain my dinosaur of a PC.
</P>
<P>
   Now here's what that means to you. If you are an ordinary home
user in the market for a PC, you no longer need to worry about
whether you can pop for the very fastest machine. And frankly you
needn't worry too much about whether the PC you buy has an AMD
Athelon chip or one made by Intel. Both chips are well-proven and
(as computer hardware goes) trouble-free.
</P>
<P>
   Nowadays you need a new mind-set for PC buying. Instead of
agonizing over the specs (pondering the merits of a 15-gigabyte
hard disk compared to those of a 21-gigabyte disk, worrying whether
16 megabytes of VRAM is enough for a video card or whether you'd be
happier with 32 megabytes), shift your worries to ones that will be
familiar to most consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Take a look at the type of customer service and technical
support you can expect after the purchase. The rule of thumb is
that big brand-name manufacturers will do the best job. It's simply
a matter of God being on the side of the big battalions. Big
companies can afford to man a tech support line 24 hours a day,
seven days a week. Some of the smaller companies cannot. Be
especially wary of companies that offer support by e-mail and Web
site only.
</P>
<P>
   Find out what the repair policies are. Will you get on-site
repair service? Do you take the PC to a local store or repair
center? Is the PC shipped off to some distant repair center? Or
will you be shipped replacement parts and be expected to replace
them yourself? There are no wrong answers. A lot depends on what
feels comfortable to you. But find out in advance.
</P>
<P>
   Finally pay attention to the offer itself. Some machines are
bundled with useless software, free Internet service or accessories
that you already have in an effort to justify a higher price. Often
you'll do better just selecting the PC you want and then buying the
accessories you actually need.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
