<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A lukewarm slide show
 &HT;    By Staff Reports
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _
</P>
<P>
   Essentially a portable lamp, the Super Show Projector and
Flashlight ($15; www.fisher-price.com) suffers the common foible of
low-grade illumination, ``hot'' and ``cold'' spots emanating from
the reflector causing the beam's periphery to be brighter than the
center. As a slide show projector, this causes inconsistent
brightness of any given frame, weakest in the middle. Yet the Super
Show's durable design and obviously easy-to-please kiddy target
market still makes it worthy of purchase, especially considering
that those exceptionally fun ViewMaster Viewer discus slides can
now be projected on the wall, floor or ceiling for everyone to
enjoy (but not in three dimensions, of course, like in the original
dual-lens solo viewers). It requires four ``C'' batteries, which
are not included. It also would have been nice to see an AC power
adapter port on the unit, but dangling a 120-volt power cord in
front of a 3-year-old is probably ill advised anyway. Rechargeable
batteries are recommended.
</P>
<P>
   CLICK AND SAY 'CHEESE!'
</P>
<P>
   Maisy's Playhouse ($20; www. soundsourceinteractive.com) brings
the charming kiddy cartoon and book icon to the digital realm in a
sparse but effective suite of interactive learning games. The
affable mouse and her interactive house, as in other incarnations,
are crudely drawn in that childlike way with delightfully mild
voice-overs coaxing kids through a series of basic
shape-recognition games with an intuitive point-and-click
interface. One of the more ingratiating aspects of Maisy's
Playhouse is found in the sound effects, which are all done with
voice rather than genuine sound samples, making the learning
experience seemingly personalized, virtual that it may be.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
