<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CBy Staff Reports
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ toybox.asap.net/legend/ _ Remember the one about
the guy with a hook for a hand who microwaved his cat and then woke
up the next morning with a kidney missing? You can make up such a
scenario at the Urban Legend Machine, where you select scenarios
and watch the site's non-patented technology, the plausible urban
myth articulator, go to work. Not too complex, but fun nonetheless.
</P>
<P>
   shareyourworld.com
</P>
<P>
   portfolios.com _ Have a burning desire to get your creative
output on the Web, but scared to death of messing with HTML, the
language of the Web? These two user-friendly sites will let you put
up your images, animations or short films with the intent of
showing off your work. Will you be discovered online? Only time,
your talent and the feasibility of these sites' business plans can
determine that.
</P>
<P>
   www.theatlantic.com/unbound/wordpolice/ _ Are you a fussy
nitpicker when it comes to language? Good! On this site, you can
become a member of the Word Police by taking quizzes designed to
test your knowledge of the English language. Warning: Even the
entrance exam is tough.
</P>
<P>
   thecenter2000.com/accesspublicrecords.htm _ It's not what you
think. Really. But it's still a good idea to check out this site,
which purports to offer you confidential FBI records by looking you
up by name, state and social security number. Just don't blame us
for the result.
</P>
<P>
   www.ficus2000.com _ Choose a candidate: an incumbent or a potted
plant. An offshoot of filmmaker Michael Moore's TV show, ``The
Awful Truth,'' this is a campaign Web site for the 20-or-so ficus
plants that are running against congressional candidates. Two of
them are in Austin, so log on and check out their platforms (Hint:
They're covered in dirt).
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
