<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Word-WordPerfect debate turns serious
 &HT;    By Jack Warner
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ This debate we've been having over Word, WordPerfect
and formatting codes has taught me something _ there's an alarming
shortage of humor amongst you.
</P>
<P>
   There has been the expected rush of e-mail over the column a few
weeks ago about whether WordPerfect's ``reveal codes'' function is
useful or merely unpatriotic. Not one of them, with the possible
exception of dear Marj Becker of Colorado, seemed to realize I was
putting you on.
</P>
<P>
   ``A code is not to keep secrets,'' one reader lectures. ``A code
is to precisely instruct the software to do what you, the operator,
wants. Word and the all-knowing Bill Gates have determined that
you, and I, don't really know what we want or don't care and so
most of the time Word makes the decision for us. Fortunately, or
unfortunately, those of you who think Reveal Codes is a bother,
don't know or don't care but some of the rest of us do.''
</P>
<P>
   Another gets downright insulting:
</P>
<P>
   ``There are, it seems, two types of writers _ those who write
simple memos, and those who are serious about writing. Word is
great for the memo writers _ you don't have to worry about
anything, just type and type and the words come out _ sort of like
`Word Processing for Dummies' ''
</P>
<P>
   She presents some elaborate formatting concepts that she says WP
does better than Word, and concludes from this that ``there are the
professional writers, who love WordPerfect, and then there are the
memo writers.''
</P>
<P>
   Forgive me, madam, but it sounds to me like you are talking
about professional formatters, not professional writers.
</P>
<P>
   The redoubtable Ms. Becker, whose praise of WordPerfect started
all this, doesn't mince words.
</P>
<P>
   ``You and your wife may be the only people on the face of the
earth who like MS Word _ no secretary-type in this office (there
are about fifteen) does. Of course, they are far too shy to bring
up the subject of its incredibly unfriendly (would that make it
user-unfriendly?) program.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are my arms permanently attached to the keyboard? Some days I
think so. I do, however, detach them long enough to `smack around'
someone who attacks my WordPerfect. So, thanks for the
opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Becker, who leaves no stone unthrown, proceeds to smack me
around a little more for an egregious grammatical error in that
column.
</P>
<P>
   A number of readers sent in their answer to J.B. McKoy's
complaint about Word not allowing him to select noncontiguous
batches of text. It does, Mr. McKoy, it does.
</P>
<P>
   I believe Jim Penland of Atlanta was in first with the solution,
which is described in Word's help file.
</P>
<P>
   ``To select a vertical-horizontal box in Word, just hold down
the Alt key and use the left mouse button to select the text,'' he
wrote. ``Simple, effective, and, I agree, practically useless!''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
