<HEADER>
A9154 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-DIGITAL-MUSIC-0712-CO     07-11 0755
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIGITAL-MUSIC-0712-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Few common chords struck in hearing over music downloads
 &HT;    By BOB DART
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A songwriting senator summoned rock stars and
dot.com entrepreneurs to testify Tuesday about whether there is an
``upside of downloading'' music on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Chairman Orrin Hatch, a Utah Republican and singer-composer of
gospel and pop songs, called a hearing of the Senate Judiciary
Committee ``to learn more about the online music marketplace and
why there is so much disharmony.''
</P>
<P>
   The committee got an earful of the continuing cacophony over
online copyright protection.
</P>
<P>
   Lars Ulrich, drummer and co-founder of the band Metallica, said
his introduction to the problem came when the firm Napster
``hijacked our music without asking'' and enabled its subscribers
to duplicate the songs for free over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, Hank Barry, the CEO of Napster, disagreed. He
said Napster's technology merely permits its 20 million members to
individually share their collections of digitalized music and that
such ``sampling'' actually promotes CD sales. On many campuses,
Napster is so popular that high-speed college computer systems are
sometimes clogged with students swapping music files called MP3's.
</P>
<P>
   Roger McGuinn, a songwriter and founder of folk-rock's Byrds
band, said he has gotten a better deal distributing his music over
his own Internet site and the online firm MP3.com than he ever did
when major labels controlled his hits like ``The Ballad of Easy
Rider.''
</P>
<P>
   But Fred Erlich, Sony Music's president of new technology, said
artists as well as record labels will suffer if the ``value chain''
is broken through free online distribution of their works and there
is no financial incentive to create and produce music.
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses did strike a few common chords: The Internet has
already changed the way recorded music reaches consumers. Even in a
digital economy, there is intellectual property and artists should
be compensated for its creation. The issues go far beyond Napster,
a pioneering company that has generated far more controversy than
revenues. And justice has to keep up with technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must protect the rights of the creator,'' said Hatch. ``But
we cannot, in the name of copyright, unduly burden consumers and
the promising technology that the Internet presents to us all.''
</P>
<P>
   Hatch said the hearing was aimed at providing information rather
than writing legislation. Action on the issue will come sooner in
the courts than in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Metallica and the major record labels have filed lawsuits
charging Napster with copyright infringements. The record companies
also sued MP3.com over its plan to immediately put a digitalized
version of a CD on a customer's computer ``locker'' when they
bought the actual CD. The problem, according to the music industry,
was that MP3.com created a library of 45,000 copyrighted CDs to be
digitally send into the ``lockers'' rather than copying the actual
purchased CD.
</P>
<P>
   But Gene Kan, developer of Gnutella, another online music
distribution system, said the music industry had better recognize
that ``the toothpaste is already out of the tube'' and adjust.
While Napster is built upon a directory of members who exchange
music with each other, Gnutella's ``community'' is connected only
by a common software that they downloaded for free. The software
lets them exchange MP3 music files without passing through any sort
of central switchboard.
</P>
<P>
   Napster and Gnutella ``are like potlucks,'' Kan explained.
``Everyone brings what he or she wants to share and perhaps
partakes in what others brought.''
</P>
<P>
   Just like movie makers had to adjust to an era of easily copied
videotapes, record companies and artists themselves are going to
have to find a way to make a profit distributing music online, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   But some other online music distribution systems are also upset
with Napster and Gnutella. Gene Hoffman, president of EMusic.com,
said his firm has licensing agreements with many artists and
independent record labels that allow him to sell downloaded CD
tracks for 99 cents apiece. But even at that price, he said, its
hard to compete with free tracks.
</P>
<P>
   For online information: www.riaa.com
</P>
<P>
   www.napster.com
</P>
<P>
   www.EMusic.com
</P>
<P>
   Bob Dart's e-mail address is bobdart(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
