<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-11 17:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9155 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      07-11 0885
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     MINORITY PARTY MISCHIEF 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARIANNE MEANS  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The minority party candidates are making merry
mischief this presidential campaign. They are not to be taken
seriously on the merits but are nonetheless potentially troublesome
for Texas Gov. George W. Bush and Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Buchanan's raw power grab for the Reform Party's federal
funds and Ralph Nader's hypocritical opportunism as the Green Party
nominee are disgusting.
</P>
<P>
   Yet both could be selfish spoilers, distorting the outcome of a
close race. And the contest between Bush and Gore does look like a
squeaker.
</P>
<P>
   There is also Harry Browne, nominee of the Libertarian Party,
but he is unlikely to be much of a factor. The Libertarian platform
is a prescription for anarchy _ repeal of Social Security, ending
the war on drugs, wiping out the income tax and funding the
military through sales taxes and tariffs. This is fantasy stuff,
not political reality.
</P>
<P>
   And something called the Southern Party is trying to get off the
ground in South Carolina, where white resentment over the
downgrading of the Confederate flag has sparked a pro-secession
move. Dream on, fellows. Remember what happened in 1865 to the last
war over the union.
</P>
<P>
   Well, no one said democracy would be easy.
</P>
<P>
   Periodically scholars, journalists and idealists trumpet the
idea that the time has finally arrived for a real third party to
rival the two major ones. It didn't happen even when Theodore
Roosevelt tried it. So why should it happen now?
</P>
<P>
   Running as an independent in 1992, Ross Perot did the best in
modern times, getting 19 percent of the vote. But he spent $65
million of his own money doing it.
</P>
<P>
   His personality was so quirky and his grasp of facts so thin
that after he ran again as the founder of the Reform Party in 1996,
he was down to only 8 percent of the vote. But it was enough to
qualify his party for $12.6 million in federal funds for this
year's election, and that's the big lure for former Republican
Buchanan.
</P>
<P>
   A recent Newsweek poll finds Bush and Gore in a dead heat, with
Nader at 6 percent and Buchanan at 2 percent. Nader, pulling from
the left, would take voters almost entirely from Gore. Buchanan's
handful was stolen mostly from Bush.
</P>
<P>
   (Buchanan is still fighting for the Reform nomination with
Natural Law Party leader John Hagelin, whose platform is Anybody
but Buchanan. The party's convention will be in August in Long
Beach, Calif.)
</P>
<P>
   The also-ran numbers are not yet enough to scare the two real
candidates in the presidential race. But what if Nader and Buchanan
or Hagelin pick up a lot more supporters in the fall once the
general election is really under way? Many voters don't seem
energized by either Bush or Gore, which means they are vulnerable
to being swayed and sidetracked.
</P>
<P>
   What if the minor candidates manage to bull their way into the
presidential debates, currently closed to hopefuls who do not have
at least a 15 percent approval rating in the polls? They are
already trying through legal ploys and public appeals.
</P>
<P>
   The media exposure, in a forum that bills Nader and
Buchanan/Hagelin as co-equals with Bush and Gore, could
significantly muddy the issues. It would keep the messages of the
two principals from coming through. And let's face it, we need to
hear them because one of the two, not these other guys, is going to
be president.
</P>
<P>
   Historically, independent and third party candidates matter very
little in the long run.
</P>
<P>
   Even Alabama Gov. George Wallace, taken seriously in 1968,
garnered only 13.5 percent running on a new American Independent
party, pulling from both Democrats and Republicans. He may have
marginally helped Richard Nixon defeat Hubert Humphrey by half a
percentage point, but opinions vary on this.
</P>
<P>
   In 1976 former Sen. Eugene McCarthy won less than 1 percent of
the vote. His time, along with the flower children who loved him in
1968, had passed. He ran on a sour-grapes ticket, and that is not
the American way.
</P>
<P>
   In 1980 former Rep. John Anderson got 6.6 percent as an
independent. Liberals saw him as a rational alternative to the
disappointing President Jimmy Carter until it dawned on them they
would be throwing away their vote to elect Ronald Reagan.
</P>
<P>
   Third parties and independents may seem appealing until they are
really examined for who they are and what they stand for.
</P>
<P>
   Nader, the famous consumer advocate, now has more than $3
million in corporate stock investments. Yet his basic campaign
theme is that corporate America stinks and that Bush and Gore
aren't doing enough to control Wall Street. So why does he support
these evil companies with his own money?
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan, trying to take over a party founded on principles that
bear little relationship to his own, deserted the Republicans
because he was not going to win their nomination. So he says he
won't change the Reform platform. He'll just espouse his own
isolationist, cultural-backlash themes while spending the party's
money.
</P>
<P>
   This is nuts. The two-party system works fine, if not perfectly.
Why can't we leave it at that?
</P>
<P>
   (Marianne Means can be reached at the e-mail address means(at)
hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
