<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELLEN-GEER-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SWITCHING GEERS
</HEADLINE>
  Stage production of `Harold and Maude' becomes a family affair 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By EVAN HENERSON 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
Talk about an offbeat family legacy.
</P>
<P>
   In 1971, actress Ellen Geer made her film debut in an oddball
little number called ``Harold and Maude.'' You might remember it:
Suicide-obsessed kid falls for an 80-year-old free spirit?
</P>
<P>
   Geer had a single scene in the film, but it was a scene-stealer.
She played Sunshine Dore, the would-be actress who ends up being
young Harold Chasen's ``last date'' arranged by his mother through
a computer matchmaking service.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was the best thing I read in quite a while,''
recalled Geer, of the now-famous script written by the late Colin
Higgins. ``You know, it's very rare to have a good experience in
film and to work with (director) Hal Ashby was extraordinary.''
</P>
<P>
   Fast forward nearly 30 years to the Theatricum Botanicum in
Topanga, where Geer serves as artistic director. In Higgins' stage
adaptation of ``Harold and Maude,'' which runs weekends through
Sept. 30, Geer will now get to tackle the role of Maude (played in
the film by Ruth Gordon). But director Heidi Helen Davis has kept
Sunshine in the family, so to speak. Ellen Geer's daughter, Willow
Geer-Alsop, will share the role with Abby Craden (OK, Craden's not
a Geer, but she's still practically family since since she's
engaged to marry Ellen's son, Ian Flanders.)
</P>
<P>
   A quirk of casting, perhaps, but for Davis, rebuilding ``Harold
and Maude'' wasn't just a matter of switching Geers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would adamantly say that I cast the people who I thought
were the best,'' said Davis, who has worked with both Craden and
Geer-Alsop in past productions. ``Every time we left the auditions,
Ellen would say, `You have to pick the right ones. Don't let family
be the deciding factor. You don't have to please me.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``They both gave wonderful readings,'' says the ever-diplomatic
Geer. `I'm glad I wasn't the director. I wouldn't have been able to
choose.''
</P>
<P>
   Once it was established the role would be double cast, neither
Sunshine said she planned to copy her predecessor. Both had seen
the film; both elected not to study it again or ask Geer for tips.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we all rented `Harold and Maude' at Halloween or
something,'' says Craden. ``When I watched it, I didn't know I was
going to be playing the role, so it wasn't from an acting point of
view. I just watched it to look at Ellen and see how beautiful she
was when she was young. It was amazing to see her do her work.''
</P>
<P>
   Geer-Alsop, who even in junior high school was aware that her
mom was part of a cult film, didn't feel extra pressure in taking
on her mother's role. ``When I saw the movie, I'm thinking, `OK,
how am I going to do this? How am I going to make it my own?''' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then, of course, at the audition, all these old actors and
friends kept walking in right before I'm about to start, so I have,
like, this huge audience.''
</P>
<P>
   Two actresses mean two interpretations. Theatricum audiences
aren't likely to confuse red-haired Geer-Alsop, a sophomore at
UCLA, and brunet Craden, an award-winning actress with professional
credits at theaters from Los Angeles to Santa Barbara.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're so different. It's marvelous,'' says Craden. ``We watch
each other, and we're completely different.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, if anybody in this production is drawing inspiration
from a family member, it's Ellen Geer herself. Geer acquired the
rights to ``Harold and Maude'' in the hopes that her 83-year-old
mother, Herta Ware, would play Maude. The timing didn't work out,
so Geer inherited the Maude mantle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I put a lot of her into it, because she is Maude,'' says Geer.
``She's the most Maude Maude I've ever met.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
