NYT-07-11-00 1701EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000711.0175 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-11 17:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9161 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-FBN-FALCONS-JAMAL-COX     07-11 1047
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-JAMAL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA - Soon after hearing a loud pop on a non-contact play
against Dallas in the Monday-night game Sept. 20, Jamal Anderson
became invisible.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson, who tore the anterior cruciate ligament in his right
knee, could barely stand, let alone stand to watch, as the Falcons
plummeted from Super Bowl XXXIII to 5-11.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt very responsible,'' he said. ``Trying to stand on the
sidelines, it was like being a ghost. After a while, I couldn't (do
it). You're there, but not there. I couldn't do anything, was
helpless. I kept thinking, `What if they forget me, forget I'm
there?' ``
</P>
<P>
   Anderson isn't forgotten. The state of his recuperation will be
the biggest story when the Falcons report to training camp Thursday
at Furman University in Greenville, S.C.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Anderson was master of his domain. But for the
past 10 months, he has been mastered by the injury and his knee.
The memory has faded of his All-Pro 1998 season, when he rushed an
NFL-record 410 times for a franchise-record 1,846 yards. By April,
Anderson was on track to participate in voluntary passing camp in
June. Then, in May, the right patella tendon from which tissue was
grafted to repair his knee became inflamed. The pain from the
tendinitis limited him to two of 16 practices. ``Jamal learned he
needs to be honest with us about how his knee feels,'' trainer Ron
Medlin said.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson resumed cutting exercises Monday, and expects to be
ready for Friday's first practice.
</P>
<P>
   However, his official status is uncertain. He tries to sound
confident about his comeback. ``Of critical importance to me is to
be able to start this camp, and quickly get to where I can just
go,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   But a few minutes later, he will say, ``I haven't set a panic
date, but I would panic in late August if this thing were still
bugging me.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson, who has Hollywood aspirations after his football
career, is the only Falcon consistently referred to by first name
only.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see so many people, after a game, they're, like, `Oh, yeah,
we played well. We got after `em,' `` he said, using a monotone
voice. ``That's just not me. I'm outgoing but laid back, if that
makes sense.''
</P>
<P>
   But Jamal insists that he's an ordinary Joe. Perhaps it's only
an act when he teases reporters, does the ``Dirty Bird'' dance in
the end zone and struts like a peacock. His house in Duluth is not
the home of an ordinary Joe. Bought after he signed a five-year,
$32 million contract in August, it is big but decorated nicely in
an understated way that belies Jamal's reputation.
</P>
<P>
   Except for the basement. There, he has a bar, a theater, game
balls from the Falcons, magazine covers, large oil paintings of
Michael Jordan and Barry Sanders, shorts that Muhammad Ali boxed in
and memorabilia signed by buddies Mike Tyson, Marcus Allen, Karl
Malone and Eddie George.
</P>
<P>
   But out back, he has a grill, where he cooks hot dogs and
burgers. He has Michelob in the fridge. His office has stacks of
stuff, and boxes of more. In the living room, there's a basket of
toys. On the kitchen counter, crumbs.
</P>
<P>
   In those surroundings, it's much easier to imagine Jamal as an
ordinary Joe.
</P>
<P>
   On the job, Anderson is the player that reporters go to for
color.But much of it's show. When the tape recorders are off,
Anderson solicits opinions, seeks advice, occasionally asks that a
secret be kept.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I'm walking through a mall or something, I come up to
people and mess with them just to disarm them, let them know I'm no
different,'' he said. Anderson has become a family man. His
daughters, 2 1/2 and 1, live with him in Atlanta, not in Salt Lake
City, where he previously spent offseasons.The names of family
members remain private.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're a lot bigger part of my life,'' he said. ``When you
get to a certain point, you're a lot more guarded - more protective
of certain things.''
</P>
<P>
   Teammates and coach Dan Reeves are hoping Anderson returns to
form soon. Last season, the Falcons were next to last in the NFL in
rushing. When Anderson ran for more than 100 yards in 12 of 16
regular-season games in 1998, Atlanta led the league in time of
possession.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest thing was he kept (the defense) off the field,''
Tuggle said. ``And you knew when Jamal hit the field, he came to
punish people. That motivated you.''
</P>
<P>
   The threat of Anderson cleared the way for the passing game,
which led the NFL in yards per passing attempt.
</P>
<P>
   ``You also missed his leadership during games, during
practice,'' Reeves said. ``Any time you have a guy who has the
confidence Jamal has, it's contagious.''
</P>
<P>
   Wide receiver Terance Mathis agrees. ``Jamal has a `Me'
attitude, and it's a good thing,'' Mathis said. ``He gives us a
little flash, a little brawn and excitement. That carried us in
`98.''
</P>
<P>
   After learning that Anderson's 1999 season was over, teammates
and coaches said the right things, the usual things about picking
up the slack. In reality, with quarterback Chris Chandler already
nursing a lame hamstring, the Falcons' season was dead.
</P>
<P>
   ``When his knee went out in that Dallas game, I think the team
as a whole lost a lot of confidence,'' Tuggle said. Revenge is
another motivator in Anderson's rehabilitation. It burns Anderson
that some fans associate his injury with his contract holdout last
summer. Some of the fan mail he has received hurt worse than having
scar tissue broken up in his knee.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's heard whispers of `one-year wonder,' `` King said. ``It
pains him.''
</P>
<P>
   Other than the sore knee, Anderson is in pretty good shape. But
these numbers pain him: 1999 19 carries, 59 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``I waited all my career to play on Monday Night Football,'' he
said, ``and then to blow out my knee on a play like that it was,
like, `This is unreal.' `` The ghost is tired of being invisible.
He expects to be back, even if he has to take every other practice
off for a while.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always put pressure on myself, but especially now,'' he
said. ``Somebody told me, and I agree, that you know you're there
when, whether they love you or hate you, they damn sure want to see
you and talk about you.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
