<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEOGAME-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KIRBY 64 IS THE BEST KIRBY GAME YET
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MALCOLM MAYHEW 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For years now, Kirby has been kind of a video-game underdog.
While your kids beg for Tomb Raider and Lara Croft, James Bond and
GoldenEye 007 and Pikachu and Pokemon (come to think of it, do
people still care about Pokemon?), Kirby just sort of sits there, a
hero to those who've bought Kirby-related games, a who's-that? to
everyone else.
</P>
<P>
   Which makes the little pink Pac-Man-like critter's games all the
more inviting; it's like your own special little club that know one
else knows _ or, ahem, cares _ about.
</P>
<P>
   Kirby's latest title, Kirby 64: The Crystal Shards (Nintendo for
N64), is easily the best Kirby game yet, if only because it
combines elements of previous Kirby titles with looking-forward
twists and turns.
</P>
<P>
   The game's story line finds Kirby teaming up with old pals
Waddle Dee and King Dedede for a trip around six planets. You guys
are hunting for Crystal Shards.
</P>
<P>
   Fans of Mario 64 will notice plenty of similarities, starting
with the hunt-for-those-crystal-thingees. Another familiar sight
will be the colorful, three-dimensional graphics. As in Mario, you
direct Kirby through 360-degree environments, meaning you can move
him in any direction possible.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, as is the case with Mario, there are several mini-games
hidden throughout, including an especially fun four-player
showdown.
</P>
<P>
   If this sounds like a complete Mario rip, well, to some extent
it is. But there are enough elements of past Kirby games _ all the
characters, some of the same game-playing styles _ to give this a
fresh, yet familiar, vibe. Dig in, Kirby fans, all 12 of ya.
</P>
<P>
   Walt Disney Pictures Presents Dinosaur (UbiSoft for Game Boy
Color): If you've seen the movie _ uh, anyone? _ you already know
the basis for this game: Lead the dinosaurs to the safety of their
nesting grounds, apparently so they can later star in Jurassic
Park.
</P>
<P>
   For a Game Boy title, this isn't bad. The graphics are
relatively decipherable, and the game has quite a bit of replay
value, in a Tetris sort of way. Too bad the movie didn't have this
much bite.
</P>
<P>
   Starcraft 64 (Blizzard Entertainment for N64): Continuing the
trend of porting over each and every Super Nintendo title to the
N64, Blizzard's update of Starcraft simply doesn't have the
firepower of other N64 games. Longtime fans of the futuristic war
game will love the strategic elements here _ building armies,
making war plans, blah de blah. But casual gamers will yawn at the
graphics and the somewhat slow gameplay. This is strictly for the
hard-core fan.
</P>
<P>
   (Malcolm Mayhew covers pop culture for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call her at (817) 390-7713, or e-mail:
mmayhew(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
