A9170 &Cx1f; tab-z
u k BC-ROEPER-HARRYPOTTER-CO     07-11 1038
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROEPER-HARRYPOTTER-COLUMN-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN CELEBRITIES ARE PILOTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use Tuesday, July 11, or thereafter.)  
 (ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's ROEPER COLUMN. For more information about
purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a
client of the ROEPER COLUMN _ contact one of the New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of the text.) 
 By RICHARD ROEPER  
 c.2000 The Chicago Sun-Times  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   As I worked my way through the 734 pages of ``Harry Potter and
the Goblet of Fire'' on Friday, every time I came across an
unfamiliar term I'd jot it down.
</P>
<P>
   Muggles, floo powder, Quidditch, Hogwarts, Mudbloods, sorting
hat, Snitch ...
</P>
<P>
   Before reaching page 100 I had scribbler's cramp and I gave up.
</P>
<P>
   One of the myriad charms of the Potter series is the expanding
glossary of terms invented by J.K. Rowling _ everything from the
wonderfully Dickensian character names (Albus Dumbledore, Cedric
Diggory, Professor Moody) to the wizard-and-witches lingo, e.g.,
memory charms and portkeys and dementors.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Rowling finishes the seven-book series, some of
these words will no doubt be in the Webster's dictionary, just like
such recent additions as ``dot-com,'' ``24-7,'' ``phat'' and ``eye
candy.''
</P>
<P>
   But at least with Potterisms we can give credit where credit is
due. The origins of many slang terms are nearly impossible to
discern; they just ooze into the popular dialogue until they're so
ubiquitous they reach Betty White.
</P>
<P>
   Right now there are dozens of exceedingly clever terms
circulating on the Web, usually under the heading ``Early 00's
Vocabulary.'' Every week someone forwards some version of the list
to me _ but I've never been able to find the author(s). Something
tells me these phrases are like urban legends and disaster jokes _
invented by a secret committee of magical, anonymous, big-brained
idea junkies, working out of a big room somewhere beneath the
streets of the city.
</P>
<P>
   If there's someone out there who can prove they invented any or
all of these terms I'd love to give you the proper kudos. Until
then, I hereby present some of my favorite entrants from the
Internet Glossary of Terms, 2000 Edition, authored by Anonymous.
</P>
<P>
   ADMINISPHERE: The rarefied organizational layers of upper
management, e.g., ``We have to do it, the orders came from the
adminisphere.''
</P>
<P>
   ALPHA GEEK: The person in your group who knows the most about
computers.
</P>
<P>
   ASSMOSIS: Process by which some seemingly incompetent people in
the office seem to absorb salary increases and promotions by
kissing up to the big boss.
</P>
<P>
   BATTLE FAXES: Flurry of hostile faxes sent between warring
lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   BEEPILEPSY: That quick body jolt you see when someone's beeper
goes off.
</P>
<P>
   BLAMESTORMING: Getting together with a group of coworkers to
talk about why a deadline was missed or a proposal was rejected.
</P>
<P>
   BODY NAZIS: Workout nuts who drive everybody else crazy with
their constant talk about exercise and their incessant nagging of
those who don't work out.
</P>
<P>
   CLM (CAREER LIMITING MOVE): Dissing your boss while she's within
earshot or mistakenly sending a nasty interoffice message to the
wrong person is a CLM.
</P>
<P>
   CHIPS AND SALSA: Another computer term, signifying hardware
(chips) and software (salsa).
</P>
<P>
   EGO SURFING: Typing in your own name on Internet search engines.
</P>
<P>
   404: Someone who's a dim bulb. The term comes from the Internet
error message, ``404 Not Found,'' meaning that the requested
document is unavailable.
</P>
<P>
   FLIGHT RISK: Employee who seems destined to leave the company
soon.
</P>
<P>
   GENERICA: Lookalike stretches of fast-food joints, strip malls,
etc., found all over suburbia, as in, ``We drove through 600 miles
of Generica, man.''
</P>
<P>
   IDEA HAMSTERS: Energetic workers who always come up with fresh
concepts.
</P>
<P>
   IRRITAINTMENT: News events that become cable-channel staples,
e.g., Elian Gonzalez, the O.J. Simpson trial, Monica Lewinsky,
Princess Di's crash.
</P>
<P>
   MOUSE POTATO: The cyber-generation's answer to the Couch Potato.
Someone who sits at the home computer for hours at a time.
</P>
<P>
   PERCUSSIVE MAINTENANCE: Attacking a technical problem by
whacking the offending machine several times.
</P>
<P>
   SEAGULL MANAGER: Midlevel executive who has a propensity for
showing up at your desk, making a lot of noise, crapping over
everything and then flying off.
</P>
<P>
   SITCOMS: (Single Income, Two Children, Oppressive Marriage.)
What yuppie families turn into when one spouse stops working to
care for the kids.
</P>
<P>
   STARTER MARRIAGE: A brief first marriage of twentysomethings
that produces no children, no property purchase, no lasting
commitment and no hard feelings.
</P>
<P>
   SWIPED OUT: What happens when an ATM card's magnetic strip has
been worn out due to constant use.
</P>
<P>
   UNINSTALLED: Fired from the job, e.g., ``They uninstalled
Freddie today!'.
</P>
<P>
   And my favorite of all has to be ...
</P>
<P>
   UMFRIEND, a term used when introducing a secret or new lover, as
in: ``This is Winona, my ... um, friend.''
</P>
<P>
   (Richard Roeper (rroeper(at)suntimes.com) is a columnist for the
Chicago Sun-Times and the author, most recently, of ``Urban
Legends: The Truth Behind All Those Deliciously Entertaining Myths
That Are Absolutely, Positively, 100% Not True!'' Roeper is also a
commentator for Fox News in Chicago and has appeared on programs
such as ``Nightline,'' ``The CBS Evening News with Dan Rather,''
``Oprah'' and ``The Drudge Report.'')
</P>
<P>
   -------------------------------------------------
</P>
