<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOREA-BANKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOREAN BANK WORKERS AGREE TO END STRIKE 
</HEADLINE>
   By SAMUEL LEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEOUL, South Korea _ The South Korean government and labor
leaders agreed on Tuesday to end a strike by bank workers who
walked off their jobs earlier in the day to protest mergers that
could lead to thousands of layoffs.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 20,000 of the country's 65,000 unionized bank
workers went on strike on Tuesday, as reports circulated about
last-minute talks between the union and government.
</P>
<P>
   The union, the Korean Federation of Bank and Financial Labor
Unions, had called the strike to protest legislation that would
authorize the creation of financial holding companies, which
regulators have suggested may be the first step in merging troubled
banks. Bank workers, like workers in other Korean industries that
have undergone major restructuring in the last two years, fear that
consolidation would lead to sweeping layoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Union leaders hailed the agreement reached on Tuesday. ``A major
achievement was in making sure government-influenced bank decisions
will no longer be allowed,'' said Lee Yong-deuk, chief of the
banking union.
</P>
<P>
   But South Korea's top financial regulator said that while the
government promised not to order banks to merge, it still intended
to proceed with its restructuring efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expect increased momentum in implementing the next round of
financial restructuring,'' said Lee Yong-keun, the chairman of the
Financial Supervisory Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Details of the agreement between the union and the government
will be announced on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Still, investors saw the announcement as a sign that the
government would not be diverted from an overhaul of financial
services. Bank stocks surged on Tuesday, even as the benchmark
stock index fell 1.72 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Bank restructuring was a part of the reform package the South
Korean government accepted in return for a $58-billion bailout from
the International Monetary Fund in late 1997.
</P>
<P>
   In December 1997, there were 33 South Korean banks, including
state-invested banks. By the end of last year, there were 23. From
December 1997 to 1998, the number of bank workers fell to 75,332
from 113,493.
</P>
<P>
   Kim Dae-shik, a professor of economics at Chung Ang University
here, noted that the government's resolve in cleaning up troubled
investment trusts weakened last year, compared with its closure of
banks in 1998. ``During the last two and a half years, there was no
set gauge that governed bank restructuring,'' he said. ``I believe
the government will use the next round of restructuring as a
milestone for its restructuring drive.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-11-00 1708EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000711.0181 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-11 17:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9174 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-AFGHAN-WOMEN-NYT &LR;      07-11 0561
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AFGHAN-WOMEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TALIBAN RETARDS U.N. EFFORTS TO AID WORKING WOMEN IN AFGHANISTAN 
</HEADLINE>
   By BARBARA CROSSETTE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ Years of United Nations efforts to help women
in Afghanistan return to work outside their homes have been set
back in recent days by the radical Islamic Taliban movement that
controls most of the country, officials said here on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, a new edict circulated in Kabul, the capital, saying
that Afghan women would no longer be allowed to work with the
United Nations or private relief organizations, the only work
available to many women who must support families in a country
devastated by decades of civil war. The edict was issued by the
Ministry of Planning, which followed up its announcement with
letters to all aid agencies in the country.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, the Taliban's religious police arrested an American,
Mary MacMakin, 71, who had been working with Afghan widows through
an organization she founded, the Physiotherapy and Rehabilitation
Support for Afghanistan. Seven Afghan women working for her also
were arrested and MacMakin, who has lived in Afghanistan off and on
for more than 30 years, refused a Taliban offer to go free and
leave her colleagues in their custody.
</P>
<P>
   The Taliban, who had taken control of most of the country by
1996, have generally opposed women working outside the home. Over
the least year, however, women had begun to return to jobs in
health, education and food services.
</P>
<P>
   U.N. officials in the region said that the edict and subsequent
arrests have frightened many Afghan women, who are staying away
from work they need rather than risk arrest at the hands of
religious police who also monitor how the women dress, demanding
that they be covered from head to toe.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the United States, which has no diplomatic relations
with the Taliban, called for MacMakin's immediate release in a
statement from the American embassy in Islamabad, the capital of
neighboring Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
   MacMakin had in the past been critical of the American boycott
of the Taliban. During a recent visit to the United States to raise
money for her struggling charity, she said that the isolation
imposed on Afghanistan by the Clinton Administration, alone and
through Security Council sanctions, was hurting the poorest Afghans
most.
</P>
<P>
   The Taliban have never been permitted to take Afghanistan's U.N.
seat, which is still held by an opposition alliance operating from
outside the country. Still, U.N. officials are able to work in the
country, a very poor nation now suffering a severe drought.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the U.N. coordinator for Afghanistan, Erick de
Mul, is expected to go to Kandahar, the Taliban's spiritual
capital, to talk with Foreign Minister Wakil Ahmed Muttawakil about
the new edicts. De Mul has spent many months negotiating with the
Taliban for small advances in women's rights, and U.N. agencies, in
particular the World Food Program, have made the hiring of women
mandatory if the Taliban want to continue receiving aid.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement on Tuesday, the United Nations said that without
the participation of women, many programs in Afghanistan will be
severely affected.
</P>
<P>
   ``Countrywide, hundreds of women would be affected by this new
edict,'' said Marie Okabe, a spokeswoman for Secretary-General Kofi
Annan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-11-00 1710EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000711.0182 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-11 17:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9176 &Cx1f; tab-z
u k BC-ROEPER-HARRYPOTTER-CO     07-11 1039
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROEPER-HARRYPOTTER-COLUMN-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARRY POTTERISMS AND WEB-SPEAK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use Tuesday, July 11, or thereafter.)  
 (ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's ROEPER COLUMN. For more information about
purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a
client of the ROEPER COLUMN _ contact one of the New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of the text.) 
 By RICHARD ROEPER  
 c.2000 The Chicago Sun-Times  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   As I worked my way through the 734 pages of ``Harry Potter and
the Goblet of Fire'' on Friday, every time I came across an
unfamiliar term I'd jot it down.
</P>
<P>
   Muggles, floo powder, Quidditch, Hogwarts, Mudbloods, sorting
hat, Snitch ...
</P>
<P>
   Before reaching page 100 I had scribbler's cramp and I gave up.
</P>
<P>
   One of the myriad charms of the Potter series is the expanding
glossary of terms invented by J.K. Rowling _ everything from the
wonderfully Dickensian character names (Albus Dumbledore, Cedric
Diggory, Professor Moody) to the wizard-and-witches lingo, e.g.,
memory charms and portkeys and dementors.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Rowling finishes the seven-book series, some of
these words will no doubt be in the Webster's dictionary, just like
such recent additions as ``dot-com,'' ``24-7,'' ``phat'' and ``eye
candy.''
</P>
<P>
   But at least with Potterisms we can give credit where credit is
due. The origins of many slang terms are nearly impossible to
discern; they just ooze into the popular dialogue until they're so
ubiquitous they reach Betty White.
</P>
<P>
   Right now there are dozens of exceedingly clever terms
circulating on the Web, usually under the heading ``Early 00's
Vocabulary.'' Every week someone forwards some version of the list
to me _ but I've never been able to find the author(s). Something
tells me these phrases are like urban legends and disaster jokes _
invented by a secret committee of magical, anonymous, big-brained
idea junkies, working out of a big room somewhere beneath the
streets of the city.
</P>
<P>
   If there's someone out there who can prove they invented any or
all of these terms I'd love to give you the proper kudos. Until
then, I hereby present some of my favorite entrants from the
Internet Glossary of Terms, 2000 Edition, authored by Anonymous.
</P>
<P>
   ADMINISPHERE: The rarefied organizational layers of upper
management, e.g., ``We have to do it, the orders came from the
adminisphere.''
</P>
<P>
   ALPHA GEEK: The person in your group who knows the most about
computers.
</P>
<P>
   ASSMOSIS: Process by which some seemingly incompetent people in
the office seem to absorb salary increases and promotions by
kissing up to the big boss.
</P>
<P>
   BATTLE FAXES: Flurry of hostile faxes sent between warring
lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   BEEPILEPSY: That quick body jolt you see when someone's beeper
goes off.
</P>
<P>
   BLAMESTORMING: Getting together with a group of coworkers to
talk about why a deadline was missed or a proposal was rejected.
</P>
<P>
   BODY NAZIS: Workout nuts who drive everybody else crazy with
their constant talk about exercise and their incessant nagging of
those who don't work out.
</P>
<P>
   CLM (CAREER LIMITING MOVE): Dissing your boss while she's within
earshot or mistakenly sending a nasty interoffice message to the
wrong person is a CLM.
</P>
<P>
   CHIPS AND SALSA: Another computer term, signifying hardware
(chips) and software (salsa).
</P>
<P>
   EGO SURFING: Typing in your own name on Internet search engines.
</P>
<P>
   404: Someone who's a dim bulb. The term comes from the Internet
error message, ``404 Not Found,'' meaning that the requested
document is unavailable.
</P>
<P>
   FLIGHT RISK: Employee who seems destined to leave the company
soon.
</P>
<P>
   GENERICA: Lookalike stretches of fast-food joints, strip malls,
etc., found all over suburbia, as in, ``We drove through 600 miles
of Generica, man.''
</P>
<P>
   IDEA HAMSTERS: Energetic workers who always come up with fresh
concepts.
</P>
<P>
   IRRITAINTMENT: News events that become cable-channel staples,
e.g., Elian Gonzalez, the O.J. Simpson trial, Monica Lewinsky,
Princess Di's crash.
</P>
<P>
   MOUSE POTATO: The cyber-generation's answer to the Couch Potato.
Someone who sits at the home computer for hours at a time.
</P>
<P>
   PERCUSSIVE MAINTENANCE: Attacking a technical problem by
whacking the offending machine several times.
</P>
<P>
   SEAGULL MANAGER: Midlevel executive who has a propensity for
showing up at your desk, making a lot of noise, crapping over
everything and then flying off.
</P>
<P>
   SITCOMS: (Single Income, Two Children, Oppressive Marriage.)
What yuppie families turn into when one spouse stops working to
care for the kids.
</P>
<P>
   STARTER MARRIAGE: A brief first marriage of twentysomethings
that produces no children, no property purchase, no lasting
commitment and no hard feelings.
</P>
<P>
   SWIPED OUT: What happens when an ATM card's magnetic strip has
been worn out due to constant use.
</P>
<P>
   UNINSTALLED: Fired from the job, e.g., ``They uninstalled
Freddie today!'.
</P>
<P>
   And my favorite of all has to be ...
</P>
<P>
   UMFRIEND, a term used when introducing a secret or new lover, as
in: ``This is Winona, my ... um, friend.''
</P>
<P>
   (Richard Roeper (rroeper(at)suntimes.com) is a columnist for the
Chicago Sun-Times and the author, most recently, of ``Urban
Legends: The Truth Behind All Those Deliciously Entertaining Myths
That Are Absolutely, Positively, 100% Not True!'' Roeper is also a
commentator for Fox News in Chicago and has appeared on programs
such as ``Nightline,'' ``The CBS Evening News with Dan Rather,''
``Oprah'' and ``The Drudge Report.'')
</P>
<P>
   -------------------------------------------------
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EDITOR: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on the ROEPER
COLUMN and other features. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NONSUBSCRIBERS: To publish a ``separate-buy'' feature article, it
must be purchased. Please contact one of these sales
representatives: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   --U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at
1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.
</P>
<P>
   --Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942.
</P>
<P>
   --Latin America: ANA PENA in New York, 212-499-3333; fax,
212-499-3382. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
