<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-11 17:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9177 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-FRANCE-CORSICA-NYT &LR;      07-11 0593
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRANCE-CORSICA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRANCE OFFERS HIGH LEVEL OF AUTONOMY TO CORSICA 
</HEADLINE>
   By SUZANNE DALEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ After months of negotiations with Corsican nationalists,
Prime Minister Lionel Jospin of France has offered the small
Mediterranean island a level of autonomy that no other French
region enjoys, including a limited right to modify laws voted in
Paris.
</P>
<P>
   The plan is aimed at ending more than 25 years of bombings and
political assassinations by Corsican separatists fighting for the
island's independence. But it was rejected almost immediately by
island leaders, who said on Tuesday that Jospin had not gone far
enough.
</P>
<P>
   The leader of the Corsican National party, Jean Guy Talamoni,
dismissed the proposals as ``hasty improvisations.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This text does not suit us,'' Talamoni said. ``It is null and
void.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, he seemed encouraged by the offer, saying he had every
intention of returning to the negotiating table, where he thought
he could get a better deal.
</P>
<P>
   Jospin has been meeting regularly with the Corsican leaders
since a cease-fire was declared in December. But he has come under
fire from the right, and even from some of his own ministers, for
conducting negotiations with people who have refused to condemn
violence.
</P>
<P>
   His proposals _ unveiled at a Monday night meeting with Corsican
officials _ offer the right to modify laws on a limited basis,
though exactly how this would work remained an open question. It
would also give Corsica's local government a range of new powers in
areas such as economic development, education, transportation, and
environment.
</P>
<P>
   And, it calls for the Corsican language, a dialect of Italian,
to become an obligatory part of the school curriculum, unless a
parent asks for an exception.
</P>
<P>
   However, it leaves several thorny issues unresolved. For
instance, the Corsicans have been asking for a general amnesty for
those involved in the political violence and a release of
``political prisoners.'' But there is no mention of these issues.
</P>
<P>
   Jospin's plan drew immediate criticism from the right, which
warned that the new powers being offered would now be sought by
other regions and would undermine the French republic. But some
analysts dismissed this notion, saying that Corsica is unique.
</P>
<P>
   ``Other regions don't have this coherence,'' said Emmanuel
Negrier, an analyst with the National Center for Scientific
Research, a Paris based study group. ``Corsica is a very specific
place. It is an island. It is not urbanized. It is behind in many
socioeconomic ways.''
</P>
<P>
   Jospin began his initiative at a time when relations between the
island and France had been at a particularly low point. In 1998,
the highest-ranking French government official on the island,
Claude Erignac, was assassinated, while walking to meet his wife
for a classical music concert in Ajaccio, the island capital. He
was shot three times in the back and twice in the neck.
</P>
<P>
   When France sent in a successor with a get-tough approach, the
result was a scandal. The official, Bernard Bonnet, was removed
from office after he was accused of ordering police officers to set
fire to a restaurant that had been built illegally on the beach.
</P>
<P>
   Polls indicate that the vast majority of Corsicans, perhaps 85
percent, want to remain a part of France. But the island's
tumultuous politics _ it's 250,000 inhabitants have 14 parties to
choose from _ are dominated by nationalists.
</P>
<P>
   The Corsican Assembly will meet this week to give its official
answer to the plan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-11-00 1713EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000711.0184 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-11 17:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9178 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-COX-DIGITAL-MUSIC-071     07-11 0755
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COX-DIGITAL-MUSIC-0712 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Few common chords struck in hearing over music downloads
 &HT;    By BOB DART
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A songwriting senator summoned rock stars and
dot.com entrepreneurs to testify Tuesday about whether there is an
``upside of downloading'' music on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Chairman Orrin Hatch, a Utah Republican and singer-composer of
gospel and pop songs, called a hearing of the Senate Judiciary
Committee ``to learn more about the online music marketplace and
why there is so much disharmony.''
</P>
<P>
   The committee got an earful of the continuing cacophony over
online copyright protection.
</P>
<P>
   Lars Ulrich, drummer and co-founder of the band Metallica, said
his introduction to the problem came when the firm Napster
``hijacked our music without asking'' and enabled its subscribers
to duplicate the songs for free over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, Hank Barry, the CEO of Napster, disagreed. He
said Napster's technology merely permits its 20 million members to
individually share their collections of digitalized music and that
such ``sampling'' actually promotes CD sales. On many campuses,
Napster is so popular that high-speed college computer systems are
sometimes clogged with students swapping music files called MP3's.
</P>
<P>
   Roger McGuinn, a songwriter and founder of folk-rock's Byrds
band, said he has gotten a better deal distributing his music over
his own Internet site and the online firm MP3.com than he ever did
when major labels controlled his hits like ``The Ballad of Easy
Rider.''
</P>
<P>
   But Fred Erlich, Sony Music's president of new technology, said
artists as well as record labels will suffer if the ``value chain''
is broken through free online distribution of their works and there
is no financial incentive to create and produce music.
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses did strike a few common chords: The Internet has
already changed the way recorded music reaches consumers. Even in a
digital economy, there is intellectual property and artists should
be compensated for its creation. The issues go far beyond Napster,
a pioneering company that has generated far more controversy than
revenues. And justice has to keep up with technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must protect the rights of the creator,'' said Hatch. ``But
we cannot, in the name of copyright, unduly burden consumers and
the promising technology that the Internet presents to us all.''
</P>
<P>
   Hatch said the hearing was aimed at providing information rather
than writing legislation. Action on the issue will come sooner in
the courts than in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Metallica and the major record labels have filed lawsuits
charging Napster with copyright infringements. The record companies
also sued MP3.com over its plan to immediately put a digitalized
version of a CD on a customer's computer ``locker'' when they
bought the actual CD. The problem, according to the music industry,
was that MP3.com created a library of 45,000 copyrighted CDs to be
digitally send into the ``lockers'' rather than copying the actual
purchased CD.
</P>
<P>
   But Gene Kan, developer of Gnutella, another online music
distribution system, said the music industry had better recognize
that ``the toothpaste is already out of the tube'' and adjust.
While Napster is built upon a directory of members who exchange
music with each other, Gnutella's ``community'' is connected only
by a common software that they downloaded for free. The software
lets them exchange MP3 music files without passing through any sort
of central switchboard.
</P>
<P>
   Napster and Gnutella ``are like potlucks,'' Kan explained.
``Everyone brings what he or she wants to share and perhaps
partakes in what others brought.''
</P>
<P>
   Just like movie makers had to adjust to an era of easily copied
videotapes, record companies and artists themselves are going to
have to find a way to make a profit distributing music online, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   But some other online music distribution systems are also upset
with Napster and Gnutella. Gene Hoffman, president of EMusic.com,
said his firm has licensing agreements with many artists and
independent record labels that allow him to sell downloaded CD
tracks for 99 cents apiece. But even at that price, he said, its
hard to compete with free tracks.
</P>
<P>
   For online information: www.riaa.com
</P>
<P>
   www.napster.com
</P>
<P>
   www.EMusic.com
</P>
<P>
   Bob Dart's e-mail address is bobdart(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-11-00 1714EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000711.0185 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-11 17:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9179 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-AOL-MEXICO12-COX     07-11 0662
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AOL-MEXICO12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AOL, STRUGGLING ABROAD, LAUNCHES SERVICE IN MEXICO
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By MARILYN GEEWAX
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ America Online Inc. began offering Internet access
service in Mexico ON Tuesday, hoping to boost its lagging
subscriber base in Latin America while expanding its ranks of
Spanish-speaking U.S. customers.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said AOL needs a ``win'' in Mexico to show investors it
can get people in poorer countries to pay monthly fees for online
services, even as other companies offer free Internet access.
</P>
<P>
   ``All eyes are on them,'' said Will Landers, director of Latin
American technology research for Credit Suisse First Boston.
Analysts question whether AOL can succeed south of the U.S. border
because the company is ``very much tied to the subscription model.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the Vienna, Va.-based online giant launched AOL
Brazil. But ``the rollout in Brazil was slower than what the market
expected,'' Landers said. Today, AOL is still running a distant
fourth among Internet providers in the Portuguese-speaking country,
in part because many Brazilians are getting free Internet access
from companies that rely solely on advertising for revenue.
</P>
<P>
   AOL Mexico plans to offer a 90-day free trial period, compared
with one free month in the United States. Mexican customers getting
unlimited access will be billed in pesos and will pay about $22 a
month, the same rate as U.S. customers.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the price, some analysts believe AOL's emphasis on
``home grown'' content and child-friendly monitoring services may
attract paying customers. ``They're aiming at Mexican families,''
said Gabriel Moreno, a high-tech industry analyst for the
International Data Corp. research firm in Mexico City.
</P>
<P>
   Because AOL offers subscribers seven user names under one
account, it opens up access to a whole family. ``Everyone can have
their own log-in and password, so parents can't read their
children's e-mail,'' Moreno said. ``But they can control what their
children look at.''
</P>
<P>
   AOL is the world's largest online service, with more than 23
million subscribers. But while the company has been phenomenally
successful in the United States, only a fraction of subscribers
lives abroad.
</P>
<P>
   After years of branching out into Europe, Asia and Latin
America, AOL is still seeing mixed results. In some European
countries, AOL dominates as an Internet access provider. But it has
done poorly in Japan, Australia and elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico is the poorest country where AOL has offered service.
Despite a population of roughly 100 million, only about 1.5 million
Mexicans have Internet accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Latin America is the fastest-growing Internet market in
the world. Analysts estimate that region's the number of users will
shoot from 8.5 million today to 29.4 million by 2003, according to
International Data Corp.
</P>
<P>
   The Spanish-language content of AOL Mexico will be available at
no increased cost to U.S.-based AOL subscribers, which means
Mexican-born residents in this country will have access to content
produced by 70 AOL staffers in Mexico City, spokeswoman Tricia
Primrose said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given the number of Spanish-speaking people in the United
States, this will be an exciting development here, too,'' Primrose
said.
</P>
<P>
   AOL Mexico will be operated as part of a joint venture with the
Cisneros Group, a Venezuelan media company that produces popular
soap operas and owns Univision, the largest Spanish-language
television network in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   AOL Mexico's competitors include Telefonos de Mexico (TelMex),
Spain's Terra Networks SA and Starmedia Network Inc.
</P>
<P>
   (Cox Mexico correspondent Susan Ferriss contributed to this
article.)
</P>
<P>
   On the Web: www.aol.com
</P>
<P>
   Marilyn Geewax's e-mail address is marilyng(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-11-00 1715EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000711.0186 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-11 17:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
