no increased cost to U.S.-based AOL subscribers, which means
Mexican-born residents in this country will have access to content
produced by 70 AOL staffers in Mexico City, spokeswoman Tricia
Primrose said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given the number of Spanish-speaking people in the United
States, this will be an exciting development here, too,'' Primrose
said.
</P>
<P>
   AOL Mexico will be operated as part of a joint venture with the
Cisneros Group, a Venezuelan media company that produces popular
soap operas and owns Univision, the largest Spanish-language
television network in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   AOL Mexico's competitors include Telefonos de Mexico (TelMex),
Spain's Terra Networks SA and Starmedia Network Inc.
</P>
<P>
   (Cox Mexico correspondent Susan Ferriss contributed to this
article.)
</P>
<P>
   On the Web: www.aol.com
</P>
<P>
   Marilyn Geewax's e-mail address is marilyng(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
