<HEADER>
A9181 &Cx1f; taf-z
u t BC-PARIS-BISTROS-2TAKES-     07-11 1455
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PARIS-BISTROS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE BISTROS OF YESTERYEAR? FLOURISHING 
</HEADLINE>
   By R.W. APPLE Jr.    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ The word ``bistro'' is used as promiscuously in Paris as
the word ``deli'' is used in New York.
</P>
<P>
   There are Greek bistros, Chinese bistros, Mexican bistros, cafes
that call themselves bistros and steak-frites joints that call
themselves bistros. Bistros are hot, and every quick-franc artist
in town wants to cash in.
</P>
<P>
   Bistros in the true sense _ the name comes from a Russian word
meaning quick _ were riding high when I first ate my merry way
around the French capital in the 1960s. Then, you could still find
most of the places that A.J. Liebling had haunted 25 years before.
But they soon went into decline, and when a revival came in the
1980s, it produced restaurants that were bistros in name only. The
decor was right _ lacquered wood storefronts, bare floors, even
zinc bars _ but not the food.
</P>
<P>
   Happily, Paris is a conservative city, slow-changing and
resistant to ``progress,'' and quite a few of the genuine articles
survive. Lovers of the sturdy, copious, grandmotherly cooking that
marks a true bistro pass favorite addresses from hand to hand, like
Russians in the communist era exchanging samizdat manuscripts. The
guidebooks may forget, but die-hard bistro owners and clients,
Frenchmen and foreigners alike, tend the flame.
</P>
<P>
   I count myself among the more avid members of that fraternity,
and my wife, Betsey, is no less keen. For us, Darroze and
Taillevent and Gagnaire are shrines to be visited occasionally, not
crammed into a single week's visit to Paris; bistros are for
relaxed, restorative, everyday chow.
</P>
<P>
   Much of it is based on humble ingredients, transformed into
culinary gold by the alchemy of slow simmering with wine and herbs.
This is the food of artisans, not artists, of guardians of
tradition, not trailblazers.
</P>
<P>
   Pot-au-feu, stuffed cabbage, navarin d'agneau, poulet au
vinaigre _ dishes like those have been and still are the mainstays
of bistro cooking. So are frogs' legs and snails, tripe and
kidneys, and old-school desserts like oeufs a la neige (floating
island) and tarte Tatin.
</P>
<P>
   No proper bistro has designer lighting, none have a maitre
d'hotel and none have Muzak. You go to eat and drink, not to
impress a client or pitch woo.
</P>
<P>
   On our last few visits to Paris, Betsey and I have revisited
most of the places on my bistro list. Here are up-to-date reports
on four of the top spots, with briefer notes on others where we
enjoyed ourselves.
</P>
<P>
   BENOIT (20 rue St.-Martin, Fourth Arrondissement,
011-33-1-42-72-25-76).
</P>
<P>
   Like a woman who wears too much makeup, Benoit has an air of
slightly suspicious glamour. Is the velvet too red, the brass too
shiny? No, it's la vraie chose, genuine down to the last potted
palm. Founded in 1912 by Benoit Martray, it has been faithfully
tended for four decades by Michel Petit, his grandson.
</P>
<P>
   That's Martray in the photo on the back wall, a beret perched
jauntily on his head and double chins deployed proudly beneath it.
His face is creased by a big smile. Jean, the handsome, cheeky
waiter, smiles, too.
</P>
<P>
   Petit is one of the last bistrotiers who buy Beaujolais in casks
and bottle it in their own cellars, in bottles identified only by a
tiny neck label. It is always a good choice.
</P>
<P>
   The food follows tradition, up to a point. In small, judicious
ways, Petit constantly strives for lighter, more contemporary
versions of the classics, with no discernible loss of flavor. There
is more parsley and less garlic in the snail butter; the hearty,
gelatinous veal knuckle is served with a barely thickened tomato
sauce; beef cheeks, with their more delicate texture, go into a
stew rather than heftier cuts.
</P>
<P>
   But you need not fear asparagus ice cream or foie gras with
rhubarb or some other abomination committed in the name of
innovation.
</P>
<P>
   The cassoulet is ideal winter fare. In hot summer weather, a
sumptuous dish of jellied fish _ a kind of cold bouillabaisse _
sometimes appears on the menu. Summer is the season as well for the
masterstroke among the restaurant's desserts, a luscious charlotte
of raspberries and wild strawberries. It is more than enough, all
by itself, to justify the star that the Michelin guide gives
Benoit. No other bistro is so honored.
</P>
<P>
   CHEZ GEORGES (1 rue de Mail, Second Arrondissement,
011-33-1-42-60-07-11).
</P>
<P>
   Bernard Brouillet's menu is still produced on an old Metro
liquid duplicator, in the red-purple script that used to be
synonymous with bistros, and the long, skinny room is still lined
with oversize mirrors.
</P>
<P>
   This is a busy, happy place, with a fine, rosy glow, where old
friends celebrate and new friends are made. Everyone talks to
everyone else, glad to be tucking into the seared onglet (hanger
steak), a tasty, chewy slab of meat showered with minced shallots,
or the excellent offal _ grilled veal kidneys with bearnaise sauce,
calf's liver topped with a thick rasher of bacon in the English
style, or veal sweetbreads in a mushroom cream sauce.
</P>
<P>
   The service is handled by charming women who have been around
since some of the bankers on whom they wait at lunch were tellers.
One of the many small pleasures of Georges is watching them fillet
the sole (a house specialty, served with a white wine sauce) with
the deftness of neurosurgeons.
</P>
<P>
   This is a neighborhood of temptations. Kenzo is two steps away,
Dehellerin's cookware store two more. The greatest of all, however,
is the bistro's wine list, packed with old Burgundies and Bordeaux
at prices half of those you would pay in a two- or three-star
gastronomic temple. Not cheap, mind you _ something 10 to 25 years
old from Dujac or Comte Armand will set you back $75 to $250 _ but
very reasonable for what you get.
</P>
<P>
   How do they do it? Some of the most famous growers, whose wines
are carefully rationed, have been supplying Chez Georges, and
eating there, for decades. The Marquis d'Angerville nipped in for
lunch just a few days before our most recent visit.
</P>
<P>
   LA GRILLE (80 rue du Fauburg-Poisonniere, 10th Arrondissement,
011-33-1-47-70-89-73).
</P>
<P>
   ``The egg is from the country, Monsieur,'' the jolly waiter
said, urging me to order the oeuf en gelee as a first course. It
was, and it was cooked to perfection, the yellow-gold yolk a little
more than soft-boiled. A small scallop of ham and a half-dozen
leaves of tarragon also helped to transform something that might
have been banal into a work of aspic art.
</P>
<P>
   That's the way it is at La Grille. Order a frisee salad and the
curly lettuce comes to the table with its crown of bacon strips
still steaming from the pan, as it should be and seldom is. Skinny
little lamb chops are delectable, says Betsey, the lamb expert.
Chocolate mousse, so dark and rich it looks almost black, is
exquisitely under-sweetened.
</P>
<P>
   But La Grille's centerpiece is the tawny turbot, with a lattice
of dark bars expertly seared into its flesh by la grille under the
baleful eye of the chef and owner, Yves Cullerre, he of the silver
handlebar mustache. It comes with a tart, ivory-hued beurre blanc.
In addition, you should order the little discus of sliced potatoes
baked with butter, plus the house Sancerre from Domaine Tabordet.
</P>
<P>
   There is something profoundly reassuring about the dozens of
coats of dark red lacquer on the walls, the circular staircase
leading up to the loos, the lace and embroidery at the windows and
on the banquettes. Here, you sense, the modern world is held at
bay.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are the last dinosaurs,'' the dumpling-shaped Mme. Cullerre
told us on our last visit, ``and we want to do things this way to
the end of our days.''
</P>
<P>
   L'AMI LOUIS (32 rue du Vertbois, Third Arrondissement,
011-33-1-48-87-77-48).
</P>
<P>
   In all the years I have been visiting this little bistro, on a
seedy side street in a banal neighborhood, it has never been listed
in the Michelin guide. The flaking dirt-brown paint on the walls,
the worn-out floor tiles and the tired tin ceiling evidently fall
short of the red book's decor requirements.
</P>
<P>
   French critics love to trash the place, not least because it has
so many American clients and because it charges such high prices;
the two things are probably not unrelated.
</P>
<P>
   When I started going there, more than 25 years ago, L'Ami Louis
had very few American clients, and no one spoke any English.
Antoine Magnin, then considered the city's master rotisseur, or
roaster, was still at his post, red kerchief tied round his neck,
and Louis Gadby, now the patron, was a young waiter. The wine list
was much slimmer (so was I) and cheaper. Nobody dreamed of calling
weeks in advance for a table, as they do now.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
