<HEADER>
A9182 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-BUSH-COX     07-11 1127
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush staff continues to play it close to the vest
 &HT;    By Ken Herman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _Here's what it's come to, above, on the fruited
plane.
</P>
<P>
   Frustrated by the George W. Bush campaign's ability to keep
secrets, the travelling press recently turned to citrus in an
effort to squeeze some information out of the candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ridge too liberal? Yes or no,'' a reporter, seeking a hint on
Pennsylvania Gov. Tom Ridge's chances at being the running mate,
wrote on an orange that was then rolled to Bush in first class.
</P>
<P>
   ``No comment,'' came the non-reply scribbled by Bush on the
orange.
</P>
<P>
   The reporters, ready with follow-up fruit, persisted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is it Keating? Yes or no,'' they asked on a second orange,
seeking information on Oklahoma Gov. Frank Keating.
</P>
<P>
   ``Same,'' wrote Bush.
</P>
<P>
   For months, as Bush filled the time between clinching the
nomination in March and formally getting it next month in
Philadelphia, the campaign has been extraordinarily successful at
controlling the flow and leakage of information. Today, some of
that information may be shared at closed-door meetings with 150 top
Republicans from around the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Bush backers began gathering Tuesday at the Hyatt Regency for
sessions, organized by the Republican National Committee, that will
be highlighted by a public speech today by Bush and a private
briefing from Karl Rove, the campaign's quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   ``This conference will help us take the next important step in
the Republican campaign of ideas,'' said Fred Meyer, former Texas
GOP chairman who is Bush's hand-picked chairman of the national
party's Victory 2000 effort to elect Republicans across the
country.
</P>
<P>
   The behind-closed-door buzz is expected to include the ongoing
search for a running mate and talk about who might get what job in
a Bush administration.
</P>
<P>
   On the record, Bush aides and confidantes _ fearing the
overconfident and arrogant label _ steer clear of talking about
anything beyond campaigning.
</P>
<P>
   ``The official word is the campaign is focused on our convention
and on Election Day. Our thoughts and planning and focus are all
leading up to Nov. 7,'' campaign spokesman Ray Sullivan said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   That means the campaign maintains the charade that nothing
involving transition is going on, preferring to have voters believe
the leadership team for the western world would be put together
between Nov. 7 and Jan. 20.
</P>
<P>
   The charade is pierced by word from a Bush confidante that
transition talks, not surprisingly, have gone on, if not at a
formal level.
</P>
<P>
   The point man on transition for now is Clay Johnson, who serves
as top man in the governor's office. Johnson was a prep school
classmate of Bush. They were roommates at Yale.
</P>
<P>
   He joined the current administration when Bush became governor
in 1995. Prior to that, he served as chief operation officer of the
Dallas Museum of Art and president of Horchow Mail Order, a gift
business that became a division of Neiman Marcus in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   Though some have targeted Johnson as the probable head of
transition if Bush wins, he downplays his current role, identifying
it only as ``repository'' of all information relating to a possible
transition.
</P>
<P>
   Early speculation on who could wind up as Bush's White House
chief of staff centers on Don Evans, the Bush buddy and former
business partner who ran the campaign fund-raising operation that
broke all records and helped buy the nomination for Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Evans is chief executive officer of Tom Brown Inc., an energy
company. Bush formally served on the company's board. Evans is a
Bush appointee as chairman of the University of Texas System
regents.
</P>
<P>
   While the selection of White House staff is all speculative, and
may never be needed, the choice of a running mate is imminent. The
Bush staff continues to play it close to the vest. Around the
country, potential running mates are filling out questionnaires
prepared by former Defense Secretary Dick Cheney, Bush's one-man
search committee.
</P>
<P>
   In Oklahoma City, Keating spokesman Dan Mahoney knows the rules
of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has done his part,'' said Mahoney, confirming that his boss
has submitted what amounts to an application. ``It needs to remain
a confidential process and that's what we are going to do.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Rep. John Kasich of Ohio is singing a similar tune.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I can say is that Dick Cheney asked me to get them some
information,'' he said this week. ``I have been contacted. That is
all I will say, period.''
</P>
<P>
   As the contenders open their lives and records to Bush, the
campaign also is fielding input, invited and otherwise, from around
the country. A California-based group, eager to see a female
president, wants Bush to pick Elizabeth Dole, a choice that looks
like a long-shot. A Houston-based group has a Friday appointment to
submit petitions with 10,000 signatures from people who want Kasich
on the ticket.
</P>
<P>
   The purveyors of uninvited input say the Bush campaign has been,
ahem, a bit difficult to deal with.
</P>
<P>
   ``Courteous would be an overstatement,'' said one person trying
to have input from the outside. ``I don't see much interest. My
phone calls have not been returned.''
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, a group headed by conservative activist Richard
Viguerie is touting the results of its survey of conservative
leaders they won't identify. Posted on the group's website _
bushrunningmate.com _ are survey results worded in an odd, negative
tone.
</P>
<P>
   The organization opted to highlight who the 183 survey
respondents don't want on the ticket, rather than who they do. Not
surprisingly, the more moderate, the more objectionable.
</P>
<P>
   Dole, Ridge, Govs. Christie Whitman of New Jersey and George
Pataki of New York, and Arizona Sen. John McCain ``topped the list
of possible running mates who might cause problems for Bush,'' the
group said.
</P>
<P>
   Respondents' favorite vice presidential candidates included U.S.
Reps. J.C. Watts of Oklahoma, Chris Cox of California and Kasich of
Ohio, as well as Colin Powell and Alan Keyes.
</P>
<P>
   The insider input on vice presidential selection has flowed from
people like Connecticut GOP Chairman Chris DePino, who is among
those whose opinions were sought by Bush.
</P>
<P>
   DePino has told Bush to pick Ridge, an abortion rights advocate
whose selection could upset religious conservatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the party is ready to accept the fact that we can
disagree on issues concerning abortion but we can agree on winning
elections,'' said DePino. ``If we can stay focused on that I don't
think there is a better candidate than Ridge.''
</P>
<P>
   You may contact Ken Herman at kherman(at)statesman.com or
445-1718.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-11-00 1718EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000711.0189 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-11 17:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9183 &Cx1f; taf-z
u t BC-PARIS-BISTROS-2NDTAKE     07-11 1177
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PARIS-BISTROS-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 PARIS: do now.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It all makes me feel like Methuselah. But every qualm vanishes
with the first magnificent mouthful of the juicy roast chicken, the
tender leg of baby lamb or the enormous rib of beef. They are
unmatched anywhere. The notably garlicky snails, scallops and
potato cake can, I admit, wreak havoc on the digestion, but for me
at least, they're worth the heartburn.
</P>
<P>
   One reason for the high prices, of course, is prime ingredients.
All over Paris this spring, restaurateurs told me that French
morels were almost unobtainable. They had been forced, several
confessed, to substitute inferior Turkish mushrooms. Not Gadby: He
showed us a big basket full of the fattest morels imaginable, which
came from Compiegne, just outside Paris. Cooked with plenty of
cream, they tasted even better than they looked. Well, they might
have; they had cost 800 francs a kilo, or $50 a pound.
</P>
<P>
   Two tips: Order one portion for two, and go not for dinner but
for lunch, especially on Sunday, when the clientele are often all
French.
</P>
<P>
   ALLARD (41 rue St.-Andre-des-Arts, Sixth Arrondissement,
011-33-1-43-26-48-23).
</P>
<P>
   Some of the soul went out of this most famous of bistros, once
the holder of two Michelin stars, when Andre Allard died and his
wife, Fernande, retired. But after years in gastronomic purgatory,
it is once again full at lunch and dinner (now served until 11:30)
almost every day. The resurrection is the work of Claude Leyrac, an
experienced bistrotier, who has had the sense to keep many old
favorites on the list: The world's best cucumber salad, crunchy and
creamy; the famous duckling with olives; the lip-smacking beef and
veal and lamb stews, and a baked custard my mother would have
envied.
</P>
<P>
   CARTET (62 rue de Malte, 11th Arrondissement,
011-33-1-48-05-17-65).
</P>
<P>
   When Marie-Antoinette Cartet ran this eight-table bistro near
the Place de la Republique, it was open only for lunch; in the
evenings, she told me, she liked to go to the theater. When
Marie-Therese and Raymond Nouaille took over 20 years ago, they
started serving dinner and installed a new kitchen. But the menu is
immutable. No one in Paris serves silkier brandade de morue, a
blend of salt cod, potatoes, garlic, cream and olive oil. And what
could be homier than Cartet's boeuf a la ficelle, a fillet
suspended in a pot of boiling stock and simmered gently, or its
lemon tart, as warmly golden as the summer sun?
</P>
<P>
   CHEZ JOSEPHINE (117 rue du Cherche-Midi, Sixth Arrondissement,
011-33-1-45-48-52-40).
</P>
<P>
   Extravagant flower displays provide islands of color in
Jean-Christian Dumonet's two sober dining rooms, and luxury abounds
on his carte. He makes a specialty of truffles, in nonpareil
omelets and ragouts, and he combines perfectly cooked langoustines
with a tangle of herbs and lettuces in a rich man's salad. But most
dishes can be ordered in half portions, which helps hold down costs
and calories. At lunch on Wednesdays, the classic leg of lamb with
white beans should not be missed; other days I favor the dark, winy
boeuf bourguignon. And mon Dieu, the wines! Two large, closely
printed pages list red Bordeaux stretching back to 1928 at
eminently fair prices.
</P>
<P>
   CHEZ SAVY (23 rue Bayard, Eighth Arrondissement,
011-33-1-47-23-46-98).
</P>
<P>
   Founded in 1923, Savy, an island of culinary modesty amid oceans
of gastronomic pretension in one of the city's richest
neighborhoods, has roots in the Auvergne, the deeply rural center
of France. The varied local clientele, including personalities from
nearby television stations, order the petit farcou, a fat,
chlorophyll-laden pancake of spinach, chard, leeks and herbs, and
the slow-cooked shoulder of lamb, falling off the bone. A jug of
Cahors and prime regional cheeses like Cantal and Roquefort will
make you purr. Eat in the narrow front room, called le wagon
(dining car) by habitues.
</P>
<P>
   LA TOUR DE MONTLHERY (5 rue des Prouvaires, First
Arrondissement, 011-33-1-42-36-21-82).
</P>
<P>
   This is a set designer's vision of a bistro, with sausages
dangling from the ceiling, red-checked cloths on the tables and
customers with Gauloises dangling from their lips. Beaujolais is
drawn straight from a barrel at the bar. I don't know which are
more Rabelaisian _ the cheerful rabble you'll find at the next
table, or the vast portions of mutton with white beans, pigs' feet
and profiteroles. A survivor of the old Halles market district, La
Tour is open 24 hours every weekday. Pot-au-feu every Thursday;
service with just the right touch of impertinence every day.
</P>
<P>
   CHEZ LA VIEILLE (1 rue Bailleul, First Arrondissement,
011-33-1-42-60-15-78).
</P>
<P>
   Adrienne Biasin, the old woman for whom this hole-in-the-wall
was named, has retired, but her bistro is bubblier, better and more
generous than ever, thanks to the new owner, the chic Marie-Josee
Cervoni. A Corsican, she has added tastes of her homeland to the
menu, including a raw ham reminiscent of Smithfield. You order a
main course (perhaps the beef stew with carrots) and help yourself
to the half-dozen starters and half-dozen desserts served family
style. Among the former, a boar terrine, well-seasoned stuffed
cabbage and a refreshing mussel and tomato salad stand out; among
the latter, prunes in red wine. Drink the peppery St.-Joseph from
the Rhone.
</P>
<P>
   Which is to say nothing of Chardenoux, and Aux Charpentiers, and
Chez Rene, and Moissonier ...
</P>
<P>
   RASPBERRY CHARLOTTE
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from Benoit, Paris
</P>
<P>
   Time: 1\ hours, plus draining and chilling times
</P>
<P>
   1} cups fromage blanc (see note)
</P>
<P>
   8 cups raspberries
</P>
<P>
   { cup plus 1 tablespoon superfine sugar
</P>
<P>
   1} teaspoons gelatin
</P>
<P>
   1 3 ounce package soft lady fingers (about 24).
</P>
<P>
   1. Place a fine sieve lined with cheesecloth over a bowl and
drain fromage blanc at room temperature for 3 hours, or in
refrigerator for 8.
</P>
<P>
   2. In a blender, food processor or food mill, combine 4 cups of
the raspberries with 1 tablespoon sugar and 1 tablespoon water. Let
sit for about 10 minutes. Puree until smooth.
</P>
<P>
   3. Transfer puree to a sieve placed over a bowl. Push puree
through sieve until it yields 1 cup. Discard solids.
</P>
<P>
   4. In a dish, combine gelatin with 2 tablespoons water and let
sit for 10 minutes. In a saucepan, heat \ cup raspberry puree until
nearly boiling. Add gelatin mixture; stir to dissolve. Remove from
heat and cool.
</P>
<P>
   5. In a mixing bowl, whisk together drained fromage blanc with
remaining raspberry puree and remaining sugar. Whisk in cooled
gelatin-raspberry mixture.
</P>
<P>
   6. Gently fold 2 cups whole raspberries into fromage blanc
mixture. Transfer mixture to a 1-quart mold, cover with plastic,
and refrigerate overnight or up to 2 days.
</P>
<P>
   7. To assemble charlotte, invert chilled mold over a plate (dip
mold in hot water to help it release). Arrange lady fingers along
sides of the charlotte. Decorate top with remaining 2 cups whole
berries.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 6 to 8 servings.
</P>
<P>
   Note: fromage blanc is available in specialty markets.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-11-00 1719EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
