<DOCNO> NYT20000711.0190 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-11 17:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9184 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-ENTREPRENEUR-COX     07-11 0752
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ENTREPRENEUR-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Real entrepreneurs roll with the times
 &HT;    By Caroline Hubbard
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA - Lindsey Cook calmly sipped a beer a week after firing
half of his employees.
</P>
<P>
   The chief executive of nschool.com, Cook had spent his day
trying to convince someone to buy the remains of his company.
</P>
<P>
   Things were bad.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, when asked if he would start another Internet company, the
40-year-old didn't hesitate. ``Yes.''
</P>
<P>
   Weeks later, he had a tentative agreement with another company.
Things were looking up. He stood at a crowded trade show, calmly
chatting with his acquaintances and remaining employees. Will he
start another company? ``Yes.'' Again, no hesitation.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is fun,'' he said. ``It is not about starting something.
It is about building something.''
</P>
<P>
   It takes a true entrepreneur to ride the roller coaster, to take
the failures and successes with a certain calm. But at a time when
things are newly tough, when starting an Internet company no longer
feels like a sure thing, the weak entrepreneurs are being weeded
out. Experts say we will see fewer people take the leap from cushy
jobs to start-ups. We will see plenty return to BellSouth and
Arthur Andersen and McKinsey. Those same experts agree the shift
may be a good thing; several months ago, too many people were
jumping on the bandwagon.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are getting back to the real entrepreneur. There for a
while, we had doctors, lawyers and Indian chiefs bailing out of
conventional jobs,'' said George Levert, a partner at Kinetic
Ventures and a 20-year veteran of the Atlanta venture capital
scene.
</P>
<P>
   ``The truly dedicated people you can't slap down. The people who
are going away don't have that drive, that fierce tenacity and
belief in what they are doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Cook thinks it is about discipline as much as dedication. A
trial attorney for many years, Cook grimaces at the thought of
returning to the courtroom but says he learned there how to manage
stress.
</P>
<P>
   ``You discipline yourself,'' he said. ``You decide, these are
the parameters of how freaked out I will get. You say, 'I am not
going to go any lower than this.' And you don't.''
</P>
<P>
   For Rod Robinson, it is flexibility. Last summer, Robinson
started GlobalMecca.com, an Internet company aimed at black
professionals. He tried for many months to get capital to market
his site but never found investors. Eventually, he changed his
business plan and began a trial partnership with a large financial
services company. He said the partnership could lead to the
financial services company buying GlobalMecca, though he is keeping
quiet on the details for now.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of it is staying power,'' said Robinson, thinking back
over the last year. ``You could easily fold up the tent and go
home.''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson also said he has learned to act positively even when he
feels down.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have brought people on board who are not entrepreneurs,''
he said. ``They go through some rough times when times are tough.
You have to constantly to be a cheerleader.''
</P>
<P>
   Not only are fewer people starting companies, fewer people are
willing to work for still-young companies.
</P>
<P>
   Nick Steele, chief executive at Atlanta start-up enfoTrust, said
he has seen the job market shift. ``People are less willing to
leave their companies ... They are taking a wait-and-see
attitude.''
</P>
<P>
   Lee Esler, a consultant on the technology team at recruiting
firm Egon Zehnder International, said executives are doing more
research on start-ups. Six months ago, people wanted to know how
much equity they got and how long until the company planned to go
public, according to Esler.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now they are asking, 'Does this company have a compelling
value proposition?''' Esler said.
</P>
<P>
   At FigLeaves, an e-commerce company that has been hit hard by
the Internet shakeout, some executives want another shot at the
start-up dream.
</P>
<P>
   And some don't. Chief Executive Ari Straus said he will
definitely work at another early stage company. But some members of
his management team are not so sure. One recently took a job at
UPS.
</P>
<P>
   Straus _ who previously worked at conservative companies such as
Kurt Salmon Associates and Deloitte Consulting _ said plenty of
people are tiring of the risky start-up life.
</P>
<P>
   ``People went panning for gold,'' he said. ``They didn't find it
and now are hopping back on their wagons and heading east as fast
as they can.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
