<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-11 17:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9200 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-HANDSHAKE-SOUL-NYTSF &LR;      07-11 0768
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HANDSHAKE-SOUL-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOUR HANDSHAKE MAY BE A WINDOW TO YOUR SOUL  
 &HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (The following ``separate buy'' article from HealthScout, a
leading online source of health and lifestyle news, is available
from the New York Times Syndicate. Please contact syndicate sales
representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 BY LIZ LYNCH  
 c.2000 HealthScout.com  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by The New York Times Syndicate) &LR;  &QL;
<P>
   Does a firm handshake really earn you a better first impression?
</P>
<P>
   Absolutely, says a University of Alabama research team. And
that's not all. Your handshake may be a window to your soul.
</P>
<P>
   Pretty heavy stuff for a couple of seconds of skin-to-skin
contact, but that's what happens when researchers get curious about
handshake etiquette.
</P>
<P>
   Led by William Chaplin, associate professor at the University of
Alabama's Tuscaloosa campus, the researchers evaluated the
handshakes of 112 study participants. Qualities measured included
strength and duration, dryness, temperature, vigor and presence of
eye contact. In addition, the participants completed four
personality questionnaires.
</P>
<P>
   Handshakes, the study found, stay consistent upon repetitions _
that is, firm handshakers stayed firm and ``limp fishes'' stayed
limp.
</P>
<P>
   And interestingly, there was some correlation between handshake
qualities and personality. Firm handshakers tended to be extroverts
and more open to new experiences than those with limp handshakes,
the researchers found. And the firm handshakers garnered more
positive impressions than the limp fishes.
</P>
<P>
   No surprises there for Sue Fox, a Los Gatos, Calif.-based
business etiquette consultant and author of the forthcoming book,
Business Etiquette for Dummies (IDG Books). ``If you think about
it, it's your first physical contact with someone, so why not make
that first physical contact a positive one?'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   To Fox, a limp handshake telegraphs that ``you're sort of
apologetic and hesitant and kind of lifeless. You want to show that
you're kind of enthusiastic and happy to meet this person.''
</P>
<P>
   Chaplin says a chance question from some undergraduates was what
started all the handshaking. The students wanted to know whether
there was any scientific basis to what etiquette consultants and
management trainers have always contended _ that a firm handshake
is key to making a positive first impression.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as I knew, no one had ever really studied it, but
certainly there was a great deal of opinion on it,'' Chaplin says.
Finding only limited mentions of handshaking and personality in
their search of the literature, Chaplin and his students decided to
create their own project.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, there's more to studying handshakes than sticking out
your hand and smiling. Chaplin and the student testers had to
thrash out such ideas as ``a neutral way to initiate a handshake''
_ palm facing to the left, thumb raised at a 45-degree angle _ so
that the study participants would set the tone of the handshake
rather than the researchers. The team also had to agree upon what
exactly constituted clamminess, limpness, firmness and so forth.
</P>
<P>
   Tricky as it can be, it was important that human beings measured
and rated the handshakes, Chaplin says. ``We could measure
handshakes with machines, but I don't think that would be about
handshaking as a whole. It would be about how strong your grip
was.''
</P>
<P>
   What surprises Chaplin most about the results? ``I was struck by
the finding that women who had a firmer handshake were being
evaluated by the testers as positively as the men,'' he says.
``That was a little bit at odds with the typical finding in the
literature [on gender differences] where women who assume a
positive, strong attitude are more negatively viewed.''
</P>
<P>
   Nice as that is to know, what do you do if you're naturally a
boneless sort? Is it possible to firm things up?
</P>
<P>
   Chaplin says he isn't quite sure. ``A handshake is very
automatic,'' he says. To change it, ``you need to become conscious
of it, think about it, and that would make it become a little bit
unnatural and communicate other things.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox is more optimistic _ and pragmatic. If you need a firm
handshake for crucial situations, there's no reason you can't
summon one up, she says. ``Maybe you can't change it overnight, but
it's just a level of awareness,'' she says. ``Fake it if you have
to. After a while, it becomes a habit if you keep doing it.''
</P>
<P>
   ----
</P>
<P>
   (The HealthScout.com Web site is at http://www.HealthScout.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
