<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-11 17:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9202 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r t BC-TRAVEL-PETS-HNS &LR;      07-11 0850
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-PETS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     THINK TWICE BEFORE FLYING WITH YOUR PET THIS SUMMER 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JULIE COOPER  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ If you thought traveling with kids was tough, try
checking Fido as luggage this summer. You can't. And if you show up
at the airport without making prior arrangements for the family
pet, you'll be in for a rude awakening.
</P>
<P>
   Most major airlines have changed their policies on flying the
pets as checked luggage after a number of incidents involving
animal deaths or near deaths on domestic airliners.
</P>
<P>
   Each airline has its own rules. Southwest Airlines accepts no
pets, only guide dogs, while TWA has a $75 fee for small pets in
the cabin and cargo area (not checked luggage). American,
Continental, Delta and United announced they would no longer accept
pets as baggage during the hot, busy summer months.
</P>
<P>
   Bottom line: If you must travel with Fluffy, allow extra
check-in time, get an approved carrier or crate, and have the
animal checked by a veterinarian. Most important _ book early.
Remember that pets in the cabin must be small enough to fit under
the seat in front of you, and all the airlines limit the number per
plane (usually two in coach and one in first class).
</P>
<P>
   ``Traveling with your pet presents many unique challenges, but
because most pet lovers consider their pets as family, they
wouldn't dream of leaving them home alone,'' said Dr. Marty Becker,
Petopia.com's chief veterinary correspondent and co-author of
``Chicken Soup for the Cat and Dog Lover's Soul.''
</P>
<P>
   ``With careful planning, traveling with your pet can be a
wonderful bonding experience,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Army Staff Sgt. Keith Thompson, who is stationed in San Antonio,
has flown several times with Bailey, a Shetland sheepdog.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never had any problems traveling with Bailey, except that
most (domestic) airlines make me feel like I'm traveling with a
convicted felon that must be caged instead of a member of my
family.''
</P>
<P>
   Bailey said he got exceptional treatment when he was transferred
to Japan and flew on ANA, All Nippon Airways.
</P>
<P>
   ``My wife and Bailey got the royal treatment when they arrived
in Tokyo,'' Thompson said. ``Someone from the airline personally
escorted my wife through customs and ensured that all of Bailey's
paperwork was in order and that they made it to their connecting
flight.''
</P>
<P>
   Minneapolis-based Northwest Airlines gets high marks for its
Priority Pet program and continues to accept pets as checked
baggage during the summer months, although restrictions apply.
Animals are not accepted when temperatures exceed 85 degrees at any
point on the itinerary. Northwest charges $75 each way for pet
transport _ both inside the cabin and checked _ for domestic
flights, and the international rate varies.
</P>
<P>
   Valinda Satterlee, whose husband serves with the Air Force in
Japan, said Northwest ``was wonderful and seemed to really care
about our four-legged family members.''
</P>
<P>
   Satterlee traveled to Japan with two children and three Lhasa
Apsos last September. They plan to return to San Antonio in 2002
when Dan Satterlee retires from the Air Force.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had two dogs in cargo because at 18 pounds they were 3
pounds over the allowed weight for carry-on pets with Northwest.
All three dogs did very well in both compartments,'' Satterlee
says.
</P>
<P>
   Airline Internet sites are the best places to get information
about traveling with pets, although other pet-related sites such as
the Human Society at www.hsus.org, Petopia.com, Pets.com and
Kindplanet.org are helpful sites on pet travel.
</P>
<P>
   Most airlines are accepting large dogs from professional pet
shippers. For more information about shipping pets, contact the
Independent Pet and Animal Transportation Association, 903-769-2267
or on the Internet at www.ipata.com.
</P>
<P>
   Air Animal, www.airanimal.com, works with pet owners and
airlines to assure ``pets are getting the best care possible'' for
transportation domestically and internationally.
</P>
<P>
   Air Animal's founder, Dr. Walter Wolf, is a veterinarian with 40
years' experience. He said people who expected to pay $50 to
transport a pet are finding that it cost upwards of $550 now. Last
year Air Animal moved more than 3,000 cats and dogs around the
world.
</P>
<P>
   ``Going to the airport and checking a dog, I believe that has
come to an end,'' Wolf said.
</P>
<P>
   He does have praise for some airlines, such as Continental.
Continental Quickpak live animal rates for pets as cargo range from
$139 for pets up to 18 pounds to $299 for pets of 120 pounds. For
more information, call the live animal desk at 800-575-3335.
</P>
<P>
   ``Continental has dedicated itself to providing the services in
an extremely controlled circumstances,'' Wolf said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he has any tips for those flying with pets, Wolf said
``people are going to have to look at alternative plans, dig deep
in their pockets or wait until September.''
</P>
<P>
   With that in mind, many boarding kennels are at or near capacity
this summer. If you decide to board your pet, book soon.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-11-00 1740EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000711.0196 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-11 17:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9208 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-ISRAEL-GRASSROOTS-071     07-11 0697
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-GRASSROOTS-0712-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WHILE SUMMIT SIMMERS, PEACE ACTIVISTS URGED TO AWAKEN
 &HT;    (450&AMP;ADD)
 &HT;    With MIDEAST-SUMMIT-0712.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Prompted by their prime minister's weakness and the
peace talks in Maryland, leaders of Israel's peace movement tried
Tuesday to awaken their followers to action.
</P>
<P>
   They fight a reputation for being dormant while their right-wing
opponents canvas the streets with banners, hold hunger strikes,
pray at the sacred Western Wall and take out newspaper ads.
</P>
<P>
   They labor under a feeling that their sluggishness in 1995 may
have helped foster the atmosphere for the assassination of
then-Prime Minister Yitzhak Rabin.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the same as today, when you had the feeling that they
were the only ones in the street,'' Galia Golan-Gild, an activist
for 22 years with Peace Now, said of her right-wing rivals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if we could have affected what happened,'' Golan
said. ``But there's a feeling that we should be doing more to
protect our leader.''
</P>
<P>
   Their leader is in trouble again.
</P>
<P>
   After just a year in office, Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak's
government is faltering under assault from opponents to peace
negotiations with the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   The so-called Peace Coalition, a collection of Peace Now and
smaller pro-peace groups, held a rally Tuesday evening on the
street near Barak's official residence.
</P>
<P>
   About 1,500 people attended to hear speeches and folk songs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems like Barak is doing the right thing, but he doesn't
get enough support, especially from people out in the streets,''
student Ori Mosenzon, 30, said at the rally. ``Many people who
support him are quiet.''
</P>
<P>
   Polls show the country about evenly split on the talks. Barak
has promised to put any peace deal before the people in a public
referendum.
</P>
<P>
   The peace activists' icon, Rabin, was assassinated by a lone
gunman after a huge peace rally Nov. 4, 1995.
</P>
<P>
   The attack and the rally came after right-wing activists had
assailed Rabin repeatedly as a traitor. Many pro-peace Israelis
feel not enough was done to answer the accusations.
</P>
<P>
   Similar accusations are now turned on Barak.
</P>
<P>
   During Tuesday's demonstration, police lined up around eight
counter-protestors from the radical anti-Arab Kach movement. They
chanted, ``He's a traitor,'' and held anti-Barak signs, including
one stating, ``Barak, the nation will deal with you.''
</P>
<P>
   Kach activist Noam Federman said that if Barak uproots Jewish
settlements in the West Bank, ``He should be prepared for people to
do violent things.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how I will react,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Kach is on the extreme end of the right-wing movement in Israel.
</P>
<P>
   An Israeli television news report Tuesday said a new Internet
Website allows people to simulate shooting at Barak.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Begin optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   The major opponent of the summit remains the settler movement,
which is effective at conventional grassroots tactics.
</P>
<P>
   There are more than 200,000 settlers in the West Bank, land
which Israel captured in the 1967 Arab-Israeli War, and is now up
for negotiation in the Camp David talks.
</P>
<P>
   Yehudit Tayar, spokeswoman for the settlers council, said the
group could spend millions of dollars, if necessary, on a campaign
against concessions in the talks.
</P>
<P>
   Barak has said he may require about 40,000 settlers to move from
their land or be under Palestinian control. Tayar said polling
showed her group hit a ``raw nerve'' with its new slogan:
``Brothers are not abandoned.''
</P>
<P>
   It harkens, she said, to the Israeli army philosophy that
comrades cannot be left behind in battle.
</P>
<P>
   The new peace movement slogan is: ``The majority chooses peace.
I do too.'' Peace Now spokesman Didi Remez said his group has only
spent about $50,000 on the effort and cannot approach the settler's
treasury.
</P>
<P>
   (Larry Kaplow's E-mail address is: larryk(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   For general news about Israel:
</P>
<P>
   www.virtualjerusalem.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
