<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-11 17:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9209 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-ISRAEL-GRASSROOTS-071     07-11 0697
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-GRASSROOTS-0712-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WHILE SUMMIT SIMMERS, PEACE ACTIVISTS URGED TO AWAKEN
 &HT;    (450&AMP;ADD)
 &HT;    With MIDEAST-SUMMIT-0712.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Prompted by their prime minister's weakness and the
peace talks in Maryland, leaders of Israel's peace movement tried
Tuesday to awaken their followers to action.
</P>
<P>
   They fight a reputation for being dormant while their right-wing
opponents canvas the streets with banners, hold hunger strikes,
pray at the sacred Western Wall and take out newspaper ads.
</P>
<P>
   They labor under a feeling that their sluggishness in 1995 may
have helped foster the atmosphere for the assassination of
then-Prime Minister Yitzhak Rabin.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the same as today, when you had the feeling that they
were the only ones in the street,'' Galia Golan-Gild, an activist
for 22 years with Peace Now, said of her right-wing rivals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if we could have affected what happened,'' Golan
said. ``But there's a feeling that we should be doing more to
protect our leader.''
</P>
<P>
   Their leader is in trouble again.
</P>
<P>
   After just a year in office, Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak's
government is faltering under assault from opponents to peace
negotiations with the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   The so-called Peace Coalition, a collection of Peace Now and
smaller pro-peace groups, held a rally Tuesday evening on the
street near Barak's official residence.
</P>
<P>
   About 1,500 people attended to hear speeches and folk songs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems like Barak is doing the right thing, but he doesn't
get enough support, especially from people out in the streets,''
student Ori Mosenzon, 30, said at the rally. ``Many people who
support him are quiet.''
</P>
<P>
   Polls show the country about evenly split on the talks. Barak
has promised to put any peace deal before the people in a public
referendum.
</P>
<P>
   The peace activists' icon, Rabin, was assassinated by a lone
gunman after a huge peace rally Nov. 4, 1995.
</P>
<P>
   The attack and the rally came after right-wing activists had
assailed Rabin repeatedly as a traitor. Many pro-peace Israelis
feel not enough was done to answer the accusations.
</P>
<P>
   Similar accusations are now turned on Barak.
</P>
<P>
   During Tuesday's demonstration, police lined up around eight
counter-protestors from the radical anti-Arab Kach movement. They
chanted, ``He's a traitor,'' and held anti-Barak signs, including
one stating, ``Barak, the nation will deal with you.''
</P>
<P>
   Kach activist Noam Federman said that if Barak uproots Jewish
settlements in the West Bank, ``He should be prepared for people to
do violent things.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how I will react,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Kach is on the extreme end of the right-wing movement in Israel.
</P>
<P>
   An Israeli television news report Tuesday said a new Internet
Website allows people to simulate shooting at Barak.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Begin optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   The major opponent of the summit remains the settler movement,
which is effective at conventional grassroots tactics.
</P>
<P>
   There are more than 200,000 settlers in the West Bank, land
which Israel captured in the 1967 Arab-Israeli War, and is now up
for negotiation in the Camp David talks.
</P>
<P>
   Yehudit Tayar, spokeswoman for the settlers council, said the
group could spend millions of dollars, if necessary, on a campaign
against concessions in the talks.
</P>
<P>
   Barak has said he may require about 40,000 settlers to move from
their land or be under Palestinian control. Tayar said polling
showed her group hit a ``raw nerve'' with its new slogan:
``Brothers are not abandoned.''
</P>
<P>
   It harkens, she said, to the Israeli army philosophy that
comrades cannot be left behind in battle.
</P>
<P>
   The new peace movement slogan is: ``The majority chooses peace.
I do too.'' Peace Now spokesman Didi Remez said his group has only
spent about $50,000 on the effort and cannot approach the settler's
treasury.
</P>
<P>
   (Larry Kaplow's E-mail address is: larryk(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   For general news about Israel:
</P>
<P>
   www.virtualjerusalem.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
