<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-11 17:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9212 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-SUMMIT-TOWN-0712-COX     07-11 0555
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUMMIT-TOWN-0712-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AS CAMP DAVID II BEGINS, MARYLAND TOWN ONCE AGAIN HOPES FOR
PEACE
 &HT;    With MIDEAST-SUMMIT-0712.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   THURMONT, Md. _ Midday traffic slips easily down Main Street
outside Tommy's Tavern, where Bob Fleagle leans against the
horseshoe-shaped bar and sips a cold Pabst Blue-Ribbon straight
from the can.
</P>
<P>
   A few minutes' drive away, up the winding road into the forested
mountains where Fleagle and his pals have been catching small-mouth
bass and hunting wild mushrooms since they were boys, President
Clinton is huddling with Israeli and Palestinian leaders in hopes
of bringing peace to the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just hope it's workable,'' proffers Fleagle, 50, taking a
break from his carpentry work at the tiny zoo down the road. ``Any
time countries are fighting like that, there's no good can come out
of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Nestled into the verdant bosom of the Catoctin Mountains, in the
shadow of the Camp David presidential retreat, tiny Thurmont
(population: 4,400), has become the focal point for global efforts
to end a half-century of conflict between Israelis and
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   Folks like Fleagle can remember the Israeli-Egyptian peace talks
at nearby Camp David in 1978. More than two decades later, many
here believe the time for peace has come.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just hoping and hoping that they wind up working something
out for those people over there,'' said Holly Bailey, owner of a
florist shop in town. ``It's a shame they've got to be over there
fighting and everything. It's just really sad.''
</P>
<P>
   Settled nearly three centuries ago by a handful of pioneer
families fleeing religious persecution in their native Germany,
Thurmont is no stranger to intractable conflict.
</P>
<P>
   It sits right between two major Civil War battles: Gettysburg,
15 miles to the North; and roughly the same distance to the South,
the spot on the Monocacy River where a Union artillery battery held
off Confederate soldiers trying to attack Washington, 70 miles
away.
</P>
<P>
   Culturally, though, Thurmont _ the name comes from a German word
that means ``gateway to the mountains'' _ is worlds away from
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   A place where the local fireman's carnival still provides a set
piece to a summer of crab cakes, ham sandwiches and fresh tomatoes,
Thurmont knows the term ``Rose Garden,'' not as a White House stage
but rather as the home of Jim and Mary Eyler.
</P>
<P>
   For 44 years, the Eylers have raised roses _ more than 300
plants, including the shoulder-high row that fences off their lawn
from pedestrians and youngsters on bikes _ at their two-story home
at the corner of Main and Carroll streets.
</P>
<P>
   Descendants of the town's frontier settlers, the Eylers _ both,
82 _ sat Tuesday at a kitchen table dominated by a lazy susan
crammed with more than two dozen bottles of prescription drugs, and
shook their heads at the prospects for Mideast peace.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ever since time began somewhere over there there's been
fighting, there's been war,'' said Mary.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Clinton pulls this off, it'll surprise me,'' she said. ``He
won't.''
</P>
<P>
   (Bob Deans' E-mail address is: bobdeans(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
