<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-11 17:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9216 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-SEMI-CON-COX     07-11 0718
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEMI-CON-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Semiconductor companies on a roll
 &HT;    By Bob Keefe
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Call it revenge of the wrench-turners.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago at the Semicon West trade conference here, talk
among attendees was about how lousy it was for them and how
ridiculously good it was for the newly monied dot-com crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, how times have changed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The dot-coms are dying,'' said John Thompson of Milliken &AMP;
Co., based in LaGrange, Ga., with just a bit of a smirk, at this
year's expo for chip company suppliers, being held in San Francisco
and in San Jose this week.
</P>
<P>
   One of an estimated 60,000 attendees at this year's Semicon
West, Thompson is in a decidedly low-tech part of the high-tech
industry. Milliken makes and sells clean room wipers _
super-sterile rags, essentially, used in semiconductor clean rooms.
</P>
<P>
   While many dot-coms and other tech types are in the financial
dumper, the nuts-and-bolts companies that keep semiconductor
companies running _ makers of everything from sophisticated silicon
etching equipment to stainless steel pipes and valves, industrial
gasses and wipers _ are having the best time they've had in years.
</P>
<P>
   _ Semiconductor equipment sales are expected to grow by nearly
37 percent this year, equipment companies estimated in a Semicon
survey. That's up from 18 percent growth last year and a whole lot
better than the dismal 22 percent drop in business two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   _ The hottest new electronics goods are more dependent on
semiconductors than ever before. As much as half of the cost of
personal digital assistants such as Palm Pilots, for instance, goes
to pay for the semiconductors inside them, according to a study by
Morgan Stanley Dean Witter &AMP; Co. By comparison, semiconductor costs
account for about 25 percent to 33 percent of the price of a
typical personal computer and 8 percent to 10 percent of the cost
of a mainframe computer.
</P>
<P>
   _ Along with strong demand, more efficient production methods
are prompting chip companies to invest in new equipment and
factories at levels not seen in years. At least 15 chip
manufacturers are planning to build new factories or revamp old
ones around the world in the next two years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The recovery remains in full-force,'' said Stanley Myers,
president and chief executive of Semiconductor Equipment and
Materials International, or SEMI, the trade group that sponsors
Semicon. ``The promise of a major ramp-up in semiconductor
manufacturing in 2000 is being realized.''
</P>
<P>
   All of that is good news in Austin, which is home to more
domestic semiconductor factories than anyplace outside Silicon
Valley and many equipment makers and suppliers. Some of the biggest
exhibitors at Semicon West include Applied Materials Inc., which
does almost all of its manufacturing in Austin, and arch-rival
Tokyo Electron Ltd., which has its domestic headquarters in Austin.
</P>
<P>
   Semiconductor makers and their suppliers know that if history is
any indication, the party won't last long. The chip business tends
to be cyclical.
</P>
<P>
   Equipment makers surveyed by SEMI said they expect their
industry to grow by only about 24 percent next year, and less than
13 percent two years from now.
</P>
<P>
   But those predictions haven't put a damper on this year's annual
gathering. Many regular Semicon exhibitors said they're getting
more inquiries than in past years. And throughout the 2,800-booth
exhibit halls, talk has been about the industry's recent rebound.
</P>
<P>
   ``In (1998) it was all doom and gloom, `` said Art Williams of
Air Systems Inc. a San Jose, Calif., contractor that supplies big
pipes and other heavy-duty gear to semiconductor companies.
``Today, everything's just red hot.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Randy Cordes, whose Minnesota company, Dynetic Systems,
sells electric motors to equipment companies, ``Everybody is giddy,
just giddy.''
</P>
<P>
   With all the good news, semiconductor equipment makers and
suppliers are engaging in a little dot-com-style partying of their
own.
</P>
<P>
   Tonight, at a party celebrating 30 years of SEMI, featured
entertainers include on-the-edge funnyman Dana Carvey and hip
retro-swing group the Cherry Poppin' Daddies.
</P>
<P>
   You may contact Bob Keefe at bkeefe(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
