   ONBUSINESS-COLUMN (Undated) _ Berkshire Partners is sticking to
its knitting. The company is still putting its money into the
traditional businesses it has backed for 14 years. By Steven Syre
and Charles Stein.
</P>
<P>
   JORDAN-COLUMN (Undated) _ If the economy continues to do well,
so will Al Gore -- provided he makes the changes that will make him
look as good to the electorate as the economy itself. By Robert
Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPORTS (s) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TEN-WIMBLEDON (London) _ The 114th rendition of Wimbledon seemed
like a two-week diversionary tactic, with uproar on the periphery
drowning out the competition on the sacred lawn. But the momentous
coronation of Venus Williams Saturday and the record reinstallation
of Pete Sampras Sunday brought the game back to its rightful
eminence. Bob Duffy. 1580 words.
</P>
<P>
   TV-SPORTS-COLUMN (Undated) --Give Mike Piazza some credit. Roger
Clemens hits him in the head and, though visibly dazed from a
concussion, Piazza says Clemens is a great pitcher -- but he
doesn't have respect for him. By Howard Manly. (Sent earlier.)
</P>
<P>
   HOLLEY-COLUMN (Atlanta) _ Sharing thoughts from the sports
world. By Michael Holley.
</P>
