<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Wednesday, July 12, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Breezes from the north will bring dry air to the Northeast and
northern Middle Atlantic states as high pressure builds toward the
region. After a cool start, abundant sun will boost readings to
near seasonal levels. Farther south, scattered showers and
thunderstorms will surround a front draped from North Carolina to
Tennessee. A few of the storms will produce heavy rain, which will
cause flooding. The remainder of the Southeast will be partly
cloudy and hot with spotty afternoon thundershowers.
</P>
<P>
   Hot weather will continue from the Plains to the eastern Rockies
on Wednesday. The heat will be tempered in eastern Colorado and
western Kansas, however, where scattered afternoon thunderstorms
will erupt.
</P>
<P>
   The Pacific states will stay dry with ample sun, though patchy
clouds will shroud the immediate coastline.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: HEAT WAVE
</P>
<P>
   A summer heat wave is gripping parts of the Plains and eastern
Rockies. In Denver, the temperature has exceeded 90 degrees every
day since June 29, including a 101-degree reading on July 6th.
Meanwhile, the mercury in Topeka, Kan., reached 100 on Monday, with
temperatures of 90 degrees or higher attained on the previous 10
days. While this region has been hot, there have been much hotter
periods. During the Dust Bowl, the temperature met or exceeded 90
in Topeka for 29 straight days in July of 1937 and 1939, while a
17-day stretch of 100-degree heat occurred in 1936.
</P>
</TEXT>
