<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-11 17:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9226 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-RONCRUISER-COX     07-11 1155
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RONCRUISER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    'I'm sorry sir, this not your PT Cruiser'
 &HT;    By Ron Wiggins
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. - When Frances Buchanan faced throat
surgery for suspected cancer last winter, her husband, Glenn, made
her a promise.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're going to come through this surgery, and when you do,
we're buying you a new car, any car you want.''
</P>
<P>
   Which struck the mother of five as odd since she was fine with
old cars and it was her husband who was the car buff. ``Oh,
really?'' she asked her husband, dryly. ``And just what car do I
want, and what color do I prefer?''
</P>
<P>
   To which Glenn readily informed her that she craved a
silver-gray PT Cruiser, Chrysler's concept car that looks like a
coupe of the '30s morphed into a panel delivery truck of the same
era. And his wife was OK with that. Really.
</P>
<P>
   ``We always said that if Detroit would make an old-looking car
with modern technology, we'd buy it,'' said Frances, who came
through her surgery in fine shape, with no signs of cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Turns out thousands of other retro buffs felt the same way.
Chrysler dealers can't keep the cars _ priced from $16,000 to
$21,000 _ in stock. So brisk is the demand for the jaunty little
Cruisers that folks who have purchased them for list price have
been able to drive them off the lot and sell them for thousands
more.
</P>
<P>
   Chrysler dealers put a stop to that practice in a hurry by
making darned sure that if anybody was going to realize windfall
profits, it would be the dealers. This they accomplished by raising
the price until they heard actual screaming, and then jacking it
some more until they heard the softer sound of people putting away
their check books and shuffling dejectedly from showrooms.
</P>
<P>
   The Buchanans knew all about Additional Dealer Profit (ADP) and
made sure they didn't have to pay it by ordering their car months
before they showed up at the dealerships. Accordingly, they
contracted with Palm Beach Auto Mall in West Palm Beach.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got everything,'' beamed Glenn. ``Leather, moon roof, the
works; $19,970. About all we didn't ask for was the chrome wheels
and a roof rack.''
</P>
<P>
   ``One of my sons surfs,'' explains Frances, ``and I did not want
to see my car turned into a surfing wagon.''
</P>
<P>
   The choice of silver gray seemed appropriate for their stage in
life.
</P>
<P>
   ``We both have our share of silver in our hair,'' laughs
Frances, ``and Glenn was wondering if we shouldn't paint a cartoon
bunny on the hood and name it The Gray Hare.''
</P>
<P>
   Great fun. And a great price by ordering before the cars were in
showrooms.
</P>
<P>
   Weeks went by.
</P>
<P>
   And for weeks Glenn would stop by the showroom and ask when he
could expect delivery of his $19,970 silver-gray Chrysler PT
Cruiser with leather seats and moon roof and no roof rack.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, in April, a Chrysler PT Cruiser, Limited Edition, just
like the one the Buchanans ordered, came in. The dealer called and
told them it wasn't their car but invited them to come in and smell
the leather.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said I would have to wait for Frances' car, but that I
could have this one for $2,400 over my contract price,'' said
Glenn.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `That's OK, I'm very patient. I'll wait.'''
</P>
<P>
   After waiting some more, a salesman confided to Glenn during one
of his visits that the Cruisers were selling $6,000 to $9,000 over
list price and that he would be smart to snap up the floor model.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I told him that I was being patient and that there was a
Cruiser with my name on it for $19,990, he said there was no
telling how long I'd have to wait.''
</P>
<P>
   Glenn mulled the matter over another few days and voiced a
suspicion to his wife: ``Momma, I think that's your car.''
</P>
<P>
   And if it wasn't, and nobody else had ordered a car that
happened to be just like the one they wanted, why couldn't they buy
it for the agreed price?
</P>
<P>
   So Glenn went back, sought out the manager and explained that if
the silver-gray PT Cruiser in the showroom was not his car, it was
enough like it, and why not close the deal on the spot? The manager
patiently explained that no, the car in question wasn't his, but
since he had been patient, and there was no telling how long it
would be before his car would be delivered, they would go ahead and
sell it to him.
</P>
<P>
   For only $1,500 more than the Buchanans had contracted to pay.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn caved. And just to show extra good will, the Auto Mall
threw in a special PT Cruiser picnic basket. ``I like to show
everybody my $1,500 picnic basket,'' Glenn said.
</P>
<P>
   The car has been a spectacular success in the neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``Three of our five kids live on our street with five of our
grandchildren,'' Frances said. ``The grandchildren are always
coming over and saying, `Mimi, can we go to the store in your
car?'''
</P>
<P>
   Glenn says a trip down Interstate 95 is always good for the
thumbs-up from assorted Mustang and BMW pilots. On Worth Avenue,
where Jags and Rolls don't get a second glance, folks gather around
with questions. The Cruiser, they are told, has a 150 horsepower,
four-cylinder engine that gets 23 mpg city, and the seats roll out
to make room to carry a small sofa.
</P>
<P>
   Their happiness, I regret to say, is not complete. Frances wants
$1,500 back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went back to the sales manager and insisted that that was
our car that they sold us, and that we should get the $1,500 back
and we'd return the picnic basket.''
</P>
<P>
   And the dealers' response?
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, they were very nice at first. They explained that it
wasn't our car and that they had bent over backward to please us,
and that I didn't understand market realities and that for example,
I couldn't expect to get into a popular restaurant without
reservations without paying the head waiter something.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I said that I had my reservation by ordering the car in
February. They said my reservation was for another car, not the one
we bought. I said, `Very well, we paid the extra $1,500 for the car
that you say was not ours. I still have a contract for a loaded
Chrysler PT Cruiser Limited Edition for $19,990 and call me when it
comes in, because I'll buy it.'''
</P>
<P>
   This declaration, according to Frances, troubled the manager.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said that it seemed to him that I was out to hurt the
dealership and that he wished he understood what I had against
them.''
</P>
<P>
   I called Palm Beach Auto Mall and was assured by a spokesman,
who asked not to be named, that the car the Buchaaler just say,
``OK, this isn't your car, but it's just like it, so we'll close
the deal at the list price and make the big bucks on your car when
it comes in''?
</P>
<P>
   The spokesman said it doesn't work that way:
</P>
<P>
   ``How could we know what the market would be when their car came
in? All I can tell you is that the Buchanans took 45 minutes to
decide, were fine with the price when they left, and that we threw
in a picnic basket and a mouse pad. When Mrs. Buchanan came back
some time later and asked for $1,500 back, it just re
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-11-00 1754EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000711.0208 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-11 17:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9228 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-PTCRUISER-COX     07-11 1398
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PTCRUISER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    PT Cruiser very popular and just as pricey
 &HT;    By Douglas Kalajian
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. - When it comes to buying a Chrysler PT
Cruiser, a snoozer is a loser.
</P>
<P>
   The Cruiser is hot. Not as in hot rod, which it looks like, nor
as in stolen, which it might be in the unlikely event that you took
your eyes off it for more than a second. No, the PT (for ``personal
transportation'') Cruiser is Pokemon hot. Tickle-Me-Elmo hot.
Cabbage Patch Kids hot.
</P>
<P>
   For those with a more mature frame of reference, it is Mustang
hot. It's been that long (36 years, if you really must count) since
any mass-produced American car rolled into the showrooms as a
gotta-have-one-right-now cultural phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
   The Cruiser was back-ordered even before its debut as a 2001
model in April after two years of peekaboo previews at car shows
and on magazine covers. The assembly plant in Mexico didn't reach
full steam until late June, but by then it was clear that the
plant's annual 180,000-car output wouldn't come close to demand.
</P>
<P>
   ``The orders are coming in faster than we can make them,'' says
DaimlerChrysler spokesman Ann Smith. A second plant is now being
prepared in Austria to supply Europe and other parts of the world.
</P>
<P>
   Who'd expect this much excitement about something that would
have looked old when the Mustang was new?
</P>
<P>
   Everyone who looks at the PT Cruiser sees something different.
From the rear, some see dad's old station wagon. Others look at the
tall roof and see a London taxi. To many, the Cruiser's bulbous
fenders and angled snout hint at the old, souped-up Fords of James
Dean movies and ZZ Top videos.
</P>
<P>
   Yvonne Mason felt a twinge of recognition when she first saw a
picture of a PT Cruiser.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looked like my first car, a '38 or '39 Plymouth,'' she
says. Her parents bought it for $150 when she learned to drive in
the mid-1950s.
</P>
<P>
   Months later, she saw a Cruiser drive by and felt an emotional
tug. Mason, a widow who works at home in Royal Palm Beach as a
bookkeeper for a roofing company, drove to the Chrysler showroom at
the Palm Beach Auto Mall in West Palm Beach only to discover that
neither she nor anyone else could buy one because there were none
in sight.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not taking orders,'' says general manager Vern Mathis.
</P>
<P>
   What they're taking are names. Dozens of them.
</P>
<P>
   When a PT Cruiser arrives from the factory, it's an event akin
to Mel Gibson stopping by the local movie house to take in a
matinee. Salesmen rush to the phones while everyone else rushes out
to ogle the car. It is no time for anyone on the waiting list to be
having a long-distance chat with Aunt Zelda.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one who gets here first gets the car,'' says salesman
Steve Lee.
</P>
<P>
   When a delivery trailer pulled in with a new Cruiser recently,
Lee was the first salesman to connect with a live prospect: Mason.
She hopped in her Mercury Grand Marquis and got to the showroom in
a flash. She had the dazed look of someone who just won the
lottery.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm so shocked they called me,'' she says. ``He had 32 or 33
names on his list.''
</P>
<P>
   Mason kept herself at the head of the line by sitting right down
at Lee's desk to sign a sales contract while her car was being
washed.
</P>
<P>
   She bought her Cruiser without driving it. Without sitting in
it. Without even seeing it.
</P>
<P>
   And, of course, without haggling. ``The price _ oh!'' she says,
rolling her eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Like others in the thrall of Cruisermania, Mason learned that
the price sticker might as well have been printed in Farsi. She
paid ``just about'' $30,000 for a top-of-the-line PT Cruiser
Limited with Deep Cranberry Pearl Coat paint, taupe-and-beige
leather interior _ and a manufacturer's suggested retail price of
$20,705.
</P>
<P>
   Don't think you'll never pay that much over sticker for any car,
because you already did: The federal government paid a New York
dealer about $10,000 over list price for each of two PT Cruisers
that it plans to crash test. The National Highway Traffic Safety
Administration insists on buying cars directly from dealers to
ensure that manufacturers don't make modifications that could
affect test results.
</P>
<P>
   The deal embarrassed DaimlerChrysler Corp., which says it
discourages dealers from charging more than the list price but has
no way to stop them. It also touched off a minor storm in Congress
and left some wondering if PT really stood for Barnum. But the
government's purchase price wasn't out of line with what Mason and
other buyers across the country are paying.
</P>
<P>
   ``People bash us,'' says Mathis, the Auto Mall's Chrysler
manager. But until the factory ships his dealership more than the
current six-to-eight cars a month, PT Cruisers will remain the
stone crabs of the auto world: strictly market price.
</P>
<P>
   One precedent was parked front-and-center in the Auto Mall
showroom, a two-seat, '30s-style roadster called the Plymouth
Prowler. This one, in blinding yellow paint, carried a factory
sticker price of $43,725 and a hand-lettered dealer sign that read
$68,775 ``current market value.''
</P>
<P>
   Go ahead and offer less. Mathis says the fast-but-cramped
Prowlers are ``sometimes hot, sometimes not.'' DaimlerChrysler has
sold just over 1,600 of them this calendar year, and they may
disappear all together this fall, along with the Plymouth brand
name. But the publicity splash the Prowler created when it went on
sale three years ago and the cult status it's earned since helped
persuade DaimlerChrysler to consider a lower-priced, higher-volume
retromobile.
</P>
<P>
   The idea has caught hold with other manufacturers. Volkswagen
boosted sales by reviving the Beetle, at least in appearance. Ford
is planning to sell a modern version of the 1955 two-seat
Thunderbird, probably listing at $35,000-plus. Chevrolet says it's
going to produce a 1940s-style pickup with a retractable roof.
</P>
<P>
   None is expected to approach the Cruiser's sales level.
DaimlerChrysler says nostalgia isn't the Cruiser's main appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``The designer was going after that romantic look _ a really
emotional car,'' Smith says. ``Young people look at it and think
it's totally new.''
</P>
<P>
   Why wouldn't they? Anyone who came of driving age in the 1980s
or '90s would think a car should look like a half-melted bar of
soap, or the box it came in. The last Chrysler to turn so many
heads was the high-finned, gas-guzzling 1957 model.
</P>
<P>
   The Cruiser is even drawing notice from auto enthusiasts, who
normally favor Japanese and European sports models. Doug Kott,
executive editor of ``Road &AMP; Track'' magazine, says he was certain
of the Cruiser's appeal when he drove the magazine's early test
model to a California race shop filled with young mechanics.
</P>
<P>
   ``It absolutely emptied the place,'' he says. ``There is
incredible interest from 25-year-olds. They all came out to
surround it.''
</P>
<P>
   Kott notes the Cruiser's ``whimsical touches, a lot of neat
things,'' many of them picked up from old-time cars: A cue-ball
shift knob on stick shifts; body-color trim on the Limited's
dashboard; a highly stylized Chrysler logo that looks like
something from the classic era.
</P>
<P>
   The Cruiser's distinctions may not go much deeper.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the PT Cruiser is just a cleverly disguised minivan,''
Kott says. The federal government actually classifies the Cruiser
as a light truck. It has lots of space and practical features like
storage bins and fold-down seats, but it also shares plenty of
parts with the company's economy cars, including a four-cylinder
engine.
</P>
<P>
   None of that seems to discourage the hot-rod and custom-car
crowd from embracing the Cruiser. ``People are already putting
flames on them,'' Smith says. There's even a PT Cruiser Club ($39
to join, but you don't have to buy the car) with a Web site
(www.ptcruiserclub.org) and plans for a national Cruiser cruise to
Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   No one can be sure whether the Cruiser's lure will hold up as
its shape becomes more familiar, but its success so far bodes well
for a new era of distinctive automotive styling, Kott says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cars across the board have become so reliable that it's much
less of a factor in making a purchasing decision,'' Kott says.
``That's where high style comes to the fore. The manufacturer that
can style something appealing will have the edge.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
