<HEADLINE>
THIS CLASSOOM DRAMA NEEDS A LONG RECESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Some shows make their points with subtlety. Others, which have
only a short summer run in which to leave a legacy, use
sledgehammers. And then there's ``Young Americans,'' another
beautiful-white-kids drama from The WB, which actually makes
sledgehammers seem subtle.
</P>
<P>
   Take the case of principal character Will Krudski (Rodney
Scott). He's the poor kid from the other side of town, son of an
abusive father, smart enough to get a scholarship to the
hoity-toity prep school through which generations of rich young men
have passed on their way to fame and even more fortune. With a name
like Krudski, it doesn't take a meeting of Mensa to know that Will
is the designated Downtrodden Man.
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't come from money or influence. He's not even sure he
belongs at Rawley Academy with guys named Scout Calhoun (Mark
Famiglietti) and Hamilton Fleming (Ian Somerhalder). But his test
scores got him in, and he's determined to stay, even after
divulging to a guy he barely knows the sort of secret that most
people would take with them to the grave. The indiscretion almost
costs him his scholarship, but we all know that's not going to
happen because there are seven more episodes to go after tonight's
premiere.
</P>
<P>
   One of Will's friends from town is Bella Banks (Kate Bosworth),
your basic stunning beauty who works at her dad's gas station.
Bella has the hots for Will's roommate, Scout, but her dad puts the
kibosh on the romance for reasons you'd expect to see on ``All My
Children.''
</P>
<P>
   Also matriculating this summer session is Jake Pratt (Katherine
Moennig), a motorcycle-riding rebel who bounces from prep school to
prep school with his own bizarre secret. (Since a guy named Jake is
played by a woman named Katherine, you can probably guess what it
is.) Jake's friendship with the loner Hamilton and _ oops! _
another indiscretion soon have Hamilton wondering aloud about his
sexuality.
</P>
<P>
   The authority figure in this cross between ``I've Got a Secret''
and ``The Facts of Life'' is Mr. Finn (Ed Quinn): teacher, crew
coach and the guy who's supposed to inspire the kids to shoot for
the stars.
</P>
<P>
   Sadly, the producers didn't aim quite so high, taking a tired
concept and giving it an uninspired treatment. In tonight's
episode, the only sparkle comes from Bosworth, who seems to be
aware that ``Young Americans'' might work better as spoof than as
semiserious drama.
</P>
<P>
   YOUNG AMERICANS
</P>
<P>
   WHAT: One-hour weekly drama about a group of teenagers attending
summer session at a New England boarding school.
</P>
<P>
   CAST: Rodney Scott, Mark Famiglietti, Kate Bosworth, Ian
Somerhalder, Katherine Moennig and Ed Quinn.
</P>
<P>
   WHEN: Series premiere Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   WHERE: The WB
</P>
<P>
   RATING: TV-PG.
</P>
<P>
   GRADE: C+
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
