<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-11 17:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9234 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-TV-DAISY-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      07-11 0890
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-DAISY-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`PULL MY DAISY': JACK KEROUAC   AND THE BEATS,   OFF THE ROAD   AND
IN A FILM 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``A splendid entertainment for the entire family _ no
sex, no violence'' was how Alfred Leslie archly plugged his new
film ``Pull My Daisy'' in Variety in 1959.
</P>
<P>
   ``And then I quoted a line of Jack's: `Doing something and
saying goodbye and saying goodbye and doing something are both the
same,''' he said. ``Which means, I think, living a life is enough
to be able to get through life, and you don't always have to be
enormously active or a great star.''
</P>
<P>
   The Jack in question is Jack Kerouac. That many of the Beats
went on to achieve a potent stardom is almost beside the point.
From its inception, Beat lent itself to myriad interpretations, but
to people like Kerouac, it derived mostly from ``beatific.''
</P>
<P>
   On Friday at 10 p.m., Channel 13/WNET will present ``Pull My
Daisy,'' a slice _ more a sliver _ of a day in the lives of the
Beats. In its television debut, the film leads a program of five
shorts that reflect the Beat philosophy, part of the channel's
independent film series ``Reel New York.''
</P>
<P>
   A sort of wry social commentary, the film is at once about
nothing and everything. There is no plot, no story, no action or
drama. Photographed in grainy black and white, a band of urban
troubadours enter a loft on the Lower East Side and wreak merry
havoc on the lives within. Slouching on a sofa, flasks in hand, the
men spout poetry and ponder spirituality, their voices sounding
oddly the same, their mouths not quite in sync with the vocal
track, which scats along to a loose, bluesy beat. Allen Ginsberg,
Gregory Corso and Larry Rivers are doing what they did best:
hanging out, kicking back, taking it all in. As the narrator, a
coolly ebullient Kerouac makes his words their own.
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Leslie and the photographer Robert Frank, the film
was based on an act from Kerouac's unproduced play ``The Beat
Generation'' and named for a poem by Ginsberg and Kerouac. The
play, in turn, was inspired by an incident in the lives of Neal
Cassady, Kerouac's partner on the road, and Cassady's wife,
Carolyn, who aspired to suburban respectability in Northern
California.
</P>
<P>
   Leslie, now 74, envisioned the project as part of a trilogy, but
almost immediately ran into a stumbling block in Kerouac's syntax.
``When I read his text and thought of the actors speaking the
lines, I thought it was insane,'' he said. ``It didn't sound right.
I decided against shooting.''
</P>
<P>
   Only after hearing Kerouac read the script himself did a concept
take shape. ``What troubled me,'' Leslie said, ``was that there
were no characters in Jack's work. All of Jack Kerouac is written
as a monologuist taking everybody's part.''
</P>
<P>
   So it was decided: Kerouac would do all the speaking for
everyone.
</P>
<P>
   Watching the film in a sound studio, Kerouac dubbed its
narration as David Amram, the composer and musician who would later
write the score for ``The Manchurian Candidate,'' sat in a booth
and played the piano.
</P>
<P>
   Not quite 30 minutes long, ``Pull My Daisy'' opened at the
Cinema 16 Film Society in Manhattan as an ``outrageous success,
though it made no money and was marginalized immediately,'' Leslie
said. After winning first prize at the San Francisco Film Festival,
it quickly lost momentum.
</P>
<P>
   He stored the film in his West 22nd Street studio, but lost it
to a 1966 inferno that killed 12 firefighters. But some scraps were
found in the rubble, and he kept them in a refrigerator until a
grant in 1990 enabled him to restore the work. A release print had
been discovered in the meantime and was presented to the Museum of
Modern Art. In 1997, the Library of Congress installed ``Pull My
Daisy'' into its film archive for safekeeping.
</P>
<P>
   ```Pull My Daisy' in 1959 looked like an insane work to
people,'' Leslie said. ``It looked chaotic and unstructured, and
people didn't know how to deal with it. But the film had a very,
very wide influence because it opened up a way for people to think
of being more independent in their vision.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a formal film, quiet in tone and movement,'' he
continued. ``It had a strong subtext of subversiveness, a Samuel
Beckett, Chehkovian kind of quality in which nothing happens. Like
a Seinfeld incident of nothing. But I thought in that you could see
the naturalness of all of the lives of people.''
</P>
<P>
   Over time, the trappings of the Beats wore thin, especially to
those at the movement's vortex.
</P>
<P>
   ```Pull My Daisy' came about largely from a group of painters
and writers who wanted to make a movie to show their children and
grandchildren what we were really like,'' said Amram, 69, who also
appeared in the film. ``The image of a beatnik had become so
horrific that it was something we couldn't identify with anymore.
</P>
<P>
   ``In `Pull My Daisy,' nobody looks like a beatnik,'' he said of
the cliched turtlenecks, berets and goatees that Kerouac likened to
a Roman Catholic school dress code, and the movement's subtext of
drugs and malaise. ``We all shared a joy of life, the ability to
work hard at what we were trying to do artistically, at having fun.
</P>
<P>
   ``The film is so lighthearted and joyous and funny, it's the
antidote to the Beat label,'' he added. ``That was the albatross
around all our necks.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-11-00 1759EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000711.0214 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-11 18:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
