<HEADER>
A9242 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-YAHOO-EARNINGS-COX     07-11 0461
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YAHOO-EARNINGS-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Yahoo shows profit, outperforms expectations
</P>
<P>
   By Frances Katz
</P>
<P>
   c. 20000 Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA - Yahoo tossed out the first pitch of the NASDAQ
earnings season Tuesday, announcing a profitable second quarter
that surpassed analysts' expectations.
</P>
<P>
   As one of the big four Internet companies, along with America
Online, Amazon and eBay, Yahoo's earnings are generally viewed as a
key indicator of the health of the Internet marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   The top portal on the Web, Yahoo reported higher than expected
earnings and said revenues more than doubled. The company reported
net income of $65.5 million, or 11 cents a share, after breaking
even a year earlier. Revenue more than doubled to $270.1 million,
from $128.6 million.
</P>
<P>
   Yahoo shares, which have fallen 29 percent in the past three
weeks amid concern about the earnings outlook, rose following
release of the higher-than-expected revenue number. They traded as
high as 114, up 8 percent from a NASDAQ close of 105 1/2.
</P>
<P>
   Yahoo has attracted more attention than usual this quarter
because of concerns that the recent dot-com fallout will make a
dent in its advertising revenues. Advertising on the Yahoo site
makes up 70 percent of the company's revenue and dot-com marketing
makes up a substantial chunk of its overall advertising.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts from Deutsche Banc recently downgraded Yahoo from a
``strong buy'' to a ``buy'' saying there will probably be less ad
spending from cash-strapped dot-coms.
</P>
<P>
   But, while most analyst agree the second quarter may be a gloomy
one for Internet stocks, they say Yahoo is too big to feel much, if
any, of the fallout.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Gristina, an analyst with Atlanta's Robinson Humphrey said
the company is in good shape.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yahoo's business model is not in jeopardy,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet is not going away and advertising is still very
effective on the Net, `` he said. ``To me it just says that they
may go into a slower period of growth, but Yahoo is still a
must-have in your portfolio.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The industry average is about 20 per cent of ad revenue
generated by the dot-coms,'' said David Card a senior analyst with
Jupiter Communications. ``Yahoo's percentage might be a little
higher, so there is some risk there.'' However Card says he doesn't
see a slowing down of dot-com advertising happening yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are talking about cutting back, but I haven't seen
anything yet,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts say the real indicator of the state of ad spending
on the Web will come next week when DoubleClick, the online company
that sells and serves advertising to hundreds of Web sites, reports
its earnings Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
