candidate, Al Gore or George W. Bush, has a medical prescription
plan that has any chance of traveling, even slightly as proposed,
through the labyrinth of the lobbyist-dominated Congress, then I
have a bridge in Brooklyn I want to sell you _ again. It makes for
great listening from the stump and, I suppose, it does position
each candidate on the issue. But, don't expect the winner to
deliver; he won't, he can't. The system won't allow it. (Kleinberg,
Cox News Service.)
</P>
<P>
   SCHUETT-COLUMN _ GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ Although my presidential
campaign lurched to a slow start, I'm happy to report things are
beginning to pick up. As of this morning we have nine votes
promised _ five from readers who agree with my suggestions for
campaign finance reform ($50 per candidate and no disclosure), two
from my friends Gail (Oregon Gail and Cape Cod Gail), and one each
from my son and his wife because they live in Philadelphia and
would like to weekend in the White House. (Schuett, Cox News
Service) MOVED.
