<P>
   LOCKHEED _ MARIETTA, Ga. _ It took Lee Rhyant a while, but he
finally found his way back to Georgia. Rhyant was born in the
Georgia town of Sasser 50 years ago. He left the state as a youth
and wound up pursuing a career in the auto and aerospace industries
up north. Now he's returned as the new man in charge at Lockheed
Martin's aircraft plant in Marietta. ``It's a homecoming,'' he said
Tuesday at a ceremony to dedicate the plant's first C-130J cargo
plane built for the Italian Air Force. ``I plan to meet some
relatives in Alabama and Georgia I've never met,'' he added. He
arrived last week as vice president and site general manager of the
plant under a new management structure set up in the wake of a
consolidation of Bethesda, Md.-based Lockheed Martin's aircraft
operations. Rhyant is the first African-American recruited to run
the plant. (Thurston, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
