<DOCNO> NYT20000711.0222 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-11 18:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9246 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-COUNTRY-DUETS12-COX     07-11 1047
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COUNTRY-DUETS12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The dynamic duo of Tim McGraw, Faith Hill breathe new life into
the country tradition
 &HT;    By Miriam Longino
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   They probably didn't know it at the time, but superstars Faith
Hill and Tim McGraw resurrected a disappearing piece of Nashville
tradition in Atlanta four years ago with the Kiss.
</P>
<P>
   On a hot July evening in 1996, the two were performing in
Centennial Olympic Park. It was three days before the bombing that
would make the venue notorious throughout the rest of the summer.
The air was heavy with humidity and rumors of a budding romance
between the two stars.
</P>
<P>
   Late into the evening, McGraw stepped into the spotlight and
began singing the sizzling R&AMP;B, Tony Rich hit ``Nobody Knows It but
Me'' _``The nights are lonely, days are so long. ... I'm missing
you, and nobody knows it but me.''
</P>
<P>
   From stage left, Hill appeared, in skintight, black-leather
pants, grabbed a microphone, and began singing back. After three
minutes of heavy flirting, the two dropped their microphones and
laid a kiss on each other that had the Atlanta crowd screaming like
hungry citizens at the Roman Colosseum.
</P>
<P>
   That was the moment the country duet was reborn.
</P>
<P>
   McGraw and Hill went on to dump fiances, get married and have
two children. When they pull into Philips Arena tonight, they are
perhaps the most hyped act in country music, with a string of
individual hits. (Hill's nearly naked romp on satin sheets for her
recent ``Breathe'' video has even made her a pop diva.) But it's
their duets _ often sappy, emotion-soaked tunes about being in luv
_ that now highlight their dance card.
</P>
<P>
   Before Tim and Faith (as they are known by their fans) began
teaming at home and in the studio, the country music duet was on
the endangered list. It had been nearly two decades since the
heyday of the format, when Conway Twitty and Loretta Lynn, Dolly
Parton and Porter Wagoner, and George Jones and Tammy Wynette
defined the style.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, it's interesting. We really haven't had any duets in
the traditional sense for a long time,'' says Johnny Gray, music
director of Atlanta country station Kicks 101.5. ``It may be
because of all the hat acts of the '90s. It was about the guys as
individuals, Garth (Brooks) and all the rest.''
</P>
<P>
   Though other genres of music have had pairings that have made
music history (such as pop's Marvin Gaye and Tammi Terrell),
country music has always been the petri dish for the style. Perhaps
it's because early Nashville was mostly a man's town, with female
vocalists relegated to the role of ``girl singer.'' Quite often, to
gain any radio airplay or national exposure, a woman had to team
with a man.
</P>
<P>
   Take Dolly Parton. The big-haired, big-chested vocalist could
circle the wagons around Porter when it came to singing, but it was
his access to Nashville's musical power base that landed her a job.
</P>
<P>
   Tammy Wynette had marginal success as a solo act on the charts
(``Apartment Number Nine'') before meeting George Jones, yet their
relationship virtually defines the term ``country duet.'' It's
primarily because their music reflected the drama of what was
happening to them in real life.
</P>
<P>
   Married to other people, George and Tammy fell hard for each
other, a tempestuous relationship that was recorded in the tabloids
and in the studio. As they were falling in love, the public heard
the sweet sounds of ``Near You.'' When they finally exchanged vows,
they made the over-the-top duet, ``The Ceremony,'' in which they
recited marriage vows into the microphone. When the hard-drinking
Jones pulled a shotgun on Wynette, producer Billy Sherrill got them
to record the ultimate song of alienation, ``Two Story House.'' As
the two tried to save their marriage in spite of the highly public
troubles, they released ``We're Gonna Hold On.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the greatest country duet team of all time was Conway
Twitty and Loretta Lynn. She had taken the spotlight as one of the
first independent women to make records in Nashville. He was one of
Nashville's hottest hitmakers. According to Lynn, the emotion in
their songs came out of mutual respect.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what was goin' on was that Conway and me would go into
the studio and try to out-sing each other,'' Lynn says, remembering
her late duet partner. ``He'd bring something in and I would try to
top him.''
</P>
<P>
   Conway and Lynn created a heated magic in the studio that has
yet to be replicated. They took the story line so essential to
country music and gave it a male/female script. ``Darlin', I knew
it was you,'' sings Loretta, as Conway literally growls back into a
telephone receiver, ``Oh, yeah, Loretta, you know it's true.''
(``As Soon As I Hang Up the Phone''). Their ``Louisiana Woman,
Mississippi Man'' has them swimming a river to get to each other.
Then, ``(Nothin's Cold as Ashes) After the Fire Is Gone.''
</P>
<P>
   As women gained autonomy in the Nashville star system, the
male/female duet all but disappeared until McGraw and Hill. From
impassioned videos featuring a very pregnant Hill (``It's Your
Love'') to bubbly singles such as ``The Way You Love Me,'' they
have turned successful individual careers into couple gold.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Tim and Faith are it, '' says Steve Mitchell, program
director for Y-106.7. ``When you listen to those songs, they are
passionate, the real deal.''
</P>
<P>
   One thing that McGraw and Hill have successfully avoided,
however, are the real-life headlines. In today's world of carefully
cultivated public imaging, none of us would know if he stormed out
in the middle of the night, or if she packed the kids in the SUV
and headed out of town. As far as the public is concerned, they are
the perfect couple, perfectly in love.
</P>
<P>
   But music, particularly country duets, has always been about
fantasy.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  To hear selections from featured duos, dial 511 and enter 8600
and Soundline number 421 for Porter Wagoner and Dolly Parton, 422
for Loretta Lynn and Conway Twitty, 423 for George Jones and Tammy
Wynette and 424 for Faith Hill and Tim McGraw. Each call costs 50
cents.
</P>
<P>
   Faith Hill
</P>
<P>
   &AMP; Tim McGraw
</P>
<P>
   8 tonight. $31.50, $61.50. Philips Arena, 1 Philips Drive,
</P>
<P>
   404-249-6400.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
