<HEADER>
A9247 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-TV-AMERICANS12-COX     07-11 0403
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-AMERICANS12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Young Americans' are a sight to see
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ah, to be young and American.
</P>
<P>
   To be young and American and stunningly gorgeous and buff of
bod. To strip down with a bunch of other perfect, underwear-clad
teenagers and run through a sun-dappled field in slow-motion to a
sparkling lake, and to plunge into that lake. And to frolic.
</P>
<P>
   To be young and slow-dancing at night; to have a literature
teacher who's incredibly cool and non-conformist and hunky even
though he's (ick!) over 30; to live in soft focus and golden
sunlight and tumble in the grass with a person even more beautiful.
</P>
<P>
   And yet. The boys and girls of ``Young Americans'' _ a new WB
series that makes ``Dawson's Creek'' feel like a Faulkner symposium
_ are not happy. Sun-drenched and shirtless and frolicsome though
they are, they have secrets.
</P>
<P>
   Requirements for admission into Rawley Academy, a New England
prep school where this summer series takes place: good grades, good
looks, lots of money, a terrible secret. Will (Rodney Scott)
cheated to get in. Scout (Mark Famiglietti) can't have his beloved,
Bella (Kate Bosworth), because they discover that they're secret
half-siblings. And Jake? Well, Jake has a certain androgynous air
and is played by an actress named Katherine Moennig, so Jake is the
only person at Rawley who isn't going shirtless all the time.
</P>
<P>
   Bella doesn't go to Rawley _ she works at her dad's garage in
the nearby town. She's supposed to be blue collar, but glows with
the aura of pampered youth, that whole tan-teeth-hair thing that
marks her as the kind of girl who gets a Beemer from daddy on her
16th birthday, not the kind of girl who does brake jobs on Beemers.
</P>
<P>
   In fairness, though, she's a swell fit for the boys of Rawley,
all of whom have frolicked right out of a Herb Ritts underwear ad
in Vanity Fair. You don't so much watch ``Young Americans'' as
ogle.
</P>
<P>
   The WB originally announced the show as a midseason replacement
for this past spring, then moved it to the summer, usually not a
show of respect from the network. Parts of the pilot were shot at
Agnes Scott College in Decatur, but don't hold that against an
otherwise fine school.
</P>
<P>
   ``Young Americans''
</P>
<P>
   9 tonight on the WB.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: D
</P>
<P>
   Phil Kloer writes for the
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
