<HEADER>
A9249 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-TASTINGS-NYT     07-11 0436
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TASTINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHERRY, THE PERFECT MATE 
</HEADLINE>
  By ERIC ASIMOV   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you scoff at the notion that pairing particular wines and
foods can create magic, here is a suggestion: Get some good
marinated Spanish olives and a bottle of dry fino or manzanilla
sherry. Chill the sherry well, pour a small glass and taste it with
the olives, then see if you don't agree that, like peanut butter
and jelly, the two belong together.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to find a beverage less understood and more
undervalued than sherry. The image of a treacly brown fluid brought
out at academic teas could not be further from the truth. In fact,
top-quality dry sherries are probably the cheapest great wines you
are likely to find.
</P>
<P>
   Authentic sherries come only from an area near the Atlantic
coast in Andalusia in southwestern Spain, bounded by the towns of
Jerez de la Frontera, Cadiz and Sanlucar de Barrameda. Sherry comes
in two types, fino and oloroso. The difference depends on a strain
of yeast called flor, which develops only on finos. It gives finos
a tangy quality and prevents them from oxidizing, so they retain
their freshness and pale color. Olorosos are darker, richer, higher
in alcohol and more expensive because they are aged longer.
</P>
<P>
   Finos are the focus here, and their styles and flavors can vary
tremendously. Those simply labeled fino are light and bone-dry with
complex aromas that can range from almonds to an attractive
petroleum quality. Manzanilla, a type of fino made only in the
seaside town of Sanlucar, is more delicate and often has a salty
quality. Amontillados are finos that have been aged, becoming
darker, softer and nuttier.
</P>
<P>
   Almost all sherries are blends, and so are not vintage wines.
When buying a fino or manzanilla, ask your retailer for the
freshest bottle. Chill it and drink it soon with shellfish, light
fish dishes, even chicken and ham.
</P>
<P>
   FINOS  &QL; 
 &QL; 
GONZALEZ BYASS , TIO PEPE $11 &QL; 
Beautifully balanced with delicious, clear flavors. &QL; 
 &QL; 
EMILIO LUSTAU , SOLERA RESERVA , JARANA $11 &QL; 
Mild petroleum aroma, complex and resonant flavors, long finish. &QL; 
 &QL; 
