<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-11 18:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9252 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-WINE-TALK-NYT &LR;      07-11 1035
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINE-TALK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEASTING LETHALLY ON CALIFORNIA'S VINEYARDS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Calif., Texas)   By   FRANK J. PRIAL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The big news in the California wine country two years ago was
the victorious conclusion to the 15-year, multi-million-dollar war
against phylloxera, a parasite killer that eventually wiped out
some 50,000 acres of prime California vineyard land.
</P>
<P>
   The diseased vines were uprooted and burned and new ones
planted, at enormous cost. One winemaker, the Robert Mondavi Winery
in the Napa Valley, reported that replanting its vineyards cost $50
million.
</P>
<P>
   The hard-won celebrations may have been premature. By 1997,
another predator had emerged in the state's southernmost vineyards
and began to spread northward with astonishing speed and
frightening results. Called Pierce's disease, it is a bacterium
spread by a tiny flying insect called the glassy-winged
sharpshooter. The insect implants the bacteria in a vine when it
feeds on the stem, and within several weeks, the vine dies.
</P>
<P>
   Several prominent wineries have shut down vineyards or parts of
vineyards because of Pierce's disease, among them Callaway
Vineyards and Winery in Temecula, in Southern California, and Bonny
Doon Vineyard, in the Santa Cruz Mountains.
</P>
<P>
   There is no cure for the disease, which kills vines by
preventing them from absorbing water and nutrients. There is no
effective method to stop this particular sharpshooter, which one
scientist called ``stunningly voracious'' at a meeting of Napa
Valley growers.
</P>
<P>
   Wine and wine grapes are a $33-billion-a-year industry in
California. The state estimates that damage from Pierce's disease
in the last two years was worth $6 million, none of which seems to
have been passed on to the consumer. Yet. But the future is
anyone's guess.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, California grape growers have been contending with
Pierce's disease for more than a century. It was first identified
near Anaheim in 1892, when it wiped out some 40,000 acres of grape
vines over a period of years. For a time it was known as the
Anaheim disease.
</P>
<P>
   A century ago and, in fact, until three years ago, the carrier
was the blue-green sharpshooter, an insect that thrives near rivers
and streams. The disease was usually controlled by replanting and
by moving vines away from streams or ponds.
</P>
<P>
   The glassy-winged sharpshooter is a more dangerous relative:
according to scientists at the University of California at Davis,
this sharpshooter can fly higher and farther than the blue-green
and can consume huge amounts of plant sap a day, the equivalent of
a 150-pound human's drinking 4,300 gallons of liquid. Patrick
Gleason, the director of the American Vineyard Foundation in Napa,
calls it ``the pterodactyl of sharpshooters.''
</P>
<P>
   The glassy-winged sharpshooter is thought to have entered
California a decade ago on ornamental plants shipped from Florida
nurseries. The insect thrives in the country's warmer regions,
which is one reason why European grape varieties like cabernet
sauvignon, merlot and chardonnay have never succeeded in Florida
and other southeastern states. Because of the sharpshooter,
Pierce's disease has also become a serious problem for Texas
vineyards.
</P>
<P>
   Its current resurgence in California has been most pronounced in
the south where, according to the state's Department of Food and
Agriculture, it has been found in San Diego, Riverside, San
Bernardino, Ventura, Orange and Santa Barbara Counties. In
Temecula, in Riverside County, the disease has wiped out nearly one
third of the wine grape vineyards in the 3,000-acre growing area.
</P>
<P>
   Both Napa and Monterey Counties are considering a nursery
certification program for ornamental and other plants purchased
elsewhere. ``We are advocating that all nursery stock from the
infested counties be inspected,'' said Corky Roche, a vineyard
consultant based in Salinas and a member of a state task force
studying Pierce's disease.
</P>
<P>
   The most vulnerable grape vines are chardonnay, which is the
state's most widely planted fine wine variety, and pinot noir,
which has been growing in popularity in recent years. Temecula and
Riverside Counties are particularly vulnerable because they also
have large groves of citrus fruits, and the sharpshooter likes to
lay its eggs in the leaves of citrus trees.
</P>
<P>
   The state's premier wine regions _ Napa, Sonoma and Mendocino
Counties, in Northern California _ have yet to encounter the
glassy-winged sharpshooter. Two weeks ago, the Napa Valley was
officially declared free of the insect by the Department of Food
and Agriculture.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are worried,'' said Ed Weber, an agricultural agent in Napa
County for the University of California. ``The insect is moving
north _ it's been found in Tulare and Fresno counties.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pierce's disease is an ongoing problem here in Napa,'' Weber
continued, ``and over the years we've had a lot of losses. But only
with the blue-green insect.''
</P>
<P>
   Meeting with growers and winemakers in March, Gov. Gray Davis
said he would sponsor legislation to provide $6.9 million in state
funds each year for the next two years and would seek another $7.1
million in federal help to fight Pierce's disease. Last year the
California Assembly appropriated $750,000 a year for three years
for research, contingent on an annual commitment of $250,000 from
the California wine and grape industry.
</P>
<P>
   Weber said that shipments of ornamental plants often presented
serious problems because they often carry the bug's eggs. ``But how
do you inspect all the plants?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   For now, he said, Pierce's disease is primarily being fought by
inspecting imported plants. Officials are trying to destroy the
sharpshooter eggs by spraying citrus trees with insecticides, and a
plan to introduce an insect called the fairy wasp, which destroys
the eggs, into infected areas, is being considered.
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, the only effective response may be what Callaway
has done: buy grapes elsewhere. George Rose, a spokesman for the
winery, said Callaway was about to introduce a line of wines made
from grapes purchased in the Central Coast area, well north of
Temecula, where these is no Pierce's disease. At least, not yet.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
