<P>
   CHINA-PRIVATE-SECTOR (Jiaxing, China) _ China has been marching
on the road of economic reform for more than two decades now, but
its private sector remains a tiny slice of an economy still
dominated by government-owned organizations. Entrepreneurs are
systematically shunned by China's banks, discriminated against by
regulators and barred from entering many industries. Barriers to
capital formation keep most private businesses from providing more
than a handful of jobs. There is growing pressure to change that.
Allowing the private sector to absorb the state's excess workers is
an obvious way to improve the economy. And there is a more pressing
reason rooted in Chinese nationalism: With World Trade Organization
membership threatening to open the domestic market wider in the
next five years, foreigners could take over a huge part of China's
economy unless it unleashes private entrepreneurs soon. By Craig S.
Smith.
</P>
