Maryland, far from the arid land that is the object of their bitter
dispute, the Israeli and Palestinian leaders began their fateful
peace summit at Camp David on Tuesday with the far-reaching, most
think improbable, goal of ending their 52-year-old conflict. On the
first day of an open-ended, secluded meeting, President Clinton
ushered the leaders, Prime Minister Ehud Barak of Israel and
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat, into the presidential retreat
where he hopes that the chemistry of the place and the moment can
induce a spirit of ``principled compromise'' that yields a
substantive peace agreement. By Deborah Sontag.
</P>
