<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-11 18:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9259 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-ESTATE-TAX-HNS &LR;      07-11 1066
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ESTATE-TAX-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     SENATE GEARS UP TO END ESTATE TAX; A LOOK AT WHO WOULD GAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARK HELM  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As the Senate moves toward repeal of the federal
estate tax, Republicans and Democrats are fighting a public
relations war over who would be helped by the measure. A look at
the numbers shows the answer is: very few.
</P>
<P>
   Republican leaders, who have gained the support of some
Democrats, argue that the tax prevents owners of family farms and
small businesses from passing along the enterprise to their
children.
</P>
<P>
   But William Gale, a senior fellow at the Brookings Institution,
a Washington think tank, says only about 2 percent of the estates
of people who die are large enough to be taxed and that very few of
these estates belong to farmers and small business people.
</P>
<P>
   ``This just isn't a tax that impacts your average family, or
even your upper middle class family except in a few rare cases,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   To give perspective, according to Gale and other tax experts,
the numbers for 1997 _ the latest available _ show that:
</P>
<P>
   _ Beneficiaries of fewer than 43,000 estates _ 1.9 percent of
the 2.3 million estates of people who died that year _ had to pay
any federal tax on the proceeds.
</P>
<P>
   _ Of the 43,000 estates taxed, about 5 percent _ or 2,400 _ paid
nearly half of the $28 billion collected in estate tax revenue that
year.
</P>
<P>
   _ Only about 1,300 farmers and small-business owners who died
left estates large enough to be taxed, and most of those estates
received special tax breaks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tax pretty much falls on the shoulders of a highly
concentrated group of rich families,'' Gale said.
</P>
<P>
   Iris Lav, an economist at the Center on Budget and Policy
Priorities, a Washington-based think tank, said repealing the
estate tax would be a ``windfall'' for the country's wealthiest
families.
</P>
<P>
   For example, she said, the 2,400 estates that paid nearly half
of all estate taxes in 1997 would have saved an average of $3.4
million each if the law had been repealed.
</P>
<P>
   ``To say repealing the estate tax is about helping farmers and
small business people just doesn't hold water when you look at the
numbers,'' Lav added.
</P>
<P>
   Under the current law, any estate worth more than $675,000 that
is left this year to a person other than an American citizen spouse
is subject to taxes that can run as high as 55 percent on the
amount above $675,000.
</P>
<P>
   However, an estate of any size may be bequeathed to a spouse
free of federal estate tax. The $675,000 figure is scheduled to
rise gradually until it reaches $1 million in 2006.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, each member of a married couple is entitled to the
basic $675,000 exemption. Thus, a couple can effectively exempt
$1.35 million from the estate tax this year, and the amount will go
to $2 million by 2006.
</P>
<P>
   In 1999, the estate and gift tax netted nearly $30 billion _
about 1.5 percent of federal revenue. By comparison, the gasoline
tax raised $39 billion, the individual income tax $879 billion and
the corporate income tax $185 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Democratic leaders plan to use the figures to convince
the public that the current law should not be repealed and is
needed to slow the trend toward a concentration of wealth.
</P>
<P>
   Ranit Schmelzer, a spokeswoman for Senate minority leader Thomas
Daschle of South Dakota, said in an interview Tuesday, ``Repealing
the estate tax is about helping a tiny number of very wealthy
people. In terms of farmers and small business owner, we're talking
about a very small slice of an already small slice of the overall
population.''
</P>
<P>
   To save the estate tax, the Democratic leadership has offered an
alternative bill that would lower the maximum tax rate from 55
percent to 44 percent and raise the exemption level from the
present $675,000 to $825,000.
</P>
<P>
   Schmelzer added that if the law needs to be changed to help
farmers and small-business owners, ``we would be all for it. But
Sen. Daschle and other Democratic leaders don't believe you need to
scrap the whole tax to help 3 percent of the people who pay it,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Schmelzer added that the estate tax already grants special
treatment, such as extended payment plans and special deductions,
to farmers and small business owners.
</P>
<P>
   But most Republicans _ and a significant number of Democrats _
argue that that the ``death tax,'' as they call it, unfairly
penalizes people for saving their money. It also hurts those
farmers and small business owners who pay large sums to lawyers and
estate planners to ensure they can pass their assets to their
children, the opponents say.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a perverse kind of tax,'' said Sen. John Kyl, R-Ariz.,
sponsor of the Senate bill to repeal the law. ``What is the
American dream? It's making sure you're children have a better
life.''
</P>
<P>
   That argument helped House Republicans persuade 65 Democrats to
support repealing the tax, garnering a lopsided 279-to-136 vote
last month. The House majority was enough to override President
Clinton's promised veto of the tax cut. But few believe that the
pro-repeal vote in the Senate, expected late this week, will be as
great.
</P>
<P>
   However, John Czwartacki, a spokesman for Senate Majority Leader
Trent Lott of Mississippi, said support for repeal has grown among
Democrats because the law is ``simply unfair.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that Uncle Sam reaches beyond the grave and takes
money away from a grieving family appalls every American,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Czwartacki added that the booming economy and the growing number
of people who own stock has changed the way Americans look at the
estate tax.
</P>
<P>
   ``Americans are beginning to realize that years of working hard
and saving to ensure a better life for their children can be
destroyed by the estate tax,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The number of taxpayers with annual incomes of $100,000 or more
soared to 8.3 million in 1998, up 15 percent from 7.2 million in
1997, according to the Internal Revenue Service.
</P>
<P>
   During the next 50 years, an estimated $30 trillion is projected
to change hands from one generation to the next in the United
States. This year Americans are expected to inherit close to $150
billion, according to a study by the Boston College Social Welfare
Research Institute.
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Helm can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address mark(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
