<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-11 18:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9261 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-NIRELAND-MARCHES-0712     07-11 0680
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NIRELAND-MARCHES-0712-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TENSE NORTHERN IRELAND AWAITS, BRACES FOR POTENTIAL TWELFTH OF
JULY FIREWORKS
 &HT;    With Photo.
 &HT;    By BERT ROUGHTON JR. 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTADOWN, Northern Ireland _ An estimated 80,000 Protestants
are expected to parade throughout Northern Ireland Wednesday to cap
off a deeply contentious period that has renewed sectarian violence
across the troubled province.
</P>
<P>
   In anticipation of the July 12 climax of the marching season,
thousands of bonfires were lit Tuesday night across the province,
which with armored cars patrolling neighborhoods has the feel of a
war zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Welcome to Beirut,'' said the cook at The Chip Wagon, a small
diner in Portadown. Down the road, a three-story stack of wooden
pallets and discarded furniture was being readied Tuesday afternoon
to be ignited. An Irish national flag topped the stack.
</P>
<P>
   The Protestant Orangemen celebrate the Twelfth of July in honor
of William of Orange's defeat of Catholic James II in 1690. The
victory secured Northern Ireland's position within the United
Kingdom, while the predominately Catholic south continued
struggling for independence until 1922 when the Republic of Ireland
was born.
</P>
<P>
   While members of the Orange Order say they are only celebrating
what for them is equivalent to the Fourth of July for Americans,
Catholics consider the marches triumphal shows of power by the
majority Protestants.
</P>
<P>
   Angered that they were forbidden by the government on July 2
from parading through two Catholic neighborhoods, the Orange Order
called for a province-wide protest. Protestants and their
supporters have engaged in a 10-day spree of violence and
disruptions.
</P>
<P>
   David Hillditch, a member of the Orange Order, told reporters
that the press has blown the disruptions out of proportion.
``Protests have been 90 percent peaceful,'' he said.
``Unfortunately a few of the hotspots have captured the
headlines.''
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, police used trained dogs to force a crowd of
Protestant loyalists to retreat from a barricade erected to block
marchers from entering the Catholic enclave near Drumcree.
Protestants have been outraged by the wall, which some have
compared to the Berlin Wall.
</P>
<P>
   After days of attacks on Catholic homes and businesses, a rural
Orange Order meeting hall was firebombed early Tuesday, sending six
Protestants to the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday afternoon, businesses in most towns and cities closed
early to give their employees a chance to get home before sunset.
By 4:30 p.m. (local time), downtown Belfast was nearly deserted.
</P>
<P>
   A leading clergyman warned that the violence threatened to spin
out of control. Patrick Walsh, the Bishop of Down and Conner, said:
``What is happening across the whole of Northern Ireland is
intolerable. We are in danger of sliding into anarchy.''
</P>
<P>
   Police have come under attack for not doing more to stop the
violence. Catholics say police haven't done enough to protect them
or to crack down on Orange protests. Scores of Catholic properties
have been attacked, including two churches in predominantly
Protestant towns.
</P>
<P>
   Ronnie Flanagan, the chief of the Royal Ulster Constabulary,
defended the actions of the police, but added that it was important
for police not provoke even stronger reactions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to judge each set of circumstances on its merits and
we have to behave proportionately,'' Flanagan said. ``Our officers
on the ground have to consider whether their intervention will make
things worse., so they have to decide how to intervene and when to
intervene.''
</P>
<P>
   Police hope that Wednesday will bring an end to the strife.
</P>
<P>
   Since July 2, authorities have recorded 280 attacks on security
forces, with 57 police officers and soldiers wounded, authorities
said Tuesday. Nearly 1,000 gasoline bombs have been seized, and 88
vehicles hijacked and burned. Police have arrested 146 suspected
rioters.
</P>
<P>
   (Bert Roughton Jr.'s E-mail address is: bertr(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
