<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-11 18:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9262 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-FASCIST-ARCHITECTURE-     07-11 1227
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASCIST-ARCHITECTURE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ITALIANS FINALLY APPRECIATING MUSSOLINI'S ARCHITECTURE 
</HEADLINE>
   By ALESSANDRA STANLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME _ In an inverted salute to Mussolini's dream of Fascism
through physical culture, the Stadio dei Marmi, a 1937 track
stadium ringed by colossal marble nude athletes is filled again _
this time by the Big Gym outdoor fitness center, a kaleidoscope of
skateboards, paddle tennis courts, aerobics classes, blaring pop
music and a two-story inflatable Pepsi can.
</P>
<P>
   Nearby, some of the most famous examples of Fascist architecture
show signs of neglect and decay, including the 25,000-foot-long
esplanade of mosaics that exalt Fascist conquests laid beneath a
towering obelisk inscribed, ``Mussolini Dux.''
</P>
<P>
   The Foro Italico, a sprawling 1930s sports complex that includes
the Stadio dei Marmi, is up for sale, part of a long inventory of
public buildings that the government is seeking to sell to reduce
its debt and meet European Union budget targets.
</P>
<P>
   Right-wing groups, including a small neofascist party, Movimento
Sociale Italiano, have papered the streets with leaflets and
posters that say, ``Hands off the Foro Mussolini,'' its original,
and still taboo, name.
</P>
<P>
   Alleanza Nazionale, a right-wing party that has severed its ties
to Fascism, calls it Foro Italico, in posters that scream,
``Culture cannot be sold!''
</P>
<P>
   Beneath the heated politics, however, the ado over the Foro
Italico signals a broader shift in Italian sensibilities. Fascist
architecture, long ignored or despised by most Italians as a
disturbing reminder of an ignoble period of their history, is
enjoying a comeback.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I started studying this architecture, people told me I
was crazy, that it was `ugly and fascist,''' Giorgio Muratore, a
professor of architecture at the University of Rome, said. ``It is
only recently that people are willing to say, `It's fascist, but it
is beautiful.'''
</P>
<P>
   Muratore has spent 30 years promoting a reappraisal of
architects like Luigi Moretti, a Mussolini follower who designed,
among other structures, a 1934 fencing pavilion, the Casa della
Scherma, which is considered the architectural jewel of the Foro
Italico. In 1981, the Justice Ministry took over the building to
hold members of the Red Brigade terrorist group and remains a
high-security courthouse, pending its sale. Moretti, who died in
1973, also designed the Watergate Hotel in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Foreigners have long vaunted the ingenuity and daring of the
Fascist architects, who sought to blend the classicism of ancient
Rome with 20th-century functionalism and rationalism. Architecture
was Mussolini's favorite mode of propaganda, and he commissioned
monumental projects like the Foro Italico and E.U.R., a vast state
office park that includes the stark Palazzo della Civilta del
Lavoro, known as the square Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   ``These architects were young, they were convinced Fascists,''
said Giorgio Ciucci, an architectural historian who heads the
National Academy of St. Luke here. ``It was a revolutionary
movement based on youth and radical change. Architects were the
interpreters of the revolution.''
</P>
<P>
   All over Italy, post offices, railway stations and entire towns
like Sabaudia, a seaside resort, reflect the grandiosity, but also
the boldness, of a totalitarian regime that took power in 1922 and
ended in 1943, when Mussolini was overthrown. He and his mistress
were executed in 1945 and hanged by their feet in a square in
Milan.
</P>
<P>
   From the end of World War II until recently, much Italian
thinking on Fascist architecture was molded by Bruno Zevi, a Jewish
architectural critic who fled the Fascists' racial laws in 1940,
returned to Italy in 1945 and, until his death in January,
pilloried architectural classicism, modern and even ancient, as the
reflection of oppression and totalitarianism. He often said, only
half-jokingly, that the ``square Colosseum'' should be blown up.
</P>
<P>
   Ordinary Italians, awash in ancient ruins and medieval,
Renaissance and Baroque treasures, mostly ignored or mocked Fascist
buildings as exemplars of bad taste. The reappraisal by
intellectuals began in earnest in the early 1990s, when the end of
the Cold War eased the the fierce politicalization of architecture,
and Fascism as a viable political movement seemed long dead.
</P>
<P>
   Younger critics and professors began detaching aesthetics from
the taint of ideology. Exhibitions, retrospectives, history books
and tourist guides signaled revived interest. In 1996, Sergio
Poretti, a professor of architecture at the University of Rome,
began publishing Do.co.mo.mo, an artsy biannual journal devoted
entirely to Fascist art and architecture.
</P>
<P>
   The controversy over the Foro Italico, however, has sparked a
more general re-evaluation of Fascist architecture. The property,
which includes the Stadio Olimpico, the largest soccer stadium
here, could bring in as much as $490 million, according to some
estimates. At least five groups, including American investment
companies, are vying to be selected to help the Italian treasury
broker the sale.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the treasury selected a division of American
Appraisal Holding, the Italian branch of American Appraisal
Associates of Milwaukee to help it assess the Foro Italico market
value.
</P>
<P>
   The property is being managed by the Italian National Olympic
Committee, which uses many of the sports areas for training. The
Stadio dei Marmi is being used by Big Gym, a fitness company, under
a summer lease.
</P>
<P>
   The center-right opposition seized the sale as a political
bludgeon, complaining that foreigners could end up erecting
McDonald's arches over a chunk of modern Italian history.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's absurd,'' Alessandra Mussolini, a granddaughter of the
dictator, said. ``It's not just a part of history. It's a part of
Rome.''
</P>
<P>
   Mussolini, a member of Parliament for Alleanza Nazionale, said
she had no problems with the Foro Italico's style _ or history. ``I
like everything Fascist, and especially the architecture,'' she
said. ``I live in a 1930s building.''
</P>
<P>
   Culture Minister Giovanna Melandri said most of the 16 Foro
Italico lots were labeled historic sites, which, under Italian law,
sharply limits their use and alterations. That did not mollify
critics on the right or left.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not enough to say, `We imposed so many conditions on the
sale that no one will want to buy it,''' Muratore, a Communist,
said. ``The Italian state should say that the Foro Italico, like
the Colosseum, is not for sale.''
</P>
<P>
   A new generation of Italians seem to like the look of the Foro
Italico, without worrying about its provenance.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's beautiful, imposing, it's majestic,'' Maria Rosaria
Iorio, 20, a major in political science at the University of Rome,
said as she gazed up at the Stadio dei Marmi while awaiting
aerobics class.
</P>
<P>
   Neither she nor her friend Luisa De Vita, 19, was sure when or
why it was built. ``I don't think its ancient,'' Iorio said.
``Maybe 19th or 20th century.''
</P>
<P>
   Told that it was built under Mussolini, the women shrugged.
</P>
<P>
   ``We studied him in school, and he didn't only do bad things,''
Iorio said. ``He built a lot of towns and schools.''
</P>
<P>
   De Vita agreed, saying: ``We have gotten so used to skyscrapers
and glass office towers, but this is closer to our roots. It's
classical, but with a modern feel.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
