<HEADER>
A9268 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-EDITORIAL-SYPHILIS-BO     07-11 0387
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-SYPHILIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE END OF SYPHILIS? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In most industrialized countries, a combination of penicillin
and sound public-health work has virtually eliminated syphilis. Not
so in the United States, but the Centers for Disease Control and
Prevention believes it could be done here for just $15 million.
Congress should quickly approve the funds, so that a historic
opportunity is not lost.
</P>
<P>
   For reasons that scientists do not understand, syphilis goes
through seven- to 10-year cycles of low and high incidence. After a
peak in 1990 of 50,000 new cases in the United States, in 1999 it
was at its lowest recorded incidence in the nation's history, just
7,000 new cases. Aiding the elimination effort is the fact that the
disease is concentrated geographically _ just 25 of the nation's
3,100 counties account for about half of all cases.
</P>
<P>
   The CDC believes that with a concerted effort now, at the low
point of the cycle, the disease could be driven down to 1,000 cases
scattered across the country, virtually eliminating it. Lacking a
vaccine, officials have no hope of eradicating it altogether, but
free testing, penicillin treatment, and notification of sexual
partners have been effective in fighting it.
</P>
<P>
   Limiting its incidence to small outbreaks, as European countries
have done, would be a triumph. Left untreated, late-stage syphilis
can wreak havoc on a range of organs. Pregnant women can pass it on
to their unborn children, many of whom die. Babies born with it are
often blind or mentally retarded. Syphilis greatly increases HIV
infection rates.
</P>
<P>
   There would undoubtedly be more pressure to fund the CDC's $15
million request if it were not for the demographics of syphilis,
which is concentrated among low-income African-Americans. Treatment
for the disease has no celebrity advocates as do breast and
prostate cancer, AIDS, and Parkinson's.
</P>
<P>
   There is also sentiment on Capitol Hill to divert some of the
$15 million toward greater efforts against other, more common
sexually transmitted diseases, such as chlamydia and human
papillomavirus. All STDs deserve increased funding, but it would be
criminal to miss this chance to make syphilis a disease of the
country's past and not its future.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-11-00 1845EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000711.0237 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-11 18:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9269 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-FFLIGHTSERV-COX     07-11 1757
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FFLIGHTSERV-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Internet Air charter provider feeling lack of funding
 &HT;    By Russell Grantham
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA - An Internet air charter provider said its fortunes
won't get airborne again until it finds money to replace $5 million
promised by one backer who reneged.
</P>
<P>
   ``We recognize the frustration that you guys must be feeling,''
company President Todd Bottorff told about a dozen investors
Tuesday at the company's annual meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Bottorff, 32, who joined the company two months ago, was
alluding to flightserv's climb from 25 cents a share to $12 a share
over 15 months, then its dive to as low as 25 cents since March.
Flightserv.com's shares closed Tuesday at about 44 cents a share.
</P>
<P>
   Bottorff said his focus is keeping expenses down and finding
capital to market the company's business, which connects business
travelers with empty seats on private chartered jets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Day one, when I got on board, we were all vigorously pursuing
that capital,'' he said. ``That is an area that has been
significantly under-emphasized.''
</P>
<P>
   Bottorff was named president and chief operating officer in May,
replacing C. Beverly Lance as president.
</P>
<P>
   Lance remains flightserv.com's chief executive officer.
</P>
<P>
   As with many Internet firms, flightserv.com's hunt for new cash
got tougher after the recent bear market for tech companies spooked
investors from many start-ups with negative cash flows and unproven
business models.
</P>
<P>
   Flightserv.com launched its ``Private Seats'' service between
Atlanta's Peachtree-DeKalb Airport and Teterboro Airport near New
York City about two months ago, with plans to serve up to 100
cities in a year.
</P>
<P>
   But company officials said flightserv.com's plans stalled after
Bahamas-based Acqua Wellington Value Fund Ltd. didn't honor the
second part of an agreement to invest $10 million by the end of
February.
</P>
<P>
   After investing $5 million in January, Acqua Wellington
``effectively reneged'' on its promise to invest more, said
flightserv Chairman Arthur Weiss.
</P>
<P>
   ``They didn't put it in, and we didn't have the money to put
into (a marketing) plan,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The company said it is ``evaluating'' whether to take legal
action against Acqua Wellington.
</P>
<P>
   Acqua Wellington officials could not be reached.
</P>
<P>
   Flightserv.com has averaged about one flight a week of one or
two passengers who manage to find its Web site at
www.flightserv.com, Bottorff said. ``I think the last flight we had
is about two weeks ago.''
</P>
<P>
   He said a strategic alliance announced last month with
Atlanta-based Worldspan offers the chance to market flightserv's
services through more than 20,000 travel agents. The electronic
travel information service is owned by units of Delta Air Lines,
Northwest Airlines and Trans World Airlines.
</P>
<P>
   Flightserv.com is in ``advanced discussions with a few funding
parties'' to provide new capital infusion, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Flightserv.com has ``a long way to go,'' said investor Matthew
J. Lee, director of reservations sales for AirTran. ``It's a novel
idea. They've oposals aimed at assisting low-income Americans.
</P>
<P>
   `DO-NOTHING-CONGRESS' COUNTER-TOUR
</P>
<P>
   Continuing his attack on what he calls a ``do-nothing-for-people
Republican Congress'' beholden to special interests, Al Gore said
today that the same ``wealthy special interests'' financing George
W. Bush's campaign are blocking progress in Congress on health and
minimum-wage legislation. ``What's going on in Washington is that
this Congress has failed to pass legislation that has very strong
bipartisan support,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   DON'T MESS WITH THE JUDGE
</P>
<P>
   It was Judge Judy who followed Al Gore's appearance on NBC's
``Today'' show this morning for an interview, and TV's famously
cantankerous courtroom judge wasn't too happy. Judy Sheindlin (her
real name) started by complaining that she'd arrived hungry and
looking forward to the ``green room'' treats, but that Gore and his
entourage had taken it over for security reasons. Judge Judy, to
host Matt Lauer: ``I think that the vice president ought to get me
a muffin. In fact, I think he should get me several muffins.'' An
apologetic Gore returned to the set with a loaded muffin tray,
knelt down on a knee and offered her a muffin. Still, she was
uncommittal about her vote.
</P>
<P>
   LOOKING FOR A LATE-INNING RALLY
</P>
<P>
   With the National Governors' Association concluding its four-day
meeting, Democratic state executives reportedly were conceding that
George W. Bush has emerged from the early stages of the campaign
the more likable candidate, hence his slight lead in national
polls. The trend has them concerned but not panicked, according to
The Associated Press. They say Al Gore will recover when voters
focus on issues. Bush's folksy style plays well when voters aren't
paying attention, the governors said, but Gore's intensity and
seriousness should be a better fit when the campaign heats up.
</P>
<P>
   GO AHEAD, HE DARES YOU
</P>
<P>
   Democrats would likely have to write off Pennsylvania, a key
battleground state they won in the last two presidential elections,
if Gov. Tom Ridge becomes George W. Bush's running mate, President
Clinton said. ``It would be a lot harder to carry it with (Ridge)on
the ticket,'' Clinton told the Patriot-News of Harrisburg after
speaking to the National Governors' Association meeting in State
College. Ridge, an abortion-rights supporter, is anathema to many
in the Republican Party's core constituency.
</P>
<P>
   IT MUST BE THOSE JUICED-UP BASEBALLS
</P>
<P>
   House Republicans reported that they have raised $90 million so
far this election cycle _ almost as much as they collected for the
entire 1998 election. Party officials said they are on track to
raise a record $125 million by the end of the year. On the other
side, House Democrats reported raising $60 million during the
previous 18 months _ more than the $42 million raised during the
entire 1997-98 election cycle.
</P>
<P>
   SPEND IT OR LOSE IT
</P>
<P>
   As they prepare to accept their parties' presidential
nominations, both George W. Bush and Al Gore are draining their
campaign treasuries. Most of it will be spent on staff, travel and
expenses associated with the upcoming national party conventions.
Bush also is developing a last-minute TV advertising campaign.
After the conventions, neither candidate will be permitted to raise
or spend private money, except to pay legal and accounting costs.
Instead, each will receive $67.6 million in taxpayer funds to
finance their fall campaigns. Bush had $7.1 million on hand as of
May 31; Gore had $9.6 million.
</P>
<P>
   ADS DOING DOUBTFUL JOB
</P>
<P>
   A month after beginning a multimillion-dollar TV ad campaign, Al
Gore is still languishing in the polls, seemingly unable to stir
the enthusiasm of apathetic voters. The Democratic National
Committee has spent about $11 million on the ads in 17 states, but
there has been little apparent movement.etween 5 and 13 percentage
points nationally.
</P>
<P>
   MEANWHILE, BACK IN TEXAS
</P>
<P>
   One thing George W. Bush has known in his more than five years
as governor of Texas is prosperity. But now Texas is facing a
budget shortfall as high as $750 million, fueled by deficits in
Medicaid and other state programs and rising costs for prison
inmates, according to the Houston Chronicle. The Legislative Budget
Board was meeting privately with state budget officials to plan an
emergency appropriations bill for January. Rob Junell, chairman of
the House Appropriations Committee, said the state's economy will
provide enough new revenues to cover the shortfall. State Democrats
are blaming the shortfall on Bush's insistence on a huge tax cut.
</P>
<P>
   TO BE CONTACTED IS TO BE IN THE GAME
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Rep. John Kasich's staff wanted it known that their boss
has been approached in regard to the Republican running mate
search. The Ohioan was asked to provide background information to
former Defense Secretary Dick Cheney, who is heading George W.
Bush's search effort, said Kasich spokesman Bruce Cuthbertson.
Kasich told the Columbus Dispatch: ``I have been contacted. That is
all I will say, period.'' Kasich, 48, is not running for
re-election.
</P>
<P>
   POWER PLANTS AND SENATE POWER
</P>
<P>
   Hillary Clinton, who has made lower utility rates a cornerstone
pledge of her Senate campaign, criticized the New York state
government for allowing the construction of new power plants along
the Hudson River without having a plan to assess demand. She also
said that New York's attempt to deregulate utility costs has not
been as successful as neighboring states', and that New York has a
``bottleneck'' bureaucratic system that's stunting competition
among power companies. Clinton called the upstate region's economy
her ``No. 1 priority'' if elected.
</P>
<P>
   REVAMPED CONVENTION
</P>
<P>
   Education, Social Security and the need for an inclusive party
are among the major themes of this year's Republican National
Convention, organizers say. George W. Bush wants to emphasize these
issues although they are more often discussed at Democratic events.
He wants to project a different image of Republicans to the nation
during the July 31-Aug. 3 convention in Philadelphia. ``Ours will
be a different kind of convention for a different kind of
Republican,'' said convention co-chairman Andrew Card.
</P>
<P>
   DE-FENSE! DE-FENSE!
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore, typing answers to online questions on the Washington
Post Web site, said the failure of a test for a national missile
defense system doesn't mean the idea is doomed, but he criticized
the version supported by opponent George W. Bush as ``more
expensive and less likely to work.'' Bush has said he's determined
to push ahead toward a missile defense system to protect the United
States and its allies even if Russia opposes it as a violation of
the 1972 Anti-Ballistic Missile Treaty. Gore wants Russia to amend
the treaty to allow a more limited system covering the 50 states.
</P>
<P>
   GIRLS JUST WANNA HAVE FUN
</P>
<P>
   Tipper Gore says her penchant for spontaneity and desire for fun
will continue even if her husband is elected and she becomes first
lady. Otherwise, ``It could be an isolating life, if you weren't
careful about that,'' she said in a Washington Post interview.
Tipper Gore once agreed to an an event in New Mexico so she could
ride in a hot air balloon, and in Florida her staff made a detour
so she could ride Space Mountain at Disney World three times.
</P>
<P>
   _ Compiled by Ernie Freda from staff and news reports.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
