<HEADER>
A9270 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-EDITORIAL-DEFENSE-BOS     07-11 0394
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-DEFENSE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEFLATED MISSILE DEFENSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If taxpayers are being asked to spend $60 billion or more on a
national missile defense that may not be able to defend the nation
against intercontinental ballistic missiles, then aren't proponents
of the unworkable system degrading the nation's defense?
</P>
<P>
   This question arises following the mechanical failure of last
week's missile interceptor test.
</P>
<P>
   Its scientific critics contend that the crucial flaws of the
system that failed in last weekend's test flight have nothing to do
with the things that went awry during that trial run. It ought to
be possible to make the missile interceptor separate from its
booster rocket, the critics assume, and there is no reason to
believe the one balloon accompanying the target warhead will not
inflate properly in future tests.
</P>
<P>
   But Saturday's uninflated balloon does serve as a road sign
pointing to the fundamental incapacity of the proposed system to do
what it will be asked to do. MIT physics professor Ted Postol, an
experienced specialist in the field of missile defense, has
analyzed data from the first fly-by test of the system and found
that the infrared sensors on its exoatmospheric kill vehicle could
not discriminate between warheads and simple countermeasures.
</P>
<P>
   When they do inflate outside the atmosphere, inexpensive mylar
balloon decoys can confound the technology of the infrared sensor _
provided that the light they emit is not much brighter than the
light emitted by a warhead hiding among hundreds of decoys that any
missile-making regime will be able to deploy. The balloon that
didn't inflate in Saturday's test flight was the only decoy
accompanying the warhead to be intercepted. It had a blatantly
different shape, and its brightness was so different from the
warhead's that the kill vehicle's sensor could hardly mistake one
for the other. In a word, the test was rigged; even if it had
succeeded, it would have proved nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Before heedless politicians and defense contractors stampede
Americans into paying for a system that may make the nation less
secure, the capabilities of the proposed system should be evaluated
by distinguished scientists who are truly independent.
</P>
<P>
   Haste, in this case, risks the greatest waste.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
