<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-NY-COWS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUT FIBERGLASS COWS OUT TO PASTURE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (REPEATING to add photo note)  
 (Attn: N.J., Conn., Ill., Switzerland)  (ART ADV:  Photos NYT5, -6, -7  are being sent to NYT photo
clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By SARAH BOXER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It's time to rain on the CowParade, the influx of
painted bovine forms that has been choking the sidewalks and parks
of New York City, Stamford, Conn., and West Orange, N.J., since
mid-June. The 500 New York cows and their suburban cousins won't be
leaving until fall, when they will be auctioned off for charity.
</P>
<P>
   COMPLAINT NO. 1: These cows are un-American. Most American cows
have their horns removed at birth. These cows, which have both
udders and horns, are Swiss milking cows.
</P>
<P>
   NO. 2: Herd mentality. Zurich had the first cow parade, Cows on
Parade, in 1998 (800 cows). Chicago got the second one, in 1999,
after a shoe salesman from Chicago saw the Zurich cow parade and
decided his city had to have a bovine event, too. (Chicago had 340
cows.) In 1999 CowParade Holdings, the for-profit corporation that
owns licensing rights to CowParade and Cows on Parade, asked the
New York City Parks Commissioner, Henry J. Stern, and Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani if New York wanted one. Sure, they said. So now New York
is copying Chicago, a cow town, and Switzerland, a cow country.
</P>
<P>
   NO. 3: Cowmerce. Each cow has been commissioned by a sponsor: a
corporation, community organization, individual or business,
including Hooters, Yahoo, The New York Times and a couple of
steakhouses. For $7,500 the sponsor chooses an artist to paint its
cow or selects a design that was submitted during an open call for
artists earlier this year. After publicizing the event through arts
organizations and news releases, CowParade received some 1,200
designs.
</P>
<P>
   NO. 4: Bad cow disease. During the open call, three cows were
rejected _ the Moonica Lewinsky cow, the Hasidic cow and a cow
covered with butcher's marks and unbecoming remarks about butchery
designed by People for the Ethical Treatment of Animals.
</P>
<P>
   NO. 5: Moonotonous. Every cow is made of 100 pounds of
fiberglass that has been molded into one of three poses: standing
(head up), grazing (head down) and supine. All cows were made by
Silvestri Inc. in Los Angeles, or by the Resource Factory in
Sarasota, Fla., both manufacturers of fiberglass figures. The only
acts left to the artists who are picked by the sponsors are
painting, decorating and naming their cows. A cow floating on its
back in an inner tube near the McGraw-Hill building looked like the
work of an udder renegade.
</P>
<P>
   NO. 6: Cowmeras. Too many tourists taking too many pictures.
</P>
<P>
   NO. 7: Puns for names. Tutancowmon, Cowapatra, Cowlerina,
Cowleidoscope, Cowmooter, Taxi Cow (used five times), Picowsso
(three times), Moondrian (twice), Mootisse (once), MooMa (four
times), Moo York (a dozen times), Moomaid, Moo Indigo, MooShoe and
Herd on the Street (three times). Toss in the requisite Holy Cows
(used twice) and Sacred Cows (seven times), and you get the
picture. These cows are a public moosance.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
