<HEADER>
A9273 &Cx1f; tab-z
u k BC-LILEKS-NADER-NEWHOUSE     07-11 0869
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LILEKS-NADER-NEWHOUSE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A LOOK BEHIND THE CURTAIN AT NADER AND HIS MERRY GREENS 
</HEADLINE>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: This article from NEWHOUSE NEWS SERVICE for
Tuesday, July 11, is available as a ``separate-buy.'' For
information about purchasing the article, contact DEBRA WEYDERT of
The New York Times Syndicate at 1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697;
e-mail: weyded nytimes.com.) 
 By JAMES LILEKS  
 c.2000 Newhouse News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's a fondness for Nader on the left. He's morally pure and
utterly upright; his Ichabody thinness underscores his ascetic
devotion to The Cause. He has substantial, tangible
accomplishments. Seatbelts. Safety glass. Mandatory
child-decapitation systems in cars, also known as airbags. The
enshrinement of the trial lawyer as the arbiter of social justice.
... Well, let's back up a bit.
</P>
<P>
   There's a fondness for Nader on the left. Seatbelts!
</P>
<P>
   And so much more. But if Nader regards the Dems as a pallid
reflection of contemporary liberalism, what does his new party, the
Greens, desire? Just visit their Web site, www.greenparty.org, and
read the merry platform. They want your money, your job, your
freedom and your car. In return you get industrial hemp and really
bad TV.
</P>
<P>
   Here are a few of their, ah, provocative demands:
</P>
<P>
   A six-hour work day with no cut in pay. (The government gives
you a ``second paycheck'' to make up the difference.) One-year paid
educational leave for every seven years worked. ``Federally
financed universal health care'' _ five words that spell utter,
irrevocable, national insolvency. Free child care. Free education
through graduate school. Yes, that's what will make America strong:
more graduate students. Guaranteed family income of at least
$26,000 per year for a mother with three children, with an extra
$3,250 per child.
</P>
<P>
   How to pay for this stuff? Nader's party has that figured out,
too. Simple: ``Build into the progressive income tax a 100 percent
tax on all income over 10 times the minimum wage.'' In the amusing
world of the Nader party, people will still work hard and produce
the excess revenue even if it's taxed at 100 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Having ruined the economy, Nader's party will ruin your
evenings: ``Re-appropriate six prime-time hours a day of commercial
broadcast time on each station for real public service
broadcasting.'' Wonderful: mandatory cable-access.
</P>
<P>
   Here's your new schedule: 4-5 p.m.: Cartoon hour. Today: Tom and
Jerry mend their differences through mediation and visualized
peace-based scenarios. 5-6 p.m.: PETA presents the Dinnertime
Parade of Slaughterhouse Horrors. 7-10 p.m.: Blurry, underlit video
of people with tremendous BO talking about hemp. A tax on the
broadcasters would pay for this programming. Of course, after six
months of this dreck, the broadcasters would have no revenue to pay
the taxes _ and that's when Nader's party would happily nationalize
them.
</P>
<P>
   If they hadn't been already demolished.
</P>
<P>
   The platform of Nader's party would ``require breakup of any
firm with more than 10 percent market share unless it makes a
compelling case every five years in a public regulatory
proceeding.'' It's Naderism taken to its logical conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   As is the next plank: ``Mandatory break-up'' of ``the largest
500 U.S. industrial and commercial corporations.'' Good _ take
that, GM! Take that, Microsoft! Let the small businessperson have a
shot, right? Well, the next plank breaks them up, too. Nader's
party calls for the ``Democratic Conversion of Small and Medium
Businesses'' to ``democratic public enterprises'' or co-ops.
</P>
<P>
   It would be voluntary, of course. It's always voluntary at
first. It's always ``voluntary'' until no one goes along. Then the
Citizen's Committee for Economic Security steps in, and it's time
to oil up the guillotine.
</P>
<P>
   But this wouldn't happen right away. Nader's party would have
its hands full with other projects. Again, reading from the
platform: ``Shut down waste incinerators, phase out landfills, and
phase in full recycling.'' Done! ``Abolish the disproportional,
aristocratic U.S. Senate.'' Done! ``Phase out fossil fuels and
phase in clean renewable energy sources.'' Your wish is our
command. Done!
</P>
<P>
   So much for the first day of the rule of Nader's party. It would
get around to abolishing perfume and scented shampoo, but that
would require working more than six hours. Leave that for Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   And there's still the educational system to fix. Nader's party
is ready to tackle the real enemy: us. ``We support a democratic
public school curriculum ... that replaces Eurocentric with
multicultural textbooks...''
</P>
<P>
   Huzzah: no more Eurocentricism. No more of those ridiculous
European ideas. Bring on the caste system of India, the infanticide
of China, the child-sex industry of Southeast Asia, the polygamy
and homophobia of sub-Saharan Africa, the misogyny of
fundamentalist Islam. In other words, get rid of European beliefs
that have made multicultural societies possible, and replace them
with a constellation of backward, irrational monocultural beliefs
that keep the rest of the world poor and oppressed.
</P>
<P>
   Nice work, Ralph. But of course it's not your platform. It's
just your party.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-11-00 1851EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
