<SLUG> BC-MARKET-NYT </SLUG>
  
 DOW GAINS FOR 3rd STRAIGHT SESSION  
 By KENNETH N. GILPIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Dow Jones industrial average rose for a third
consecutive session Tuesday, lifted by continued good earnings news
from old-line cyclical companies and optimism that the Federal
Reserve may have finished raising interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   Led by International Paper, which reported better-than-expected
second-quarter results Tuesday, and Alcoa, which beat Wall Street
estimates on Monday, the Dow gained 80.61 points, or 0.8 percent,
to 10,727.19.
</P>
<P>
   ``International Paper and Alcoa sort of set the tone and brought
back a lot of the cyclical areas of the market,'' said James
Paulson, chief investment officer at Wells Capital Management.
``Technology stocks faded late in the day, but by and large most of
the market was pretty strong.''
</P>
<P>
   Strength in cyclical stocks as well as good performances from
drug, oil services and integrated oil companies led the Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500 index, which rose 5.26 points, or 0.4 percent, to
1,480.88.
</P>
<P>
   Technology stocks did not fare so well.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq composite index fell 23.87 points, or 0.6 percent, to
3,956.42. JDS Uniphase, which fell for a second consecutive day,
and Yahoo were among the biggest losers.
</P>
<P>
   Worries about second-quarter earnings helped to drag Yahoo down
4{, to 105{. But after the market closed, the company reported
earnings that beat Wall Street estimates by 2 cents a share. After
hours, Yahoo rebounded and traded as high as 114.
</P>
<P>
   International Paper was among the best-performing Dow stocks. It
surged 3[, to 35 1/16. And Alcoa rose for a second consecutive
session, closing at 32{, up 3.
</P>
<P>
   The gains spilled over into other so-called cyclical stocks. The
Morgan Stanley Cyclical Index jumped 11.53 points, to 492.16.
</P>
<P>
   ``Concern about an unfriendly Fed is persistently coming out of
the market,'' said Jonathan Olesky, head of block trading at Morgan
Stanley Dean Witter. ``That is causing investors to show interest
in rate-sensitive areas like papers, chemicals, metals and autos.
It has been a pretty broad move.''
</P>
<P>
   Financial service stocks, which would also stand to benefit if
the Fed stops raising interest rates, also did well Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Citigroup rose 1|, to 66~. Merrill Lynch gained 2 13/16, to 129.
And Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette rose 2[, to 47{.
</P>
<P>
   Integrated oil and oil services stocks did well after BP Amoco
announced a sharp increase in capital spending for the next three
years.
</P>
<P>
   Schlumberger, a chief supplier to BP Amoco, gained 6 5/64, to 74
61/64. Halliburton rose 4 47/64, to 46 49/64. And Baker Hughes
gained 3 29/32, to 34\.
</P>
<P>
   Among the big oil companies, BP Amoco gained 1 3/16, to 51 5/16.
And Exxon Mobil closed at 80 9/16, up 2 7/16.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-11-00 1859EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000711.0244 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-11 19:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9278 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-SF-AIDS-HNS &LR;      07-11 0834
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SF-AIDS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     LAWMAKER URGES 25 PERCENT CUT IN S.F. AIDS FUNDING 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JUDY HOLLAND  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Government investigators told Congress Tuesday that
San Francisco gets nearly twice the federal AIDS funding per
patient than other cities receive, a finding that a key Republican
lawmaker said was indefensible.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Tom Coburn, R-Okla., said research by the General
Accounting Office showed that San Francisco receives $5,958 in
federal Ryan White program money for each AIDS case, while 50 other
cities hard hit by the epidemic receive an average of $3,000.
Coburn called for slashing the city's share by 25 percent over five
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we need to do is make sure that the black teenager with
HIV in my district has access to the same funding as someone living
in the middle of San Francisco,'' Coburn told the House
subcommittee on health and environment. The panel is drafting the
House version of the five-year Ryan White program, which
</P>
<P>
   will then be melded into a compromise with the Senate-passed
version.
</P>
<P>
   The Ryan White program provides federal aid for medication and
health care for people who don't have private insurance but who
aren't poor enough to qualify for Medicaid.
</P>
<P>
   Legislation sponsored by Coburn and Rep. Henry Waxman, D-Calif.,
would cut San Francisco's share by $4.5 million over five years,
from $35 million a year to $31.5 million, according to
congressional staffers, unless Congress dramatically increases
total funding for the program.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to focus on eliminating disparities in service,''
Waxman said.
</P>
<P>
   Coburn said the current formula essentially pays for San
Francisco residents who have already died of the disease.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't defend that,'' Coburn said. ``No one can defend
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Janet Heinrich, associate director of the GAO _ the
investigative arm of Congress _ told the panel that the HIV/AIDS
epidemic is spreading to woman and children and that the geographic
focus of the disease is becoming more diffuse.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Claude Earl Fox, administrator of the federal Health
Resources and Services Administration, which runs the program,
agreed there is a need to reexamine how the funds are doled out.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of inequities,'' Fox testified. ``We agree you
should not be disadvantaged by where you live.''
</P>
<P>
   But he added: ``We do believe that communities should be
protected from these funding shifts. We do not want to see huge
disruptions in funding.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Anna Eshoo, D-Calif., said a 25 percent cut in San
Francisco's AIDS funding would be ``potentially devastating.''
</P>
<P>
   Eshoo said it would amount to ``an abrupt pulling out of the rug
from under the program. It would leave the Bay Area without a
safety net.''
</P>
<P>
   Eshoo said the ``tidy, cookie-cutter numbers game they have put
out'' is misleading. She said the GAO report fails to consider that
many people with AIDS live longer than 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   Eshoo complained that the distribution formula undercounts the
number of people with AIDS because it assumes that people with the
disease will die within 10 years of being diagnosed. But, as a
result of new drug therapies, AIDS patients are living longer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Bay Area is being penalized for keeping people healthy,''
Eshoo said.
</P>
<P>
   Fred Dillon, public policy director for the San Francisco AIDS
Foundation, who attended the hearing, said afterward that the
city's per-patient cost is higher than other places because the
cost of living there is so inflated.
</P>
<P>
   Dillon also said San Francisco needs more federal funding
because of the high concentration of people with AIDS in the city _
51 cases per 100,000, the fourth highest in the country behind New
York City, Fort Lauderdale and Miami, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   When the Ryan White program began in 1991, payments to
communities were based on a formula that took into account a city's
total number of AIDS cases, both living and dead. San Francisco's
share of the money was relatively large because the epidemic had
started there a decade earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Congress changed the funding formula in 1996 to base the
distribution of money on the number of living AIDS patients. This
step would have slashed San Francisco's funding, except Congress
specifically limited the cuts to avoid damaging existing programs.
</P>
<P>
   Jeanne White, the mother of Ryan White, the hemophiliac teenager
from Kokomo, Ind., who contracted the disease through tainted blood
and died in 1990 at age 19, choked back tears and urged Congress to
``keep this program strong.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I witnessed first hand the ravages of this disease'' she said.
``As a mother, I just wanted to reach out and make everything
better, but I couldn't.''
</P>
<P>
   She said the Care Act ``makes real Ryan's dream of compassion
Ryan never understood those who wanted to deny care to people with
AIDS.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Judy Holland can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address judy &LR; hearstdc.com).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-11-00 1906EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
