<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-DUCASSE-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DINNER FOR 4 AT DUCASSE AND A $1,500 BILL TO PROVE IT 
</HEADLINE>
   By WILLIAM GRIMES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The signing of the check at Alain Ducasse is a
special moment. No matter how lively the chatter at the table has
been, a hush descends, and tense faces regard the slick, itemized
printout in their midst with unfeigned awe. With exquisite timing,
a waiter appears and holds up a velvet display board containing a
dozen finely made pens. It's hard not to feel that you are about to
sign a document imposing humiliating terms of surrender. It's a
measure of the delicacy at Ducasse that you are allowed to do it in
high style.
</P>
<P>
   With the arrival of Alain Ducasse at the Essex House, a new era
in New York dining has begun. It is far too early to draw any
conclusions about the food. But the style, the rituals and the
price structure are already in place. Dining at Ducasse is like
learning to eat all over again. New Yorkers are falling all over
themselves to take lessons.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing gets New York's blood up like the challenge of an
unattainable reservation. It's like a dripping hunk of red meat
hung just out of reach of a pack of howling dogs. That's exactly
what Ducasse offered when he announced, some months ago, that he
and his eight-star Michelin reputation would be taking up residence
in the Essex House, in the dining rooms of what used to be Les
Celebrites. Getting in would be half the challenge. The restaurant
seats 65, and there would be one seating a night. Lunch would be
offered twice a week. The restaurant would be closed on weekends.
</P>
<P>
   The second half of the challenge would be the bill. In a bold
see-you, raise-you move, Ducasse declared that his prix-fixe would
cost $160, far more than even the most expensive four-star
Manhattan restaurants. As it turned out, the a la carte menu also
scaled new heights. Appetizers reached the thrilling $50 level.
Entrees toyed with $75, then mincingly retreated to $74. The
message was clear: if you wanted to dine at Ducasse, money would be
no object. But then, it would be a meal cooked by the world's most
celebrated chef.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, Ducasse understood a thing or two about marketing. The
moment the phone and fax lines at Ducasse were plugged in, the rush
was on. Within days, the waiting list for a table was reported to
be 2,700 names long. Faithful patrons of Ducasse's restaurants in
Europe have first call on the tables. At the moment, the restaurant
is not taking reservations. Tables are booked through October, and
November reservations cannot be made until Aug. 1. Anyone lucky
enough to secure a reservation must leave a credit-card deposit of
$150 a person.
</P>
<P>
   Die-hard foodies were staring straight into the abyss. Like
everyone else, I was on the outside looking in. In order to remain
anonymous, I have to make reservations in the guise of an ordinary
diner (and sign the bill with a pseudonym as well). But ordinary
diners, at the moment, have less than a snowball's chance of
landing a table at Ducasse.
</P>
<P>
   After I'd spent a week scratching my head over the problem and
making no progress, fate intervened. An acquaintance who had
finagled a table by posing as a longtime Ducasse patron decided
that his credit card might not be up to the near-decathlon trial of
strength that it would face at the restaurant. Would I care to step
into the breach?
</P>
<P>
   You bet.
</P>
<P>
   What follows is an account of My Dinner With Alain. It is not a
review. The New York Times would never review a restaurant open
only two weeks, and after only one visit. In fact, given the
difficulties of landing a reservation, it's anyone's guess when a
review might materialize. One visit took some scheming. Repeating
the feat four or five times will require cunning, extraordinary
luck or Zenlike patience.
</P>
<P>
   But like Howard Carter after penetrating the tomb of
Tutankhamen, I feel compelled to offer the world a glimpse of the
splendors I have witnessed.
</P>
<P>
   Les Celebrites was an elegant room, and after a $2 million
renovation, so is Ducasse. The main dining room, now outfitted with
back-to-back circular booths and well-spaced tables, has a
luxurious feel, with Brazilian rosewood walls and silk upholstery
whose wavy motif suggests rippling water. Throw pillows in the
booths add a sybaritic touch. In a direct assault on Manhattan
manners, waiters propose that the women let loose their purses and
rest them on silk-wrapped cubes thoughtfully placed at table side.
</P>
<P>
   The Celebrites paintings by Elke Sommer and Phyllis Diller have
disappeared, to be replaced by some appalling works by the
cosmically awful Arman. On this occasion, he has glued trumpets,
French horns and other brass instruments to brown linen canvas and
dripped thick, waxy strands of color over them. They make a very
odd partner to a series of large black-and-white landscape
photographs. I did not penetrate the secret recesses of the Salon
de Soie, a private dining room that seats 12, or eat at the
200-year-old oak chef's table in the kitchen. Perhaps later.
</P>
<P>
   Ducasse makes every effort to assure diners that they are
getting special treatment. The special-effects parade begins with
mineral water, offered in a stainless steel carrier pack that holds
a half-dozen varieties. To read the wine list, a tall foldout card
with five panels, requires breaking a wax seal. When diners leave
the table, their entree is transferred to a warming cart. At the
end of the meal, a cart bearing pots of growing herbs makes the
rounds. The diner who desires a verbena tea gets to watch a waiter
grasp the plant in a white-gloved hand and then snip a few leaves
with a pair of silver scissors. As a postscript to the desserts, a
happy trolley comes rolling over, laden with lollipops, madeleines,
jellied fruits, financiers and large apothecary jars filled with
nougats and caramels.
</P>
<P>
   The recipients of this largesse take it as their due. At the
moment, the crowd at Ducasse seems to be made up of world travelers
used to feasting at Ducasse's top restaurants. There is none of the
self-conscious display and neck-craning that I expected to see.
Diners are not checking one another out. They make a dull group, to
tell the truth _ well-heeled, deliberate feeders who will be
dipping their beaks in vintage Champagne in London or Paris next
week. The New York onslaught, in other words, is still poised. The
scene has not yet materialized.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   My meal began with a plateful of paper-thin discs the size of
poker chips. Our waiter announced them as rye-flour crisps topped
either with Parmesan cheese, sun-dried tomatoes, citrus, or black
pepper. These four taste themes, he explained, would be woven
throughout the meal. That they were limp and greasy did not appear
to be part of the thematic plan.
</P>
<P>
   The four-theme crackers reflected a highly conceptual bias at
Ducasse. Black-and-white photographs on the walls, for example,
express the four elements of earth, air, fire and water. The menu
is florid and cryptic, divided into categories like ``aquatic,''
``land,'' and ``vegetal'' (the Ducasse team is a little shaky on
English). It takes a sharp eye to tease out the dividing line
between appetizers and entrees, especially on the menus that do not
show prices. (Ducasse stays with the traditional French practice of
showing prices only to the host at the table.) I puzzled over the
italic typeface highlighting two dishes. The first was spaghettini
with sauteed vegetables, crushed black truffles, Ligurian olive oil
and basil; the second was lightly breaded veal sweetbreads doused
in roasting juices.
</P>
<P>
   ``These reflect Ducasse's two restaurants, in Paris and Monte
Carlo,'' our waiter explained. The pasta and olive oil suggest the
Italian influences that show up on the Monte Carlo menu. The
sweetbreads allude to the richer, more classical Parisian menu. The
wine list, too, has a rhetorical style, with a high-flying
introductory paragraph in French and English, explaining the
philosophy behind the three main categories: Continental,
Mediterranean and oceanic.
</P>
<P>
   The meal included several highlights, beginning with foie gras
poached in pepper court bouillon, a long, thick slab of almost
comic proportions. I may be wrong, but I remember it as hanging
over the plate.
</P>
<P>
   The veloute of spring peas also made an impression. Poured over
a little heap of pea pods and radish greens, it came with crab
fingers fried to a crisp blond finish and a mysterious silver
implement with medical implications. The gleaming object stumped
our table for at least 10 minutes before someone deduced that it
was a set of pincers for picking up the crab fingers.
</P>
<P>
   Less inspiring was a pink block of wild salmon, served very
simply on tile-shape potatoes, which was sandbagged by a viciously
acidic peppered vinegar reduction. Dishes kept showing up in front
of the wrong diners.
</P>
<P>
   Our sommelier showed a take-charge style. When he saw a bad
choice on the way, he did not hesitate to throw his body in front
of it. ``What do you think about Chateau X,'' I asked, silently
patting myself on the back for an ingenious pick. The sommelier had
an answer. ``No,'' he said. That ended that.
</P>
<P>
   I am happy to get firm opinions firmly expressed. The world has
no room for a wishy-washy sommelier, but I was a little dismayed to
see him steer me immediately toward a $345 Burgundy.
</P>
<P>
   Ducasse boasts a waiter-to-diner ratio of nearly one to one (55
waiters to 65 diners), and you can feel it. The whizzing back and
forth can be dizzying, the crush of carts more impressive than rush
hour on the Van Wyck Expressway.
</P>
<P>
   But the real display of well-oiled teamwork took place in the
brilliantly lighted and lavishly renovated kitchen, on display
through a large square window. I got a good look at the show, all
four hours of it, and it proceeded through distinct phases. At
first, the scene resembled the operating room on ``ER,'' with the
patient's prospects in serious doubt. With time, the mood seemed to
lighten, although it was hard to tell, since never once, in all the
time I observed the kitchen, did a chef ever betray even the hint
of a smile.
</P>
<P>
   Toward the end, I watched them all scrubbing their saucepans and
washing down their cutting surfaces. Around midnight, I expected to
see the janitor come in with an electric floor polisher.
</P>
<P>
   Only one actor was missing from the drama, the man who would
have made My Dinner With Alain the stuff of legend. That was Alain
Ducasse himself. No one necessarily expects to see the great chef
at his many restaurants _ he has 11 of them, after all, all over
the planet. It's his little joke to say, from time to time, ``I am
at all my restaurants all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   But you might think that less than two weeks into opening the
most expensive restaurant Manhattan has ever seen _ the last
restaurant, Ducasse has said, that will bear his name _ that he
would be nervously pacing the quarterdeck, sniffing sauces and
making sure that each $74 entree came out of the kitchen just so.
But he apparently had other fish to fry, in this case the new Tokyo
branch of Spoon, his Parisian diner. Or maybe he does not want to
hear the screams of anguish when the checks arrive.
</P>
<P>
   I accepted mine with stoic calm. But then again, it wasn't
coming out of my pocket. Taking pen in hand, I affixed my signature
to a bill that totaled nearly $1,500 for four diners, tip not
included. In one Olympic clean-and-jerk motion, I had broken all
previous records by several hundred dollars. I felt the kind of mad
exhilaration that criminals must feel when they've done something
terribly, irrevocably wrong.
</P>
<P>
   As I picked up my complimentary craquelin on the way out,
presented in a shiny royal-blue shopping bag, it occurred to me
that I was back to square one. I had eaten at Ducasse. Fine. Now,
how would I get back in? And would I ever lay eyes on Ducasse? &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
