<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHARK-CANCERCURE-NEWHOUSE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHARK CARTILAGE IS BACKBONE OF CONTENTION OVER CANCER `CURE' 
</HEADLINE>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: This article from NEWHOUSE NEWS SERVICE for
Tuesday, July 11, is available as a ``separate-buy.'' For
information about purchasing the article, contact DEBRA WEYDERT of
The New York Times Syndicate at 1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697;
e-mail: weyded nytimes.com.) 
 ART ADV: With photo of shark cartilage (NNS4). 
 By ROBERT COHEN  
 c.2000 Newhouse News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Andrew J. Lane has long believed a cure for cancer
may be swimming around the warm waters of the South Pacific in the
cartilage of man-eating sharks.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Lane's unorthodox views have caught the full attention of
the federal government.
</P>
<P>
   In the past year, authorities have sought to ban Lane from
selling his shark cartilage supplement and fined him $1 million for
deceptively marketing his product as a cure for cancer.
</P>
<P>
   But they've also agreed to fund a multimillion-dollar National
Cancer Institute study to see whether his claims have scientific
merit.
</P>
<P>
   Lane, president of Lane Labs USA in Allendale, N.J., said he
finds himself in a crossfire between the natural dietary supplement
law that allows nontraditional products to be sold over the counter
without federal approval, and the separate law governing
pharmaceuticals that requires rigorous scientific data and Food and
Drug Administration certification.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a real dilemma for us,'' Lane said. ``We are a company
that focuses on natural supplements, but we test them like
pharmaceutical companies test medicines, and maybe the problem the
FDA has with us is they don't know where to place us on the
matrix.''
</P>
<P>
   The FDA and the Federal Trade Commission counter that Lane's
predicament is of his own making.
</P>
<P>
   In separate complaints, they have charged Lane with stepping
over the legal boundaries by touting unproved cancer claims about
his shark cartilage supplement and marketing his product as if it
were a drug without the necessary clinical studies and approvals.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't promote something as a drug and then turn around and
say it is a dietary supplement,'' said FDA spokesman Brad Stone.
``Once you make drug claims, in our view, that renders it as an
unapproved drug.''
</P>
<P>
   Although shark cartilage products are used in the United States
by more than 50,000 people for medical conditions such as cancer,
the NCI -- now sponsoring two shark cartilage clinical trials,
including the one on Lane's product -- said there are no
authoritative studies showing this substance helps cancer patients.
</P>
<P>
   In the studies so far, ``The response rate to cartilage therapy
for these (cancer) patients has not been impressive,'' an NCI
report said.
</P>
<P>
   The FDA, in its federal lawsuit filed in Newark, N.J., in
December, asked for an order banning Lane Labs from selling three
products. These were BeneFin, which is made from shark cartilage
and promoted as a cancer treatment; SkinAnswer, a topical skin
cream sold as a cancer treatment; and MGN-3, a rice bran extract
sold to treat cancer and HIV.
</P>
<P>
   Lane said his company will fight the charges and not bow to what
he called a government ``intimidation process.'' Lane Labs sells
270 caplets of BeneFin for $78.26.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, the FTC settled its own lawsuit against Lane
Labs and Cartilage Consultants of Short Hills, N.J., a firm run by
Lane's father, I. William Lane. The FTC charged the two companies
with deceptive marketing and advertising of BeneFin and SkinAnswer
through the Internet and other means by making false claims that
the products were ``clinically proven'' to treat or cure cancer.
</P>
<P>
   The settlement includes a $1 million fine, with Lane Labs paying
$550,000 to reimburse consumers and using the other $450,000 to
help pay for part of its share of the already approved NCI trial of
the BeneFin shark product that will be conducted by researchers at
the Mayo Clinic.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey White, director of the Office of Cancer Complementary
and Alternative Medicine at NCI, said Lane's legal trouble is ``not
a welcome situation.''
</P>
<P>
   White said the NCI chose Lane's BeneFin and another shark
cartilage substance produced by Aeterna Laboratories in Canada as
part of its broad congressional mandate to look at alternative
therapies.
</P>
<P>
   He said the government-sponsored Phase 3 clinical studies do not
represent an endorsement or mean there will be positive results.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we are trying to do is develop a database about these
products, and it could well be that this data will be negative,''
White said. ``The mere fact we are studying it doesn't imply there
will be a good chance of success.''
</P>
<P>
   The use of shark cartilage as a cancer treatment was popularized
in 1993 by I. William Lane. The elder Lane, an agricultural
biochemist, wrote a book titled ``Sharks Don't Get Cancer'' and a
1996 revision titled ``Sharks Still Don't Get Cancer.''
</P>
<P>
   The first book, the subject of a ``60 Minutes'' broadcast in
1993, described positive results from shark cartilage treatments.
It was followed by aggressive marketing of the shark cartilage
supplement by Lane's son.
</P>
<P>
   The anti-cancer theory behind shark cartilage is that it has
properties that block the growth of the tiny blood vessels that
feed tumors.
</P>
<P>
   But the most recent study, conducted by the independent Cancer
Treatment Research Foundation, tested shark cartilage powder on
advanced-stage cancer patients and found it neither slowed their
disease nor improved their quality of life.
</P>
<P>
   In April, scientists reported at the annual meeting of the
American Association of Cancer Research that sharks do get cancer,
contrary to the title of Lane's books.
</P>
<P>
   Both Lanes say they knew this all along, but the publisher of
the book wanted a bold title. They have said this fact does not
detract from their belief that shark cartilage has anti-cancer
properties.
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   John Harshbarger, director of the Registry of Tumors in Lower
Animals at George Washington University, said he and an associate
found 40 examples of tumors, about half in sharks and the remaining
in skates, rays and other shark relatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``These shark cartilage products have been promoted by the books
that say sharks don't get cancer, and sharks still don't get
cancer. We have examples that sharks do get cancer,'' Harshbarger
said. ``These books are misleading.''
</P>
<P>
   Charles Simone of Lawrenceville, N.J., an oncologist who
concluded an FDA-approved clinical cancer study a year ago on 30
patients using shark cartilage powder, is also a skeptic.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is enough out there to say it probably doesn't work,''
Simone said. ``I saw no way to benefit cancer patients at all. This
is not the way to go. We have to look at something else.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-11-00 1910EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000711.0251 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-11 19:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9285 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e BC-KIDSBOOKS-AZR &LR;      07-11 0835
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KIDSBOOKS-AZR </SLUG>
  
 BC-KNOWLEDGE-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    CHILDREN'S BOOKS HOLD REAL ANSWERS(a) 
 &HT;    (Duplication warning: RESENDING FOR THOSE WHO MAY HAVE MISSED
THIS. Moving in the ``E'' and ``L'' categories) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By RICHARD NILSEN(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   We all have our embarrassing little secrets. Mine is that I read
children's books.
</P>
<P>
   I started when I was a small boy, raiding our tiny elementary
school library for such kinder classics as Roy Chapman Andrew's
(beginitalic)All About Dinosaurs, (enditalic)and have continued to
this day.
</P>
<P>
   It was never the fictional or fairy tale books I latched onto
but the histories, biographies, science and natural history books.
Herbert S. Zim was my god.
</P>
<P>
   The books were filled with the answers to the questions I had
when I was in third grade. Why do some whales have teeth and others
baleen? How does an airplane stay in the air? Why is an egg shaped
that way?
</P>
<P>
   I still have questions, and books still provide answers. Or when
they don't give me answers, they show me the path to find my own
answer.
</P>
<P>
   But sometimes jumping straight into a serious adult tome is
confusing. The experts who write them know much more than I do. And
they don't care about my ignorance. As a result, they can write
well beyond my poor ability to understand them on first go-round.
They are either written with the assumption that you already have
the rudiments, or they are polemical and assume you know the
disputed territory, or they are specialist books filled with a new
vocabulary you haven't learned yet.
</P>
<P>
   That's where children's books come in.
</P>
<P>
   Children's books give you the simplified, coherent version that
the adult books won't deign to provide.
</P>
<P>
   I am aware that the version the children's book gives is often
distorted, grotesquely simplified and sometimes just plain wrong.
But that doesn't matter: They provide a start, a map to the subject
at hand and give you an orientation that can later be fleshed out,
made more subtle and transcended. But you have to begin somewhere.
</P>
<P>
   It is important to realize that knowledge is not merely a
collection of facts. We are bombarded with facts daily, and it
hasn't made any of us smarter. It just means we have more to
forget. And we do.
</P>
<P>
   Knowledge is a set of interrelationships between facts. The
interrelationship has a shape and coherence that cannot be
constructed from the facts alone.
</P>
<P>
   I am reminded over and over about Einstein and facts. ``If I
need a fact, I can look it up,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   You can understand information by two different metaphors. I
choose what I call the ``tree of knowledge.'' It has roots and
branches and creates a unified, simple idea. There may be many
leaves on the tree, but if you keep the shape of the tree in mind,
the leaves - the facts - will turn out to be just where they need
to be.
</P>
<P>
   The other metaphor - the one we come across daily in TV
newscasts, magazine articles and written driving exams - is what I
call ``fact confetti.'' This is the blizzard of unconnected data
that piles up across our road. Get me a snowplow.
</P>
<P>
   If you think of history as a bunch of dates and names - 1588,
1492, June 6, A.D.79 - it's no wonder you have trouble remembering
it. But if you know the great flow, the big picture, all the
details make sense where they come.
</P>
<P>
   They are more than merely dates associated with the Spanish
Armada, the expulsion of Jews from Spain, D-Day or the destruction
of Pompeii, they are part of the inevitable flow of history.
</P>
<P>
   If you have a systemic view of anatomy, no bone will be
unconnected to its neighbor. If you know the division between
bivalves and univalves, the shells you find at the beach have an
instant home - a kind of mailbox in your brain - where they belong
and fit comfortably.
</P>
<P>
   I often have found that if I have forgotten a fact, I can
re-create it accurately by knowing its context. It is better to
know how the French Revolution fits into the change from the Age of
Enlightenment to the Age of Romanticism. If you feel the larger
flow, then you remember that the French Revolution (beginitalic)has
(enditalic)to come after the American one.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, once you have created enough of these ``trees of
knowledge'' on a large number of subjects, then you start seeing
the forest instead of the trees, and it becomes easier and easier
to fit a new shrub into the even larger system. All with almost
none of the pain of trying to learn facts by rote.
</P>
<P>
   Children's books give you a sense of the flow and very few
facts. If later you discover that the tree of knowledge you gained
from the kid's book is flawed, you can trim it or replant it, but
it has served its purpose. It has got you in the door.
</P>
<P>
   And, if you never get beyond a children's book, well, you still
know more than most people.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Contact the reporter at Richard.Nilsen(a)Arizona &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Republic.com or call (602) 444-8823.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Bustos/The Arizona Republic
</P>
