<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-11 19:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9290 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e BC-NEW&AMP;NOTABLE-AZR &LR;      07-11 0744
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW&AMP;NOTABLE-AZR </SLUG>
  
BC-NEW&AMP;NOTABLE--AZR(a) 
 &HT;    NEW &AMP; NOTABLE BOOK REVIEWS(a) 
 &HT;    (Duplication warning: RETRANSMITTING FOR THOSE WHO MAY HAVE
MISSED THIS.Moving in ``E'' and ``L'' categories) 
 &HT;    ((For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By ANNE STEPHENSON(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 Special for The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are Anne Stephenson's capsule reviews of new book:
</P>
<P>
   ``Jim the Boy''
</P>
<P>
   ByTony Earley
</P>
<P>
   (Little, Brown, $23.95)
</P>
<P>
   It's difficult to describe a book like this, a small gem that
appears without fanfare and quietly puts other novels to shame.
It's the story of 10-year-old Jim Glass, whose father died a week
before he was born and who has been raised by his mother and her
three unmarried brothers, known collectively to Jim as ``the
uncles.'' They are a makeshift but solid family, working their
North Carolina farm during the years of the Great Depression. The
action, like the book cover, is deceptively simple, involving a new
suitor for Jim's mother, a new friend for Jim at school and a trip
with one of his uncles that opens Jim's eyes to the world beyond
the small town of Aliceville. Earley, who writes beautifully and
yet with studied restraint, creates a tangible world with these
characters and conveys the deep and lasting importance of small
events in a boy's life. As always, the simplest stories are the
most difficult to tell - and this one is a triumph.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mountain City''
</P>
<P>
   By Gregory Martin
</P>
<P>
   (North Point, $21)
</P>
<P>
   Mountain City, Nev., is a mile long, limit to limit. Its
business district consists of seven buildings, including a gas
station and a bar. There are no stoplights or stop signs. Only 33
people live there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I come and go,'' writes Martin, ``but when I'm there, that
makes 34.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin's family has run the general store in Mountain City since
1958, but their ties to the place go back to their Basque
ancestors, who settled there during the 1800s. Through the drastic
population swings of the boom and bust mining towns, they have hung
on, taking jobs that kept them in the landscape they had come to
love. But life in Mountain City is fading fast. Martin writes this
meticulous memoir as if he hopes to preserve some affectionate but
unsentimental sense of his family and their home before they are
gone.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me,'' he says, ``home is the place I can't keep from
disappearing.''
</P>
<P>
   Sure enough, by the end of the book Mountain City's population
is only 31.
</P>
<P>
   ``I Rant, Therefore I Am''
</P>
<P>
   By Dennis Miller
</P>
<P>
   (Doubleday, $21.95)
</P>
<P>
   Are you ready for some venom? Actually, that word is inadequate
to describe the rancorous, sump-sucking (Miller's term) disdain the
author feels for just about anybody or anything at any given time.
Among his targets: people who watch daytime talk shows (''I swear,
you can still see the jelly on their foreheads where the
electroshock terminals were attached''), the war on drugs (''If we
had any actual commitment, you'd be able to look at a map and see a
smoking hole where Colombia once was'') and the film ``Elizabeth''
(It's about ``some chick who's kind of nice-looking, then she
becomes Queen of England and gets all ugly and bald''). Whatever
will he say about football? These rants are from Miller's TV show,
and judging from sales of his previous collections, you'd think
they're very funny. We think what's hilarious in a monologue falls
flat on a page. Of course. that's just our opinion. We could be
wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gig''
</P>
<P>
   Edited by John Bowe, Marisa Bowe and Sabin Streeter
</P>
<P>
   (Crown, $25)
</P>
<P>
   Here are selections from the Working column featured in the Web
magazine ``Word,'' which for several years has sent interviewers
across the country to listen to people talk about their jobs.
Included here are a corporate headhunter, a crime-scene cleaner, a
financial adviser, a bus driver, a McDonald's worker, a buffalo
rancher, a diet center owner, a porn star, a professional
snowboarder, an actress, an FBI agent, a palm reader, a plastic
surgeon, a waitress and many others. A UPS driver admits that he
gives lousy service to customers who don't tip well at Christmas, a
gun store owner says he is ``basically unemployable - I have a
problem with authority figures,'' and a paparazzo describes the day
actor Alec Baldwin punched him and broke his nose for trying to
shoot video of Baldwin bringing home his newborn daughter. The
interviewees, many of whom are remarkably candid, are identified by
their real names.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-11-00 1915EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000711.0257 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-11 19:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9291 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-BUSH-JESUS-COX     07-11 0574
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-JESUS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Jewish group slams Bush over `Jesus Day' proclamation
 &HT;    By Ken Herman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The American Jewish Congress on Tuesday scolded Gov. George W.
Bush for declaring a ``Jesus Day'' in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The New York-based organization, which works to maintain the
separation of church and state, called the Bush proclamation an
``egregious example'' of an elected official trying to
``accommodate the religious views'' of constituents.
</P>
<P>
   ``The principal problem with Governor Bush's proclamation is not
that it acknowledges the important civic contributions of a
particular faith, but that it assumes that the profound regard in
which the teachings and person of Jesus Christ are held by the
Christian community are the norm for all residents of the state of
Texas,'' said Phil Baum, executive director of the American Jewish
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush proclamation was issued in conjunction with June 10
``March for Jesus,'' an annual event held in cities around the
country.
</P>
<P>
   ``Throughout the world, people of all religions recognize Jesus
Christ as an example of love, compassion, sacrifice and service,''
Bush said in what was called an ``official memorandum.'' ``Reaching
out to the poor, the suffering and the marginalized, he provided
moral leadership that continues to inspire countless men, women and
children today.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush, a Methodist who speaks openly about his religious beliefs,
said at a December debate that Christ was the political or
philosophical hero with whom he most identifies ``because he
changed my heart.''
</P>
<P>
   In the June proclamation, Bush included a call for ``all Texans
to answer the call to serve those in need.
</P>
<P>
   ``By volunteering their time, energy or resources to helping
others, adults and youngsters follow Christ's message of love and
service in thought and deed,'' he said in the proclamation.
</P>
<P>
   Baum said that call is difficult to follow for the state's
``Jews, Muslims, Buddhists, members of other faith groups and
non-believers, all of whom are entitled to equal respect.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush spokeswoman Linda Edwards said the proclamation stemmed
from the governor's belief ``in acknowledging nonprofit
organizations for the good works that they do, without endorsing,
necessarily, all the goals or objectives of those organizations.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Governor Bush is sensitive to the concerns of the American
Jewish Congress but is also mindful of the longstanding tradition
of governors of both parties to honor individuals or organizations
for their good works,'' Edwards said.
</P>
<P>
   She also noted that Bush has issued proclamations honoring a
variety of religions organizations, including Sikh, Baha'I, Hindu
and Jewish houses of worship.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997 and 1998, he issued proclamations noting the March for
Jesus and declaring a ``March for Jesus Days'' in each year.
</P>
<P>
   Baum said all proclamations honoring religious organizations
``are offensive and erode the protection afforded minority beliefs
by the constitutional doctrine that we are all better off when
religion and state are kept separate.'' He urged governors to
resist ``sectarian pronouncements.''
</P>
<P>
   This year's Jesus Day proclamation was issued at the request of
Paul and Kathy Sanchez of Lockhart, the Central Texas
representatives of the March for Jesus organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``Governors of all states make various proclamations of certain
days to commemorate certain segments of their constituencies. Th
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-11-00 1916EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000711.0258 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-11 19:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9292 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-MIDEAST-SUMMIT-0712-C     07-11 0968
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-SUMMIT-0712-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON OPENS CAMP DAVID II URGING PARTIES TO SEEK COMPROMISE
 &HT;    With SUMMIT-TOWN 0712; ISRAEL-GRASSROOTS-0712.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   THURMONT, Md. _ Setting his sights on securing ``a just and
enduring'' peace in the fractious Middle East, President Clinton
opened high stakes negotiations Tuesday between Israeli and
Palestinian leaders at the secluded presidential retreat where a
dramatic accord was reached two decades ago.
</P>
<P>
   Kicking off the talks with a stroll through the rolling
woodlands of Camp David, Clinton and his guests _ Israeli Prime
Minister Ehud Barak and Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat _ smiled
at reporters and shared light conversation on their way to the
brick-and-clapboard lodge where negotiations began.
</P>
<P>
   In a light-hearted sign of the tensions between them, though,
Barak and Arafat started off with a brief but animated exchange
over who should enter the Laurel lodge first. Each tried to defer
to the other.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, Arafat wagged his finger at Barak, tripping off a
bit of mutual backslapping and arm tugging before Barak followed
Arafat through the doorway. Clinton looked on laughing from inside
the lodge, where the three leaders and senior aides met for half an
hour.
</P>
<P>
   White House aides shrugged off the diplomatic slapstick.
</P>
<P>
   ``They greeted each other in a very friendly way,'' White House
spokesman Joe Lockhart told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``The atmosphere is good, and the mood is serious,'' Lockhart
said. ``I felt that they were both here on a serious attempt to
make peace.''
</P>
<P>
   As he left the White House for the half-hour helicopter flight
to Camp David _ the secluded presidential retreat in the cool,
green Catoctin Mountains five miles from this western Maryland town
_ Clinton stopped short of predicting success.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he warned that ``profound and wrenching questions,''
must be settled during what promise to be up to a week of grinding
talks centered on a slate of contentious issues at the core of a
half-century of war and enmity between Israelis and Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   Those issues include the question of Palestinian statehood,
borders, the future of Jerusalem and the extent to which
Palestinian refugees may return to former homelands now controlled
by Israel.
</P>
<P>
   As he has stressed in the past, Clinton reiterated that neither
side should expect a clean win on all issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``There can be no success without principled compromise,''
Clinton said in his White House departure remarks.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton called last week for the talks, saying negotiators for
both sides had reached an impasse that has ground the peace process
to a dangerous stalemate.
</P>
<P>
   Building on that theme, he warned the parties Tuesday against
believing that time was on their side, that either one might
improve their negotiating prospects by stalling or by kicking
painful decisions down the road.
</P>
<P>
   ``The parties have proven that peace is possible when they are
determined to make it,'' Clinton said. ``In the process, they have
passed the point of no return. The only way forward now is
forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton hopes to tie up in the coming days a marathon diplomatic
undertaking kicked off at Camp David in 1978, when President Jimmy
Carter brokered a breakthrough peace accord between Israeli Prime
Minister Menachem Begin and Egyptian President Anwar Sadat.
</P>
<P>
   That agreement called for Israel and the Palestinians to resolve
their outstanding disputes over the next five years, an objective
Clinton hopes to attain before he leaves July 19 for the annual
Group of Eight summit in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   The weight of history fell with a thud here on this 18th-Century
crossroads at the foot of the Catoctin Mountains.
</P>
<P>
   The town's 4,400 residents have grown used to seeing
presidential motorcades whiz up and down its otherwise quiet
streets. They've even accepted the inconvenience of having Clinton
take over the Maple Run golf course at the edge of town, once a
dairy farm and source of pancake syrup from the sugar maple trees
that still abound in these parts.
</P>
<P>
   This week, though, the town is inundated with more than 300
members of the international press corps, as well as scores of
high-level White House aides and U.S., Israeli and Palestinian
diplomats.
</P>
<P>
   Most town folk voiced pessimism about the prospects for a
comprehensive peace accord.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know, that war's been going on forever ain't it,''
said 24-year-old Jeremy Hahn, who served four years in the Marine
Corps before returning to Thurmont to cut hair _ $7 for a flat top
_ in his dad's barber shop.
</P>
<P>
   ``All we're going to do is give 'em more money, they'll go back
there and shoot each other,'' Hahn said. ``That's the way I see
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Arafat arrived at 1 a.m. ET at Camp David, where he was greeted
by U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright. Barak arrived five
hours later, also welcomed by Albright.
</P>
<P>
   At 11:30 a.m. ET, the president arrived, met briefly with top
Middle East aides, then met for about 40 minutes with Arafat on the
back porch of Clinton's lodge, the Aspen cottage. After Arafat
left, Clinton met for nearly an hour, in the same spot, with Barak.
</P>
<P>
   Strolling in between his Middle East guests along a pathway
through the wooded presidential retreat, Clinton smiled at
reporters but refused to answer questions, in keeping with the news
blackout the parties agreed upon to prevent media leaks from
spoiling the talks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We pledged to each other we would answer no questions and
offer no comment,'' Clinton said. ``I'd like to set a good
example.''
</P>
<P>
   (Bob Deans' E-mail address is: bobdeans(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
