r l BC-NEW&AMP;NOTABLE-AZR &LR;      07-11 0744
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW&AMP;NOTABLE-AZR </SLUG>
  
BC-NEW&AMP;NOTABLE--AZR(a) 
 &HT;    NEW &AMP; NOTABLE BOOK REVIEWS(a) 
 &HT;    (Duplication warning: RETRANSMITTING FOR THOSE WHO MAY HAVE
MISSED THIS.Moving in ``E'' and ``L'' categories) 
 &HT;    ((For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By ANNE STEPHENSON(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 Special for The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are Anne Stephenson's capsule reviews of new book:
</P>
<P>
   ``Jim the Boy''
</P>
<P>
   ByTony Earley
</P>
<P>
   (Little, Brown, $23.95)
</P>
<P>
   It's difficult to describe a book like this, a small gem that
appears without fanfare and quietly puts other novels to shame.
It's the story of 10-year-old Jim Glass, whose father died a week
before he was born and who has been raised by his mother and her
three unmarried brothers, known collectively to Jim as ``the
uncles.'' They are a makeshift but solid family, working their
North Carolina farm during the years of the Great Depression. The
action, like the book cover, is deceptively simple, involving a new
suitor for Jim's mother, a new friend for Jim at school and a trip
with one of his uncles that opens Jim's eyes to the world beyond
the small town of Aliceville. Earley, who writes beautifully and
yet with studied restraint, creates a tangible world with these
characters and conveys the deep and lasting importance of small
events in a boy's life. As always, the simplest stories are the
most difficult to tell - and this one is a triumph.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mountain City''
</P>
<P>
   By Gregory Martin
</P>
<P>
   (North Point, $21)
</P>
<P>
   Mountain City, Nev., is a mile long, limit to limit. Its
business district consists of seven buildings, including a gas
station and a bar. There are no stoplights or stop signs. Only 33
people live there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I come and go,'' writes Martin, ``but when I'm there, that
makes 34.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin's family has run the general store in Mountain City since
1958, but their ties to the place go back to their Basque
ancestors, who settled there during the 1800s. Through the drastic
population swings of the boom and bust mining towns, they have hung
on, taking jobs that kept them in the landscape they had come to
love. But life in Mountain City is fading fast. Martin writes this
meticulous memoir as if he hopes to preserve some affectionate but
unsentimental sense of his family and their home before they are
gone.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me,'' he says, ``home is the place I can't keep from
disappearing.''
</P>
<P>
   Sure enough, by the end of the book Mountain City's population
is only 31.
</P>
<P>
   ``I Rant, Therefore I Am''
</P>
<P>
   By Dennis Miller
</P>
<P>
   (Doubleday, $21.95)
</P>
<P>
   Are you ready for some venom? Actually, that word is inadequate
to describe the rancorous, sump-sucking (Miller's term) disdain the
author feels for just about anybody or anything at any given time.
Among his targets: people who watch daytime talk shows (''I swear,
you can still see the jelly on their foreheads where the
electroshock terminals were attached''), the war on drugs (''If we
had any actual commitment, you'd be able to look at a map and see a
smoking hole where Colombia once was'') and the film ``Elizabeth''
(It's about ``some chick who's kind of nice-looking, then she
becomes Queen of England and gets all ugly and bald''). Whatever
will he say about football? These rants are from Miller's TV show,
and judging from sales of his previous collections, you'd think
they're very funny. We think what's hilarious in a monologue falls
flat on a page. Of course. that's just our opinion. We could be
wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gig''
</P>
<P>
   Edited by John Bowe, Marisa Bowe and Sabin Streeter
</P>
<P>
   (Crown, $25)
</P>
<P>
   Here are selections from the Working column featured in the Web
magazine ``Word,'' which for several years has sent interviewers
across the country to listen to people talk about their jobs.
Included here are a corporate headhunter, a crime-scene cleaner, a
financial adviser, a bus driver, a McDonald's worker, a buffalo
rancher, a diet center owner, a porn star, a professional
snowboarder, an actress, an FBI agent, a palm reader, a plastic
surgeon, a waitress and many others. A UPS driver admits that he
gives lousy service to customers who don't tip well at Christmas, a
gun store owner says he is ``basically unemployable - I have a
problem with authority figures,'' and a paparazzo describes the day
actor Alec Baldwin punched him and broke his nose for trying to
shoot video of Baldwin bringing home his newborn daughter. The
interviewees, many of whom are remarkably candid, are identified by
their real names.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-11-00 1916EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000711.0261 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-11 19:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9297 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-ADS-MULLEN-BOS &LR;      07-11 0619
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ADS-MULLEN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MULLEN FACES LOSS OF L.L. BEAN, MONSTER.COM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a blow to its prestige and revenues, ad agency Mullen
acknowledged Tuesday that it could lose two premier clients, Maine
retailer L.L. Bean Inc. and Monster.com of Maynard, the job-search
and career-management Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Mullen and L.L. Bean have ``mutually agreed to part ways,'' said
Mullen chief executive Joe Grimaldi a few hours after Monster.com
announced that it had hired Pile and Co., a Boston consulting firm,
to conduct an ad agency review on its behalf.
</P>
<P>
   Because Mullen, New England's third largest ad agency, has been
invited to participate in that review, it is possible that Mullen
could still get to keep Monster.com's business.
</P>
<P>
   Mullen created considerable buzz for Monster.com with a 1999
Super Bowl ad. The ad featured kids who said things like, ``When I
grow up, I want to be a yes-man,'' and ``When I grow up, I want to
claw my way up to middle management.'' But a Monster.com ad that
aired during this year's Super Bowl attracted less notice.
</P>
<P>
   Though they became public on the same day, the decisions by L.L.
Bean and Monster.com to reevaluate their ad strategies were
unrelated and coincidental in their timing, Grimaldi said.
</P>
<P>
   Even if Mullen were to lose both L.L. Bean and Monster.com as
clients, their departures would deduct only about $25 million from
Mullen's annual billings, Grimaldi insisted.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to more than $80 million in new business, Mullen still
projects billings of $400 million this year, up from $340 million
in 1999, Grimaldi said.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement accompanying the announcement that it is seeking
an ad agency review, Monster.com chief executive Jeff Taylor said:
``We have had a successful partnership with Mullen. Monster.com has
experienced tremendous growth over the last two years, and the
challenges associated with establishing this brand _ and continuing
our push in the US market _ are compounded by our aggressive global
growth strategies.''
</P>
<P>
   Taylor's statement suggests that Monster.com might be seeking an
ad agency far larger than Mullen, a small shop based in Wenham,
Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Monster.com said that the assignment it is putting into review
could be worth $75 million to $90 million a year to the winning ad
agency.
</P>
<P>
   L.L. Bean also has asked Pile and Co. to conduct an ad agency
review, but Mullen said it will not be a participant.
</P>
<P>
   At its peak, L.L. Bean spent $25 million a year on advertising,
said L.L. Bean spokesman Rich Donaldson.
</P>
<P>
   In theory, losing as much as $115 million in billings could be a
crushing blow to a mid-size agency such as Mullen.
</P>
<P>
   But Grimaldi claimed that the actual economic impact on Mullen
of losing both accounts would be so small that no layoffs would be
needed at an agency that employs 380 staffers.
</P>
<P>
   In the advertising business, perception is often reality, and
losing high-profile clients can hurt an agency's reputation as a
hot shop. The loss of L.L. Bean and the possible loss of
Monster.com come at a time of transition for Mullen.
</P>
<P>
   About a year ago, a unit of the Interpublic Group of Cos. of New
York bought a majority stake in Mullen.
</P>
<P>
   A short time later, agency founder James Mullen gave over
day-to-day control of the ad agency to a management team led by
Grimaldi and chief creative officer Edward Boches.
</P>
<P>
   Mullen is well regarded. In appraising 1999 performance, Adweek
gave Mullen some of the highest marks awarded to a local agency.
Mullen's clients include Swiss Army Brands, Nextel Communications
Inc., Four Seasons Hotels and Resorts, and a division of General
Motors Corp.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-11-00 1919EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000711.0262 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-11 19:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9298 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-RACE-HOUSTON-ABRIDGED     07-11 1266
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RACE-HOUSTON-ABRIDGED-ART-$ADV13-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRICKS, MORTAR AND COALITION BUILDING IN HOUSTON 
</HEADLINE>
   (Fifteenth in series)  
 (For release Thursday, July 13)  
(EDS: Since Sunday, June 4, and for the subsequent six weeks, The
New York Times has published a series of articles, ``How Race Is
Lived in America.'' The series is the outcome of a yearlong effort
by a team of Times reporters to capture some of the voices of
ordinary people and some of the troubling issues that Americans
continue to face. These stories, two or three each week, will be
approximately 6,000 words. The News Service will move each story in
advance, and an abridged version will also move, at approximately
3,000 words. They will move in the ``a'' news category and will
carry a slug of the form BC-RACE-SLUG-NYT. Because the articles are
organized into chapters, papers with severe space restraints may
choose to spread a single article over several days. Please see
RACE-SERIES-ADVISORY-NYT for a detailed list, or call 888-346-9867
or 212-556-1927.) 
 (ART ADV: Photos NYT150-156 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.)  
 By MIREYA NAVARRO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ It was an anonymous woman in the balcony who started
the song, in a small voice, and as the notes drifted over the
auditorium, heads turned and a hush fell.
</P>
<P>
   Soon those around her joined in, hesitantly at first, then more
boldly, until the triumphant words of the hymn widely known as the
Negro National Anthem seemed to be cascading to the floor of the
hall.
</P>
<P>
   There, more of the political faithful filling the Wortham Center
picked up the tune as they rose from their seats, and now hundreds
were singing in a tide of jubilation that swept over the stage, as
if to embrace Lee P. Brown, who had stood along with them, visibly
moved. He had become Houston's first black mayor that inaugural day
in 1998, and to many in the audience, he was a symbol of newfound
strength.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lift every voice and sing,'' the people sang, ``till earth and
heaven ring. Ring with the harmonies of liberty!''
</P>
<P>
   For all their joy, though, the day had been more than a
celebration of victory for blacks. It had also been a testament to
how racial and ethnic groups in Houston had put aside their
suspicions and rivalries and come together largely out of
self-interest to achieve power.
</P>
<P>
   In the audience were faces from that winning coalition. There
was Richard G. Castaneda, 54, a Mexican-American who owned an
engineering firm in metropolitan Houston. He had cast his lot with
Brown and become active in his campaign because he had trusted the
candidate when he said he would be fair to Latinos. And as a
businessman who got 70 percent of his work through a Houston
affirmative action program, Castaneda needed an open door at City
Hall.
</P>
<P>
   He had had doubts about supporting a black candidate, he said.
There were distant, bruising memories of being harassed by blacks.
But he had recognized that in Houston, where blacks, Anglos and
Hispanics each made up roughly a third of the population, the 21st
century would require interracial alliances in both politics and
business if any one group's interests were to be served. Hispanics,
he said, might even act as a swing group, allying themselves with
Anglos or blacks when it served their interests.
</P>
<P>
   But watching Brown bask in his moment of triumph, Castaneda
said, he also felt apprehensive. ``I wanted to see who he would
surround himself with,'' he remembers thinking. ``Who is he going
to turn the power over to?''
</P>
<P>
   Only rows away from Castaneda at the Wortham Center sat Richard
W. Lewis, 51, a white man with a large stake in Brown's victory. It
was Lewis who had nudged Castaneda, a business associate, to help
the campaign and to bring his Latino friends on board.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis was no friend of affirmative action. In backing Brown, who
was, he had risked alienating the people he worked with, breaking
ranks with his own Houston Contractors Association, of which he was
a past president. The group, most of whose members were white, had
supported the white Republican front-runner largely because he
opposed affirmative action.
</P>
<P>
   But Lewis, who describes himself as a ``Republican from the
womb,'' had fallen in behind Brown, a Democrat, on the basis of a
simple calculation: Brown would win. And as the owner of a local
construction company, Lewis, too, depended on a friendly City Hall.
Ninety percent of his business came from municipal contracts.
Backing the man he presumed would be the next mayor seemed only
prudent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to be in a position of influence,'' he said, ``and
you can't influence a loser.''
</P>
<P>
   But when he heard the Negro hymn swelling up from the crowd, he
said, he suddenly felt unwelcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``It turned me off,'' he recalled. Imagine that the Republican
had won, he said, ``and we had started singing the Confederate
song. It would have been equally out of place. It alienated you,
and that was the specific purpose of it, I'm sure.''
</P>
<P>
   Brian G. Smith, who is black, also had a lot riding on Brown's
victory, although he happened to be out of town on Inauguration
Day. Smith, a 41-year-old architect who runs his own construction
inspection company in Houston, had worked, like Lewis, as a Brown
fund-raiser and with both Lewis and Castaneda on the new mayor's
transition team. He was counting on Brown's election to provide
opportunities for blacks like him who do business with the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``The feeling had been that whites would stay in control of
Houston,'' Smith said. Now, ``it was like, `Wow! Our day has come.'
It felt like, at this time, it was good to be black.''
</P>
<P>
   More than anything, Smith had wanted a mayor friendly to
affirmative action. He remembered the affront of being denied work
because he was black. Like Castaneda, he owed most of his business,
95 percent, to the city law that sets aside about 18 percent of
city contracts for companies owned by minorities and women. And for
Smith, public projects like water systems, stadiums and rails were
where the money was.
</P>
<P>
   So his support for Brown, like that of the other men, had
largely been bound up with his business interests. Which was
nothing new for him. From the day Smith started his company, in
1987, business had driven his political involvement, he said, no
matter the candidate's color.
</P>
<P>
   ``For selfish reasons,'' he said. ``Trying to get work.'' This
time, with a black mayor, he said, ``I hoped for access.''
</P>
<P>
   REAFFIRMING AFFIRMATIVE ACTION
</P>
<P>
   Access, influence, money: all had been part of the political
calculus for Castaneda, Smith and Lewis. In the end, all three had
put practical considerations ahead of racial ones. Much as he
yearned for a black mayor, Smith said, he would have opposed Brown
if he had not supported affirmative action.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis, for his part, swallowed any misgivings because, he said,
Brown was ``a sincerely decent man'' whom the white community could
do business with.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you worry about is getting a radical,'' he said. ``I
don't want a Klan member as mayor, or a black militant.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown was no radical. He had been Houston's police chief in the
1980s. In 1990, David Dinkins, New York's only black mayor, lured
Brown to the city to be its police commissioner, a job in which he
took some heat for the roundly criticized police response to racial
violence in the Crown Heights section of Brooklyn. He had also been
President Clinton's director of national drug control policy.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When the polls closed in a runoff election in 1997, Brown had
vindicated the men who had gambled on him, defeating the Republican
Rob Mosbacher, a businessman and son of a former commerce secretary
in the Bush administration, by 6 percentage points. Though Anglos
made up slightly more than half the turnout, Brown had won with 97
percent of the black vote, 66 percent of the Hispanic and 23
percent of the Anglo, according to an exit poll by Robert M. Stein
of Rice University.
</P>
<P>
   For Smith and Castaneda, the election of Lee Brown, a strong
advocate of affirmative action, was reassuring. They could be
confident of continued business with the city under the program,
especially since it had just dodged a bullet.
</P>
<P>
   A conservative initiative to scrap the city's program had been
on the ballot that election year. The measure reflected a national
mood against programs intended specifically to benefit minorities.
But thanks to a record turnout by minority voters, and despite a
2-to-1 Anglo vote to scuttle the program, the law was preserved.
That gave Houston the distinction of being the only major city in
the country to retain affirmative action in a challenge at the
polls.
</P>
<P>
   To Lewis, affirmative action was just another form of welfare
that in effect robbed him of profits. In his ample business with
the city, he had been required to subcontract to minority-owned
firms even when it was not to his financial advantage.
</P>
<P>
   It was thus a measure of his pragmatism that he could still back
Brown despite their polar differences on a critical campaign issue.
Lewis had decided that it was only one issue.
</P>
<P>
   As he analyzed the mayoral race in 1997, he said, he could see
that Anglos in Houston were outnumbered in the aggregate by blacks,
Latinos and Asians from Vietnam, China and India. Demographic
trends were also suggesting that Anglos would dwindle in numbers
even more. The days of conservative Republican mayors _ his own
choice, he acknowledged, if he had had his druthers _ were pretty
much gone.
</P>
<P>
   So his city, the nation's fourth largest, had been transformed.
``I feel like I can't do anything about it,'' he said. Except work
with it.
</P>
<P>
   In the two and a half years since Brown's inauguration, the
pragmatism that drew the three men together has begun to bear fruit
in the form of new business and political alliances and an
opportunity to collaborate on a major city water project.
</P>
<P>
   But to Castaneda, the new order is less about Brown than about
the larger demographic forces. ``Regardless of who is mayor now,
that mayor has to be accountable to a lot of people,'' he said. ``I
don't think there's any way that in the future anybody can screw us
over. We've just learned too much about the political system for
that to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   He and others have also learned what can be gained through a
system of ``racial coalitions,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you measure it in terms of dollars,'' he said, ``we've
never made as much money as we're making.''
</P>
<P>
   THE MIDDLE PLAYS BOTH ENDS
</P>
<P>
   In the tug of war between blacks and Anglos, Hispanics can pull
on either end of the rope. Richard Castaneda began to demonstrate
this shortly after the election.
</P>
<P>
   He was raising money to pay off the mayor's campaign debt and
calling Anglo engineers he knew, many of whom belonged to the trade
group that had supported Brown's opponent. They would be wise, he
told them, to deal with the Brown administration outside of the
trade group _ and to be associated with the allies of the mayor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told them, `We can help you,''' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In exchange, the bigger Anglo-owned firms would help smaller
Hispanic ones land work, at least as subcontractors. And they would
pool money to donate to political candidates, to make them pay
attention.
</P>
<P>
   His case was persuasive. An informal Hispanic-Anglo alliance
christened the Dirty Dozen was born, and it raised more than
$100,000. Hispanic engineers had not only won points with the mayor
by helping retire his debt; with City Hall as the lure, they had
reeled in Anglos for common gain.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the Dirty Dozen _ there are actually 15, and 10 of them
are Anglo _ chase projects together, send work one another's way
and meet with city officials as a group.
</P>
<P>
   Castaneda and his partner at Omega Engineers, Edelmiro Castillo,
who is also in the Dirty Dozen, have a second power base: the
Houston Hispanic Architects and Engineers, a 50-member association
that tries to cultivate good relations both with big companies and
with politicians.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Castillo, the president of the Hispanic group, got a
call from his counterpart with a group of Asian-Americans.
Minorities should unite, the Asian architect said. Castillo agreed.
The timing was right. They had a fair-minded black mayor. A
bustling economy had turned Houston into a boomtown for the
construction industry. There were lawsuits testing affirmative
action.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to say we're the coalition of the minority
groups,'' Castillo said, ``and whenever there are any decisions
made, we want to be a part of it.''
</P>
<P>
   A glue binding Houston's minority groups was the city's
affirmative action program, which set goals, not quotas, for
minority participation. The program ensured minority-owned
companies that they would have a shot at getting a piece of city
contracts. The companies' political connections at City Hall
ensured that they would have an edge on the minority competition.
</P>
<P>
   Castaneda used to think affirmative action was for losers. He
called it ``white-collar welfare,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But that was before he went into business for himself in the
1980s just as Texas' oil and construction industries were going
bust, and he went through half his savings in six months to support
his family. Affirmative action saved his business, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Not all opportunity should be predicated on skin color,
Castaneda said; a person's ability and determination are still the
primary ingredients for success. But before the affirmative action
law passed, in 1984, about 1 percent of city contracts went to
firms owned by minority group members and women; now about 18
percent do. He said he wondered if the number would not go back to
single digits if the law disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``My conscience tells me that affirmative action is a good way
to give people opportunities without social upheaval,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Teaming with Anglos on one hand and nonwhites on the other,
Houston's Hispanics display a kind of cross-racial dexterity that
blacks and whites appear to manage less easily. Castaneda has a
theory about why. ``There's still big mistrust between the whites
and the blacks,'' he said, ``and I think it's still much easier for
each group to get together with Hispanics than each other.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis agrees that Anglos and Latinos get along better. Latinos
are less confrontational than blacks, less ``hardheaded,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He prides himself on working with people of different races. His
foreman of 10 years, Leroy Robinson, is black. His crews are mostly
Latino. He is a mentor to minority business owners. And he defends
his trade group, saying it welcomes everybody. It is the minorities
who shun it, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't separate yourself and then holler integration,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   For Lewis, affirmative action was all downside. By making him
give minority-owned firms almost a fifth of the construction work
he gets from the city, he said, the law forces him either to
subcontract work that his company could do itself or to pass up
Anglo subcontractors who charge less.
</P>
<P>
   ``Affirmative action is unconstitutional,'' he said. ``Why don't
we just call it Anybody But Whites?''
</P>
<P>
   His main argument against the program is that it is no longer
needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first got into construction, it was a bunch of
cowboys,'' he said. ``They were drinking and chasing women. Now, by
and large, they are business people. They take Metamucil at 8
o'clock and go to bed at 9.
</P>
<P>
   ``That changes the way everybody looks at each other. When I
hire a man, I could care less what color you are. If you're
dependable, if you don't steal, we embrace you.''
</P>
<P>
   If someone like Castaneda needs affirmative action after 16
years in business, he said, maybe he should not be in business.
</P>
<P>
   The notion that affirmative action is a crutch, to be accepted
with shame, angers Smith. ``I don't cease being black, or being
discriminated against,'' he said, an edge in his voice. ``That
doesn't change, so I'm not trying to graduate out of this.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``If there's nothing to force majority firms to
contract minority firms, they wouldn't do it. Why split the pie if
you can have all of it? It is a race issue, but it has more to do
with money.''
</P>
<P>
   Affirmative action, Smith said, has been ``the only thing in the
last 200 years that has excluded whites.''
</P>
<P>
   ``So I can't feel sorry for them.''
</P>
<P>
   A CALCULATED MOVE PAYS OFF
</P>
<P>
   Lewis, Castaneda and Smith all say they have no complaints about
how the mayor has treated them.
</P>
<P>
   In part because of their connections to the Brown
administration, ties that were forged during the 1997 campaign, the
three were selected to join a team of industry professionals
competing for a $100 million contract to build the Northeast Water
Purification Project. The team is led by a group of private
companies that also chose the men because they brought racial
diversity to the table. Though the project is not subject to
affirmative action regulations because it is being built with
private money, it will still need to obtain approval from the city,
the plant's client, and the City Council is made up of blacks,
whites, Latinos and one Asian-American. In this case, Castaneda
says, political realities have dictated the need for diversity,
with or without the law.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Utopia, this is how it should work,'' Castaneda said.
</P>
<P>
   But whatever promise of equal opportunity is embodied in that
team, it is not a reason to scrap affirmative action, he said. Even
with a mixed population and a multi-hued council to represent it,
he said, there would be no guarantee that minority companies would
be given a fair shake in an industry still dominated by Anglo-owned
companies. And in politics, he said, even a minority leader could
be bought or could enter into an alliance out of self-interest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think you can leave it up to people's judgment,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis, Smith and Castaneda all agree that one of Brown's
legacies will be the way he has led minorities, not just blacks,
into government.
</P>
<P>
   THE FUTURE
</P>
<P>
   As recently as 1960, whites made up 70 percent of the city's
population, blacks 23 percent and Hispanics 7 percent. By 1997,
whites were 35 percent, blacks 28 and Hispanics 31. By 2030, it is
projected, Latinos will account for more than 50 percent of the
population of Harris County, which includes Houston. Whites,
meanwhile, will dip to 21 percent and blacks to 11 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But whatever movement there is toward greater Hispanic power,
Lewis is not troubled by it. He said he did not know many whites
who fretted about their shrinking numbers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're not concerned about it as long as green controls,'' he
said. ``They're the establishment. That's the establishment you
have to blend with, and if you're not going to blend, you're not
going to be accepted.''
</P>
<P>
   If one prospect is a kind of assimilation, as Lewis envisions,
and another is continued ethnic divisions, as others predict, yet
another is long-term coalitions, which Castaneda said he hoped for.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the blacks and Hispanics made a coalition, they could do a
lot,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   To Smith, blacks may have achieved power at City Hall just in
time to hand it over to Latinos. ``At some point, we are not going
to be able to get a black mayor,'' he said. ``I hope we'll have a
Hispanic mayor that we can trust to be inclusive.''
</P>
<P>
   A more immediate issue is the fate of affirmative action. Some
city officials see it as a stabilizing force, but with lawsuits
pending, opponents like Lewis expect a court to strike down the
city law any day. Already, the Brown administration has endorsed
two new race- and gender-neutral contracting programs.
</P>
<P>
   When the time comes for the men to cash in or retire, they plan
to retreat to their separate worlds. Castaneda thinks of moving
permanently to a lakeside home near San Antonio. Lewis plans to
live at least part of the time in Matagorda. Only Smith feels
rooted in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   The three have made a living in the same arena, sometimes
helping each other get jobs, sometimes coming together out of
mutual interest. But outside that arena, they said, they were not
sure whether they would have any reason to see one another again.
</P>
<P>
   Most relationships outside the family are superficial anyway,
Castaneda said.
</P>
<P>
   And though Houston has made him feel ``95 percent comfortable''
around other ethnic groups, he said, there is that remaining 5
percent, which he calls distrust.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know they're watching what they say,'' Castaneda said of
Lewis and Smith, ``because under normal circumstances, they could
be saying something insensitive towards me.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith, who views opposition to affirmative action as racist,
said he had nothing in common with Lewis except their support for a
mayoral candidate. He said he felt closer to Castaneda.
</P>
<P>
   But Lewis says friendship is not the point; tolerance is _
``where we don't have this open hostility toward one another.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You work together well; we treat each other civilly,'' he
said. ``We send each other work.
</P>
<P>
   ``How close are we supposed to be?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
