<HEADLINE>
U.S. CHILDREN BORN WITH HIV NOW REACHING TEEN YEARS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By LEIGH HOPPER 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DURBAN, South Africa _ Of the estimated 10,000 children living
in the United States born with HIV due to mother-to-infant
infection, approximately 2,400 are now teen-agers, according to a
new report presented Tuesday at the 13th International AIDS
Conference.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors say these youngsters, some of whom have been taking 15
to 17 pills a day for much of their lives, are poised to do the
things teens do: rebel, and become sexually active.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something very few centers planned for,'' said Dr. Mark
Kline, a pediatric AIDS specialist at Texas Children's Hospital,
who is attending the conference. ``I view it as a kind of good
problem to have.''
</P>
<P>
   The number of children born to HIV-infected women in the U.S.
increased rapidly in the 1980s and then plateaued in the early
1990s, according to the study from the national Centers for Disease
Control and Prevention. Successful anti-HIV drugs, which became
available in the mid-1990s, have allowed more infected children in
the United States and Western Europe to reach adolescence, said
lead author Dr. Mary Lou Lindegren of the CDC.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers said these youngsters need prevention strategies
specifically targeted at them: family planning, education about
sexual health and how to protect themselves and others.
</P>
<P>
   ``With this population, the earlier, the better,'' Lindegren
said. ``They're approaching their sexual debut _ we have an
opportunity to intervene early. Waiting until they are 13 is too
long.''
</P>
<P>
   Kline, who has many such patients in his practice, said frank
conversations with patients about sexuality, partner notification,
substance abuse and condom use are imperative.
</P>
<P>
   He strongly advises patients against sexual activity, stressing
that it's better to wait ``until they are ready for a longer,
monogamous relationship with a partner who knows their infection
status.'' Because some will probably become sexually active anyway,
he makes sure patients understand how the virus is spread,
dispelling myths such as that HIV can't be spread by oral sex.
</P>
<P>
   The second issue facing children with HIV is adhering to their
daily drug regimen. Some of the protease inhibitors, which block
the virus's ability to reproduce, are nearly an inch long and
unpleasant to take. Kline said children can be ``resourceful'' in
figuring out ways to avoid taking the drugs.
</P>
<P>
   In a study of the anti-HIV drug saquinavir, six out of 25
children failed the therapy and the level of HIV in their blood
remained high. Upon investigation, Kline discovered that five of
the six barely had any of the drug in their blood at all. When he
questioned the patients and their parents, he learned some of the
youngsters had been creative: One patient fed his pills to the
family dog, another stuffed them under cushions, and another child
flushed her pills down the toilet.
</P>
<P>
   The obstacles increase as patients reach their teens. Kline said
young patients who have always been cooperative about taking their
medicine suddenly balk. And when they don't take the drugs, they
become sick.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's heartbreaking. . . . They want to fit in and anything
that sets them apart is bad,'' Kline said. ``This is not unique to
HIV. The juvenile diabetic is a classic one.''
</P>
<P>
   A related CDC study of data from a biennial youth survey
suggested that sexual risk behavior in teens is declining,
reversing an upward trend in sexual intercourse among adolescents
during the 1970s and 1980s. Between 1991 and 1999, condom use
increased from 46.2 percent to 58 percent among high school
students. The percentage of 14- to 18-year-olds who reported having
sex declined from 54.1 percent to 49.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
   There was a 16 percent decrease in the number of teens reporting
four or more sexual partners in a lifetime. CDC researchers
attributed the declines to broad-based prevention efforts.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY
</P>
