<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-11 19:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9312 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-SANDM-RAID-BOS &LR;      07-11 0901
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SANDM-RAID-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLICE FIND MORE THAN 50 AT INTERNET-ORGANIZED S&AMP;M CLUB 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CINDY RODRIGUEZ  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATTLEBORO, Mass. _ They wore leather, studs, and not much else.
</P>
<P>
   More than 50 people from all over New England paid $25 to enter
a taboo world, where they sought sexual pleasure in the form of
spankings, domination, bondage, and taunts.
</P>
<P>
   One woman bent over as another flogged her with a wooden
spatula. Their leader _ the so-called ``dungeon master'' _ watched
over the group, to keep the sadomasochism club members in line.
</P>
<P>
   Since February, police say, the group met regularly in a room on
the fourth-floor of a former tool &AMP; dye mill in this old mill city
where nighttime attractions are VFW dances and the hot-plate
special at Morin's Diner.
</P>
<P>
   Few knew about the wild times behind door 318 _ above which
read: ``ANGER WITHIN'' _ until it ended Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   That's when police, looking into a report of stolen music
equipment at the converted brick building, stumbled upon the S&AMP;M
club.
</P>
<P>
   They seized whips, chains, paddles, a spiked leather glove, an
S&AMP;M manual and other assorted pain-giving devices. And they charged
two people: the leader and a woman.
</P>
<P>
   The woman's crime? Spanking another woman with a wooden spatula.
</P>
<P>
   Police charged Stefany Reed _ a 38-year-old internet cosmetics
company vice president who lives in Manhattan _ with assault and
battery, even though the woman she ``punished'' consented.
</P>
<P>
   As word of the club and the charges spread, it's cut a quick
divide among those who say S&AMP;M groups should be illegal and others
who say consenting adults should be free to engage in
non-conformist sex acts, as long as no one gets injured.
</P>
<P>
   ``I myself don't get spanked or spank. I'm not into it. It's not
my thing,'' said Matt Slobogan, 24, a jazz drummer who rents
practice space at the building. ``But I don't think we should stop
other people from doing it.''
</P>
<P>
   For others who frequent downtown, though, the break-up of the
club is a relief.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't want stuff like that going on in the
neighborhood,'' said Brian, 48, an addiction counselor who asked
that his last name be withheld. ``It attracts other things, like
prostitution and selling drugs.''
</P>
<P>
   Though it was unclear when, or if, the law has been applied to
people involved in S&AMP;M acts in Massachusetts, the case is
proceeding. A pretrial hearing is scheduled for July 26 in
Attleboro District Court.
</P>
<P>
   But some legal specialists question the law itself. ``Speaking
generally, I would caution law enforcement against using criminal
laws to police consensual private adult activities,'' said Jennifer
Levi, staff attorney for Gay &AMP; Lesbian Advocates &AMP; Defenders, an
organization which has studied prosecutions of people who engage in
non-traditional sex.
</P>
<P>
   ``Laws such as assault and battery should not be relied on as
proxy for enforcing moral judgments about private conduct,'' she
said, adding that she did not know any of the details of the
Attleboro case.
</P>
<P>
   When the police entered the building, they were looking for
guitars, not a sex party. Detectives Timothy Cook and John Otrando
arrived just before 11 p.m. Saturday to investigate the theft of
music equipment from one of the dozens of rooms rented to artists,
musicians and others in the hulking red-brick warehouse.
</P>
<P>
   Inside, boards are nailed against the walls, with spray-painted
messages. One reads ``Time heals all.'' In communal bathrooms,
ribbons of aged fly paper hang from the ceiling, dotted with
long-dead insects.
</P>
<P>
   Known as The Foster Building, it sits diagonally across the
street from the Attleboro Police Department. The owner, William
Boots, could not be reached. The property manager did not return
messages.
</P>
<P>
   As the officers climbed the concrete stairs up to the fourth
floor, Cook and Otrando spotted a woman collecting money at a
table, according to court documents. She also had a list of names
and e-mail addresses, leading them to believe partygoers found out
about the get-together via the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The detectives then discovered several rooms with between 50 to
60 adults, some completely naked, some halfway there.
</P>
<P>
   Court records indicate that Benjamin Davis, a clean-shaven
23-year-old computer consultant who lives in Hudson, N.H., rented
the rooms.
</P>
<P>
   Police charged him with assaulting Detective Cook, as well as a
number of other charges: exhibiting or lending articles for
self-abuse, keeping a house of ill fame for lewdness, operating
without a ``Doing Business As'' certificate, and eight counts of
carrying a dangerous weapon.
</P>
<P>
   Police also charged him with ``accessory to assault and battery
before the fact'' for commanding Reed to flog a woman.
</P>
<P>
   Davis and Reed were released on bail. Neither could be reached
for comment. At the Wellesley company where he works, a
receptionist Tuesday said Davis would be returning to work
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   But it was the topic of conversation all over the city, from
coffee shops to those who frequent the converted mill building.
</P>
<P>
   Men attending an alcohol recovery program in a downstairs space
known as ``The Bottom Line'' joked outside the building.
</P>
<P>
   One man, who did not want to give his full name because he's in
treatment, feigned disappointment. ``When I found out,'' said Bob
K. ``I was like, `Why wasn't I invited?' ''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
