<SLUG> BC-OPED-SPORTSPARENTS-KATZ-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT IS A HOCKEY GAME WORTH? 
</HEADLINE>
   (New York Times OpEd for Wednesday, July 12, and thereafter.)  
 ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's OPED news service. For more information
about purchasing this article as a separate-buy' _ or becoming a
client of the OPED news service _ contact one of the New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of the text.)  
 By BOB KATZ    
 c.2000 New York Times    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LEXINGTON, Mass. _ Parents of children involved in organized
sports may be tempted to think that the tragedy in suburban Boston
last week, when a fight between two hockey dads turned fatal, has
nothing to do with them. We'll tell ourselves that an event like
that has more to do with the individuals involved than with youth
sports in general.
</P>
<P>
   But marginalizing the episode at the Reading, Mass., ice rink is
just a convenient way to deflect troublesome concerns before they
creep too close. Sideline parents are quite familiar with the
syndrome of getting worked up at their kids' sporting events.
</P>
<P>
   Watching your child compete is a singularly wrenching
experience. Nobody is immune from bad behavior. I have watched in
disgust as some jerk lambastes a hapless 8-year-old (``Use your
left foot!''), only minutes later to hear myself howling an equally
pointless rant (``Watch the ball!'').
</P>
<P>
   Whenever the topic of bad sideline behavior arises, it is often
dismissed as a situation that has always been with us. Many
parents, especially fathers, seek another shot at thwarted glory
through their children.
</P>
<P>
   But something different is at work these days, whatever the
special circumstances of last week's confrontation, and it's
becoming severe.
</P>
<P>
   Over-the-top parental intensity does not have to turn fatal to
be seen for what it clearly is: adults intruding on children's
games. People who might previously have viewed sports as little
more than an extracurricular activity are buying into the more
serious notion that sports is a metaphor for success. From the glib
homilies of the basketball coach Pat Riley and other jock
proselytizers to the sports analogies used by high-flying corporate
chiefs to explain upticks on the Nasdaq, the culture is awash in
the notion that these are more than mere games.
</P>
<P>
   The message, unwittingly accepted by too many parents, is that a
child's success or failure on the playing field is somehow a
meaningful indicator of his or her potential to do well in life.
Any suggestion that life is a far broader experience than can be
neatly contained in a win-lose paradigm gets swept aside.
</P>
<P>
   Few parents, of course, are so deluded as to believe that their
child is preparing for the Olympics or the major leagues, but when
they speak openly of how youth sports build winners by inculcating
drive and guts and perseverance, they are projecting forward to the
world of adult achievement. That is one large burden to place on
what might otherwise be casual games.
</P>
<P>
   It is my fear that the tragedy at the suburban Boston ice rink
involved two dads who in their zeal to do right by their sons
simply forgot what youth sports are all about _ children acquiring
skills that enable them to have fun and to enjoy life more. This
ought to be plenty, for child and parent alike.
</P>
<P>
   (Bob Katz is working on a book about fathers, sons and organized
sports.)
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
