<SLUG> BC-TUFTS-DEAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US ENVOY TO SOUTH KOREA TO HEAD DIPLOMACY SCHOOL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (i and a coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES A. RADIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The US ambassador to South Korea is stepping down to
become dean of Tufts University's Fletcher School of Law and
Diplomacy, the school confirmed Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen W. Bosworth, a career diplomat who previously was
ambassador to Tunisia and to the Philippines, was appointed to the
top job in Seoul in 1997, before which he was deeply involved in
efforts to lower tensions surrounding North Korea's nuclear power
capabilities.
</P>
<P>
   Bosworth, 60, also was chairman of the board of Dartmouth
College, of which he is a graduate.
</P>
<P>
   The appointment, which takes effect in February, was mentioned
informally at the Fletcher School's commencement in late May but no
announcement was made at the request of Secretary of State
Madeleine K. Albright and Bosworth, acting dean Joel P. Trachtman
said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea was not to prejudice his ability to deal with the
issues of the Korean Peninsula,'' Trachtman said.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the school mailed its 5,000 alumni letters from
Peter Ackerman, chairman of its board of overseers, informing them
of the identity of the new dean.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given the sensitive international negotiations the
dean-designate is involved in, we cannot release his name beyond
the Fletcher community,'' Ackerman wrote in the letter, which was
dated June 2000 but not received by some alumni until this week.
</P>
<P>
   Trachtman, who was a member of the committee that chose
Bosworth, said Bosworth was selected because he ``understands what
a school of international relations needs to be, understands
private sector topics, NGO (non-governmental organization) topics,
and knows the problems of education generally.'' Citing Bosworth's
service at Dartmouth, Trachtman said, ``He knows what tenure cases
look like, he knows what budgets look like.''
</P>
<P>
   The Fletcher School, in suburban Medford, offers graduate-level
programs in international relations and law.
</P>
<P>
   State Department officials and South Korea's embassy in
Washington seemed taken by surprise at the change, which comes at a
time when communist North Korea and democratic South Korea, long
frozen in an enmity of Cold War-vintage, finally are taking steps
toward reconciliation. South Korea's President Kim Dae Jung and his
North Korean counterpart, Kim Jong Il, recently met in Pyongyang,
and expanded business and personal exchanges across their highly
fortified boundary are in the works.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have any information about his resigning,'' said a
State Department official, who spoke on condition of anonymity and
suggested that a reporter contact the embassy in Seoul and speak
with Bosworth directly. ``The ambassador's plans are his to make,''
the official said.
</P>
<P>
   At South Korea's mission in Washington, minister for political
affairs Myung Hwan Yu said the embassy had not been officially
notified of the resignation, and therefore would make no comment.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his three ambassadorial appointments, Bosworth
has served as the State Department's director of policy planning
and as deputy assistant secretary for both economic affairs and
inter-American affairs. Outside government, he was president of the
US-Japan Foundation, and taught international relations at Columbia
University, in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps his most delicate, and potentially dangerous, assignment
_ as executive director of the Korean Peninsula Energy Development
Organization _ immediately preceeded his appointment to Seoul. In
that job, he directed the startup and initial operation of an
organization that is constructing two nuclear power plants in North
Korea and delivering 500,000 tons of fuel oil to the North annually
in return for the dismantling of North Korea's nuclear-weapons
capability.
</P>
</TEXT>
