<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-11 19:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9322 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-MIDEAST-ANALYSIS-BOS &LR;      07-11 0890
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-ANALYSIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SERIOUS TALK, BUT NO BIG DEVELOPMENTS EXPECTED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN DONNELLY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In the annals of summitry, an unscripted moment
Tuesday at Camp David may be remembered for ages.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton had already entered Laurel Cottage at the
Maryland retreat. As Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak and
Palestinian President Yasser Arafat approached the doorway, each
tried to step aside so the other could enter.
</P>
<P>
   Neither budged. They planted their feet. They pretended to
wrestle like miniature, aging Sumo warriors. With an international
television audience watching live, the longer it went the easier it
was to see child's play become a matter of national honor. Who was
mightier? Israeli or Palestinian?
</P>
<P>
   Then, a laughing Clinton, the man who hopes to be peacemaker,
opened the double doors and the two leaders strolled in together,
smiling.
</P>
<P>
   For the president and the peoples of the Middle East, they can
only hope that the moment turns out to be a foreshadowing of things
to come, that after some tussling in the negotiations, Barak and
Arafat walk out together with a deal done.
</P>
<P>
   This is a critical moment in the long history of war over who
controls the Holy Land. No matter the outcome, the stakes loom
large. But, say many onlookers, expectations should be in line with
the history of the nine years of Israeli-Palestinian negotiations,
starting with the Madrid Conference in 1991. That foreshadows
incremental movement, not a blockbuster deal.
</P>
<P>
   It means that a conflicting reality envelopes these talks that
were hastily called by Clinton: The summit itself is historic
because the leaders of the Israelis and Palestinians are finally
addressing the most serious issues that have separated them for 52
years of conflict, but not many expect the talks to make history.
</P>
<P>
   Before the discussions began Tuesday, Clinton himself placed the
talks in the context of previous negotiations of Middle East peace,
starting with the Israeli-Egyptian pact that grew out of Camp David
in 1978, ``to Madrid, to Oslo, to the first handshake on the lawn
between Prime Minister (Yitzhak) Rabin and Chairman Arafat, to the
peace between Israel and Jordan, and the agreement at Wye River.''
</P>
<P>
   But after such a long list of deals, how far have the Israelis
and the Arabs come? Some look at it in the historic context, saying
that the reality today of a framework of peace deals was
unthinkable in the months after the 1967 and 1973 wars.
</P>
<P>
   Others see it through the prism of day-to-day life. For
Palestinians, that outlook is grim, considering the paucity of jobs
and economic opportunities and the vastly unequal footing between
them and their Israeli neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   These talks are about core issues for the entire Middle East:
Who controls Jerusalem, a spiritual center for Muslims, Jews and
Christians? What happens to the 3 million Palestinian refugees
living in exile? If a Palestinian state is declared, what are its
borders? What are its powers? What happens to the 170,000 Jewish
settlers have built permanent housing on land deeded to Palestinian
families?
</P>
<P>
   All this to be decided in seven days at Camp David?
</P>
<P>
   Hanan M. Ashrawi, who has participated in past Palestinian
negotiations and now has taken the role as one of Arafat's
spokespeople, said Tuesday that such a short time frame was either
a ``last-ditch attempt or heroic or a foolhardy attempt.''
</P>
<P>
   She clearly was worried about the last alternative coming true.
She also sounded a warning that the Palestinians weren't going to
be pushed around, that they wouldn't cave to ``the politics of
panic,'' a coda that says a deal must be done now or the
opportunity is lost forever.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real issue is what are the positions being adopted by the
sides concerned, and what role does the US envisage for itself, and
what kind of clout or pressure can it exercise _ not just on the
Palestinians, which is a historical habit ... (while) the Israelis
get away with the carrots,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   By that, she meant the Clinton administration may be a fair
broker in the negotiations, but it also must dole out a peace
dividend to both.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the obstacles and the short time frame, there has been
an historic shift in one important dynamic leading up to the talks:
Both sides now have made it a priority to tackle the so-called
final status issues _ Jerusalem, borders, statehood, settlers.
</P>
<P>
   The Palestinians have always favored such an approach, while the
Israelis have resisted it. But now, with Barak's governing
coalition in pieces, it seems in his interest to pull together a
larger package than a smaller one.
</P>
<P>
   All three leaders' needs aren't that complicated.
</P>
<P>
   Barak needs the Palestinians to end their historic conflict, a
united Jerusalem, a big US aid package, Israel's security intact
and most Jewish settlements remaining in place. Arafat needs a
legitimate state, a piece of Jerusalem, some settlers out and US
and international money.
</P>
<P>
   And Clinton? ``He just needs people smiling at the end of
this,'' said Geoffrey Aronson, head of the Foundation for Middle
East Peace, a Washington think tank.
</P>
<P>
   Just like they smiled Tuesday going into Laurel Cottage. The
pictures a week from now will tell the story.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
