   Lead story:
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-TALKS (Thurmont, Md.) _ Ledeall: In the verdant hills of
Maryland, the Israeli and Palestinian leaders began their fateful
peace summit at Camp David with the far-reaching, most think
improbable, goal of ending their 52-year-old conflict. On the first
day of an open-ended, secluded meeting, President Clinton ushered
Prime Minister Ehud Barak of Israel and Palestinian leader Yasser
Arafat into the presidential retreat where he hopes that the
chemistry of the place can induce a spirit of ``principled
compromise'' that yields a substantive peace agreement. By Deborah
Sontag.(We plan to move the story by 8:30 p.m. ET in ``i'' news
file.) 1,300 words.
</P>
<P>
   Story runs under a 3-column, 1-line hed and 3-column photo.
</P>
<P>
   With photos, NYT2,3, and a graphic.
</P>
<P>
   Top center story:
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-DRUGS (Washington) _ A possible compromise is emerging
in congressional talks on drugs. By Robert Pear. (Scheduled to move
by 9 p.m. ET in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   Off-lead story:
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-PRIVATE-SECTOR (Jiaxing, China) _ China has been marching
on the road of economic reform for more than two decades now, but
its private sector remains a tiny slice of an economy still
dominated by government-owned organizations. Entrepreneurs are
systematically shunned by China's banks, discriminated against by
regulators and barred from entering many industries. Barriers to
capital formation keep most private businesses from providing more
than a handful of jobs, but there is growing pressure to change
that. By Craig S. Smith. (Scheduled to move by 8:30 p.m. ET in
``f'' news file.) 2,000 words.
</P>
<P>
   Reefer: SCI-MERCURY-RISK (Undated) _ A panel of scientists
declares that levels of the most hazardous form of mercury in the
environment pose an unacceptable health risk, particularly to
children born of mothers who eat fish during pregnancy, and must be
reduced. The finding, in a report released by the National Research
Council of the National Academy of Sciences, clears the way for the
EPA _ after years of delays _ to write new regulations that would
force power plants to cut emissions of mercury. By Andrew C.
Revkin. (Scheduled to move by 8 p.m. ET in ``a'' news file.) 900
words.
</P>
<P>
   FOLD
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-BEACHES (Los Angeles) _ For years, Southern California has
been engaged in the struggle to get rid of the brown haze that
hangs over the skyline on a hot summer day. Now the region is
caught up in another struggle that will provide a new test of its
political will and the social conscience of the people who live
there: rethinking a system that dumps trillions of gallons of
polluted storm water every year into the ocean off some of Southern
California's most fabled beaches. By Barbara Whitaker. (Scheduled
to move by 9 p.m. ET in ``a'' news file.) 2,000 words.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-FUNDRAISING (Washington) _ A look at the Democrats bid
to topple the Republicans' fragile, six-seat majority in the House
of Representatives and their fund-raising efforts. By John M.
Broder and Don Van Natta. (Scheduled to move by 8 p.m. ET in ``p''
news file.) 1,300 words.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   BOTTOM
</P>
<P>
   FASCIST-ARCHITECTURE (Rome) _ The Italian government is going to
sell some of the jewels of Fascist architecture which has upset
Romans, who now treasure it after years of despising it. By
Alessandra Stanley. (The story has moved in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   Story runs under 3-column photo.
