<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-11 19:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9325 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-MIDEAST-SUMMIT-0712-1     07-11 1117
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-SUMMIT-0712-1STLD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDs: writes thru with adds, updates, tightening throughout
 &HT;    CLINTON OPENS CAMP DAVID II URGING PARTIES TO SEEK COMPROMISE
 &HT;    With SUMMIT-TOWN 0712; ISRAEL-GRASSROOTS-0712.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   THURMONT, Md. _ Setting his sights on securing ``a just and
enduring'' peace in the fractious Middle East, President Clinton
opened high stakes negotiations Tuesday between Israeli and
Palestinian leaders at the secluded presidential retreat where a
landmark accord was reached two decades ago.
</P>
<P>
   Kicking off the talks with a stroll through the rolling
woodlands of Camp David, Clinton and his guests _ Israeli Prime
Minister Ehud Barak and Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat _ smiled
at reporters and shared light conversation on their way to the
brick-and-clapboard lodge where negotiations began.
</P>
<P>
   In a light-hearted sign of the tensions between them, Barak and
Arafat started off with a brief but animated exchange over who
should enter the Laurel lodge first. Each tried to defer to the
other.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, Arafat wagged his finger at Barak, tripping off a
bit of mutual backslapping and arm-tugging before Barak followed
Arafat through the doorway.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton looked on laughing from inside the lodge, where the
three leaders and senior aides met for half an hour before breaking
up into smaller groups for sessions that stretched into the night.
</P>
<P>
   White House aides, meanwhile, shrugged off the diplomatic
slapstick.
</P>
<P>
   ``They greeted each other in a very friendly way,'' White House
spokesman Joe Lockhart told reporters here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The atmosphere is good, and the mood is serious,'' he said.
``I felt that they were both here on a serious attempt to make
peace.''
</P>
<P>
   As he left the White House Tuesday aboard Marine One for the
half-hour flight to Camp David _ the secluded presidential retreat
in the cool, green Catoctin Mountains five miles from this western
Maryland town _ Clinton stopped short of predicting success.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he warned that ``profound and wrenching questions,''
must be settled during what promise to be up to a week of grinding
talks centered on a slate of contentious issues at the core of a
half-century of war and enmity between Israelis and Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   Those issues include the question of Palestinian statehood,
borders, the future of Jerusalem and the extent to which millions
of Palestinian refugees may return to former homelands controlled
by Israel since the 1967 Arab-Israeli War.
</P>
<P>
   As he has stressed in the past, Clinton reiterated that neither
side should expect a clean win on all issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``There can be no success without principled compromise,''
Clinton said in his White House departure remarks.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton expressed hope, though, that this week would lead to a
breakthrough settlement that he and his predecessors have sought
for decades in the region that is home to three of the world's
great religions and two-thirds of the known crude oil reserves.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have an opportunity to bring about a just and enduring end
to the Israeli-Palestinian conflict,'' said Clinton, who planned to
spend the night at Camp David. ``That is the key to lasting peace
in the entire Middle East.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton called last week for the talks, saying negotiators for
both sides had reached an impasse that has ground the peace process
to a dangerous stalemate.
</P>
<P>
   Building on that theme, he warned the parties Tuesday against
believing that time was on their side, or that either one might
improve their negotiating prospects by stalling or by kicking
painful decisions down the road.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have passed the point of no return,'' Clinton said. ``The
only way forward now is forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton hopes to tie up in the coming days a marathon diplomatic
undertaking set in motion at Camp David in 1978, when President
Jimmy Carter brokered a breakthrough peace accord between Israeli
Prime Minister Menachem Begin and Egyptian President Anwar Sadat.
</P>
<P>
   That agreement called for Israel and the Palestinians to resolve
their outstanding disputes over the next five years, an objective
Clinton hopes to attain before he leaves July 19 for the annual
Group of Eight summit in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   In a twist, Barak is staying in the Dogwood cottage, where Sadat
stayed during the 13-day summit 22 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat is holed up in the Birch cottage, where Israeli leader
Begin stayed in 1978.
</P>
<P>
   The weight of history fell with a thud here on this 18th-Century
crossroads at the foot of the Catoctin Mountains.
</P>
<P>
   The town's 4,400 residents have grown used to seeing
presidential motorcades whiz up and down its otherwise quiet
streets. They've even accepted the inconvenience of having Clinton
take over the Maple Run golf course at the edge of town, once a
dairy farm and source of pancake syrup from the sugar maple trees
that still abound in these parts.
</P>
<P>
   This week, though, the town is inundated with more than 300
members of the international press corps, as well as scores of
high-level White House aides, presidential security teams and U.S.,
Israeli and Palestinian diplomats.
</P>
<P>
   Many townsfolk voiced pessimism about the prospects for a
comprehensive peace accord.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know, that war's been going on forever ain't it,''
said 24-year-old Jeremy Hahn, who served four years in the U.S.
Marine Corps before returning to Thurmont to cut hair _ $7 for a
flat top _ in his dad's barber shop.
</P>
<P>
   ``All we're going to do is give 'em more money, they'll go back
there and shoot each other,'' Hahn said. ``That's the way I see
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Arafat arrived at 1 a.m. (ET) at Camp David, where he was
greeted by U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright. Barak
arrived five hours later, also welcomed by Albright.
</P>
<P>
   At 11:30 a.m. (ET), the president arrived, met briefly with top
Middle East aides, then met for about 40 minutes with Arafat on the
back porch of Clinton's lodge, the Aspen cottage. After Arafat
left, Clinton met for nearly an hour, in the same spot, with Barak.
</P>
<P>
   Strolling in between his Middle East guests along a pathway
through the wooded presidential retreat Tuesday afternoon, Clinton
smiled at reporters but refused to answer questions, in keeping
with the news blackout the parties agreed upon to prevent media
leaks from
</P>
<P>
   spoiling the talks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We pledged to each other we would answer no questions and
offer no comment,'' a smiling Clinton said. ``I'd like to set a
good example.''
</P>
<P>
   (Bob Deans' E-mail address is: bobdeans(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
