<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TUFTS-DEAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US ENVOY TO SOUTH KOREA TO HEAD DIPLOMACY SCHOOL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (i and a coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES A. RADIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The US ambassador to South Korea is stepping down to
become dean of Tufts University's Fletcher School of Law and
Diplomacy, the school confirmed Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen W. Bosworth, a career diplomat who previously was
ambassador to Tunisia and to the Philippines, was appointed to the
top job in Seoul in 1997, before which he was deeply involved in
efforts to lower tensions surrounding North Korea's nuclear power
capabilities.
</P>
<P>
   Bosworth, 60, also was chairman of the board of Dartmouth
College, of which he is a graduate.
</P>
<P>
   The appointment, which takes effect in February, was mentioned
informally at the Fletcher School's commencement in late May but no
announcement was made at the request of Secretary of State
Madeleine K. Albright and Bosworth, acting dean Joel P. Trachtman
said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea was not to prejudice his ability to deal with the
issues of the Korean Peninsula,'' Trachtman said.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the school mailed its 5,000 alumni letters from
Peter Ackerman, chairman of its board of overseers, informing them
of the identity of the new dean.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given the sensitive inernational negotiations the
dean-designate is involved in, we cannot release his name beyond
the Fletcher community,'' Ackerman wrote in the letter, which was
dated June 2000 but not received by some alumni until this week.
</P>
<P>
   Trachtman, who was a member of the committee that chose
Bosworth, said Bosworth was selected because he ``understands what
a school of international relations needs to be, understands
private sector topics, NGO (non-governmental organization) topics,
and knows the problems of education generally.'' Citing Bosworth's
service at Dartmouth, Trachtman said, ``He knows what tenure cases
look like, he knows what budgets look like.''
</P>
<P>
   The Fletcher School, in suburban Medford, offers graduate-level
programs in international relations and law.
</P>
<P>
   State Department officials and South Korea's embassy in
Washington seemed taken by surprise at the change, which comes at a
time when communist North Korea and democratic South Korea, long
frozen in an enmity of Cold War-vintage, finally are taking steps
toward reconciliation. South Korea's President Kim Dae Jung and his
North Korean counterpart, Kim Jong Il, recently met in Pyongyang,
and expanded business and personal exchanges across their highly
fortified boundary are in the works.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have any information about his resigning,'' said a
State Department official, who spoke on condition of anonymity and
suggested that a reporter contact the embassy in Seoul and speak
with Bosworth directly. ``The ambassador's plans are his to make,''
the official said.
</P>
<P>
   At South Korea's mission in Washington, minister for political
affairs Myung Hwan Yu said the embassy had not been officially
notified of the resignation, and therefore would make no comment.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his three ambassadorial appointments, Bosworth
has served as the State Department's director of policy planning
and as deputy assistant secretary for both economic affairs and
inter-American affairs. Outside government, he was president of the
US-Japan Foundation, and taught international relations at Columbia
University, in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps his most delicate, and potentially dangerous, assignment
_ as executive director of the Korean Peninsula Energy Development
Organization _ immediately preceeded his appointment to Seoul. In
that job, he directed the startup and initial operation of an
organization that is constructing two nuclear power plants in North
Korea and delivering 500,000 tons of fuel oil to the North annually
in return for the dismantling of North Korea's nuclear-weapons
capability.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-11-00 1948EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000711.0286 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-11 19:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9329 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-BOSNIA-MASSACRE-ART-N     07-11 1030
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOSNIA-MASSACRE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THOUSANDS OF BOSNIANS RETURN TO TRAGIC SITE FOR MEMORIAL SERVICE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By CARLOTTA GALL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SREBRENICA, Bosnia-Herzegovina _ Sitting on the grass weeping,
Tima Mehmedovic pointed to the spot where she had last seen her
husband. Five years ago to the day, he was among thousands of men
from Srebrenica who were taken away by Serbian forces and killed in
probably the worst massacre of civilians Europe has witnessed since
World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday she was among thousands of Muslim women and a few dozen
men, relatives of the dead or those still missing, who returned to
the site for a memorial service. They came in fleets of buses,
under heavy police protection. Many of them, like Mehmedovic, were
returning to their hometown for the first time since those fateful
days in 1995, when at the height of the war in Bosnia they were
separated from the men, herded on to buses and trucks and deported.
</P>
<P>
   More than 3,500 people attended Tuesday's short prayer service
in the compound of a vacant battery factory, women in traditional
head-scarves and baggy pants mingling with Western diplomats and
United Nations officials. Alija Izetbegovic, the Bosnian Muslim
leader, also attended, the first high-level Bosnian official to
visit the scene since the war.
</P>
<P>
   Srebrenica represents the darkest days of the war not only for
the Bosnian Muslims, but also for the United Nations and its
troops, whose task had been to safeguard the town, but who failed
in the face of the Serbian onslaught. In recognition of that failed
mission, U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan sent a message to the
people of Srebrenica on Tuesday expressing his remorse.
</P>
<P>
   For the Serbs now living in the area, the subject is explosive
and the ceremony was an unwelcome reminder of the world's
opprobrium for the massacre. Srebrenica is now populated only by
Serbs and lies in the Serbian entity within Bosnia, where few
Muslims have dared return since the war.
</P>
<P>
   Townspeople stood on street corners to watch the buses go by and
a few young men made gestures and whistled and jeered. ``They want
to blame the Serbs for everything and want the world to think the
Serbs are bad,'' said Stevo Lazarevic, a car factory worker who
stood with a group of Serbs watching the buses arrive.
</P>
<P>
   But the day passed without any violence. ``We came here, not to
take revenge, not to forgive,'' said Mustafa Ceric, the chief
Muslim cleric in Bosnia, as he led the prayers. ``We are here to
let the world know that we will not abandon our request for
justice.''
</P>
<P>
   For Mehmedovic, a mother of three, it was both frightening and
painful. ``I don't know what I feel, but it's very hard,'' she
said, twisting a handkerchief in her hands. ``I will never forget
this place, but I am afraid of going crazy,'' she said, looking
around tearfully.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, she had sought refuge in the factory compound with her
husband and grown son, along with about 20,000 others, hoping that
the 450 Dutch troops stationed here would ensure their protection.
After two days in the compound, a Serbian soldier allowed her and
her son to get on a truck and leave as her husband was held back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I last saw him standing on the asphalt road there,'' she said,
pointing to the entrance to the compound. ``I do not know what
happened to him. We never found him. We do not know anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of men disappeared during those few days. Hundreds
were separated from their wives and children in front of the Dutch
troops at the compound and were hauled off and executed. Thousands
more tried to escape through the wooded hills to avoid the Serbian
military and make the long trek to Bosnian-controlled territory.
Only a few made it; the vast majority were killed on the way or
captured and then shot in mass executions.
</P>
<P>
   Those buried in mass graves in the area were moved and reburied
in some cases. Many of the men who died in the hills have never
been found.
</P>
<P>
   War crimes investigators have found and exhumed more than 4,000
bodies from sites in the area but have been able to identify only
80, according to Kathryne Bomberger of the International Commission
on Missing Persons. The slow process of identification means that
hundreds or even thousands of relatives are still waiting for news
about their loved ones.
</P>
<P>
   ``This day is shameful for the international community,'' said
Kadira Jusic, a neighbor of Mehmedovic, sitting beside her on the
grass. ``Why did they let them kill us? They were innocent people,
all of them who died. And it's shameful that five years later we
cannot find their bodies,'' she said, her voice sharp, her eyes
brimming with tears.
</P>
<P>
   Reconciliation between Serbs and Muslims remains far off and
plans for refugees to return home remain just that. Only three
Muslims have returned to live in the town of Srebrenica, which is
filled with Serbian refugees from other areas, and they face a
precarious existence. Serbs have set fire to at least four houses
in Srebrenica in the last month, targeting those being prepared for
returning Muslims. Just hours before Tuesday's ceremony another
house was ablaze, that of an old Muslim woman who had been planning
to return home in two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Hajrudin Nalic, 45, is one of the three Muslims who have
returned. He reclaimed his flat in May and keeps a low profile,
drinking coffee with the old neighbors he knew from before but not
mixing with the newcomers. ``The first night I was very scared, but
I have not been threatened,'' he said. He has painted the flat and
is planning to bring his wife and two daughters to join him.
``Everyone has to go back to their homes,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Unemployed and struggling to pay rent in Tuzla, he had decided
to try to come back and reclaim the cafe he used to run in
Srebrenica. Yet a month ago, the cafe was looted, then demolished,
brick by brick. ``I do not take it as a message to leave but I am
not sure if I can manage now,'' he said sadly. ``But I am going to
try. That's why I came.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
