<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-11 19:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9330 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-CHRIS-ISAAC-COX     07-11 0494
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHRIS-ISAAC-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Quipster rocker Isaak a TV star-to-be
 &HT;    By Kevin Thompson
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ Who is Chris Isaak? And more important, why
is Showtime giving him a series?
</P>
<P>
   Those were the first questions on my mind after learning some
minor rock star with cool hair was going to star in his own Larry
Sanders -like show. While I've heard Isaak's sultry ``Baby Did A
Bad Bad Thing'' many times _ how could you miss the commercials for
Stanley Kubrick's ``Eyes Wide Shut?'' _ I never knew it was Isaak
who sang it.
</P>
<P>
   But during his hilarious 30-minute chat with reporters during
the Television Critics Association press tour, I understood why
Showtime likes this guy. Seen-it-all TV critics don't laugh much
during this 21-day conference where the new fall shows, movies and
specials are unveiled. Isaak, however, had us all in stitches. Try
getting a straight answer from him. Good luck. You'll have a better
chance of finding Jimmy Hoffa.
</P>
<P>
   For instance: Chris, how did the show come about?
</P>
<P>
   ``They came to me and said, `Chris, you have relatively little
or no talent... maybe rock 'n' roll wasn't the place for you. Maybe
TV is where you'll be better used.'''
</P>
<P>
   With cameras following you around, is ``The Chris Isaak Show''
jumping on the reality TV craze?
</P>
<P>
   ``No, we're not trying to copy or hop on that bandwagon.
Although, every week, we do vote out one member.''
</P>
<P>
   What will your fellow musicians think of the show?
</P>
<P>
   ``The musical community doesn't get cable... they're musicians,
you know. If they see it, they'll go, `How are you here? I just saw
you on TV.'''
</P>
<P>
   OK, we tried.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Chris Isaak Show ''debuts in December and will air for 17
weeks. And if Isaak is as quick-witted as he was last weekend,
Showtime could have a hit on its hands. The behind-the-scenes
series promises to take an irreverent look at the sinful,
party-all-the-time world of rock music. Isaak, who plays a
``version'' of himself, his real life band members and a team of
fictional characters will be shadowed by cameras on the road, in
the studio and everywhere in between. Think Big Brother meets
Behind the Music.
</P>
<P>
   The series has writers, but I'm not sure if they're needed. It
would be hard to top Isaak's off-the-cuff riffs. ``He's such a
funny guy,'' says Andrew Schneider, the show's executive producer.
``We just follow him around with a tape recorder. It's the easiest
job we ever had.''
</P>
<P>
   It's easy to understand why people will compare Isaak's series
to ``The Larry Sanders Show''. But Isaak says that would be a
mistake. ``I don't think we could do his show, or if we tried, we'd
probably fall short,'' says Isaak, sounding serious for the first
time. His somber tone didn't last long, though.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's going to be more like `The Monkees','' Isaak
says, cutting a devilish smile. ``Only filthy.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
