<SLUG> BC-FBN-IRVIN-RETIRE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cowboys Irvin makes official his retirement
 &HT;    By Ken Sugiura
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA - He strutted, preened and ran afoul of the law. He
caught passes, won Super Bowls and played until common sense
dictated he could not play anymore.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe no one stood as a symbol of the success and the reckless
behavior of the 1990s Dallas Cowboys more than Michael Irvin, the
star wide receiver who was both playmaker and troublemaker.
</P>
<P>
   Irvin, 34, announced his retirement Tuesday afternoon at Texas
Stadium in Irving, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to say goodbye,'' said Irvin.
</P>
<P>
   Irvin was one-third of the celebrated Cowboys offensive
triumvirate, with quarterback Troy Aikman and running back Emmitt
Smith, that returned the team to its former glory. The final
first-round pick made in Tom Landry's 29-year tenure as the
Cowboys' coach, Irvin helped raise Dallas from the depths of a 1-15
season in 1989 to three Super Bowl titles, 1992, 1993 and 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Irvin's season and ultimately his career ended Oct. 10 at
Philadelphia's Veterans Stadium. After catching a pass from Aikman,
Irvin's head slammed into the turf, and he became temporarily
paralyzed. Tests revealed that he had been born with a narrow
spinal column, which put him at greater risk to suffer permanent
paralysis if he sustained another neck injury.
</P>
<P>
   The reception from Aikman was the 750th of his career, tying him
with Hall of Famer Charlie Joiner for ninth in league history.
Irvin finished his 12-year career tied for third with seven
1,000-yard seasons. His 11,904 yards gained rank ninth. He holds
almost every Dallas career and season receiving record.
</P>
<P>
   Irvin's image, though, will extend beyond clutch first-down
catches and gyrating touchdown dances. The trouble he and his
Cowboy teammates found worsened an image problem that the NFL still
is fighting.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, Irvin was arrested in a drug bust in a hotel room in
the company of two self-employed models, only to ask the police,
``Can I tell you who I am?''
</P>
<P>
   He pleaded no contest to cocaine possession. On Thursday, Irvin
completed his four years of probation.
</P>
<P>
   Irvin will join Fox Sports Net as an analyst.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a sad day,'' Irvin said, ``but a great day.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
