r l BC-HANDYMAN-COX     07-11 1205
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HANDYMAN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Professional handymen supplanting the domestic variety
 &HT;    By Stephen J. O'Brien
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas - Like millions of American women these days, Waco
resident Janie Estrada doesn't always turn to her husband when a
man's touch is needed around the house. She often has to call in a
professional.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, she was looking for a few chores done when she
called Jim Jeffery, owner of Waco-based Old Fashioned Services, a
professional handyman business.
</P>
<P>
   ``My husband doesn't have time to do a lot of things around the
house,'' Estrada said. ``His work keeps him very busy and it's
convenient to just call someone like Jim and have them come do
it.''
</P>
<P>
   It's the sad story of the near extinction of the domestic
handyman, who once roamed free in his native habitat, the American
homestead, fixing leaky faucets and cleaning stopped-up storm
gutters. Evenings and weekends were a time when the man of the
house donned a tool belt and went about taking care of the things
that make a house a liveable home.
</P>
<P>
   As Estrada can attest, though, times are different in the 21st
century. Busy schedules continue to decimate the last refuge of the
do-it-yourself species: free time. Add to the mix the fact that
people have more disposable income for hiring out professional
help, and you've got the perfect recipe for the eradication of the
domestic handyman.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still think men know how to fix things as much as they did
back in the old days, but they simply don't have time,'' said Waco
resident John Savage, who has been a professional handym
</P>
<P>
   an for 18 years. ``They have a jillion things to do. They just
don't stay at home anymore. They used to stay around the house on
the weekends with the kids and take care of things, but it's
different now.''
</P>
<P>
   As a construction worker, Estrada's husband easily has the
skills to take care of jobs around the house. But being a
successful builder means staying busy. That's when Jeffery's phone
rings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted some things hauled away, but my husband couldn't do
it,'' Estrada said. ``He could do that kind of stuff if he had more
time.''
</P>
<P>
   With fewer handyman husbands, professionals like Savage and
Jeffery have plenty of business. They're called on to trim trees,
clean gutters, repair dishwashers, install stereo systems and, of
course, fix leaky faucets. In the last 20 years, the demand for
professional handymen has expanded the once modest business into a
multimillion-dollar industry nationwide, according to the National
Association of Home Repair Clubs.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffery, who has been a professional handyman for more than 13
years, says most of his clients are either women who don't have a
man around the house or households with men not interested in
getting their fingers dirty.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got all kind of clients: retired people, doctors,
lawyers, widows, college kids. You name it,'' Jeffery said. ``I do
all kinds of things - just about any job you can think of other
than building things.''
</P>
<P>
   Hillsboro homeowner Richard Huley, 64, admits the average man
these days probably does less around the house than in previous
decades. His dad used to fix everything himself. Those skills were
passed down, but Huley said it's sometimes too easy to make a phone
call and pay a few extra dollars to have someone else worry about
the problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think back in the old days people fixed things up themselves
because they didn't have a choice,'' Huley said. ``They didn't have
the money to call someone up every time something broke.''
</P>
<P>
   With disposable income sitting in the bank account, homeowners
like Huley find plumbing projects and other household chores easy
to pass on to hired help, said Bill Augustine, president of the
association of home repair clubs.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of things a homeowner could do, but do you
want to do it?'' Augustine said. ``Is it worth your time? Being
able to do something and wanting to do it are two different
things.''
</P>
<P>
   The lack of fix-it-up gumption doesn't mean husbands and dads
aren't breaking sweat around the house, Augustine said.
</P>
<P>
   Homeowners who attend fix-it-up classes at the Home Depot in
Waco, for example, learn to take care of little jobs, but most of
do-it-yourself curriculum focuses on big-time projects like
building decks, laying tile and installing kitchen cabinets.
</P>
<P>
   ``We emphasize that we empower people to do things. This is one
way we do that,'' company spokeswoman Mandy Holton said. ``The
courses are very popular. People love to tackle big projects. When
someone comes over to your house, you want to show them something
you've built.''
</P>
<P>
   Fixing a dripping faucet apparently isn't glamorous enough.
</P>
<P>
   Some say it's a study in modern handyman philosophy, a
reflection of a Bob Vila generation hammer-bent on building
colossal decks and embarking on major projects. The old-fashioned
handyman, though, is missing, Augustine said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Back in the old days, you knew how to fix things and if you
didn't your neighbor did,'' he said. ``Somebody around you knew how
to work on plumbing, someone knew about electricity and there was
probably someone nearby who could work on cars. You asked for
advice on how to do things.''
</P>
<P>
   That's left women like Estrada looking for help.
</P>
<P>
   Hireahusband.com is a handyman company based in Dallas where
people can call professionals to take care of domestic repair jobs
once tackled by the man of the house. Waco school teacher Charis
Cavil is a good example. She said her husband, a teacher at Texas
State Technical College, is a good companion and a loving mate, but
when it comes to having a fix-it-up man around the house, she often
turns to the professionals.
</P>
<P>
   ``My husband stays pretty busy,'' Cavil said. ``Generally, we're
both pretty busy and when things go wrong we don't have time to fix
it or don't know how.''
</P>
<P>
   With the diminishing population of the domestic repairman has
risen people like Bob Lees, a 72-year-old professional handyman in
the Waco area. The retired engineer repairs electrical and
mechanical household items. He installs sound systems and does a
little painting, too. In the last year and a half he's hung about
200 ceiling fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``A great percentage of my regular customers are wives of
professional people,'' Lees said. ``(The husbands) don't want to
turn a screwdriver, don't have the time or don't know how.''
</P>
<P>
   Lees has worked for more than 500 homeowners since he started
the ``little'' business four years ago. It likely won't be slowing
down anytime soon, either. More and more people in the Waco area
and across the country feel crunched for time these days, and a
positive economic outlook means that for the foreseeable future,
they're likely to have the money to hire professionals.
</P>
<P>
   It's a promising future if you're in the business of being the
hired man around the house.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started by working around the neighborhood for ladies who
didn't have anyone to fix things,'' he said. ``It's grown from
there. Now, there's about as much work as I can handle.''
</P>
<P>
   Stephen O'Brien can be reached at sobrien(at)wacotrib.com or at
757-5722.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
