<HEADER>
A9339 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f BC-CHINA-PRIVATE-SECTOR-     07-11 0894
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-PRIVATE-SECTOR-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 JIAXING: and AMF.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Despite its free-market facade, even Shanghai's economy is less
than 10 percent private. Many of the city's chrome and glass
storefronts contain state-owned businesses or joint ventures
between state-owned and foreign companies. Collectives, businesses
owned by local government organizations, make up much of the rest.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, China's official media rarely use the term ``private,''
preferring to call such businesses ``people-operated.''
</P>
<P>
   The Communist Party's ambivalence toward the private sector is
evident even in Wenzhou, a coastal city in Zhejiang province that
is considered the cradle of the country's private economy. Ninety
percent of the people there are supported by private enterprise.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you get rich, remember your origins,'' reads a billboard
there bearing the likenesses of Mao Tse-tung, Deng Xiaoping and
Jiang Zemin above the road to the airport. A similar slogan is
painted in white Chinese characters on a red banner stretched
across one of the bustling thoroughfares in town.
</P>
<P>
   Jiang toured Wenzhou's biggest private companies in May and
championed the role of business in helping China develop. But he
also called for greater Communist Party representation in private
companies.
</P>
<P>
   China's private sector got its start 20 years ago near Wenzhou,
in the lush green hills surrounding the glassy Ou River. A small
river town named Qiaotou became a trading entrepot between Shanghai
button makers and garment factories farther down the coast after
Deng allowed free markets to sprout around the country.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, many Qiaotou families were making buttons themselves. They
pooled resources to build a button market, now housed in a new,
buttonlike circular building at the center of town.
</P>
<P>
   Jin Wenwu recalls growing up in a cramped three-story house
filled with buttons, which he sealed in plastic bags with heat from
a candle.
</P>
<P>
   By the time he was a teen-ager, the family had begun punching
buttons from plastic sheets and drilling holes in the buttons using
crude, hand-operated machines.
</P>
<P>
   The business grew along with others in town until there were too
many button makers, forcing a wave of mergers that created China's
first companies with shareholders. Jin now owns a 25 percent stake
in one of the merged companies.
</P>
<P>
   Above the roar of buttons tumbling in a dozen rotating polishing
machines, Jin says the government offers no help, but has not
interfered with his business either _ yet. An official called the
other day asking for a list of party members who work in his
factory.
</P>
<P>
   Because relationships with officials are still so crucial, many
private business owners are really just opportunists exploiting
their party connections. The resulting corruption has not helped
improve the private sector's image. One of the most celebrated
entrepreneurs, Mou Qizhong, was recently sentenced to life in
prison for fraud.
</P>
<P>
   Other businesses disguise themselves as government-owned
entities to survive. Guo Hongnian and four friends pooled $72,000
in 1992 to establish a liquefied cooking gas factory in Shanghai.
But as a private company, they could not get the proper license to
sell their gas.
</P>
<P>
   They paid a city-owned cooking gas supplier $30,000 in return
for registering them as a collective enterprise, and their business
took off. Its assets are worth about $12 million today.
</P>
<P>
   Much of China's economic growth in the last 20 years has come
from such variants of private enterprise. But the fuzzy ownership
structure has limited their growth into bigger companies. Banks and
outside investors are reluctant to finance the collectives because
it is not clear to whom the enterprises belong.
</P>
<P>
   When Guo, 52, wanted to cash out of the cooking gas concern, for
example, the city ruled that the assets belong to the collective
and that he and his friends are, in effect, nothing more than
employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll fight for these assets the rest of our lives,'' insisted
Guo, shuffling a sheaf of dogeared papers that he said proves his
case.
</P>
<P>
   Despite all the problems, there is a growing sense in China that
the private sector is an idling dynamo about to shudder to life.
All that is needed is a mechanism to give private owners access to
capital.
</P>
<P>
   The government is already talking about expanding the two stock
exchanges to make it easier for fledgling companies, including
private ones, to raise money. And it is talking about letting
foreign-owned companies list shares for buying and selling by
Chinese.
</P>
<P>
   That would encourage foreigners to pump money into young
companies because it would give investors an easy way to get their
money out later.
</P>
<P>
   Already, Internet companies are providing the most energetic
private business growth because of foreign venture capital pouring
into the country.
</P>
<P>
   Given the current harsh environment, those private companies
that do play by the rules and survive end up remarkably healthy,
with resilient streams of revenue.
</P>
<P>
   Yu quit a state-owned machine tool factory to start repairing
trucks in 1977. The business grew along with traffic on the roads
and he never needed to borrow.
</P>
<P>
   Having beaten the system once, he is confident his new venture
will succeed even though he has never been up in a blimp. ``When we
build one, I'll be the first passenger,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
