<HEADER>
A9340 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-HOCKEYDAD-KILLING-BOS     07-11 0827
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOCKEYDAD-KILLING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME PROTEST LIGHTNESS OF CHARGE IN HOCKEY DAD DEATH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOANNA WEISS AND ERICA THESING  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   READING, Mass. _ They're still reeling from the knowledge that
an infamously brutal fight took place in their town. Now, nearly a
week after Michael Costin was beaten to death at a local hockey
rink _ and days after Thomas Junta was charged with manslaughter _
residents of this woodsy bedroom community have a new concern.
</P>
<P>
   Given the shockingly violent nature of Costin's death, many say
the charges against Junta seem too light.
</P>
<P>
   ``If serious consequences aren't faced by people who are
consumed by that kind of rage, I'm just concerned that we won't be
able to stem this kind of thing,'' said Selectman George Hines.
</P>
<P>
   Residents are voicing similar complaints to each other and in
telephone calls to Matthew Nestor, chairman of the Board of
Selectmen. A securities lawyer who spent five years as an assistant
district attorney, Nestor said he's received a stream of calls from
neighbors, friends and residents, asking why Junta, a Reading
resident who pleaded not guilty on Monday, wasn't charged with
second-degree murder.
</P>
<P>
   ``When people initially come up to me, it's with puzzlement and
confusion,'' Nestor said. ``I have to tell you, I'm sending them
away mad.''
</P>
<P>
   Nestor said he disagrees with District Attorney Martha Coakley's
office, and believes the charges against Junta should have been
upgraded from the start.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors have said that after a verbal argument about rough
play by youngsters during a practice session escalated into a
shoving match, Junta, 42, pinned Costin, 40, to the ground, held a
knee to his chest, and banged his head against the ground until
Costin lost consciousness.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors charged Junta with a misdemeanor _ assault and
battery _ just after the fight, allowing him to go free until
Monday's arraignment. The fact that Junta turned himself in to
authorities before his arraignment, Nestor said, likely contributed
to Junta's relatively low bail.
</P>
<P>
   While prosecutors asked for $250,000 bail, District Judge Thomas
Brennan set it $50,000 surety or $5,000 cash, which his family met.
</P>
<P>
   But Nestor said Junta could have been charged with assault with
a deadly weapon: the concrete floor of the Burbank Ice Arena. And
he said he believes that Junta's actions meet the criteria for
second-degree murder.
</P>
<P>
   A murder, by law, is defined as an unlawful killing accompanied
by malice. And prosecutors can prove malice by demonstrating one of
three things: intent to kill, intent to cause grievous bodily
injury, or intent to cause an action that a reasonable person would
know creates a substantial likelihood of death or grievous bodily
harm.
</P>
<P>
   At the very least, Nestor said, Junta should have known that
bashing the Lynnfield man's head into concrete could cause
``grievous bodily harm.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very puzzled,'' Nestor said. ``Those facts _ it's not even
a close call.''
</P>
<P>
   Anson Kaye, a spokesman for Coakley, said he couldn't discuss
details of the case. He did say that the district attorney's office
and police gave ``all due regard'' to the circumstances of the
case, and that ``the facts support a charge for manslaughter.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Kaye, a manslaughter charge must show ``a death
resulting from a reckless and wanton act,'' such as ``assault and
battery that results in death, or excessive use of force in
self-defense.''
</P>
<P>
   A second degree murder charge, Kaye said, requires ``probable
cause for malice, which includes a specific intent to kill.''
</P>
<P>
   At his arraignment, Junta's attorney Thomas Orlandi, said Junta
acted in self-defense. He said he started the confrontation because
he wanted to protect the children on the ice, who were playing
roughly under Costin's supervision.
</P>
<P>
   Several residents said the same. ``Five-thousand-dollar bail is
a ridiculously low bail. I think bail should have been set much
higher and I think he should have been held.''
</P>
<P>
   But others said they would accept the court's decision, and
defer to legal professionals.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all part of the judicial system. That's what it exists
for,'' said Peter True, 59, a resident here for 30 years. ``People
have opinions about it, but that's life. The court's there for a
reason.''
</P>
<P>
   Nearly everyone interviewed expressed concern for Junta's wife
and children, who are well-known in sporting circles in this
sports-hungry town. Junta's wife coaches local kids in swimming,
and his daughter is a star on the high school girls' hockey team.
</P>
<P>
   Hines said he believes local residents will treat the rest of
the Junta family with sympathy and kindness.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people are realistic about assessing where the blame
belongs,'' he said. ``I don't think they'd snub his family. But
they do think the blame belongs with him, and what he did goes
beyond acceptable behavior.''
</P>
</TEXT>
