<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-ISRAEL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISRAELIS DEMONSTRATE FOR AND AGAINST BARAK'S PEACE EFFORTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (With MIDEAST-TALKS) 
 By JOEL GREENBERG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ As the Camp David summit meeting got under way
Tuesday, Vered Melki stood on a curbside near the residence of
Prime Minister Ehud Barak and held up a hand-lettered sign that
said, ``Go _ bring us peace.''
</P>
<P>
   She was one of about 1,500 demonstrators who turned out for a
rally in support of the embattled prime minister, whose governing
coalition and parliamentary majority crumbled this week, but who
insists he still has the popular backing of the Israelis who
elected him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have the feeling that this is the moment of truth, and after
all the politics recently, I wanted Barak to see that there are
people behind him and that he's not alone,'' Melki said.
</P>
<P>
   The summit meeting is raising the political temperature on the
streets here. The rally Tuesday evening was one of a series of
demonstrations by both supporters and opponents of Barak and his
peace efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Near Barak's residence Tuesday evening, motorists could choose
from competing bumper stickers handed out by teen-agers. One said:
``The majority has decided: peace.'' Another warned: ``Barak is
losing the country.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, Jewish settlers and their supporters on the
political right, alarmed by the prospect of a handover of land they
live on to the Palestinians, have dominated, holding protests and
posting signs that proclaim: ``Uprooting settlements tears apart
the nation,'' and ``You don't abandon your brothers.''
</P>
<P>
   Their activities _ which included a prayer meeting Tuesday at
the Western Wall and the start of a hunger strike by founders of
the settlement movement _ are expected to climax in a mass
demonstration on Sunday night in Tel Aviv.
</P>
<P>
   Peace advocates, fearing that Barak might be exposed to the kind
of incendiary protests that preceded the assassination of Prime
Minister Yitzhak Rabin in 1995, have vowed to respond, starting
with the rally Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea is to have a presence on the street, to counter the
impression that the public is against the peace process, which is
simply not true,'' said Galia Golan of the Peace Now movement.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the turnout at the pro-Barak demonstration Tuesday night was
lower than expected by organizers. This was despite persistent
calls in the media in recent days by prominent liberal writers,
among them Amos Oz, for an outpouring of public support for the
prime minister.
</P>
<P>
   Many people who back the peace effort were too complacent, said
Moshe Hay, who came to the rally from Kibbutz Dvir. ``They figure
that Barak will do the job,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   There seems to be a greater sense of urgency in the rightist
camp, especially among settlers afraid they may lose their homes.
</P>
<P>
   On the fringes of the peace rally Tuesday night, a group of
schoolchildren brought in from the West Bank settlement of Rimonim
held up signs and chanted slogans.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want peace, but not at our expense,'' said 12-year-old
Dotan Cohen. ``Barak is selling us out.''
</P>
<P>
   A more ominous tone was struck by a handful of placard holders
from the banned extreme rightist party Kach, who sang, ``He's a
traitor,'' an epithet they had hurled at Rabin.
</P>
<P>
   At the pro-Barak rally, Rabin's daughter, Dalia Rabin, a member
of parliament, promised that this time such slogans would not go
unanswered.
</P>
<P>
   ``The street will feel, the street will know, the street will
see who the real majority is,'' she said, ``and it is no longer
silent.''
</P>
</TEXT>
