<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-SUMMIT (Washington) _ Nudged by President Clinton's call
for ``principled compromise,'' Israeli and Palestinian negotiators
set off on the latest quest for Mideast peace at Camp David, the
isolated presidential retreat in rural Maryland. By GREG McDONALD.
</P>
<P>
   ESTATE-TAX (Washington) _ As the Senate moves toward repeal of
the federal estate tax, Republicans and Democrats are fighting a
public relations war over who would be helped by the measure. A
look at the numbers shows the answer is: only the very rich. By
MARK HELM. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   SF-AIDS (Washington) _ San Francisco's share of federal money
for AIDS treatment and prevention per patient is nearly twice that
of other cities with high rates of the disease, the General
Accounting Office tells a congressional panel. Amid strong
resistance from lawmakers and officials in the San Francisco Bay
Area, key House negotiators have cut the city's share of AIDS funds
while increasing money for 50 other cities. By JUDY HOLLAND.
(Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL NEWS (``i'' category)
</P>
<P>
   HIV-CHILDREN (Durban, South Africa) _ Of the estimated 10,000
American children born with HIV caused by mother-to-infant
infection, some 2,400 are now teen-agers, according to a new report
presented at the International AIDS Conference. These youngsters,
some of whom have been taking 15 to 17 pills a day for their entire
lives, are about to become sexually active. By LEIGH HOPPER.
(Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   VIDEO-BIRTHS (Houston) _ Some hospitals have begun banning
couples from videotaping the birth of a child out of concern the
tapes could be used in lawsuits. The restriction stems from a $15
million settlement a hospital paid to a family that had claimed its
video showed evidence of malpractice. By LISA TEACHEY.
</P>
<P>
   SPACE-STATION (Houston) _ Hoping to cast aside a two-year legacy
of delay, Russia prepares to launch its large crew module to the
international space station. Secured atop a Proton rocket, the
43-foot-long spacecraft will house astronauts assigned to live and
work aboard the station. By MARK CARREAU.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ The minority political parties are
making merry mischief in this campaign for George W. Bush and Al
Gore. Patrick Buchanan's raw power grab in the Reform Party and
Ralph Nader's opportunism as the Green Party nominee are disgusting
to watch. They could be spoilers who distort the outcome of a close
race. The two-party system works just fine. Why can't we leave it
at that? By MARIANNE MEANS. (Already filed.)
</P>
</TEXT>
