<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-11 20:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9348 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-EPISCOPALIANS12-COX     07-11 0733
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EPISCOPALIANS12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Episcopal Church fails to endorse rite for same-sex union
 &HT;    By Gayle White
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ The Episcopal Church stopped just short Tuesday of
moving toward creating a rite that could be used by same-sex
couples in commitment ceremonies.
</P>
<P>
   The House of Deputies, half of the bicameral General Convention
of the 2.5-million-member denomination, overwhelmingly passed a
resolution recognizing that some people in the church live in
``lifelong committed relationships'' outside heterosexual marriage.
</P>
<P>
   But the body failed narrowly to ask for development of a liturgy
``by means of which the church may express'' support of committed
relationships outside the sacrament of marriage.
</P>
<P>
   A majority of both the lay delegations and clergy delegations in
the House of Deputies would have had to approve the request for it
to move into the House of Bishops for approval. It fell short by
fewer than five delegations in laity and one delegation in clergy.
</P>
<P>
   The House of Bishops is expected to take up the remainder of the
resolution today.
</P>
<P>
   The triennial General Convention was the third mainline
Protestant body to take up the issue this summer. Both the
quadrennial General Conference of the United Methodist Church and
the General Assembly of the Presbyterian Church (U.S.A.) rejected
efforts to recognize same-sex unions.
</P>
<P>
   Arguing against development of rites that would support same-sex
relationships, several deputies warned of an exodus of people who
disagree.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look around you,'' said the Rev. Kendall Harmon of South
Carolina. ``There are people sitting here today who will not be
here at the next convention . . . Let not this house tear asunder
what God has joined together.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Peter Cook of Western Louisiana said that to develop
rites recognizing same-sex relationships before the church takes a
theological position on the subject would be ``destructive to the
unity of our church.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I can imagine no greater recipe for confusion and division,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. William A. Doubleday of New York called the proposal
for rites a ``grace-filled resolution'' and said it would make the
church ``open to new ways of ministering to God's people.''
</P>
<P>
   Also speaking for the rites, the Rev. Michael W. Hopkins of
Maryland, national president of the Episcopal gay rights group
Integrity, said, ``to set standards without liturgical support is
to refuse to extend the best of pastoral care this church has to
offer.''
</P>
<P>
   The resolution as passed says the church expects relationships
to ``be characterized by fidelity, monogamy, mutual affection and
respect, careful, honest communication, and the holy love which
enables those in such relationships to see in each other the image
of God.''
</P>
<P>
   It never mentions homosexuality or same-sex relationships and,
in fact, leaves the door open for church support of heterosexual
relationships outside marriage.
</P>
<P>
   Herb Gunn, a lay deputy from Michigan, cited elderly couples who
might choose not to marry because of economic reasons but who want
their commitment to each other recognized by the church.
</P>
<P>
   ``In our diocese of Michigan, we've heard their appeals,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the other implications, both opponents and proponents of
same-sex unions saw the vote on establishing rights as a
significant step in setting church policy about homosexuality.
</P>
<P>
   ``It elevates the relationship between members of the same
gender ... to the same status as traditional heterosexual
marriage,'' said the Rev. David Anderson, a spokesman for the
American Anglican Council, a conservative caucus in the church.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson said he was pleased that the resolution brought the
issue into the open. ``It's an up or down vote'' on approval of
same-sex unions, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Susan Russell, a spokeswoman for Integrity, disagreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not black and white,'' Russell said. ``It's a continuum
of a process ... It's not the whole enchilada, but there's enough
guacamole here that I can go for it.''
</P>
<P>
   By setting a high standard for all relationships, she said, the
church is making ``a huge step forward, not just for gay and
lesbian people but for the church's understanding of marriage.''
</P>
<P>
   Gayle White writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
