<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-OLIGARCHS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUTHORITIES MOVE AGAINST LEADING ENERGY, MEDIA COMPANIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID FILIPOV  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Russian authorities Tuesday struck against several
leading energy and media companies suspected of wrongdoing, just
days after President Vladimir Putin promised to end special
privileges for the country's business elite.
</P>
<P>
   Police and security officials seized documents from a major
media company and Russia's largest natural gas conglomerate, filed
charges of tax evasion against the country's largest oil firm and
threatened criminal charges against the owner of a huge mining
concern unless he pays a $140 million fine.
</P>
<P>
   The moves against entrenched business elites here were
unprecedented in post-Soviet Russia, and unthinkable until Putin's
rapid rise to power. The companies involved owned by four powerful
members of the club known here as the ``oligarchs,'' tycoons who
have built business empires through what are widely seen here as
shady dealings and close ties to the Kremlin of former President
Boris N. Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
   Police and prosecutors gave no indication they were acting on
Kremlin orders, or that the raids were part of an organized action
against the oligarchs. But some observers saw a connection between
prosecutors' sudden desire to peer into the financial dealings of
conglomerates that have been thriving for years and Putin's
state-of-the-nation speech on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   There, Putin repeated his call to end favorable treatment for
Russia's biggest enterprises. He also suggested that private media
outlets have been turned into ``mass misinformation outlets and
into a means of struggle against the state.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It is clear that open season has been declared on the
oligarchs,'' commented Eric Kraus, an analyst at NIKoil investment
bank.
</P>
<P>
   Police and security officials seized bundles of documents
Tuesday from Media-Most company, Russia's largest privately owned
media empire, and its flagship NTV television station as officials
pursued their case against owner Vladimir Gusinsky.
</P>
<P>
   The raid there was the second in three months _ although this
time the police did not have masks and automatic weapons _ and it
followed Gusinsky's four-day detention last month when he was
charged with defrauding the government of $10 million. The
investigation of Gusinsky, whose media have criticized the Kremlin,
has brought widespread assertions from abroad and from liberals in
Russia that a press crackdown is under way.
</P>
<P>
   Another police raid targeted Media-Most's largest creditor and
shareholder, Gazprom, which owns a quarter of the world's natural
gas reserves. Some analysts believe the Kremlin has pressured
Gazprom to call in its loans, a move that would force Media-Most
out of business.
</P>
<P>
   Others suggest the moves are orchestrated by tycoons closely
linked to Putin's rise to the Kremlin, and known here as ``The
Family,'' to push out competitors. According to this line of
analysis, going after Gusinsky, one of the weaker oligarchs
financially, was the first shot of a campaign against bigger fish _
like Gazprom's head, Rem Vyakhirev.
</P>
<P>
   ``The golden dream of The Family is to take control over
Gazprom,'' said Andrei Ryabov, an analyst for the Carnegie Center
in Moscow. ``They send out these signals ... against Gusinsky as a
part of the pressure campaing against Gazprom.''
</P>
<P>
   Less likely, analysts say, is that the government is making good
on Putin's pledge to create an equal playing field for all
businesses. Analysts point to Putin's choice for chief prosecutor,
Vladimir Ustinov, whose history of Family ties suggest he will
continue the prosecutors' sad post-Soviet history of pursuing
inquiries on the basis of political expediency rather than
legality.
</P>
<P>
   One example may be the criminal case opened against the
leadership of Russia's largest oil company, Lukoil, for alleged tax
evasion. Earlier this year, said Kraus of NIKoil, which is partly
owned by Lukoil, the oil company won an award from Russia's chief
tax inspector for its honesty in paying taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Another case in point is the recent pressure put on the
businessman whose company has a controlling stake in Norilsk
Nickel, Vladimir Potanin. The Moscow prosecutor's office filed suit
last month saying that the company should be returned to the state,
but it was rejected. Excerpts of a letter to Potanin from First
Deputy Prosecutor Yury Biryukov, published Tuesday by a leading
newspaper, suggested the magnate pay $140 million to the state or
face criminal charges.
</P>
<P>
   ``This letter is a letter from a racketeer to a businessmen,''
said Boris Nemtsov, a senior legislator close to Potanin. Nemtsov
said he would suggest to Putin that the level playing field is not
happening.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly,'' he said, ``there are businessmen who are close to
the authorities, and businessmen who are far from them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
