<SLUG> BC-BKN-HAWKS-CAMP </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hawks' rookies, free agents get test as Atlanta Summer Shootout
opens
 &HT;    By Maiya Hayes
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA - It's time for redemption.
</P>
<P>
   After their 0-3 performance last year, the Atlanta Hawks are
shooting for an undefeated record in this year's Atlanta Summer
Shootout. The three-day tournament at Life University in Marietta
will match the Hawks' rookies and free agents against counterparts
from the Milwaukee Bucks, Miami Heat and Indiana Pacers.
</P>
<P>
   Hawks coach Lon Kruger said the shootout is just an extension of
practice. Kruger said he is not expecting his team to blow out
opponents or play flawlessly. His players have had just three days
of practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a case of trying to execute some things defensively,
execute some things offensively,'' Kruger said. ``Trying to
transfer some things from a practice situation to a game-like
situation. And that's all part of the development that takes place
individually and as a team.''
</P>
<P>
   Miami's team will feature second-round picks guard Eddie House
of Arizona State and center Ernest Brown of Indian Hills Junior
College. The Bucks' roster includes 7-foot-1 center Joel Przybilla,
the ninth draft pick acquired from Houston. Also playing for the
Bucks will be second-round guards Michael Redd of Ohio State and
Jason Hart of Syracuse. Forward Primoz Brezec of Slovenia and guard
Jaquay Walls of Colorado will play for the Pacers .
</P>
<P>
   Hawks rookie forward Hanno Mottola said he is not nervous about
today's game against the Heat. He said he expects Miami to be in
the learning phase, just as his team is.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their attitude is going to be the same as ours,'' Mottola
said. ``They're not going to have 12 veterans out there. It's going
to be the same kind of guys. I don't think anyone expects us to be
able to execute defensively and offensively with ease.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's going to be some struggle because it's still early,''
he said. ``As long as we try hard and try to improve every day, I
think that's the biggest thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Kruger has conducted motivational practices, in which players
and coaches have done a lot of supportive huddling and
hand-clapping. He said one of his main objectives has been to boost
players' self-confidence and energy levels for games.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to compete hard (and) play with enthusiasm and
intensity,'' he said. ``Otherwise, there's no reason to think that
you're going to do better than the other team. So, that's just a
starting point for the team, and these guys are establishing
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Guard Jason Terry didn't need a lot of encouragement to get
hyped for today's game. Terry, a rookie in last year's tournament,
said it is time for the Hawks to start a winning streak.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be exciting,'' he said. ``I'm ready to get back
out there after a disappointing season last year. This is the time
to get something back.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
