u p BC-BUSH-NYT &LR;      07-11 0659
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH URGES MOVES TO PROMOTE ADOPTION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mich.)   By ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROYAL OAK, Mich. _ Gov. George W. Bush declared Tuesday that
``foster care ought to be a bridge to adoption'' and called for
measures to promote adoption, including grants to states and an
increase in the adoption tax credit.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, the presumptive Republican presidential nominee, announced
the proposals as he returned to his ``compassionate conservative''
themes and planned several weeks of appearances devoted to social
welfare measures for low-income and struggling Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Bush illustrated the day's theme by visiting the Judson Center
here, which provides support services to families. He listened as a
panel of young people, parents and officials described their
experiences with foster care.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas governor briefly outlined his ideas to change foster
care from a permanent situation for many children to a way station
toward adoption or toward a child's return to his biological
family. He proposed $1 billion in grants over five years to be used
by states to try to keep children with their biological families if
those homes are considered safe.
</P>
<P>
   He also proposed increasing the adoption tax credit, which was
signed into law by President Clinton in 1996, to $7,500 from $5,000
at a cost of $1 billion over five years.
</P>
<P>
   And Bush called for spending $300 million more over the same
period to be used for vouchers to assist teen-agers, usually about
18 years old, who are leaving the foster care system. The vouchers,
of up to $5,000 per person, could be used for college tuition or
vocational training.
</P>
<P>
   The governor said he would require states to conduct criminal
background checks on prospective foster-care parents and adoptive
parents. Federal law currently allows states to opt out of the
checks.
</P>
<P>
   Bush pointed to his own state as a leader in improving foster
care and the adoption system. The number of children who can be
permanently adopted rose to 2,123 in 1999 from 1,033 in 1996
because of procedures developed to keep children from languishing
in foster care, an aide to Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   The Gore campaign immediately tried to undercut Bush's
credibility on children's issues by pointing to such findings as a
1999 report that ranked Texas next to last among the 50 states in
the number of children living in poverty.
</P>
<P>
   ``The facts speak for themselves,'' said Kym Spell, a Gore aide.
``Bush's record in Texas is short on compassion and long on broken
promises.''
</P>
<P>
   For most of the 45-minute panel session, Bush simply questioned
the panelists or listened as they told inspirational tales of
overcoming difficult family situations. Television cameras filmed
the kinds of scenes that have become a Bush campaign staple: the
candidate governor surrounded by minority children.
</P>
<P>
   ``I appreciate the spirit of love that exists inside these
walls,'' Bush said, as he sat under a blue banner proclaiming
``Strong Families, Safe Children.''
</P>
<P>
   Former Lt. Gov. Connie Binsfeld of Michigan told Bush that
states need more flexibility in using federal funds, as well as
more money to help foster parents who want to adopt children from
troubled homes but who cannot afford their medical and
psychological care.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could talk for two days, governor,'' she said, ``because _
''
</P>
<P>
   But Bush interrupted her, saying, ``I don't know if I could
listen for two.''
</P>
<P>
   At another point Bush hugged one of the two foster sons that
Sierra Craig was adopting as he talked to her about the adoption
tax credit. He tried to draw out her 11-year-old son, Eric.
</P>
<P>
   ``What grade are you in?'' the governor asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sixth,'' the boy whispered.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said: ``That's good. I was in sixth grade once, too.''
</P>
<P>
   The governor spent most of the day in this battleground state at
three receptions intended to raise nearly $2 million for the
national and state Republican parties.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
