<SLUG> BC-MICKEY-ART-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mickey Mouse art case has court date
 &HT;    By Bill Douthat
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Seizing early sketches of Mickey Mouse
in a foreclosure could expose the ``cultural treasures'' to
irreparable damage, an attorney for a financially strapped cartoon
museum argued in court Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Moving the fragile pencil drawings would take about three to
four weeks of preparation, attorney Nancy Colman told Circuit Judge
Water Colbath.
</P>
<P>
   SunTrust Bank asked Colbath Tuesday to grant it possession of
the sketches because the International Museum of Cartoon Art in
Boca Raton is $170,000 in arrears on mortgage payments. The museum
owes $1.1 million on a $3 million loan it took out in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   After listening to both sides for about a hour, Colbath said he
would issue a ruling later.
</P>
<P>
   The museum's curator testified that the 36 drawings are worth
from $3.2 to $3.7 million because they are the earliest existing
drawings of the cartoon figure that became the icon of Walt
Disney's entertainment empire.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are historic artifacts and they should not be endangered
unnecessarily,'' said curator Stephen Charla. ``They are at the
safest place they could be.''
</P>
<P>
   The drawings are not exposed to direct light and are protected
by a black cloth at night, Charla said. Sunlight and temperature
changes could be damaging, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Laslo G. Schwartz, a conservator who has inspected the drawings,
said they are regarded as ``Mickey Mouse's birth records'' and
deserve careful handling. Even tilting the framed drawings the
wrong way could rip the paper, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The bank's attorney, Lisa Hermann, said the bank would exercise
care in moving and storing the drawings.
</P>
<P>
   Hermann objected to the references to the drawings as cultural
treasures.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm failing to understand if they are such cultural treasures,
why would they be pledged for this loan?'' Hermann said.
</P>
<P>
   Colman said the bank and another guarantor of the loan requested
the drawings be included as collateral.
</P>
<P>
   The museum, opened in Mizner Park by Beetle Bailey creator Mort
Walker, is working with another financial institution to refinance
its mortgage, Colman said.
</P>
<P>
   billdouthat(at)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
