</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOUR-DE-FRANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARMSTRONG, THE LEADER, DISPLAYS POWER IN THE PYRENEES 
</HEADLINE>
   By SAMUEL ABT    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   REVEL, France _ ``The Tour is finished,'' Eddy Merckx decided
Tuesday. He found no dissenters. Who could disagree with a man who
won five Tours de France and 520 other races? Who, furthermore,
could disagree after watching Lance Armstrong break a lot of legs,
as the riders put it?
</P>
<P>
   ``He did a very strong ride, an exceptional ride,'' Merckx said,
referring to Armstrong's facile demonstration of power Monday in
the Pyrenees. ``It's over.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not only the best rider but the most serious. He races
all season, not just one month, like so many others,'' a dig at
those, unlike the Merckx of old, who care exclusively about victory
in the Tour de France. ``Lance has won his second Tour. What he did
yesterday nobody has done for years.''
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong, the Texan, and Merckx, the Belgian champion of the
1970s, long one of Armstrong's heroes, are close friends. That did
not appear to influence Merckx's judgment, which is universally
shared.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never seen anybody climb so swiftly,'' Raymond Poulidor,
who finished second in the Tour a handful of times in the days of
Jacques Anquetil and Merckx, said Tuesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Only Armstrong is still reserved about the outcome. ``Form is a
funny thing _ it comes slowly and goes away quickly,'' he said
Monday. Tuesday he said that he had balked at having Champagne
served at the team dinner after the Pyrenees stage because he
finished second, not first.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we win in Paris, there will be Champagne,'' he said, ``but
Paris is a long way off.'' The Tour ends there on July 23.
</P>
<P>
   Another former champion who raved about Armstrong's performance
was Greg LeMond, the other American who won the Tour and who is in
France for a reunion of his old Z team, with which he finished
first in the world's greatest bicycle race in 1989 and 1990. ``I
haven't seen anybody dominate a race like that, ever,'' said
LeMond, who also won the Tour in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   He watched the mountain stage on television. In it, the leader
of the U.S. Postal Service team built an overall lead of more than
four minutes over his rivals. Merckx watched it in person, offering
commentary for Belgian television then and his opinions Tuesday in
Revel as he awaited the finish of the 11th of 21 daily stages.
</P>
<P>
   With the rivals that Armstrong has buried in the standing
awaiting possible revenge on the next big climb on Thursday, two
low-ranked riders were given their freedom Tuesday. The two,
Santiago Botero, a Colombian with Kelme in 45th place, and Erik
Dekker, a Dutchman with Rabobank in 61st place, made the most of
it.
</P>
<P>
   Bolting away at Kilometer 14 of the 218.5-kilometer (135-mile)
jaunt, the two riders got as far as 14 minutes 44 seconds ahead.
</P>
<P>
   That was serious. Although Dekker started the day more than 26
minutes behind Armstrong, Botero was 17:40 behind. With the 14:44
lead, the Colombian was in second place over all on the road, the
realm of dreams. In addition, he is a good climber, unlike Dekker,
and could be a factor in the four days in the mountains ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Led by U.S. Postal Service, the pack began chasing and the lead
descended to manageable proportions. At the finish, Dekker was an
easy first in the sprint, completing the stage in 5:05:47, a speed
of 43 kilometers an hour (27 miles an hour).
</P>
<P>
   His victory in the second stage of the 87th Tour also increased
his lead in the race for the most aggressive rider. Botero
collected a bundle of points over six small climbs en route to
friendly Revel and rose from fifth to second place in the
competition for king of the mountains.
</P>
<P>
   The vanguard of the pack finished 4:51 behind the two leaders,
with a larger group 14 seconds slower.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong held his overall lead of 4:14 over Jan Ullrich, a
German with Telekom and the 1997 Tour champion, in second place and
5:10 over Christophe Moreau, a Frenchman with Festina, in third
place. Botero jumped to 30th place over all and Dekker to 47th.
</P>
<P>
   The stage began in Bagneres de Bigorre in the foothills of the
Pyrenees and wended east through placid countryside, with long
vistas of sunflower fields and pastures spotted with horses and
cattle. The narrow, curvy road passed through avenues of plane
trees and tidy villages.
</P>
<P>
   In short, the tourist's France. But any tourist coming here
should pack earmuffs and an umbrella. The weather was cool _ 14
degrees Celsius (57 Fahrenheit) near noon _ windy and
intermittently rainy. Summer seems to have skipped France this
year.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
