<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORLD-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIDDLE EAST
</P>
<P>
   IRAN: ACQUITTED IN STUDENT ATTACK
</P>
<P>
   A military court acquitted a former Tehran police chief of
ordering an attack on a student dormitory that led to a week of
pro-reform protests. The verdict brought immediate criticism from
students. Farhad Nazari and 17 subordinates were charged with
injuring scores of students and killing one in the attack last
July. Two defendants were found guilty. ``Such rulings will lead to
social insecurity and people will lose their confidence in the
judiciary,'' said Ibrahim Sheik, a student leader, a sentiment
echoed by other students.
</P>
<P>
   IRAN: KHATAMI PLEA TO U.S.
</P>
<P>
   President Mohammad Khatami, on a visit to Germany, urged the
United States to take the next step toward reviving diplomatic
relations with Tehran. ``You can be sure that when the United
States has the key in its hand, it will not give it away,'' he said
on German public television. He said he recognized a ``new turn''
in Washington, but that the shift did not go far enough.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   AUSTRIA: PANELISTS TO BE NAMED
</P>
<P>
   The European Court of Human Rights will announce today the names
of three people who will examine Austria's rights record. They will
concentrate on minority rights, refugees and immigrants and the
political nature of Joerg Haider's far-right Freedom Party. The
review could lead to an end to Austria's political isolation within
the European Union. Possible candidates are former President Martti
Ahtisaari of Finland; the former European Commission president,
Jacques Delors; former Prime Minister Carl Bildt of Sweden and the
onetime European Union human rights envoy to Bosnia, Elisabeth
Rehn.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN: ROYAL CENTENARY
</P>
<P>
   Britain began a formal celebration of the 100th birthday of the
Queen Mother with a full dress service of thanksgiving at St.
Paul's Cathedral attended by the British royal family, royalty from
other European countries, Prime Minister Tony Blair and other
senior politicians and uniformed men and women from military units
with which she is associated. The Queen Mother, whose birthday is
Aug. 4, took the cheers of thousands of well-wishers from the steps
of the church.
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO: 19 EX-AIDES HELD
</P>
<P>
   Authorities arrested 19 men who served as municipal officials in
Mexico City during the 1994 to 1997 tenure of former Mayor Oscar
Espinosa Villareal, charging them with crimes ranging from
embezzlement to abuse of authority. They were among 75 civil
servants sought in a corruption investigation led by the city's top
prosecutor, who has asked the Congress to impeach Espinosa, now the
tourism minister, on fraud charges.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA
</P>
<P>
   ETHIOPIA, ERITREA: U.N. ROLE
</P>
<P>
   A group of United Nations liaison officers will arrive in
Ethiopia and Eritrea by the end of next week, in the first stage of
a peacekeeping operation to enforce the cease-fire that the two
nations signed last month, a senior United Nations military
official said in Asmara, the Eritrean capital. But the official,
Maj. Gen. Timothy Ford, said it would be several months before the
full force was deployed. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
