<HEADER>
A9364 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-MENTALLYILL-COX     07-11 1085
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MENTALLYILL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Two celebrate end of battle to stay out of mental hospitals
 &HT;    By Bill Osinski
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA - Finally, E.W. and L.C. are home.
</P>
<P>
   At a hearing before a federal judge in Atlanta on Tuesday,
Elaine Wilson and Lois Curtis _ previously identified by their
initials in their struggle to stay out of state mental hospitals _
celebrated the end of their legal battle with smiles and carefully
thought-out responses.
</P>
<P>
   Their case has already had a significant impact on the way care
is provided to mentally disabled people nationwide, according to
mental health experts.
</P>
<P>
   Wearing their best blue dresses, Wilson and Curtis each
confidently strode to the courtroom podium to tell U.S. District
Court Senior Judge Marvin Shoob what their landmark victory means
to them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now that I'm in the free world, I love my freedom,'' said
Wilson, 48, who had been institutionalized at least 36 times.
``When I was in the hospital, I felt like I was in a little box,
and I couldn't get out.''
</P>
<P>
   Curtis, 32, said the settlement means she can now the right to
do little things she was never allowed to before, like go to her
room and listen to her radio.
</P>
<P>
   More than three years ago, Shoob ruled that arbitrarily denying
Wilson and Curtis a community-based life amounted to segregation of
persons covered by the Americans With Disabilities Act. Last year,
the U.S. Supreme Court upheld that ruling. On Tuesday, Shoob
accepted a joint final agreement between the two plaintiffs and the
defendant, the state of Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   The settlement provides a guarantee that Wilson and Curtis will
be provided community-based housing and training programs for the
rest of their lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a major civil rights decision,'' said Ira Burnim,
legal director of the Bazelon Center for Mental Health Law, in
Washington, D.C. The impact on mental health issues is comparable
to that of the Brown v. Board of Education decision in the area of
racial equality, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly half the states have already initiated planning on how to
comply with the decision, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sue Jamieson, the Atlanta Legal Aid Society attorney who
represented the two women, credited Shoob with setting the legal
precedent that led to the ultimate victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``We clung to your ruling like a lifeboat,'' she told the judge.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Supreme Court ruling, federal officials have told
Medicaid directors in every state that they must review their
funding patterns to provide community-based care for mentally
disabled clients who can function in community settings, she said.
In Georgia, a commission is expected to issue its report on the
issue to Gov. Roy Barnes this month.
</P>
<P>
   Legalities aside, Wilson and Curtis are proving the high court
right with practically every step they take in the real world. Both
women have major difficulties to deal with, but both say they're
doing just fine.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson has been in and out of state mental hospitals at least 36
times in her 48 years. Sometimes, she'd wind up on the streets.
</P>
<P>
   Life on the inside wasn't a horror story; mostly, it was just
bleak, Wilson said. ``They'd always tell you to take your medicine
and go sit down,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She and her mother got attorneys for the Atlanta Legal Aid
Society to take her case. (Later, Curtis was added as a plaintiff).
While the case progressed, she has lived in community-based housing
and attended training programs on weekdays. For the past nine
months, she has lived in the northwest Atlanta home of Sabrina
Sutton, a nurse and home care provider.
</P>
<P>
   Sutton said Wilson is becoming like a member of the family.
</P>
<P>
   ``Elaine has come a long, long way,'' she said. ``She picks up
on all the things the kids say. I deal with her like I do my
10-year-old.''
</P>
<P>
   There has been a dramatic decline in the types of behavior that
used to result in Wilson's return to the mental hospital, Sutton
said. Now, if Wilson starts to throw a temper tantrum, she's
reminded that she won't be permitted to go shopping if her behavior
doesn't improve. Usually, it does.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson doesn't even want to go to outpatient psychiatric
clinics, because she says, ``That's where crazy people go,'' Sutton
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody wants to be treated like they're somebody,'' Sutton
said. ``Everybody deserves a chance to live independently.''
</P>
<P>
   Curtis spent about half of her first 27 years in state mental
hospitals, and they don't teach manners there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lois used to be very combative and destructive,'' said Sandra
Shields, director of Foundation of Exceptional Achievers, the
training program that Curtis attends on weekdays. ``I've seen her
throw guys around.''
</P>
<P>
   Curtis had picked up a two-pack-a-day cigarette habit at the
hospitals, and she got to the point where she would make some very
inappropriate trades for cigarettes, Shields said. And when she
first came to the center, she'd scour the grounds for cigarette
butts, she said.
</P>
<P>
   But now, Curtis may still want a cigarette, but she stops and
says something like, ``I know it's not good for me,'' and she
passes.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of being withdrawn, she speaks up in classes. She's
working toward a general equivalency diploma. She has displayed
real talent in art, and her sketches of people she's met or seen in
magazines make for lively wall decor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know how to cook. I know how to clean. I know how to pay my
rent,'' Curtis said.
</P>
<P>
   No longer is Curtis treated as a defective person who must be
cut off from the rest of society, Shields said. ``Here, she just
has a disability she has to work on, like everybody else.''
</P>
<P>
   Burnim said despite the victory in Wilson and Curtis' case,
there are many thousands of people still needlessly confined in
state mental hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   The old thinking was that mental hospitals were ``safe havens''
for people who couldn't make it in the real world, he said. ``But
in fact, the dynamic is not good when you put a lot of people with
serious problems in the same place.''
</P>
<P>
   And in the hospital setting, he added, there's little chance to
learn real-world skills and little motivation to change bad
behaviors.
</P>
<P>
   In court Tuesday, Curtis told Shoob of the things she has
learned to do for herself. ``I take my medicine and bathe myself at
night, then I get up in the morning and make my own bed.''
</P>
<P>
   Responded the judge: ``You've done better than a lot of lawyers
who've appeared before me.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
