<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOCKHEED-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lockheed Martin plant greets leader
 &HT;    By Scott Thurston
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MARIETTA, Ga. _ It took Lee Rhyant awhile, but he's found his
way back to Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   Rhyant was born 50 years ago in the small South Georgia
community of Sasser. He left the state as a child and eventually
pursued a career in the auto and aerospace industries up north.
</P>
<P>
   Now he's returned as the new man in charge at Lockheed Martin's
aircraft plant in Marietta and the first African-American hired to
run it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a homecoming,'' Rhyant said Tuesday at a ceremony to
dedicate the first C-130J cargo plane being built at the plant for
the Italian air force.
</P>
<P>
   ``I plan to meet some relatives in Alabama and Georgia I've
never met,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Rhyant started work last week as vice president and site general
manager of the Marietta plant under a new management structure that
emerged from the consolidation of Bethesda, Md.-based Lockheed
Martin's aircraft operations earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   The shakeup put the Marietta plant under the control of a newly
created Lockheed Martin Aeronautics Co., based in Fort Worth,
Texas. It is headed by Dain Hancock, a Lockheed Martin veteran in
Fort Worth. Rhyant's predecessor in Marietta, Tom Burbage, is
executive vice president of the new unit.
</P>
<P>
   Terry Graham, who had been Burbage's No. 2 in Marietta, has
announced his retirement, and his chief operating officer position
won't be filled.
</P>
<P>
   That leaves day-to-day responsibility for Marietta operations
squarely in Rhyant's lap.
</P>
<P>
   Lockheed Martin announced Rhyant's hiring in mid-May, two days
after a group of African-American employees filed a racial
discrimination suit claiming mistreatment at the Marietta plant.
</P>
<P>
   The timing called extra attention to Rhyant's race.
</P>
<P>
   In a brief interview at Tuesday's C-130J ceremony he said there
was no connection as far as he's concerned.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can honestly say the process of my coming here is more than
a year old,'' he said. He said his presence will influence work
force issues ``only if I do a good job'' and declined specific
comment on the suit.
</P>
<P>
   Many other issues confront Rhyant. Employment at the plant has
dwindled to about 7,000 following a work-force reduction of more
than 20 percent initiated last year. It may drift lower in coming
months as Lockheed Martin finishes consolidating management layers
in the new aircraft unit.
</P>
<P>
   ``My challenge is to continue to make this plant very cost
competitive and make the transition to (a consolidated) company,''
Rhyant said. ``And we need to do it while upholding the dignity and
respect for all workers.''
</P>
<P>
   Rhyant, the plant's fifth chief in six years, said he expects to
make some operational changes but added it's too early to be more
specific.
</P>
<P>
   He said he believes the worst is over for the Marietta plant.
The plant's viability has been in question because of early
troubles in the 5-year-old C-130J program, along with doubts about
whether the plant's other primary product, the F-22 fighter, would
be built in Marietta or built at all.
</P>
<P>
   Lately, C-130J sales have gained some momentum and the F-22's
future appears more stable. Lockheed Martin announced last spring
it had decided against moving final F-22 assembly from Marietta to
Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel as though (the Marietta plant is) on an upward trend
now, or I wouldn't have come,'' Rhyant said. ``I made a very
conscious decision to make the change that I did.''
</P>
<P>
   After leaving Sasser, Rhyant lived in Florida and graduated from
Bethune-Cookman College. He moved to the Midwest to join Allison
Gas Turbine, a division of General Motors, in 1972 and held a
succession of plant management positions. He remained with the
company in Indianapolis after its acquisition by jet engine maker
Rolls-Royce.
</P>
<P>
   Most recently he was vice president of production operations for
Rolls-Royce.
</P>
<P>
   Rhyant and his wife, Evelyn, will live in east Cobb and have
grown twin sons.
</P>
<P>
   Hancock and Burbage also attended Tuesday's C-130J ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   Hancock agreed the Marietta plant's future has brightened. ``As
long as the C-130J and F-22 remain sound programs, we have a
healthy future,'' he said. Burbage said one of Rhyant's challenges
is to convince employees of that and end a brain drain among
engineers and technicians that's occurred as a byproduct of the
uncertainty.
</P>
<P>
   Burbage also said he hopes Rhyant's tenure will be longer than
that of the past few plant chiefs, including himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope we're past the point where we're trying something
different every year,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   LEE E. RHYANT
</P>
<P>
   _Title: Vice president and site general manager, Lockheed Martin
plant in Marietta.
</P>
<P>
   _Previous job: Vice president for production operations,
Rolls-Royce aviation engines, Indianapolis
</P>
<P>
   _Education: MBA, Indiana University; bachelor's degree in math
and business, Bethune-Cookman College
</P>
<P>
   _Age: 50
</P>
<P>
   _Family: Wife Evelyn, grown twin sons
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
