</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-REFUGEES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PALESTINIAN REFUGEES IN LEBANON ANXIOUS OVER SUMMIT 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV:  Photo NYT8  is being sent to NYT photo clients.  Map  is
being sent to NYT graphics clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase
one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(See also MIDEAST-TALKS) 
 By JOHN KIFNER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   AIN EL HILWE CAMP, Lebanon _ Ahmed Hajar carefully unfolded the
tattered deed, written in Arabic script, dated 1946, and affixed
with a double row of green and purple tax stamps from the British
Palestine mandate that described the farm his family owned in what
is now Israel.
</P>
<P>
   He showed the government of Palestine identity card, No. 3665,
that had belonged to his father, Mahmout. His elderly uncle,
Muhammad, sitting beside him on a couch in the two rooms where
seven people live in this fetid refugee camp, still carries his
identity card from the mandate, faded and worn.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then, we had workers on our land,'' the uncle remembered about
the farm where they grew oranges, bananas and vegetables near the
sea in a village then called Smeirya. ``Now we must work in other
people's lands. It is difficult when you have once been an owner.''
</P>
<P>
   They are among more than 3 million Palestinian refugees _ _
80,000 of them crammed into three-quarters of a square mile of
misery in this camp near Sidon _ whose future is one of the issues
facing the Camp David summit meeting opening Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 200,000 Palestinian refugees are still in Lebanon.
Times are hard for them here, but they sense that they are not on
the top of the negotiators' agenda. They are bitter and fearful as
they wait for news, worried that they will be left out of any
settlement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I must tell you, Arafat only represents himself,'' said
Mahmoud Haleilel, a 19-year old student. ``He does not represent
us.''
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-years ago, the refugees here were a swaggering, heavily
armed ``state within a state.'' But their presence annoyed many
Lebanese, particularly Christians, who feared they would be _ as
the phrase went _ ``implanted'' here, and they became an issue in
the bloody 15-year civil war.Now, the refugees are largely confined
to their camps and forbidden any but the most menial jobs.
</P>
<P>
   The 1982 Israeli invasion ended the Palestinian military
presence in mostly-Muslim West Beirut and in southern Lebanon.
Syria soon ousted Arafat's remaining forces around the northern
city of Tripoli. Battles between rival factions further weakened
the Palestinians. And from May, 1985, to April, 1987, the Shiite
Muslim Amal militia, acting at the behest of Syria, laid siege to
the Palestinian areas in the ``Camps War,'' in which more than
1,600 people died.
</P>
<P>
   The camps today are surrounded by Lebanese troops, staffing
sandbagged checkpoints in helmets and flak jackets despite the
sweltering heat. Though Palestinians traditionally have had a high
level of education, regulations issued in 1990 barred them from
more than 60 professions, including medicine, law and engineering.
</P>
<P>
   The camp itself is a warren of cinderblock houses, built
literally on top of each other, because there is no other room but
up. Tiny, dark passageways lead to crowded rooms. Children are
everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   The streets are so narrow that when two cars try to pass,
monumental traffic jams result, resolved only by much patient
backing and maneuvering. Walls are decorated with faded paintings
of the Palestinian flag, revolutionary slogans and old heroes like
Che Guevera. Clusters of young men stand about with nothing to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is like we are in a jail here,'' said Assef Moussa, 28,
launching into a hand-waving string of grievances, in which the
word  &UR; mamnoua &LR;  _ Arabic for forbidden _ figured repeatedly. Lately,
it seemed, the government had stopped construction materials from
coming into the camps in order to prevent any further building.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am a physician, but I don't have the right to work here,''
said Dr. Ahmad Ghassem Halabi, who is allowed to practice only at a
clinic inside the camp. ``Here we face a very difficult situation,
a miserable situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the families here fled from parts of northern Israel in
1948 and are now into their third generation as refugees. Many left
in the widespread panic over news of the massacre in the Arab
village of Dier Yassin.
</P>
<P>
   Some families still have the keys to their old houses, carried
with them because they believed the promises of Arab armies that
they would be back home in a week. The old people keep alive the
memories of more than half century ago. The young make grandiose
demands that they return to the old villages.
</P>
<P>
   ``My father gave me this before he died,'' said Ahmed Hajar, a
gray-haired man who was born here, smoothing out the torn folds in
the old deed. ``He told me also, the Jews pushed out the
Palestinians. Really, he said, they stole your land. Remember this.
Don't forget this. This is your country. Your country is very, very
beautiful.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What my father taught me, I teach my son,'' he added, putting
his arm around his big-eyed 13-year old son Mahmoud, adding that
he, like many Palestinians here, took his children on Sunday into
the area of south Lebanon Israel had occupied until May so he could
look across the border.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is your country,'' he asked gently.
</P>
<P>
   ``Palestine,'' the boy replied.
</P>
</TEXT>
