<SLUG> BC-CONVERGENT-TCS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONVERGENT BUYS FLORIDA TELECOM SOFTWARE FIRM 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn.: Fla.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER J. HOWE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Convergent Networks of Lowell, Mass., which makes advanced voice
and data telecommunications devices, said Tuesday it has spent more
than $100 million to buy a Florida telecom software company and
boost its product offerings and prospects for an autumn initial
public offering.
</P>
<P>
   Convergent is issuing stock with value ``significantly north of
$100 million'' to acquire Technology Control Services Inc. of Fort
Lauderdale, said Convergent chief executive John C. Thibault.
</P>
<P>
   TCS makes so-called softswitch products, which allow telephone
companies to add services such as call forwarding and calling cards
to their networks. Convergent sells combined voice-data switches
that use a fraction of the space of older telecom gear.
</P>
<P>
   The Convergent-TCS move mirrors recent efforts by Siemens AG to
create Unisphere Solutions of Chelmsford, Mass. from three area
telecom start-ups and a Siemens unit and the May acquisition of
Cornice Communications of Andover by Ennovate Networks Inc. in
Boxborough.
</P>
<P>
   In each case, companies aiming to go public have concluded they
can boost their value more quickly by acquiring other private
companies and building a bigger range of product offerings. Given
the recent choppiness in the technology IPO market, some analysts
think pre-IPO mergers make more sense for a start-up than going
public and then using their stock to buy companies to fill in
market gaps.
</P>
<P>
   Thibault said combining 100-person TCS with 140-person
Convergent ``on a pre-IPO basis gives us a company with much more
value than the two parts on a standalone basis.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We think this positions us uniquely in the marketplace'' by
being able to offer by fall a ``next generation broadband switch''
that includes calling services that now would require partnerships
with at least two other vendors, Thibault said. It will also speed
Convergent's move into global markets by a year or more.
</P>
<P>
   TCS customers include British Telecom, which uses its switching
platform for a unified messaging service combining e-mail, voice
mail, and faxes. Convergent has announced sales of over $50
million, including pacts with Global NAPS of Quincy, WanTel of
Oregon and Duro Communications of Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Silicon Valley networking giant Cisco Systems Inc. owns a
minority interest in TCS and will carry that stake over to
Convergent.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether he would be interested in a sale of the company to
acquisition-hungry Cisco as an alternative to going public,
however, Thibault said, ``We are exclusively focused on building
the company as an independent entity and we look forward to
completing an initial public offering later on this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe we have an opportunity like a Sonus Networks or a
Sycamore or an Akamai,'' three of the hottest recent local telecom
startups to go public, ``to build a company of substantial value to
our shareholders and customers and employees,'' Thibault said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-11-00 2027EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
