<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-11 20:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9368 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-MIDEAST-TALKS-ART-2TA     07-11 0840
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-TALKS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISRAELI AND PALESTINIAN LEADERS BEGIN SUMMIT MEETING AT CAMP
DAVID 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: 2nd Take is scheduled to move by 9:30 pm ET) 
(ART ADV: Photos _ NYT2,3,4 _ are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients. Nonsubscribers can
purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By DEBORAH SONTAG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   THURMONT, Md. _ Israeli and Palestinian leaders began their
fateful peace summit at Camp David on Tuesday with the far-reaching
goal of ending their 52-year-old conflict.
</P>
<P>
   On the first day of an open-ended, tightly secluded meeting,
President Clinton ushered the leaders into the presidential retreat
where he hopes that the chemistry of the place and the moment can
induce a spirit of ``principled compromise'' that yields a
substantive peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, the only one of the three leaders who spoke publicly on
Tuesday, talked in idealistic terms about securing a ``just and
enduring end'' to the conflict and about the ``gift of peace'' that
the leaders could give their children. But officials on all sides
acknowledge that a good, partial agreement would represent a
significant accomplishment and may be the only realistic end to
this fluidly scheduled, seat-of-the-pants-style summit meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, there is no guarantee of success,'' Clinton said at
the White House before flying to Camp David. ``But not to try is to
guarantee failure.''
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to erase a point of friction with the Americans,
Israel appears ready to announce soon that it will abandon or
postpone its $250 million deal to sell the Phalcon aircraft
advanced radar system to the Chinese. Israeli government spokesmen
said on Tuesday night that the Israeli-American dispute over the
plane, which has soured relations between Israel and many of its
backers in the administration and on Capitol Hill, will be resolved
by the end of the summit.
</P>
<P>
   Arriving for their opening three-way meeting on Tuesday
afternoon, Prime Minister Ehud Barak of Israel and Palestinian
leader Yasser Arafat did a smiley little dance at the entrance to
the Laurel Cabin at Camp David. It was a stubborn jig as each
sidestepped to try to make the other enter first into the crucible
of decision-making.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, with Barak's hand on his elbow, Arafat crossed the
threshold one beat ahead of the Israeli prime minister, who
constantly says that, ``It takes two to tango,'' for peacemaking to
work.
</P>
<P>
   The light-hearted but highly principled moment offered a glimpse
at the steely determination with which each Middle Eastern leader
is approaching the negotiating table, a rectangular one,
apparently, at which 21 American, Israeli and Palestinian delegates
sat on Tuesday to open their talks. But it was the only glimpse
offered into what the Americans, imposing a news blackout, are
trying to make an airtight environment safe from the pressures of
public scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   ``The atmosphere is good, and the mood is serious,'' Joe
Lockhart, the White House spokesman, said. And that is about all he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Under leafy boughs, and in cabins named for trees, the Israelis
and the Palestinians were transported far from the cramped, dusty
and conflicted Middle East into the expansive, verdant hills of
Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   Barak was far away from the political crisis that crippled his
government on Monday, and Arafat was nowhere near the demonstrators
who marched on Tuesday in the West Bank to demand that he not sell
them out.
</P>
<P>
   Barak was placed in the Dogwood Cabin, which President Anwar
Sadat of Egypt stayed in 22 years ago when the successful
Israeli-Egyptian peace summit opened to complete public skepticism
about what it could accomplish. Arafat was given the Birch Cabin
that Prime Minister Menahem Begin of Israel occupied then.
</P>
<P>
   Publicly, in what seemed a vivid illustration of why the
Americans are imposing the news blackout, senior negotiators for
the two sides have expressed contrasting views of the possibilities
of achievement. Shlomo Ben Ami, the Israeli internal security
minister, said on Monday that he felt confident that an agreement
could be reached. Abu Ala, speaker of the Palestinian legislature,
said that he did not comprehend how Ben Ami could speak with such
confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Palestinian position will never change,'' Abu Ala said in
an interview with the Voice of Palestine. ``And the Israeli
positions have its well-known `no's.' So how can the minister talk
about an agreement?''
</P>
<P>
   Israeli television reported on Tuesday night that the Americans
want all the thorny issues _ borders, Jewish settlements in the
West Bank, Palestinian statehood, water, the fate of the
Palestinian refugees and the future status of Jerusalem _ to be
discussed in parallel at the talks. This would put Jerusalem, a
seemingly irresolvable point of contention, on the formal
negotiating table for the first time in the seven years since the
Israelis and the Palestinians have been talking.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-11-00 2030EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
