<DOCNO> NYT20000711.0318 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-11 20:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9369 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-JANUS-MARKETPLACE-NYT     07-11 1151
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JANUS-MARKETPLACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET PLACE: SPINOFF OF JANUS MAY BE HELD DOWN BY COMPANIES IT
KEEPS 
</HEADLINE>
   By DANNY HAKIM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   What is Janus Capital worth?
</P>
<P>
   Janus, the nation's hottest seller of mutual funds, will be
officially spun off Wednesday from its parent, the railway operator
Kansas City Southern Industries.
</P>
<P>
   For over a year, Janus executives and some of its top fund
managers have openly denounced the transaction because the fund
company is being packaged with Kansas City Southern's three other,
far smaller financial holdings under the name Stilwell Financial
Inc. The executives argue that their company would be assessed a
greater value in the market if it traded on its own.
</P>
<P>
   A recent spate of acquisitions, spurred in part by a growing
appetite for globalization, has indeed put lofty prices on some
asset managers, far more than that put on the Stilwell offering.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think investors will continue to push management to unlock
the value of Janus,'' said Henry McVey, an analyst at Morgan
Stanley Dean Witter.
</P>
<P>
   In the most heated of the recent deals, Thomas F. Marsico, once
the star manager of the firm's Janus Twenty fund, agreed to sell
the remaining half of his three-year-old company, Marsico Capital
Management, to Bank of America. The transaction values Marsico at
$1.1 billion. Given that the fund complex manages about $15
billion, most analysts consider it a generous price at 7.3 percent
of assets.
</P>
<P>
   Using that pricing benchmark, Janus, which manages $309 billion,
could be worth more than $20 billion. By comparison, Stilwell,
which includes Kansas City Southern's stakes in the asset managers
Berger Associates and Nelsons Money Managers as well as the
financial services data processing firm DST Systems _ had a market
capitalization of $9.8 billion as of Tuesday's close. (The stock
has been trading on a so-called when-issued basis, which allows for
transactions in anticipation of a security's issuance.)
</P>
<P>
   Acquisitions, of course, often bring premiums to public
companies, in anticipation of synergies. And some other recent
deals have been for less lofty prices than Marsico's. At the low
end, United Asset Management has agreed to be acquired by the South
African money manager Old Mutual for less than 1 percent of its
assets. More typical pricing has been 2 to 4 percent of assets,
though stock analysts say cash flow may be a more useful measure
than assets under management.
</P>
<P>
   Still, should Janus not merit a top-tier valuation? After all,
the company, noted for its big bets on technology stocks, has
arguably been the mutual fund firm to profit most from the bull
market. Its assets have more than quadrupled since the end of 1997,
when it ran just $67.3 billion, and its funds continue to outsell
those of Fidelity Investments and the Vanguard Group.
</P>
<P>
   Most stock analysts who have followed Janus say the company is
being held back by its packaging with Stilwell. Salomon Smith
Barney even has a 20 percent ``holding company discount'' on
Stilwell as a hedge against the possible departure of any of Janus'
star portfolio managers. Salomon estimates that Stilwell is trading
at 15 times its earnings, while the average for asset managers is
18. Janus, it argues, merits closer to 25.
</P>
<P>
   ``Janus is worth, at a minimum, double what it's currently
valued at.'' said Steven Eisman, an analyst at CIBC World Markets.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce R. Brewington of Putnam, Lovell Securities said Stilwell's
preliminary trading puts it in the low end of asset managers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd argue that they're a premier franchise, so they'd go in
excess of the median,'' Brewington said. ``Janus would be better
served as a stand-alone entity. The company could be worth $20
billion.''
</P>
<P>
   In truth, asset managers are enjoying a surge in popularity
after a year of doldrums. The Putnam, Lovell Index of Publicly
Traded Money Managers, which tracks 17 asset management firms,
gained 30 percent the first half of the year, compared with a 1
percent drop in the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index. Last year,
the index gained 16 percent, four percentage points behind the S&AMP;P
500.
</P>
<P>
   And Stilwell's stock is likely to get at least some small boost
as it is added to the S&AMP;P 500 at the end of trading Wednesday, and
asset managers that mimic the index add the stock to their
portfolios.
</P>
<P>
   Mark L. Constant, an analyst at Lehman Brothers, sees less room
for improvement than the other stock analysts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Would things be better if they spun off separately'' from
Berger and the other units? Constant asked. ``Yes, they would be
better valued, but not astronomically.''
</P>
<P>
   Constant noted that separating Janus, at this point, could
create billions of dollars in tax consequences. And one of Kansas
City Southern's main arguments for the Stilwell deal is that it is
structured as a tax-free spinoff.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be awarded the tax-free status, it must be a clear
separation of businesses that operate in different industries,''
said Michael Herley, a spokesman for Kansas City Southern. That
made it necessary to group all of Kansas City Southern's financial
holdings together.
</P>
<P>
   Putting Janus alone, Herley added, ``would have jeopardized the
tax-free status.''
</P>
<P>
   Further, Kansas City Southern management says that Janus' full
value will be appreciated. ``We do not believe the holding company
structure will trade at a discount,'' Herley said.
</P>
<P>
   Janus officials have disagreed with both points, but the crux of
the dispute comes down to control. In effect, it is a spinoff in
reverse, with the railroad being cast off. Landon Rowland, chairman
and chief executive of Kansas City Southern, is vacating that job
to become chairman and chief executive of Stilwell.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland will continue to walk a delicate balance with Janus'
founder, Thomas Bailey, who sold the majority of his company in
1984. Stilwell will be even more heavily dependent on Janus than
was Kansas City Southern.
</P>
<P>
   Janus accounted for more than 90 percent of Kansas City
Southern's revenue and operating income. Eisman suggests that
Stilwell shareholders, who will get two Stilwell shares for each
share of the railroad, could stage a proxy fight to wrest control
of Stilwell. But that would be difficult to win. A more likely
possibility is that Stilwell, or Janus, could be a takeover
candidate. Or some of Janus' star managers could walk away and
start their own firms, as Marsico once did.
</P>
<P>
   For the moment, though, it appears that little will change at
Janus. Kansas City Southern, under Rowland, has left Bailey to run
Janus.
</P>
<P>
   A thaw between the two managements may even be in the offing.
Janus is now seriously considering Kansas City Southern's
invitation to recommend candidates to fill some of Stilwell's board
seats.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now that we're stuck with Stilwell,'' said Stephen Stieneker,
a Janus vice president, ``we have to try and make the best of it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
