<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MRSCLINTON-NAACP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRST LADY, SPEAKING TO NAACP, TAKES AIM AT BUSH 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Ohio, Va., Md.)   By NEIL A. LEWIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ Hillary Rodham Clinton, blending her roles as a
Senate candidate and first lady, told the annual convention of the
NAACP here Tuesday that it should not be beguiled by the assurances
of Gov. George W. Bush that he abhors discrimination and is
committed to enforcing civil rights laws.
</P>
<P>
   Standing in for President Clinton, who had been scheduled to
appear Tuesday but was instead presiding over the Mideast summit
meeting at Camp David, Clinton did not mention Bush by name. But
she made it clear that her biting criticisms were directed at the
expected Republican presidential nominee, who appeared before the
convention on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said it was gratifying that the annual meeting of the
National Association for the Advancement of Colored People was
attracting the kind of political guests who had shunned the group
in the past, an allusion to Bush's appearance after Bob Dole had
declined to attend the group's convention when he was the
Republican nominee in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Even though someone may speak to you, Clinton told the
delegates, it is wise to ``watch what they do and not what they
say.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm all for compassion,'' she said, lightly mocking Bush's
assertions that he understands the pain of discrimination. ``I
think it's wonderful when people feel `real bad' when there's
discrimination. It's fine when people say they are `truly
compassionate' about hate crimes.''
</P>
<P>
   But, Clinton said: ``We need to move beyond mere compassion. We
need to move to conviction to do something so we can move beyond
the injustices of our country.''
</P>
<P>
   At times during her 35-minute speech, Clinton sounded very much
like her husband, using a down-home style to offer parables from
the Bible and drawing warm applause from the audience. She even
occasionally lapsed into a pronounced drawl, as in talking to ``mah
friends,'' only to revert to her flat ordinary speech. Vice
President Al Gore, the expected Democratic presidential nominee, is
to address the convention Wednesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Bush received a surprisingly warm welcome on Monday, noting
wryly that his predecessors as Republican presidential nominees had
not always been eager to appear before the NAACP.
</P>
<P>
   Julian Bond, the chairman of the board of the NAACP, told
reporters Tuesday that while the delegates were delighted that Bush
appeared, they were disappointed that he did not address specific
concerns like affirmative action or the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   He said that both Clinton and Ralph Nader, the Green Party
candidate, who also spoke to the convention Wednesday, offered
genuine substance in their talks, in contrast to Bush, who he said
``viewed his appearance as a photo opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said she remembered how moved she was in 1963 when, as a
high school student, she heard a speech in Chicago by the Rev. Dr.
Martin Luther King Jr. His message that day to stay involved in the
civil rights revolution, she said, has stayed with her.
</P>
<P>
   She went on to note that she has recently taken a great interest
in how the Senate operates, an indirect reference to her campaign
for Senate in New York.
</P>
<P>
   In that regard, she said, the Republican-controlled Senate has
blocked consideration of four black nominees to federal appeals
courts. She said the Republicans were blocking votes on James Wynn
and Roger Gregory to the 4th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals, based
in Richmond, Va.; Johnnie Rawlinson to the 9th Circuit, based in
California; and Kathleen McGee Lewis to the 6th Circuit, based in
Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tell the United States Senate to let these nominees go,'' she
shouted.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-11-00 2037EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
