<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-11 20:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9375 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BKC-CHAPEL-HILL-COX     07-11 0821
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-CHAPEL-HILL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Doherty gets job of a lifetime
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Several years ago, when Matt Doherty decided he wanted to be a
head coach his mentor, Dean Smith, told him to ``find a job where
you can envision retiring.''
</P>
<P>
   Doherty thought he had done just that in March of 1999 when he
was named head coach at the University of Notre Dame. It seemed
like a perfect fit. He was an Irish Catholic kid from Long Island
whose grandmother had come from County Kerry, Ireland, just like
Bobby Cremins' parents. On the day he was named Notre Dame's coach,
Walter and Mary Doherty fought back tears as the proudest parents
on the planet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Matt Doherty, Notre Dame _ that sounds like a fit,'' Mary
Doherty beamed to her son.
</P>
<P>
   When Doherty took Notre Dame to the NIT championship game and a
22-15 record in his rookie season as a head coach, he appeared set
for a long and successful run in South Bend.
</P>
<P>
   But then Smith, his basketball godfather, called and offered him
a job that he never dared dream about; the only job that would have
made him leave Notre Dame after only one year; the job of a
lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   As painful as the exit from Notre Dame would be, as much as it
would hurt to say goodbye to something he had just begun to build,
Doherty had to bite his quivering lower lip Tuesday night and
gratefully take the keys to the college basketball dynasty that is
the University of North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Doherty, 38, has been in training for this day since 1980, when
arrived at North Carolina as a gangly 6-8 forward. He was a
McDonald's All-American, but in 1982 he was the starting forward on
a team that included Michael Jordan, James Worthy, and Sam Perkins.
He became the consummate role player on a team that went 32-2 and
beat Georgetown and Patrick Ewing for the national championship.
</P>
<P>
   Playing with that kind of talent, Doherty still averaged 9.0
points over his career. When he left North Carolina, his 446 career
assists was third on the school's all-time list behind Phil Ford
and Jimmy Black.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't make it in the NBA and decided to give the real world
a try. He was a bond salesman in New York for a while and worked
for an executive search firm in Charlotte, N.C. Neither job got his
juices flowing the way basketball always had. He tried to scratch
the itch by working as an analyst with the Davidson basketball
network.
</P>
<P>
   He was warned by Smith and others. Don't coach unless it's
something that you absolutely have to do. He did.
</P>
<P>
   Doherty stayed in Charlotte and worked for three years as an
assistant at Davidson before another member of the Carolina family,
Roy Williams of Kansas, brought him to Lawrence in 1992. At Kansas,
Doherty got high marks for his attention to detail and his ability
as a recruiter. He signed nine high school All-Americans for the
Jayhawks. After seven years he was ready to be a head coach and,
thanks to recommendations from Smith and Williams, he got the job
at Notre Dame.
</P>
<P>
   Some have wondered if the emotional Doherty is tough enough to
handle the slings and arrows that must be absorbed at the upper
echelon of Division I basketball.
</P>
<P>
   Notre Dame's players have the answer. After losing an exhibition
game by 24 points, a newspaper headline called the team
``lackadaisical.'' He put a copy in every players' locker. After
304 windsprints, he vowed they would never lose again for lack of
effort. After Notre Dame upset No. 1 UConn last season, he dove
headfirst in the mass of bodies celebrating at the Joyce Athletic
Center.
</P>
<P>
   After three years of the underappreciated but low-key Bill
Guthridge, Doherty has been hired to bring the passion back to
Carolina basketball. He must to do that and also find a way to beat
a guy named Krzyzewski, who has his own dynasty just eight miles
down 15-501 in Durham.
</P>
<P>
   Doherty learned how to be a head coach from Williams. Williams
learned from Dean Smith. And Tuesday Doherty returned to Chapel
Hill to complete the circle.
</P>
<P>
   MATT DOHERTY FILE
</P>
<P>
   _Full name: Matthew Francis Doherty.
</P>
<P>
   _Birthdate: Feb. 25, 1962.
</P>
<P>
   _Birthplace: East Meadow, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   _Education: Bachelor's degree in business administration, North
Carolina, 1984.
</P>
<P>
   _Playing experience: North Carolina, 1980-84.
</P>
<P>
   _Coaching experience: Notre Dame, head coach, 1999-2000; Kansas,
assistant coach, 1992-99; Davidson, assistant coach, 1989-92.
</P>
<P>
   _Coaching record: 22-15.
</P>
<P>
   _Family: Married to the former Kelly Propst of Concord, N.C.;
two children, Tucker, 3, and Hattie Fitzgerald, 10 months.
</P>
<P>
   _Career highlights: Led Notre Dame to the NIT finals in his
first season as coach; started three years at North Carolina, where
he played with Michael Jordan, Sam Perkins, Brad Daugherty, James
Worthy and Kenny Smith and helped the Tar Heels win the 1982
national championship.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
