<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-11 20:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9376 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-BKN-DUNCAN-COX     07-11 0832
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-DUNCAN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Spurs' Duncan says he's going to remain with San Antonio
 &HT;    By Mark Rosner
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Tim Duncan stepped up to a podium and back into
his life Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Duncan, a free agent pursued by the Orlando Magic, television
cameras and reporters for nearly two weeks, confirmed that he will
remain with the San Antonio Spurs, at least for a few years.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking during a news conference at a San Antonio resort hotel,
Duncan and his attorney, Lon Babby, said details of a contract have
not been reached. Duncan appears to favor a three-year deal. NBA
rules allow him to sign for seven. Babby said a three-year contract
``is definitely a possibility.'' Duncan, who became a free agent
July 1, can not re-sign with the Spurs until Aug. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Duncan, 24, gave no particular reason for remaining in San
Antonio, other than saying ``basketball'' was the biggest factor,
meaning he thinks the Spurs' have a better chance to win than does
Orlando.
</P>
<P>
   With his announcement, Duncan, a reluctant celebrity, can
finally throw people off his trail: The local TV station's
helicopter that hovered over his house. The sport utility vehicle
carrying media that followed him from the airport.
</P>
<P>
   ``It been a tough one,'' said Duncan, who was accompanied
Tuesday by his girlfriend, Amy Sherrill, and a close friend, Marc
Scott, as well as Babby. ``Orlando had a lot to offer. It was a
great visit down to Orlando and it made my decision a lot tougher
than I thought it was going to be. I just like what I have here. I
decided to stay here another couple of years as we work it out and
figure out what is going to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   The Spurs, 1999 NBA champions, feel the combination of Duncan
and David Robinson gives them the foundation they need to make a
run at dethroning the Los Angeles Lakers, who won the title in
2000.
</P>
<P>
   Trying to surround those two with more talent, the Spurs had
Derek Anderson, a free-agent guard from the Los Angeles Clippers,
in San Antonio Tuesday for a visit. The Spurs will also make a run
at Charlotte guard Eddie Jones, although salary cap restrictions
will make luring him difficult, if not impossible. The Spurs were
trying to attract Detroit's Grant Hill, who said he will sign with
Orlando.
</P>
<P>
   By signing a shorter contract than allowed, Duncan can monitor
how well the aging Spurs restock with younger players.
</P>
<P>
   Babby said Duncan was businesslike during discussions with the
Spurs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think basketball is the primary thing. But he's had a
wonderful three years here, and wonderful relationships. I think
the burden was on some other place to encourage him to leave.
Orlando set an extremely high standard. To the credit of the Spurs,
they were able to meet and exceed that standard,'' Babby said.
</P>
<P>
   Duncan did not ask Spurs' Coach and General Manager Gregg
Popovich for guarantees about whom the Spurs would add to their
roster.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one can promise you what is going to happen,'' Babby said.
``All you can do is try to put yourself in the best possible place
to accomplish your goals.''
</P>
<P>
   That is where Robinson was a factor. Though he turns 35 in
August and has a bad back and aching knees, Robinson has indicated
he wants to play another three years.
</P>
<P>
   Having the 7-foot-1-inch Robinson by his side allows Duncan to
play forward, a position he prefers. With the Spurs, the 7-foot
Duncan has only played center when Robinson is not in the game.
Duncan might have been stuck at center for Orlando, which has no
one close to the caliber of Robinson.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson and Duncan met for more than an hour last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just sat down and talked a little while, just to kind of
get on the same page, put some things on the table, see what kind
of answers came up,'' Duncan said. ``I liked the talk; I liked what
came out of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Babby, ``Tim wanted to gather all the information on
David's plans and David's feeling about the future of this team.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Duncan does not reveal much of himself, he was touched by
the response from businesses and fans in San Antonio during the
last few weeks. Billboards featured the message ``Stay Tim Stay.''
H-E-B grocery stores distributed 300,000 placards saluting and
encouraging him. Even Popovich had placards and flags pasted to his
car.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was incredible, beyond anything I expected,'' Duncan said.
``It was a bit overwhelming at times. But it was great. Very
flattering.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Duncan won't miss the helicopter or the news trucks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't even going to bring that up,'' he said. ``Since you
brought it up, it was rather annoying. I'm glad the process is
over. I hope people will stop following me.''
</P>
<P>
   Duncan, who injured his left knee April 11, is in the early
stages of rehabilitation. Duncan does not know if he will be able
to compete in the Olympics, which begin in mid-September. Training
camp opens Aug. 25.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
