u i BC-RUSSIA-MEDIA-NYT &LR;      07-11 0729
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-MEDIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIAN MEDIA CONGLOMERATE SEARCHED AGAIN BY AUTHORITIES 
</HEADLINE>
   By MICHAEL WINES    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Prosecutors searched the offices of Media-Most, the
nation's largest private media conglomerate, Tuesday for the second
time in two months, stepping up a criminal investigation that
skeptics call an effort to silence one of the Kremlin's few
prominent critics.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutors also sought documents from Gazprom, the huge
state-run natural gas monopoly, which is Media-Most's biggest
financial supporter, apparently as part of a continuing inquiry
into the media company's finances.
</P>
<P>
   The raids took place one month after the prosecutors briefly
imprisoned the conglomerate's owner, Vladimir Gusinsky, in
connection with the same inquiry, which is said to involve an
allegation of financial impropriety in his purchase of a television
station from the government.
</P>
<P>
   They followed by days a series of confrontations between
Media-Most and the government, perhaps capped by a veiled reference
to Gusinsky in a ``state of the nation'' speech delivered on
Saturday by President Vladimir Putin.
</P>
<P>
   In that speech Putin said unrestricted freedom of the press was
essential to Russian democracy. But he added that the main threat
came not from the government, but from tycoons who wielded their
newspapers and television stations against each other and, at
times, the state.
</P>
<P>
   A few other tycoons have media holdings. But Gusinsky's company
is the only media conglomerate to come under legal and financial
pressure from the government.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, agents of the Russian prosecutor general and the
Federal Security Service _ the heir to the KGB's domestic
intelligence activities _ served search warrants at the
headquarters of Media-Most and the offices of NTV, a subsidiary
that runs the nation's only independent broadcast network.
</P>
<P>
   They carted away a sheaf of financial documents from the
headquarters, Media-Most officials later said, but took only a list
of shareholders from the NTV office.
</P>
<P>
   Two months ago, shotgun-toting prosecutors and tax police
officers appeared at Media-Most headquarters in ski masks and
camouflage, staging a telegenic raid and search that many critics
then saw as a warning to Gusinsky to tone down his attacks on
Kremlin policies including the war in Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutor general's office said Tuesday that the latest
seizures were a routine part of its inquiry, which apparently
centers on Gusinsky's purchase of a St. Petersburg television
station in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The deputy prosecutor general who is leading the inquiry, Vasily
Kolmogorov, said in a letter to Parliament last week that Gusinsky
had swindled the government out of at least $10 million in the
deal.
</P>
<P>
   Gusinsky has vigorously denied that, and has refused to answer
questions in what he calls a sham inquiry. In Tuesday's search,
investigators apparently focused on Media-Most's relations with
Gazprom.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Moscow city prosecutors announced that they had
arrested a reporter for a prominent NTV program on charges of drug
smuggling. NTV officials denied any connection to the suspect.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, the best-known NTV commentator, Yevgeny Kiselyov,
delivered a broadside against Putin, accusing the president of
harboring imperial ambitions.
</P>
<P>
   Putin's role in all this, if any, remains obscure. He has said
he has no involvement in the prosecution of Gusinsky.
</P>
<P>
   But on a visit to Europe last month, he publicly questioned
Gazprom's financial support of Media-Most. Since then, Gazprom,
which is almost 40 percent owned by the government, has asked
Gusinsky to settle accounts. In all, Gazprom has guaranteed loans
to Media-Most totaling about $380 million.
</P>
<P>
   Several other of Russia's richest men came under fire Tuesday as
well. Tax authorities accused top executives at the nation's
biggest oil company, Lukoil Holding, of hiding company revenues
from taxation, the news agency Interfax reported. The company
denied the accusations, saying it got a clean bill of health from
the tax authorities last month.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, the prosecutor general demanded that another
magnate, Vladimir Potanin, reimburse the government $140 million
for its sale of an undervalued stake in Norilsk Nickel, a mining
company. Potanin called the demand blackmail and asked for a court
hearing.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
