u a BC-ABUSE-RESEARCH-NYTR &LR;      07-11 0377
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABUSE-RESEARCH-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROFESSOR LINKS ANIMAL ABUSE TO DOMESTIC VIOLENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN BOYANOSKI   
 Herald-Journal, Spartanburg, S.C.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SPARTANBURG, S.C. _ A recent study by a professor at the
University of South Carolina-Spartanburg indicates that people who
abuse animals may be more likely to abuse family members as well.
</P>
<P>
   The research, by Clifford Flynn, a sociology professor, showed
that many times women in abusive relationships, and even their
abusers, viewed the animal as part of their family. He said he at
first found that odd, but then realized this was the link between
the two forms of abuse.
</P>
<P>
   ``Violence in families is multidimensional,'' Flynn said. ``The
abuser will attack anybody for control, and if they believe the pet
is part of the family they will attack the pet as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Flynn performed his research in spring 1998 by questioning women
at an abuse clinic in Spartanburg County. He later did a second
survey with USCS students to solidify the research. He presented a
paper on the project in April to the Midwest Sociological Society
in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Flynn said he found that violence against pets can be a random
act of aggression, like hitting the animal as it enters a room, or
it can take the form of abusing an animal for revenge on the other
person in the relationship.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's another way for men to exert control in a relationship,''
Flynn said. ``They can use a pet as leverage. It's scapegoating.''
</P>
<P>
   Flynn said his research is part of a growing trend in sociology
in which researchers to try to find a link between human and animal
relationships.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a field that has really been ignored for years,'' Flynn
said. ``Animals are such a big part of our lives, and it doesn't
make sense not to look at them as part of our interactions.''
</P>
<P>
   He said his study also showed that women in abusive
relationships sometimes refused to seek help because of fears the
abuser would hurt the animal more.
</P>
<P>
   Flynn said that by looking for warning signs in animal abuse,
law enforcement agencies may be able resolve other problems. ``We
need to take animal abuse more seriously,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   (The Herald-Journal is part of the New York Times Regional
Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-11-00 2051EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000711.0335 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-11 20:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9392 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-EMPLOYEE-THEFT-ART-2T     07-11 1114
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EMPLOYEE-THEFT-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAKING AT THE OFFICE: THEFT BY EMPLOYEES IS BIGGER AND BOLDER 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By GREG WINTER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Clifton Richards was more than just a mailroom clerk. He tackled
the phones, mastered new software and bought supplies at the Social
Science Research Council, a nonprofit foundation where he worked in
New York. Always friendly, invariably dependable, he seemed to be a
true asset, his co-workers say. He even dressed better than many of
the staff, they say.
</P>
<P>
   Then, $650,000 in checks turned up missing over three months,
the foundation says, and the U.S. Postal Police were called in to
investigate. In March, Richards was charged with bank fraud,
accused of stealing 22 grant payments from the company's mail and
pawning them off to an intermediary for pennies on the dollar.
(Efforts to reach him or his lawyer for comment were unsuccessful.)
</P>
<P>
   Now, the shaken managers of the foundation are setting up
security protocols they never knew they needed. ``It's analogous to
what one would do when someone burglarizes your home,'' said Craig
Calhoun, the president. ``You change the locks; you put in a
burglary system. But that doesn't mean you're invulnerable or can
stop this from happening again.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, in enterprises of all sizes and shapes, from shoestring
nonprofits to giant corporations, the scale of employee theft has
soared. Spurred by the gold-rush mentality of the late 1990s,
emboldened by technology and quick to prey on the loose financial
controls at start-ups and small companies, workers at every rung of
the corporate ladder are stealing more money than ever before,
fraud examiners say.
</P>
<P>
   Though it is unclear how much the number of incidents has grown,
a 1998 survey of 5,000 businesses, government agencies and
nonprofits calculated an average loss of $624,000 from check fraud
by employees, including forgeries and mailroom theft, nearly twice
the figure in a 1994 poll. The survey, by consultants for KPMG, the
accounting firm, also found that the looting of company bank
accounts by employees using ATM cards had more than doubled, to an
average of $300,000.
</P>
<P>
   Theft and misuse of company credit cards by employees tripled,
to an average loss of more than $1.1 million, from 1994 to 1998,
the KPMG survey showed. And the average loss from employee expense
account abuse grew to $141,000, nearly seven times what it was four
years earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Fraud investigators say these statistics only scratch the
surface of a surge in workplace larceny. Anonymous surveys are one
thing. But, fearful of bad publicity, companies are loath to report
theft cases to law enforcement, masking a problem that has grown
alongside the soaring economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the early 1980s, when I first started in this business, I
was not a very busy person,'' said Toby Bishop, a partner in the
fraud division at Arthur Andersen, the consulting firm. ``Today, I
can't handle all of what comes in the door.''
</P>
<P>
   When the Association of Certified Fraud Examiners, which is
based in Austin, Texas, conducted one of the nation's first
comprehensive studies on employee fraud in 1996, it reported that
companies typically lost 6 percent of their annual revenues to such
theft, roughly twice most earlier estimates.
</P>
<P>
   Two years later, in a survey of 587 fraud examiners, nearly 70
percent said that fraud levels had increased since the initial
report and that they expected the trend to continue.
</P>
<P>
   Fraud examiners attribute much of the recent wave of office
criminality to the stock market boom that has created hordes of
overnight millionaires and stirred impatience with the occasional
pay raise.
</P>
<P>
   ``You see the guy down the street who cashed in his stock
options and is now worth a million dollars, and you're still making
$30,000,'' said John Warren, general counsel of the fraud
examiners' group. ``It makes it easier to rationalize fraudulent
behavior.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there is the widening gap between executive and worker
compensation. Edward Wolff, an economics professor at New York
University, says corporate chief executives made an average 400
times what their average employees did in 1998, up from a ratio of
just 40 a decade earlier. The disparity in pay has fueled
discontent and eroded loyalty to such a degree that stealing on the
job is often seen as acceptable behavior, fraud investigators say.
</P>
<P>
   ``It used to be extremely rare that anyone would acknowledge
theft taking place,'' said Jim Baker, founder and president of
Baker Technologies Inc. in Rowlett, Texas, who has been
investigating fraud for 30 years. ``Now it's rare that we don't
hear of someone knowing about it. People have a cavalier attitude.
There's no shame attached to theft.''
</P>
<P>
   One consequence of the growth in such theft has been a large
gain in the number of fraud investigators. Membership in the
Association of Certified Fraud Examiners, the principal
professional group, has increased to about 25,000 from about 8,200
in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   ``They see it as a growth industry,'' Warren, the general
counsel, said.
</P>
<P>
   Stealing often starts in the mailroom, a favorite haunt of
unscrupulous employees, investigators say.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you get a new employee, where do you stick them?'' said
Patrick Casey, a federal postal inspector and spokesman for the
postal police. ``The mailroom. That's often the lowest-paying job
in the corporation, yet a lot of the company's money goes through
there. Criminals sometimes seek out those jobs because they realize
they will have access to the ingoing and the outbound checks.''
</P>
<P>
   But workplace theft is costliest when committed by high-ranking
employees, who tend to have the most access to funds. According to
the fraud examiners' association, the median loss from crimes by
managers is $250,000, four times that of crimes by employees. And
the median loss from owners and executives is $1 million, 16 times
that of their employees.
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, workplace thieves have become easier to catch.
Technology has expanded the arsenal of video cameras, decoys and
other tools used by fraud investigators. But computers, modems and
the Internet also offer employees new ways of tampering with
financial records, transferring funds and covering their tracks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a double-edged sword,'' said Bill Olsen, the mid-Atlantic
director for business fraud and investigation at Arthur Andersen.
``With the same technology we're using to detect and deter fraud,
there are people out there who are using it to commit crimes.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Many investigators also worry that a growing inattention to the
issue is making it easier for employees to steal. As labor
shortages threaten rapid growth, companies are becoming more likely
to forgo thorough background checks so as to speed up hiring.
</P>
<P>
   And with the pressure to post record earnings quarter after
quarter, many businesses have cut back on departments like
accounting and security that help detect theft but do not generate
revenue. Start-ups, racing to post profits, are particularly short
on checks and balances.
</P>
<P>
   ``Internal controls are still very much viewed as cost
centers,'' said Richard H. Girgenti, director of investigations at
KPMG. ``What doesn't dawn on management is the connection between
money spent on fraud protection and the bottom line.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, even the most elaborate safeguards can fail. The Social
Science Research Council says, for example, that Richards came from
an employee agency that professed to do background checks. The
foundation itself has five accountants in a staff of just 50, an
unusually high ratio, even in the private sector.
</P>
<P>
   Richards has yet to stand trial on the federal charges. The
complaint says that he admitted taking the checks and that a teller
at Chase Manhattan Bank approved cashing them. Investigators say
they suspect that the teller deposited the stolen checks in false
accounts. The bank said it was looking into the matter and would
reimburse the foundation if any wrongdoing was uncovered.
</P>
<P>
   The foundation said it did not know anything was amiss until
students who had been awarded research grants started calling from
schools around the world, asking when the money would arrive. Then
it took weeks to track down the source of the thefts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The scariest thing is that we kept watching it happen and it
kept coming,'' said Kristine Dahlberg, the foundation's chief
financial officer.
</P>
<P>
   Inadequate staffing and an atmosphere of trust often make
nonprofits susceptible to theft, but investigators say that most
fraud still occurs at corporations, large and small, where money
and opportunities for fraud abound.
</P>
<P>
   Many regard the ever-increasing trend toward corporate mergers
as a prime opportunity for white-collar criminals. ``When merging
with companies that have different profiles, management's eyes are
off the ball,'' said David Sherwin, a partner with Ernst &AMP; Young
who oversees the company's fraud surveys. ``There is no real status
quo anymore. The old benchmarks are no longer valid, so it becomes
easy for fraud to go undetected.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve Albrecht, associate dean at the Marriott School of
Management at Brigham Young University, says that in his
consultations with national banks, he noticed fraud levels rising
33 percent a year from 1996 to 1998. As huge mergers become common
and layoffs ensue, Albrecht said, employees cease to identify with
the companies they work for, developing a sense of detachment that
makes theft simpler to justify.
</P>
<P>
   ``Employees are not viewed as long-term investments; they're
viewed as short-term assets that can be bought and sold,'' Albrecht
said. ``As a result, there's not the allegiance to the organization
that there used to be.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
