<DOCNO> NYT20000711.0337 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-11 20:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9396 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-CHUCK&AMP;BUCK-FILM-ART-2     07-11 1038
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHUCK&AMP;BUCK-FILM-ART-2TAKES-$ADV16-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A REFRESHING CURVE IN A STRAIGHT SUMMER 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, July 16) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By JAMIE MALANOWSKI    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Insinuating its way into a summer of movies of negligible
ambiguity _ many are the attractions of ``Gladiator,'' ``The
Patriot'' and ``The Perfect Storm,'' but their ability to provoke a
tentative, questioning mood in the viewer is not among them _ comes
one of the major chew bones of this year's Sundance Film Festival,
``Chuck and Buck.'' The movie, which was scheduled to open July 14,
is about boyhood friends who re-encounter each other after many
years; Chuck has gone on to become a Los Angeles record company
executive, professionally accomplished and successfully affianced,
while Buck hasn't gone on to anything except a huge case of
arrested development, a large part of which involves keeping the
memory of their boyish sex play burning like an eternal flame. It's
a movie that careers into one cringe-inducing circumstance after
another: The sexuality of children, the old relationship that will
not die, the overweening confidence of jerks, the cruelty of the
panicked, the geek who will not go away. And it's a comedy!
</P>
<P>
   Written by Michael White, it also stars Michael White. ``What
people create is a fulfillment of a wish that we are conscious of
or unconscious of,'' said the Freudian White.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see this in other people's movies, and sometimes you wonder
whether moviemaking is anything more than that. It's like all they
want to do is see Sharon Stone uncross her legs, and the whole
movie is built around that moment.'' Audiences will note that White
did not take the competent, has-his-act-together Chuck part, but
the goofy, pathetic, disruptive Buck part. ``Chuck and Buck'' is,
of course, fiction _ of course it's fiction _ but it's hard to
think of anyone in recent years who's made as riskily revelatory an
artistic statement as Michael White.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd always felt sort of oppressed by images of perfection,''
said White, 29, who features within his credit-packed writing
career two seasons on the perfect-teen television series ``Dawson's
Creek.'' ``Perfect people living perfect lives, the Aaron Spelling
version of things that just infiltrates Hollywood generally. And so
when I see people on TV or in the movies who are more misfits, I
feel that's sort of healing, to see that there are people like you
out there.''
</P>
<P>
   White traces his empathy to his upbringing. He was raised in
northern California in a religious household. His father, Melvin
White, is a clergyman who was the ghostwriter of books for Jerry
Falwell, Jim and Tammy Faye Bakker, Pat Robertson and Billy Graham.
The Whites went to a fundamentalist summer camp, where in the
mornings campers would lift their arms in the air and practice the
rapture they'd feel at the Second Coming _ fundamentalist
calisthenics. Several years ago, after he had finished putting his
two children through college, the elder White came out of the
closet and became a gay activist, critical of the religious right
for its intolerance toward gays. He had, however, come out to his
family a decade before. ``My dad ended up having to stay closeted
and my parents had to pretend they were still married'' _ they are
now divorced _ ``and he had to keep taking these jobs to basically
keep me in school. It was a very tortured extended experience for
him.''
</P>
<P>
   White's father recalled that Michael went his own way, even as a
child. ``Mike is a kid who refuses to do what's anticipated,''
Melvin White said. ``He refuses to play with the common paradigms.
I remember him saying to me, `You're not gay, that's just a
construct that limits you.' That's when he was 16.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael White, who is tall and thin, with a reedy voice, hair
like strawberry blond grass and eyeballs drawn by Dr. Seuss, said
the idea for ``Chuck and Buck'' came to him after several years of
living a writerly existence in Hollywood and feeling frustrated
both socially and creatively. ``The social side,'' he said over
dinner in Manhattan late last month, ``was always about putting
your best face forward, meeting people, getting work, being in the
mix, being liked. Creatively, there was the frustration of going
through the development process in both TV and the movies.
`Dawson's Creek' was such a show about people who were beautiful
and articulate. And so much of development is about: `How do you
make this character more likable? How are you going to fall in love
with them quicker in the movie?' `Chuck and Buck' is about a
reaction to that destructive way of creating a script. I thought,
`I'm going to create a character who has all the characteristics of
what you hope you aren't.''' He set up an alter ego struggle: Chuck
is the handsome, successful character you project to the world, and
Buck is the character who's confused and a nuisance and has nothing
to offer. ``And I really wanted to tap into the Buck side,'' White
said.
</P>
<P>
   What obviously gives the movie its tension, both comic and
dramatic, is Chuck and Buck's old sexual relationship, something
Chuck wants to hide as much as Buck wants to revive. As his father
would say, White has refused to play with common paradigms.
``There's been a lot of hi-jinxy mainstream Hollywood comedies,
like `What About Bob?' or `The Cable Guy,' '' White said, ``where
the undercurrent of homoeroticism is a central part of where the
comedy comes from. I wanted to push the envelope. And there's also
the mainstream version of the character with arrested development,
a Rain Man or a Forrest Gump, a character who's a touchstone
through which people access the child in themselves. But these
characters are idealized. I was thinking, all people have
sexuality. There was a kid in my neighborhood who had Down
syndrome, and everyone went out of their way to be inclusive and to
be sensitive to his needs. But the minute he would grab my sister
or fondle her inappropriately, immediately all the good intentions
would cave in. And to me, it was kind of comical.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   The resultant screenplay _ about characters you like, feel for,
dislike and are dismayed and repelled by, pretty much all at once _
was, in White's word, polarizing.
</P>
<P>
   ``People not only told me they wouldn't finance it,'' he said,
``but their reactions were hostile. They were, like: `Why are you
doing this? Why do you want to make this? But a lot of people loved
the script.'' One of them was Miguel Arteta, the director of the
critically acclaimed indie ``Star Maps'' (1997). ``Movies about
obsessed people usually end in bloodbath,'' Arteta said. ``Mike
shows that Buck is just a character with a big hole in his heart
that he's trying to fill.'' Arteta quickly agreed to direct the
screenplay and took the project to Open Cities, a New York-based
production company that wants to foster artistic freedom, and it
underwrote filming.
</P>
<P>
   Then came casting. White, who acted at Wesleyan University in
Middletown, Conn., and has had tiny parts in films and on
television, seems to enjoy performing, especially in scenarios of
his own invention. His father said: ``Mike gave me and my partner
his Toyota 4Runner so we could make trips to the Home Depot, and he
bought himself a Lincoln Town Car, with the dark windows and
everything, and a chauffeur's hat. And he wears the hat when he
drives himself around. `Dad,' he says, `It feels like I'm always
going to the airport.'''
</P>
<P>
   White had harbored a desire to play Buck even as he was writing:
``It felt like it would be a challenge to play Buck, a way of
engaging with the material in a more intensely creative way. And
because the movie is about alter egos inside you that you're afraid
to show, I thought it would be very gutsy for me to just go for
it.'' And besides, he added, ``I really never thought anyone would
see the movie.''
</P>
<P>
   He can no longer remember whether it was he or Arteta who
actually floated the idea first, but he was cast promptly,
particularly after Arteta cast the Weitz brothers, Chris and Paul,
the makers of ``American Pie.'' Chris plays Chuck, and Paul _ pay
attention now _ portrays an actor who is playing a character in a
play who is based on Chuck. ``It was an amazing, funny, fluent,
confident script that didn't succumb to any of the usual cliches,''
Chris Weitz said. ``But to be truthful, I told Miguel I'd do the
part even before I read it.''
</P>
<P>
   White's performance, Arteta said, turned out to be compelling:
``Emotionally, he's telling you exactly what's going on at all
times. You know, he had to cry a lot in that movie, and whether it
was a tight shot or a wide shot, he went for it every time. Then he
went home depleted.''
</P>
<P>
   Being the front man for this movie has been strange, White said:
``It did seem like it was generating a lot of discussion at
Sundance. After spending years on stuff that was palatable and easy
to digest, I felt this is finally what I intended. People were
talking about sexuality, about relationships, taking different
sides. That's the most exciting part of writing, when the story
lingers beyond the telling of it in discussion and debate.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the debut of ``Chuck and Buck,'' White has been sent
screenplays with parts earmarked for him. ``Much like you'd
expect,'' he said, ``dumb bananas and computer whizzes.'' He said
he was interested in acting again _ ``I should take a part in an
action movie, just so when people see my performance in `Chuck and
Buck,' they'll say, `Oh, he's acting.''' Right now, however, he is'
focused on writing. He's at work on two pilots and two screenplays
for the producer Scott Rudin, and is hopeful that financing will
come through for another screenplay he has done for Arteta, which
he describes as `` `Madame Bovary' meets `Raising Arizona.'''
</P>
<P>
   And he's still jazzed about ``Chuck and Buck'': ``If I had just
written it, I would feel proud. But because I'm in it, it's just
weird for me. Because now people have reactions not only to the
movie but to me, personally. A lot of people really want to engage.
A lot of them want to, like, tell you their own story, and I don't
really want to be the receptacle for all the insanity this movie
may provoke. And clearly I'm also leaving myself open to a lot of
speculation and discussion. I was in a restaurant the other day,
and someone came up to me and said, `I saw your movie, and I have
just one question _ is it autobiographical?' And I thought, `Be
careful what you wish for.'
</P>
<P>
   ``But it's been so interesting to create an alter ego of
yourself, one that's what you're most afraid of showing to the
world, and to do it on such a big scale. In L.A., people put their
best face forward and get accepted, but how meaningful is that? But
if you put your most twisted and vulnerable side forward and people
accept or don't accept it, it just feels more intense.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a meaningful experience. It feels so naked.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
