<HEADER>
A9398 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-HOLOCAUST-MEMOIR-NYT &LR;      07-11 0826
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLOCAUST-MEMOIR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLOCAUST FICTION TURNS OUT TO BE FACT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Md., Tenn., Germany)   By RALPH BLUMENTHAL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was, critics said, one of the more harrowing Holocaust
novels, a prominent German writer's stark tale of a Jewish stamp
dealer's hairbreadth escapes from the Nazis, in the end hidden in
the subcellar of a cooperative Ukrainian.
</P>
<P>
   But to Jakob Littner, that was no novel. That was his life.
</P>
<P>
   Now a professor's literary sleuthing has stripped away a veneer
of fiction from the work, ``Jakob Littner's Notes from a Hole in
the Ground,'' published in 1992 by the German writer Wolfgang
Koeppen, and given the book new standing as fact.
</P>
<P>
   In truth, said the professor, Reinhard Zachau, chairman of the
German department at the University of the South in Sewanee, Tenn.,
Koeppen appropriated Littner's memoir after assisting its first
brief publication in Germany in 1948. Littner died in New York in
1950. Koeppen who had achieved literary fame in the 1950s with a
trilogy of novels about Germany's postwar struggles, died in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Now, largely based on Zachau's research, Littner's original book
has been published for the first time in English, and once again as
nonfiction and as Littner's own work. Under his original title,
``Journey Through the Night,'' it was published in June by the
Continuum International Publishing Group of New York and London.
</P>
<P>
   ``While there have been several Holocaust `memoirs' that have
been unmasked as fictions,'' Continuum said in a statement, ``this
is perhaps the first time that a Holocaust `novel' turns out to be
a fabrication based minutely on a genuine Holocaust memoir.''
</P>
<P>
   In response to complaints from Littner's survivors in 1993,
Thomas Sparr, an editor at Koeppen's publisher, Juedischer Verlag,
a Jewish subsidiary of Suhrkamp Verlag, one of the largest German
publishing houses, wrote that the company ``never denied but rather
confirmed that the book contains'' Littner's ``Notes.'' Koeppen
``gave the notes an adequate form,'' he said, and acknowledged
Littner in the title. But the designation of novel was later
dropped.
</P>
<P>
   Yet scholars and Littner's relatives fault Koeppen's book as
misleading. ``There was gross misrepresentation involved in calling
the work a novel,'' said Zachau, who tracked down Littner's
original manuscript. ``And then there was something more subtle,
the perpetuation of changes Koeppen made 40 years earlier when he
took liberties with a straightforward if terrifying narrative to
make it into something more literary and mythic, something more
aesthetic.''
</P>
<P>
   A Hungarian-born Polish citizen, Littner was living with his
family in Munich when the war sent him fleeing back to Poland and
then to Zbaracz near Tarnopol, in Ukraine, where the SS was killing
Jews. His son and daughter-in-law were trapped in the besieged
Warsaw ghetto and sent anguished pleas for food until the letters
abruptly stopped. Littner's wife and sisters were also killed by
the Germans. But Littner was secretly sustained by a Christian
woman, Christine Hintermaier, who was his partner in the stamp
business.
</P>
<P>
   Littner; the woman who would become his second wife, Janina; and
another son, Richard, found refuge in a vault under the cellar of a
Ukrainian's house, for which they paid extravagantly, in one case
with gold bridgework that Littner tore from his mouth. After nine
months all but buried alive, the three were liberated in March
1944.
</P>
<P>
   Littner emigrated to New York in 1947, his manuscript in the
hands of a Munich publisher. Koeppen later said he was retained to
work on the book in exchange for food packages from Littner,
although when the book, ``Notes from a Hole in the Ground,'' came
out in a small printing in Germany in 1948, only Littner's name was
on it as the author.
</P>
<P>
   But Koeppen had made changes. Where Littner had issued a plea
for forgiveness and written, ``It is not for people to judge
others,'' Koeppen _ in Littner's voice _ had gone further, calling
Nazism's crimes ``beyond human judgment,'' a liberty that one
critic called ``Aryan chutzpah.''
</P>
<P>
   The texts of the 1948 and 1992 books were the same, Zachau said,
but Koeppen had added an introduction in which he claimed
authorship. ``I ate American rations and wrote the story about the
suffering of a German Jew,'' Koeppen wrote. ``In doing so it became
my story.''
</P>
<P>
   Skeptical, Zachau tracked down a relative of Littner's in
Maryland, Kurt Nathan Gruebler, a retired engineer, who had a copy
of Littner's original manuscript and authorized its publication.
Gruebler's name appears on the cover of the new book, and he is
credited as its translator and editor.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps Koeppen, as a German gentile and literary talent, just
felt the need to buttress Littner's memoir, said Zachau. But he
added, ``probably the best way to come to grips with Nazism would
simply have been to let Jakob Littner speak for himself.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-11-00 2059EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
