<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-11 21:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9400 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-BOLSHOI-BALLET-ART-$A     07-11 1313
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOLSHOI-BALLET-ART-$ADV16-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A COOLER BOLSHOI, BEARING BALANCHINE 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, July 16) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By ANNA KISSELGOFF    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Power and passion: The Bolshoi Ballet's dancing has been
synonymous with these qualities, making it a company like no other.
Virtually sold out for its appearances at Lincoln Center Festival
2000 this week, as it was for its recent five-city U.S. tour, the
fabled troupe from Moscow returns to New York for the first time in
10 years, and with its potent mystique intact.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, as Aleksei Fadeyechev says: ``It is a different
company now. Each time chooses its own dancers.'' Fadeyechev, who
was one of the Bolshoi stars in 1990, was made the ballet troupe's
artistic director in 1998 by Vladimir Vasiliev, the superstar named
to the new and double post of general and artistic director of the
entire Bolshoi Theater in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   By ``different,'' Fadeyechev, interviewed during the tour last
month in Washington, was referring to a way of dancing, not the
company's vicissitudes since Yuri Grigorovich, its pre-eminent
choreographer, was forced out as artistic director in a power
struggle. In 1990, Grigorovich was at the helm and dancers like
Fadeyechev still danced in the Bolshoi's heroic manner.
</P>
<P>
   This thrilling style, epitomized earlier by Vasiliev's muscular
bravura, has yielded to a more contemporary and classical look, in
Fadeyechev's view. The dancers are slimmer now and have been
influenced by Western models.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Bolshoi dancing retains its dynamic imprint _ what
Fadeyechev calls ``expressiveness with a spiritual springboard,''
reaching beyond technique to uplift the viewer. Traditionally the
company has been more willing to break the rules of academic style
than its rival in St. Petersburg, the Kirov Ballet. The latter's
dancing was pure, all could agree, but the Bolshoi's was more
exciting.
</P>
<P>
   Like most cliches, this appraisal holds true _ as Americans saw
recently in two Bolshoi signature pieces, ``Don Quixote'' and
Leonid Lavrovsky's ``Romeo and Juliet.'' Nonetheless there have
been changes. The company has brought a generation of young dancers
new to New York. Thanks to the freedom of the post-Communist era,
George Balanchine's ballets, once frowned upon because they had no
stories, have been added to the programming.
</P>
<P>
   When the Lincoln Center Festival presents the troupe at the New
York State Theater from July 18 through July 23, Vasiliev's staging
of ``Giselle'' will open the run.. The second program, a mixed
bill, includes Balanchine's ``Symphony in C.''
</P>
<P>
   Like the Kirov, which performs other Balanchine works, the
Bolshoi has no resident choreographer and is in search of a
repertory. But unlike the Kirov Ballet, whose head, Oleg
Vinogradov, was replaced by a de facto director after a financial
scandal, the Bolshoi seems to thrive on internal dissension.
</P>
<P>
   As a general administrator who is also, unlike his predecessors,
artistic director of the entire Bolshoi, Vasiliev has a major role
in running its opera and ballet troupes. Having the equivalent of
two artistic directors for ballet means built-in tension, which
manifested itself when Vasiliev lost his first ballet director,
Vyacheslav Gordeyev, in 1997. Aleksandr Bogatyrev died soon after
serving briefly as interim ballet director. Fadeyechev noted that
Vasiliev ``decides on the repertory for the entire theater.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Nina Ananiashvili, the Bolshoi ballerina who dances
regularly with American Ballet Theater, is known to have urged the
staging of the Balanchine works ``Mozartiana,'' ``Agon,''
``Symphony in C'' and, next season, ``Bugaku.'' Fadeyechev restaged
``Don Quixote'' and said it was his idea to invite the French
choreographer Pierre Lacotte to choreograph, in 19th-century style,
a version of ``The Pharaoh's Daughter,'' a nearly forgotten ballet
by Marius Petipa.
</P>
<P>
   Vasiliev, interviewed separately in Washington, spoke proudly of
the Bolshoi range. Its two poles this year were symbolized by the
contemporary dance-drama of Boris Eifman's ``Russian Hamlet'' (seen
in New York with the Eifman company) and the pageantry of ``The
Pharaoh's Daughter,'' acclaimed for its spectacular cascade of
classical dances. Vasiliev has, however, been criticized in the
press as an administrator and for his stagings of opera and ballet,
notably ``Swan Lake.'' Reports in Russian magazines suggest he is
on the way out.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, he is in a vulnerable position, having been
directly appointed by the former president, Boris Yeltsin, when the
Bolshoi, the Kirov, the Hermitage Museum and a few other museums
were classed as national institutions directly responsible to the
president. Whatever presidential protection was available to the
directors of these institutions is now in doubt. They have just
been returned to the jurisdiction of the Ministry of Culture.
</P>
<P>
   Under a proposal from Valery Gergiev, director of the Kirov
theater, the Bolshoi and Kirov theaters would be united under one
administration, as in the Office of Imperial Theaters in czarist
days. Since Gergiev would obviously be at the head of this joint
administration, the Bolshoi's defenders predict that this would
spell the end of one of the companies, and they will make sure that
it is not the Bolshoi.
</P>
<P>
   The Kirov ``is a wonderful company,'' Fadeyechev said. ``But
it's the second company.'' The Kirov corps was once supreme, he
added, ``but you will see in `La Bayadere,' ours is now the best.
Our company has changed and has more precision and clarity.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of the more emotionally profound style of the past,
Fadeyechev added: ``I admired the old style and regret that it is
gone, but style develops. The point of the Moscow school is that it
is a tradition passed down from person to person, not by videotape.
Marina Semyonova started in Leningrad, but she was a Bolshoi
ballerina and she still coaches at 92. She is part of the history
of the Bolshoi.''
</P>
<P>
   The ballet masters Fadeyechev has put into place are credited by
many in the company with having raised the overall level. They
include his father, Nikolai Fadeyechev, the eloquent danseur noble
who partnered Maya Plisetskaya in the 1950s and 1960s, and Boris
Akimov, remembered for his passionate performances in the 1970s.
They are the inheritors of a specifically Russian tradition, in
Fadeyechev's view.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Bolshoi is part of international culture,'' he said, ``and
not a minor part. Yet it is a Russian theater because it also
embodies Russian culture. Nina Ananiashvili dances abroad but her
schooling is Russian.''
</P>
<P>
   Illustrating with a detail, he agreed that Bolshoi ballerinas
like to throw both arms upward in a jete although textbook style
would have them lower.
</P>
<P>
   When you throw your arms up in a jete, you get an effect. It's
expressive, not for show but for what you feel inside. Yes, it is
part of a tradition. The little nuances that make up ballet style
consist of where your arm is, what is your speed, what preparations
you make for a step or how expressive you are. Ours is a big open
style. We were taught to cover the full stage in a leap.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked why the Bolshoi has lost fewer dancers to the West than
the Kirov in St. Petersburg after the the fall of Communism,
Fadeyechev replied with a smile, like a true Muscovite: ```Have you
ever tried to live in Petersburg?'' For many, Moscow is the more
exciting city. ``The atmosphere is better in our company,''
Fadeyechev said. The Bolshoi dancers have also made more use of a
new contract system that permits guest appearances abroad. Even
Fadeyechev has a contract. The latest is for one year, and he
wonders aloud how he can plan a repertory under these conditions.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
