<HEADER>
A9406 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w BC-CONGRESS-DRUGS-NYT &LR;      07-11 1311
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-DRUGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE CHAIRMAN OFFERS MEDICARE DRUG PLAN 
</HEADLINE>
   By ROBERT PEAR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With the battle over prescription drugs shifting to
the Senate, the chairman of the Senate Finance Committee has broken
with House Republicans and will propose a government-administered
program to offer drug benefits to all Medicare recipients, senators
of both parties said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Democrats and White House officials said that they were
surprised and pleased by the proposal from the panel's influential
chairman, William Roth, R-Del., and that they believed it would
increase the chances of adding drug benefits to Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   Roth will go over his proposal at a closed meeting of the
Finance Committee on Wednesday. The panel will have an opportunity
to amend and vote on it later this month.
</P>
<P>
   A bill passed last month by the House would give subsidies to
insurance companies to entice them into providing drug benefits to
people on Medicare _ an approach opposed by President Clinton and
by most Democrats in Congress, who say it is unlikely to work.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers said Roth clearly intended to depart from the House
bill, under which private insurers would administer drug benefits
and bear much of the financial risk.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, a Senate Republican aide said, under Roth's
proposal, ``the government would bear the insurance risk and take
responsibility for administering the benefit, as it does with the
rest of Medicare.''
</P>
<P>
   The House bill was passed by a vote of 217-214, largely along
party lines. Democratic senators said Roth's proposal was much
better than the House bill because drug coverage would be
integrated into Medicare, the health insurance program for the
elderly and disabled.
</P>
<P>
   Several Democrats said they could work with Roth, a conservative
Republican who is running for re-election in a tight race against
the governor of Delaware, Thomas R. Carper, a Democrat. Roth's
proposal for a government-administered drug program would almost
certainly have appeal to older Delaware voters.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Republican leaders gave no immediate indication of how
they would respond to Roth's proposal. Senate Majority Leader Trent
Lott, R-Miss., neither embraced nor rejected it. John S.
Czwartacki, a spokesman for Lott, said Tuesday night that the
majority leader ``has no comment at this time.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats see Medicare drug benefits as one of their most potent
political issues in this year's elections. Congress is far from
passing any bill acceptable to Clinton, and many lawmakers believe
a stalemate is the most likely outcome. But Senate Democrats said
Roth's efforts could help narrow the gap between the parties,
increasing the chances that drug benefits might be added to
Medicare this year.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Jennings, the health policy coordinator at the White
House, said he did not know all the details of Roth's proposal.
But, he said, if Roth has rejected the idea of subsidizing
insurance companies to provide drug benefits, ``that would
represent a very important step forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Bob Graham, D-Fla., said: ``I am very pleased at what I've
heard of Senator Roth's proposal. He accepts the fact that
prescription medication is a central part of a modern health care
system, not the red-headed third cousin at the family picnic that's
shuffled off to the side and treated in a demeaning manner.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Graham added: ``Senator Roth puts drug coverage
into the family of Medicare, rather than having it isolated in a
private insurance plan. We know in advance that private insurers
are very reluctant to offer free-standing drug coverage.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Richard H. Bryan, D-Nev., sounded a similar note, saying:
``The chairman appears to have crossed the Rubicon and is embracing
a prescription drug proposal within Medicare. In my view, that is
very significant.''
</P>
<P>
   Under Roth's proposal, Medicare beneficiaries would have two
options if they wanted freedom in choosing their doctors. They
could stay in the original fee-for-service program, with the
existing benefits, premiums, deductibles and co-payments. Or they
could enroll in a high-option plan, which would provide drug
benefits but would also charge more for certain services, like
laboratory tests and home health care.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an explicit tradeoff,'' said a Republican who helped
draft the plan. ``The co-payments, the co-insurance, would save
money. The money could be reinvested to provide a richer package of
benefits.''
</P>
<P>
   In April, when asked to describe their strategy for passing drug
legislation, White House officials said they pinned their hopes on
the Finance Committee, where members of the two parties have a
history of working together. Mr. Roth has solicited the views of
the 19 other committee members in hopes of sending a bill to the
Senate floor with bipartisan support.
</P>
<P>
   Roth's proposal incorporates many features of a bill devised by
moderate Democrats on the committee, including Graham and Sen.
Charles Robb of Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   While Republican leaders have not weighed in on Roth's proposal,
their aides said the lawmakers were pleased that Roth was adhering
to the budget blueprint adopted by both houses of Congress in
April. That blueprint set aside up to $40 billion over five years
for Medicare drug benefits. Clinton and congressional Democrats say
they never accepted that limit and want to spend more on drug
benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Public response to Roth's proposal will depend on the answers to
two questions: How much will beneficiaries have to pay for drug
coverage? And how much will they receive in benefits? Details of
the proposal were still being adjusted Wednesday night, to reflect
cost estimates from the Congressional Budget Office.
</P>
<P>
   Roth's desire to charge beneficiaries a fee for home health
services provoked a predictable outcry from the industry.
</P>
<P>
   James C. Pyles, a lawyer for the American Association for Home
Care, said: ``The idea of a co-payment on home health care is
monumentally stupid. It would hit the sickest, most vulnerable
patients, who tend to be the highest users of home care.'' Medicare
spending on home care dropped 45 percent in the last two years, to
$9.7 billion in 1999, from $17.5 billion in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Roth's proposal, as described Tuesday by senators and their
aides, includes these elements:
</P>
<P>
   _ A new office would be established in the Department of Health
and Human Services to administer drug benefits and to negotiate
contracts with health maintenance organizations serving Medicare
beneficiaries. The office would be separate from the current
Medicare agency, the Health Care Financing Administration, but
would work closely with it.
</P>
<P>
   _ Medicare would pay a larger share of a person's drug bills as
those expenses increased. While the details are still being worked
out, the government might pay half of drug costs below a specified
level _ perhaps $3,500 or $4,000 a year _ and 80 percent of costs
beyond that. By contrast, under many Democratic proposals, the
government would pick up 100 percent of drug costs above some
level, like $4,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   _ The government would hire private companies to help manage
drug benefits for the elderly, to negotiate discounts from drug
manufacturers and to set up networks of drugstores in different
parts of the country.
</P>
<P>
   _ In the high-option Medicare plan, the government would
establish a single deductible for the two existing parts of
Medicare. The program now has separate deductibles, $100 a year for
doctors' services and $776 for inpatient hospital care. In
addition, there would be a separate deductible for drug insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Under Clinton's plan and under the bill passed by the House, the
government would offer subsidies to employers to encourage them to
continue providing drug benefits to retirees. Roth is not proposing
such subsidies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
