<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-11 21:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9410 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-MAURY-TV-2TAKES-$ADV1     07-11 1305
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAURY-TV-2TAKES-$ADV16-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAVING THE WORLD, ONE SEXY TEEN-AGER AT A TIME 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, July 16) 
 By JEFF MacGREGOR    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   It seems to me that having created the Internet, the wireless
electronic pocket organizer and Oreos that turn your milk bright
blue when you dunk 'em, humankind has reached its technological
apogee. In so doing, we've solved our most fundamental problems:
``How can I deliver, to someone far away, an annoying online sales
pitch for deeply discounted off-season Adirondack time shares?''
and ``I'm a wealthy day trader and an idiot _ what day is it?'' and
``Why is my cookie so tasty yet not at all artistically ambitious
or challenging to the eye?''
</P>
<P>
   This is, of course, the best of all possible times to be alive
in this, the best of all possible worlds. Given our many
perfections in the physical realm, then, our automotive
heated-leather seating surfaces and our battery-operated Furbys and
our trip to the moon, shouldn't we turn our collective genius
inward, and begin to map the complex strivings of the human spirit?
Should we not use our abundant leisure to embark upon great voyages
of self-discovery? Should we not, at last, realize the dream of a
thousand generations long gone and enter a new golden age of
behavioral, sociological and philosophical enlightenment? A
renaissance of the heart, a millennium of inner peace?
</P>
<P>
   Happily for our benighted species, that very process has begun.
The ethical, moral and teleological questions that for so long had
the likes of Aristotle and St. Anselm and Lord Lloyd-Webber tossing
fitfully in their sleep are finally being answered. The dark
turnings of human nature are being illuminated. Our primitive quest
for the grace that surpasseth understanding is well under way. And
thanks to the most useful and compassionate technology of them all,
television, we can watch this postmodern reformation of human
character played out five days a week. Several times each day, in
fact.
</P>
<P>
   And who, you ask, are we to thank for this inspiring stampede
toward a brighter future? Grateful citizens, relieved theologians
and giddy philosophers everywhere need really remember only one
name: Maury Povich. For it is on his daytime talk show that we as a
nation now seek to wrestle with nothing less than original sin
itself.
</P>
<P>
   It turns out that our last 2,000 years of thoughtful argument
over mysterious issues of redemption and damnation were nothing but
a huge waste of time. We were barking up the wrong tree of
knowledge, apparently, because perdition and sin and low
self-esteem, Povich has recently discovered, along with smoking,
drinking and breaking curfew, can be averted by one simple thing.
By just yelling at our children, or, better still, by hiring burly
professionals to yell at our children, we can make the world a
sweeter place.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Maury'' show is, to quote a recent issue of Entertainment
Weekly, this season's ``biggest success story'' in syndicated
daytime television. The show's ratings are up some 19 percent since
last year, and it now occasionally outpoints the popular ``Rosie
O'Donnell Show'' in the same time slot here in New York. This
``daytime yakker'' has got the ``big mo,'' they say. How did
``Maury'' do it? How did the show go from eponymous also-ran to
daytime juggernaut, more highly rated than even ``The Jerry
Springer Show,'' and now running neck and neck with the neckwear
savant Regis Philbin and the soon-to-be-marginally-less-ubiquitous
Kathie Lee Gifford? What's all the shouting about?
</P>
<P>
   The shouting is about shouting, actually, because ``Maury'' has
bootstrapped itself into the American brainpan by making volume a
virtue and battling evil at the top of its lungs. During the May
sweeps period, in which ratings are translated into advertising
rates and, therefore, profits, wayward teen-agers and delinquent
children of all stripes were being remade as model citizens on
programs subtitled ``My Wild Teen Needs Boot Camp!'' and ``Stop
Staring at My Teen Daughter's Body!'' and ``My Teen Needs Sex To
Survive!'' Oh, do these kids get yelled at!
</P>
<P>
   The premise for each episode of these behavioral makeovers,
which ran in heavy rotation during sweeps, is easily explained, and
their architecture rarely varies. Maury, clad in the stylish
vestments of the media priesthood (black V-neck sweater over a
white T-shirt), solemnly intones an introduction to the day's
battle of Right (Maury) against Wrong (teen girls who dress too
provocatively!, teen girls who dress too provocatively and verbally
abuse their mothers!, teen girls who dress too provocatively and
verbally abuse their mothers while trying to choke them! Teen girls
who smoke, drink, do drugs and have sex! Have unprotected sex! Have
unprotected sex with multiple partners and dress too
provocatively!). A bare handful of shows will include a teen-age
boy. He will seem lonely and confused.
</P>
<P>
   What follows is as ritualized as a high Mass. A worried mother
is brought onto the set. She is introduced, usually by her first
name only and with no further identification. We don't know where
she's from or how she came to be here. (Fathers are entirely absent
on the vast majority of these programs.) She then describes to
Maury, who looks on with an expression of beatific sympathy, her
daughter's pattern of delinquency. Most of the girls, it seems,
dress far too provocatively for someone their age (which ranges on
the shows I've seen from 8 to about 15; apparently all the bad
18-and-ups are over on the Springer show) and are engaged in risky
pursuits like smoking and imbibing hard liquor and having _ did we
mention this yet? _ sex. The mother's tearful monologue is only
occasionally interrupted for a Maurian sidebar like, ``And how many
times has she been arrested?'' or ``And then she tried to choke
you?'' or ``And how old is the oldest guy you've seen hit on her?''
The mothers are never asked if they're any good at mothering, or
work instead at a Hell's Angels meth lab in the desert. It seems,
rather, that the troubled adolescent has simply been possessed by
an evil spirit.
</P>
<P>
   By now the studio audience is groaning in disgust and seems very
anxious to meet this hell-bound Lolita. Maury obliges and we cut to
a jittery, hand-held shot from backstage, where the invariably
halter-wearing or tube-topped youngster is either slouching,
pacing, standing confrontationally with arms akimbo or gyrating in
an overtly, dare we say, provocative manner. Irrespective of body
position, each delivers an articulate rebuttal to whatever Mom just
said, generally along the lines of ``I'm 14 and I'm a grown-up
woman and I can live any way I want to and men buy me things
because of my big bosoms and I smoke and I drink and I don't care
what that (bleep) says, 'cause she's a (bleep) and don't know
nothin' about me.''
</P>
<P>
   We cut back to Povich, who clucks his tongue and introduces the
debutante in question. She enters the main stage to the derisive
catcalls of the audience. Her response? ``You don't know (bleep)
about (bleep), so shut up!'' Maury, familiar, no doubt, with
Robert's Rules of Order, gavels the crowd into line with the
shouted phrase ``Wait a minute! Wait a minute!'' and his
prosecution of the case begins. This takes the form of repeating
everything the girl just said, while she nods and says ``uh-huh.''
Satisfied that we're all on the same page, sex-and-violence-wise,
Maury cuts sharply to the epistemological heart of the matter.
``Why?'' he yodels, his face a medieval woodcut of dour concern,
``Why would you do this?'' Snapping her gum and clearly
overmatched, the girl answers for all humanity when she says: ``I
don't know. It's fun, I guess.'' O, weakness! O, vanity! Thus is
the scene set for the impending exorcism.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   Over the course of the next few segments, paced by the
commercial breaks (of which ``Maury'' has many, most having
something to do with getting the disability settlement you so
richly deserve, or with the show's own solicitations for further
troubled, well-built teen-agers), Povich introduces several more
mothers and their fallen angels, each as beguiling and foulmouthed
as the first. All the girls seem to break Maury's mighty heart with
the news that they want to be exotic dancers when they grow up. The
stage is filled with pain, fret and woe; mothers at their wits' end
and incorrigible daughters in skimpy outfits, and Maury Povich
wrangling it all with only his near-rabbinical persistence and his
cue cards to help him.
</P>
<P>
   There are two main variations of what comes next. In the first,
less elaborate version, a couple of streetwise counselors are
called on to scare the Satan straight out of these children. On
some shows, the first counselor, usually quite a bombshell, seems
to be a former sex worker or a contrite stripper or a recovering
porn star who's there to tell the girls that the glamorous adult
entertainment industry isn't the daffy hayride it's made out to be.
Again, credentials and bona fides remain murky to viewers. Her
fellow counselor is usually a large, loud man with a superfluity of
biceps and a larynx the size and density of an anvil. This becomes
evident backstage during the ensuing videotape piece in which he
roars questions at the hard-bitten little ragamuffins like ``You
think you're bad? You think you're BAD?''
</P>
<P>
   To which the girls can only reply with modest silence. The
former burlesque queen, however, is more specific, if less
explosive; asking if they all want to die of a drug overdose or get
stabbed to death in an alley. Waiting to hear other options,
perhaps, no one answers. This means that it's time to put the
recalcitrant darlings into the van and drive them to Times Square.
Upon arrival, they gather in front of a neon sign advertising one
of the few remaining neighborhood sex shows _ to be yelled at some
more. ``Don't you want to have your dignity?'' bellows one
counselor. ``Do you want to get AIDS?'' shrieks the other. Next
thing you know (``Maury'' editors play fast and loose with
chronology in these pieces) everyone is standing in that alley next
to a very sinister Dumpster. ``Don't you know that you have to love
yourself?'' brays one. ``I love you!'' screams the other. Regret is
mumbled. Sniffles snuffled. Tears roll down pubescent cheeks and
order is restored to the universe. These girls won't go bad. At
least not until someone turns off those camera lights. Fade to
black.
</P>
<P>
   In version two, usually titled ``Teen Boot Camp,'' the scantily
clad miscreants are inventoried as before, but are then confronted
by men in camouflage fatigues and freshly blocked troopers' hats.
Now it's two large men yelling, ``You think you're bad? You think
you're BAD?'' (One assumes this to be an effective line of inquiry
for many certified psychotherapists.) The kiddies are then hauled
off to a boot camp, the location and identification of which are
also unclear in some cases; although I caught one show wherein it
was actually specified as a facility of the Colorado County
Juvenile Boot Camp, located in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Upon arrival, the yelling begins in earnest and so do the
pushups. With various unidentified drill instructors hollering at
them, ``Don't you know you have to love yourself?'' the jumpsuited
teens are forced to realize the error of their mulish ways by
hauling buckets full of water, eating without utensils and cleaning
up after themselves. ``Sir, yes, sir!'' After a few days of basic
training (compressed into seconds on tape) sniffles are heard
again, tears course down reformed faces and tough love conquers
all.
</P>
<P>
   The bonus round on the boot camp shows, though, is the girls'
return from the Inferno. Having been walked through Hell by Master
Sgt. Virgil and his shock troops, they are meek as lambs. Hell,
apparently, has many toilets that need scrubbing with a toothbrush.
The girls reappear, sometimes wearing matching black berets and
antisexy khaki coveralls _ paramilitary angels, really _ and are
weepily reunited with their moms. Hugs abound and smiles widen and
each has a little gift for Uncle Maury, too.
</P>
<P>
   Maury is happier than anyone at how things turned out, and
speaks in a generous and gentle whisper to each of the girls.
``What was it like at night being alone in a cell?'' or ``Were you
scared?'' he'll ask, and then extract from each the assurance that
they'll never be bad or choke dear mother again. On one such show
each was promised a free college education if she could remain
revirginized. Souls saved, Maury presents his benediction. Turning
to the nearest mother he says, ``As adults we have to assess our
behavior, too.'' Chin quivering as if she's hooked to an outlet
offstage, Mom agrees. ``Absolutely,'' she chokes out. Roll credits.
</P>
<P>
   Original sin thwarted and the rites of absolution performed in
44 minutes, plus commercials.
</P>
<P>
   Maury's not the only one with a new take on ``Crime and
Punishment.'' The stalwart Sally Jessy Raphael sends more than her
fair share of malevolent teens to boot camp on her syndicated show,
too, especially if they trash her green room right on camera; but
her version lacks the dire brio Maury brings to the work. Maury has
about him the evangelical enthusiasm of a tent-show revivalist.
Sally seems to have lost her zest for it, and often as not when
reading her cue cards has the appearance of a zoo employee who's
inadvertently been darted by her own tranquilizer gun.
</P>
<P>
   That morning television now regularly flirts with this kind of
quasi-kiddie pornography and gets away with it should trouble
someone, somewhere. But daytime television doesn't seem to merit
much serious criticism these days, or cultural oversight; it has
become a fact of life that these shows escape examination or
community outcry. At least ``The Jerry Springer Show'' only
humiliates and abuses consenting adults. Perhaps that's why the
ratings are down.
</P>
<P>
   Even behind the fig leaf of moral reclamation, though, shows of
the teen boot camp genre trade on the misdirected and theatrical
sexualization of minors. Parents are confused by nothing more than
the sexual maturing of their own children, I suppose, so the
punitive aspect of these programs, the stamping out of early and
inappropriate fires, may explain their popularity among some
daytime viewers. What mother, after all, hasn't been appalled or
frightened by the behavior of her teen-age daughter at one time or
another? Comfort lies in seeing that behavior punished and things
set right.
</P>
<P>
   The creepy titillations that also underlie shows of this nature,
however, are a different story. Guests on every talk show
everywhere are coached by their segment producers to be lively,
animated and demonstrative. One can only wonder what these children
_ and they are children, no matter how they're built _ are being
told to do and say by the producers.
</P>
<P>
   At a time when one in five wired youngsters say they've been
sexually approached on the Internet, when every advertising medium
from television to billboards to radio to magazines packages and
repackages sex as a marketing tool, when the secret cash cows among
the dot-coms are pay pornography sites and an online search for
``schoolgirl sex'' or ``teen sex'' produces hundreds of thousands
of hits, can we really be shocked, surprised or self-righteous
about the fact that our children spit out lungfuls of the very
sexuality we immerse them in? And, having taught them these
responses, doesn't it seem unjust to punish them in the village
square just to satisfy our own bad appetite for revenge? Are we mad
at them or at Britney Spears and Christina Aguilera, the sexually
aggressive soft-core prom queens of MTV? Or do we simply punish our
children publicly because we resent living in an entertainment
nation co-opted by the tastes and buying patterns of teen-agers?
</P>
<P>
   Like Maury says, ``As adults we have to assess our behavior,
too.''
</P>
<P>
   Absolutely.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
