<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-IRVINRETIRE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Emotional Irvin steps away from Cowboys
 &HT;    By Gary Estwick
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas - For Michael Irvin, pushing off cornerbacks
seemed easy compared to fighting back emotions Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   With Texas Stadium as his backdrop and three Super Bowl banners
waving
</P>
<P>
   in the background, Irvin ended his 11-year association with the
Dallas
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys the way his family wanted him to - on his feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Playing the game is a blessing,'' said Irvin, a wide receiver
who holds
</P>
<P>
   almost every major Cowboys receiving record. ``But walking away
was a
</P>
<P>
   blessing. And I have to take that blessing.''
</P>
<P>
   Irvin was injured Oct. 10. Following a reception, his head
slammed
</P>
<P>
   into the hard turf of Philadelphia's Veterans Stadium,
temporarily
</P>
<P>
   paralyzing him.
</P>
<P>
   Tests revealed that he sustained a herniated disc, but they also
</P>
<P>
   detected that Irvin was born with a narrow spinal cord.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors said because of that genetic condition another blow to
his
</P>
<P>
   head or neck could be lethal.
</P>
<P>
   He stuttered when asked when the idea of retirement really hit
him.
</P>
<P>
   Irvin thought back to earlier this offseason when he was playing
with
</P>
<P>
   his kids. His wife started crying.
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked 'Why are you crying?' `` said Irvin, who has a solid
chance of
</P>
<P>
   making the Pro Football Hall of Fame. ``She said, 'I just always
want to
</P>
<P>
   make sure you're able to play with the kids. '
</P>
<P>
   ``From a physical standpoint, I could probably still line up and
play
</P>
<P>
   football, but I knew that there would never be peace if I played
again.''
</P>
<P>
   Irvin, 34, who was a free agent, said he didn't plan on testing
the market
</P>
<P>
   for his services elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never wanted to give my heart to any other team than the
Dallas fans
</P>
<P>
   because that's what they gave me,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Former teammate Daryl Johnston said more than anything the
Cowboys will miss Irvin's work ethic.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really pushed a lot of us as teammates to work as hard as
him
</P>
<P>
   because you wanted to reach the same goals that he did,''
Johnston said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You watched him work as hard as he did, as great of a player
as he was,
</P>
<P>
   and it just forced everyone else to work that hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Dallas coach Dave Campo agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my opinion, you're looking at the most competitive receiver
to ever
</P>
<P>
   play the game,'' Campo said. ``Whatever Michael did, whether it
</P>
<P>
   was playing dominoes, whether it was basketball, on the practice
field,
</P>
<P>
   in games, he has that little something extra that it takes for
him to be
</P>
<P>
   the best at whatever he did.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys prepped for life after Irvin in February,
</P>
<P>
   acquiring receiver Joey Galloway from Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout his years in Dallas, Irvin. along with Troy Aikman
and Emmitt
</P>
<P>
   Smith, was one of the ``triplets.'' He shared great and not so
great
</P>
<P>
   times.
</P>
<P>
   Those problems included a 1996 motel-room drug bust, which led
to an
</P>
<P>
   NFL suspension, 800 hours of community service and four years of
</P>
<P>
   probation, which was lifted Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Irvin was falsely accused of sexual assault in December
1996 and
</P>
<P>
   in 1998 training camp he cut the neck of a teammate during a
scuffle
</P>
<P>
   over a haircut.
</P>
<P>
   At his farewell announcement, current and former Cowboys were on
present to wish him farewell, including Larry Allen, Johnston and
Deion Sanders, now with the Washington Redskins.
</P>
<P>
   Irvin won't leave football completely. He will work with Fox
Sports
</P>
<P>
   Net next season.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
