<DOCNO> NYT20000711.0350 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-11 21:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9414 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-ZAKS-THEATER-$ADV16-A     07-11 1004
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ZAKS-THEATER-$ADV16-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON THE REBOUND IN A SAFE HAVEN: HARD WORK 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.J., N.H., Mass. Germany)   (For release Sunday, July 16)  
 &HT;    (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By ROBIN POGREBIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``Epic Proportions.'' ``The Civil War.'' ``The
Cripple of Inishmaan.'' ``Capeman.'' One would think a director
might want to hide out for a while and recuperate after such a
string of flops.
</P>
<P>
   But the director in question is Jerry Zaks, who not so very long
ago also produced a string of hits, including ``Six Degrees of
Separation,'' ``The House of Blue Leaves,'' ``Lend Me a Tenor'' and
``Guys and Dolls,'' each of which won him a Tony Award _ not to
mention his Tony nominations for ``A Funny Thing Happened on the
Way to the Forum,'' ``Anything Goes'' and ``Smokey Joe's Cafe.''
</P>
<P>
   He has been in the business long enough to know that the best
way to heal is to keep on working. So, sitting in the cool darkness
of the Roundabout Theater Company's newly refurbished American
Airlines Theater, where his Broadway production of ``The Man Who
Came to Dinner'' opens on July 27, Zaks did not deny that the last
few years have been trying ones. But he also seemed anything but
defeatist. ``I think you've got to look at the big picture,'' he
said. ``I believe my best work is ahead of me.''
</P>
<P>
   Some would argue that Zaks has not so much failed his more
recent projects as that they have failed him. New comedies, even
more than straight plays, are a dying breed on Broadway. In large
part because writers have defected to television and movies,
producers say good funny material is increasingly hard to come by.
With plays costing $1 million or more to mount, comedies have also
become risky business, unless they are pretested London imports.
</P>
<P>
   ``Producers are afraid,'' said Rocco Landesman, the president of
Jujamcyn Theaters. ``They see enough of them fail.''
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, the few American comedies that have made it to
Broadway lately have died quick deaths, namely last season's
``Wrong Mountain'' by David Hirson and ``Taller Than a Dwarf'' by
Elaine May. In the 1998-99 season, of course, there was Rob
Bartlett's ``More to Love: A Big Fat Comedy.'' It wasn't.
</P>
<P>
   Emanuel Azenberg, who produces Neil Simon's work on Broadway,
said that writing funny is harder than it used to be, that Jewish
humor and African-American humor are no longer novel and that the
comic writers of the 1930s and 1940s have not been replaced. ``I
don't know what's funny about society now,'' Azenberg said. ``A
good comedy is not jokes, it's organic situations.''
</P>
<P>
   While Zaks, 53, is reluctant to blame the material, it is clear
that the pool of potential projects is not as deep as it once was.
``I read fewer and fewer scripts that make me laugh out loud,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Zaks said, experience coupled with success breeds
a kind of hubris, the kind that makes a director feel as if he can
triumph, whatever the obstacles. ``Because you are confident in
your skills as a director, you think you can make anything work,''
he said. ``And learning that is not the case when the material
doesn't support it is a hard lesson.''
</P>
<P>
   Why venture into problematic material at all? Zaks said that if
he had known it was problematic, he wouldn't have done it in the
first place. ``That's like saying you shouldn't have fallen in love
with someone,'' he said. ``It's not rational. It's an emotional
response.''
</P>
<P>
   The director said he had had that emotional response to ``The
Man Who Came to Dinner,'' the 1939 comedy by George S. Kaufman and
Moss Hart, after directing a reading of it about three years ago
for the Roundabout, which then decided to mount a full-fledged
production in its new theater on 42nd Street.
</P>
<P>
   The show stars Nathan Lane _ who also did the reading _ as
Sheridan Whiteside, a curmudgeonly New York writer and critic based
on Alexander Woollcott, who fractures his hip on the front steps of
a well-to-do family's Ohio home and torments the occupants during
his recuperative stay. Monty Woolley originated the role on
Broadway, where the play ran for 21 months and was subsequently
made into a movie.
</P>
<P>
   The cast of the current production also includes Jean Smart,
Stephen DeRosa, Byron Jennings, Lewis J. Stadlen and Julie Halston,
all of whom inhabit the luxurious living room set designed by Tony
Walton that pays tribute to the Roundabout's elegant surroundings,
the renovated Selwyn Theater.
</P>
<P>
   Zaks said he had refused to do the show without Lane, whom he
had directed in ``Guys and Dolls,'' ``Laughter on the 23d Floor,''
``A Funny Thing'' and a reading of Stephen Sondheim's musical
``Assassins.''
</P>
<P>
   The two men both said they had enjoyed creating Whiteside.
``Nathan and I talk a lot about how much does the character need at
any given moment to dispatch the people he's irritated by,'' Zaks
said. ``Does he need a BB gun? Does he need a bazooka? And
modulating that is important, lest he come across as just mean.''
</P>
<P>
   It is this kind of thinking through of a play that seems to
animate and sustain Zaks, whom colleagues describe as hard to get
to know. He takes obvious pride and comfort in perfecting a
production's theatrical details: how speeding up the delivery of a
line can suddenly make it funny; how a nail file might prove to be
a comic piece of business; how closing a door at the wrong moment
can kill a laugh. For Zaks, it seems, the work itself is a refuge _
safe and solid ground, the place where he calls the shots and feels
secure in his own capacity to make things right with the world.
</P>
<P>
   This production is the sum of thousands of little moments that
we have investigated, played with and orchestrated,'' Zaks said.
``There is no way to describe the joy I feel in the back of the
house when the audience is having a great time. Aside from my kids,
it's my greatest pride.''
</P>
<P>
   (MORE)  &QL; 
 &QL; 
</P>
<P>
   In talking about how he directs, Zaks keeps mentioning trust as
paramount _ how his collaboration with Lane is strong because the
actor has faith in him. ``I depend upon the kindness of
playwrights, I also depend on the brilliance of really good
actors,'' Zaks said. ``An actor like Nathan, who's got his craft
right at his fingertips, he trusts me to suggest and shape and
observe. You feel kind of unlimited potential when you have that
connection.''
</P>
<P>
   Zaks' guardedness and his emphasis on trust seem to resonate
with his background. Born in Germany, he is the son of Holocaust
survivors. His mother, Lily, was liberated at Auschwitz; his
father, Cy, a kosher butcher, escaped the Nazis by masquerading as
a Gentile.
</P>
<P>
   Zaks was brought up in Paterson, N.J., and planned on becoming a
doctor. But after taking a date to see a Dartmouth production of
``Wonderful Town'' in his sophomore year, he was hooked and dropped
his pre-med classes.
</P>
<P>
   A heavy young man, he went on a diet and regularly closed
himself in a studio to dance to musicals like ``Hello, Dolly!''
until he was exhausted. He lost 40 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   After earning an MFA at Smith College, Zaks started acting in
New York with the Ensemble Studio Theater. He supported himself
with commercials and jobs in children's theater _ playing young
versions of Thomas Edison, Abraham Lincoln and Benjamin Franklin.
His first directing project was ``The Soft Touch,'' by Neil
Cuthbert in the mid-1970s. ``I stood in the back and fell in love
with directing,'' Zaks said. ``All of a sudden, I was getting a
different satisfaction than I got as an actor, but of the same
magnitude. It felt so good.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1986, he directed ``The House of Blue Leaves,'' the first in
a series of well-received productions for Lincoln Center Theater,
including ``Six Degrees of Separation,'' ``The Front Page'' and
``Anything Goes.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   ``He was responsible for the liftoff of this theater from a
standstill,'' said Bernard Gersten, executive producer of Lincoln
Center Theater. ``So my regard for Jerry and his talents is
boundless.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   Paradoxically, perhaps, these early hits made Zaks a tough act
even for him to follow. ``When you have a burst of success
initially, they're all waiting and praying for you to fail,'' Lane
said. ``It's hard to keep that up, and eventually something is not
going to work.
</P>
<P>
   ``People say things _ nasty, nasty things _ and no matter how
successful you've been or how confident people think you are, it
hurts. It's just the nature of show business. It has its ups and
downs. People love you for a little and then they turn on you.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, some might question why Zaks turned his energies toward
``The Civil War,'' Frank Wildhorn's song cycle, or ``Epic
Proportions,'' Larry Coen and David Crane's comedy about making a
``Ten Commandments''-style movie in the 1930s _ both of which
closed on Broadway because of lack of business. Or, they might ask,
why did Zaks decide to come in as a ``production supervisor'' on
last season's Broadway revue ``Swing!'' _ which was directed and
choreographed by Lynne Taylor-Corbett _ as well as try to rescue
Paul Simon's ``Capeman'' in 1998, for which he was uncredited in
the show's program.
</P>
<P>
   Landesman said that if Zaks had consulted him before taking on
``Epic Proportions,'' he would have advised against it. ``I would
have asked, `Is this a good enough play to bring out the best of
what you can do?''' Landesman said.
</P>
<P>
   Others believe that Zaks' work on ``Swing!'' _ a revue like the
longrunning ``Smokey Joe's Cafe,'' which Zaks directed in 1995 _ as
a ``production supervisor'' is the equivalent of script-doctoring
in the movies and unworthy of Zaks' considerable skills.
</P>
<P>
   Zaks responds that ``Epic Proportions'' made him laugh and that
``The Civil War'' _ which was overseen by Gregory Boyd at the Alley
Theater in Houston before Zaks took it on _ offered an opportunity
to do a show about an important subject. ``Swing!,'' he said, was a
challenge in terms of creating a unified whole out of several
disparate musical pieces.
</P>
<P>
   Landesman, who about 10 years ago gave Zaks an annual salary and
an office in exchange for getting first crack at his projects, said
he would like to see Zaks originate more material _ even though
``Smokey Joe's Cafe,'' ``The Civil War'' and ``Swing!'' were all
Jujamcyn shows. But he said he still believed that Zaks was the
best Broadway had to offer. ``There are more hits still in him,''
Landesman said. ``I have total confidence in the guy.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked what lessons he drew from his recent directing
experiences, Zaks demurred. ``It's painful, it's personal and it's
private,'' he said. ``I try not to live there too long.''
</P>
<P>
   But he continued: ``The work itself is no less fulfilling.
Obviously, I would prefer that something have a healthy and long
run. If it doesn't, it's because not enough people wanted to see
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Although he has been bitter about reviews and sometimes
surprised by them, Zaks said he did not hold critics responsible
for a show's ultimate demise. While his production of Larry Shue's
farce ``The Foreigner'' Off Broadway in the mid-1980s, for example,
was largely dismissed, it ran for about three years on the strength
of word of mouth.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   ``A negative review never helps, but I don't think it's the
difference between something running and not running,'' Zaks said.
``I take pride in it all. I always hope that it's good enough that
someone will leave the theater and tell someone, `You have to see
this.'''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Zaks speaks of ``The Man Who Came to Dinner''
as if it belongs in another category, as if he is grateful for a
return to quality. ``I'd forgotten how good it feels to be
presiding over material as special as I think this is,'' he said.
``Sitting through this is something I look forward to and it's been
a while since I felt that.''
</P>
<P>
   Lane said the project clearly agrees with his friend. ``I've
never seen Jerry this happy, never seen him this relaxed,'' he
said. ``Hopefully, it's a tribute to the work we've been doing and
his own maturity. I've never seen him quite like this before.''
</P>
<P>
   Zaks said he had been going through a tough time in his private
life because his wife had been ill and that ``personal life has an
impact on the work.'' They have two daughters _ 12 and 18. Zaks met
his wife, Jill Rose, a former dancer, while doing a national tour
of ``Grease'' during Zaks' acting days _ he played Kenickie, she
played Frenchie.
</P>
<P>
   But while Zaks worries about what he could have done to make
certain shows better, he does not seem to obsess about whether
various misfires might damage his reputation in the long run. ``The
people who put on shows know what I do,'' he said. ``And they
haven't seemed any more reluctant to have me do what I do because a
couple of shows haven't worked at the box office.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Professionally and personally, things couldn't be better,'' he
said. ``It's showtime.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-11-00 2123EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
