<HEADLINE>
CARTER AND BRUINS NO CLOSER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY MARRAPESE-BURRELL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ During the weekend of the NHL draft, with the league's
brain trust gathered in Calgary, Alberta, Bruins forward Anson
Carter thought his phone was going to ring with the news that
Boston had traded him.
</P>
<P>
   Carter, who became a restricted free agent July 1, heard that he
was a likely candidate to change teams. The rumor that the Bruins
were shopping him persisted in the days before the draft and
continues. It has followed the 26-year-old Carter all the way to
Los Angeles, where he is rehabilitating from shoulder and wrist
surgeries.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm holding out that there's a possibility I will be back,''
said Carter. ``But my gut feeling is that I won't be back, to tell
you the truth. I definitely have the feeling that the word is out
there. I'm not surprised about that at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could come from the organization _ I'm almost positive
that's where it's coming from. I think they might (perceive) I view
myself as `X' and they view me as `Y' and therefore, instead of
having to deal with this problem, `Why not move him and see what we
can get for him?'
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a professional and if that's the case I'm going to do my
thing regardless of where I am. At the same time, if I'm going to
be back with the Bruins, I want to be signed by training camp
because it is a big year.''
</P>
<P>
   This is not the first time Carter and Bruins management have
haggled over a contract. They went through a difficult time in the
summer of 1998 when he was up for renewal. Carter missed all of
training camp and the first month of the season before coming to
terms on a two-year deal.
</P>
<P>
   Carter believes he is worth more than the Bruins are willing to
pay him. He had hoped to avoid turmoil with an extension similar to
the one the Bruins and center Jason Allison ironed out before
Allison's surgeries. But it wasn't to be.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right from the initial talks, the feeling I got is that they
view me as a certain kind of player and I view myself as being
another kind of player in terms of salary structure,'' said Carter.
``We're not even close right now. You'd like to say we're close,
and there's a chance, but we're not. It is early, but based on my
past dealings with the organization, this could take a while. If
not, I'll probably end up being traded.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter said he's not surprised at the impasse. The shock is that
he's not already elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be honest, I thought I was getting traded at the draft,''
he said. ``I told my friend (goalie) Kevin Weekes that I thought
for sure I was getting traded. It turned out he got traded instead
of myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter thought it might be easier this time because he has the
right to file for arbitration, something he didn't have two summers
ago. But he doesn't believe the Bruins view him any differently.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't even seem like it's a big deal now,'' he said.
``Now I have it and you're still hearing the same thing. I'm not
really worried about it. My priority is rehabbing my wrist and my
shoulder. I'm six weeks ahead of schedule so I'm pretty pumped
about that.''
</P>
<P>
   If the sides, down the road, don't get any closer, Carter said
he'd be quicker to ask for a trade than wait it out and try to find
another option such as playing in the IHL, as he did in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would use the beginning of camp as an ideal date,'' he said.
``I think the ball's in their court because I can't negotiate with
myself. We haven't heard from them in about two months. It's up to
them to decide what they want to do, if they want me on their squad
or not and at what cost. If that's not the case, maybe they should
move me.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter said he's not worried about what may happen, but he has
thought long and hard about the possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't see them trading Joe (Thornton) and (Sergei
Samsonov),'' he said. ``They've invested so much money into their
first-round picks. If things don't work out with one of the three
of us, I might be the logical guy to deal. I've played all those
scenarios a million times through my head already.''
</P>
<P>
   If he does get traded, he won't have many loose ends to tie up.
He decided to rent in the Boston area rather than buy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I looked into buying but then I decided to rent a place,'' he
said. ``I thought about it because I didn't get the feeling that I
was one of those guys they wanted to build around. That was my gut
feeling. Just because of what we went through, the whole contract
negotiation, and how far apart we were, and how they view me as a
hockey player. I got the feeling I wasn't going to be here very
long.''
</P>
<P>
   Bruins president/general manager Harry Sinden acknowledged that
progress has been slow, as it has been around the league with all
restricted free agents.
</P>
<P>
   ``We aren't having any communications right now,'' said Sinden.
``He's been out a long time with his injuries. His got started much
earlier than anyone else's but it hasn't gone anywhere. All
indications are that it is (going to be very difficult), yes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
