u i BC-MIDEAST-TALKS-1STLD-W     07-11 0321
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-TALKS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 THURMONT, Md.: been talking.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Many think that each side's intractable claims on the holy city
make the issue irresolvable, although Israeli television reported
that Barak was prepared to compromise on all issues, including
Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials said that Barak has indicated in his
public statements and, again, in his private statements, that he
must return to Israel with some kind of a deal if he hopes to hold
his government together.
</P>
<P>
   However, Clinton, who was to spend the night at Camp David with
the two leaders, is unlikely to offer specific proposals for a few
days, hoping instead to spend the first sessions airing out the
issues.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials said they expect the ``crunch days''
for negotiators to be next Monday and Tuesday, ahead of Clinton's
scheduled departure next Wednesday for Okinawa and a meeting with
leaders of the industrial nations.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Before arriving in the United States early on Tuesday morning, a
senior Israeli official told Israeli reporters aboard Barak's plane
that the prime minister was unruffled by the defection of three
rightist parties from his coalition and a no-confidence motion in
parliament that barely failed. The official, trying to put a
positive spin on events, said that Barak considered it an
accomplishment that the parties had stayed in his government for a
year.
</P>
<P>
   He also said that Barak believed that his position at the summit
would be strengthened by the fact that he had not spent the last
year at the helm of a narrow, dovish government.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinian officials worried quietly that Americans and
Israelis would pressure them into making unwanted concessions
because of Barak's political problems, referring to frequent
mentions of the idea that Barak represented the best peace partner
they could hope for.
</P>
</TEXT>
