<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMMIE-COMEDY-$ADV16-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW THEY STUFFED A COMMUNIST BIKINI 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, July 16) 
 By J. HOBERMAN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The phrase ``Communist musical comedy'' may sound like an
oxymoron, but even the officially achieved utopia of
no-longer-extant East Germany required a few measures of utopian
song-and-dance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hot Summer,'' the teen-age musical that was the DDR's
second-highest-grossing film in 1968, is not quite socialism
a-go-go but it's an entertaining artifact nonetheless.
</P>
<P>
   Like most movies produced in East Germany, ``Hot Summer''
(Icestorm International, 91 minutes, German with English subtitles)
is virtually unknown here _ although the strident, vaguely martial
title song, staged amid the scrubbed streets of downtown
Karl-Marx-Stadt, was excerpted in ``East Side Story,'' the sardonic
1997 documentary about Communist musicals by the independent
filmmakers Dana Ranga and Andrew Horn.
</P>
<P>
   Directed in wide-screen and pastel colors by the former
cameraman Joachim Hasler, ``Hot Summer'' is a collectivist romantic
fling. A group of 10 hitchhiking high school girls compete with a
comparable band of high school boys to see who can arrive first at
their vacation spot on the Baltic coast. The contest continues,
amid much cavorting on the beach, after they arrive: The boys play
a series of pranks (releasing mice in the girls' dorm); the girls
respond with taunting songs (``They think they're such big guys but
really they're babies in disguise'').
</P>
<P>
   Produced as part of a new emphasis on genre entertainments that
followed a ban of 11 mildly critical films, ``Hot Summer'' was not
the first East German musical, but it was the first youth musical.
Two of the stars, Frank Schoebel and Chris Doerk, were a popular
singing duo. Although labeled the ``East German `Grease''' by its
American distributors, ``Hot Summer'' is closer at heart to the
teen-age drive-in fare produced by American International Pictures.
(The oompah beat and regimented choruses also recall ``The Sound of
Music'' _ albeit with discreetly honking saxophones and twanging
guitars.)
</P>
<P>
   Made at the height of the international youth movement _ the
year AIP switched from ``How to Stuff a Wild Bikini'' to the
incendiary ``Wild in the Streets'' and Jean-Luc Godard unleashed
the cannibal hippies of ``Weekend'' _ ``Hot Summer'' is
relentlessly cheerful and upbeat. Authority is embodied by an
understanding cop and there is barely a hint of rebellion _ some
mild complaining about parents notwithstanding. The youths are
further characterized by a concern for culture. Two teen-agers
presage a night in the hayloft with prolonged quoting of classic
verse; another girl lectures her colleagues on Brecht's alienation
effect. The main dramatic tension pits the individual against the
group. Everybody does everything together, including shouting in
unison. The crucial question: ``Are we a collective or an ordinary
gang?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Hot Summer'' is part of the ongoing series of East German
films newly released by Icestorm International in association with
the University of Massachusetts. The video transfer is
well-produced in a letterbox format with new, thoroughly adequate
English subtitles. In the post-Communist Germany, ``Hot Summer''
has become a cult film in somewhat the same spirit that East
Germany's quaintly functional package designs have become
collectibles and the Communist ``kinderhymnes'' of the defunct Free
German Youth organization have been reissued on CD.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
