<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000711.0359 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-11 21:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9423 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-MIDEAST-SUMMIT-BOS &LR;      07-11 1113
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-SUMMIT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARAFAT, BARAK FACE `WRENCHING QUESTIONS,' CLINTON SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANN SCALES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   THURMONT, Md. _ President Clinton launched Camp David's second
Mideast peace summit Tuesday, saying Israeli Prime Minister Ehud
Barak and Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat ``face profound and
wrenching questions'' that will require compromises from both
sides.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking on the White House lawn before departing for the
presidential retreat, Clinton said the road to peace ``is a two-way
street'' and that ``both sides must find a way to resolve competing
claims.''
</P>
<P>
   In bringing together the two leaders in the rustic setting of
Camp David in the Catoctin Mountains, about 75 miles north of
Washington, Clinton is hoping that geography will once again play a
part in presidential and Mideast history. The retreat was the site
where then Israeli Prime Minister Menachem Begin and Egyptian
President Anwar Sadat struck a peace deal in 1978, under then
President Jimmy Carter.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said resolving the 52-year-old Israeli-Palestinian
conflict was the key to achieving a lasting peace in the Middle
East. ``Of course there is no guarantee of success, but not to try
is to guarantee failure,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The high stakes summit is taking place against the backdrop of a
series of deadlines. Clinton, who has only five months remaining on
his presidency and would like his legacy to include bringing peace
to the Middle East, rearranged his schedule this week to clear all
but part of Thursday for the peace talks. He was staying at Camp
David.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll do everything I can over the coming days to see that this
moment of promise is fulfilled,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The clock is also ticking toward the Sept. 13 deadline that
Arafat has publicly set for unilaterally declaring statehood, and
analysts say time is no friend either to Barak, whose political
base is steadily eroding and whose arrival here was delayed by a
government crisis and a parliamentary vote of no confidence that he
narrowly survived.
</P>
<P>
   Though all three leaders are in a race against time, the issues
may not be easily resolved, having defied solution in the seven
years since Israel agreed to begin turning over territory to the
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   They range from East Jerusalem, which the Palestinians seek as
their capital but which Barak insists will never be relinquished,
to the claims of Arab refugees to homes in Israel from which they
fled or were ousted after Israel's founding a half-century ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``The two leaders face profound and wrenching questions, and
there can be no success without principled compromise,'' Clinton
said before departing the White House for the talks.
</P>
<P>
   After arriving at Camp David Tuesday, Clinton went immediately
into a meeting with his US negotiating team. Afterwards, he took
turns meeting with Arafat and Barak on the back porch of the Aspen
presidential cabin _ about 30 minutes with Arafat and 50 minutes
with Barak.
</P>
<P>
   Later, the three men strolled side-by-side down an asphalt road
to the Laurel cabin for the first three-way talks of the summit.
Pausing for a photo op, Clinton put one arm around Barak and the
other around Arafat.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton refused to comment on how the meetings were going,
saying all sides had agreed not to publicly comment on the
substance of their meeting. Asked if that was the only agreement
they had reached so far, Clinton shot back, ``That would be
answering a question,'' drawing chuckles.
</P>
<P>
   But that was not the only funny moment of the day. That was
reserved for when Arafat and Barak, both seeking to be courteous,
could not agree on who should enter the cabin first.
</P>
<P>
   Once that was figured out _ Arafat went first _ the three men
and 18 aides (eight for Clinton and five each for Barak and Arafat)
met for half an hour at a long rectangular table. White House press
secretary Joseph Lockart described the atmosphere of the meeting as
``good,'' adding, ``The discussions have been serious.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton later held an evening round of one-on-one meetings with
Arafat and Barak.
</P>
<P>
   To make time for the summit, Clinton had canceled plans to speak
Tuesday afternoon to the annual convention of the National
Association for the Advancement of Colored People, posponing his
speech until Thursday morning, when he will already be in
Washington for a congressional medal of honor ceremony on Capitol
Hill.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, meanwhile, Hanan M. Ashrawi, a spokeswoman for
Arafat, told reporters at the National Press Club that the
Israeli-Palestinian talks should start with the premise of a return
to the borders before the 1967 Six-Day War and the return of more
than 3 million refugees now outside the country.
</P>
<P>
   Barak has rejected both demands, but Israeli press reports that
he was prepared to make sizable territorial concessions had
contributed to his pre-summit political woes.
</P>
<P>
   Ashrawi insisted several times Tuesday that Israel could not
strong-arm the Palestinians into a deal.
</P>
<P>
   Making peace, she said, ``is not a concession bestowed by the
strong on the weak, or it is not a result of an imposed or a faulty
agreement, but rather comes from dealing with the causes of
conflict.''
</P>
<P>
   She didn't sound optimistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``We understand that the American initiative to call for the
summit is _ I don't know if you can call it a last-ditch attempt or
heroic or a foolhardy attempt to try to achieve something within a
very short period of time. The most that they (the Americans) hope
for is to prevent further deterioriation or a breakdown.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott said he spoke to
Clinton and expressed his ``desire to be helpful'' in financing a
peace settlement. Lott said he would ``have to consider the
American taxpayer,'' but that he had not set a limit on how much in
US funds Clinton could approve.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it'd be a responsible thing for me to put a cap
at this point,'' Lott said.
</P>
<P>
   Lott also spoke to Barak and ``wished him well.'' But Lott said
he did not go into details with Barak about the peace process.
</P>
<P>
   Lott's involvement in foreign affairs marked a change in his
relationship with White House officials, whom he earlier accused of
purposely leaving congressional Republicans out of the loop. Last
month, Lott complained the Clinton administration ``had stopped the
appropriate consulting process.'' More recently, however, Lott said
Sandy Berger has been in frequent contact, and Lott seemed pleased
Tuesday with his role in the Mideast talks.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
John Donnelly and Anne Kornblut of the Globe staff contributed to
this report from Washington.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
