<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-11 21:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9425 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-MIDEAST-SUMMIT-HNS &LR;      07-11 1117
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-SUMMIT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MIDEAST TALKS PAST `POINT OF NO RETURN,' CLINTON TELLS TWO SIDES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   THURMONT, Md. _ President Clinton urged the Israeli and
Palestinian leaders to seek a ``principled compromise'' Tuesday as
he opened the Camp David summit in a high-stakes bid to resolve the
remaining obstacles to a long-sought Middle East peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Declaring the two sides ``have passed the point of no return,''
Clinton told Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak and Palestinian
leader Yasser Arafat that they must move forward to end more than a
half-century of violence between their peoples.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both sides must find a way to resolve competing claims, to
give their children the gift of peace. It will take patience and
creativity, and courage,'' Clinton said shortly before his first
round of meetings with the two leaders at the Camp David
presidential retreat four miles from this small, rural town.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton met first with Arafat at about noon and then with Barak
a short time later, as he sought to gauge their attitudes going
into the summit and what concessions it will take in order to
produce a final settlement.
</P>
<P>
   White House spokesman Joe Lockhart said all three leaders had
agreed to impose a news blackout during the summit aimed at
preventing any substance of the discussions from being leaked to
the press.
</P>
<P>
   For their part, the leaders had little to say as they strolled
along a winding asphalt path on their way to the Laurel cabin. They
stopped only briefly to pose for press photographers, but declined
to answer questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We pledged to each other we would answer no questions and
offer no comment, and I'd like to set a good example,'' Clinton
said, as he stood with one arm around Barak, the other around
Arafat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is that the only agreement you have reached so far?'' one
reporter ventured.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would be answering a question,'' Clinton replied,
laughing.
</P>
<P>
   A few minutes later, Barak and Arafat could be seen engaged in a
playful tugging match, as each sought to give way to the other when
entering the Laurel cabin to begin their first face-to-face
session. It appeared that the two, still smiling, finally gave up
their brief, diplomatic tango and crossed the threshold together.
But a U.S. official said later that Arafat finally acceded to
Barak's courtesy and walked through the door ahead of him.
</P>
<P>
   The amusing scene, which played itself out as Clinton stood by
laughing, belied the tough work ahead and the hard-line differences
that remain between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton spoke of the difficulty before the talks began.
</P>
<P>
   ``The two leaders face profound and wrenching questions, and
there can be no success without principled compromise. The road to
peace, as always, is a two-way street,'' Clinton said, adding that
he believes Barak and Arafat ``recognize this is a moment in
history which they can seize.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, there is no guarantee of success, but not to try is
to guarantee failure,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is hoping that the remoteness and history of Camp David,
where former President Carter helped Israel and Egypt forge their
peace deal in 1978, will encourage Barak and Arafat to break down
the final barriers to a comprehensive peace settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Noting the progress already made in the Arab-Israeli peace
process, from the historic Camp David accords to the Oslo agreement
seven years ago establishing the framework for a
Palestinian-Israeli peace, Clinton said, ``the parties have proven
that peace is possible when they are determined to make it.''
</P>
<P>
   The president suggested last week that it might be possible to
attain at least the outline of a final deal before he departs July
19 for the annual summit of the Group of Eight leading industrial
nations in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   But White House officials have since played down the idea of
wrapping up a deal in a matter of days, saying that it may be
necessary to resume the talks when Clinton returns from Japan or
hold a second round of negotiations at Camp David later in August.
</P>
<P>
   No matter how the talks unfold, striking a deal will not be
easy. It will have to settle their competing claims to Jerusalem,
the final borders of a Palestinian state, the status of Palestinian
refugees and what to do about 40,000 Jewish settlers in the West
Bank who will have to be moved.
</P>
<P>
   The Palestinians demonstrated how difficult the task is.
Speaking at the National Press Club in Washington on Tuesday,
Palestinian spokeswoman Hanan Ashrawi said that life for her people
``has become worse under the peace process.''
</P>
<P>
   The Israelis, she said, have failed to meet many of the terms
set out in the Oslo accords of seven years ago that were designed
to guide the transfer of lands captured in the 1967 Six Day War
back to the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Israel has returned control of only about 40 percent of
the occupied lands. June 23 was supposed to be the deadline for
Israel's withdrawal from nearly all of the West Bank and Gaza
Strip. Ashrawi said Israel has also allowed the expansion of
Israeli settlements in the West Bank to continue and has tightened
its control over Jerusalem even more.
</P>
<P>
   ``Israel should not come to the negotiations with extremist
positions, such as not returning to the 1967 boundaries or
maintaining sovereignty over Jerusalem,'' Ashrawi said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being extremely realistic, I don't expect to see a miraculous,
substantive breakthrough because the issues are complex. I have
read the Israel proposals and the gap is extremely wide. It will
take a great deal of effort to find areas of consensus, even
convergence,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Barak, meanwhile, is entering the talks reportedly ready to
relinquish Israeli control of up to 90 percent of the West Bank,
including the strategic Jordan Valley, and may be prepared as well
to redivide Jerusalem in order to make room for a Palestinian
capital.
</P>
<P>
   The status of Jerusalem and the final boundaries of a
Palestinian state are the thorniest of all the issues involved in
the peace process. Barak's positions have outraged Israeli
hard-liners who are basically opposed to any peace deal that
sacrifices Jewish settlements in the occupied territories or gives
up any part of the old walled city of East Jerusalem to Palestinian
control.
</P>
<P>
   Three factions of his ruling coalition have already resigned
because of the Israeli leader's eagerness to make peace. Barak was
able to survive a vote of confidence in the Israeli Knesset on
Monday, but he has promised that any agreement reached at the
summit will be put to a vote of the Israeli people.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY
</P>
