<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-11 21:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9426 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-PULITZER-PHOTOGRAPHY-     07-11 1408
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PULITZER-PHOTOGRAPHY-$ADV16-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAD NEWS DOES   BEAT OUT THE REST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, July 16)  
 By VICKI GOLDBERG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Now for the bad news: good news is on vacation.
Permanently.
</P>
<P>
   In the news media, anyway, ``no news is good news'' just might
be read as ``there is no such thing as good news,'' something local
television has been trying to convince viewers of for years. That
goes double for news photography: the news photographs you remember
are likely to compose a litany of grief and terror, from the murder
of Lee Harvey Oswald to the execution of a Vietcong prisoner on the
streets of Saigon to the dragging of a dead American soldier's body
through the streets of Mogadishu, Somalia.
</P>
<P>
   Pictures of those three events won Pulitzer Prizes. A show
called ``The Pulitzer Prize Photographs: Capture the Moment,'' at
the Newseum/NY in midtown Manhattan through Sept. 23, reinforces
the widespread impression that news tends to be violent and morbid.
Smiles, joy, tenderness and near misses exist in the Pulitzer
world, and fine extended captions relate that some of the rescue
attempts recorded here were successful, but most of the more than
100 pictures are almost equally endowed with visual distinction and
despair. Plummeting bodies, starving children and dead men in the
dust tend to crowd out the reassuring images of soldiers reunited
with their families and policemen being nice to little boys.
</P>
<P>
   The Pulitzer Prizes were established by Joseph Pulitzer, the
newspaper magnate, early in this century, with a bequest of $2
million to Columbia University to set up a school of journalism and
prizes for journalism, letters, music, drama and education as well
as traveling scholarships. (The university's president was at first
reluctant, fearing that a journalism school would diminish its
intellectual reputation.) The first prizes were given in 1917. In
1942, photography was added to the list, appropriately, for
photographs had already taken over the news. Tabloids and picture
magazines had made photographs not only central but essential. On
March 1, 1920, for example, The New York Times had no photographs
at all, but on an average day in 1938, The Times published a
picture on almost every news page. The Pulitzer Prize board created
a separate category for feature photographs in 1968, after faster
film and new small cameras like the Nikon had changed the
photographic territory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Capture the Moment,'' the largest collection of Pulitzer
Prize-winning photographs ever shown in this country, includes
pictures for every year from 1942 to 1999 except for 1946, when the
judges thought no entry worth a prize.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition moves to the Newseum in Arlington, Va., in
the.newseum.org. Curiously, the first large survey of this
distinctly American award was recently put on in Japan by and for
the Japanese, who have won Pulitzers a couple of times. (Pulitzer
submissions must have appeared in an American newspaper but need
not be by American citizens.)
</P>
<P>
   The first Pulitzer Prize-winning photograph was a picture of a
group of strikers beating a man; the 1999 photographs recorded the
carnage of the embassy bombing in Nairobi and several stages in the
Monica Lewinsky affair: from violence to violence, with a stop at
sex and shame.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   The common cant is that news (and games and films and music and
so on) have become more violent, which may well be true, but it is
a mistake to think the news was once a teddy bear that turned into
a grizzly when other media came along.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   Newspapers have included some measure of violence ever since
they stopped being commercial reports or political party organs in
the 1830s and began to sell for as little as a penny, appeal to a
broader audience and redefine news as accounts of large and small
events all over the world. Penny papers carried entire transcripts
of murder trials, something the old-fashioned kind of paper claimed
to find shocking. By the 1840s, engraved illustrations changed the
look of the news, and numerous papers found that pictures of
accused murderers, not to mention engravers' reconstructions of
actual killings, infallibly improved circulation figures.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the great bulk of visual news was and remains pretty tame,
relatively inert and unthreatening. It might be an image of rival
politicians pretending to respect each other, or the publicity
photograph of someone who was alive enough to pose for it until he
died of a heart attack last night, or perhaps a picture of football
players imitating pile drivers in a championship maneuver. Images
like these do not bore holes in the memory. The pictures that do,
though fewer, crowd out the rest by the size of the reaction they
create. Tragedy and violence get our attention, partly because they
are so fearsome, partly because they are, outside of a war zone,
relatively unusual. Dog bites man isn't news because it's all too
ordinary. Murder, on the other hand, is no more of an everyday
occurrence for most people than man bites dog.
</P>
<P>
   Relative rarity is obviously not the whole story. The pictures
of the kinds of events that have dominated the Pulitzers _ a
Japanese about to run a sword through a politician; a plane crashed
and burning in a suburban yard; a wounded soldier clinging
desperately to a priest in the midst of gunfire; a young woman
screaming over a dead student at Kent State _ are uncommon in many
ways. They are uncommonly well observed, which does not necessarily
mean artistic or aesthetic. They do capture a moment, a drama, at
some hideous and telling peak, stopping time so precipitously that
the mind involuntarily braces for what is implied and what must
come next _ the sword in the flesh, the crumpled bodies hidden now
by smoke.
</P>
<P>
   Danger, suffering and death magnetize the eyes for reasons that
are embedded in the nature of human existence. Pain and suffering
are hardly rare and death is ultimately ubiquitous, no matter how
uncommon it may be to meet it at the end of a sword. All of us
expend huge amounts of (mostly unconscious) energy avoiding even
thinking about pain or death, particularly our own, but pictures
are just removed enough and the people in them unknown and
unknowable enough to make looking at them seem temporarily safer
than dwelling on ourselves.
</P>
<P>
   Death is probably the ultimate fascination: what is it? what
happens when it arrives? what does it look like? how will it come
to me and how will I face it? Not that way, the news picture
whispers; not at that extreme. If that plane crashed, doesn't that
mean that mine has a better chance of arriving safely? Although
pictures of suffering, torture, starvation, death inflicted on the
innocent can make us judge humankind harshly and diminish our
self-respect in the process, to some small degree they might also
be reassuring: not me, not this time, not ever.
</P>
<P>
   Photographs of extreme situations frequently carry with them an
aura of derring-do, of danger and unbearable emotion outside the
fierce events they picture. How did the photographer get that
picture? Why did fate arrange for someone to be there at that
precise and hazardous instant? It goes without saying that war
photographers were under fire at the moment they clicked the
shutter, heroically or foolishly but certainly professionally
recording history, or at least garnering information. Many have
died in pursuit of that goal, and the death rate is increasing as
military, rebel and terrorist groups put journalists onto their hit
lists. Other kinds of dangers also attend the job. Photographers
chronicling refugees and starvation must have to overcome the
normal reactions of horror and pity in order simply to make the
pictures.
</P>
<P>
   Some burn out. In 1993, Kevin Carter, a South African
photojournalist, took a grim picture of a Sudanese child trying to
crawl to a feeding center while a vulture sat nearby. He chased the
bird away after taking the picture, and then he cried. After the
photograph was published, people reacted with outrage: why hadn't
he picked the child up? In fact, journalists had been expressly
instructed not to touch famine victims because of the risk of
disease. Nonetheless, Carter was torn by regrets. Doubtless he had
other troubles as well. He died in 1994 at the age of 33, an
apparent suicide _ three months after he won the Pulitzer. (MORE)  &QL; 
 &QL; 
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, the attractions of violent (or malevolent) imagery were
neither discovered nor invented by the camera or by other modern
media. Long before photography, hangings and beheadings were
memorialized in inexpensive woodcuts that were snapped up by the
droves of people who came out for the occasions or were unfortunate
enough to miss the main events. Well into the 19th century,
executions were holidays in many countries, and schools were let
out so that children could witness them. It was generally believed
that witnessing the rewards of sin would deter the witnesses from
following the same road, and that the sinner's repentance would be
particularly instructive.
</P>
<P>
   Public executions went private as governments realized that the
excitement they occasioned would not only fail to improve crime
statistics but could even incite disturbances. The moral value of
witnessing is still the main rationale for photographs of all kinds
of calamities, despite the intrusion of sensationalism into the mix
(or its continued presence). The first principle is that the public
needs to know, the second is the lingering belief that a public
aware of injustice will do something to correct it. The kinds of
horrifying news pictures that are sometimes called immoral and
charged with pandering to our baser instincts and provoking
copy-cat behavior may have begun in idealism and a photographer's
yearning for a righteous place to stand.
</P>
<P>
   An actual place to stand, a location, is as important in
photojournalism as it is in real estate; no amount of talent will
suffice if the photographer is not where the action is. In the
early years of the Pulitzer Prizes, in 1947 and 1954, two amateurs
won the awards. The first was a college student who grabbed his
camera when he heard fire trucks and snapped a woman plunging
through the air as she jumped to escape the flames. The second
amateur was a woman who was behind a truck when the truck's
steering went out of control and sent its cab dangling perilously
over the edge of a bridge. As her husband went to the rescue, she
took a picture of one of the two truck drivers being pulled to
safety on a rope, and won a Pulitzer. (The other driver made it,
too, seconds before the cab burst into flames and plunged to the
rocks 70 feet below.)
</P>
<P>
   The fact that amateurs could beat out the pros says something
about the nature of news, the omnipresence of cameras and the
democratizing nature of consumer technology. Years ago, inexpensive
and easy-to-operate cameras made almost everyone a potential
recorder of the news. The video camera did it again, and the
Internet is democratizing the means of distribution. Tiny cameras
are currently threatening to be everywhere, in computers and Palm
Pilots and cell phones. The next time a man bites a dog, someone
will probably record it.
</P>
<P>
   That's the good news. It might be hard to find more. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-11-00 2131EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
