<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Yahoo's Quarterly Profit Beats Analysts' Estimates
</P>
<P>
   Yahoo posted better-than-expected quarterly earnings, quelling
investor concerns that consolidation and business failures among
struggling dot-coms might hurt its revenue base. Yahoo reported net
income of $65.5 million, or 11 cents a share, exceeding analysts'
projections of 10 cents a share. Revenue was $270.1 million, up
from $128.6 million in the period a year earlier, and beat
analysts' forecasts of $240 million. Shares of Yahoo fell $4.50, to
$105.50, before the results were announced, but they rebounded as
high as $121 in after-hours trading.
</P>
<P>
   China Looks to Pick Up Reform Pace
</P>
<P>
   Though China has been marching on the road toward economic
change for more than two decades, barriers to capital formation
keep most private businesses from providing more than a handful of
jobs. There is growing pressure to change that. With World Trade
Organization membership expected to open the domestic market wider
to foreign companies, foreigners could take over a huge part of the
economy unless China unleashes private entrepreneurs soon.
</P>
<P>
   A majority of Senate Republicans urged their leader, Trent Lott,
to delay until September a vote on a major bill establishing
permanent normal trade relations with China.
</P>
<P>
   Lessons on Capability and Integrity
</P>
<P>
   Ronald Dollens, chief executive of Guidant, says he learned
life's lessons from his father during drives to and from work at
the family grocery store: ``He taught me about integrity and
respecting people no matter what their stature. He had a
wallhanging in the kitchen: `Don't try to teach a pig to sing. It
wastes your time and annoys the pig.' I have that saying framed in
my office. It reminds me that you have to start with a certain
amount of capability or you're pretty limited in what you can do.''
</P>
<P>
   Dow Rises Again, but Nasdaq Falls
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average rose for a third consecutive
session, gaining 80.61 points, or 0.8 percent, to 10,727.19. The
Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index rose 5.26 points, or 0.4 percent,
to 1,480.88, but technology stocks slumped, and the Nasdaq
composite index fell 23.87 points, or 0.6 percent, to 3,956.42.
</P>
<P>
   Virgin Atlantic Ushers In Cell Calls
</P>
<P>
   Virgin Atlantic Airways has introduced a system that routes
incoming cellular calls to handsets at passengers' seats. Incoming
calls ring quietly on passenger earphones or are announced as a
text message on in-seat video screens.
</P>
<P>
   Most United States airlines said that they would reduce some
fares by about 25 percent into December, trying to maintain the
strong traffic levels seen recently.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyer in Coke Case Is Restricted
</P>
<P>
   A federal judge ordered a Florida lawyer who is representing
four black former Coca-Cola employees in a racial-discrimination
lawsuit not to interfere with the settlement reached last month
between Coke and four other employees with similar claims.
</P>
<P>
   Profit Triples at International Paper
</P>
<P>
   International Paper, the maker of paper and forest products,
said that its second-quarter profit more than tripled as a result
of higher prices and cost-cutting. The results beat Wall Street
expectations by a penny. Shares of International Paper rose $3, to
$35.25. International Paper had dropped 43 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
   Harper to Acquire British Publisher
</P>
<P>
   HarperCollins Publishers agreed to acquire Fourth Estate, a
small and highly regarded British publishing house based in London
whose authors include the popular historian Dava Sobel and the
novelist Annie Proulx. Terms were not disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   Bank Strike Ends in South Korea
</P>
<P>
   The South Korean government and labor leaders agreed to end a
strike by bank workers who walked off their jobs to protest mergers
that could lead to thousands of layoffs.
</P>
</TEXT>
