<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-11 21:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9441 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRO     07-11 0575
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 
 PERSONALS: Staying on Top of the Trends 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Eds: This story also moved in the ``l'' lifestyle news
file.) &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By LEAH GARCHIK &QC;  &LR; 
 &UR; c.2000, San Francisco Chronicle &LR;  &QC; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
A poll in the latest Ladies' Home Journal found that if voters were
ever to elect a female president,  &UR; Elizabeth Dole &LR;  and &UR; Hillary
Clinton &LR;  would be tied for 31 percent of the vote. Next most
popular candidate would be  &UR; Judge Judy &LR; , with 21 percent.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; AMERICA'S SWEETHEARTS SPEAK OUT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Darva Conger &LR; , the bride of a would-be millionaire who appears
in this month's Playboy, explained to the Chicago Sun-Times that
she posed because ``Playboy offers a safe haven, a comfortable,
credible way of making some money.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Conger's ex-husband,  &UR; Rick Rockwell &LR; , rather
ungallantly told DailyRadar.com that he didn't care for the photos.
``My view of a person's beauty changes positively or negatively,
depending upon their behavior and personality. Right now, I think
the Elephant Man is more appealing. If I had known Darva wanted to
take naked pictures so badly, I would have taken a Polaroid on our
honeymoon.''
</P>
<P>
   P.S. The former Mrs. Rockwell is auctioning the wedding ring and
car she won on the show on BuyBidWin.com, with proceeds going to
Easter Seals and the United Cerebral Palsy Fund.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; DOWN ON ``THE PATRIOT'' &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Spike Lee &LR;  writes to the Hollywood Reporter to complain that
``The Patriot,'' the new  &UR; Mel Gibson  &LR; movie, is a ``whitewash of
history.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I kept wondering, where are the slaves?'' he wrote. ``Who's
picking the cotton? `The Patriot' dodged around, skirted about or
completely ignored slavery. The film is pure, blatant American
Hollywood propaganda.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; George &LR;  and  &UR; Barbara Bush &LR;  were on a yacht that ran aground
on July 4, reports the Boston Herald, and had to be rescued by
Kennebunkport (Maine) firefighters and the Coast Guard.
</P>
<P>
   _ Industry gossip has it that &UR; Philip Roth &LR; 's newest novel, ``The
Human Stain,'' has been optioned by Lakeshore Entertainment, which
wants  &UR; Will Smith  &LR; to play the lead, a light-skinned black who
passes for white.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Robert Downey Jr. &LR; , serving a three-year prison sentence for
drug possession, has been sending his friends art and writings.
``It's like anagrams and all this weird other s_,'' friend  &UR; Josh
Richman  &LR; told Vanity Fair. ``I mean, it's so prison!''
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Geoffrey O'Brien &LR;  reveals, in a New York Review of Books
essay about  &UR; Marx  &LR; Brothers books, that  &UR; Julius &LR;  (who later became
 &UR; Groucho &LR; ) performed when he was 16 in a 1906 benefit for victims of
the San Francisco earthquake. Also on the bill were the
singers &UR; Lillian Russell &LR;  and  &UR; Yvette Guilbert &LR;  (the
long-black-gloved model for  &UR; Toulouse-Lautrec &LR; ).
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no longer a distance between foreground and
background. On the contrary, what we consider our work _ that is,
the objects we produce, whether they are books, cinema, systems,
objects, spaces or language _ is, in fact, embedded in the
thickness between the foreground and background. The objects, in
effect, are formed of the world beyond them. And that world has
produced a new and volatile set of forces, conditions and
practices.''
</P>
<P>
   _  &LR; Think-tank-meister  &LR; Bruce Mau &LR; , who apparently thinks
there's &LR;   &LR; something new under the sun and it's pretty darned
impressive, &LR;   &LR; as quoted in Metropolis magazine.  &LR;
</P>
