<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-11 21:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9445 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-BUDGET-TEXAS-COX     07-11 0865
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUDGET-TEXAS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Era of state budget surpluses may be over in Texas
 &HT;    By Gary Susswein
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas - The era of state surpluses may be giving way to
a new era of budgetary belt-tightening in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   State leaders plan to use higher-than-expected tax revenues from
this year to cover about $610 million in cost overruns in the
current 2000-2001 budget. Once they've done that, they don't expect
to have much extra cash left to roll into the 2002-2003 budget,
which begins Sept. 1, 2001. That two-year budget will be crafted
when lawmakers reconvene in January.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be ample revenue in the state to meet the current
obligations,'' Lt. Gov. Rick Perry said Tuesday. ``Over and above
those obligations, I don't expect much of a budget surplus. We are
going to be fiscally conservative.''
</P>
<P>
   Perry and others said the state can afford to pay for existing
school, social service and criminal justice programs even as Texas'
population grows. But it won't be able to expand those programs, as
it did when it approved teachers' pay raises and increased
eligibility for children's health insurance last year.
</P>
<P>
   Unanticipated revenue in the 2000-2001 budget has been estimated
at $1 billion, though exact figures won't be available until
December. In addition to that money, about another $150 million is
expected to be left over by other agencies. After paying off the
overruns, the state would have about $540 million to roll over to
the next budget cycle _ less than 10 percent of what it rolled from
the 1998-1999 budget into the current budget.
</P>
<P>
   The budget overruns are being caused by higher-than-expected
costs in existing state programs. Those rising costs and dwindling
surpluses could have repercussions in the presidential race between
Gov. George W. Bush and Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Critics on Tuesday blamed the new fiscal trend on $1.7 billion
in tax cuts that Bush helped push through the Legislature last
year. They also faulted the Legislature's unwillingness to pump
money into the state's $70 million rainy-day fund.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was clear when we had a so-called surplus that the
governor's top priority for it was tax cuts. This now shows what
the weaknesses of that was,'' said Dick Lavine of the Center for
Public Policy Priorities. The nonprofit group generally opposes tax
cuts because it says there are unmet needs in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to anticipate (that there will be) unanticipated
expenses. We had established, during the dark days of the late
1980s, a rainy-day fund which has now been drained to almost
nothing,'' Lavine said.
</P>
<P>
   State officials dismissed those criticisms and downplayed the
$610 million in unanticipated expenses in health care and criminal
justice. Since the state also is receiving more tax dollars than
expected this year, lawmakers said they will be able to cover costs
when they meet again in January.
</P>
<P>
   ``We may not have done as good a job at estimating costs, but
it's more than made up for by increased revenue so there is no
budget crisis,'' said Senate Finance Committee Chairman Bill
Ratliff, R-Mount Pleasant.
</P>
<P>
   Ratliff and others blamed the overruns _ the highest in recent
sessions _ on flawed projections of prescription drug costs for
Medicaid recipients and on the state's prison population.
</P>
<P>
   The overruns in the current $98.2 billion budget include $440
million in unexpected health care costs _ most of that from the
higher-than-expected prescription drug costs and some from
inaccurate projections at the Texas Council on Alcohol and Drug
Abuse. They also include $170 million in unanticipated criminal
justice expenses, including the prison costs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The number of people being paroled out of prison is fewer than
we thought would occur,'' said House Appropriations Chairman Rob
Junell, D-San Angelo. ``There's no way when you're in a two-year
budget cycle that you can predict (accurately) unless you
over-appropriate, which I don't want to do.''
</P>
<P>
   The inaccurate projections coincide with the first slowdown in
the state surplus in more than a decade. Texas still is collecting
more revenues this year than officials had projected, but those
anticipated revenues will likely be smaller than they were during
the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   The apparent slowdown stems from several factors, including the
recent tax cuts and a slight cooling of the state's economy, which
was growing about 7 percent a year in the late 1990s and is now
growing between 4 percent and 5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going at a moderate growth rate while we had been going
at a blistering growth rate for awhile,'' Comptroller Carole Keeton
Rylander said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush spokeswoman Linda Edwards said she believes the state still
will see some surplus at the end of the budget cycle. And she said
the criticisms of Bush's tax cuts rang hollow.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly a bipartisan majority of both the House and Senate
agreed with Governor Bush that in times of plenty we should meet
state needs and fund priorities such as education and return the
leftover surplus to the taxpayers who earned it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
