<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-11 21:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9446 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-TAPE-COX     07-11 0697
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAPE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Viewing of Grunow shooting video set for Friday
 &HT;    By Susan Spencer-Wendel
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ In a 300-seat room usually used for
assembling jurors, the public can see and judge for themselves the
shooting that rocked a community.
</P>
<P>
   A public viewing of the Lake Worth Middle School surveillance
tape of Nathaniel Brazill firing at Barry Grunow is being set for 3
p.m. Friday at the Palm Beach County Courthouse. The tape, said to
be about 30 seconds long with unclear and distant images, will be
played repeatedly while people are there.
</P>
<P>
   The rare public assembly to view the evidence is a compromise
solution Circuit Judge Richard Wennet ordered last week. Wennet
ruled the tape is a public record and should be released, as all
evidence normally is in a criminal case.
</P>
<P>
   But Wennet forbid any photography or reproduction of it,
preventing the images from appearing in newspapers and on
television which Brazill's attorneys argue would hurt his client's
right to a fair trail.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's showing in the assembly room on the first floor of the
courthouse in West Palm Beach is the court's way of making the tape
public.
</P>
<P>
   People who attend will be asked to sign a form acknowledging the
no-photo policy. Members of the press must also sign before
attending a separate viewing scheduled for 2 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Chief Judge Walter Colbath Jr. said he'd be surprised if more
than 100 people showed up. ``I could be unpleasantly surprised,
too,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   So he and courthouse administrators are preparing for more.
Roughly 20 bailiffs or sheriff's deputies will be on hand, Colbath
said. ``They will be there as a subliminal reminder not to take
photographs.''
</P>
<P>
   Anyone caught taking a photograph will be detained and possibly
held in contempt of court, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Those who have seen the surveillance tape say it's no more than
30 seconds long, grainy and of poor quality, shot from far down the
Lake Worth Middle School hallway.
</P>
<P>
   Right after the May 26 shooting, Robert Hatcher, now the
school's principal, and police reviewed the tape to make sure the
image had been recorded. Hatcher said Tuesday he cannot see one
positive aspect of showing what he saw to the public.
</P>
<P>
   None of the school's staff members have ever asked to see it and
he doubts anyone ever will, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Brazill's defense attorneys had not seen the tape when they
moved to block its release, saying it would violate their
13-year-old client's right to a fair trial. The images would be
played over and over and potential jurors would be prejudiced,
Robert Udell said.
</P>
<P>
   The Palm Beach Post and Fort Lauderdale Sun-Sentinel pressed to
have the tape released, arguing it was a critical piece of evidence
and the media and public have a right to see it.
</P>
<P>
   Udell had not seen footage when he made that argument. Since
then, he has seen it and said Brazill's actions on the tape support
the argument that the shooting of Grunow was a tragic accident.
</P>
<P>
   In an already-released videotaped statement Brazill gave to
police right after the shooting, he says the gun went off
accidentally and that he didn't mean to shoot Grunow, a teacher he
considered a good friend.
</P>
<P>
   Brazill is charged as an adult with first-degree murder and he
faces life in prison if convicted. He's also charged with attempted
first-degree murder for pointing the pistol at another teacher
after shooting Grunow. That action, observers say, can also be seen
on the videotape.
</P>
<P>
   The Grunow family has said through their attorney, Bob
Montgomery, that they support whatever the criminal process calls
for, even release of the tape, as painful as it may be.
</P>
<P>
   Montgomery, who would likely represent the family in any civil
lawsuit stemming from the shooting, said Tuesday that he has asked
for a copy of the tape for future reference.
</P>
<P>
   The family could view that, if they chose to, he said, adding
that some of Grunow's siblings may want to see what happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly not Pam though,'' Montgomery said of Grunow's widow.
</P>
<P>
   susanspencerwendel(at)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
