<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-11 22:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9452 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-CHINA-U.S.-NYT &LR;      07-11 0789
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-U.S.-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOP TRIES TO DELAY VOTE IN THE SENATE ON CHINA BILL 
</HEADLINE>
   By ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A majority of Senate Republicans Tuesday urged
their leader, Trent Lott, to delay until September a vote on a
major bill establishing permanent normal trade relations with
China, an approach that Democrats and business leaders said could
imperil the measure.
</P>
<P>
   Lott said he had made no decision, and renewed his promise to
try to cut through several procedural and political hurdles and
bring up the measure by the end of this month, before Congress
adjourns for its five-week summer recess.
</P>
<P>
   But in his strongest signal yet that imminent passage of the
China trade bill was in jeopardy, Lott told reporters that waiting
until September ``is not as big a problem as some people fear.''
</P>
<P>
   Business leaders and President Clinton have pressed the Senate
to follow the House's lead, and quickly pass a bill that would end
Congress' annual review of China's trade status, before it gets
caught up in election-year politics. In a telephone conversation
Tuesday, Clinton again asked Lott to schedule a vote by month's
end.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the bill have at least 70 votes, more than enough
to defeat a filibuster. Even so, the final vote has been delayed
since the House passed the measure in May because Lott has given a
higher priority to passing several spending bills. Also
complicating speedy passage is the prospect of several amendments
that could force the measure back to the House for a second vote.
</P>
<P>
   But Democrats accused Republicans of postponing action on the
trade bill to extract concessions on spending bills and to allow an
issue that divides Democrats to fester on through the party's
nominating convention in August.
</P>
<P>
   ``Delay is danger,'' said Sen. Max Baucus, a Montana Democrat.
``This is putting politics above policy.''
</P>
<P>
   But at their private weekly luncheon Tuesday, several Senate
Republicans recommended that Lott use the remaining two and a half
weeks before the recess to focus on top-priority tax and spending
bills, and set a date in September for the China trade bill vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it makes a difference if we wait until
September,'' said Sen. Rod Grams, a Minnesota Republican who three
weeks ago had urged Lott to hold a vote by July 4. ``We need to
vote on it, but I know we have other priorities.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike supporters in the House, who fought for votes until the
final minutes, backers of the bill in the Senate have always had
the votes to lock up a large victory. But supporters want to
approve a clean version of the House bill, free from amendments
that would force the measure back to the House for a potentially
volatile second vote.
</P>
<P>
   Several senators, including Jesse Helms of North Carolina and
Phil Gramm of Texas, both Republicans, as well as Paul Wellstone, a
Minnesota Democrat, have signaled their intention to offer
amendments on China's record on human rights, religious liberties
and labor conditions.
</P>
<P>
   But the biggest hurdle has been a measure sponsored by Sens.
Fred Thompson, a Tennessee Republican, and Robert G. Torricelli, a
New Jersey Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   Their measure would require the administration to monitor
China's record on the spread of nuclear weapons. It would impose
automatic sanctions on China if there is ``credible evidence'' of
exports of certain types of prohibited weaponry.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton would have discretion to waive some penalties, but
others would be automatic. Nonetheless, the administration and
business leaders have opposed the measure as unnecessary, and
harmful to United States diplomacy and American companies that
trade with China.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the Senate is on record with this harsh rhetoric and these
extraordinarily harmful sanctions, I think it could seriously
poison the well'' with China, said Sen. Tom Daschle of South
Dakota, the Democratic leader.
</P>
<P>
   Daschle said he might be able to support the anti-proliferation
measure if significant changes were made, including removing the
bill's focus on China.
</P>
<P>
   In response, Thompson said Tuesday he has dropped sanctions
affecting food and medicine. Republican aides said they were also
modifying other provisions, including the steps that triggered
sanctions, to appease critics.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson has insisted that the Senate vote on his measure before
taking up the China trade bill. He has threatened to offer it as an
amendment if that does not happen.
</P>
<P>
   In the Senate, process is important, and Lott said he was trying
to work out all the competing parties and proposals. ``The Senate
is going to pass China P.N.T.R.,'' Lott said. ``It's not a question
of `if.' It's a question of when and in what condition.''
</P>
</TEXT>
