<HEADER>
A9456 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-TOBACCO-COX     07-11 0825
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOBACCO-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Phillip Morris proposes $75 million to compensate Florida
smokers
 &HT;    By George Bennett
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Instead of the record-shattering $154 billion punitive
damages penalty proposed by an attorney for sick Florida smokers,
tobacco giant Philip Morris floated a figure about one-thousandth
as large Tuesday in an historic class-action trial.
</P>
<P>
   As closing arguments continued in the two-year-old trial,
tobacco lawyers called the penalty proposed Monday by smokers'
attorney Stanley Rosenblatt a ``death warrant'' that violates
Florida law.
</P>
<P>
   Philip Morris attorney Dan Webb told jurors that his company,
which owns Marlboro and controls about half the U.S. cigarette
market, should not pay any punitive damages because it has changed
its ways.
</P>
<P>
   But in a nod to jurors who have already ruled twice against the
tobacco industry, Webb suggested several hours into his closing
argument that, if there were to be a punitive damages award, a
``fair amount'' for his client would be $75 million.
</P>
<P>
   Rosenblatt, who represents an estimated 300,000 to 700,000
Floridians with smoking-related illnesses, had suggested a penalty
at least 1,000 times larger for Philip Morris.
</P>
<P>
   Rosenblatt said Philip Morris should pay between $75 billion and
$118 billion and the entire industry should pay between $123
billion and $196.8 billion as punishment for decades of misleading
the public about the hazards of smoking.
</P>
<P>
   Rosenblatt said an ``appropriate, just'' penalty for the
industry would be $154 billion _ which is about 30 times more than
the biggest jury award ever in a U.S. product-liability case.
</P>
<P>
   Tobacco attorneys fought back Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``His demand for $154 billion or more _ it's not ridiculous.
It's so far beyond what the law and evidence allows that it makes a
mockery of this case,'' Webb told jurors.
</P>
<P>
   ``It does nothing more than invite you to become a runaway,
out-of-control jury,'' Webb said.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for four other tobacco companies are expected to make
closing arguments today and Thursday in the nation's first smokers'
class-action suit to come before a jury.
</P>
<P>
   Before jurors were seated Tuesday, R.J. Reynolds lawyer Ben Reid
asked Judge Robert Kaye to tell the jury that Rosenblatt's punitive
damage request was illegal because Florida law forbids a verdict
that would bankrupt a company.
</P>
<P>
   The tobacco companies say they have a combined value of about
$15 billion, or one-tenth the amount Rosenblatt requested.
</P>
<P>
   Kaye turned down Reid's request, but said attorneys could raise
the issue in their closing arguments.
</P>
<P>
   Webb did just that.
</P>
<P>
   ``That amount is a death warrant because that amount will
destroy each of these companies not once but 10 times over,'' Webb
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you award $6 billion, you've got Philip Morris. It's gone.
It's history. It's out of here,'' Webb said. The company lists its
net worth as $6.4 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Webb said Philip Morris should not pay any punitive damages
because it has discontinued the practices that jurors found
objectionable in earlier phases of the trial.
</P>
<P>
   The jurors who will decide on punitive damages have already
found the tobacco companies guilty of misleading the public about
the addictiveness and deadliness of cigarette smoking. The jury
also awarded $12.7 million to three smokers with cancer who were
deemed to be representatives of the entire class of Floridians with
smoking-related illnesses.
</P>
<P>
   After spending hours arguing against any award, Webb conceded
late Tuesday that jurors might disagree.
</P>
<P>
   If so, he said, they should base any penalty on Philip Morris'
current assets and liabilities, which yield a balance of about $1.5
billion in cash on hand. Figuring that Florida has about 5 percent
of the nation's smokers, Webb arrived at the $75 million figure
using a felt-tip marker on a tablet of paper on an easel.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would be a fair amount, if that's what you decide, that
you disagree with Mr. Webb and all my arguments,'' the attorney
said. Philip Morris and other tobacco companies agreed in 1998 to
pay about $250 billion during the next 25 years to the 50 states as
part of a settlement in which the states agreed not to sue the
companies. The agreement also calls for the cigarette makers to
eliminate outdoor advertising, contribute to youth smoking
prevention programs and make other changes.
</P>
<P>
   ``This agreement has had a profound effect on Philip Morris and
how it does business,'' said Webb, who said the company is
effectively on ``permanent probation'' under the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``The conduct has changed and therefore the purpose of deterring
our conduct ... has been accomplished,'' Webb said. ``If the Philip
Morris of today has stopped engaging in the misconduct and the men
and women who did it are gone, what is accomplished by punishing
the Philip Morris of today?''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
