<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ESTATE-TAX-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATORS WORKING UP TO VOTE   ON REPEAL OF THE ESTATE TAX 
</HEADLINE>
   By RICHARD W. STEVENSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Senate took a first step Tuesday toward a vote
on a Republican proposal to repeal the federal estate tax, and
Democrats scrambled to avoid defections that could allow passage of
the bill later this week.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation, which passed the House last month with support
from some Democrats, would gradually eliminate the federal tax on
large estates. Republicans said the tax robs many people at death
of much of any wealth they have accumulated for their heirs, and
hits family-owned farms and small businesses particularly hard.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea that the federal government would reach into the
grave and pull back half of a life's work offends people regardless
of race, sex, region, financial situation or anything else,'' said
Sen. Trent Lott of Mississippi, the Republican majority leader.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton has signaled that he would veto the estate tax
bill. But mindful that 9 of 45 Democratic senators have endorsed
repeal of the estate tax, Democratic leaders unveiled an
alternative proposal Tuesday that would eliminate the tax for most
family-owned businesses and farms but leave it in place for a
relatively small number of multimillion-dollar estates.
</P>
<P>
   But it was unclear whether Democrats would be able to block the
Republican bill as it confronts a procedural hurdle. To cut off
debate on the bill and bring it to a final vote, the legislation's
sponsors would have to muster 60 votes, meaning that Republicans
would have to be joined by at least five Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   The nine Democrats who support estate tax repeal sent a letter
to Lott urging him to allow consideration of the Democratic
alternative as well as other Democratic amendments.
</P>
<P>
   So far Lott and his Democratic counterpart, Thomas Daschle of
South Dakota, have been unable to agree on what measures should be
considered, and if there is no agreement that Lott could force a
vote on cutting off debate later this week.
</P>
<P>
   Daschle said he is confident that all 45 Democrats will stick
together to block a final vote on the bill if Republicans do not
allow them to vote on the amendments they want to offer. But Lott
said that if he can find a way to have a final vote, the bill would
win support from as many as 70 senators.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican bill would decrease federal revenues by $104
billion over the first 10 years, and $750 billion in its second
decade. Democrats said their alternative would reduce revenues by
$64 billion over the first 10 years and $300 billion over the
second decade.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats said that by insisting on full repeal of the tax,
Republicans were intent on handing over a huge chunk of projected
federal budget surpluses to the rich while doing nothing to address
issues of concern to working people who do not have the luxury of
worrying about multimillion-dollar estates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do we want to provide meaningful estate tax reform?'' Daschle
said. ``Of course. But do we really want to give those
multibillionaires the opportunity to pass on estates absolutely tax
free?
</P>
<P>
   Under current law, estates valued at up to $675,000 are exempt
from federal taxation, and the exemption is scheduled to rise to $1
million in 2006. Family-owned businesses and farms are exempt up to
$1.3 million. Above those levels, estates are subject to a
graduated tax with a top rate of 55 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The issue has become politically potent as the 76 million
members of the baby boom generation, their wealth swollen by the
strong economy and stock market, have begun estate planning.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
