<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KELSO-COLUMN12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cultivating an interest in Herbs
 &HT;    By John Kelso
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   We're going to try to set the world record right here in Austin
for packing the most number of guys named Herb into an herb bar.
</P>
<P>
   I'll admit that I don't know what the world record for the most
number of Herbs in an herb joint is, because, frankly, this is such
a silly idea that I doubt it has ever been attempted.
</P>
<P>
   This all began when my boss and I were driving by The Herb Bar
at 200 W. Mary St., where you can find tarot card readings, herbal
tinctures and essential oils, and I'm not talking about Quaker
State. As we drove past, my boss made a comment about how funny it
would be to invite all the guys named Herb to gather at The Herb
Bar at some later date, hold a celebration of Herbs, and take a
group picture of all the Herbs.
</P>
<P>
   If you're a Herb, and you want to be member of the International
Order of Herbs, and you would like to be in the group photo, just
give me a holler at the e-mail address listed at the bottom of this
column, and later we'll get together at The Herb Bar.
</P>
<P>
   I have spoken with Twila Dawn Willis, owner of The Herb Bar,
which doesn't really have a bar but does have herbs, though it has
no Herbs. She thinks this is a great idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know any Herbs, so now I'll get to meet some,'' said
Willis, who doesn't have anyone named Rosemary working for her. She
said the name of her business sometimes throws people off. ``Uh, I
do have people who come in and think it's an actual bar,'' she
said. ``They think they can get a drink here. I just send 'em to
Trophy's.''
</P>
<P>
   I hope to get Herb Kelleher, chief executive of Southwest
Airlines, to show up. In fact, on Monday I called his office in
Dallas to invite him. ``He would need something in writing, but his
calendar is booked for the year,'' said Vickie Shuler, his
executive assistant.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe I should mail Herb Kelleher a bottle of Wild Turkey. I
hear he likes that.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, you can get a drink at The Herb Bar. On Monday morning
when I visited, they had a jug of Dandy Blend instant dandelion
beverage set up on a bar in the back room. I don't think that's
going to interest Herb Kelleher much, though. I don't blame him. My
idea of a good time isn't drinking weeds.
</P>
<P>
   You know, there sure is a shortage of Herbs these days. ``It's
not in fashion anymore,'' Willis said, speaking of Herb, not herb.
``Things come and go. I had an aunt named Mabel, and you don't hear
of anyone named Mabel.'' I bet there's a Mabel at the Buda truck
stop.
</P>
<P>
   Seriously, it really is hard to name many famous Herbs. Other
than Kelleher, you've got '50s Hoosier humorist Herb Shriner,
trumpeter Herb Alpert, pro football Hall of Famer Herb Adderley and
late newspaper columnist Herb Caen.
</P>
<P>
   President Herbert Hoover could have been a Herb, but they called
him Herbert. If it had been him instead of George Bush who had
blown beets on that guy in Japan, they would have called him
Herbert Heaver, but that's another matter altogether.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, if you're a Herb and you want to become a member of
the International Order of Herbs, give me a shout. And if Rosemary
wants to join us, she's welcome if she's got the thyme.
</P>
<P>
   You can e-mail John Kelso at jkelso(at)statesman.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
