<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VOTERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ENDORSEMENTS AND DEBATES WERE SIGNIFICANT, POLLING PROJECT FINDS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Pa., N.H., Iowa)   By ADAM CLYMER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Endorsements and debates played critical roles in
this year's contests for presidential nominations, according to
findings of a huge polling project conducted by the Annenberg
Public Policy Center of the University of Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   Nightly tracking polls of voters in Iowa and New Hampshire, for
example, showed that Vice President Al Gore's Jan. 5 debate attack
on Bill Bradley over health care and his Jan. 8 blast over a
Bradley vote on flood relief had a distinct effect on Democratic
voters, and halted the former New Jersey senator's momentum.
</P>
<P>
   ``In two debates, Bradley effectively lost the nomination,''
said Kathleen Hall Jamieson, director of the Annenberg center.
</P>
<P>
   Endorsements cut both ways, Jamieson said. For example, the
endorsement of Gov. George W. Bush by the National Right to Life
Committee won him votes from abortion opponents in his race against
Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., but cost him votes among Republican
supporters of abortion rights. That endorsement, she said, ``may
have misled people into thinking McCain was more pro-choice than he
actually was.''
</P>
<P>
   Jamieson described the value of endorsements as a shortcut for
voters ``seeking information about candidate stands.''
</P>
<P>
   The key to deriving impact from endorsements, she said, was
usually to advertise them. In Iowa, for example, only 19 percent of
Democrats were aware of the endorsement of Bradley by Sen. Paul
Wellstone of neighboring Minnesota, who campaigned frequently with
him. But 75 percent knew that one of their senators, Tom Harkin,
had endorsed Gore. The Harkin support was shown often in Gore
advertisements on radio and television. The Wellstone endorsement
was not shown at all. Instead, Bradley's campaign used an
advertisement showing that he was being backed by Sen. Daniel
Patrick Moynihan, D-N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Another important finding was that knowing the source of a
political advertisement can be critical to its effectiveness.
Jamieson found that a Bush radio advertisement accusing McCain of
opposing spending for cancer research was widely known across the
country and had a big impact on female voters, although it was
broadcast only in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Those who knew that the Bush campaign had sponsored the
advertisement were 11 percentage points less likely to believe it
than those who did not, Jamieson said. If it had been sponsored by
a group calling itself Citizens for Breast Cancer Research, for
instance, it might have been even more effective, she said.
</P>
<P>
   These findings are among the first from a polling effort that
began last December and will end only next January, after more than
100,000 interviews on Americans' political opinions, knowledge and
use of media.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
