<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Age notions getting old
 &HT;    By Rowland Nethaway
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   At the same time that Congress is arguing over providing health
care for elderly Americans, old folks are complaining that they are
not old.
</P>
<P>
   A peppery friend of my mother gets upset when the ``press,''
which is me, refers to someone her age as elderly, old or senior.
</P>
<P>
   I wouldn't dare ask, but the woman must be in her 70s, maybe her
80s. She is healthy and sharp, and evidently feels like she is in
her 20s.
</P>
<P>
   I can't pin her down on her definition of elderly, old or
senior. It's a moving target. That enables her to avoid being
called old.
</P>
<P>
   If, as the saying goes, we are as old as we feel, she may have a
point.
</P>
<P>
   People definitely are living longer. If they take care of
themselves, people in their 60s today can be as vigorous as people
in their 40s were a century ago, perhaps only a few generations
ago.
</P>
<P>
   A British study estimates that the retirement age will rise to
80 in the next 25 years as life expectancy continues to increase.
</P>
<P>
   More than 30 million Americans are members of AARP, a nonprofit
association ``dedicated to shaping and enriching the experience of
aging for our members and for all Americans.''
</P>
<P>
   This group, which was founded in 1958, accepts members at the
age of 50. Is 50 old? If so, we will elect an old president in
November. Both Al Gore and George W. Bush are over 50.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the commentary that accompanied the announcement of the
mapping of the human genome included musings about how this
information will be used to extend life.
</P>
<P>
   Medical researchers have claimed that it is reasonable to assume
that normal life expectancy can be doubled when scientists learn to
take advantage of a person's genetic code.
</P>
<P>
   If that's true, my mother's friend, fast-forwarded into the
genetic future, could be 160 and still complaining about the
``press'' referring to someone her age as old.
</P>
<P>
   If people continue to live longer, stay healthy and retire
later, why should they automatically qualify for government
benefits when they hit 62 for Social Security or 65 for Medicare?
</P>
<P>
   Heck, at 65 people in the near future would be somewhere between
young adults and middle aged, according to some of the experts
quoted when the human genome announcement was made.
</P>
<P>
   It would make no sense to pay Social Security to people who are
still capable of playing major league baseball.
</P>
<P>
   If Nolan Ryan could throw heat in the majors at 46, then his
great-grandson might be able to do the same at 92. At that point,
it certainly wouldn't be right for people to be drawing Social
Security or Medicare, much less all those senior citizen discounts.
</P>
<P>
   Today there are people who are spry and vigorous at 80 while
other people at 60 are feeble and barely hanging on.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps chronological age should be dropped as the measurement
to determine how old a person is. Some sort of new measurement
needs to be developed that can gauge a person's mental and physical
abilities. A calendar certainly can't do that.
</P>
<P>
   I'm sure there are octogenarians today who are superior drivers
compared to many motorists in their teens and 20s. When it comes to
issuing driver's licenses, there is no need to single out any
group, young or old.
</P>
<P>
   Test them all with the same test. Weed them out based on the
ability _ or inability _ to drive.
</P>
<P>
   Testing people to determine their eligibility to draw benefits
designed to help elderly Americans cope with old age will be more
difficult.
</P>
<P>
   But if the retirement age rises to 80 in the next 25 years, the
country will need a new definition of old.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
