<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DRAINING-HOLLYWOOD-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARYLAND OPENS FILM OFFICE, BUT TELLS HOLLYWOOD IT'S NOT POACHING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JESSE HIESTAND 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ By opening a film office in Los Angeles this
month, Maryland has joined a growing list of states and countries
setting up shop in Hollywood's back yard to woo away production
business.
</P>
<P>
   The move by the Maryland Film Office comes in the wake of a
recent report that ``runaway production'' is picking up pace, with
the number of major features shot in California dropping 33 percent
in 1999 over the previous year.
</P>
<P>
   But veteran Los Angeles film location manager Ken Haber, who
will promote the Free State from a small office in Benedict Canyon,
said Maryland seeks to complement, not compete with, California by
offering unique locales.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maryland has virtually all of the looks of the East Coast,
from New England down through the South and even the Midwest,''
Haber said. ``None of these are things that would affect films that
need to be shot in L.A.''
</P>
<P>
   And if Chesapeake Bay, some 5,000 miles of coastline and lush
forests are not enough of a draw, the state has waived its 5
percent sales tax for any production-related services or purchases,
said Michael B. Styer, director of the Maryland Film Office, an
agency of the state's Department of Business and Economic
Development.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not trying to take away work from Southern California,''
Styer said. ``A certain number of films, because of the types of
locations they need, don't have a California look.''
</P>
<P>
   For their part, Los Angeles officials see little threat from
Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one can match our looks, the weather, our locations and our
crews,'' said Morrie Goldman, spokesman for the Los Angeles County
Entertainment Industry Development Corp., which grants permits for
television and film productions on Los Angeles city and county
land. ``From a marketing perspective, it makes sense for them to be
here. They're not the first and won't be the last.''
</P>
<P>
   Florida and Virginia already have offices in Los Angeles,
joining England and other countries that either have full-time film
offices here or rely on their tourism promoters.
</P>
<P>
   Canada has lured away a lion's share of the runaway production
through favorable currency exchange rates and by offering rebates
and other financial incentives to producers who work there and hire
its citizens.
</P>
<P>
   That helped contributed to a 10 percent decline in feature films
made in the U.S. last year over 1998 figures, according to a report
last month by the film industry think tank ECO2000.
</P>
<P>
   Feature film and television production in Maryland has grown
steadily in the past few years, reaching record levels in fiscal
year 2000 by adding an estimated $77 million to the state's
economy, according to its film office.
</P>
<P>
   Features shot there either entirely or in part in the past year
include ``The Replacements,'' starring Keanu Reeves and Gene
Hackman, and ``Blair Witch II,'' the sequel to the highly
successful independent horror film set in the Maryland woods.
</P>
<P>
   The state was also used exclusively to shoot the new Warner
Bros. television series ``Young Americans,'' set to debut Wednesday
night.
</P>
<P>
   Maryland officials hope their Los Angeles office, opened July 1,
will give them better access to Hollywood's decision makers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to know about things earlier in the game that we
wouldn't otherwise know over here on the East Coast,'' Styer said.
</P>
<P>
   In his 10-year career, Haber has worked with directors Oliver
Stone, Rob Reiner, Frances Ford Coppola and Clint Eastwood and
served as location manager on such feature films as ``Thelma and
Louise,'' ``The Thin Red Line,'' ``Fatal Attraction'' and ``The
Bridges of Madison County.''
</P>
<P>
   While not alarmed by the outsiders' moves, the California Film
Commission has launched its own counteroffensive through a
state-funded program to reimburse filmmakers for the cost of having
local, state or federal employees monitor filming.
</P>
<P>
   ``California has stepped up its efforts to make the state even
more attractive to filmmakers,'' said Karen Constine, director of
the film commission. ``We have so many locations to choose for
filmmakers that everything they're looking for can be found here.''
</P>
<P>
   x x x
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
