<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; SEE _  &LR; A half-century after George Orwell painted ``Big Brother''
as a threat, a San Francisco startup named cEverything has turned
round-the-clock observation via the Internet into a thriving
business.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike conventional security cameras that rely on videotape that
has to be picked up and rewound to be viewed, cEverything's
Web-based service uses tiny video cameras and the World Wide Web to
let managers of restaurants, bars, convenience stores and other
businesses monitor operations anytime, from anywhere.  &UR; BY &LR; 
 &UR; PETER SINTON &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; GROW (COLUMN) _ &LR;  Kobe, Japan, is turning to two Bay Area dot-coms
to help it rebuild from the devastating earthquake that struck five
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Kobe Mayor Kazutoshi Sasayama has come to San Francisco to
unveil an infrastructure development Web site Wednesday to help
Kobe spread the word about more than $4 billion in construction
opportunities. Projects include a new Kobe Airport slated to open
in 2005, an international multimedia and entertainment city on a
port island and a huge medical industrial development project.
 &UR; COLUMN BY PETER SINTON &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; YAHOO _  &LR; Yahoo Inc. reported higher-than-expected earnings
yesterday amid concerns that the Internet portal industry's growth
is slowing because of declining online advertising.
</P>
<P>
   The Santa Clara, Calif., Web portal company said it earned $65.5
million (12 cents per share) in the second quarter, compared with
$27 million (5 cents) in the year-ago period. The firm's revenue
more than doubled from the same period last year, rising to $270.1
million from $128.5 million.  &UR; BY VERNE KOPYTOFF &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; ALLADVANTAGE _  &LR; Just months ago, paying people to surf the Web
seemed like such a groundbreaking business model that Hayward,
Calif., startup AllAdvantage.com snared $100 million in investment
on top of $34 million from last year, and dozens of copycats popped
up in its wake.  &UR; BY CARRIE KIRBY &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; NETWORTH (COLUMN) _  &LR; These days, you don't have to be a big fiber
optics company like JDS Uniphase or Corning to be a hit on Wall
Street. All you need is a few grams of fiber in your corporate
diet, and investors will devour your stock. A growing list of
little-known companies are seeing their shares rise to astronomical
_ some would say unsustainable _ heights after they announce, or
even hint, that they have a fiber optics product, division or
customer.  &UR; COLUMN BY KATHLEEN PENDER &LR;
