<SLUG> BC-YAHOO-EARNINGS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YAHOO REPORTS STRONG EARNINGS DESPITE FEARS OF
ADVERTISING  SLOWDOWN
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By VERNE KOPYTOFF 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Yahoo Inc. reported higher-than-expected
earnings yesterday amid concerns that the Internet portal
industry's growth is slowing because of declining online
advertising.
</P>
<P>
   The Santa Clara, Calif., Web portal company said it earned $65.5
million (12 cents per share) in the second quarter, compared with
$27 million (5 cents) in the year-ago period. The firm's revenue
more than doubled from the same period last year, rising to $270.1
million from $128.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   Yahoo's earnings, which beat Wall Street's expectations by 2
cents a share, were being watched closely by financial analysts as
a bellwether for other Web portals. Over the past month, several
analysts have questioned whether portal companies like Yahoo could
continue rapid growth given that many of their dot-com advertisers
were wounded by the stock market slide this spring.
</P>
<P>
   But Yahoo's earnings seem to have dispelled some of those fears.
The company said that fewer than 10 percent of its advertisers are
in financial trouble and that its advertising sales to more stable
brick-and-mortar companies is strong.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the company's increased revenue was attributed to a
growing number of users and overseas expansion. It also added 800
online merchants during the quarter for a total of 11,300.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yahoo blew away the revenue number, basically addressing
concerns about the dot-com slowdown,'' said Bob Walberg, an analyst
for Briefing.com, an online investor advisory service. ``I think
this is very good news for Yahoo.''
</P>
<P>
   Yahoo, the third-most-popular Web portal, is especially
vulnerable to fluctuating marketing budgets because nearly 80
percent of its revenue comes from advertising. A study by Lehman
Bros., the New York investment bank, found that 63 percent of
Yahoo's top 200 advertisers are dot-coms, many of which have been
suffering in recent months.
</P>
<P>
   But analysts cautioned that Yahoo's strong earnings does not
necessarily mean that all Internet portals are safe. They said that
Yahoo and Amercia Online have such big audiences that most
companies feel compelled to advertise on them.
</P>
<P>
   That is not the case with less-popular Internet portals like
Lycos, AltaVista and Goto.com, analysts said. For example, NBC
Internet, the San Francisco online arm of General Electric, said in
June that its earnings would be lower than expected for the rest of
the year, partly because of a slowdown in advertising.
</P>
<P>
   ``The second- and third-tier portals run the risk of being
squeezed,'' said Michele Slack, an analyst for Jupiter
Communications, the market research company.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the problem is that many dot-com advertisers have gone
out of business or laid off large portions of their staffs in
recent months. Among them are Toysmart.com, the online retailer,
and Reel.com, the movie video retailer.
</P>
<P>
   Others have seen their stocks plunge, delayed initial public
offerings and tried to reduce expenses. For example, Drkoop.com,
the troubled medical Web site, renegotiated its multimillion-dollar
partnership with America Online.
</P>
<P>
   In reaction to the online advertising slump, many portals are
trying to diversify. Some are trying to recruit more traditional
advertisers like Coca-Cola and Procter &AMP; Gamble, though most
analysts doubt that this can offset all the losses.
</P>
<P>
   Yahoo is making additional efforts. Last month, it began selling
a customized version of its Internet portal to corporate clients.
It also recently bought Egroups, the online community e-mail site
in San Francisco, which allows for more economical advertising
because people can be targeted based on their interests.
</P>
<P>
   Fears about slower growth have pushed Yahoo's stock down
significantly in recent weeks. The stock, which rose as high as
$250 in January, ended the day yesterday at $105.50. In after-hours
trading, the company's shares surged as high as $121.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Verne Kopytoff at  &LR; verne(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
