<DOCNO> NYT20000711.0395 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-11 22:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9480 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-ALLADVANTAGE-PAYSITE-     07-11 1208
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALLADVANTAGE-PAYSITE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 PAY-TO-SURF NOT PAYING OFF FOR WEB SITES  &HT;     By CARRIE KIRBY 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Just months ago, paying people to surf the Web
seemed like such a groundbreaking business model that Hayward,
Calif., startup AllAdvantage.com snared $100 million in investment
on top of $34 million from last year, and dozens of copycats popped
up in its wake.
</P>
<P>
   But what looked groundbreaking then seems foolhardy now.
</P>
<P>
   It's no surprise that AllAdvantage had to withdraw its initial
public offering last week, citing adverse market conditions, said
Omar Sacirbey, senior editor for IPO Reporter. The market is fed up
with companies that are giving away millions of dollars in hopes of
earning money sometime in the future, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't be giving stuff away anymore,'' Sacirbey said.
``Investors just aren't into that anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   AllAdvantage pays its members 53 cents an hour to browse the Web
while viewing advertisements displayed in a floating window called
a viewbar that hogs about 10 percent of the screen space. But the
biggest earners make their money _ as much as thousands of dollars
a month _ through the plan's pyramid scheme aspect: Members earn 10
cents an hour for each new member they refer.
</P>
<P>
   AllAdvantage plans to turn a profit by collecting demographic
data about the company's 2.9 million active members, then selling
advertising that's super-targeted to those members' interests.
AllAdvantage learns about its members through surveys and by
tracking _ with permission _ what Web pages they visit.
</P>
<P>
   But so far, the phenomenal advertising revenues AllAdvantage was
banking on have not materialized. AllAdvantage has taken in a mere
$14.4 million from its March 1999 launch to March this year.
Meanwhile, every 45 days, the company sends its members checks _
$49.8 million since its inception. All told, AllAdvantage has lost
$102.7 million. Its financial filings state that it expects to be
unprofitable for the foreseeable future.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is that highly targeted advertising, so promising in
theory, doesn't exist yet in practice.
</P>
<P>
   Fortune magazine recently called AllAdvantage the ``dumbest
dot-com in the world.'' What does that make the company's 40-odd
copycats, smaller startups that hoped to follow its path to riches?
The me-toos include the Bay Area's Spedia, ClickRebates and Jotter.
Then there are variations on the theme: Radiofreecash.com pays
people to listen to Internet-based radio broadcasts, and
AdSavers.com users earn money for downloading advertisements that
play like screensavers. Most of these companies are tiny and have
little outside capital, although there are exceptions: Santa Clara,
Calif.'s ClickRebates and Washington, D.C.'s AdSavers.com each have
$3 million in venture funding.
</P>
<P>
   AllAdvantage first showed signs of stumbling last month, when it
reduced the number of hours that members could surf for pay each
week from 25 to 15, while raising the hourly ``wage'' from 50 to 53
cents.
</P>
<P>
   The company also raised the minimum amount it would cut a check
for and changed its payment schedule from monthly to every 45 days.
Because users money for each new member they sign up, and for the
125,000 members with 20 or more referrals, the changes reduced
monthly checks by hundreds of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   The changes were a way of controlling costs after many more
people than expected signed up, said Alex Gourevitch, an
AllAdvantage spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   ``The entire growth of the program took us aback,'' Gourevitch
said. ``We had 2 million members signed up before we knew it.''
About 15,000 new members sign up each day.
</P>
<P>
   While not all the AllAdvantage wannabes have had the ``problem''
of becoming too popular, too soon, they share AllAdvantage's
difficulty in selling targeted ads.
</P>
<P>
   Some AllAdvantage ads appear when the viewer visits a related
site; for example, Eve.com ads appear when AllAdvantage users visit
the beauty section of iVillage.com. But most of AllAdvantage's ads
are general, not targeted, the company disclosed in financial
documents.
</P>
<P>
   Advertisers aren't ready for highly targeted ads, said
Gourevitch.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no question that there have been issues with
educating the advertisers,'' he acknowledged.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most (ad buyers) are not set up in their marketing departments
to utilize the targeting that is available,'' said Rich LeFurgy,
chair of the Internet Advertising Bureau, an industry group whose
members include America Online, Microsoft and AllAdvantage.
``There's a lot more work required than there is in doing a media
buy on network television or cable.'' LeFurgy is also an
AllAdvantage investor and board member.
</P>
<P>
   To make matters worse, said analyst Michele Slack of New York's
Jupiter Communications, supply currently exceeds demand for ad
placements on the Internet. That puts ad-dependent companies in a
tight spot.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone in the space is going to be desperate for ad
dollars,'' Slack said.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers say Internet advertising has a bright future _ for
those companies that survive long enough to see it. Advertisers are
spending 54 percent more online this year than they were last year,
according to AdZone Interactive, which measured this year's
Internet ad sales at $1.26 billion so far. Forrester Research
expects annual Internet ad spending to hit $33 billion orldwide by
2004.
</P>
<P>
   AllAdvantage employs ``media strategists'' to show advertisers
how targeting could benefit them. The company also plans to
introduce a new strategy it calls ``behavioral targeting.'' The
idea is not just to show users an ad for binoculars when they're
visiting a bird-watching page, but to notice that this user
frequently visits pages related to wildlife and to show that user
wildlife-related ads on a regular basis.
</P>
<P>
   All this surveillance may seem invasive, but pay-to-surf program
members agree to give the information up. AllAdvantage's privacy
policy states that it doesn't provide specific names or e-mail
addresses to its advertisers, just aggregated information about
surfing habits.
</P>
<P>
   Many companies in this space, including AllAdvantage, are
branching out beyond the pay-to-surf model. AllAdvantage recently
started a program that pays members to read e-mail ads. The company
is dabbling in e-commerce, letting users rent antivirus software
using the money in their AllAdvantage accounts.
</P>
<P>
   But without IPO cash, analysts warn that AllAdvantage and its
copycats may not survive to see their plans pan out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm pretty skeptical,'' said Jupiter's Slack. ``If they can't
continue to get funding in the meantime, then they're going to have
problems. I think right now their business model is highly
questionable.''
</P>
<P>
   Another specter haunting pay-to-surf companies is cheating.
Several programs available online let users get paid without
viewing any ads. Some programs simulate surfing activity without
requiring the user to be at the computer; others block out the ads.
AllAdvantage's financial filings acknowledge that these programs
have become effective and difficult to detect and warns that the
use of the software could seriously damage AllAdvantage's business.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Carrie Kirby at  &LR; ckirby(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
