<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-11 22:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9481 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-GROW-SINTON-SFCHRON &LR;      07-11 0753
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GROW-SINTON-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GROW A BUSINESS: MAYOR OF KOBE, JAPAN, KNOWS WHERE TO FIND
WEB  ASSISTANCE
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By PETER SINTON 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Kobe, Japan, is turning to two Bay Area dot-coms
to help it rebuild from the devastating earthquake that struck five
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Kobe Mayor Kazutoshi Sasayama has come to San Francisco to
unveil an infrastructure development Web site Wednesday to help
Kobe spread the word about more than $4 billion in construction
opportunities. Projects include a new Kobe Airport slated to open
in 2005, an international multimedia and entertainment city on a
port island and a huge medical industrial development project.
</P>
<P>
   Sasayama is going against the traditional Japanese approach of
sticking with known and mostly homegrown financiers and
contractors. His enlistment of the two Bay Area companies to
develop the Web site is part of that strategy.
</P>
<P>
   One is Infrastructureworld.com, a South San Francisco, Calif.,
company started by former Bechtel Enterprises Chairman Cordell Hull
with $11 million in private financing to facilitate development of
major construction projects worldwide. The other is B2B Accelerator
by Neptune Technologies, a Santa Clara, Calif., company that
specializes in helping companies build business-to-business
marketplaces.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our mission was to build the first government-to-business site
to attract people to work on or make investments in infrastructure
projects,'' said Tim Burr, B2B Accelerator's senior vice president
of marketing. Hull, a distant relative of the former secretary of
state of the same name, added that the Web site
( &LR; www.infrastructureworld.com/ikobe &LR; ) will allow Kobe to ``reach a
broader audience more quickly and is further evidence of Japan's
move to open up its economy.''
</P>
<P>
   TURNSTONE'S TURN: Everyone talks about how IPOs have been
pounded and that's true for many dot-coms, especially if you look
at how the stocks have fared since their opening trading price
rather than offering price to select investors.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, new issues did surprisingly well in the first half
of 2000, especially when compared with the stock market indexes.
</P>
<P>
   The 50 local companies that went public in the first six months
of this year were up an average of 84 percent, according to IPO
Monitor. By contrast, the Dow Jones industrial average skidded
nearly 9 percent and the Nasdaq composite slipped nearly 3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   By comparison, the 41 Bay Area companies that went public in the
first half of last year gained an average 138 percent. For all of
1999, the 126 local companies that went public soared a stunning
358 percent on average.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the lower trajectories this year, Northern California
new issues continue to outperform the average IPO in the United
States by a 2-to-1 ratio.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the 504 companies that went public across the country
gained an average 191 percent, according to IPO Monitor. In the
first half of 2000, the 212 companies that launched IPOs gained 38
percent on average.
</P>
<P>
   The nation's top IPO so far this year is Turnstone Systems Inc.,
a maker of equipment and software that allow installation of
high-speed online connections from remote locations. The Mountain
View, Calif., company soared from $29 on February to $165.67 on
June 30 for a 471 percent gain.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike many hot IPOs, even investors who bought Turnstone for
$97 at the end of its first day of trading are looking good. And so
far this month, Turnstone is up another 19 percent to $197.50.
</P>
<P>
   Investors' infatuation with high tech is definitely not over.
Eight of the top 12 new public companies in the country in the
first half are high-tech firms based in the Bay Area, according to
IPO Monitor.
</P>
<P>
   They are No. 3 Nuance Communications, up 441 percent; No. 6 ONI
Systems, up 328 percent; No. 7 Quantum Effect Devices, up 283
percent; No. 8 New Focus, up 272 percent; No. 10 Stanford
Microdevices, up 270 percent; No. 11 Numerical Technologies, up 243
percent; and No. 12 Centillium Communications, up 242 percent.
</P>
<P>
   It should be noted that 15 of the 50 local IPOs fell below their
offering prices. The dogs of the bunch are both dot-coms that shed
more than 80 percent of their value: ImproveNet, a Redwood City,
Calif., provider of online home improvement information and
services, fell to $2.50 from $16. Pets.com, a San Francisco online
retailer of pet products, dropped to $2.15 from $11.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Peter Sinton at  &LR; entrepreneurs(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
