   To make matters worse, said analyst Michele Slack of New York's
Jupiter Communications, supply currently exceeds demand for ad
placements on the Internet. That puts ad-dependent companies in a
tight spot.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone in the space is going to be desperate for ad
dollars,'' Slack said.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers say Internet advertising has a bright future _ for
those companies that survive long enough to see it. Advertisers are
spending 54 percent more online this year than they were last year,
according to AdZone Interactive, which measured this year's
Internet ad sales at $1.26 billion so far. Forrester Research
expects annual Internet ad spending to hit $33 billion orldwide by
2004.
</P>
<P>
   AllAdvantage employs ``media strategists'' to show advertisers
how targeting could benefit them. The company also plans to
introduce a new strategy it calls ``behavioral targeting.'' The
idea is not just to show users an ad for binoculars when they're
visiting a bird-watching page, but to notice that this user
frequently visits pages related to wildlife and to show that user
wildlife-related ads on a regular basis.
</P>
<P>
   All this surveillance may seem invasive, but pay-to-surf program
members agree to give the information up. AllAdvantage's privacy
policy states that it doesn't provide specific names or e-mail
addresses to its advertisers, just aggregated information about
surfing habits.
</P>
<P>
   Many companies in this space, including AllAdvantage, are
branching out beyond the pay-to-surf model. AllAdvantage recently
started a program that pays members to read e-mail ads. The company
is dabbling in e-commerce, letting users rent antivirus software
using the money in their AllAdvantage accounts.
</P>
<P>
   But without IPO cash, analysts warn that AllAdvantage and its
copycats may not survive to see their plans pan out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm pretty skeptical,'' said Jupiter's Slack. ``If they can't
continue to get funding in the meantime, then they're going to have
problems. I think right now their business model is highly
questionable.''
</P>
<P>
   Another specter haunting pay-to-surf companies is cheating.
Several programs available online let users get paid without
viewing any ads. Some programs simulate surfing activity without
requiring the user to be at the computer; others block out the ads.
AllAdvantage's financial filings acknowledge that these programs
have become effective and difficult to detect and warns that the
use of the software could seriously damage AllAdvantage's business.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Carrie Kirby at  &LR; ckirby(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-11-00 2230EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000711.0399 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-11 22:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9484 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-VARIG-SILVA-NYT &LR;      07-11 1018
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VARIG-SILVA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A REAL AIRCRAFT MAN RUNNING BRAZIL'S TOP AIRLINE 
</HEADLINE>
   By JENNIFER L. RICH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAO PAULO, Brazil _ Ozires Silva, the new president of Brazil's
largest airline, Varig, says he has earned the right to speak his
mind about airplanes. He assembled models as a child, flew military
jets in the air force and built passenger jetliners into the
country's leading export business.
</P>
<P>
   So Silva, 69, a former top executive of the Embraer aircraft
maker, is blunt about the problems that he says confront Varig _
high costs, big debts, excessively stringent government rules and a
bad reputation among the flying public.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hostility that our society has toward air transportation
companies is palpable,'' Silva said. To remake Varig, he said, ``we
have to remove these obstacles; you have to have soil that is
relatively fertile in order to grow.''
</P>
<P>
   Silva, who had been a member of the Varig board, was appointed
in May to replace Fernando Pinto as president after the airline
reported a $53 million loss last year and its debt grew to almost
$1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Pinto was not directly blamed for Varig's problems _ the
Brazilian economy was a large reason. The recession last year
caused passenger numbers to drop precipitously, while the
devaluation of the real, Brazil's currency, virtually doubled the
industry's already large stock of dollar-denominated debt.
</P>
<P>
   Of Varig's three major Brazilian competitors, one, Vasp, is
battling to keep creditors from repossessing its planes, while the
others, TAM and Transbrasil, have entered into what amounts to a
merger that enabled them to cut flights and costs.
</P>
<P>
   Pinto, nonetheless, did make some strategic decisions that hurt
Varig. One of the most notable was a cutback in routes to save
money. United States carriers quickly filled the gap and have been
taking away a larger percentage of Varig's international
passengers.
</P>
<P>
   As it became more obvious that the company needed a strong hand
Varig's board decided Silva was that hand.
</P>
<P>
   Silva has made a career of his love for airplanes. At age 13, he
was already building them: models imported from the United States
to his small town in the interior of the state of Sao Paulo. Even
as a child, he remembered in an interview, he would open the kits
and wonder why, with so many natural resources, Brazil even had to
import wood for the base of the plane.
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked myself why Brazil had fallen behind in this race,''
Silva said. ``Why couldn't Brazil manufacture its own planes?''
</P>
<P>
   The question stuck with Silva for 25 years, as his fascination
with aviation grew. At 17, he joined the air force. He had his
start as a pilot by carrying mail and supplies to distant outposts
in the middle of the Amazon, landing his hydroplane on the region's
snaking uncharted rivers.
</P>
<P>
   By his late 20s, Silva, who was already a seasoned pilot, had
become a flight instructor at the Galeao air base in Rio de
Janeiro. It was there, he said, during a particularly illuminating
3 a.m. flight check over the crescent shaped Atlantic beaches, that
he decided to return to his passion of building airplanes.
</P>
<P>
   After earning a degree in aeronautical engineering at the
Aeronautical Technology Institute in Sao Paulo state, Silva came up
with the design for the Bandeirante, the first-ever regional
commercial jet.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the time, we never imagined that we would be able to export
the plane, so we didn't give much thought to the name and used
something very Brazilian,'' Silva said. ``It turned out to be a
huge complication. Imagine an American trying to say Bandeirante.
It eventually became the Bandit.''
</P>
<P>
   Appealing to nationalist sentiments that Brazil should build its
own planes, Silva finally persuaded the government and the military
to support him. Embraer, known formally as Empresa Brasileira de
Aeronautica, was born.
</P>
<P>
   ``On Dec. 22, 1969, the minister of the air force called me to
his office and said that Embraer had to begin operations on Jan. 2,
1970, and that I was to be the president,'' Silva said. ``I was
shocked. When I tried to convince him that I was not the person for
the job, he told me: `You have already created enough problems for
me. Don't create another,' and threw me out of his office.''
</P>
<P>
   The decision was fortuitous. Silva ran Embraer off and on for 21
years until its privatization in 1995. Despite some bumps in the
road, many consider Embraer the country's greatest corporate
success. Indeed, the company is currently Brazil's largest
exporter.
</P>
<P>
   With Varig, Silva has a similar challenge _ to build a
competitive airline. As a start, he plans to renegotiate the
company's debts with banks and leasing companies. He also wants to
take over some of the routes that his competitors have been forced
to give up in recent months.
</P>
<P>
   Silva said he also would concentrate on using his influence in
military and aviation circles to persuade lawmakers in Brasilia to
relax the stringent controls that govern the air transport industry
in Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   His first priority, he said, will be to press for the removal of
price controls, which now limit how much the airlines can charge on
domestic and international routes. Until the restrictions are
removed and the airlines are allowed to adjust prices to fill
seats, he said, Varig and other Brazilian carriers would have
trouble making money.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I go to Congress, I am not going to ask them to get rid
of price controls,'' Silva said. ``I am going to ask them to
explain to me why they exist in the first place. They won't have an
answer because there isn't one.''
</P>
<P>
   The government says changes will be made. A bill before Congress
would create a National Civil Aviation Agency, which would be
responsible for reorganizing the entire industry to increase
competitiveness. How and when the changes will be made remains
unclear, but Silva says he plans to be in the middle of those
decisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the end, I would like to contribute to creating conditions
so that the next 500 years of Brazil are different than the last
500 years,'' Silva said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-11-00 2231EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000711.0400 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-11 22:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9485 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-SEE-SURVEILLANCE-SFCH     07-11 1648
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEE-SURVEILLANCE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 BIG BROTHER'S WATCHING THE STORE  &HT;     By PETER SINTON 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
``The telescreen received and transmitted simultaneously. ... There
was of course no way of knowing whether you were being watched at
any given moment. How often, or on what system, the Thought Police
plugged in on any individual ... was guesswork. It was even
conceivable that they watched everybody all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   George Orwell, ``1984''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
SAN FRANCISCO _ A half-century after George Orwell painted ``Big
Brother'' as a threat, a San Francisco startup named cEverything
has turned round-the-clock observation via the Internet into a
thriving business.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike conventional security cameras that rely on videotape that
has to be picked up and rewound to be viewed, cEverything's
Web-based service uses tiny video cameras and the World Wide Web to
let managers of restaurants, bars, convenience stores and other
businesses monitor operations anytime, from anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   For example, James Thomas, owner of four Subway sandwich shops
in San Francisco, no longer has to drop in to see if his employees
are behaving properly or wearing appropriate uniforms, thanks to
video cameras mounted at each location.
</P>
<P>
   Teri Hope, owner of Los Gatos Coffee Roasting Co., said
cEverything cameras and online monitoring all but eliminated
``short ringing of sales'' where an employee doesn't record all
transactions and pockets the difference.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's Mark Gilpin, owner of Diva's in San Francisco, who
credits cEverything for stopping theft at his gay nightclub and
letting him track whether employees serve customers or try to pick
them up _ a no-no. ``It lets me watch operations from 6 a.m to 2
a.m seven days a week if I want to, even if I'm not there,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sh1  &LR; Growing Acceptance
</P>
<P>
   CEverything has installed more than 3,000 cameras at about 1,000
sites in the past few months.
</P>
<P>
   The company's operations are part of what seems to be the
growing acceptance of Webcams. So-called ``reality'' television
programs that show folks surviving on a Pacific island or in a
century-old London house have become big hits.
</P>
<P>
   Online cameras now broadcast live images of tourist sites and
rites from such places as the roof of San Francisco's
Exploratorium, Yellowstone National Park's Old Faithful geyser, the
panda pen at the San Diego Zoo, Jerusalem's Western Wall and the
decks of cruise ships.
</P>
<P>
   And Webcams increasingly are creeping into the workplace. They
have been installed at construction sites, child-care facilities,
nursing homes and even kennels to help ensure safety and promote
good behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Some employees have balked at constant Webcam observation,
although few are willing to say much on the record. ``You can't
think about it,'' said one of Thomas' Subway staff during a
particularly busy lunchtime, ``You just have to do your job.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, as security cameras have shown, it is perfectly legal
to film employees where they work so long as they are informed of
it and there is some public notice. Cameras in bathrooms or
dressing rooms are not allowed.
</P>
<P>
   Some privacy advocates find the widening use of cameras in the
workplace troubling. ``Video cameras that are on all the time
intrude on the privacy of employees and customers,'' said Barry
Steinhardt, associate director of the American Civil Liberties
Union. He conceded, however, ``There are few legal restrictions.''
</P>
<P>
   CEverything founder and Chairman Michael Trimarco is quick to
insist cEverything is not a ``Big Brother'' service designed to
stop theft or enslave employees.
</P>
<P>
   Backed by $6 million in venture capital with about $25 million
more on the way, the South-of-Market-Street startup is pitching its
services as ``real-time management'' tools to help small and
midsize businesses improve employee productivity and customer
relations.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike conventional video services from security companies such
as ADT, Sensormatic and Johnson Controls, cEverything's offer more
than just video monitoring, which starts at $100 a month for one
camera and $135 for three cameras.
</P>
<P>
   On top of this basic service, cEverything will pile on
additional features for an extra monthly fee. These services
include up to 30 days of video archiving, live tracking of cash
register receipts and online group purchasing of supplies.
</P>
<P>
   CEverything also plans to let clients hear as well as see what
is going on online, process credit card transactions and track
customer traffic and preferences.
</P>
<P>
   Besides managing data flowing out of the business, the company
envisions using the same broadband connections to stream in music,
music videos, games and other entertainment. To beef up management,
cEverything in April brought in Glenn Bacheller as chief executive
officer. Bacheller had been president of the Jamba Juice, Noah's
Bagels and Baskin Robbins chains.
</P>
<P>
   Couldn't Be Everywhere
</P>
<P>
   Trimarco got the idea for cEverything while earning an MBA at
Harvard University three years ago and simultaneously running a
handful of Sorbetto Authentic shops in malls with his brother.
</P>
<P>
   The problem was how to oversee operations when they couldn't be
at the Sorbetto shops, which was most of the time. So the brothers
spent more than $3,500 per location to install cameras, dedicated
phone lines and other gear to monitor business.
</P>
<P>
   After Harvard, Trimarco went to work for Lehman Bros. in New
York, specializing in tax arbitrage, but his mind was on Italian
ices and how the Internet and faster, cheaper broadband service
could make online monitoring a commercial success.
</P>
<P>
   Trimarco and attorney Dave Hong co-founded cEverything in early
1999 with $800,000 from friends and family. In January, Crosspoint
Venture Partners invested $6 million in the company.
</P>
<P>
   Crosspoint partner Jim Dorrian is excited by the market for
``remote management'' services. Before the advent of cheap
broadband services, he said, more than 350,000 restaurant operators
and well over 1 million other small businesses could neither find
nor afford the type of services offered by cEverything.
</P>
<P>
   The basic problem for owners of multiple restaurants and other
businesses is ``they can't be all places at once,'' said Bacheller.
``Now they can monitor traffic and make staffing decisions without
driving from one place to another.''
</P>
<P>
   The maxim ``When the cat's away, the mice will play,''
apparently holds true in many workplaces, said Trimarco. When
managers are around, employees are a lot more attentive, he said.
They don't spend as much time talking with friends on the phone or
in the store. They do little things for customers like make eye
contact and say ``please'' and ``thank you.'' They are careful
about the way they handle food and money.
</P>
<P>
   Two Views at a Time
</P>
<P>
   Subway franchise owner Thomas is sold on cEverything. Since
March, he has installed two cameras _ one in the customer service
area, one over the kitchen _ at three of his stores and is placing
cameras in the fourth shop. The cost: less than $150 per store
including a digital-subscriber-line connection and three days of
video archiving.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can pick up two cameras simultaneously from my home office
or anywhere else,'' said Thomas. ``I can see the cash drawer
opening and in the future I bet a zoom lens will let me see the
denomination of the bill.''
</P>
<P>
   He said security was his main motivation in buying the
cEverything service. Aside from the inconvenience of going from
store to store to collect video security tapes, he noted that a
thief could steal the tapes along with the cash receipts. That is
not possible with cEverything since the video information is
archived on cEverything servers at a secure remote location.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas also uses the system to monitor employees' work habits.
He said this has helped him spot employees who do not check in on
time, who do not wear required caps, who gab too long with friends
and who give away food.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, employees are more on their toes and Thomas figures
the system will allow him to increase profits on his combined $1
million or so in annual receipts by 1 or 2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas acknowledged that ``in the wrong hands, (the cEverything
system) could be demoralizing and have a reverse effect.'' But he
said he has been careful not to ``call up and berate employees
about small things like a dirty table or taking a break too many.''
</P>
<P>
   Diva's nightclub owner Mark Gilpin also is aware of the dark
side of online observation. When he installed four cameras on three
floors of his Post Street club, he recalled, ``There was
resentment. Some employees joked about `God is watching.' ''
</P>
<P>
   But Gilpin maintains he won their support after sitting down
with employees and explaining how the system would improve their
security and safety. For example, he said it makes it easy to spot
troublesome patrons who are ``eighty-sixed'' (banned) during one
shift but reappear during another.
</P>
<P>
   Hear Everything Too?
</P>
<P>
   Gilpin and Thomas both want to try cEverything's audio
monitoring service next, especially if it allows two-way
conversations without the need to dial numbers on a telephone.
</P>
<P>
   CEverything co-founder Hong, a former attorney at Morrison &AMP;
Forrester in San Francisco, said cEverything's management services
have been carefully reviewed by the Wilson Sonsini law firm and
comply with legal statutes.
</P>
<P>
   While Hong maintained it is permissible to monitor what
employees say in the course of their work if they are so informed,
he added that audio service is in the test phase.
</P>
<P>
   But privacy experts already are worried. The ACLU's Steinhardt
said monitoring what employees say to each other or customers at
the cash register ``sounds very troubling because wiretapping laws
prevent unconsensual recording of private conversations.''
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Peter Sinton at  &LR; psinton(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-11-00 2232EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000711.0401 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-11 22:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9487 &Cx1f; ttd-z
