<P>
   Attention editors: Since Sunday, June 4, and for the
subsequent six weeks, The New York Times has published a series of
articles, "How Race Is Lived in America." The series is the outcome
of a yearlong effort by a team of Times reporters to capture some of
the voices of ordinary people and some of the troubling issues that
Americans continue to face. The following photos NYT's 150-156 are
the fourteenth set of photos to move with that series.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT156) MATAGORDA, Texas -- July 11, 2000 -- RACE-HOUSTON-7
-- Richard W. Lewis, a blunt, wisecracking businessman in Houston, at
his church in Matagorda, a small Texas town on the Gulf of Mexico,
where he is a singing minister. Lewis, who describes himself as a
"Republican from the womb," backed Lee P. Brown, a Democrat, in his
run for the office of mayor of Houston, on the basis of a simple
calculation: Brown would win. As the owner of a local construction
company, Lewis depended on a friendly City Hall. Ninety percent of
his business came from municipal contracts. Backing the man he
presumed would be the next mayor seemed only prudent. (Monica
Almeida/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT155) HOUSTON -- July 11, 2000 -- RACE-HOUSTON-6 --
Richard W. Lewis, a blunt, wisecracking businessman in Houston. Lewis
was no friend of affirmative action, but ninety percent of his
business came from municipal contracts. Backing the man he presumed
would be the next mayor, Lee P. Brown, seemed only prudent. In
backing Brown, Lewis had risked alienating the people he worked with,
breaking ranks with his own Houston Contractors Association, of which
he was a past president. "I wanted to be in a position of influence,"
says Lewis, "and you can't influence a loser." (Monica Almeida/The
New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT154) HOUSTON -- July 11, 2000 -- RACE-HOUSTON-5 -- Brian
G. Smith, a 41-year-old architect who runs his own construction
inspection company in Houston, with his son Micah at a ceremony for
his older son Brian's scout troop. More than anything, Smith had
wanted a mayor friendly to affirmative action. Smith remembered the
affront of being denied work because he was black.  So his support
for Lee P. Bown, had largely been bound up with his business
interests. (Monica Almeida/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT153) HOUSTON -- July 11, 2000 -- RACE-HOUSTON-4 -- Brian
G. Smith, center,  a 41-year-old architect who runs his own
construction inspection company in Houston, at work. Smith was
counting on Houston mayor Lee P. Brown's election in 1998 to provide
opportunities for blacks like him who do business with the city. "The
feeling had been that whites would stay in control of Houston," says
Smith. Now, "it was like, 'Wow! Our day has come.' It felt like, at
this time, it was good to be black." (Monica Almeida/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT152) SAN ANTONIO, Texas  -- July 11, 2000 --
RACE-HOUSTON-3 -- Teaming with Anglos on one hand and nonwhites on
the other, Houston's Hispanics display a kind of cross-racial
dexterity that blacks and whites appear to manage less easily.
Richard G. Castaneda, 54, a Mexican-American, has a theory about why.
"There's still big mistrust between the whites and the blacks," he
says, "and I think it's still much easier for each group to get
together with Hispanics than each other." Castaneda, at the San
Fernando Cathedral in his native San Antonio, where he lighted a
candle for his late son. The 270-year-old cathedral is a spiritual
and cultural center for Latinos. (Monica Almeida/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT151) HOUSTON -- July 11, 2000 -- RACE-HOUSTON-2 --
Richard G. Castaneda, at a power lunch with the Houston mayor, Lee P.
Brown. Castaneda, a Mexican-American, had cast his lot with Brown and
become active in his campaign because he had trusted the candidate
when he said he would be fair to Latinos. He had had doubts about
supporting a black candidate, he said. But Castaneda had recognized
that in Houston, where blacks, Anglos and Hispanics each made up
roughly a third of the population, the 21st century would require
interracial alliances in both politics and business if any one
group's interests were to be served. (Monica Almeida/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT150) HOUSTON -- July 11, 2000 -- RACE-HOUSTON-1 -- The
election of Lee P. Brown, Houston's first black mayor in 1998, was a
testament to how racial and ethnic groups in Houston had put aside
their suspicions and rivalries and come together largely out of
self-interest to achieve power. Brian G. Smith, 41, Richard G.
Castaneda, 54, and Richard W. Lewis, 51, left to right, all had put
practical considerations ahead of racial ones. (Monica Almeida/The
New York Times)
</P>
