<P>
   (NYT12) SAN FRANCISCO -- JULY 11, 2000 -- TECH-FOREIGN-BOS --
Many companies are working hard to recruit the best talent they can
find despite the shortage of workers with technical skills. Internet
firms such as HotDispatch, HelloBrain, Guru.com, WebPRN and eLance
are connecting companies with scarce labor. These sites have workers
sign confidentiality agreements that prevent them from discussing
their projects in detail. This allows firms to keep the projects from
being leaked to competitors. Ben Ruedlinger, a 24-year-old, MIT
graduate student freelances for a Silicon Valley company called
HelloBrain.com. (Barry Chin/The Boston Globe)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) BOSTON -- July 11, 2000 -- WRONGFULLY-IMPRISONED-BOS
-- In 1995, 16-year-old Donnell Johnson was accused and later
convicted of murdering a nine-year-old boy. At 22, Johnson is now
looking ahead. After being incarcerated and proclaiming his
innoccence for six years, his body was confined behind bars, but not
his mind. In prison, Johnson renewed his faith, earned a high school
diploma, and emerged wanting to study psychology. A break in the
murder case came last summer when the district attorney who'd always
said Johnson was a killer, began to reconsider his position after
learning of Johnson's innocence from gang members involved in the
killing. Johnson at Dorchester Temple Baptist Church in Boston.
(Suzanne Kreiter/The Boston Globe)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) MANSFIELD, Mass. -- July 11, 2000 --
SMARTERKIDS-SHAKEOUT-BOS -- Hoping to leap ahead of its competitors,
SmarterKids.com, an online toy company plans to exclusively sell
educational toys. Executives at SmarterKids.com hope to distance
themselves from Wall Street's hostility and an ongoing shakeout that
has snuffed out several of their online competitors, including
Toysmart.com, Red Rocket and ToyTime. The company is forging ahead
into new areas such as test preparation and tutoring services. Inside
the giant SmarterKids.com warehouse in Mansfield, Mass., Mark
DeChambeau, vice president of operations. (Pam Berry/The Boston
Globe) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) NEW YORK -- July 11, 2000 -- OBIT-GAULT --  Henri
Gault, a journalist and food critic, who with his longtime colleague
Christian Millau gave the name nouvelle cuisine to modern French
cooking, died at his summer home at St.-Sulpice-en-Pareds in
southwestern France Monday. He was 71. The cause of death was a heart
attack, according to a spokesman for the GaultMillau magazine in
Paris. Henri Gault, right, and his partner, Christian Millau,
traveled to New York in 1981 to promote their new "GaultMillau Guide
to New York." (Sara Krulwich/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) AIN EL HILWE CAMP, Lebanon -- July 11, 2000 --
MIDEAST-REFUGEES -- There are more than 3 million Palestinian
refugees, 80,000 of them crammed into three-quarters of a square mile
of misery in a camp near Sidon, Lebanon, whose future is one of the
issues facing the Camp David summit meeting which opened Tuesday.
They are bitter and fearful as they wait for news, worried that they
will be left out of any settlement. Muhammad Hajar holding deeds,
written in Arabic script, dated 1946, from the British Palestine
mandate that described the farm his family owned in what is now
Israel. A nephew, Ahmed Hajar, held the uncle's identity card.
(Courtney Kealy/The New York Times) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) NEW YORK -- July 11, 2000 -- NY-COWS-3 -- It's time to
rain on the CowParade, the influx of painted bovine forms that has
been choking the sidewalks and parks of New York City, Stamford,
Conn., and West Orange, N.J., since mid-June. The 500 New York cows
and their suburban cousins won't be leaving until fall, when they
will be auctioned off for charity. Every cow is made of 100 pounds of
fiberglass that has been molded into one of three poses: standing
(head up), grazing (head down) and supine. All cows were made by
Silvestri Inc. in Los Angeles, or by the Resource Factory in
Sarasota, Fla., both manufacturers of fiberglass figures. "Piano
Cow," in Stamford, Conn. (Librado Romero/The New York Times) *LITE
