<HEADER>
A9495 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-CAMPAIGN-LAWS-NY     07-11 0450
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-CAMPAIGN-LAWS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: SHREDDING THE CAMPAIGN LAWS 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Wednesday, July 12:
</P>
<P>
   Using an array of dubious legal strategies, the Republican and
Democratic parties have for years circumvented many of the nation's
campaign fund-raising laws. Now comes word that the House
Republican Campaign Committee is so worried about winning
congressional races this year it is considering defying a 1974 law
that limits what state and national parties can spend in
coordination with candidates. Such an action would be another
flagrant violation of the spirit of the election laws at a time
when the public has been disgusted by campaign spending and
fund-raising excesses.
</P>
<P>
   Proponents of busting the spending limits base their case on a
recent decision by the 10th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals, which
declared them unconstitutional. But the U.S. Supreme Court has yet
to be heard on the matter, and in any case the appeals court ruling
applies only to the six states within its jurisdiction _ Colorado,
Kansas, New Mexico, Oklahoma, Utah and Wyoming. Indeed the Federal
Election Commission took an unusual step in June, warning the
parties that the ruling applies only to these states and that, if
the Supreme Court overrules the 10th Circuit, it would apply the
law retroactively to any violations.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court has ruled that parties may spend unlimited
amounts of money for candidates as long as the spending is not
coordinated with the candidates themselves. But the money at issue
in the new case is money that would in fact be spent in direct
coordination with the candidates and their campaigns. If parties
were allowed to spend money this way, it would encourage anyone who
had given the legal amount to a candidate to turn around and give
it to a party on his behalf. Such a step would mark another
evisceration of the whole concept of curbs on fund-raising and
spending.
</P>
<P>
   The House Republican effort comes at a time of anxiety over
winning seats. As John Broder and Don Van Natta report in today's
Times, Democrats actually have more in the bank at present than
Republicans for House races. But being behind should not tempt
Republicans to gut the law. The fact that they are considering such
a step, first reported in The Wall Street Journal and The
Washington Post, suggests that campaign leaders have learned no
lessons over the past few years _ no lessons from the public demand
for campaign reform, no lessons from the growing popular cynicism
and revulsion over a corrupt political system. It would be
insulting for House Republicans to show brazen disrespect for the
law as well.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-11-00 2242EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000711.0408 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-11 22:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9496 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w BC-CONGRESS-FUNDRAISING-     07-11 1109
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-FUNDRAISING-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN BATTLE FOR THE HOUSE, DEMOCRATS GRAB MONEY EDGE _ FOR ONCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Subs grafs 2-4 to clarify and tighten; pickup 5th graf pvs,
Although the ...) 
 (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By DON VAN NATTA Jr. and JOHN M. BRODER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In an aggressive bid to topple the Republicans'
fragile six-seat majority in the House of Representatives, House
Democrats have built and substantial financial advantage over the
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic Congressional Campaign Committee had $37.4
million in the bank at the end of last month, $15.2 million more
than the National Republican Congressional Committee had, according
to second-quarter fund-raising reports to be filed this week at the
Federal Election Commission. The gap has more than doubled since it
first became apparent at the end of the last reporting period in
March.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats' $37.4 million is the highest cash-on-hand figure
in the party's history. It is 10 times the amount they had in the
bank at a similar point in 1998 and seven times as much as they had
in reserves in July 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Republicans have raised more money overall for
House contests, their edge over Democrats is far less pronounced
than in previous election cycles and the Democrats have husbanded
their resources. Republicans, on the other hand have spent $68
million of the $90 million raised for House races.
</P>
<P>
   According to Democratic Party officials, their unprecedented
financial success is due in part to lingering anger at the
impeachment of President Clinton and in part because the goal of
retaking control of the House is in sight. As an example of the
Democrats' newfound fund-raising prowess, a dozen nonincumbent
Democratic candidates for House seats in contested districts have
already raised $1 million or more for their races. At this point in
1998, not a single nonincumbent Democratic House candidate had
raised $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts from both parties say that 30 to 40 House races will be
competitive this fall and those races are expected to cost at least
$3 million each and even more in areas where television advertising
costs are high, party strategists said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Both parties had raised record sums through June 30 for House
contests, although the Republicans, who have raised $90 million,
have spent much more of what they have raised than the Democrats,
who have raised $60 million. The fast pace of party fund raising
for House races means that there will be many contests in which the
amount of money spent will swell into seven figures, amounts seen
more often in Senate contests. And recent federal appeals court
ruling in Colorado has encouraged the political parties to consider
ignoring federal spending limits on individual candidates' races.
</P>
<P>
   The large unlimited contributions known as soft money made up
two-thirds of the $60 million raised by the Democratic Party and
about half of the $90 million raised by the Republican Party. Much
of the federally restricted ``hard'' money raised by Republicans
comes through direct mail, a form of political fund raising that is
extremely expensive. So the Republicans have spent substantial sums
raising still more money.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to close the widening cash gap with Democrats, the
House Republicans have started a $16 million program, named
Battleground 2000. The money for the fund is being donated by
Republican members of the House, from their own campaign funds, in
amounts ranging from $700,000 from a few House Republican leaders
to $10,000 from House freshmen. It will be spent to support
Republicans who face tightly contested challenges in carefully
selected districts nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will look at each individual district and see what
Republicans need most _ get out of the vote campaigns, media
campaign, phone banking,'' said Marit Babin, a spokeswoman for the
Republican congressional committee.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the Republican push to narrow the gap, campaign finance
experts say they cannot remember the last time the Democrats held
such a dramatic cash-on-hand advantage over the Republicans, who
have routinely out-raised the Democrats by at least a 2-to-1 margin
for many years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The congressional Democrats are in a far stronger financial
position than the Republicans going into the general election,''
said Fred Wertheimer, the president of Democracy 21, which
advocates overhauling campaign finance law. ``And to my knowledge,
that has never happened before.''
</P>
<P>
   Led by Rep. Dick Gephardt of Missouri, the minority leader, and
Rep. Patrick J. Kennedy of Rhode Island, the Democratic campaign
committee has used a variety of methods to attract large donations
from individuals and corporate political action committees.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Democrats expect to raise $1 million at an Aug. 27
fund-raiser in Newport, R.I., featuring the singer Tony Bennett.
The event is being billed as a chance for big donors and corporate
lobbyists to rub elbows with senior House Democrats who will become
committee chairmen if the Democrats regain control of the chamber.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic committee is also getting a substantial assist
from Clinton, who has headlined 14 events for House candidates,
raising $8.3 million. Vice President Al Gore has appeared at three
major House fund-raising dinners in recent months, bringing in $3.8
million.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy, chairman of the Democratic House committee, said that
money is flowing to House candidates in part because many donors do
not believe Democrats will gain seats in the Senate and are
uncertain about Gore's ability to defeat Gov. George W. Bush for
the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're clearly benefiting from the perception that we
need to have a last line of defense,'' Kennedy said. ``We need to
have an insurance policy if this does not end up being a banner
year for Democrats'' elsewhere on the ballot.
</P>
<P>
   He said that his job is to ensure that House candidates in tight
races have the resources to compete and declared that the goal was
within reach.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way things are shaping up now,'' Kennedy said, ``we're not
going to lose a single seat for lack of money.''
</P>
<P>
   A longtime Democratic fund-raiser also attributed the party's
success to an abiding hunger to retake the House. ``We've been out
six years and people are hungry,'' said the fund-raiser, who spoke
on condition of anonymity. ``They're anxious to get back in.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   David Plouffe, the executive director of the Democratic
Congressional Campaign Committee, said that donors of all kinds had
helped fatten the committee's accounts. Small contributions are
coming in at a record pace, he said, as well as large gifts from
unions, including a $1 million check from Local 1199 of the Service
Employees International Union, the largest single contribution the
committee had ever received.
</P>
<P>
   Plouffe said the committee was getting ``a lot more from the
Washington corporate community'' _ meaning lobbyists _ as well as
an increase in gifts from wealthy Democrats who in the past gave
chiefly to presidential and Senate candidates.
</P>
<P>
   He also said that Democratic House members have already
contributed $5 million to the committee from their own campaign
accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Spending on House races by Republicans in particular could be
increased significantly by a new campaign finance loophole that was
created in May by a federal appeals court in Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   The 10th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals, which covers Colorado
and five other Western states, struck down a 1976 federal election
law that limits how much money political parties are permitted to
spend directly on behalf of individual House and Senate candidates.
The cap was $67,000 per House district. Although the ruling covers
only six Western states, House Republican leaders and strategists
are considering a plan to funnel millions of dollars in highly
contested races nationwide. The decision will likely be appealed to
the U.S. Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   Since the appeals court decision, the Federal Election
Commission has issued an unusual statement that warns the political
parties that the $67,000 limits are still in effect.
</P>
<P>
   ``No decision has been made'' on whether to heed or ignore the
FEC's warning, said Babin, the House Republican committee
spokeswoman. ``Our lawyers are still looking at it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
