<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEUTSCHE-VOICESTREAM-475&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEUTSCHE TELEKOM MAY PURSUE BOTH QWEST AND VOICESTREAM 
</HEADLINE>
   By ANDREW ROSS SORKIN and EDMUND M. ANDREWS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In its mating dance with several U.S. and European partners,
Deutsche Telekom's eye has turned toward a deal that would involve
acquiring both VoiceStream Wireless Corp. and Qwest Communications
International Inc., executives close to Deutsche Telekom said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   However, Deutsche Telekom's newfound attention to VoiceStream
and Qwest may also be simply a negotiating ploy to make its other
possible partners _ particularly the Sprint Corp. _ jealous.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last several days, talks between Deutsche Telekom,
Germany's largest telephone operator and VoiceStream, which
recently acquired Omnipoint Communications, the mobile telephone
operator in New York, have intensified, executives close to the
talks said. Deutsche Telekom has informally offered as much as $37
billion for VoiceStream, which has never turned a profit, according
to the executives. At the same time, Deutsche Telekom is
increasingly leaning toward buying Qwest, which if combined with
VoiceStream would give the German conglomerate both a wireless and
fixed-line network that would span most of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   If Deutsche Telekom were to acquire VoiceStream, it would
eliminate any possible bid for Sprint, to which it has made
informal overtures over the last two weeks, the executives said.
Sprint agreed to be acquired by WorldCom Inc. last year, but the
companies are expected to announce this week that they will abandon
the deal because of opposition from regulators. The unraveling of
that transaction makes Sprint attractive to Deutsche Telekom
because it has both a nationwide wireless network through Sprint
PCS and a fixed-line network. But a deal with VoiceStream and Qwest
would effectively replace an acquisition of Sprint, perhaps at a
lower cost.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said a Deutsche Telekom-VoiceStream combination made
sense because VoiceStream's network is based on a standard called
global system for mobile communications, or GSM, which is used in
Europe and parts of Asia and would effectively allow the company to
offer a seamless worldwide wireless network. The deal would also
likely clear regulator hurdles, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   Yet it remains unclear whether Deutsche Telekom is primarily
interested in VoiceStream as an alternative to Sprint or as a
bargaining chip, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe that Deutsche Telekom, through its reported offer
for VoiceStream, might be sending a signal to Sprint as it attempts
to get Sprint management to take note that there are other
candidates for acquisition in the U.S.,'' said Frank Marsala, vice
president for equity research at ING Barings, in a report.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Sprint fell $4.25 Tuesday, to $47.50, while
VoiceStream rose $14.125, to $139.0625, and Qwest fell 43.75 cents,
to $54. In Frankfurt, shares of Deutsche Telekom fell 2.15 euros,
to 59.25 euros, or $56.47.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Deutsche Telekom has a long history of being left at the altar,
analysts said. Its effort to acquire Telecom Italia collapsed last
year, and, most recently, it held talks to acquire Qwest. That deal
was scuttled by U S West, which was in the midst of its own merger
with Qwest. Now that Qwest's deal with U S West has been completed,
analysts said it would be much easier to complete a deal with
Deutsche Telekom.
</P>
<P>
   Despite its interest in VoiceStream and Qwest, the company
continues to court Sprint along with Cable and Wireless PLC of
Britain and, to a lesser extent, Global Crossing Ltd., based in
Hamilton, Bermuda, executives close to the company said.
</P>
<P>
   Other suitors for VoiceStream could also emerge. NTT DoCoMo,
Japan's largest mobile telephone operator, and France Telecom,
which recently acquired Orange PLC, Britain's third-largest mobile
telephone company, have both looked at VoiceStream, though neither
are actively negotiating to buy the company, executives close to
those companies said.
</P>
<P>
   VoiceStream has about 2.3 million customers and licenses across
much of the United States. But it remains a start-up company in
many respects, with revenue of only $665.7 million and a loss last
year of $580 million.
</P>
<P>
   That means any acquirer will have to plan for continued heavy
spending beyond the purchase price to build up the business.
</P>
<P>
   One person who has looked closely at the company said it was
expensive by many measures. At its current market value of $30
billion, he said, the company's value works out to about $15,000 a
customer, compared with about $6,000, which France Telecom paid for
Orange.
</P>
<P>
   VoiceStream does own licenses in major metropolitan areas like
New York City and Chicago. But it does not have properties in many
key areas of the United States, including California.
</P>
<P>
   If Deutsche Telekom offered as much as $37 billion, it would be
paying $175 a share. Though the German telephone giant has amassed
a war chest several times that size for acquisitions, the purchase
would force it to define its next steps more precisely than it has
so far.
</P>
<P>
   The chairman of Deutsche Telekom, Ron Sommer, has repeatedly
said he wanted to make big acquisitions and that the United States
was a top priority.
</P>
<P>
   But Telekom executives have been vague about their strategic
vision, repeating almost mantra-like that they have targeted ``four
pillars'' of future growth: mobile communications; online services;
access to the Internet and high-speed data networks; and system
services.
</P>
<P>
   In an intriguing twist, Goldman, Sachs owns 4.5 million shares
of VoiceStream and has the right to name one of its 16 board
members. Goldman is also advising Deutsche Telekom on its
acquisition strategy. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
