<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-11 22:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9500 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-AME-BISHOP-460&AMP;ADD-NY     07-11 1236
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AME-BISHOP-460&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER 213 YEARS, AME CHURCH CHOOSES A WOMAN AS A BISHOP 
</HEADLINE>
   By LAURIE GOODSTEIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI _ In a groundbreaking step for a church that hews to
tradition, the African Methodist Episcopal Church on Tuesday night
elected its first woman bishop in its 213-year history.
</P>
<P>
   As church members wept and whooped with emotion in the packed
convention hall here, the Rev. Vashti Murphy McKenzie, a dynamic
preacher and community organizer, was swept up in a mob embrace by
her children and husband, supporters and members of her church in
Baltimore. Escorted past the rows of voters, she embraced the
bishop who had first ordained her, and took the bishops' podium
flanked by her sweaty and tearful family and a corps of women
ministers and lay leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brothers and sisters, because of God's mercy and grace, we are
able to stand here in the sun,'' she said in a firm, clear voice.
``The stained glass ceiling has been pierced.''
</P>
<P>
   McKenzie, who is the pastor of Payne Memorial AME Church in
Baltimore, is the first woman bishop to be elected in any of the
three predominantly black Methodist denominations. The AME is the
nation's oldest black denomination, and has often taken a leading
role in civil rights battles and the push for black economic
advancement. The post of bishop in the AME Church is prestigious,
and can transform a local pastor into a national leader.
</P>
<P>
   McKenzie was among 42 candidates for four open seats as bishop,
and another candidate was a woman, the Rev. Carolyn Tyler Guidry,
who as a presiding elder supervises 19 AME churches in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need some female leadership,'' said Crissandra Abernathy, a
church member from St. Louis, as a wave of McKenzie supporters in
red T-shirts swept by. ``She's committed. She knows what she's
doing. And she has the charisma for the job. This is a new
generation, and you have a whole new set of leaders coming up.''
</P>
<P>
   The voting in the convention center in Cincinnati was as
passionately contested as any presidential race. Overseeing the
proceedings from a long table on the dais sat the church's 20
bishops, all of them male, many of them grey with age.
</P>
<P>
   The denomination has 20 bishops in all, 19 assigned to
geographical districts and one responsible for ecumenical
relations. Once elected, bishops serve until retirement. The job
comes with a salary that is usually more than $100,000, and other
perquisites include paid housing and travel costs, and a car and
driver. But some of candidates who are pastors at large,
influential churches already live with such perks.
</P>
<P>
   The AME Church was founded when a group of black worshipers were
forced from their knees while praying at a segregated church in
Philadelphia in 1787. It is now an international organization, with
more than 8,000 congregations and 2.5 million members.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   More than 10,000 church members from the United States, Africa,
the Caribbean, England and Canada on Tuesday filled rows of chairs
on the floor of the Cincinnati Convention Center, which could hold
one and a half football fields, for the vote. Among them were 1,800
voting delegates who registered their choices on electronic
keypads, the first time the group has voted without paper ballots
at its general conferences, which are held every four years to
elect officials and make decisions on everything from budgets to
missionary priorities.
</P>
<P>
   The election was hotly contested and highly political, with
candidates making their way through the convention center shaking
hands and waving, like members of Congress at a county fair.
Supporters dressed in matching T-shirts and caps paraded through
the convention center chanting and singing and carrying signs with
pictures of their favorites. Candidates hand out pencils and water
bottles, hair gel and even toothpaste imprinted with their names.
McKenzie's campaign set up a television screen just inside the
doors of the convention center to play over and over a video
promoting her accomplishments.
</P>
<P>
   The election of bishops was delayed by a day, in part because of
a controversy over how many bishops would retire. Bishops in the
AME church are supposed to retire at 75, but lawyers were called in
to resolve disputes over the birth dates of several long-serving
bishops.
</P>
<P>
   The conflict came to a head late Monday night when Bishop Hamel
Hartford Brookins resisted a vote by the delegates in favor of his
retirement. Angry shouting erupted from the convention floor and
the bishops on the dais, and there was a brief attempt to evict
reporters. Eventually Brookins, who in the last decade weathered
financial scandal in his post, was allowed to be ``located''
instead of retired. Under that arrangement, he will be able to stay
on for four more years and serve at-large, on full salary, but a
new bishop will be elected to his seat.
</P>
<P>
   The friction was an indication that many in the church are ready
to see new leaders replace the older generation.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get the sense among many of the delegates,'' said Mike
McKinney, communications director for the general conference,
``that it is time for new leadership.''
</P>
<P>
   Candidates began campaigning as many as four years earlier, at
the last general conference. and some spent the intervening years
traveling around the country and preaching from different pulpits
to make their faces familiar to the voting delegates. Some
candidates were said to spend as much as $40,000 a year in the
quest for a bishop's seat. Supporters say McKenzie raised tens of
thousands of dollars from her sorority, Delta Sigma Theta. She
would only acknowledge that she received ``great support'' from the
group.
</P>
<P>
   The AME Church is the first of the three predominantly black
Methodist denominations, which also include the African Methodist
Episcopal Zion Church and the Christian Methodist Episcopal Church,
to select a woman bishop.
</P>
<P>
   The United Methodist Church elected a woman as bishop in 1981,
and the Episcopal Church consecrated is first woman bishop in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   It was 1964, at the church's 37th general conference in
Cincinnati, when the first woman candidate ran for bishop in the
AME Church. The pathbreaker was the Rev. Carrie T. Hooper, an
evangelist, author and composer from New York, said Dr. Bettye
Collier-Thomas, a history professor at Temple University and the
author of ``Daughters of Thunder: Black Women Preachers and their
Sermons, 1850-1979'' (Josie Bass, 1997).
</P>
<P>
   Only 13 delegates voted for Hooper, even though women had 230 of
the 1,067 votes at the general conference, said Collier-Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   ``What has happened is, in the last 30 years,'' said
Collier-Thomas, ``you have more women who felt there was an
opportunity for them to become ordained and to pastor churches.
They went to seminary, they've got degrees, and their numbers have
really risen. But the majority of them in terms of African-American
women find they can't find a pastorate. Many are assistant
ministers, which I call the stained-glass ceiling.''
</P>
<P>
   McKenzie addressed those women Tuesday night in her victory
speech, saying, ``I stand here tonight on the shoulders of the
unordained, women who serve without affirmation or appointment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't stand here alone, but there is a cloud of witnesses
who sacrificed, died and gave their best,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
