<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RED-LOBSTER-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED LOBSTER WANTS TO NET YOUNGER CUSTOMERS 
</HEADLINE>
   By JASON HALL   
 Herald-Tribune, Sarasota, Fla.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARASOTA, Fla. _ When it comes to mid-priced seafood restaurant
chains, Red Lobster is about the only game in most towns.
</P>
<P>
   Though it controls 40 percent of the national market in casual
seafood dining, the Orlando-based chain commands only about 5
percent of the casual dining market overall.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I think Red Lobster, I don't think casual restaurant,''
said Peter Langlois, a restaurant industry analyst. ``I think
seafood restaurant.''
</P>
<P>
   Red Lobster chief executive Dick Rivera wants to get more casual
diners thinking about his restaurant, especially younger customers,
who tend to make snap decisions about where to eat.
</P>
<P>
   He is spending about $300,000 per restaurant for renovations,
plus countless hours on employee retraining, to reinvent the way
customers think about Red Lobster. He is updating the look, turning
up the music and trying to make Red Lobster a dinner destination
rather than just a seafood place.
</P>
<P>
   The most aggressive marketing in company history accompanies the
changes, enticing customers to ``Try the new Red.''
</P>
<P>
   The Tampa area was chosen as a test market because of its
strength. Red Lobster has 14 restaurants in the Tampa market. They
consistently show profits and are among the company's best in
customer satisfaction ratings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We figured if we could improve the experience here, we could
do it anywhere,'' Rivera said.
</P>
<P>
   The problem with Red Lobster, Rivera said, is not profits.
Fiscal 2000, which just ended for the chain, was a record-setting
year as sales passed $2 billion for the first time ever. The chain
has seen 10 straight quarters of same-restaurant sales growth. For
the year, profits were up 6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   So why fix something that apparently isn't broken? Because
Rivera knows that Red Lobster is not mentioned in the same breath
as leading casual-dining chains such as Outback Steakhouse, T.G.I.
Friday's and Chili's, and he wants it to be. To do that, he said,
Red Lobster has to maintain relationships with its core customers
while simultaneously attracting new ones.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you don't work to freshen them some time, they're going to
get stale,'' Rivera said. ``It's just like any other
relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   What the chain has done in the Tampa market, and will do across
North America over the next four years, is enlarge the bar areas;
update the menu with more daring flavors; place a premium on
alcoholic beverage, appetizer and dessert sales; and modernize the
interior and exterior of its buildings.
</P>
<P>
   The 53-year-old Rivera is no stranger to change at large
restaurant chains. He began his career with Steak &AMP; Ale in the
1970s and while there, oversaw the rollout of the Bennigan's
restaurant concept.
</P>
<P>
   After a couple of moves in the early 1980s, Rivera took on the
tough assignment of running T.G.I. Friday's Inc. in 1987. Once
popular as a watering-hole type of restaurant, Friday's was
struggling to survive when Rivera arrived. By updating the menu and
building a better brand identity _ much of what he plans to do at
Red Lobster _ Rivera spurred growth and took Friday's back to the
position of segment leader in casual dining.
</P>
<P>
   The chain started in Lakeland in 1968, and grew quickly after
being acquired by General Mills in 1970. Red Lobster's parent
company, Darden Restaurants went public as a separate company in
1995. Growth has been consistent over the years, and Red Lobster is
by far the largest casual dining seafood chain in America, with 654
restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   But when he arrived at Red Lobster in 1997, Rivera recognized
that many of the chain's customers were older, and those customers
had been coming for a long time. In other words, company
demographics showed that most younger Americans didn't consider Red
Lobster when making quick decisions about where to eat lunch or
dinner.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've just sort of lost touch with what had gone on in casual
dining and in seafood,'' Rivera said. ``People have just sort of
forgotten about us.''
</P>
<P>
   Rivera ordered changes that had an immediate effect in the focus
groups and exit surveys, he said. Guests at the remodeled Red
Lobster restaurants reported eating the same food, but they had a
better time. They drank more alcoholic beverages and ordered more
appetizers and desserts.
</P>
<P>
   Rivera then committed the company to making the changes across
the board. Instead of doing it piece by piece, as stores come due
for remodeling, Rivera decided to tie a promotional campaign to the
changes and execute them market by market, beginning with Tampa.
</P>
<P>
   (Jason Hall writes for The Herald-Tribune, Sarasota, Fla., which
is a member of The New York Times Regional Newspaper Group. This
article wad distributed by The New York Times News Service.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
