<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-AIDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: AIDS IN SOUTH AFRICA 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Wednesday, July 12:
</P>
<P>
   South Africa, the host of the world AIDS conference this week,
has 4.2 million people who are infected with the AIDS virus, more
than any other nation. It also has the world's fastest-growing
epidemic, with infection rates that rose from 13 percent to 20
percent in the last two years. While AIDS is tragic everywhere, it
is particularly so in South Africa, a nation with a wealthier and
more effective government and health care system than other
sub-Saharan African countries.
</P>
<P>
   South Africa has an extensive program of AIDS education, and
most of its citizens know what HIV, the virus that causes AIDS, is
and how it is transmitted. Yet that has not led to the practice of
safe sex. South Africa needs creative solutions to cut the
prevalence of AIDS among groups such as miners and truck drivers,
whose itinerancy contributes greatly to the disease's spread. It
needs money to care for orphaned children, and to extend its
clinics and hospitals to poor areas, train and hire health workers
and buy equipment and drugs.
</P>
<P>
   President Thabo Mbeki's musings on whether HIV actually causes
AIDS are unhelpful and have discouraged condom use. Millions of
dollars of last year's AIDS budget in South Africa were not spent
on time. Mbeki's government only recently reversed its policy that
the drug AZT, used worldwide to cut mother-to-child transmission,
was unsafe. Stronger leadership on the problem in Uganda and
Senegal has helped to reduce the prevalence of infection in those
countries. A frank and vocal approach to AIDS from high-level
officials can promote safe sex and reduce the stigma of AIDS, which
is so great in South Africa that people shun available services and
refuse to wear condoms or bottle-feed infants for fear others will
suspect.
</P>
<P>
   Since South Africa's health system does function in many places,
it is in a better position than its neighbors _ which will need
Western help to build health systems from scratch _ to offer real
treatment, perhaps even the protease inhibitors that have made AIDS
a more manageable disease for the wealthy. Treatment also gives
people a reason to get tested, slowing the spread of AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest obstacle is the cost of medicine, which is often
higher in South Africa than in Europe. In recent months
pharmaceutical companies, the World Bank, governments and
foundations have promised donations of drugs or new money, in some
cases hundreds of millions of dollars' worth. Donated drugs are
important, but South Africa is proposing a more sustainable
solution _ making cheap versions of still-patented drugs or
importing them at less than the makers charge. These steps were
blocked by Washington _ which has since changed its view _ and the
pharmaceutical industry. Wealthy countries should support South
Africa, and help all of Africa to get drugs at the lowest possible
prices.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-11-00 2255EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
