<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-DISCRIMINATION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE CURBS LAWYER IN BIAS CASE AT COCA-COLA 
</HEADLINE>
   By CONSTANCE L. HAYS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   A federal judge Tuesday ordered Willie E. Gary, a Florida lawyer
who is representing four black former Coca-Cola employees in a
racial-discrimination lawsuit against the company, not to interfere
with the settlement reached last month between Coke and four other
employees with similar claims.
</P>
<P>
   Details of the settlement are expected to be announced in
October. The company said on June 14 that it had reached a
settlement ``in principle,'' and would turn to specialists to work
out issues including the size of the cash payments to plaintiffs.
The settlement extends to all current and former salaried Coke
employees who are black who have worked at the company since April
1995, and is expected to include policy changes inside the company
as well as cash. The plaintiffs contended that they were denied
promotions, raises and other advancement because of their race.
</P>
<P>
   In a two-page ruling issued late Tuesday, the judge overseeing
the case, Richard W. Story of U.S. District Court in Atlanta,
prohibited Gary and his firm from soliciting employees who would be
covered by the settlement to sign retainers that would give Gary's
firm a percentage of any cash award from the settlement.
</P>
<P>
   The judge also ordered Gary and his firm not to discuss the
lawsuit with employees unless the employees initiated the
discussion, and prohibited him from communicating with any named or
prospective class member directly or through public statements.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling was in response to a motion made on June 29 by Cyrus
Mehri, the lead lawyer in the federal racial-discrimination lawsuit
filed against Coke in April of last year. Gary filed a
discrimination lawsuit against Coke, seeking $1.5 billion in
damages, in Georgia state court last month. Gary is also
representing four plaintiffs who originally were represented by
Mehri in the federal lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   In the motion, Mehri said Gary had been trying to persuade black
employees to sign agreements that would give the Gary firm 25
percent of any class-action settlement the individuals receive.
Some employees have said they will opt out of the settlement
because Gary told them he could get them larger cash awards.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Coke said the company had no comment. Gary and
his assistant did not return telephone messages seeking comment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
