<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-11 22:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9506 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e BC-LEAP-AZR &LR;      07-11 1076
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAP-AZR </SLUG>
  
BC-LEAP-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    MORMON AUTHOR MAKES 'LEAP' THROUGH ARTWORK(a) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By BARBARA YOST(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Your story goes here.(Undated) - True to her Mormon upbringing,
author Terry TempestWilliams felt ``set apart'' while writing about
the cancer deaths of her mother and grandmothers in her book
``Refuge.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Mormon church, to be set apart means a kind of state of
grace when the faithful feel especially called to spirituality.
</P>
<P>
   As she wrote Refuge, Williams was able to keep herloved ones
alive. But when she finally published the book in 1991, their souls
returned to heaven, and Williams was left alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a devastating loss,'' she said. ``They were gone.''
</P>
<P>
   Though tragic, that loss led her to a new spiritual journey,
which became the basis for her current work ``Leap ``(Pantheon
Books, $25). Leap is an intimate tapestry that weaves two disparate
themes: Williams' Mormon faith and her discovery of a 15th-century
painting that would obsess her for seven years.
</P>
<P>
   Which is the backdrop, and which is the main story?
</P>
<P>
   ``They are equal,'' Williams said .
</P>
<P>
   Known for her ecological activism and environmental
</P>
<P>
   writings, Williams, 44, is a fifth-generation Mormon who grew up
near Salt LakeCity. At 19, she married writer Brooke Williams in a
temple wedding.
</P>
<P>
   Today she clings to the faith of her childhood butsays ``I am
not orthodox.'' In Leap, she turns a questioning eye on her church
while embracing its catechism.
</P>
<P>
   But it is her relationship with Flemish painter Hieronymus
Bosch's masterwork The Garden of Earthly Delights that provides the
ornate frame for contemplation and an unexpectedly rich portrait of
a woman in love {ndash} with art.
</P>
<P>
   The affair began in the wake of her grief over thedeaths not
only of her mother and grandmothers but also the previous deaths of
fourother women in her family, all ``downwinders'' - suspected
victims of an environment
</P>
<P>
   poisoned by nuclear testing conducted in Nevada in the 1950s.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, Williams and her husband decided to heal their grief
with a trip to Spain.
</P>
<P>
   The day after arriving in Madrid, Williams went to the
</P>
<P>
   Prado, the city's premier museum and home to masterpieces by
Picasso, Dali,Goya, El Greco and Velazquez. As she entered a small
gallery, she found herself standing in front of a three-panel
painting that looked like a landscape, like the view from a window
onto a wondrous and complex scene of angels and devils and impish
mortals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I stopped in my tracks,'' Williams said. ``I had seen that
painting before.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams remembered that reproductions of the left and right
panels, depicting heaven and hell, had hung over her bed at her
grandmother's house. The larger center panel was an unfamiliar
surprise.
</P>
<P>
   ``My body was flooded with memories,'' she said. 'I sent me
literally into a search.''
</P>
<P>
   As that search began, she and Brooke extended their four-day
stay in Madrid to three weeks. Williams returned again and again to
view the painting that had captivated her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't leave,'' she said. ``It was like falling in love.''
</P>
<P>
   Her tryst took her back to Madrid nearly every year.
</P>
<P>
   She kept journals like a schoolgirl writing a romantic diary.
Four years into the affair, she decided to write a work of
non-fiction and to weave religion into her story.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know I was on a spiritual path,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But she believes that is what happens when ``dogma shatters and
spirituality rises.''
</P>
<P>
   She began to contemplate: ``What do I believe?''
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, her father, Salt Lake City pipeline fitter John
Tempest, chided her for her obsession with Bosch. She'd had a vivid
imagination since childhood. Was there really such a painting, he
teased?
</P>
<P>
   When she insisted there was, he declared he would go
</P>
<P>
   along on her next visit. So father and daughter made the trip,
walking into theBosch gallery together, prepared to share Williams'
vision.
</P>
<P>
   Instead they found a blank wall bearing only a
</P>
<P>
   postcard reproduction of the Garden.
</P>
<P>
   A guard explained in Spanish and broken English that
</P>
<P>
   the aging triptych was undergoing restoration. He tried to
convey to JohnTempest the nature of the work, especially a section
depicting adultery. Grasping forwords, he finally shouted,
``Lewinsky!''
</P>
<P>
   Tempest returned home, but Williams stayed in Spainanother
month, tracking down the sisters restoring the painting. Convinced
ofher passion, Teresa and Davila Rocio allowed Williams to watch
them work and
</P>
<P>
   even one day handed her a cotton ball soaked in solvent,
inviting her to cleanone small portion.
</P>
<P>
   As she drew the cotton over a nude man with ablueberry for a
head, she felt a connection with his creator:
</P>
<P>
   ``I am the woman the blueberry man is courting; myeyes, mouth
want his lip-luscious face just ripe to place on the center ofmy
tongue. I want, I want to suck every ounce of juice, sweet
blueberry juice, from his blueberry head. ...''
</P>
<P>
   Although the Mormon-owned newspaper, the Deseret News,
</P>
<P>
   has chosen not to review Leap, Williams does not feel the wrath
of thechurch for her frank writings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have not been excommunicated,'' she said with asmile. ``I'm
not trying to change
</P>
<P>
   the church. I have no ax to grind. My upbringing isMormon, and
that is the lens I see the world through. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a book about faith, what happens when ourinstitutions
no longer feed us.''
</P>
<P>
   Four months ago, after completing Leap, Williams
</P>
<P>
   returned to Madrid for one last rendezvous. By now, the Garden
was brilliant in itsrefurbishment and had been moved out of the
Bosch gallery, displayed on aplatform, roped off from visitors.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, too, had moved from Salt Lake City to thegentle hamlet
of Castle Valley, 27 miles east of Moab, population 200.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a way, we were both restored,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In Castle Valley, Williams continues to work for theenvironment.
She serves on the
</P>
<P>
   board of the Southern Utah Wilderness Alliance, whosemission is
to preserve 7 million acres of red rock country. In her own
town,she works with the Castle Rock Collaboration for the
protection of 5,000 acresof pristine land vulnerable to
development.
</P>
<P>
   In the center panel of her beloved painting is a tinyoman
surrounded by birds, one hand cupped to her ear.
</P>
<P>
   Williams is that woman, she said, ``listening to thebirds,
listening to the land.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
