<HEADLINE>
TAXPAYERS MERIT BULK OF SURPLUS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: Somewhere on the road to November's election, the
Democrats' view of a tax cut has shifted from risky scheme to smart
politics.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Vice President Al Gore's tax cut package has
escalated to $500 billion. This still leaves a big gap between his
proposal and the $1.3 trillion relief plan being pushed by GOP
rival George W. Bush, but it's early in the game.
</P>
<P>
   Some may say Bush is laying it on exceedingly thick as a
campaign ploy, but even as large as his tax reduction proposal
appears, it nevertheless remains woefully short of being enough to
meet a taxpayer fairness test.
</P>
<P>
   With each passing month, the estimates of long-term budget
surpluses continue to climb, and the latest stands at $4.2 trillion
over the next decade. Putting aside the reality of how much of this
extra money will come from surplus Social Security tax revenue and
thus add to the national debt, the numbers raise an overlooked
question: Whose money is it?
</P>
<P>
   If there is any surplus beyond that generated by excess Social
Security revenue, all such tax overpayments should be returned to
the taxpayers.
</P>
<P>
   As one sage analyst observed recently, Washington pols are
playing a sly game by calling the overage a ``budget surplus''
rather than a ``tax surplus,'' which is what it really is. If
America's political leaders were honest, they'd acknowledge that
the money belongs in the first instance to those who paid it into
federal coffers.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who has seriously pondered the governed's rightful
relationship with those who govern understands that government has
a rightful claim only to what it needs to discharge its legitimate
responsibilities. If a government takes in more money than needed
to fund its obligations, this represents abuse of political power.
</P>
<P>
   What critics of big business fail to comprehend in their role as
advocates of big government is that the real robber barons are
those in government who take what they have no right to take by
virtue of their position of government power.
</P>
<P>
   A confused reader recently asked why a private-sector profit is
widely perceived as a result of gouging, and therefore bad, while a
public-sector surplus of tax revenue is broadly accepted as a
positive development.
</P>
<P>
   It's a good question because, as the reader noted,
private-sector transactions are voluntary. Thus, profits are
dependent on creating and meeting demand for a good or service
usually offered by any number of competitors.
</P>
<P>
   In our dealings with government, conversely, nobody is
``buying'' anything voluntarily, but rather being compelled by law
to fork over as much of the fruit of our labor as political leaders
think they can get away with taking. Nothing about it is voluntary.
Either you knuckle under and pay up, or you suffer the legal
consequences.
</P>
<P>
   In a more enlightened political climate, both Bush and Gore
would be feeling much more heat to increase their tax-cutting ante,
because the citizenry would be demanding a more equitable shake.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, too many Americans have bought into the idea that it's
a good thing for Washington to gouge taxpayers. Put another way,
obscene profits are somehow a good thing when generated by
burdensome taxation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
