<SLUG> BC-NETWORTH-PENDER-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NET WORTH: EVEN SMALLER PLAYERS BENEFITING FROM FOCUS ON
FIBER  OPTICS
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By KATHLEEN PENDER 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The san Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ These days, you don't have to be a big
fiber-optics company like JDS Uniphase or Corning to be a hit on
Wall Street. All you need is a few grams of fiber in your corporate
diet, and investors will devour your stock.
</P>
<P>
   A growing list of little-known companies are seeing their shares
rise to astronomical _ some would say unsustainable _ heights after
they announce, or even hint, that they have a fiber-optics product,
division or customer. Some are up more than 1,500 percent in the
past year.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are several companies that have some small portion or a
new focus in fiber technology,'' says Nikos Theodosopoulos, an
analyst with UBS Warburg. ``Investors should do a lot of due
diligence before they buy those stocks. When you peel the onion,
some have good things inside, some do not.''
</P>
<P>
   Shares in Adept Technology have tripled since the San Jose maker
of factory automation hardware and software said in early May that
Corning would use Adept's robots to automate parts of its
fiber-optics assembly process.
</P>
<P>
   Santa Clara's Coherent makes lasers for all kinds of
applications, ranging from semiconductor manufacturing to cataract
surgery to Disneyland light shows. The company has had a nice
financial turnaround, but a big reason its stock is up 321 percent
in the past year is that it also makes fiber-optic components and
lasers used to manufacture them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've only gotten into this market in the past year,'' says
Peter Schuman, Coherent's investor relations director. Fiber
accounts for less than 5 percent of total revenues, ``but it's
growing rapidly,'' from $470 million last year to $264 million in
the first six months of this year, he says.
</P>
<P>
   Rudy Kluiber, manager of State Street Research's Aurora fund,
says, ``I've liked (Coherent) in the past. It's a leader, it's
profitable and growth is accelerating. But it's not necessarily one
I'd buy'' at today's price.
</P>
<P>
   Shares in Newport Corp., which makes test and measurement
equipment, are up 1,657 percent in the past year, mainly because
its sales to fiber optics component makers like JDS Uniphase are
growing. They accounted for 24 percent of revenue last year, and 37
percent in the first quarter of this year.
</P>
<P>
   Keithley Instruments sells measurement equipment mainly to
makers of telecom chips and electronic components. But it also has
some fiber-optics customers, so naturally its shares have advanced
almost 1,700 percent over the past 12 months.
</P>
<P>
   Other companies with strands of fiber include Aeroflex and Zigo,
which both make test and measurement equipment, and GSI Lumonics, a
Canadian laser maker.
</P>
<P>
   GSI confirmed it's doing something in fiber optics, but has
never said exactly what, according to Brian Piccioni, an analyst
with Nesbitt Burns. But who cares? Its stock is up 660 percent over
the past year.
</P>
<P>
   Piccioni recommended GSI about a year ago, when it was around $5
(U.S.) He figures the move up to $20 was based on ``actual
operating results.'' He changed his rating to a hold when the stock
was in the low $20s. He can't explain its continued march up to $40
(it closed yesterday at $33.61), but he suspects it's
fiber-related.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like the dot-com situation, where everyone prices out
these bizarre eventualities,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Fiber optics is seen as the solution to the Internet bandwidth
problem because its uses beams of light to carry data, voice or
video at speeds 10 to 100 times faster over long distances than a
conventional communications cable.
</P>
<P>
   One reason these quasi-fiber companies are on a roll is because
there aren't enough real ones to go around. The big guys keep
buying them up.
</P>
<P>
   San Jose's JDS had barely finished buying E-Tek Dynamics when it
announced Monday that it wants to buy rival SDL Inc. (JDS stock
fell $5.44 yesterday to $95.69 after falling $15.06 yesterday. That
brought the value of the offer down to $33.7 billion from an
initial $41 billion. SDL shares fell $2.69 yesterday to $318.)
</P>
<P>
   After JDS, SDL and E-Tek were the biggest pure-play
component-makers, although Corning, Lucent Technologies and Nortel
Networks have big component operations. Lucent and Nortel have
considered spinning off their fiber divisions, to take advantage of
the market's infatuation with the sector.
</P>
<P>
   Some investors say the little guys might try the same strategy.
And because they're so small, it doesn't take much to get their
stocks in a lather.
</P>
<P>
   Max Schuetz, an analyst with Thomas Weisel Partners, warns
investors to ``be wary of all of them. Optical components is a
tremendously difficult game, even for top-tier players, like Lucent
and Nortel.''
</P>
<P>
   Analyst Jim JungJohann of CIBC World Markets agrees. ``People
are looking for any way to play this,'' he says. ``These companies
are trading like they're all A-grade companies. It's my opinion
you'll start to see a stratification into A, B and C players, as
people become more intelligent investors.''
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Kathleen Pender at  &LR; kpender(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
