<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS-DODGERS RIVALRY NEEDS A SPARK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Maybe you had the same reaction as I had to word
that the New York Yankees-New York Mets feud has flared up again,
the result of the unusual ``subway doubleheader'' and the beaning
of Mike Piazza by Roger Clemens.
</P>
<P>
   You heard the Mets canceled plans for their All-Stars to share a
charter flight to Atlanta with the Yankees' All-Stars, and bounced
Yankees players from the Shea Stadium weight room.
</P>
<P>
   And you thought, Isn't that typically beastly behavior by those
greasy New Yorkers. You thought, There's no place for brushback
wars and the risk of grave bodily injury in a civilized society.
</P>
<P>
   You thought, If only the Dodgers and Angels were that much fun.
</P>
<P>
   On the one hand, can't everybody just get along? On the other
hand, how entertaining when they don't.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets-Yankees dustup should inspire us to wonder again what
can be done to encourage a healthy level of hatred between the
Dodgers and Angels when they open the second half of the season
Thursday through Saturday at Dodger Stadium?
</P>
<P>
   The seeds of a Dodgers-Angels feud have been blowing around in
the sea breeze for 40 years now, ever since the teams shared Dodger
Stadium and Walter O'Malley swindled his tenants into paying for
half of the landscaping toiletries in return for none of the
parking revenue. But the seeds _ of a feud, not the landscaping _
have never taken hold and sprouted.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels expressed bitterness from time to time because the
Dodgers treated them as if they didn't exist. What the Angels
failed to understand is that the Dodgers treated (begin
ital)every(end ital) other team as if it didn't exist. For years at
Dodger Stadium it was easier to find the periodic table of the
elements than the out-of-town scores.
</P>
<P>
   The advent of regular-season, interleague play has changed
things a little. It might actually have hurt the Angels, because it
made the preseason Freeway Series redundant and signaled the demise
of what was, for Anaheim, a big revenue producer. But since
fostering regional rivalries is supposed to be the whole point of
interleague play, it has put a premium on creating a rivalry here
at long last.
</P>
<P>
   To that end, Dodgers managing partner and chairman Bob Daly
encouraged general manager Kevin Malone to pursue trades with the
Angels last winter. Nothing panned out, including controversy. The
Dodgers and Angels still haven't swung a major deal since the
seven-player swap that sent Frank Robinson, Bill Singer and a young
outfielder named Bobby Valentine to Anaheim and brought Andy
Messersmith and Ken McMullen to Los Angeles _ in 1972.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike the case of the Yankees, once forbidden by their
intensely territorial owner George Steinbrenner from dealing with
the Mets, there doesn't appear to be a competitive reason for the
Dodgers' and Angels' unwillingness to trade. It could be that
neither team wants anything from the other.
</P>
<P>
   That's one obstacle to a Dodgers-Angels war. They're too
similar.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers have a star at first base; the Angels have a star at
first base. The Angels have a budding star at third; the Dodgers
have a budding star at third. The Dodgers' most dangerous bat is in
left field; the Angels' most dangerous bat is in left field. The
Angels have new guys at second and short; the Dodgers have new guys
at second and short. The Dodgers' relief ace is having an off year;
the Angels' relief ace is having an off year.
</P>
<P>
   Neither team has a spare starting pitcher to trade. (Who does?)
</P>
<P>
   So a trade is out, for now, as a way of creating friction along
the L.A.-Orange County line.
</P>
<P>
   How about a home-and-home doubleheader? That was quite a
spectacle in New York, the helicopter shots of the team buses
making the drive from Shea Stadium to Yankee Stadium between games.
The trouble is that the chances of making it from downtown L.A. to
Anaheim in less than three hours in the late afternoon are slim.
</P>
<P>
   How about a brushback pitch? Both teams have hitters who, like
Piazza, are worth trying to back off the plate. The question is
whether both teams have pitchers capable of throwing straight
enough and hard enough to scare anybody.
</P>
<P>
   How about some old-fashioned jealousy? The Yankees or Mets or
both are always threats to win a pennant. Maybe what we need is for
the Angels to win something and the Dodgers to care enough to get
angry. OK, so maybe this is a project for the future.
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times headline writer described the Yankees-Mets
flareup as ``an opera bouffe.'' I'm from Los Angeles, so I don't
know opera, much less bouffe, but it looks like more fun than third
place.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
