<SLUG> BC-EDUCATION-BOARD-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER RESIDENCY QUESTION, KANSAS BOARD OF EDUCATION MEMBER SKIPS
MEETING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KATE BEEM  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOPEKA, Kan. _ The empty chair and the whispered question
provided a tangible undercurrent at Tuesday's Kansas Board of
Education meeting: Where is Scott Hill?
</P>
<P>
   The answer: At his home in Montana, pondering whether to resign
from his 6th District seat on the state board.
</P>
<P>
   The Kansas attorney general has said that Hill, who moved to
Montana earlier this year to run his father's ranch, must prove he
is a Kansas resident or either leave the board or face a court
order to remove him.
</P>
<P>
   The matter of Hill's residency came to light last month after
the state board voted 6-4 to transfer 84.5 square miles in
north-central Kansas from the Chapman School District to the
adjoining Abilene School District. Without Hill's vote, the land
transfer would have failed.
</P>
<P>
   The Chapman district has sued in Shawnee County District Court
to have the order set aside. A hearing is set for 9 a.m. Thursday
at the Shawnee County Courthouse in Topeka.
</P>
<P>
   Chapman officials maintain that Hill has relinquished his Kansas
residency and moved to Montana, where he voted in a primary last
month.
</P>
<P>
   Hill said Tuesday from Montana that he was not ready to publicly
announce his decision.
</P>
<P>
   Some residents of his district, which includes parts of 21
counties in north-central Kansas, think it is time for Hill to go.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm pleased today that Scott Hill's not sitting there
voting,'' Chapman Superintendent Tony Frieze told the board.
</P>
<P>
   Frieze and others said Hill had lobbied to transfer the land
from Chapman to Abilene. But board Chairman Harold Voth said in a
break in the meeting that he never discussed the matter with Hill
until after the vote.
</P>
<P>
   John W. Campbell, senior deputy attorney general, sent a letter
to Hill in late June, saying it appeared that Hill was no longer
living in the district he was elected to represent. Hill has been
registered to vote in Montana since April 25 and voted in the June
6 Montana primary.
</P>
<P>
   Hill has until Monday to respond.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday also marked 11 months since the board voted on new
science standards that de-emphasize evolution. Several speakers,
including Brown University biologist Ken Miller, urged the board to
return to standards that included evolution, the theory that living
things share common ancestors but have changed over time.
</P>
<P>
   One speaker, Rebecca Messall of Overland Park, asked the board
for a ``permanent moratorium'' on implementing any new science
standards in Kansas. She told the board she had found links between
science documents used to write the standards and the eugenics
movement, which held that certain races were superior to others.
</P>
<P>
   The eugenics movement of the early 20th century led to such
horrors as forced sterilizations and the Holocaust, Messall wrote
in a paper she presented to the board.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
