<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAMPAIGN NEWS AND NOTES 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NADER IS MINNESOTA BOUND
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Jesse Ventura of Minnesota has become a must-stop on the
campaign circuit of presidential contenders. So it should not be a
surprise that Ralph Nader, the Green Party nominee, plans to come
calling on Ventura on Friday. Nader said he asked for a meeting
with Ventura because he has ``a lot of ideas for him as governor.''
Nader also wants to seek Ventura's counsel on ballot access matters
_ and on finding his way into the presidential debates. Does Nader
want an endorsement, too? He said he never asks for endorsements,
and that Ventura is not about to make one. But, Nader said, ``you
don't have to leap a chasm of logic to realize I'd like that.''
</P>
<P>
   THE REPUBLICANS: ALLUSIONS TO CAMPAIGNS PAST
</P>
<P>
   The year 1948 has suddenly loomed large in the presidential
race. It began when the Bush campaign turned to Sen. Strom
Thurmond, R-S.C., to blunt Al Gore's efforts to look Trumanesque as
he attacks Congress as a ``do-nothing-for-the-people'' legislature.
The long-serving Thurmond noted in a statement issued by the Bush
campaign that he had actually ran for president against Harry S.
Truman. ``Mr. Gore, I knew Harry Truman. I ran against Harry
Truman. And Mr. Gore, you are no Harry Truman,'' Thurmond said,
paraphrasing a line about John F. Kennedy that Lloyd Bentsen, the
1988 Democratic vice presidential nominee, used against his
opponent, Dan Quayle. Democrats quickly noted that Thurmond ran
against Truman in 1948 as a segregationist Dixiecrat. And they
pointed out that the statement was released on the same day that
Bush was appearing before the NAACP and speaking of bettering
relations between Republicans and black voters. ``Political
doublespeak, thy name is George W. Bush,'' said Jenny Backus, the
press secretary for the Democratic National Committee.
</P>
<P>
   THE POLLS: THE RIDGE FACTOR FOR BUSH
</P>
<P>
   A new poll in Pennsylvania shows that Gov. George W. Bush would
benefit significantly in that important battleground state if he
added Gov. Tom Ridge to his ticket. The Keystone Poll, conducted by
the Center for Politics and Public Affairs at Millersville
University, shows a statistical dead heat in a head-to-head
contest, with Bush at 44 percent and Gore at 40 percent. The survey
of 634 registered voters has a sampling error of plus or minus 4
points. If Ridge is added to the Republican ticket, Bush's lead
extends to 51 percent to 39 percent, beyond the margin of error.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WEDNESDAY'S SCHEDULES
</P>
<P>
   GEORGE W. BUSH _ Austin, Texas
</P>
<P>
   AL GORE _ Baltimore and Livingston and Englewood, N.J.
</P>
</TEXT>
