<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-LINCOLN-COTTAGE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: LINCOLN READ HERE 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Wednesday, July 12:
</P>
<P>
   The summer cottage where President Abraham Lincoln sought
solitude and relief from the pressures of office was also the place
where he wrote the Emancipation Proclamation, the most important
document of his administration. Anderson Cottage, located four
miles north of the Capitol, has served as a summer home for at
least five other presidents. It was a particular favorite of
Lincoln, who would spend summer afternoons reading underneath the
canopy of a copper beech tree that still stands by the cottage.
</P>
<P>
   If any house is deserving of rescue it is this one, and it is
thus heartening to learn that the National Trust For Historic
Preservation is raising money from private sources to repair the
cottage and add new facilities, including an educational center.
There is already $750,000 in public money in hand, drawn from the
Save America's Treasures program, which is underwritten by
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The 14-room house, in Early Gothic Revival style, currently
serves as an office for the U.S. Soldiers' and Airmen's Home and is
therefore federal property. Its use as office space, its general
neglect and Washington's legendary humidity have damaged the
cottage over the years, and leaking radiator pipes are threatening
its interior woodwork.
</P>
<P>
   The money, as well as President Clinton's recent designation of
the house as a national monument, will protect a 157-year-old
landmark and allow the general public to share its history. As an
important link to the Lincoln era, the cottage's accessibility to
the public is of fundamental educational and national significance.
</P>
<P>
   The effort also reflects well on the whole idea of
public-private partnerships. Save America's Treasures is run
jointly by the White House Millennium Council, established by
Hillary Rodham Clinton two years ago, and the National Trust.
Altogether, the council plans to contribute $30 million in federal
money this year to help preserve 71 endangered historical sites,
and the National Trust a similar amount. Together they will do much
to sustain some of the nation's most compelling pieces of history.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
