<HEADLINE>
MEXICAN MURDER SUSPECT IS SOUGHT BY U.S. 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The United States is seeking the extradition from
Mexico of a man suspected of killing an American anti-drug agent in
Arizona in 1994, officials said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Agustin Vasquez Mendoza, who was placed on the FBI's 10
Most-Wanted list four years ago, was arrested in Puebla, Mexico, on
Sunday by Mexican federal police working with U.S. law enforcement
authorities, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Vasquez, 30, is being sought for the murder of Richard Fass, a
special agent of the U.S. Drug Enforcement Administration. Vasquez
and several associates are accused of killing Fass, who was working
undercover as a potential buyer of 22 pounds of methamphetamine.
</P>
<P>
   Donnie R. Marshall, the DEA administrator, said a ring led by
Vasquez specialized in the robbery of drug dealers and took part in
murders, kidnappings and other crimes.
</P>
<P>
   ``His apprehension proves to drug traffickers around that world
that no one who harms or kills a DEA agent, law enforcement officer
or other public official will be allowed to remain free,'' Marshall
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
