u a BC-NJ-WHITMAN-PHOTOS-NYT     07-11 0790
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-WHITMAN-PHOTOS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITMAN DEFENDS FRISKING OF BLACK MAN IN '96 PHOTO 
</HEADLINE>
  By DAVID KOCIENIEWSKI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. _ Gov. Christie Whitman on Tuesday defended a 1996
trip in which she cheerfully frisked a black man while accompanying
police officers, and suggested that a photograph of the encounter
was being misrepresented and exploited by her political opponents.
</P>
<P>
   The frisking was photographed when the governor went along with
state troopers one night as they patrolled in Camden, the state's
most impoverished city. In her first extensive public comments on
the incident, Whitman brushed aside criticism from civil rights
leaders who say her actions showed an insensitivity to the racial
profiling allegations that have dogged the New Jersey Police for
more than a decade.
</P>
<P>
   When asked whether she would apologize to the man in the picture
_ who was stopped for suspicious activity, searched by troopers,
patted down by the governor and released _ Whitman declined. ``An
apology would be too easy,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The governor said that in making the rounds with state troopers,
she was simply being a ``hands-on governor,'' trying to understand
the complexities and dangers of law enforcement. Whitman also said
her only regret was that the picture would be used by her political
adversaries to detract from her efforts to improve Camden's
neighborhoods and her steps to overhaul the state police and
discourage racial bias.
</P>
<P>
   ``Am I sorry that this picture is being taken out of context to
undermine the work we've done?'' she said. ``Yes. Am I sorry that
there is a picture out there that can be extrapolated to try to
make me look like something I am not? Of course.
</P>
<P>
   ``But am I sorry that I went in with the state police and I
wanted to show them that I would do anything for them? No. The
citizens of Camden are better off then they were in 1996.''
</P>
<P>
   The governor's statements came at a news conference on Ellis
Island, where she presented a $1 million check to rehabilitate the
immigration museum, and her remarks were intended to put the
controversy behind her. But news coverage of the incident has
mounted in recent days, and Whitman was followed by a television
cameras from local stations and national networks.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Al Sharpton, whose protest against the state police
closed the Atlantic City Expressway last summer, said he and the
Black Ministers Council of New Jersey planned to hold protests
around the state and at the Republican National Convention late
this month. Those demonstrations could be politically embarrassing
to Whitman, whose supporters have been suggesting her as a possible
vice-presidential nominee or, if George W. Bush wins the White
House, a Cabinet member or ambassador.
</P>
<P>
   ``They say a picture is worth a thousand words,'' Sharpton said.
``It might be worth a vice-presidential nomination.''
</P>
<P>
   The photograph, taken by a state trooper, was recently
subpoenaed in a lawsuit by several other officers, who contend that
they were victims of discrimination, but has not yet been entered
into evidence. The Associated Press obtained a copy last week and
it has since been widely publicized on television and in print.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   According to troopers and a lawyer who is representing officers
who are suing the state police, a supervisor whose subordinates
went along on the 1996 patrol with Whitman had promised a week of
paid vacation to any trooper who could get a picture of the
governor's frisking a black suspect, and used a racial slur to
describe blacks.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman said Tuesday she was never told that a reward was being
offered for a picture, and said she still thought race had nothing
to do with the decision to frisk the man.
</P>
<P>
   ``Race was not a factor,'' Whitman said. ``He had already been
identified as a suspect.''
</P>
<P>
   But defense lawyers predicted Tuesday that the the photograph
would help them fight the criminal case against two troopers
charged in the April 1998 shooting that catapulted racial profiling
to the top of the state's political agenda. In that shooting,
Troopers James Kenna and John Hogan face charges of attempted
murder for wounding three unarmed black men during a traffic stop
on the New Jersey Turnpike. They are also accused of filing false
reports to conceal the race of the drivers they stop.
</P>
<P>
   If the troopers stand trial, the picture will be used to assert
that officers were encouraged to use race in selecting whom to stop
and arrest, said Jack Arsenault, the lawyer who represents Kenna.
``There'll be a lot of evidence that this is how they were trained,
that one of the factors in profiling criminals is race,'' Arsenault
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-11-00 2324EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
