<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-ROBLEDO-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WYNALDA HOPES TO TURN IT AROUND
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ For all that Eric Wynalda has meant to U.S.
Soccer, his Major League Soccer career has been defined more by his
mouth and injuries than his goal striking abilities.
</P>
<P>
   He left his previous two stops, in San Jose and Miami, with
unfinished business, never living up to the reputation he carved
for himself during three World Cup appearances and as a promising
young striker with F.C. Saarbrucken of the German Bundesliga.
</P>
<P>
   Last week Wynalda was dealt from Miami to New England for
midfielder Ivan McKinley. The move reunited Wynalda with his
friend, John Harkes, and coach Fernando Clavijo, whom he has played
with.
</P>
<P>
   Wynalda, who has 34 goals in 106 appearances with the U.S., is
finally on a real contender for the MLS title. New England is
second behind New York/New Jersey in the East, and Tuesday the Revs
added 26-year-old Spanish striker Jose Luis Morales, formerly of
Real Madrid.
</P>
<P>
   ``I need this team more than this team needs me,'' said the
31-year-old Wynalda, hoping to turn his bad fortune around. ``I'm
not here to be a hero, I'm just excited to be part of it. I want to
finish out the year strong and make a run at a championship.''
</P>
<P>
   That usually sounds like Wynalda in the beginning, optimistic
and full of expectations. At some point, however, he usually starts
whining about playing time or injuries.
</P>
<P>
   But at least he admits his own faults.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've created some of my own bad press and I'm aware of that,''
said Wynalda. ``But I'll tell you what, when you are me, when
you've been around as long as I have, people are going to have
their opinion of the way things should be done.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to understand that 90 percent of the players who
play in this league don't know what it's like to be anywhere else.
Sometimes things come out the wrong way.''
</P>
<P>
   Wynalda's troubles began in 1997 when former San Jose coach
Laurie Calloway accused Wynalda of saving himself during MLS
matches for National team games. Wynalda missed 22 of 37 games that
season, mostly because of a nagging groin injury.
</P>
<P>
   More injuries limited Wynalda to only 16 of 32 games in 1998,
prompting San Jose to trade Wynalda to Miami in the offseason.
</P>
<P>
   Wynalda's career in Miami took a big blow before it started.
While on loan to Leon of the Mexican first division, Wynalda
suffered an ACL tear, limiting him to only six games with the
Fusion in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   This season Wynalda appeared in only six games with Miami
because of a calf injury and had arguments with coach Ivo Wortman
over playing time. Wortman was fired and replaced by Ray Hudson.
Hudson then had his run-ins with Wynalda, casually questioning the
severity of Wynalda's most recent injury. Wynalda didn't appreciate
it, which subsequently led to last week's trade.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't appreciate him making a mockery of my health, I don't
think my injury was treated with the utmost seriousness,'' said
Wynalda. ``I like Roy, I think he's a great guy, but I just didn't
see anything funny about what he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to be on the field, I don't like watching games,
especially when we're losing a lot of those games.''
</P>
<P>
   Wynalda is hoping to be injury free when the Revolution meets
New York/New Jersey on Saturday. This is a pivotal time for
Wynalda. He's in the last year of his MLS contract, and while he's
still popular, he knows his MLS career is incomplete.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without a doubt the injuries I've sustained and the bad luck
I've had has worn on me,'' said Wynalda. ``I have more in common
with (injury riddled) Tab Ramos than people know, but the important
thing is to get it right and use the remaining days of my career to
its full advantage.''
</P>
<P>
   With back-to-back World Cup qualifiers in hostile Central
American surroundings, U.S. National team coach Bruce Arena added
veteran Tab Ramos to the mix. The U.S. opens Group ``E'' semifinal
matches against Guatemala in Mazatenago on Sunday, followed by a
trip to Costa Rica the following week.
</P>
<P>
   Ramos, a veteran of the 1990, '94 and '98 World Cups, has played
well for the New York/New Jersey MetroStars since returning from a
calf injury. Ramos feels his experience is the primary reason Arena
selected him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely,'' Ramos said. ``I feel the team can do fine
without me. They're playing well, but it can never hurt to have a
little depth and experience in the games that really matter.''
</P>
<P>
   To avoid distractions, the U.S. team is arriving in Mazatenago
just a day before the match and will bring its own food. These are
dangerous trips. In the past, the U.S. players have been hit with
batteries and an array of other objects. Galaxy defender Paul
Caligiuri once had mace sprayed on him.
</P>
<P>
   ``The environment on the road makes the difference,'' said
Ramos. ``It has nothing to do with what happens between the lines
of the field because both teams want to win and it's going to be a
tough game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's everything else around you, the things that get thrown at
you; the way people treat you the whole time you're there. Those
are the types of situations that are uncommon, that you usually
don't see at friendly games. Games in Central American are even
more difficult because of all the politics involved with
representing the United States.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
