<SLUG> BC-NY-TRUANCY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NYC'S SUMMER SCHOOL EFFORT PLAGUED BY TRUANCY 
</HEADLINE>
   By ANEMONA HARTOCOLLIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Despite an intensive weeklong campaign to round up
truants, more than 130,000 students in kindergarten though 12th
grade _ nearly 40 percent _ are missing from the most ambitious
summer school program in New York City's history, the Board of
Education said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The poor attendance is a costly and potentially embarrassing
culmination to months of obsessive planning. And it shows how hard
it is to make a difference in the lives of children, even when
everything seems in place on paper, in a system as big and complex
as New York City's.
</P>
<P>
   As summer school opened last Wednesday, Chancellor Harold Levy
and Mayor Rudolph Giuliani had announced with much fanfare that
more than 300,000 students were registered. More than 200,000 of
those students are required to go, and the rest are being strongly
urged to attend because of poor performance.
</P>
<P>
   Levy, who was hired in January for his management skills,
conceded that the rocky start of summer school was a setback. ``The
real honest answer is, we should have 100 percent attendance on the
mandatory side,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   So far, 24 percent of the students mandated to attend in third
through eighth grade have not showed up, and half of the high
school students required to attend are absent. While the rate of
absenteeism among mandatory students is about the same as last
year, when the city experimented with a much smaller summer school
program, expectations were much higher this year, as the Board of
Education and Giuliani vowed to end social promotion, the automatic
advancement of students with their age group, even if they are
failing.
</P>
<P>
   Across the city on Tuesday, a survey of more than a dozen
schools by The New York Times found scattered problems with
classrooms that lacked air-conditioning, schools that were not
providing transportation, and some that were serving bag lunches
instead of hot meals.
</P>
<P>
   But attendance was by far the biggest obstacle.
</P>
<P>
   From Bushwick to Harlem, many teachers were standing in front of
nearly empty classes. The Board of Education has budgeted $150
million on instruction alone, for small classes of 12 to 15
students, yet many schools had just six to eight students in a
class, and some had as few as three.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
