r s BC-FBN-IRVIN-RETIRES-TEX     07-11 1083
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-IRVIN-RETIRES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS' IRVIN BIDS PLAYING DAYS, FANS FAREWELL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RAY BUCK 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Michael Irvin, who leaves the Dallas Cowboys
with 20 team receiving records, three Super Bowl rings and five Pro
Bowl appearances, waited until Tuesday to retire in what was an
emotionally charged news conference at Texas Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Irvin wore a mustard-colored shirt and tie that matched his
mustard-colored suit. His heartfelt farewell _ something he
considered inevitable for several months _ was juxtaposed amid his
laughter and his tears, as the normally glib Irvin struggled at
times to get the words out.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not hard to say goodbye to the game. I'll say goodbye to
playing football,'' said Irvin, choking back the tears. ``But it's
hard to say goodbye to playing football here for America's Team,
America's fans. I just want to say, `Thank you.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The day that Irvin, 34, decided never to play football again
came this off-season when his wife, Sandi, watched tearfully as
Irvin played in the backyard with his four children. Her tears were
for what might have been if the career-ending spinal injury
suffered Oct. 10 at Philadelphia had left Irvin with life-altering
paralysis.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Irvin has all his faculties and should live a normal
life. He moves into a broadcasting career with Fox Sports Net and
will work alongside Chris Myers on a weekly NFL TV show.
</P>
<P>
   ``From a physical standpoint, I can probably still line up and
play football,'' said Irvin, who learned immediately after his Oct.
10 neck injury in Philadelphia that he has a congenital condition
known as cervical stenosis, in which an abnormally narrow spinal
column increases the chance of paralysis if the spinal cord again
suffers trauma.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I knew that there would never be peace with my wife or
peace with my family if I ever played again,'' said Irvin,
recalling that scene in his backyard several months ago. ``And so,
from that moment on, I pretty much rationalized that I would never
play the game again.''
</P>
<P>
   Irvin sent laughter through the gathering of media, family,
friends and about a dozen former teammates and coaches Tuesday when
he added: ``Would I be stupid enough to still be playing football
if I was alone, by myself? Most definitely.''
</P>
<P>
   Irvin did receive what he believed to be approval from at least
one neurosurgeon to continue his career, if Irvin himself ``really
wanted to.'' But he said his mind was made up for him by those who
love him most: his wife and children, and his mother, Pearl, in
Fort Lauderdale, Fla., along with a large family that includes his
16 siblings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never really went hunting for that doctor,'' Irvin
acknowledged. The decision to retire ``was an emotional thing, a
family thing.''
</P>
<P>
   What the Cowboys will miss from Irvin, often called ``the
Playmaker,'' will be his 750 career catches (tied for 10th all-time
in the NFL), his 11,904 career yards (ninth all-time) and his 65
career regular-season touchdown catches (most by a Cowboys
receiver).
</P>
<P>
   But probably more than the gaudy numbers, the Cowboys will miss
Irvin's legendary work ethic and his leadership.
</P>
<P>
   ``What made Michael so special was the way that he worked,''
Cowboys quarterback Troy Aikman said. ``He practiced every day as
if he was going up against the San Francisco 49ers in the NFC
Championship.''
</P>
<P>
   Dave Campo, who has coached on teams in which Irvin played at
the University of Miami and with the Cowboys since 1989, expressed
disappointment Tuesday that his first year as a head coach at any
level will have to unfold without Irvin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Folks, you are looking at the most competitive receiver to
ever play the game,'' Campo said.
</P>
<P>
   Owner Jerry Jones added: ``We will not replace Michael Irvin in
what he has meant to the Dallas Cowboys. We have to get there
(without him) ... but we have to get there in a little different
way now.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys have the fastest tandem of receivers in team history
in Joey Galloway and Rocket Ismail, but they lack a proven
possession receiver, the role defined by Irvin before his neck
injury.
</P>
<P>
   Irvin brought a sense of togetherness to a team sport. His
belief that ``a team has to be a family'' was echoed in his words
Tuesday, as Campo began inquiring immediately after Tuesday's news
conference how to use some of Irvin's comments as a teaching tool
for young players in training camp, which begins next week.
</P>
<P>
   Irvin's popular image took a hit in March 1996. On his 30th
birthday, he was arrested during an early-morning drug bust at an
Irving hotel, along with two women and a former college and Cowboys
teammate, Alfredo Roberts. Cocaine was found in the room.
</P>
<P>
   Irvin received a five-game league suspension at the start of the
1996 season. He entered a plea of no contest to the felony drug
charge, and received 800 hours of community service and four years
of deferred probation, which he completed last week.
</P>
<P>
   In December 1996, Irving was falsely accused by a woman of
sexual assault. Only after the incident had been well-publicized
nationally did the woman admit that her story was not true.
</P>
<P>
   Irving's career was further muddied by his rumored involvement
in ``Scissorgate,'' an incident in which teammate Everett McIver
received a cut to his neck during the Cowboys' 1998 training camp.
The incident was followed by coach Chan Gailey's decision before
the 1999 season to hand Irvin a reduced role in the offense after
he had caught only one touchdown pass during the '98 season.
</P>
<P>
   Irvin expressed little complaint publicly, and had caught three
touchdown passes in the first three games when he suffered a neck
injury on what appeared to be a routine catch-and-tackle in the
first quarter at Philadelphia. As Irvin lay motionless on the
Veterans Stadium artificial turf, he lost feeling in both arms and
legs for about 15 minutes, and fans booed. This prompted one
Philadelphia newspaper to write the next day: Unspeakable, even for
us.
</P>
<P>
   Irvin was asked recently by his 2-year-old son, Michael, how to
tackle. Irvin began to show him, then was overwhelmed by the
feeling of how lucky he is to be able to show him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've shared some great times, and I've shared some
not-so-great times here,'' Irvin said. ``But never once in my heart
did I ever see myself playing for anyone other than Jerry Jones, or
for any team other than the Dallas Cowboys, or for any fans other
than Cowboys fans.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
