<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-LeBRETON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRVIN'S LAST DANCE SKIPS THE BIG FALL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LeBRETON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Yo, Mike. Loved the suit.
</P>
<P>
   And the little story about your ``happiest moment as a Cowboy''
being a block you once threw for Emmitt Smith? Priceless.
</P>
<P>
   And what's that? You said you knew it was time to retire when
your wife got tears in her eyes, worried that you'd get hurt again
and wouldn't be able to play with your kids? Man, the TVs ate that
up.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Irvin, lest we had forgotten, always did know how to
play to an audience.
</P>
<P>
   And so he bid goodbye to football in both dramatic and disarming
fashion Tuesday. In a news conference at Texas Stadium, Irvin
reminisced about the good times while lightly stiff-arming aside
the bad ones.
</P>
<P>
   It was only casually alluded to during the news conference, but
Irvin was forced to retire from the Dallas Cowboys because doctors
discovered that he has a condition called spinal stenosis that,
with another hit, could cause permanent paralysis.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning this fall, Irvin announced, he will become a
studiocommentator on Fox Sports Net's ``NFL This Morning'' show on
Sundays.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mother always said that when God closes a door, he opens up
another one,'' Irvin said.
</P>
<P>
   By all means, yes, let's bring mom and God into this.
</P>
<P>
   From coach Dave Campo's opening hug to the announcement of
Mike's new gig, it was grand theater. If you are an Irvin fan, you
probably rose to your feet, shouting bravos.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of us, I assume, were supposed to act like those NFL
officials _ keep the yellow flags in our pockets and look the other
way.
</P>
<P>
   Either reaction is fine. Irvin deserves the hosannas that have
come his way this week.
</P>
<P>
   But before we line the path to his Mercedes with palms, let's
make sure we get the complete perspective straight.
</P>
<P>
   Irvin, by any measure, was a great NFL receiver and played a
starring role in the Cowboys' rise to Super Bowl prominence. Yet,
his indiscretions helped bring about the end of the franchise's
glorious '90s ride.
</P>
<P>
   One incident? On the scales of the justice system, that may be
true.
</P>
<P>
   But Irvin's 1996 arrest, busted with cocaine and two
``self-employed models,'' became the cause celebre that resonates
throughout the franchise to this day.
</P>
<P>
   Irvin's ultimate no-contest plea led to a five-game suspension
in the 1996 season. The Cowboys lost three of those five games.
Without home-field advantage, they were ousted from the playoffs by
the Carolina Panthers.
</P>
<P>
   The franchise hasn't won a playoff game since.
</P>
<P>
   It all took its toll. Because of the Cowboys' off-field
headlines, owner Jerry Jones made a public display of wanting to
cleanse the team's image. Coach Barry Switzer didn't help things by
being nabbed at the airport in 1997 with a pistol in his gym bag.
In the draft, the club passed on All-Pro receiver Randy Moss,
fearing that he had a too-cloudy past.
</P>
<P>
   At training camp in 1998, Irvin was involved in a scuffle over a
haircut with teammate Everett McIver. Brandishing scissors, Irvin
left a two-inch gash in McIver's neck, an episode that could have
been termed a violation of Irvin's probation and sent the receiver
to jail.
</P>
<P>
   But the Cowboys whitewashed the stabbing. New coach Chan Gailey
took a credibility broadside by being forced to awkwardly tap dance
around the incident.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, it all helped to take the shine off the Cowboys'
star.
</P>
<P>
   It has been said that Irvin paid his debt, served his community
service and kept a clean public ledger in recent times. Yes, on the
overall scheme of forgiveness, he deserves a second chance.
</P>
<P>
   Or is it third? I forget.
</P>
<P>
   What we can measure for certain is his impact as a Cowboys
player for 12 seasons. He was a tireless worker and an unmatched
competitor.
</P>
<P>
   As coach Dave Campo said, the Cowboys will sorely miss Irvin's
``tenacity.'' Nobody seemed to want to win more than Michael Irvin.
</P>
<P>
   His Hall of Fame credentials are solid. But again, Irvin's
off-field troubles might dim the glare from his three Super Bowl
rings and the 750 passes he caught. Electors should vote him in,
though not the first year.
</P>
<P>
   At his final news conference Tuesday, dressed in a
mustard-colored suit, Irvin seemed to swallow away a tear as he
talked about the friendships and the good times he enjoyed with the
Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want to say thank you,'' he said. ``I just want to tell
everyone thanks for the support, thanks for the moments. I hope I
gave you just a few moments of great feelings and happiness.''
</P>
<P>
   Irvin should know that he did.
</P>
<P>
   It was a grand ride. As we shout our hosannas, don't forget that
it could have been even grander. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
