<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-IRVIN-LEGACY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRVIN'S LEGACY CARRIES NO TARNISH WITH TEAMMATES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Michael Irvin was holding court in typical
Michael Irvin fashion.
</P>
<P>
   It was early in training camp last season and ``The Playmaker''
was delivering a colorful, expletive-filled speech about the
problems he was having with then-Dallas Cowboys coach Chan Gailey
and the possibility of his finishing his career with another team.
</P>
<P>
   He ended his rant saying, ``Y'all are going to miss me when I'm
gone. But whenever I do leave, just say `There goes a ``baaad''
man.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Irvin had no idea then that the end was so near. A congenital
spinal condition forced him to announce his retirement Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   To invoke an expression from another bygone era, Irvin was Super
Bad during a 12-year stint with the Cowboys. His career included
three Super Bowl titles and concluded with his owning every major
receiving record in team history.
</P>
<P>
   Simply put, Irvin remade ``Shaft'' well before Samuel L. Jackson
decided to recreate the 1970s movie icon.
</P>
<P>
   With the game on the line, who comes through 10 times out of 10?
Irvin.
</P>
<P>
   Can you dig it?
</P>
<P>
   Irvin, however, played as hard off the field as he did on it
with jewelry, tailored suits, limousines and all-night partying.
</P>
<P>
   A few missteps, including pleading no contest to felony drug
possession in 1996, tainted his image, turning him from the toast
of Dallas during the team's championship run to being the prime
example of the evils of modern-day sports.
</P>
<P>
   Now that he's gone, his baggage has left some doubt as to how he
will be remembered _ as one of the baddest football players to ever
play the game or just a bad guy.
</P>
<P>
   Those who knew him best _ his teammates who played alongside him
for much of his career _ say their lasting memory of Irvin is their
first: a dedicated, hard-working football player who strove to be
the best.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is the hardest working guy that I have ever been associated
with,'' retired Cowboys fullback Daryl Johnston said. ``He was
always there early in the morning lifting weights, he was running
late on the track to make sure that he was in shape. I have not
been associated with anybody on this team during my tenure with the
Dallas Cowboys that worked as hard as Michael Irvin did.''
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys quarterback Troy Aikman, who combined with Irvin to
create one of the league's all-time greatest pass-catching
combinations, said Irvin's first legacy is that he's the most
prolific receiver in Cowboys history. Aikman said Irvin achieved
greatness because of his work ethic.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is arguably the hardest-working athlete I've ever been
around,'' Aikman said. ``He wasn't blessed with the greatest speed.
He wasn't blessed with a lot of the athletic ability that some
players are, but he made up for it with desire and his work ethic.
I think his competitiveness and his will to win are two things that
define him and separated himself from a lot of other receivers.''
</P>
<P>
   Aikman understands that Irvin's indiscretions might have clouded
some people's view of him as a football player. But he said that
would be unjust to Irvin, who produced some of the most exciting
moments in NFL history.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you think of Michael you think of him making the big
plays in the big games,'' Aikman said. ``He had a lot of those
moments in addition to the enthusiasm and excitement he brought to
the game. Those are things I remember when I think of him on the
field.
</P>
<P>
   ``Michael was a great football player. I don't know if he is
spoke of in those terms often enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys safety Darren Woodson echoed Aikman's remarks, saying
people tend to forget how great Irvin was and what he meant to the
Cowboys' success.
</P>
<P>
   ``They want to read the headlines and see all the bad things
that happened to the Cowboys and Irvin,'' Woodson said. ``They
forget this guy was here until the wee hours in the morning working
out by himself and pushing his teammates to get to that level.''
</P>
<P>
   Woodson recalled what Irvin did for ``the Cowboys' organization,
bringing guys up and making us competitive.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He made us compete against him in practice,'' Woodson said.
``That's why we won. It carried on to the game. We competed in the
game. That's how we got three Super Bowl rings. Other teams had the
same talent. But we competed harder than other teams during the
games because of Michael.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, indeed, there goes a ``baad'' man. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
