r s BC-FBN-IRVIN-INJURY-TEX     07-11 0469
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-IRVIN-INJURY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRVIN FINDS A FOE HE CAN'T BEAT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Listen to people talk about Dallas Cowboys
receiver Michael Irvin and the first thing they will say is that
he's an intense competitor.
</P>
<P>
   Irvin hated to lose at anything _ whether it was pickup
basketball, football, wind sprints or dominoes.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Irvin, the driving force behind Cowboys Super Bowl
title teams in the 1992, 1993 and 1995 seasons, won a lot. And even
when he didn't win, he didn't go down without giving his all.
</P>
<P>
   That is until Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Not only was his retirement from the game a personal setback,
but it's the worst kind because he lost without being allowed to
put up a fight.
</P>
<P>
   Irvin wanted to fight and compete as he always had.
</P>
<P>
   But against this opponent _ cervical stenosis, a congenital
condition that consists of narrowing of the spinal canal _ Irvin's
methods were helpless. The condition makes him more susceptible to
permanent paralysis if he had received another hit to the neck or
back.
</P>
<P>
   Irvin got a taste of what his competitor was like Oct. 10 when
he experienced brief paralysis after a first-quarter hit at
Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   His doctors told him to quit. And so did his family.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could line up and play, but there would be no peace if I
played,'' Irvin said. ``No peace with my wife and no peace with my
family.''
</P>
<P>
   Irvin joins three other players known to have been forced from
the NFL because of a narrow spinal canal: former Houston Oilers
linebacker Frank Bush, former Green Bay Packers cornerback Tim
Lewis and former Detroit Lions defensive back Harry Colon.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Andrea Halliday, a neurosurgeon at the University of
Texas-Southwestern Medical Center, said spinal stenosis is a
condition that normally affects older people and is degenerative in
nature.
</P>
<P>
   She said that for some people, such as Irvin, it is a condition
that people are born with.
</P>
<P>
   Halliday, who has not studied Irvin's case, said surgery is an
option for some people, though maybe not football players.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can do surgery that enlarges the canal,'' Halliday said.
``But because the neck would not be as strong as it was before
surgery it might be counterproductive for football players.''
</P>
<P>
   Also making the situation tough on Irvin was that his body,
which he has taken pride working on throughout his career, failed
him.
</P>
<P>
   However, Halliday said Irvin's top-rate conditioning is probably
what allowed him to play as long as he did without incident.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that he is in good condition kept him from having
more problems with it,'' Halliday said. ``His neck is so strong, it
kept him from having the extreme range of motions that get people
in trouble with stenosis.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-11-00 2352EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
