<SLUG> BC-FBN-IRVIN-JONES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JONES HAS HAD SPECIAL FONDNESS FOR IRVIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RAY BUCK 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Jerry Jones fell just short Tuesday of assuring
that Michael Irvin will be included in the Dallas Cowboys' Ring of
Honor someday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't imagine saying anything about the Ring of Honor
without Michael Irvin's name coming to mind,'' Jones said after
Irvin's retirement announcement at Texas Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Irvin, meanwhile, made no qualms about fully expecting to
eventually join Bob Lilly, Roger Staubach, Tony Dorsett, Tom Landry
and six other former Cowboy greats inside the famed ring.
</P>
<P>
   Jones would only say that nothing has been planned for Irvin _
yet _ and that there is no timetable after a retirement
announcement to honor a prospective ring member.
</P>
<P>
   Jones has never hidden his fond feelings for Irvin, who was the
team's last link to the Landry years. In 1988, Irvin became
Landry's last No. 1 draft pick (11th overall). Jones bought the
team a year later.
</P>
<P>
   Some feel that Irvin is Jones' favorite all-time Cowboy. Jones
would only say that Irvin is probably the most unique Cowboy.
</P>
<P>
   ``What made Michael so unique was that he not only was extremely
talented, he also was an entertainer. He really helped put on a
show,'' Jones said. ``And he had a way of pushing his body to
alarming heights. I've had trainers tell me that they were afraid
Michael would hurt himself out there. Those are the things that
made him probably the most unique player I've ever been around.''
</P>
<P>
   In 12 seasons, Irving became the most prolific receiver in
Cowboys history, as well as one of the NFL's top 10 in career
catches (750) and career yards (11,904), despite playing in a
balanced offense that included what possibly one day will be the
NFL's all-time leading rusher, Emmitt Smith.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have respect for Michael Irvin,'' said Jones, who recalled
Tuesday the story of how Irvin immediately volunteered to visit
Oklahoma City in the aftermath of the 1995 bombing and lend support
to the families of the victims.
</P>
<P>
   These same skills of caring and leadership will be missed with
the Cowboys, Jones pointed out.
</P>
<P>
   ``His ability to do anything it took to win, then basically call
on that power and use it in a leadership role was beyond anything
I've ever seen anywhere,'' Jones said. ``He would use his will, his
courage, his intensity ... to inspire players, coaches and everyone
else in the organization. You just can't replace that.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Irvin's five-game NFL drug suspension in 1996, and the
controversy it brought to the Cowboys, Jones still can't help but
see the irony here.
</P>
<P>
   ``I regretted what happened,'' Jones said. ``Because I knew that
Michael Irvin was not about hurting himself or his teammates. He
was about getting his team ready to play. That was where his heart
was.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones believes that Irvin was born to play football.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think his abilities could only have been brought out in
football,'' Jones said. ``He was able to exhibit the kind of
emotion that it takes to play above the pain, above the fray.
Michael Irvin had the competitiveness, the combativeness and the
courage that it takes to play this game.''
</P>
<P>
   Unique skills, indeed.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
